const RAW: string =
"{\"docs\":[{\"itemId\":\"A.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"A\",\"label\":\"Visual Biology — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/A-Visual-Biology/A-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"The human body runs on ten integrated systems, each with a specific job. Optometry boards test this at two levels: knowing which system does what (systemic disease connections to the eye), and knowing the detailed anatomy of the head and neck (where the orbit sits, what cranial nerves run nearby, and how sinuses relate to orbital disease). The twelve cranial nerves are the bridge between general anatomy and ocular anatomy — CN2 through CN7 all directly affect vision, eye movement, or ocular sensation. Understanding which nerve does what, where it travels, and what breaks when it is damaged is foundational for both A and F subject questions. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does a pituitary adenoma cause bitemporal hemianopia?\\\" The answer traces from general anatomy (pituitary is in the sella turcica, above the sphenoidal sinus) through head/neck anatomy (optic chiasma sits above the pituitary) to visual pathway pathology. One anatomy question links three subjects.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"Why are there 12 cranial nerves instead of, say, 4 or 20? Because the head and face are extraordinarily complex sensory and motor territory. The face processes vision, smell, taste, hearing, balance, and facial sensation while controlling chewing, swallowing, facial expression, and eye movement — all from one compact anatomical region. 12 separate nerve pairs evolved to handle this complexity without a tangled, unreliable superhighway. Why are cranial nerves numbered by their order of exit from the brain? Because they are numbered anatomically from front to back (rostral to caudal). CN1 (olfactory) exits most anteriorly from the cerebrum. CN12 (hypoglossal) exits most posteriorly from the medulla oblongata. The number tells you roughly where in the brain the nucleus sits and where the nerve exits the skull. Why does sinus disease commonly spread to the orbit? Because the paranasal sinuses share bony walls with the orbit. The ethmoid sinus is separated from the medial orbit by the thin lamina papyracea. When sinusitis erodes through this wall, orbital cellulitis results directly.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"Cranial nerve Greek kranion — skull A nerve arising directly from the brain rather than the spinal cord; 12 pairs total Gyri Greek gyros — circle Convolutions (folds) of the cerebral cortex Sulci Latin sulcus — furrow Shallow grooves between gyri Fissures Latin fissura — cleft Deep grooves dividing major brain regions Haversian system Named after Clopton Havers The structural unit of compact bone; contains Haversian canals, lamellae, and osteocytes Meninges Greek meninx — membrane Three protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord (dura, arachnoid, pia) Fontanels French — soft spot Membrane-filled gaps between infant skull bones; close as ossification completes Foramen magnum Latin — large hole Largest foramen in the skull; connects medulla oblongata to spinal cord\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"The 10 Systems of the Human Body — with their optometric relevance: System Main Organs Optometric Connection I. Integumentary Skin, nails, hair, glands Eyelid skin; Meibomian/Zeis/Moll glands; melanin and UV protection II. Skeletal 206 bones, cartilage, joints Orbital bones (7 bones of the orbit); skull foramina; nasolacrimal canal III. Muscular Muscles, tendons, aponeuroses Extraocular muscles, LPS, orbicularis; Müller's muscle (smooth) IV. Nervous Brain, spinal cord, 12 CN, 31 spinal nerves Visual pathway; CN2–7 (all directly ocular); ANS (pupil control) V. Circulatory Heart, arteries, veins Ophthalmic artery (CRA); central retinal artery/vein; anterior ciliary artery VI. Respiratory Lungs, airways Sarcoidosis → uveitis; systemic hypoxia → retinal vessel changes VII. Digestive GI tract, liver, pancreas Liver disease → jaundice; Crohn's → episcleritis/uveitis VIII. Excretory/Urinary Kidneys, bladder, ureters Hypertension (renovascular) → hypertensive retinopathy; Wilson's disease → Kayser-Fleischer ring IX. Reproductive Gonads, uterus, prostate Pregnancy → IOP changes; Graves' disease (thyroid = adjacent system) → exophthalmos X. Endocrine Pituitary, thyroid, adrenals, pancreas Diabetes → diabetic retinopathy; Graves' disease → thyroid eye disease; pituitary adenoma → bitemporal hemianopia The most board-tested systemic connections to the eye: Diabetes (retinopathy), Hypertension (retinopathy), Thyroid disease (TED/Graves'), Sarcoidosis (uveitis), Multiple Sclerosis (optic neuritis), Syphilis (Argyll-Robertson pupil), and Tuberculosis (choroiditis). The 12 Cranial Nerves — the ocularly relevant ones in detail: Mnemonics for the 12 CNs in order: \\\"Oh, Oh, Oh, To Touch And Feel A Girl's Vagina, Ahh, Heaven\\\" (Olfactory, Optic, Oculomotor, Trochlear, Trigeminal, Abducens, Facial, Auditory/Vestibulocochlear, Glossopharyngeal, Vagus, Accessory, Hypoglossal) Mnemonics for Sensory (S), Motor (M), or Both (B): \\\"Some Say Money Matters But My Brother Says Big Brains Matter Most\\\" (S, S, M, M, B, M, B, S, B, B, M, M) CN Name Type Exit Optometric Function I Olfactory Sensory Ethmoid foramina Smell; rarely tested in optometry II Optic Sensory Optic canal Vision; visual pathway; pupillary afferent III Oculomotor Motor SOF (medial) All EOMs except SO and LR; LPS; pupil sphincter (parasympathetic via ciliary ganglion) IV Trochlear Motor SOF (lateral) Superior oblique only; CN4 palsy = head tilt to opposite shoulder V Trigeminal Both V1=SOF, V2=foramen rotundum, V3=foramen ovale V1 (ophthalmic): corneal sensation, conjunctiva, upper lid, lacrimal gland; V2 (maxillary): lower lid, cheek; V3: jaw muscles VI Abducens Motor SOF (medial) Lateral rectus only; CN6 palsy = esotropia VII Facial Both Stylomastoid foramen Orbicularis (CN7 palsy = lagophthalmos); lacrimal gland secretion (via greater petrosal nerve) VIII Vestibulocochlear Sensory Internal auditory meatus Hearing/balance; VOR testing IX Glossopharyngeal Both Jugular foramen Throat sensation, taste (post. 1/3 tongue) X Vagus Both Jugular foramen Longest CN; visceral motor/sensory XI Accessory Motor Jugular foramen Trapezius, SCM muscles XII Hypoglossal Motor Hypoglossal canal Tongue movement CN2 — Optic Nerve: the four segments: 1. Intraocular (0.7–1.0mm) — from optic disc through lamina cribrosa — unmyelinated nerve fibers (no myelin = transparent) — shortest segment 2. Intraorbital (30mm = longest segment) — from globe to optic canal — S-shaped curve → allows free eyeball movement without traction on the nerve — myelinated, sheathed with all 3 meningeal layers 3. Intracanalicular (4–10mm, avg 6mm) — passes through optic canal with ophthalmic artery and sympathetic nerve 4. Intracranial (10mm) — from optic foramen to optic chiasma CN3 — Oculomotor: what breaks when it fails: CN3 PALSY (complete): 1. Ptosis (complete) — LPS paralyzed 2. Eye turns DOWN and OUT — SR, IR, MR paralyzed; LR and SO still active 3. Dilated, fixed pupil — sphincter pupillae paralyzed (parasympathetic) 4. Cycloplegia — ciliary muscle paralyzed; can't accommodate 5. Diplopia Note: CN3 carries pupillomotor fibers on its OUTSIDE surface → Compression (aneurysm, herniation) affects pupil FIRST Ischemia (diabetic CN3 palsy) affects muscle FIRST , spares pupil This distinction is critical in emergency evaluation CN4 — Trochlear: the only motor CN that is: Thinnest (2,150–3,400 fibers) and most slender Longest intracranial course (75mm) Only CN emerging from the DORSAL surface of the brainstem Only CN completely decussated (innervates contralateral SO) CN4 palsy → hypertropia + extorsion → head tilt to OPPOSITE shoulder (Bielschowsky test) CN5 — Trigeminal: the three divisions and their optometric importance: V1 (Ophthalmic division) — pure sensory, exits via SOF Branches: a. Nasociliary → long ciliary nerves (cornea + dilator pupillae sympathetic fibers) → infratrochlear (lacrimal sac, conjunctiva, eyelids) → anterior + posterior ethmoidal b. Lacrimal nerve → lacrimal gland + skin of lids (parasympathetic from CN7 hitches a ride here to reach lacrimal gland) c. Frontal nerve → supraorbital + supratrochlear → upper lid, forehead, scalp V2 (Maxillary division) — sensory + motor, exits foramen rotundum Branches: zygomatic, infraorbital → lower lid, cheek, upper lip, upper teeth V3 (Mandibular division) — both, exits foramen ovale Motor: muscles of mastication (temporalis, masseter, medial + lateral pterygoid) Sensory: lower lip, lower teeth, jaw, external ear CN6 — Abducens: short facts: Shortest intracranial course 3,600 nerve fibers Innervates only the IPSILATERAL lateral rectus CN6 palsy → LR paralyzed → MR unopposed → esotropia with diplopia on lateral gaze Raised ICP can stretch CN6 (long course hugging skull base) → false localizing sign CN7 — Facial: why it matters for optometry: Motor to orbicularis oculi (eye closure) — CN7 palsy = lagophthalmos = corneal exposure Carries parasympathetic to lacrimal gland (via greater petrosal → vidian nerve → pterygopalatine ganglion → zygomatic → lacrimal nerve) Test: brow raise, eye closure, smile (assesses full course) Lesion above geniculate ganglion → facial palsy + dry eye (lacrimal fibers affected) Lesion below geniculate → facial palsy, tearing preserved The Skull — key bones and foramina: 8 PAIRED BONES of the skull: Palatine, Parietal, Temporal, Inferior nasal concha, Maxilla, Nasal, Zygoma, Lacrimal Mnemonic: \\\"Please Put Towel In My New Zipper Luggage\\\" 5 UNPAIRED BONES : Frontal, Ethmoid, Sphenoid, Occipital, Vomer Mnemonic: \\\"Frequent Explorers Seek Out Villages\\\" KEY SKULL FORAMINA : Foramen magnum (occipital bone) → medulla/spinal cord junction; CN XI Optic canal (lesser wing of sphenoid) → CN2 , ophthalmic artery, sympathetic SOF (between wings of sphenoid) → CN3 , 4, 5-ophthalmic, 6, superior ophthalmic vein IOF → CN5 maxillary, infraorbital artery Foramen ovale → CN5 mandibular Foramen rotundum → CN5 maxillary Stylomastoid foramen → CN7 (facial) Jugular foramen → CN 9, 10, 11 The Brain — lobes and their visual functions: CEREBRUM LOBES : Frontal lobe — frontal eye fields ( FEF ): voluntary saccade generation Parietal lobe — somatosensory; posterior parietal cortex: spatial attention, optic ataxia Temporal lobe — auditory; inferior temporal: object recognition (ventral \\\"what\\\" stream); Meyer's loop Occipital lobe — PRIMARY VISUAL CORTEX (Area 17/V1); striate cortex; striae of Gennari — Area 18 (parastriate/V2), Area 19 (peristriate/V3) BRAIN STEM FUNCTIONS for optometry: Midbrain: — Superior colliculus: reflex eye movements toward visual stimuli — Edinger-Westphal nucleus: pupillary constriction + accommodation ( CN3 parasympathetic) — CN3 nucleus, CN4 nucleus Pons: — CN6 nucleus ( PPRF = paramedian pontine reticular formation = horizontal gaze center) — CN7 nucleus; lacrimal nucleus ( CN7 parasympathetic) Medulla: — CN 9, 10, 11, 12 nuclei The Paranasal Sinuses — orbital infection spread: 4 PARANASAL SINUSES : 1. Maxillary (largest) — ceiling = orbital floor → floor fracture = blowout 2. Frontal — above orbit; roof fracture → pneumocephalus risk 3. Ethmoidal (\\\"honeycomb\\\") — shares medial orbital wall (lamina papyracea) → Ethmoidal sinusitis = most common cause of orbital cellulitis 4. Sphenoidal — above = pituitary gland + CN2 → sphenoidal sinusitis = retrobulbar neuritis\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"CNs that enter the orbit via SOF vs Optic Canal: Via Optic Canal Via SOF CN2 (optic) CN3 (oculomotor) Ophthalmic artery CN4 (trochlear) Sympathetic nerve CN5 ophthalmic (V1): frontal, lacrimal, nasociliary CN6 (abducens) Superior ophthalmic vein Board clue \\\"Vision and blood supply\\\" \\\"Everything that moves or senses the orbit\\\" CN3 palsy: compressive vs ischemic: Feature Compressive (aneurysm) Ischemic (diabetic) Pupil Dilated, fixed (AFFECTED FIRST) Spared (pupil normal) Onset Sudden, painful Gradual, may be painless EOM Paretic Paretic Emergency? YES — posterior communicating artery aneurysm; life-threatening Medical management; self-resolves in weeks Board clue \\\"Pupil involved = surgical emergency\\\" \\\"Pupil spared = vascular; watchful waiting\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"Total cranial nerves 12 pairs CN1, 2 from cerebrum; CN3-12 from brainstem Adult skull bones 22 bones (without ossicles + mandible) Reference Optic nerve intraorbital length 30mm (longest segment) S-shape allows eyeball movement Optic nerve intracanalicular 4–10mm (avg 6mm) Vulnerable to compression CN4 intracranial length 75mm (longest intracranial) Most prone to closed head trauma CN4 fiber count 2,150–3,400 Thinnest motor CN CN3 fiber count 24,000 Largest motor CN Foramen magnum Largest skull foramen Medulla-spinal cord junction Anterior fontanel closes 18–24 months Largest fontanel (bregma)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"12 cranial nerves — \\\"Oh, Oh, Oh To Touch And Feel A Girl's Vagina, Ahh Heaven\\\" Olfactory, Optic, Oculomotor, Trochlear, Trigeminal, Abducens, Facial, Auditory, Glossopharyngeal, Vagus, Accessory, Hypoglossal Type (S/M/B) — \\\"Some Say Money Matters But My Brother Says Big Brains Matter Most\\\" S, S, M, M, B, M, B, S, B, B, M, M Ocular CNs — \\\"2 Sees, 3 Moves Most, 4 Spins (SO), 5 Feels, 6 Abducts (LR), 7 Closes\\\" CN2 = vision; CN3 = most EOMs + pupil; CN4 = SO; CN5 = sensation; CN6 = LR; CN7 = orbicularis closure Sinus-to-orbit spread Ethmoidal → Orbital cellulitis (shared lamina papyracea) Sphenoidal → Retrobulbar neuritis (CN2 sits above) Paired skull bones — \\\"Please Put Towel In My New Zipper Luggage\\\" (8 paired) Palatine, Parietal, Temporal, Inferior nasal concha, Maxilla, Nasal, Zygoma, Lacrimal Unpaired skull bones — \\\"Frequent Explorers Seek Out Villages\\\" (5 unpaired) Frontal, Ethmoid, Sphenoid, Occipital, Vomer\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"12 CRANIAL NERVES — OCULAR FOCUS ───────────────────────────────────── CN2 → Optic canal → VISION CN3 → SOF (medial) → SR, IR, MR, IO, LPS + pupil sphincter + accommodation CN4 → SOF (lateral) → SO only CN5V1 → SOF → cornea, conjunctiva, upper lid, lacrimal gland sensation CN5V2 → Foramen rotundum → lower lid, cheek CN6 → SOF (medial) → LR only CN7 → Stylomastoid → orbicularis + lacrimal secretion (via greater petrosal) PARANASAL SINUS → ORBITAL DISEASE ─────────────────────────────────── Ethmoid sinus → ORBITAL CELLULITIS (lamina papyracea breach) Sphenoid sinus → RETROBULBAR NEURITIS ( CN2 above sinus) Maxillary sinus → BLOWOUT FRACTURE (orbital floor ceiling) Frontal sinus → PNEUMOCEPHALUS (roof injury) BRAIN LOBES → VISUAL FUNCTION ─────────────────────────────── Frontal: voluntary saccades ( FEF ) Parietal: spatial processing (\\\"where\\\" stream) Temporal: object recognition (\\\"what\\\" stream) + Meyer's loop Occipital: PRIMARY VISUAL CORTEX (Area 17, 18, 19)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"CN3 carries only motor fibers CN3 carries both somatic motor (EOMs, LPS) AND parasympathetic (pupil sphincter, ciliary muscle via ciliary ganglion/short ciliary nerve). CN4 innervates the ipsilateral superior oblique CN4 is the only cranial nerve completely decussated — it innervates the CONTRALATERAL superior oblique. Pupil involvement in CN3 palsy can be safely observed Pupil-involving CN3 palsy is a surgical emergency until proven otherwise (posterior communicating artery aneurysm). Must rule out aneurysm immediately. CN5 V1 is the largest branch of the trigeminal V3 (mandibular) is the largest branch. V1 (ophthalmic) is the smallest branch and pure sensory. Orbital cellulitis spreads from the sphenoidal sinus Orbital cellulitis most commonly spreads from the ETHMOIDAL sinus (shared lamina papyracea with medial orbital wall). Sphenoidal sinusitis causes retrobulbar neuritis (CN2 involvement), not orbital cellulitis. CN6 has the longest intracranial course CN4 has the longest intracranial course (75mm). CN6 has the SHORTEST intracranial course but is still vulnerable to increased ICP from its long course along the skull base.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer CN for vision CN2 (optic) CN for most EOMs + pupil constriction CN3 (oculomotor) CN for SO only CN4 (trochlear) — contralateral CN for corneal sensation CN5 V1 (ophthalmic) via nasociliary CN for LR only CN6 (abducens) CN for eye closure + lacrimal secretion CN7 (facial) Thinnest motor CN CN4 (trochlear) Only completely decussated CN CN4 CN3 palsy: compressive vs ischemic distinction Compressive = pupil dilated; ischemic = pupil spared Sinus → orbital cellulitis Ethmoidal sinus (lamina papyracea) Sinus → retrobulbar neuritis Sphenoidal sinus (CN2 sits above) Occipital lobe function Primary visual cortex (Area 17) Foramen for CN7 exit Stylomastoid foramen Foramen for CN2 + ophthalmic artery Optic canal (lesser wing of sphenoid) Paired skull bones (8) Palatine, Parietal, Temporal, Inf. nasal concha, Maxilla, Nasal, Zygoma, Lacrimal\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"1. A 58-year-old hypertensive patient wakes up with right-sided ptosis, right eye turned outward and downward, and pupil 7mm and non-reactive. What is the diagnosis and what does the pupil finding suggest? A. Right CN6 palsy; ischemic B. Right CN3 palsy; compressive (aneurysm suspected) C. Right CN3 palsy; ischemic (diabetic) D. Right CN4 palsy; ischemic Answer B. Right CN3 palsy; compressive — aneurysm must be ruled out immediately. Complete right CN3 palsy presents with: ptosis (LPS paralyzed), eye down and out (SR/IR/MR paralyzed; unopposed LR + SO), dilated non-reactive pupil (sphincter pupillae paralyzed). The KEY finding is the dilated, non-reactive pupil — parasympathetic pupillomotor fibers run on the outside surface of CN3. External compression (aneurysm of the posterior communicating artery) preferentially affects these outer fibers FIRST, causing early pupil involvement. Ischemic CN3 palsy (diabetes, hypertension) affects the inner motor fibers first while sparing the outer pupillomotor fibers. Pupil-involving CN3 palsy = surgical emergency until neuroimaging rules out aneurysm. CN6 palsy causes esotropia, not the down-and-out eye. CN4 palsy causes hypertropia/head tilt, not ptosis. 2. A child presents with preseptal eyelid swelling, proptosis, restricted eye movement, and fever. What is the most likely source of infection based on anatomy? A. Sphenoidal sinus B. Maxillary sinus C. Frontal sinus D. Ethmoidal sinus Answer D. Ethmoidal sinus. Orbital cellulitis in children most commonly originates from the ethmoidal sinus. The medial orbital wall (lamina papyracea of the ethmoid) is extremely thin and directly adjacent to the ethmoidal air cells. Bacterial sinusitis erodes through this wall, spreading infection into the orbit. The presentation — preseptal and postseptal involvement, proptosis, restricted EOM, fever — is the classic orbital cellulitis picture. The sphenoidal sinus is posterior to the orbit and relates to CN2 (retrobulbar neuritis), not direct orbital spread. The maxillary sinus relates to the orbital floor (blowout fractures). The frontal sinus relates to the orbital roof.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1-01-human-biology-systems-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A1-01 — Human Biology and the Body Systems\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"HUMAN BIOLOGY SYSTEMS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: 10 body systems with their optometric connection for each; 12 cranial nerves in order with function; which 4 sinuses and which orbital problem each causes. Core targets: CN2 through CN7 — name, what it does, what fails when it's damaged Compressive vs ischemic CN3 palsy — the pupil distinction Ethmoidal sinus → orbital cellulitis pathway (why this sinus, not others) Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the orbit from an anterior view. Label where CN2, CN3, CN4, CN5-V1, CN6, and CN7 enter or exit. Draw the four sinuses and label which ones border the orbit. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a student why a pituitary tumor causes bitemporal hemianopia and not some other visual field defect — connecting skull anatomy, pituitary location, optic chiasma position, and decussation pattern in one explanation without using the word \\\"chiasma\\\" until your final sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back CN for vision? CN2 (optic) CN that innervates SO? CN4 (trochlear) — contralateral SO CN for LR only? CN6 (abducens) CN for eye closure? CN7 (facial) — orbicularis oculi Pupil-involving CN3 palsy → Surgical emergency (aneurysm) Pupil-sparing CN3 palsy → Ischemic (diabetic); watchful waiting Thinnest / longest intracranial CN? CN4 (thinnest motor; longest intracranial 75mm) Sinus → orbital cellulitis? Ethmoidal Sinus → retrobulbar neuritis? Sphenoidal Area 17 of brain? Primary visual cortex (occipital lobe) Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Orbit diagram + CN map + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (pituitary tumor) 4th 1 week CN3 compressive vs ischemic from scratch Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"The orbit is a bony pyramid-shaped socket that houses and protects the eyeball. Seven bones form its walls, and four openings let nerves and vessels pass in and out. Six muscles attach to the outside of the eyeball and move it in all directions — four straight ones (recti) that pull the eye along predictable axes, and two oblique ones that rotate and tilt it. Each muscle has one nerve assigned to it, and three nerves control all six muscles between them. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"If the lateral rectus is the only muscle that abducts the eye, what happens when CN6 is damaged?\\\" Follow that thread and you've taught the entire EOM innervation framework in one clinical story.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Why do the oblique muscles have secondary and tertiary actions instead of just one action like the recti? Because the obliques insert behind the equator of the eyeball at an angle. Why does the insertion angle matter? Because a muscle's action depends on where it pulls relative to the eye's axis of rotation — not just where it attaches. Why does the superior oblique not simply elevate the eye if it passes over the top? Because after the trochlea redirects the tendon, it pulls the back of the eye upward and inward — which rotates the front of the eye downward (depression) and nasally (intorsion). Why does that matter clinically? Because in CN4 palsy (superior oblique), the patient loses intorsion and depression — they tilt their head to the opposite shoulder to compensate, which is the basis of the Bielschowsky head tilt test.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Orbit Latin orbita — wheel track, circuit The bony socket the eye \\\"rotates\\\" within Annulus of Zinn Named after Johann Gottfried Zinn (anatomist) The fibrous tendinous ring at the orbital apex — the common origin of 4 recti + LPS + SO Trochlea Greek trokhilia — pulley The fibrocartilaginous loop on the orbital roof that redirects the SO tendon — acts as a mechanical pulley Recti Latin rectus — straight The four straight muscles that run along the orbital walls Oblique Latin obliquus — slanting The two muscles whose paths are angled relative to the visual axis Adduction Latin ad — toward + ducere — to lead Moving the eye nasally (toward the midline) Abduction Latin ab — away + ducere — to lead Moving the eye temporally (away from midline) Intorsion / Incycloduction The 12 o'clock point on the cornea rotates nasally Inward wheel-rotation of the eye Extorsion / Excycloduction The 12 o'clock point on the cornea rotates temporally Outward wheel-rotation of the eye Lamina papyracea Latin — paper-thin plate The thinnest orbital wall (medial, ethmoid bone) — the wall that fractures first\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"The orbit as a protective system: The orbit is not just a hole in the skull. It is designed with deliberate structural logic: The medial wall is the thinnest (lamina papyracea of ethmoid) — it fractures preferentially in blunt trauma, which protects the eye by absorbing force. A fracture here is called a blowout fracture , and the eye recedes inward (enophthalmos). The lateral wall is the thickest and strongest — it takes the brunt of direct lateral trauma. The floor is thin and sits above the maxillary sinus — fractures here cause inferior rectus entrapment, restricting upward gaze. How the EOMs move the eye: The recti run straight from the annulus of Zinn to their scleral insertions, so their action is relatively direct. The obliques are different: Superior Oblique path: Origin (sphenoid, above optic foramen) → belly runs forward to the TROCHLEA (pulley on orbital roof) → tendon bends BACKWARD at 55° → passes UNDER the superior rectus → inserts on SUPERO-POSTERIOR quadrant of sclera Result: pulls the back of the eye upward → eye rotates DOWN (depression) + nasally (intorsion). Abduction is tertiary. Inferior Oblique path: Origin (maxilla floor, lateral to nasolacrimal groove) → belly passes OUTWARD and BACKWARD at 51° → passes UNDER the lateral rectus → inserts on SUPERO-POSTERIOR quadrant of sclera Result: opposite of SO → Extorsion (primary), Elevation (secondary), Abduction (tertiary).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"The 7 bones of the orbit — remembered as \\\"My Favourite Sexy Zebra Loves Playing Eternally\\\": Maxilla (floor + medial wall) Frontal (roof) Sphenoid (lateral wall + apex — greater + lesser wings) Zygomatic (lateral wall) Lacrimal (medial wall) Palatine (floor) Ethmoid (medial wall — the thin lamina papyracea) The 4 walls and their defining features: ROOF (triangular) ├── Frontal bone + lesser wing of sphenoid ├── Lacrimal gland fossa (supero-lateral) └── Trochlea attachment point (4mm from orbital margin) The roof separates the orbit from the frontal sinus above and the cranial cavity — which is why orbital roof fractures can allow air into the skull (pneumocephalus) or cause CSF leaks. The trochlea sits just 4 mm behind the orbital margin here; a direct blow to the superomedial orbital rim can fracture it, and when the pulley breaks, SO function collapses even if CN4 is intact. MEDIAL WALL (quadrilateral) — THINNEST ├── Sphenoid, Maxilla, Ethmoid (lamina papyracea), Lacrimal bone └── Lacrimal sac fossa (nasal side) The ethmoid is a spongy, air-filled bone — it was never built to take impact. It fractures intentionally, like a crumple zone, dissipating force before it reaches the eyeball. This is protective by design. The same thinness that makes it fracture easily is also why ethmoidal sinusitis spreads directly into the orbit, causing orbital cellulitis — the infection simply erodes through the paper-thin wall. FLOOR (triangular) ├── Maxilla, Palatine, Zygomatic └── Maxillary antrum (sinus) sits below — fracture = blowout The floor is thin because it shares its lower surface with the ceiling of the maxillary sinus — a hollow air space that provides zero structural support from below. When the floor cracks from blunt trauma, the sinus opens up and the inferior rectus (or its surrounding fat) herniates downward into the sinus, getting trapped. The patient then cannot look up — not because CN3 is damaged, but because the muscle is physically stuck. This is the classic blowout fracture presentation: enophthalmos + restricted upgaze + infraorbital nerve numbness. LATERAL WALL (triangular) — THICKEST ├── Greater wing of sphenoid + Zygomatic bone └── Lateral orbital tubercle (Whitnall's tubercle) at zygomatic bone — attachment point for check ligament of LR, Lockwood's ligament, lateral palpebral ligament, LPS aponeurosis The lateral wall is where the globe is most exposed to direct blows — a punch, a ball, an elbow. The greater wing of sphenoid and zygomatic bone are dense cortical bone, which is why lateral wall fractures are rare and indicate severe force when they do occur. The lateral orbital tubercle (Whitnall's tubercle) is not just a bony bump — it is the single attachment point for four critical structures simultaneously, making it a key surgical landmark. Damage here disrupts lateral eye stability, eyelid position, and LPS function all at once. The 5 orbital openings and what passes through them: 1. Optic canal (lesser wing of sphenoid) → CN2 , Ophthalmic artery, Sympathetic nerve The optic canal runs completely surrounded by bone inside the lesser wing of sphenoid — normally excellent protection. But the sphenoidal sinus sits directly below it, and severe sphenoidal sinusitis can erode through that bone and inflame CN2, causing retrobulbar neuritis. That direct anatomical relationship explains why a sinus infection can present with sudden vision loss. 2. Superior orbital fissure ( SOF ) — between greater + lesser wing of sphenoid → CN3 , CN4 , CN5 (ophthalmic: frontal, lacrimal, nasociliary), CN6 , Superior ophthalmic vein Every motor nerve to the EOMs — CN3, CN4, CN6 — plus the entire sensory supply of the orbit — CN5 ophthalmic — all pass through this single fissure. A mass, aneurysm, or inflammation at the orbital apex that compresses the SOF simultaneously paralyzes all EOM movement AND wipes out orbital sensation. This is orbital apex syndrome: total ophthalmoplegia plus numbness of the periorbital skin and cornea. One opening, complete orbital shutdown. 3. Inferior orbital fissure ( IOF ) — below SOF → CN5 (maxillary: infraorbital + zygomatic nerves), Infraorbital artery, Inferior ophthalmic vein, Sympathetic The infraorbital nerve (a branch of CN5 maxillary) runs through the IOF, travels along the orbital floor, and exits at the infraorbital foramen just below the orbit to supply sensation to the cheek, lower eyelid, upper lip, and upper teeth. This is why an orbital floor blowout fracture causes numbness of the cheek — the nerve gets compressed or torn as it runs through the fractured floor. When a patient reports numbness after an orbital punch, the floor is the first place you look. 4. Anterior + posterior ethmoidal foramina (fronto-ethmoidal suture) → Ethmoidal nerves 5. Nasolacrimal canal → Nasolacrimal duct The 4 paranasal sinuses and their orbital relationships: 1. Maxillary sinus (Antrum of Highmore) — largest sinus, pyramidal cavity — ceiling = orbital floor → floor fracture opens into this sinus — opens at middle meatus of nose 2. Frontal sinus — in frontal bone, separated by septum — roof = anterior cranial fossa → roof fracture can cause meningitis — opens via ethmoidal infundibulum/frontonasal duct 3. Ethmoidal sinus (\\\"honeycomb\\\") — spongy air cells forming the medial orbital wall (lamina papyracea) — anterior + middle cells open at middle meatus — posterior cells open at superior meatus — direct neighbor to orbit → ethmoidal sinusitis = orbital cellulitis risk 4. Sphenoidal sinus — lies in body of sphenoid, opens at superior meatus — structures ABOVE it: pituitary gland + CN2 (optic nerve) — sphenoidal sinusitis → retrobulbar neuritis ( CN2 inflammation through the thin bone above) The sinuses are not just air spaces — each one borders a critical structure. The maxillary sits under the orbital floor, the ethmoid forms the medial wall, and the sphenoidal puts the pituitary and optic nerve directly at risk when infected. Orbital fascia — the soft tissue framework inside the orbit: 1. Periorbita — periosteum of the bony orbit — derived from the dura mater of the optic nerve meninges — loosely adherent to orbital bones (can be stripped in surgery) 2. Orbital septum / Palpebral fascia — extension of periosteum from orbital margins inward to orbicularis oculi — fuses with the LPS aponeurosis at the upper eyelid Functions: a. Separates eyelids from orbital contents — prevents orbital fat from herniating forward b. Acts as a barrier preventing spread of eyelid infections into the orbit 3. Tenon's capsule / Bulbar fascia — wraps the entire eyeball from entrance of the optic nerve to the limbus — firmly adherent to bulbar conjunctiva at limbus — thickens at the lower pole of the eyeball where it fuses with fascial sheaths of IR and IO → forms the Ligament of Lockwood (suspensory ligament of the eyeball) Function: a. Suspends and cushions the eyeball within the orbit Think of the orbital fascia as the orbit's internal scaffolding. Periorbita lines the walls. The orbital septum is the door between the eyelid and the orbit — when it's intact, lid infections stay in the lid; when it's breached, orbital cellulitis begins. Tenon's capsule is the eyeball's sock — it lets the eye rotate freely while holding it suspended within the fat compartments. EOM summary — the master table: Before reading this table, fix one mechanical principle in your head: the closer a muscle inserts to the limbus, the greater its mechanical leverage and the stronger its pull. MR at 5.5 mm is nearest — it is the strongest recti muscle. SR at 7.7 mm is farthest — it has to pull harder and at an angle, which forces it to develop secondary and tertiary actions. That is not a coincidence; it is leverage physics. Muscle Origin Insertion Limbus distance Primary Secondary Tertiary Nerve Medial Rectus Annulus of Zinn Sclera (nasal) 5.5 mm (nearest) Adduction — — CN3 Lateral Rectus Annulus of Zinn (2 heads) Sclera (temporal) 6.9 mm Abduction — — CN6 Superior Rectus Annulus of Zinn Sclera (superior) 7.7 mm (farthest) Elevation Intorsion Adduction CN3 Inferior Rectus Annulus of Zinn Sclera (inferior) 6.5 mm Depression Extorsion Adduction CN3 Superior Oblique Sphenoid (above optic foramen) Supero-posterior sclera (behind equator) 7–18 mm Intorsion Depression Abduction CN4 Inferior Oblique Maxilla (orbital floor) Supero-posterior sclera (behind equator) 5–14 mm Extorsion Elevation Abduction CN3 Recti insert IN FRONT of the equator. Obliques insert BEHIND the equator. This single fact explains why obliques have complex multi-axis actions. Think of it this way: pulling the front of a ball spins it cleanly along one axis (predictable, single-direction). Pulling the back of a ball from an angle tips it in two or three directions simultaneously. Recti pull the front — simple, single action. Obliques pull the back at an angle — complex, multi-axis action. The anatomy produces the physiology.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Feature Superior Oblique Inferior Oblique Origin Sphenoid (above optic foramen) Maxilla (orbital floor) Path Forward to trochlea, then bends BACK Outward and backward from floor Passes under Superior Rectus Lateral Rectus Primary action Intorsion Extorsion Secondary action Depression Elevation Nerve CN4 (Trochlear) CN3 (Oculomotor) Board clue Only muscle innervated by CN4; palsy = head tilt toward opposite shoulder Only EOM with no bony origin — starts as a tendon from the floor Feature SOF contents Optic Canal contents Nerves CN3, CN4, CN5 (ophthalmic), CN6 CN2, sympathetic Vessels Superior ophthalmic vein Ophthalmic artery Board clue \\\"Anything that moves the eye or feels the orbit\\\" \\\"Vision + blood supply to retina\\\" Surgical procedures — Exenteration vs Evisceration vs Enucleation: These three sound similar and boards love to test them. The key is what gets removed and what stays. Feature Exenteration Evisceration Enucleation What is removed Entire orbital contents (eye + adnexa + sometimes eyelids) + part of bony orbit Internal contents of eyeball only (may include cornea) Entire eyeball only What is preserved Nothing inside the orbit Sclera + EOMs intact All orbital structures except the eyeball Main indication Large orbital tumors, orbital extension of intraocular tumors Endophthalmitis unresponsive to antibiotics; cosmesis of blind eye Malignant intraocular tumors; painful blind eye; trauma (prevent sympathetic ophthalmia); phthisis; congenital anophthalmia Board clue Most radical — removes everything including bone Keeps the scleral shell — prosthesis fits directly Removes the whole globe but leaves the socket intact for prosthesis Sympathetic ophthalmia — this is why enucleation is indicated after severe penetrating ocular trauma. If the injured eye (exciting eye) is not removed within 2 weeks, the healthy fellow eye (sympathizing eye) can develop a granulomatous uveitis that blinds both eyes. Removing the exciting eye breaks the immune trigger.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Orbital dimensions 40mm height, 40mm width, 40mm depth Volume = 29–30 mL. Even a 4 mL increase (blood, pus, tumor) causes proptosis — the orbit has no room to expand, so the eyeball gets pushed forward instead Optic canal dimensions 4–10 mm long Completely surrounded by bone inside the lesser wing of sphenoid — protected unless sphenoidal sinusitis erodes through Lateral orbital tubercle 11 mm from fronto-zygomatic suture (on zygomatic bone) Precise surgical landmark — 4 structures attach here simultaneously Limbus distance — MR 5.5 mm (nearest) Closest insertion = best mechanical leverage = strongest recti muscle. This is why convergence (both MRs pulling simultaneously) is the most powerful EOM movement Limbus distance — SR 7.7 mm (farthest) Being farthest means SR pulls at a 23° angle to the visual axis — it cannot produce pure elevation alone. The angle forces secondary intorsion and tertiary adduction as unavoidable byproducts LR insertion 6.9 mm LR is the only muscle abducting the eye. In CN6 palsy, LR fails and MR acts unopposed — the eye is pulled permanently nasally, producing esotropia. The amount of esotropia tells you how complete the palsy is Palpebral fissure 8–11 mm height, 27–30 mm width The normal measurement. Widening (Dalrymple's sign) suggests LPS overaction or Müller's muscle excess, as in thyroid eye disease. Narrowing suggests ptosis or Horner's SO total length 60 mm (longest EOM total) Long because it travels from the orbital apex all the way to the trochlea and then bends back to insert posteriorly — the longest path of any EOM IO total length 37 mm (shortest EOM) Short because it originates near the front of the orbital floor — it has almost no belly, hence no tendon or a minimal 1–2 mm one Trochlea location 4 mm from superior orbital margin on frontal bone Without the trochlea's 55° redirection, SO would pull the eye forward and upward from its origin at the apex — a completely different action. The trochlea is the anatomical reason SO depresses instead of elevates\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"The 7 orbital bones — \\\"My Favourite Sexy Zebra Loves Playing Eternally\\\" Maxilla, Frontal, Sphenoid, Zygomatic, Lacrimal, Palatine, Ethmoid EOM innervation — LR6 SO4 AO3 Lateral Rectus → CN6 Superior Oblique → CN4 All Others → CN3 Wall thickness rule — \\\"Medial is minimal, Lateral is lateral steel\\\" Medial = thinnest (lamina papyracea). Lateral = thickest. Recti vs. obliques insertion rule Recti insert IN FRONT of equator — pull the front of the eye = predictable axis action Obliques insert BEHIND the equator — pull the back of the eye = complex multi-axis action SOF vs. Optic Canal analogy (IT frame) Think of the optic canal as the dedicated fiber line (vision only — CN2 + blood supply). The SOF is the general-purpose port (everything else that moves the eye or senses the orbit).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"APEX (posterior) BASE (anterior = orbital opening) | |-- Optic Canal: CN2 , Ophthalmic A., Sympathetic | |-- Annulus of Zinn (tendinous ring) | |-- MR ( CN3 ) | |-- LR ( CN6 ) | |-- SR ( CN3 ) | |-- IR ( CN3 ) | |-- SO ( CN4 ) → runs to TROCHLEA → bends back → inserts posterior | |-- LPS ( CN3 ) ← not an EOM but shares origin | |-- SOF (lateral to optic canal): CN3 , CN4 , CN5- ophthalmic, CN6 , Sup. ophthalmic vein | |-- IOF (below SOF ): CN5- maxillary, Infraorbital A., Inf. ophthalmic vein | IO originates from FLOOR (maxilla) — only EOM not from Annulus of Zinn\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"The superior oblique elevates the eye Its PRIMARY action is intorsion. Depression is secondary. (IO elevates; SO depresses.) CN3 innervates all EOMs CN4 innervates SO; CN6 innervates LR. All others are CN3. The medial wall is the strongest It is the thinnest and weakest (lamina papyracea). The lateral wall is the thickest. Confusing SOF and Optic Canal. CN2 goes through the optic canal, not the SOF. CN3 goes through the SOF. All EOMs originate from the Annulus of Zinn IO originates from the maxilla (orbital floor). It is the only EOM without an origin at the annulus. MR nearest vs. SR farthest from limbus. Board questions reverse these. MR = 5.5 mm (nearest, strongest). SR = 7.7 mm (farthest). Evisceration removes the whole eye Evisceration removes only the internal contents; the sclera and EOMs are preserved. Enucleation removes the whole eyeball. Sphenoidal sinusitis causes orbital cellulitis Ethmoidal sinusitis causes orbital cellulitis (medial wall is shared). Sphenoidal sinusitis causes retrobulbar neuritis (CN2 is above the sinus). \\\"The orbital septum is part of the eyelid\\\" — It is the boundary between the eyelid and the orbit. When intact it protects the orbit; when breached, infection spreads from preseptal cellulitis into orbital cellulitis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer 7 bones of the orbit Maxilla, Frontal, Sphenoid, Zygomatic, Lacrimal, Palatine, Ethmoid Thinnest orbital wall Medial (lamina papyracea of ethmoid) Thickest orbital wall Lateral (greater wing of sphenoid + zygomatic) Optic canal contents CN2, ophthalmic artery, sympathetic nerve SOF contents CN3, CN4, CN5-ophthalmic (frontal, lacrimal, nasociliary), CN6, superior ophthalmic vein EOM innervation rule LR6 SO4 AO3 Only EOM innervated by CN4 Superior Oblique Only EOM with no Annulus of Zinn origin Inferior Oblique (originates from maxilla) Primary action of SO Intorsion Primary action of IO Extorsion MR limbus distance 5.5 mm (nearest = strongest) SR limbus distance 7.7 mm (farthest) SO total length 60 mm (longest EOM) Recti insert In front of equator Obliques insert Behind equator Orbital fascia layers (3) Periorbita → Orbital septum → Tenon's capsule Orbital septum function Barrier between eyelid and orbit — breach = orbital cellulitis Tenon's capsule thickening Lockwood's ligament (with IR + IO fascia) = suspensory ligament of eyeball Evisceration vs Enucleation Evisceration = contents only (sclera stays); Enucleation = whole eyeball removed Sympathetic ophthalmia Enucleate traumatized eye within 2 weeks or fellow eye develops granulomatous uveitis Sphenoidal sinusitis → Retrobulbar neuritis (CN2 is above the sinus) Ethmoidal sinusitis → Orbital cellulitis (medial wall = lamina papyracea = shared wall)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"1. A 45-year-old patient presents with vertical diplopia that worsens when looking down-and-inward. He tilts his head toward his left shoulder when reading. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis? A. Right CN3 palsy B. Left CN6 palsy C. Right CN4 palsy D. Left CN3 palsy Answer C. Right CN4 palsy. CN4 (trochlear) innervates the superior oblique. The SO's primary action is intorsion, secondary is depression. When it fails, the eye cannot depress or intort — this causes vertical diplopia worse on downgaze and in adduction (looking down-inward). The patient compensates by tilting the head toward the opposite shoulder (here, left), which is the classic Bielschowsky head tilt. A CN3 palsy would cause a larger picture — ptosis, dilated pupil, and the eye would be down and out. CN6 palsy causes horizontal diplopia (esotropia), not vertical. 2. Which of the following correctly lists the contents of the superior orbital fissure? A. CN2, ophthalmic artery, CN3 B. CN3, CN4, CN6, superior ophthalmic vein C. CN2, CN3, CN4, CN6, ophthalmic artery D. CN5 maxillary division, infraorbital artery Answer B. CN3, CN4, CN6, superior ophthalmic vein. The SOF carries CN3 (oculomotor), CN4 (trochlear), CN5-ophthalmic division (via its branches: frontal, lacrimal, nasociliary), CN6 (abducens), and the superior ophthalmic vein. CN2 and the ophthalmic artery pass through the optic canal — not the SOF. The inferior orbital fissure carries CN5 maxillary division and the infraorbital artery (option D).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-01-orbit-and-extraocular-muscles-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-01 — The Bony Orbit and Extraocular Muscles\",\"text\":\"Close this note before picking up the pen. Rule: write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"ORBIT AND EXTRAOCULAR MUSCLES\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set 5 minutes. Write everything you can retrieve: bones, walls, openings, EOM names, origins, insertions, actions, innervations. Circle every gap when you check. Core targets for this brain dump: The 7 bones of the orbit from memory (use the mnemonic) All 6 EOMs with their nerve supply What passes through the optic canal vs. the SOF Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the orbital opening (a rough pentagon shape). Label the 4 walls with their bones. Mark the optic canal and SOF on your diagram. Write the contents of each next to them. No peeking until you've labeled every structure. What to reproduce: The 4-wall bone map + the two main openings with contents labeled. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write 4–5 sentences explaining why the superior oblique depresses the eye instead of elevating it, without using the word \\\"trochlea.\\\" Teach-back prompt: \\\"Explain how the direction of a muscle's pull — not its position — determines its action.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Thinnest orbital wall? Medial (lamina papyracea of ethmoid) EOM innervation rule? LR6 SO4 AO3 Contents of optic canal? CN2, ophthalmic artery, sympathetic nerve Primary action of SO? Intorsion Primary action of IO? Extorsion MR limbus distance? 5.5 mm (nearest) Only EOM NOT from annulus of Zinn? Inferior Oblique (maxilla floor) CN4 palsy head tilt direction? Toward the OPPOSITE shoulder Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the path of the superior oblique from origin to insertion — every stop in order. Then write what each segment of the path contributes to its final action. No looking until you've completed the full sequence. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st review Today (same session) Brain Dump 2nd review Tomorrow Blank Diagram + Flash Cards 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write 4th review 1 week later SO path sequence from scratch Final check 2 weeks later All 5 drills — flag anything shaky\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"The eyelids are the eye's first and most active line of defense — they blink 15 times a minute, spread tears across the cornea on every closure, and physically block foreign bodies from reaching the eye. The conjunctiva lines the inside of the lids and covers the front of the eyeball, and its goblet cells produce the mucin that makes the tear film stick to the cornea. The lacrimal system produces tears and drains them away — the gland makes them, the blink spreads them, the puncta collect them, and the nasolacrimal duct carries them into the nose (which is why you get a runny nose when you cry). The tear film itself is a three-layer structure, and each layer has one job: the lipid layer prevents evaporation, the aqueous layer carries oxygen and antibodies, and the mucin layer anchors the whole film to the cornea. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does a contact lens wearer get dry eyes faster than a spectacle wearer?\\\" That question leads directly to the tear film layers, blink rate, and goblet cell function simultaneously.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Why does blinking matter for vision, not just protection? Because without a fresh tear film, the corneal surface becomes irregular. Why does an irregular corneal surface matter? Because the tear film's oily top layer creates the smooth optical surface the eye needs to focus light cleanly — if it breaks up, incoming light scatters instead of focusing. Why does the tear film break up at all? Because the oily lipid layer evaporates, thinning until it can no longer hold the aqueous layer beneath it in place. Why can't the eye just produce more tears to compensate? Because the real problem in most dry eye is not volume — it is either too little mucin (so the film doesn't stick) or too little lipid (so it evaporates too fast). Adding more aqueous layer doesn't fix either problem. Why does this matter clinically? Because Schirmer's test measures aqueous production, and TBUT measures film stability. A patient can have normal Schirmer's but low TBUT — meaning they produce enough tears but the film breaks up before the next blink. These are different problems requiring different management.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Tarsus Greek tarsos — flat surface, sole of foot The dense fibrous plate that gives the eyelid its rigid structure; the \\\"skeleton\\\" of the eyelid Meibomian glands Named after Heinrich Meibom (1638–1700) Sebaceous glands embedded in the tarsus; produce the oily lipid layer of the tear film Palpebral Latin palpebra — eyelid Anything related to the eyelid (palpebral conjunctiva, palpebral fissure, pars palpebralis) Fornix Latin — arch, vault The fold of conjunctiva at the deepest part where the eyelid conjunctiva meets the bulbar conjunctiva; the \\\"pocket\\\" of conjunctival space Punctum Latin — point The tiny opening at the medial end of each eyelid through which tears enter the drainage system Canaliculus Latin — small canal The narrow tube connecting the punctum to the lacrimal sac Nasolacrimal Naso (nose) + lacrimal (tear) The duct that carries tears from the lacrimal sac into the nasal cavity Goblet cell Named for their goblet/cup shape Unicellular glands in the conjunctival epithelium that secrete mucin Lysozyme Greek lysis — dissolution + enzyma — enzyme Antibacterial enzyme in tears that breaks down bacterial cell walls; also called muramidase TBUT Tear Break-Up Time Time in seconds from last blink to first dry spot on cornea — measures tear film stability Chemosis Greek kheme — clam shell (gaping shell) Swelling/edema of the conjunctiva, most prominent at the loose fornix\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"The blink cycle — how eyelids make vision possible: Blinking is not just protective — it is optical maintenance. On every blink: The upper lid descends (orbicularis oculi contracts, LPS relaxes) The lid margin spreads a fresh layer of tear film across the cornea The lid reopens (LPS contracts, orbicularis relaxes) The fresh tear film gives the eye 10–15 seconds of stable optical surface before it begins to break up The next blink renews it Rate: 15 blinks/minute spontaneous. Contact lens wearers blink less, which is one reason their tear film breaks up faster. The lacrimal secretory pathway: Two levels of tear production: BASIC SECRETION (reflex-independent) → Glands of Krause (at fornix) + Glands of Wolfring (at tarsus) → Always on — maintains baseline tear volume between emotional/reflex events REFLEX SECRETION (nerve-controlled) → Main lacrimal gland → Triggered by: corneal irritation ( CN5 ), bright light, emotion, CN7 stimulation The parasympathetic pathway to the lacrimal gland (this is a board-tested sequence): CN7 nucleus (pons) — lacrimal nucleus ↓ Motor fibers exit with CN7 ↓ Geniculate ganglion (no synapse here — just passes through) ↓ Greater petrosal nerve (exits petrous temporal bone) ↓ joins with Deep petrosal nerve (sympathetic post-ganglionic from carotid plexus) ↓ = Vidian nerve / Nerve of pterygoid canal ↓ Pterygopalatine (sphenopalatine) ganglion — SYNAPSE here ↓ Post-ganglionic fibers join CN5 maxillary → zygomatic nerve ↓ Communicating branch to lacrimal nerve ( CN5 ophthalmic) ↓ Lacrimal gland → increased secretion Why does this matter? Because CN7 damage above the geniculate ganglion causes decreased tearing (dry eye) in addition to facial paralysis. CN7 damage below the geniculate only causes facial paralysis — tearing is spared. The level of the lesion determines whether the lacrimal gland is involved. The tear drainage pathway: Tear film on cornea ↓ (blink pumps tears medially) Lacrimal lake (medial canthus) ↓ Lacrimal puncta (upper + lower, 0.3mm opening) ↓ Lacrimal canaliculi (vertical 2–3.5mm → horizontal 8mm → meets lacrimal sac) ↓ Lacrimal sac (12mm long × 6mm wide; on medial orbital wall) ↓ guarded by valve of Beraud (inferior pouch = sinus of Arlt) Nasolacrimal duct (12–24mm; runs in nasolacrimal canal) ↓ guarded by valve of Hasner Inferior meatus of nose The nasolacrimal duct is the last part of the drainage system to open during fetal development — this is why newborns can have congenital nasolacrimal duct obstruction (epiphora in neonates), which usually resolves by 6–12 months as the duct fully opens.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Histologic layers of the eyelid — skin to conjunctiva: 1. SKIN + SUBCUTANEOUS TISSUE — thinnest skin in the body (loose areolar connective tissue, no fat) — so thin you can see vessels through it when edematous 2. MUSCULAR LAYER a. Orbicularis oculi ( CN7 ) — sphincter of eyelid ├── Pars orbitalis (peripheral) — forcible closure; pulls forehead/temple/cheek ├── Pars palpebralis (central) │ ├── Preseptal — over orbital septum │ └── Pretarsal — over tarsus; blink involves this layer only └── Pars lacrimalis — attached to lacrimal sac; pumps tears into drainage system b. Levator palpebrae superioris ( CN3 ) — elevates upper eyelid Origin: lesser wing of sphenoid (above lateral Annulus of Zinn) Insertion: tarsal plate + skin of eyelid (forms superior orbital furrow) c. Müller's muscle (Sympathetic nerve) — tonic elevator Superior: origin = underside of LPS → inserts at superior tarsal plate Inferior: origin = fascial expansion of IR → inserts at inferior tarsal plate So what: Müller's is the fine-tuner. LPS does the heavy lifting (elevates 15mm); Müller's adds 2–3mm of tone. Horner's syndrome paralyzes Müller's → 1–2mm partial ptosis. CN3 palsy paralyzes LPS → complete ptosis. 3. TARSUS (fibrous skeleton) — dense fibrous connective tissue; contains Meibomian glands Upper tarsus: 11mm vertical diameter Lower tarsus: 5mm vertical diameter Thickness: 1mm | Length: 25–30mm 4. CONJUNCTIVA (innermost layer) — see Conjunctiva section below Eyelid glands — what each produces and where it opens: Gland Type Opens at Layer produced So what Meibomian / Tarsal Modified sebaceous; holocrine Lid margin (posterior to gray line) Lipid layer of tear film (mainly) 30–40 upper lid, 20–30 lower lid; dysfunction = evaporative dry eye Zeis Sebaceous At base of cilia Lipid layer (minor contribution) Infection = hordeolum externum (external stye) Moll Sweat (apocrine) Between cilia at lid margin Sweat component Infection = hordeolum externum Krause Accessory lacrimal Fornix (20 upper, 6–8 lower) Aqueous layer (basic secretion) Main basic secretors; present even without CN7 stimulation Wolfring Accessory lacrimal At tarsus Aqueous layer (basic secretion) Located at tarsal border; also basic secretors Goblet cells Unicellular mucinous Conjunctival surface Mucin layer of tear film Numerous at fornix, fewer at bulbar, absent at limbus and lid margins The distinction between basic and reflex secretion is clinically important: after denervation of the main lacrimal gland (CN7 palsy), basic secretion from Krause and Wolfring is preserved. The eye is not completely dry, but reflex tearing (crying, irritation) is lost. Eyelid measurements — upper vs lower: Feature Upper Eyelid Lower Eyelid Height 11 mm 5 mm Width 25–30 mm 25–30 mm Tarsal glands 30–40 20–30 Eyelashes 150 75 Cilia direction Outward and upward Outward and downward Horizontal furrow More distinct (formed by LPS) Less distinct (formed by orbicularis) LPS Present Absent Lid margin position 2 mm below upper limbus At or 1 mm below lower limbus The horizontal furrow on the upper lid is visible in normal adults because LPS inserts into the skin — that crease is literally the tendon marking. In ptosis from LPS dysfunction, this crease becomes abnormally high or disappears. Conjunctiva — 3 parts: PALPEBRAL ( TARSAL ) CONJUNCTIVA — lines the inner surface of the eyelids — firmly adherent to tarsus (cannot be separated) — so tightly bound that chemosis (swelling) never affects this portion BULBAR CONJUNCTIVA — loosely covers the front of the sclera — firmly adherent only at the limbus — looseness = allows eyeball movement without tearing conjunctiva FORNIX CONJUNCTIVA — the deep pockets where palpebral and bulbar conjunctiva meet — very loose = allows the greatest range of eye movement — same looseness = first place to swell in chemosis — Superior fornix: 10mm from limbus (more Krause glands here) — Inferior fornix: 8mm from limbus (more lymphoid follicles here) — Lateral fornix: 14mm from limbus — No medial fornix (replaced by plica semilunaris and caruncle) Cul-de-sac: the 2mm-deep space between bulbar and palpebral conjunctiva. Holds 20–30 µL of tears — this is the reservoir that absorbs eye drops. Drops instilled here spread across the conjunctival surface on the next blink. Conjunctiva histologic layers: Layer 1 — Stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium └── Contains goblet cells (unicellular mucin-secreting glands) — Most abundant: fornix — Moderate: bulbar conjunctiva — Absent: lid margins and limbus Why: goblet cells at the fornix serve as the main mucin reservoir. Loss of goblet cells (from trachoma, pemphigoid, chemical burns, SJS ) = mucin-deficient dry eye = poor tear film stability. Layer 2 — Lamina propria / Substantia propria ├── Blood vessels ├── Nerves ├── Glands of Krause (accessory lacrimal — aqueous basic secretion) ├── Glands of Wolfring (accessory lacrimal — aqueous basic secretion) ├── Mast cells (allergy responders — IgE → histamine release) ├── Lymphocytes, plasma cells, PMNs (immune surveillance) └── Lymphoid follicles (especially inferior fornix) Tear film — 3 layers (outermost to innermost): LAYER 1 — LIPID / OILY LAYER Thickness: 0.2–0.9 µm (avg 0.5 µm) — thinnest layer Source: Meibomian glands (mainly) + Zeis glands (minor) Composition: wax esters (35%), cholesterol (30%), phospholipids (16%), triglycerides (4%), free fatty acids (2%), free sterols (2%) Functions: a. Retards evaporation of the aqueous layer beneath it b. Creates the smooth, regular optical surface of the precorneal film c. Provides lubrication at the lid/eye interface d. Prevents overflow epiphora (hydrophobic barrier / lipid strip) Board clue: Meibomian gland dysfunction ( MGD ) = lipid deficiency = evaporative dry eye. Schirmer's test will be NORMAL (aqueous is fine); TBUT will be LOW . LAYER 2 — AQUEOUS LAYER Thickness: 6.5–7.5 µm (avg 7 µm) — THICKEST layer Source: Glands of Krause + Wolfring (basic) and main lacrimal gland (reflex) Composition: 98% water + NaCl, K, HCO3 , urea, glucose (2.5 mg%), proteins Proteins: albumin (60%), globulin (15–20%), lysozyme (21–25%) Immunoglobulins: IgA (major — 17mg/100ml), IgG, IgE, IgM (negligible) Functions: a. Supplies atmospheric O2 to corneal epithelium (cornea is avascular) b. Carries antimicrobial agents (lysozyme + IgA) c. Flushes debris and desquamated cells d. Supports vertical tear film stability LAYER 3 — MUCIN LAYER Thickness: 0.02–0.05 µm — thinnest true layer Source: Goblet cells of conjunctival epithelium Function: Converts the hydrophobic corneal epithelium surface to hydrophilic so the aqueous layer can spread and stick. Board clue: Without mucin, tear film cannot spread across the cornea regardless of how much aqueous is present. Goblet cell loss = mucin-deficient dry eye. The three-layer model from outermost to cornea is: **Oil → Water → Mucus** (OWM). Memory anchor: \\\"Oil covers Water covers Mucus\\\" — or think of salad dressing: oil on top, water underneath, and the \\\"stickiness\\\" (mucin) at the surface it clings to.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Schirmer's test vs TBUT — which problem does each detect: Feature Schirmer's Test Tear Break-Up Time (TBUT) What it measures Volume of aqueous tear production Stability of the tear film Tool used 35×5 mm Whatman #41 filter paper (IsoSol strip) Fluorescein dye + cobalt blue filter on slit lamp Procedure Hook at lateral lower lid for 5 minutes Instill fluorescein, measure seconds from last blink to first dry spot Normal value (Schirmer I, no anesthesia) 10–25 mm >10 seconds Abnormal <6 mm = hyposecretion (KCS/dry eye); >25 mm = hypersecretion <10 seconds = unstable film (dry eye) What layer problem Aqueous layer deficiency Lipid or mucin layer deficiency Board clue Sjögren's syndrome → very low Schirmer's MGD or goblet cell loss → normal Schirmer's, low TBUT Basic vs Reflex secretion: Feature Basic Secretion Reflex Secretion Source Glands of Krause + Wolfring Main lacrimal gland Nerve control Not controlled by nervous system CN7 (parasympathetic) via pterygopalatine ganglion Rate 0.9–2.2 µL/min Variable (triggered) Stimulus Always on Corneal irritation, bright light, emotion, nasal stimulation Clinically Preserved in CN7 palsy Lost in CN7 palsy (no crying, no reflex tearing) Board clue \\\"Basal tears\\\" — the maintenance supply \\\"Lacrimation\\\" — the overflow response Crocodile tears (Bogorad syndrome): After CN7 lesions at the facial ganglion, regenerating salivary nerve fibers can be misdirected to the lacrimal gland — so the patient tears when eating (salivary stimulus triggers lacrimal secretion instead). This is the clinical meaning of \\\"crocodile tears.\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Spontaneous blink rate 15 blinks/min CL wearers blink less → tear film breaks up faster → dry eye Palpebral fissure 8–11 mm height, 27–30 mm width Dalrymple's sign = widened fissure (Müller's overaction — thyroid eye disease) Upper tarsus height 11 mm LPS inserts here — LPS paralysis = complete ptosis; Müller's paralysis = 1–2mm ptosis Lower tarsus height 5 mm Lower lid has less tarsal support — explains lower lid laxity with age Lacrimal punctum size 0.3 mm Small enough to require dilation before probing (probing for nasolacrimal obstruction) Canaliculus horizontal length 8 mm Relevant to lacrimal probing depth; damage here = permanent epiphora Lacrimal sac dimensions 12mm long × 6mm wide Dacryocystitis = infection here; palpable mass below medial palpebral ligament Nasolacrimal duct length 12–24 mm Opens at inferior meatus; last to open in development Tear pH 7.3–7.7 (average 7.4) Ophthalmic solutions outside pH 6.6–7.8 cause discomfort Schirmer's I normal 10–25 mm / 5 min <6 mm = dry eye; used with anesthesia removes reflex → measures basic secretion TBUT normal >10 seconds <10 seconds = dry eye or MGD; measured with fluorescein + cobalt blue filter Lipid layer thickness 0.2–0.9 µm (avg 0.5 µm) Thinnest layer of tear film Aqueous layer thickness 6.5–7.5 µm (avg 7 µm) Thickest layer — most of the tear film volume Tear film total thickness 6.5–7.7 µm Very thin — about the width of a single corneal epithelial cell Krause glands at upper fornix 20 glands More than lower (6–8) — explains why upper fornix produces more basic tears\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Tear film layers from outside to cornea — \\\"Oil Waters Mucin\\\" (OWM) Lipid (oil) → Aqueous (water) → Mucin Gland-to-layer source pairs Meibomian/Zeis → Lipid layer Krause/Wolfring + Main lacrimal gland → Aqueous layer Goblet cells → Mucin layer Lacrimal drainage order — \\\"Pretty Little Canals Send Nasal Tears\\\" (PLCSNT) Puncta → (Lacrimal) Canaliculi → (Lacrimal) Sac → Nasolacrimal duct → Nose CN7 lacrimal pathway — \\\"7 Goes Petrosal to Vidian to Palate\\\" CN7 → Greater petrosal → Vidian nerve → Pterygopalatine ganglion → Zygomatic → Lacrimal nerve → Lacrimal gland Müller's vs LPS ptosis rule Müller's paralyzed (Horner's): 1–2 mm droop (partial ptosis) LPS paralyzed (CN3 palsy): complete ptosis (eye fully closed) Goblet cell distribution rule — \\\"Most at Fornix, None at Limbus\\\" Fornix > bulbar > lid margin > limbus. Where cells are most loose, cells are most numerous.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"EYELID CROSS-SECTION (upper lid, medial to lateral) ───────────────────────────────────────────────── Skin (thinnest in body) ↓ Orbicularis oculi [ CN7 ] ├── Pars orbitalis (outer) — forcible closure └── Pars palpebralis (inner) — blink; pars lacrimalis pumps tears ↓ Orbital septum ← BARRIER between eyelid and orbit ↓ LPS aponeurosis [ CN3 ] → inserts into tarsus + skin (forms lid crease) ↓ Müller's muscle [Sympathetic] → inserts into superior tarsus ↓ TARSUS (fibrous skeleton) → contains Meibomian glands ↓ Palpebral conjunctiva (firmly adherent to tarsus) TEAR FILM (on corneal surface) ───────────────────────────── [ AIR ] LIPID LAYER (0.5 µm) ← Meibomian + Zeis AQUEOUS LAYER (7 µm) ← Krause + Wolfring (basic) + Main LG (reflex) MUCIN LAYER (0.03 µm) ← Goblet cells [ CORNEAL EPITHELIUM ] LACRIMAL DRAINAGE ────────────────── Tear lake (medial canthus) → Puncta (0.3 mm) → Canaliculi [vertical 2–3mm → horizontal 8mm] → Lacrimal sac [12mm × 6mm] (sinus of Maier + sinus of Arlt/valve of Beraud) → Nasolacrimal duct [12–24mm] (valve of Hasner) → Inferior meatus of nose\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"The aqueous layer is produced only by the main lacrimal gland The basic aqueous secretion comes from accessory glands (Krause + Wolfring). The main lacrimal gland only activates for reflex secretion. Schirmer's test measures tear film stability Schirmer's measures aqueous volume. TBUT measures stability (lipid + mucin integrity). The thinnest layer of the tear film is the aqueous layer The aqueous layer (7 µm) is the thickest. The lipid (0.5 µm) and mucin (0.03 µm) layers are much thinner. Goblet cells are found throughout the conjunctiva equally Most at fornix, fewer at bulbar, absent at lid margins and limbus. Complete ptosis from Horner's syndrome Horner's paralyzes Müller's muscle, causing only 1–2 mm partial ptosis. Complete ptosis requires LPS paralysis (CN3 palsy). The nasolacrimal duct opens at the middle meatus It opens at the inferior meatus, guarded by the valve of Hasner. \\\"Pars lacrimalis of orbicularis aids blinking\\\" — Misleading. Its specific role is pumping tears into the lacrimal sac, not blinking. Blinking involves pars palpebralis. \\\"CN7 damage always causes dry eye\\\" — Only if the lesion is above the geniculate ganglion (greater petrosal nerve affected). Below the geniculate = facial paralysis only; tearing is preserved.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Tear film layers (outside to cornea) Lipid → Aqueous → Mucin Thickest tear film layer Aqueous (7 µm) Thinnest tear film layer Mucin (0.03 µm); lipid is thinnest measurable (0.5 µm) Lipid layer source Meibomian glands (mainly) + Zeis Aqueous basic secretion source Glands of Krause + Wolfring Aqueous reflex secretion source Main lacrimal gland (CN7) Mucin layer source Goblet cells of conjunctiva Goblet cells absent at Lid margins and limbus Schirmer's test normal 10–25 mm / 5 min (without anesthesia) TBUT normal >10 seconds CN7 innervates lacrimal via Greater petrosal → Vidian → pterygopalatine ganglion → lacrimal nerve Nasolacrimal duct opens at Inferior meatus of nose (valve of Hasner) Müller's paralysis ptosis 1–2 mm (partial) — Horner's syndrome LPS paralysis ptosis Complete ptosis — CN3 palsy Upper eyelash count 150 Lower eyelash count 75 Lysozyme % in tears 21–25% of tear protein Major Ig in tears IgA (secretory) Lacrimal sac infection Dacryocystitis — swelling below medial palpebral ligament Crocodile tears cause CN7 lesion → salivary fibers misdirected to lacrimal gland\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"1. A 35-year-old patient complains of chronic eye irritation, foreign body sensation, and redness worsening in the afternoon. Schirmer's test (without anesthesia) measures 18 mm bilaterally. Tear break-up time is 5 seconds. Which of the following is the most likely underlying problem? A. Aqueous-deficient dry eye from lacrimal gland hyposecretion B. Lipid layer deficiency from Meibomian gland dysfunction C. Excessive tear drainage due to punctal stenosis D. Conjunctival goblet cell hyperplasia Answer B. Lipid layer deficiency from Meibomian gland dysfunction. The normal Schirmer's test (18 mm — well within 10–25 mm) rules out aqueous deficiency. The short TBUT (5 seconds, normal >10 seconds) indicates the tear film is breaking up too quickly despite adequate aqueous volume. The lipid layer (from Meibomian glands) is what prevents evaporation and maintains film stability. When it is deficient, the aqueous layer evaporates rapidly and the film collapses before the next blink. This is evaporative dry eye — the most common form. Symptoms worsen in the afternoon because Meibomian gland secretions accumulate and solidify with reduced blink-driven expression over the day. 2. A 6-week-old infant is brought in with persistent unilateral epiphora and a mucopurulent discharge since birth. The most likely diagnosis is: A. Congenital glaucoma B. Dacryocystitis secondary to nasolacrimal duct obstruction C. Neonatal conjunctivitis from gonorrhea D. Lacrimal gland agenesis Answer B. Dacryocystitis secondary to nasolacrimal duct obstruction. The nasolacrimal duct is the last segment of the lacrimal drainage system to fully open during development. In up to 20% of newborns, the valve of Hasner (at the nasal opening of the nasolacrimal duct) remains membranous at birth. Tears cannot drain, accumulate in the lacrimal sac, and become secondarily infected. This presents as persistent unilateral epiphora with mucopurulent discharge starting shortly after birth. Management is conservative (massage over lacrimal sac, topical antibiotics) — most resolve spontaneously by 12 months. Probing is performed if obstruction persists beyond that. Congenital glaucoma would present with photophobia, tearing, buphthalmos, and corneal edema — not mucopurulent discharge. Neonatal gonorrheal conjunctivitis presents in the first 2–5 days of life with severe bilateral purulent discharge, not epiphora.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-02-eyelids-conjunctiva-lacrimal-system-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-02 — Eyelids, Conjunctiva, and Lacrimal System\",\"text\":\"Close this note before picking up the pen. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"EYELIDS, CONJUNCTIVA, LACRIMAL SYSTEM\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set 5 minutes. Write everything you can retrieve — tear film layers and sources, lacrimal drainage pathway, eyelid muscles and nerves, Schirmer's and TBUT values, gland names and what they produce. Circle every gap. Core targets: Three tear film layers in order with their source gland and primary function The complete lacrimal drainage pathway from punctum to nose Müller's muscle vs LPS — nerve, function, and ptosis result when paralyzed Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw two diagrams side by side: The tear film cross-section (label all 3 layers with thickness and source gland) The lacrimal drainage pathway (label every structure from punctum to inferior meatus) Do not look until both are fully labeled. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write 4–5 sentences explaining why a patient with Sjögren's syndrome has a very low Schirmer's test but a patient with Meibomian gland dysfunction has a normal Schirmer's test yet still suffers from dry eye — without using the words \\\"aqueous\\\" or \\\"lipid.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Tear film order (outside to cornea)? Lipid → Aqueous → Mucin Thickest tear film layer? Aqueous (7 µm) Source of mucin layer? Goblet cells of conjunctiva Schirmer's test I normal? 10–25 mm / 5 min TBUT normal? >10 seconds Nasolacrimal duct opens at? Inferior meatus (valve of Hasner) Müller's paralysis = ? ptosis 1–2 mm partial ptosis (Horner's) LPS paralysis = ? ptosis Complete ptosis (CN3 palsy) Goblet cells absent at? Lid margins and limbus Basic aqueous secretion from? Glands of Krause + Wolfring Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the parasympathetic pathway from the CN7 nucleus in the pons to the lacrimal gland — every stop in order, naming each structure. Then write what happens clinically if the lesion is above vs below the geniculate ganglion. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st review Today Brain Dump 2nd review Tomorrow Blank Diagram + Flash Cards 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write 4th review 1 week later CN7 lacrimal pathway from scratch Final check 2 weeks later All 5 drills — flag anything shaky\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"The cornea and sclera are both made of collagen — the same raw material — but they look and behave completely differently. The sclera is white and opaque because its collagen fibers are bundled randomly in every direction, scattering light. The cornea is clear because its collagen fibers are arranged in perfectly parallel, evenly spaced layers that let light pass straight through. Transparency is not a different substance — it is a different geometry. The cornea is also the eye's first and most powerful lens, bending light more than any other structure in the optical system. It is nourished without blood vessels, kept alive by the tear film in front and aqueous humor behind, and kept transparent by an endothelial pump that continuously removes water from the stroma. The moment that pump fails, the cornea swells, clouds over, and vision collapses. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"The cornea and sclera are both collagen. Why is one clear and the other white?\\\" Follow that to the fiber arrangement, then to why the endothelium is the most critical layer in the whole cornea.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Why does the cornea have no blood vessels? Because blood vessels are opaque — they would block the light path needed for vision. Why doesn't the cornea die without blood vessels? Because the tear film supplies oxygen from the air, the limbal capillaries supply it from the periphery, and the aqueous humor supplies glucose and oxygen from behind. Why does the cornea swell when the endothelium fails? Because the stroma is hydrophilic — it constantly pulls water in from the aqueous. The endothelium's Na-K ATPase pump actively pushes that water back out, maintaining a precise hydration level. When the pump fails, water accumulates in the stroma. Why does water in the stroma cause loss of transparency? Because swelling disrupts the regular spacing of collagen fibrils. When the regular spacing is lost, fibrils scatter light instead of letting it pass through — the cornea becomes cloudy, exactly like a wet piece of regular paper. Why is this clinically catastrophic? Because corneal endothelial cells do not regenerate. Unlike epithelial cells which divide and replace themselves rapidly, endothelial cells are post-mitotic — once damaged, they are gone permanently. This is why Fuchs' endothelial dystrophy is so serious and why endothelial cell count before surgery matters.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Cornea Latin corneus — horn-like The clear, horn-like front window of the eye — avascular and extremely sensitive Sclera Greek skleros — hard The tough white outer coat that forms 5/6 of the eyeball wall Limbus Latin — border, threshold The 1–2 mm transition zone where cornea meets sclera — not just anatomical, but clinically critical (contains drainage angle) Stroma Greek — bed, layer The thick middle layer of the cornea (90% of its thickness); the \\\"mattress\\\" of collagen Descemet's membrane Named after Jean Descemet (18th c.) The basement membrane of the endothelium — elastic, resistant to perforation Descemetocele Descemet + Greek kele — hernia A balloon-like protrusion of Descemet's membrane through a perforated corneal stroma — the stroma gives way but Descemet holds Endothelium Greek endon — within + thele — nipple The innermost single-cell layer of the cornea; critical for deturgescence via Na-K pump Deturgescence Latin de — away + turgescere — to swell The active dehydration of the corneal stroma maintained by the endothelial pump Pachymeter Greek pakhys — thick + metron — measure The instrument that measures corneal thickness Keratocyte Greek keras — horn + kytos — cell The flat, stellate cells within the corneal stroma that produce and maintain the collagen matrix Emissarium Latin — outlet Channels through the sclera through which nerves and vessels pass\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Why the cornea is transparent — and why the sclera is not: Both are made of Type I collagen. The difference is purely organizational: CORNEA (transparent) Collagen fibrils: — small diameter (25–35 nm) — equal spacing between fibrils — arranged in parallel lamellae — each lamella runs perpendicular to the next Result: Incoming light waves cancel out (destructive interference of scattered waves) → light passes straight through SCLERA (opaque) Collagen fibers: — large diameter (varies widely) — irregular spacing — randomly interlacing in all directions Result: Light is scattered in every direction → white, opaque appearance This is the most important concept in this note. The same material, organized differently, produces completely opposite optical behavior. Any condition that disrupts the regular fiber spacing of the cornea — edema, scarring, dystrophy — causes opacity by the same mechanism that makes the sclera white. The endothelial deturgescence cycle: The corneal stroma is hydrophilic — it actively draws water from the aqueous humor. Left alone, the stroma would absorb water until it swells and becomes opaque. The endothelium prevents this: Aqueous humor (behind cornea) ↓ (water passively enters stroma — it cannot be stopped) CORNEAL STROMA ↑ (endothelium actively pumps Na+ and HCO3 - out) ↑ (water follows osmotically) Na-K ATPase pump in endothelium → electrolytes out → water follows → stroma stays at 75–80% water (optimal for transparency) When the pump is inhibited (ouabain, cyanide, contact lens-induced anoxia) or the cells are lost (Fuchs' dystrophy), water accumulates: Stroma swells → fibers spread apart → opacity Epithelial bullae form (bullous keratopathy) — painful, vision severely reduced Corneal wound healing — 5 stages: Stage Cellular response Biochemical response I Stromal edema, epithelial cell mitosis + sliding Swelling II PMN and mononuclear stromal invasion Increased hydrolase activity; degradation of MPS and collagen III New fibroblasts and mitosis New pre-collagen formation; new MPS (dermatan sulfate) IV Collagen formation Collagen synthesis V Healed stroma Normal hydrolase activity, normal MPS and collagen concentration Why this matters: corneal scars form because new collagen laid down in healing is not as regular as original corneal collagen — hence the scar is less transparent. Bowman's layer never regenerates at all; its loss is permanent.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"The 6 corneal layers — anterior to posterior: 1. CORNEAL EPITHELIUM (10% of corneal weight) — Stratified squamous non-keratinized, 5–6 cell layers — Cell types: ├── Surface cells (squamous + microvilli) — traps tear film; smooth optical surface ├── Wing cells (polyhedral, middle) └── Basal cells (columnar; rest on basement membrane 60–65 nm thick) — Joined by tight junctions (desmosomes); attached to Bowman's by hemidesmosomes — CAN regenerate (rapid mitosis of basal cells) — Water content: 70% — Contains: ATP , glycogen, glutathione, Vit C, ACh, AChE 2. BOWMAN 'S MEMBRANE (12 µm) — Acellular, hyalinized, felt-like collagen — Anterior condensation of stroma — not a true \\\"membrane,\\\" just denser stroma — CANNOT regenerate — scar = permanent opacity — Rupture is rare — Less resistant to trauma and microorganisms than endothelium 3. CORNEAL STROMA / SUBSTANTIA PROPRIA (90% of total thickness — thickest) — Avascular; rich in unmyelinated sensory nerves (nasociliary, CN5 ) — Organized in 200–250 collagen lamellae, each perpendicular to adjacent lamellar — Contains: ├── Keratocytes (corneal corpuscles) — produce and maintain collagen ├── Collagen fibrils (regular spacing = transparency) └── MPS /glycosaminoglycans (4–4.5% dry weight) — bind water, maintain hydration — Water content: 75–80% — If fibers lose regular spacing (edema, scar) → opacity 4. DUA 'S LAYER (6–15 µm) — Recently identified layer between stroma and Descemet's — Despite being very thin, extremely strong: withstands up to 2 bars (200 kPa) — Impervious to air 5. DESCEMET 'S MEMBRANE (10 µm) — True basement membrane of endothelium (produced and secreted by endothelium) — Very elastic and resistant to perforation — When stroma perforates, Descemet's can bulge forward → DESCEMETOCELE — CAN regenerate (secreted by endothelium) — Rich in glycine and hydroxyproline (collagen-like material) — Rupture is COMMON (unlike Bowman's where rupture is rare) 6. CORNEAL ENDOTHELIUM — Single layer of flat hexagonal (mesothelial) cells — Bathed by aqueous humor — Na-K ATPase pump → active transport of Na+ and HCO3 - out → water follows — Maintains stromal dehydration (deturgescence) — CANNOT regenerate — endothelial cell loss is permanent — Normal cell count: ~2500 cells/mm² (decreases with age and surgery) — Damaged by: ouabain, cyanide, large gas-impermeable CL (Sattler's veil), Fuchs' dystrophy — Innervation: NOT innervated by nasociliary nerve (the only corneal layer with no innervation along with Descemet's) The regeneration rule: Epithelium = YES (rapid). Bowman's = NO (permanent scar). Stroma = PARTIAL (new collagen is less organized). Dua's layer = limited data. Descemet's = YES (endothelium secretes it). Endothelium = NO (post-mitotic cells). The sclera — structure and measurements: SCLERA — \\\"White of the eyeball\\\" — Dense, fibrous, collagenous; 5/6 of outer eyeball coat — Covered externally by Tenon's capsule + bulbar conjunctiva — Normal fluid content: 65–70% → Increase to 80% = loses opacity (becomes more transparent) → Decrease to 40% = also loses opacity THICKNESS (varies by location — clinically important) — Thickest: at entrance of CN2 = 1.0 mm — Thinnest: at intersection of recti muscles in front of equator = 0.3 mm Why this matters: the thinnest point is where the EOMs attach. Excessive intraocular pressure or staphyloma preferentially occurs here because the sclera cannot resist expansion at its weakest point. RADIUS OF CURVATURE : 12 mm (vs cornea 7.8 mm — sclera is flatter) SCLERAL OPENINGS : 1. Anterior scleral foramina — at limbus → Perforated by anterior ciliary arteries (ACAs) 2. Posterior scleral foramina — at entrance of optic nerve → CN2 , central retinal artery ( CRA ), long + short posterior ciliary arteries (PCAs), posterior ciliary nerves HISTOLOGIC LAYERS (3): 1. Episclera — outermost; vascular (from ACA ); loose connective tissue Clinical: episcleritis = inflammation here (superficial, benign) scleritis = deeper inflammation involving scleral stroma (more serious) 2. Scleral stroma / proper — middle; dense, IRREGULARLY interlacing collagen This irregular arrangement is the reason the sclera is opaque 3. Lamina fusca / dark layer — innermost; contains melanocytes Fuses with the suprachoroidal space — the interface between sclera and choroid The limbus — the clinically critical transition zone: The limbus is only 1–2 mm wide, but it contains the entire aqueous humor drainage apparatus. Understanding its landmarks is essential for glaucoma. LIMBUS — anterior to posterior (from cornea toward angle): Schwalbe's line — marks where Descemet's membrane ends — most anterior extension of trabecular meshwork — visible on gonioscopy as a thin white glistening line — Sampaolesi's line = pigment deposited along Schwalbe's line (seen in pigment dispersion, PXF ) Trabecular meshwork (TM) — band of connective tissue fibers from Descemet's periphery to scleral spur — filters aqueous humor into Schlemm's canal — anterior zone = less pigmented, less filtration — posterior zone = more pigmented, more filtration (where most AH exits) Schlemm's canal (Sinus Venosis Sclerae) — tube encircling the anterior chamber within the scleral sulcus — collects aqueous humor from TM and drains into episcleral veins — normally not visible — seen only when filled with blood (on gonioscopy) Scleral spur — posterior boundary of TM / anterior boundary of ciliary body band — insertion point for longitudinal ciliary muscle fibers — appears as whitish band on gonioscopy GONIOSCOPY LANDMARKS (anterior to posterior — mnemonic: \\\"She Takes Some Cash Paying\\\") S — Schwalbe's line T — Trabecular meshwork S — Scleral spur C — Ciliary body band P — Peripheral iris\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Cornea vs Sclera — the same material with opposite properties: Feature Cornea Sclera Collagen fiber arrangement Regular, parallel, uniform spacing Irregular, randomly interlacing Optical property Transparent Opaque (white) Proportion of eyeball 1/6 5/6 Radius of curvature 7.8 mm (steeper) 12 mm (flatter) Blood supply Avascular (nourished by tear film + AH + limbal capillaries) ACA + long + short PCA Innervation Nasociliary nerve (CN5) — except Descemet's and endothelium Long + short posterior ciliary nerves Functions Refraction (43D); protective window Protection; maintains globe shape; attachment for EOMs Board clue Fiber regularity = transparency Fiber irregularity = opacity Bowman's membrane vs Descemet's membrane — the two corneal \\\"barriers\\\": Feature Bowman's Membrane Descemet's Membrane Location Between epithelium and stroma Between stroma and endothelium Thickness 12 µm 10 µm Composition Acellular hyalinized collagen (anterior stroma condensation) True basement membrane; collagen-like (glycine, hydroxyproline) Produced by Stroma (not a true membrane) Endothelium (secreted by it) Can it regenerate? NO — permanent scar if damaged YES — endothelium regenerates it Rupture frequency RARE COMMON When it protrudes Cannot (has no elasticity) Descemetocele — balloon-like bulge through stroma defect Board clue Scar from keratitis = Bowman's damaged Descemetocele = stroma gone, Descemet's intact Epithelium vs Endothelium — clinical consequences of damage: Feature Epithelial damage Endothelial damage Regeneration YES — basal cells divide rapidly NO — post-mitotic, loss is permanent Effect on cornea Localized staining with fluorescein; usually heals Corneal edema, bullous keratopathy, permanent clouding Severity Usually temporary Potentially vision-threatening and permanent Example condition Corneal abrasion, contact lens-related SPK Fuchs' endothelial dystrophy; surgical trauma Board clue \\\"Heals in 24–72 hours\\\" \\\"Cannot regenerate; cell count matters\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Corneal refractive power 43 diopters More than the lens (20D at rest). Corneal surgery (LASIK) works because changing curvature changes power significantly Corneal index of refraction 1.376 Used in keratometry calculations Corneal central thickness 0.52–0.56 mm Measured by pachymeter — thin cornea = risk in refractive surgery; thick = suspect IOP readings Corneal peripheral thickness 0.7–1.0 mm Cornea thickens toward the periphery Corneal radius of curvature 7–8.5 mm (avg 7.8 mm) Steeper cornea = more power. Keratoconus = cone shape = irregular steep curvature Corneal horizontal diameter 11–12 mm Wider than vertical (10–11mm) — cornea is a horizontal oval, not a circle Bowman's thickness 12 µm Cannot regenerate — loss = permanent scar Descemet's thickness 10 µm Can regenerate; descemetocele when stroma perforated Dua's layer thickness 6–15 µm Withstands up to 2 bars (200 kPa) pressure Corneal stroma water content 75–80% Maintained by endothelial pump; rises in edema Scleral thickness at CN2 1.0 mm (thickest) Most protected region Scleral thickness at recti 0.3 mm (thinnest) Site of staphyloma, risk area for perforation in surgery Scleral radius of curvature 12 mm Flatter than cornea; not refractive Scleral normal fluid content 65–70% Abnormal either way: >80% or <40% = loses opacity\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"The 6 corneal layers — \\\"Every Brave Soldier Deserves Exceptional Endurance\\\": Epithelium → Bowman's → Stroma → (Dua's) → Descemet's → Endothelium Regeneration rule — \\\"Ep-Yes, Bow-No, Des-Yes, Endo-No\\\": Epithelium: YES Bowman's: NO Descemet's: YES Endothelium: NO Why cornea is clear — \\\"RANRTIC\\\" (7 key reasons): R egular collagen fiber arrangement A vascular N on-keratinized epithelium R egular fiber spacing (equal distance) T ear film forms smooth refracting surface I mpermeable tight junctions (prevents water entry) C onstant endothelial pump (maintains hydration balance) Scleral thickness rule — \\\"Thick at the back, thin at the middle (recti):\\\" Thickest = entrance of CN2 (optic nerve) = 1.0 mm Thinnest = EOM insertion zone (front of equator) = 0.3 mm Gonioscopy landmarks — \\\"She Takes Some Cash Paying\\\": Schwalbe's → Trabecular meshwork → Scleral spur → Ciliary body → Peripheral iris\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"CORNEAL LAYERS (anterior to posterior) ────────────────────────────────────── TEAR FILM ────────────────────────────────── (5–6 cell layers) EPITHELIUM Water 70% | Tight junctions | CAN regenerate ────────────────────────────────── (12 µm, acellular) BOWMAN 'S Felt-like collagen | NO regeneration | Rupture rare ────────────────────────────────── (90% corneal thickness) STROMA Regular parallel lamellae | Keratocytes | MPS | Water 75-80% ────────────────────────────────── (6–15 µm, newly confirmed) DUA 'S LAYER Strong, impervious to air ────────────────────────────────── (10 µm, elastic) DESCEMET 'S Basement membrane of endo | CAN regenerate | Descemetocele if exposed ────────────────────────────────── (single hexagonal cell layer) ENDOTHELIUM Na-K pump | Deturgescence | NO regeneration | Fuchs' = fatal here ──────────────────────────────────────────────── AQUEOUS HUMOR LIMBUS LANDMARKS (anterior → posterior, gonioscopy) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── Schwalbe's line (end of Descemet's) ↓ Trabecular meshwork (filtration) ↓ → → → → Schlemm's canal (collection) → → → → episcleral veins Scleral spur (ciliary muscle attachment) ↓ Ciliary body band ↓ Peripheral iris\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"The thickest corneal layer is the epithelium Stroma is 90% of corneal thickness. Epithelium is 10% of corneal weight. Bowman's membrane can regenerate if damaged It cannot regenerate. Descemet's membrane can regenerate because endothelium secretes it. The cornea is thicker at the center than the periphery Central thickness (0.52–0.56 mm) is THINNER than peripheral (0.7–1.0 mm). The cornea thickens toward its edges. The cornea is a perfect circle Horizontal diameter (11–12mm) is wider than vertical diameter (10–11mm). The cornea is an oval, wider horizontally. Endothelial cells regenerate after damage Endothelium is post-mitotic. Each cell lost is gone permanently. Remaining cells spread to fill the gap, which reduces cell density over time. The sclera is thickest at the EOM insertion zone Thinnest (0.3mm). Thickest at the CN2 entrance (1.0mm). Descemetocele means Descemet's membrane has ruptured Descemetocele is the intact Descemet's bulging through a perforation in the overlying stroma. The membrane is intact but exposed. Nasociliary nerve innervates all corneal layers It innervates all layers EXCEPT Descemet's membrane and endothelium.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Corneal refractive power 43 diopters (most powerful lens in the eye) 6 corneal layers (anterior to posterior) Epithelium → Bowman's → Stroma → Dua's → Descemet's → Endothelium Thickest corneal layer Stroma (90% of total thickness) Layer that cannot regenerate Bowman's (and Endothelium) Layer that can regenerate Epithelium, Descemet's Why cornea is transparent Regular parallel collagen fiber arrangement; avascular; endothelial deturgescence Why sclera is opaque Irregular randomly interlacing collagen fibers — scatter light Endothelial pump Na-K ATPase — removes water from stroma (deturgescence) Descemetocele Stroma perforated; Descemet's bulges forward like a balloon Fuchs' dystrophy Endothelial cell loss → pump failure → permanent corneal edema Corneal innervation Nasociliary nerve (CN5) — all layers except Descemet's and endothelium Corneal central thickness 0.52–0.56 mm (measured by pachymeter) Scleral thickest point 1.0 mm at CN2 entrance Scleral thinnest point 0.3 mm at EOM insertion Scleral opacity mechanism Same as cornea explanation — irregular fiber = scatter = white Limbus width 1–2 mm; contains TM and Schlemm's canal Gonioscopy landmarks (5) Schwalbe's, TM, scleral spur, ciliary body, peripheral iris\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"1. A 70-year-old patient presents with progressive, painless bilateral vision loss. Slit lamp examination shows corneal edema with a beaten-metal appearance of the endothelium on specular reflection. Central pachymetry is 680 µm bilaterally. Which of the following best explains the pathophysiology? A. Failure of goblet cells to produce mucin for the tear film B. Loss of endothelial Na-K ATPase pump function leading to stromal edema C. Disruption of tight junctions in the corneal epithelium D. Degeneration of Bowman's membrane preventing epithelial adhesion Answer B. Loss of endothelial Na-K ATPase pump function leading to stromal edema. This is Fuchs' endothelial dystrophy. The endothelium normally pumps Na+ and HCO3- out of the stroma — water follows osmotically, keeping the stroma at 75–80% water. In Fuchs', endothelial cells degenerate and are not replaced (endothelium is post-mitotic). As cell density falls below a critical threshold, the pump cannot maintain deturgescence. Water accumulates in the stroma, disrupting the regular collagen fiber spacing and causing light scatter (opacity). Pachymetry above 600 µm (normal 520–560 µm) confirms stromal swelling. The \\\"beaten-metal\\\" or \\\"hammered silver\\\" appearance on specular microscopy is the endothelial guttata — excrescences on Descemet's membrane that are pathognomonic of Fuchs'. Goblet cells, tight junctions, and Bowman's membrane are unrelated to this presentation. 2. During gonioscopy, the examiner identifies a thin, white, glistening line at the most anterior portion of the trabecular meshwork. What structure is this? A. Scleral spur B. Schwalbe's line C. Sampaolesi's line D. Schlemm's canal Answer B. Schwalbe's line. Schwalbe's line marks the peripheral termination of Descemet's membrane and the most anterior extension of the trabecular meshwork. It appears as a thin, white, glistening line projecting slightly into the anterior chamber. The gonioscopic order from anterior to posterior is: Schwalbe's line → trabecular meshwork → scleral spur → ciliary body band → peripheral iris. Sampaolesi's line (option C) is pigment deposited along Schwalbe's line — seen in pigment dispersion syndrome and pseudoexfoliation — and would appear as a pigmented line, not a white one. The scleral spur appears as a whitish band posterior to the TM. Schlemm's canal is not normally visible unless blood-filled.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-03-cornea-and-sclera-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-03 — Cornea and Sclera\",\"text\":\"Close this note before picking up the pen. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"CORNEA AND SCLERA\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set 5 minutes. Write: all 6 corneal layers in order with one key fact each, scleral thickness at two locations, reason cornea is transparent, what the endothelial pump does and what happens when it fails. Circle every gap. Core targets: The 6 corneal layers anterior to posterior with their thickness or key property The regeneration status of each layer (yes/no) Why cornea is transparent and sclera is not — in one sentence each Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw a cross-section of the cornea. Label all 6 layers with their thickness. Mark which layers can regenerate with ✓ and which cannot with ✗. Draw an arrow showing where the Na-K pump acts and in which direction it moves water. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write 4–5 sentences explaining to a first-year optometry student why Fuchs' endothelial dystrophy causes vision loss — starting from the cell level and ending at the optical consequence. Do not use the words \\\"edema\\\" or \\\"dystrophy.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Corneal refractive power? 43 diopters 6 corneal layers in order? Epithelium → Bowman's → Stroma → Dua's → Descemet's → Endothelium Layer that cannot regenerate (2)? Bowman's membrane + Endothelium Scleral thickest point? 1.0 mm at CN2 entrance Scleral thinnest point? 0.3 mm at EOM insertion (in front of equator) Descemetocele? Stroma perforated; Descemet's bulges forward intact Why cornea transparent? Regular parallel collagen + avascular + endothelial pump Why sclera opaque? Irregular, interlacing collagen fibers scatter light Corneal central thickness? 0.52–0.56 mm (pachymeter) Gonioscopy landmarks (5)? Schwalbe's, TM, scleral spur, ciliary body, peripheral iris Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the full mechanism of what happens when the corneal endothelium fails — starting from the cell, through the pump failure, to the molecular disruption, to the optical consequence, to the clinical presentation. Write it without stopping; fill any gaps with your best reasoning, then check. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st review Today Brain Dump 2nd review Tomorrow Blank Diagram + Flash Cards 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write (Fuchs') 4th review 1 week later Full endothelial failure sequence Final check 2 weeks later All 5 drills — flag shaky areas\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"The uveal tract is the eye's vascular middle coat — a continuous layer of blood vessels, pigment, and smooth muscle running from front to back. The iris at the front controls how much light enters by changing pupil size. The ciliary body in the middle produces the fluid that fills the eye (aqueous humor) and drives the accommodation mechanism through its muscle. The choroid at the back is a dense vascular blanket that nourishes the outer retina and absorbs stray light to keep vision sharp. All three share the same blood supply and are connected — inflammation in one frequently spreads to the others, which is why uveitis can affect the entire tract simultaneously. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"If you could only keep one layer of the uveal tract, which would it be and why?\\\" The answer reveals whether they understand accommodation, aqueous production, or retinal nutrition — all three are clinically irreplaceable.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Why does the ciliary body produce aqueous humor? Because the avascular cornea and lens need nutrients and oxygen but cannot receive blood directly. Why can't they receive blood directly? Because blood vessels are opaque — they would obstruct the light path and destroy visual acuity. Why does the ciliary muscle need to relax the zonules to achieve accommodation? Because the lens is naturally elastic and would round up on its own if unsupported. The zonules under tension from the ciliary ring actually flatten the lens. When the ciliary muscle contracts, it reduces the ring diameter, reducing zonule tension, and the lens elasticity rounds it up. Why does the choroid need to be so heavily pigmented? Because it sits directly behind the photoreceptors. Any stray light that passes through the retina without being absorbed by a photoreceptor would reflect back and blur the image. The melanin in the choroid absorbs it, functioning like the black paint inside a camera body. Why does uveitis spread easily within the uveal tract? Because the iris, ciliary body, and choroid are continuous — one unbroken vascular tissue. The same blood vessels and inflammatory mediators flow through all three, so inflammation triggered at one point propagates along the tract.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Uvea Latin uva — grape The uveal tract resembles a grape skin — a dark, vascular membrane Iris Greek — rainbow Named for the variety of colors it can display; the visible colored ring of the eye Collarette French — small collar The circular ridge on the iris that separates the pupillary zone from the ciliary zone Miosis Greek meiosis — lessening Pupil constriction (smaller pupil) Mydriasis Greek mydriasis — dilation Pupil dilation (larger pupil) Ciliary body Latin cilia — eyelashes Named for the fringe-like ciliary processes; the production site of aqueous and the motor of accommodation Pars plana Latin — flat part The flat, non-vascular posterior portion of the ciliary body — preferred surgical entry site Pars plicata Latin — folded part The folded, vascular anterior portion with ciliary processes — produces aqueous Choriocapillaris Greek khorion — membrane + capillary The innermost vascular layer of the choroid — wide-bore capillaries that supply the outer retina Bruch's membrane Named after Karl Wilhelm Ludwig Bruch The thin innermost layer of the choroid separating it from the RPE\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Accommodation — how the ciliary body changes lens power: RELAXED STATE (distance vision) Ciliary muscle RELAXED → ciliary ring diameter LARGE → Zonules of Zinn TAUT (under tension) → Lens pulled flat (less convex) → Less refractive power → focused for distance NEAR VISION (accommodation) Stimulus: blur on retina (near object) → Parasympathetic signal via CN3 short ciliary nerve → Ciliary muscle CONTRACTS (annular action) → Ciliary ring diameter DECREASES → Zonules RELAX (tension released) → Lens springs into natural round shape (more convex) → More refractive power → focused for near Think of the zonules as a set of rubber bands stretching the lens flat. When the ciliary muscle contracts, it narrows the ring they're attached to, releasing the stretch. The lens is not being squeezed into shape by the muscle — it is being released from the flattening the zonules were imposing on it. Aqueous humor production at the ciliary process: The non-pigment epithelium of the pars plicata secretes aqueous through three mechanisms: Ultrafiltration — from ciliary capillaries (pressure-driven) Active secretion — Na-K ATPase pumps Na+ into the posterior chamber; water follows osmotically Active transport — carbonic anhydrase drives HCO3- secretion The aqueous flows from the posterior chamber → through the pupil → into the anterior chamber → drains through the trabecular meshwork → Schlemm's canal → episcleral veins. Iris pupillary reflexes: DIRECT LIGHT REFLEX : Light → retina → optic nerve → pretectal nucleus (midbrain) → bilateral Edinger-Westphal nucleus → CN3 → ciliary ganglion → short ciliary nerve → sphincter pupillae → MIOSIS (both eyes) CONSENSUAL : same pathway but the contralateral eye constricts (pretectal nucleus projects bilaterally to both EW nuclei) PSYCHIC REFLEX : Fear → hypothalamus → sympathetic pathway → dilator pupillae → MYDRIASIS\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"The Iris: IRIS (12mm diameter; hangs behind cornea, in front of lens) | ├── PUPILLARY ZONE (central; from pupil to collarette) | — flat, due to atrophy of pupillary membrane | — sphincter pupillae sits here (circular muscle; CN3 ; miosis) | └── CILIARY ZONE (peripheral; from collarette to iris root) — irregular (iris crypts): inner smooth, middle furrowed, marginal cribriform — dilator pupillae sits here (radial muscle; sympathetic; mydriasis) HISTOLOGIC LAYERS (anterior to posterior): 1. Anterior border layer — flat hexagonal cells; no tight junctions (aqueous can enter stroma) 2. Anterior limiting membrane — condensation of anterior stroma 3. Iris stroma — loose CT; sphincter, dilator, blood vessels ( GIC ), pigment cells in GAGs 4. Posterior pigment epithelium (2 layers) a. Anterior pigment epithelium — spindle cells; ciliary zone b. Posterior pigment epithelium — polyhedral cells; pupillary + ciliary zone Blood supply of iris: Greater iris circle (circulus iridis major) = 2 long posterior ciliary arteries + 7 anterior ciliary arteries — forms a ring at the ciliary body. Lesser iris circle (at collarette) = branches from GIC. The Ciliary Body (6mm wide): CILIARY BODY | ├── UVEAL PORTION (adjacent to sclera) | — Lamina suprachoroidea | — Ciliary muscles (3 types of smooth muscle) | — Blood vessel layer | — Lamina vitrea | └── EPITHELIAL PORTION (adjacent to posterior chamber) | ├── PARS PLANA (4mm wide; from ora serrata to pars plicata) | — LEAST vascular → preferred surgical entry site | └── PARS PLICATA (2mm wide; ciliary processes) — 60–70 folds/processes (most vascular) — Produces aqueous humor CILIARY MUSCLES (smooth, innervated by CN3 ): ├── Longitudinal (Brücke's) — outermost; from scleral spur; bulk of muscle ├── Radial — from anterior Brücke's; oblique fibers └── Circular — innermost; parallel to lens equator; site of zonule attachment [ CONTRACTS TOGETHER → annular action → reduces ring diameter → relaxes zonules] The Choroid: CHOROID (from ora serrata to optic nerve entrance) — dark pigmented membrane; firmly adherent at optic nerve — separated from sclera by perichoroidal space of Schwalbe (contains: long PCA + 2 long ciliary nerves) Thickness: — posterior pole: 0.25mm ( THICKEST — most metabolically active) — anterior pole: 0.10mm ( THINNEST ) HISTOLOGIC LAYERS (outer to inner): 1. Lamina fusca / Suprachoroidea — collagenous + elastic fibers — contains: smooth muscle fibers, melanocytes, endothelial cells, long + short PCA , long + short ciliary nerves — interface between sclera and choroid 2. Blood vessel layer (3 sub-layers): a. Haller's layer — large anastomosing veins (outer) b. Sattler's layer — medium anastomosing veins (middle) c. Choriocapillaris (Membrane of Ruysch) — wide-bore capillaries (inner) → supplies RPE and outer retinal photoreceptors → gives 65–85% of total retinal blood flow → ischemia >1 hour = irreparable photoreceptor damage 3. Bruch's membrane (Lamina Vitrea / Lamina Basalis Choroidea) — 7 µm thick; structureless — RPE firmly adherent to its inner surface — In AMD : Bruch's membrane thickens and drusen accumulate beneath RPE\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Sphincter vs Dilator pupillae: Feature Sphincter Pupillae Dilator Pupillae Location Pupillary zone (central iris stroma) Ciliary zone (radial in iris stroma) Muscle type Circular (ring) Radial (spoke-like) Innervation Parasympathetic CN3 (short ciliary nerve) Sympathetic (long ciliary nerve) Action when contracted Miosis (constriction) Mydriasis (dilation) Drug that mimics Pilocarpine (miotic) Phenylephrine (mydriatic) Drug that blocks Atropine (cycloplegic/mydriatic) — Board clue \\\"Fight or flight dilates — rest constricts\\\" Same rule Pars plana vs Pars plicata: Feature Pars Plana Pars Plicata Width 4 mm 2 mm Location Posterior (near ora serrata) Anterior (near iris root) Vascularity Least vascular Most vascular Function Structure; surgical access zone Produces aqueous humor Surgical use Preferred entry for vitreoretinal surgery Avoids Board clue \\\"Flat and safe — surgical entry here\\\" \\\"Vascular and productive\\\" Pupillary disorders — the 4 key ones: Disorder Mechanism Lesion site Key sign Board clue Adie's (tonic) pupil Damaged parasympathetic post-ganglionic Ciliary ganglion or short ciliary nerve Slow/tonic reaction to light; responds to 0.125% pilocarpine; loss of deep tendon reflex \\\"Accommodates but reacts slowly; benign, peripheral\\\" Argyll-Robertson Central pretectal lesion blocks light reflex but spares near reflex Pretectal area (midbrain) Accommodates but doesn't react to light; small, irregular, bilateral; neurosyphilis \\\"Prostitute pupils — accommodates but doesn't react; tabes dorsalis\\\" Horner's syndrome Sympathetic pathway interruption Anywhere along 3-neuron sympathetic chain Miosis + partial ptosis (1–2mm) + anhidrosis \\\"Cocaine test: doesn't dilate in all Horner's\\\" Marcus-Gunn (RAPD) Relative afferent defect Optic nerve or severe retinal disease Pupil dilates (escapes) when light swings from normal to affected eye Swinging flashlight test — affected eye = paradoxical dilation\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Iris diameter 12 mm Reference for normal iris size Normal pupil size 3–4 mm Miosis = <2mm; mydriasis = >5mm Ciliary body width 6 mm total Pars plana (4mm) + pars plicata (2mm) Ciliary processes 60–70 folds Each secretes aqueous — drugs that reduce these reduce IOP Choroid posterior thickness 0.25 mm (thickest) Most metabolically active; first affected in choroidal ischemia Choroid anterior thickness 0.10 mm (thinnest) Near ora serrata Bruch's membrane thickness 7 µm Thickens with age and in AMD Choriocapillaris blood flow 65–85% of retinal blood flow Loss = outer retinal ischemia within 1 hour Adie's pupil — pilocarpine dose 0.125% Denervation supersensitivity — responds to very low dose Normal C/D ratio 0.3 >0.5 suspicious for glaucoma\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Uveal tract layers front to back — \\\"I Can Change\\\" Iris → Ciliary body → Choroid Ciliary muscle fibers front to inner — \\\"Long Ropes Circle\\\" Longitudinal (Brücke's) → Radial → Circular Pupillary reflex rule — \\\"PNS = Constrict; SNS = Dilate\\\" Parasympathetic (CN3) → sphincter → miosis Sympathetic → dilator → mydriasis Argyll-Robertson vs Adie's — \\\"Both accommodate but don't react\\\" Adie's: peripheral (ciliary ganglion); unilateral; benign; responds to 0.125% pilocarpine Argyll-Robertson: central (pretectal); bilateral; neurosyphilis; does NOT respond to pilocarpine Choroid layers outer to inner — \\\"Lamina Haller Sattler Chorio Bruch's\\\" Lamina fusca → Haller's → Sattler's → Choriocapillaris → Bruch's\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"IRIS CROSS-SECTION (nasal to temporal) ────────────────────────────────────── ANTERIOR BORDER LAYER (no tight junctions) ↓ ANTERIOR LIMITING MEMBRANE ↓ IRIS STROMA ├── Sphincter pupillae [ CN3 — MIOSIS ] — in pupillary zone ├── Dilator pupillae [Sympathetic — MYDRIASIS ] — in ciliary zone ├── Blood vessels (Greater iris circle = 2 long PCA + 7 ACA ) └── Pigment cells ↓ POSTERIOR PIGMENT EPITHELIUM (2 layers of melanin-packed cells) UVEAL TRACT CROSS-SECTION (front to back) ────────────────────────────────────────── [ CORNEA ] IRIS → controls pupil size (sphincter/dilator) ↓ CILIARY BODY → produces AH (pars plicata) + accommodation (muscle) ├── Pars plicata (2mm, vascular, AH production) └── Pars plana (4mm, avascular, surgical entry) ↓ CHOROID → nourishes outer retina (choriocapillaris) ├── Lamina fusca (outer) ├── Haller's → Sattler's → Choriocapillaris (inner vascular layers) └── Bruch's membrane → RPE adherent here [ RETINA ]\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Ciliary muscle contraction tightens the zonules to round the lens Ciliary contraction RELAXES the zonules. The lens rounds up on its own (elastic recoil) once tension is released. The pars plicata is used for vitreoretinal surgery access Pars plana is the surgical entry site (least vascular). Pars plicata is avoided (most vascular). Argyll-Robertson pupil is benign peripheral neuropathy Adie's is benign peripheral. Argyll-Robertson is central neurosyphilis (tabes dorsalis). Choroid is thickest at the anterior pole Thickest at the posterior pole (0.25mm). Thinnest anteriorly (0.10mm). Pilocarpine 0.125% constricts all pupils Normal pupils do not respond to this low dose. Only denervation-supersensitive pupils (Adie's) respond. The sphincter pupillae is in the ciliary zone Sphincter is in the pupillary zone (central). Dilator is in the ciliary zone (peripheral).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Uveal tract components Iris → Ciliary body → Choroid Sphincter pupillae innervation Parasympathetic CN3 (short ciliary nerve) Dilator pupillae innervation Sympathetic Ciliary body aqueous production site Pars plicata (non-pigment epithelium of ciliary processes) Surgical entry site in ciliary body Pars plana (least vascular) Ciliary muscle action in accommodation Contracts → reduces ring → relaxes zonules → lens rounds up Choroid thickest point Posterior pole (0.25 mm) Layer supplying outer retina Choriocapillaris (65–85% retinal blood flow) Layer between choroid and RPE Bruch's membrane (7 µm) Argyll-Robertson cause Neurosyphilis/tabes dorsalis; pretectal lesion Adie's cause Ciliary ganglion/short ciliary nerve damage; benign Adie's pilocarpine test dose 0.125% (denervation supersensitivity) Normal pupil size 3–4 mm Iris diameter 12 mm\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"1. A patient is asked to look at a near target. Both pupils constrict. When a bright light is shone into the right eye, neither pupil constricts, but both constrict with near gaze. The left eye shows the same pattern. Which of the following best describes this condition? A. Bilateral Adie's pupils B. Argyll-Robertson pupils C. Bilateral Marcus-Gunn pupil D. Bilateral Horner's syndrome Answer B. Argyll-Robertson pupils. Argyll-Robertson pupils are pathognomonic for neurosyphilis (tabes dorsalis). The hallmark is light-near dissociation: \\\"accommodates but does not react to light.\\\" The pretectal lesion disrupts the afferent arc of the pupillary light reflex while sparing the accommodation-convergence near reflex pathway (which travels more ventrally in the brainstem). This produces bilateral small, irregular pupils that constrict with near gaze but not with light. Bilateral Adie's is possible but would show tonic (slow) near constriction and loss of deep tendon reflexes, not the complete absence of light response. Marcus-Gunn involves a relative afferent defect — it does not cause bilateral failure of the light reflex in both eyes. 2. During a vitreoretinal surgical procedure, the surgeon enters the eye through which of the following structures to minimize bleeding risk? A. Pars plicata B. Limbus C. Pars plana D. Iris root Answer C. Pars plana. The pars plana is the posterior, flat, avascular portion of the ciliary body (4mm wide, extending from the ora serrata to the pars plicata). Its relative avascularity makes it the preferred and safest entry point for vitreoretinal surgery, reducing hemorrhage risk. The pars plicata (anterior 2mm, most vascular) contains the ciliary processes and is avoided. The limbus is used for anterior segment surgeries (e.g., cataract). The iris root is fragile and its incision would damage the angle and drainage structures.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Close the note before picking up the pen. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"UVEAL TRACT\\\" at the top. 5 minutes. Write the three components, what each does, their innervation, and two clinical consequences per structure. Circle gaps. Core targets: Ciliary muscle contraction → what happens to zonules → what happens to lens The 3 ciliary muscle fiber types in order Choroid layers (5) from sclera to retina Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the iris cross-section from anterior border layer to posterior pigment epithelium. Label where the sphincter and dilator muscles sit (which zone for each) and their nerve supply. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain accommodation to a student without using the words \\\"contraction\\\" or \\\"relax\\\" — describe it purely in terms of what tension does to the lens and what removing tension allows. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Ciliary body accommodation — which nerve? CN3 (short ciliary nerve; parasympathetic) Aqueous produced by? Non-pigment epithelium of pars plicata Pars plana vs pars plicata — surgical entry? Pars plana (least vascular) Choroid thickest? Posterior pole 0.25 mm Layer supplying outer retina? Choriocapillaris Argyll-Robertson — what disease? Neurosyphilis (tabes dorsalis) Adie's pilocarpine dose? 0.125% (denervation supersensitivity) Sphincter muscle zone? Pupillary zone (central) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete accommodation pathway: from the retinal blur stimulus through the neural pathway to the ciliary muscle, through the zonular and lens mechanics, to the final focused near image. Every step. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Blank Diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (accommodation) 4th 1 week Full accommodation sequence Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-04-uveal-tract-iris-ciliary-body-choroid-extended-topics-anterior-chamber-angle-and-posterior-chamber\",\"heading\":\"Extended Topics: Anterior Chamber, Angle, and Posterior Chamber\",\"topic\":\"A2-04 — Uveal Tract: Iris, Ciliary Body, and Choroid\",\"text\":\"Anterior Chamber (5.11): ANTERIOR CHAMBER Location: Between cornea (front) and iris/pupil (back) Shape: Biconvex space Volume: Total: 0.20–0.25 mL Central portion (deepest): 3 mm deep Peripheral portion: shallowest Contents: Aqueous humor Index of refraction: 1.336 BOUNDARIES : Anterior: Corneal endothelium + Descemet's membrane Posterior: Anterior face of iris + lens (through pupil) Periphery: The angle (trabecular meshwork) THE ANGLE (iridocorneal angle): — The drainage site of aqueous humor — Contains: trabecular meshwork → Schlemm's canal → episcleral veins — Gonioscopy landmarks (anterior to posterior): Schwalbe's line → Trabecular meshwork → Scleral spur → Ciliary body band → Peripheral iris Why the angle matters: Aqueous flows from posterior chamber → through the pupil → into anterior chamber → drains at the angle. Open-angle glaucoma occurs when TM resistance increases without angle closure. Angle-closure glaucoma occurs when iris physically blocks the angle, preventing drainage entirely. The difference in these two mechanisms drives their completely different management. Posterior Chamber (5.14): POSTERIOR CHAMBER Location: Between posterior iris surface and anterior lens + zonules + anterior vitreous face Volume: 0.06 mL (much smaller than anterior chamber) Boundaries: Anterior: Posterior iris surface Posterior: Anterior lens capsule + zonular fibers Lateral: Ciliary body processes (pars plicata) Contents: Aqueous humor (produced here by ciliary processes) Flow path: Produced in posterior chamber → through pupil → anterior chamber → angle → drainage Clinical significance: Posterior synechiae (iris-to-lens adhesions from uveitis) can seal the pupil and block aqueous flow from posterior to anterior chamber → iris bombé (iris bows forward) → secondary angle-closure glaucoma. This is the mechanism that makes anterior uveitis management urgent. Numbers added: Structure Measurement Significance AC depth (central) 3 mm Shallow AC = risk for angle closure AC volume 0.20–0.25 mL Reference PC volume 0.06 mL Site of AH production AH index of refraction 1.336 Same as vitreous\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"The lens is a living, transparent, protein-packed structure with no blood vessels and no nerve supply — it survives entirely on the aqueous humor bathing it. It changes shape to focus near objects, a process that progressively fails as the lens stiffens with age (presbyopia). Behind the lens sits the vitreous, a gel that fills most of the eyeball, holds the retina against the back wall, and maintains the globe's shape. Aqueous humor is the clear fluid produced in the posterior chamber by the ciliary body, which then flows through the pupil into the anterior chamber and drains out through the trabecular meshwork. It is not the same as vitreous — aqueous is a flowing, replenishable fluid that nourishes the avascular structures at the front of the eye. When its drainage is obstructed, pressure rises and glaucoma results. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does the posterior surface of the lens have greater curvature than the anterior?\\\" The answer connects refractive power distribution, accommodation mechanics, and why cataract surgery involves approaching from the front.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Why does the lens become presbyopic with age? Because the lens fibers keep forming throughout life — new ones are added at the periphery, pushing older ones toward the center. Why does that cause presbyopia? Because the older central fibers compress, harden, and lose elasticity. The harder the nucleus, the less the lens can round up when the zonules relax. Why can't the lens reverse this? Because the lens has no blood vessels and no way to remove or remodel old fibers. Every fiber formed stays for life. By age 45, the accumulated central mass is stiff enough that accommodation amplitude is functionally insufficient for near work. Why does aqueous humor need to flow continuously? Because it is the only nutrition source for the avascular cornea and lens. It carries glucose and oxygen in and removes metabolic waste. Stagnant aqueous would quickly exhaust the supply and starve both structures. Why does obstructed outflow cause glaucoma specifically? Because IOP is a balance between production rate and outflow resistance. The ciliary body keeps producing AH at a constant rate regardless of pressure. If outflow is blocked, pressure keeps rising. Above a certain IOP, the optic nerve axons at the lamina cribrosa are mechanically compressed — the axons die, the ganglion cells die, and visual field is permanently lost.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Crystalline lens Latin crystallinus — crystal-clear The transparent biconvex structure behind the iris Zonule of Zinn Named after anatomist Johann Gottfried Zinn The suspensory ligament of the lens — 140 delicate fiber bundles from the ciliary body to the lens capsule Presbyopia Greek presbys — old man + ops — eye Age-related loss of accommodation due to lens nuclear hardening Capsule Latin capsula — small container The smooth acellular envelope surrounding the entire lens Cataract Latin/Greek — waterfall (describing cloudy vision) Opacification of the lens — any disruption of the regular protein arrangement causes scattering Vitreous Latin vitreus — glassy The clear gel filling the posterior 4/5 of the eyeball Muscae volitantes Latin — flying flies Vitreous floaters; opacities from remnants of the hyaloid system Hyaloid canal (Cloquet's canal) Greek hyalos — glass + eidos — form The remnant canal of the hyaloid artery running through the vitreous Deturgescence Latin — to de-swell Active dehydration of the corneal stroma by endothelial pumping Episceral venous pressure Epi — upon + scleral vein Normal ~10 mmHg; if elevated (Sturge-Weber, carotid-cavernous fistula), IOP rises without increased AH production\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Aqueous humor circulation — the full cycle: PRODUCTION : Non-pigment epithelium of pars plicata (ciliary processes) → 3 mechanisms: ultrafiltration + Na-K ATPase secretion + carbonic anhydrase → Rate: 2 µL/min FLOW PATH : Posterior chamber (formed in pars plicata) ↓ (flows through pupil) Anterior chamber ↓ (reaches angle at limbus) Trabecular meshwork (filters AH) — 80% of outflow ↓ Schlemm's canal ↓ Episcleral veins → systemic venous circulation UVEOSCLERAL OUTFLOW : 20% via space of Schwalbe and ciliary muscle space → Absorbed into suprachoroidal space IOP balance equation: IOP = AH production rate ÷ AH outflow facility + episcleral venous pressure Normal IOP : 10–21 mmHg (fluctuates 2–5 mmHg daily; highest in AM) IOP RISES when: → AH production increases → Outflow resistance increases (TM blockade = open-angle glaucoma) → Outflow path physically blocked (iris touches TM = angle-closure glaucoma) → Episcleral venous pressure rises IOP FALLS when: → Production reduced ( CAI drugs = acetazolamide; beta-blockers = timolol) → Outflow improved (prostaglandins increase uveoscleral outflow) → Osmotic agents draw water out (mannitol IV) Lens protein structure and cataract formation: Normal lens: Crystallins (lens proteins) in regular arrangement → Low molecular weight proteins → Regular spacing → transparent (like corneal collagen) Cataract formation: Any of these disrupts the arrangement: a. Oxidative damage to crystallins (aging, UV) b. Metabolic disruption (diabetes → sorbitol accumulation in lens → osmotic swelling) c. Trauma → disrupts capsule → aqueous enters → lens proteins hydrate and scatter light d. Drug-induced (steroids → posterior subcapsular cataract) e. Congenital (rubella → nuclear/perinuclear opacity)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"The crystalline lens: LENS (biconvex; 9–10mm diameter; 4–5mm thick) Anterior pole RC = 10mm | Posterior pole RC = 6mm (Posterior surface has GREATER curvature — more convex) STRUCTURES (outside to center): 1. LENS CAPSULE (acellular; thickest BM in body) Anterior: 15µm (thickest at periphery = 18.2µm — site of zonule attachment) Posterior: 2.2µm (thinnest) 2. LENS EPITHELIUM Anterior only: single row of cuboidal cells → At equator: become columnar → elongate into LENS FIBERS (Posterior epithelium: only during development) 3. LENS FIBERS — Long prismatic 6-sided bands (albuminoid material) — Newest fibers: outermost (cortex) — Old fibers: compressed centrally → form NUCLEUS — Onion-like layered arrangement (concentric) 4. LENS NUCLEUS — Old, compressed, sclerosed lens fibers — Increasing nuclear mass = decreasing accommodation = presbyopia Optical values of the lens: Property Value Note Refractive power at rest 10–15 D (avg ~20D total) Less than cornea but variable (accommodation) Index of refraction (central) 1.43 Higher than periphery = gradient index optics Index of refraction (peripheral) 1.386 Gradient helps reduce spherical aberration Water content 65% Much less than cornea (78%) — less flexible as age adds proteins Protein content 30–35% Highest protein content of any tissue in the body The vitreous: VITREOUS (fills posterior 4/5 of eyeball) Total volume: 4.5 mL | 80% gel + 20% liquid (50% liquid in aging) Composition: water 98.5%, collagen fibrils, hyaluronic acid (gel property), electrolytes, vitrein, hyalocytes (macrophages) STRUCTURES : Fossa patellaris/lenticularis — saucer-shaped depression anteriorly matching posterior lens curvature — vitreous fits here like a contact lens fits the cornea Limiting membrane (vitreous cortex) — condensation of vitreous gel; present everywhere except: a. Zonular cleft (where zonules cross) b. Area of Martegiani (at optic disc) | ├── Anterior hyaloid | — starts 2mm from ora serrata | — attached to posterior lens capsule by hyaloideo-capsular ligament | └── Posterior hyaloid — from zonular cleft to area of Martegiani — attached to ILM of retina by collagenous fibers Hyaloid canal (Cloquet's canal) — remnant of hyaloid artery — starts at optic disc (area of Martegiani — funnel-shaped) — passes as 1–2mm narrow canal through vitreous — expands anteriorly in fossa lenticularis — Muscae volitantes: opacities from remnants of hyaloid system = vitreous floaters\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Aqueous humor vs Vitreous humor: Feature Aqueous Humor Vitreous Humor Location Anterior + posterior chambers Posterior chamber (vitreous chamber) Volume AC: 0.20–0.25 mL; PC: 0.06 mL 4.5 mL (largest compartment) Consistency Clear fluid; constantly flowing Clear gel; not replaced Production site Non-pigment epithelium (pars plicata) Formed during development; not produced in adult Functions Nourish cornea/lens; maintain IOP; maintain corneal shape Distend eyeball; hold retina in position; maintain focal distance Water content 98.1% 98.5% Replaced if lost Yes — produced continuously No — vitreous loss = replaced by aqueous (not same properties) Board clue \\\"The river\\\" — always flowing, always renewed \\\"The gel cushion\\\" — set in development, degenerates with age Anterior vs Posterior lens capsule: Feature Anterior Capsule Posterior Capsule Thickness 15 µm (up to 18.2 µm at periphery) 2.2 µm (thinnest) Role Basement membrane of anterior epithelium Basement membrane of posterior epithelium (absent in adult) Thickest BM in body? Yes — anterior lens capsule No Surgical importance Site of capsulorhexis in cataract surgery Preserved intact in extracapsular extraction (holds IOL) Zonule attachment At periphery of anterior capsule At posterior capsule\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Normal IOP 10–21 mmHg Above 21 = ocular hypertension; IOP fluctuates highest in AM AH flow rate 2 µL/min Used in calculating outflow facility Anterior chamber volume 0.20–0.25 mL Small — explains rapid IOP rise with minimal obstruction Posterior chamber volume 0.06 mL Very small; AH formed here, exits through pupil Episcleral venous pressure ~10 mmHg Floor IOP cannot fall below this without obstruction Trabecular outflow 80% of AH Site of resistance in POAG Uveoscleral outflow 20% Prostaglandins work here Vitreous volume 4.5 mL Largest intraocular compartment Vitreous gel fraction 80% (becomes 50% in aging) Syneresis = gel liquefies with age → floaters, PVD risk Lens diameter 9–10 mm Increases throughout life (never stops growing) Lens thickness 4–5 mm Increases with age and accommodation Anterior capsule thickness 15 µm Thickest BM in body Posterior capsule thickness 2.2 µm Thinnest capsule — easily torn in surgery Lens refractive power 10–15 D at rest; up to ~34D maximally Adds to corneal power; total system ~60D\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Aqueous humor flow — \\\"Post Chambers Pupil Anterior Trabecular Schlemm Episcleral\\\" (PCPATS-E) Posterior chamber → Pupil → Anterior chamber → Trabecular meshwork → Schlemm's canal → Episcleral veins IOP formula concept — \\\"Production minus Outflow plus Veins\\\" IOP ∝ (AH production) / (outflow facility) + episcleral venous pressure Lens capsule rule — \\\"Front is fat, Back is thin\\\" Anterior capsule (15–18µm) >> Posterior capsule (2.2µm) Lens layers from outside to center — \\\"Cap Epi Fiber Nuc\\\" Capsule → Epithelium → Fibers (cortex) → Nucleus Why lens proteins cause cataract — \\\"Same as cornea stroma story\\\" When protein arrangement is disrupted (by oxidation, osmotic stress, trauma), proteins aggregate and scatter light — the same principle as edematous corneal stroma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"LENS CROSS-SECTION ────────────────── ANTERIOR POLE (RC = 10mm, less curved) CAPSULE (15 µm ant; 2.2 µm post) EPITHELIUM (single cuboidal layer — anterior only) CORTEX (newest lens fibers; softest) NUCLEUS (oldest fibers; compressed; hardest) CORTEX CAPSULE POSTERIOR POLE (RC = 6mm, more curved) AQUEOUS HUMOR CIRCULATION ────────────────────────── [Ciliary process (pars plicata)] → Produces AH ↓ POSTERIOR CHAMBER (0.06 mL) ↓ [through PUPIL ] ↓ ANTERIOR CHAMBER (0.20–0.25 mL) ↓ [reaches angle] ├── 80% → Trabecular meshwork → Schlemm's canal → Episcleral veins └── 20% → Uveoscleral outflow (ciliary muscle space) VITREOUS ───────── POSTERIOR LENS CAPSULE ← Fossa patellaris (depression where vitreous fits) ← Anterior hyaloid (attached to posterior lens capsule) VITREOUS GEL (4.5 mL) [Hyaloid canal runs through center from disc to lens] ← Posterior hyaloid (attached to ILM of retina) RETINA ( ILM )\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"The anterior lens capsule is thinnest Posterior capsule (2.2µm) is thinnest. Anterior (15µm) is thickest — and is the thickest basement membrane in the body. Aqueous and vitreous are the same fluid Aqueous is a clear flowing fluid produced continuously; vitreous is a gel formed during development and not replaced. Different compositions, locations, and functions. IOP is maintained by the vitreous IOP is maintained by aqueous humor production and outflow balance. Vitreous contributes to globe shape but not to IOP dynamics. The posterior lens surface is less curved than the anterior Posterior RC = 6mm (more curved/steeper). Anterior RC = 10mm (less curved/flatter). Greater curvature = more refractive power. Uveoscleral outflow accounts for 80% of AH drainage Trabecular outflow = 80%. Uveoscleral = 20%. Prostaglandins increase uveoscleral outflow. Presbyopia is due to ciliary muscle weakness Presbyopia is due to nuclear hardening of the lens. The ciliary muscle may still work; the lens simply cannot respond because it has lost elasticity.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Aqueous production site Non-pigment epithelium of pars plicata (ciliary processes) AH flow rate 2 µL/min Trabecular outflow % 80% (primary drainage) Uveoscleral outflow % 20% Normal IOP range 10–21 mmHg Episcleral venous pressure ~10 mmHg (IOP floor) Vitreous volume 4.5 mL Vitreous composition 98.5% water; hyaluronic acid gives gel property Lens refractive power at rest 10–15 D Anterior capsule thickness 15 µm (thickest BM in body) Posterior capsule thickness 2.2 µm (thinnest) Presbyopia mechanism Lens nuclear hardening; old fibers compress centrally Hyaloid canal Remnant of hyaloid artery; Cloquet's canal; area of Martegiani at disc end Muscae volitantes Vitreous floaters; remnants of hyaloid system Why lens is avascular Blood vessels would obstruct the optical path\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"1. A 55-year-old patient has had increasing difficulty reading. Their distance vision remains 20/20. Amplitude of accommodation measures +0.5D. Which of the following is the primary mechanism? A. Ciliary muscle atrophy reducing zonular tension B. Posterior displacement of the lens reducing its refractive power C. Progressive hardening of the lens nucleus reducing elastic recoil D. Zonule degeneration preventing transmission of ciliary muscle force Answer C. Progressive hardening of the lens nucleus reducing elastic recoil. Presbyopia develops because the lens adds new fibers throughout life, compressing older fibers centrally into an increasingly hard nucleus. The nucleus loses its elasticity. Even when the ciliary muscle contracts and releases zonular tension, the stiff nucleus cannot round up sufficiently to increase power for near focus. The ciliary muscle itself remains functional in early presbyopia — the problem is purely in the lens. Zonule degeneration does not typically cause presbyopia; subluxation (e.g., Marfan's) causes different problems. Posterior lens displacement would reduce accommodation range but is not the primary mechanism of presbyopia. 2. Which of the following most accurately describes the composition of aqueous humor relative to plasma? A. Higher protein content than plasma B. Higher ascorbic acid concentration than plasma C. Lower osmolarity than plasma D. Higher glucose concentration than plasma Answer B. Higher ascorbic acid concentration than plasma. Aqueous humor is actively secreted — not just a filtrate of plasma — so certain components are concentrated above plasma levels. Ascorbic acid (vitamin C) is actively pumped into the AH at concentrations 15–20× higher than plasma. It serves as an antioxidant protecting the lens and cornea from oxidative damage. Protein content is very low (25 mg% vs. plasma ~7000 mg%) — the blood-aqueous barrier restricts protein entry, keeping AH optically clear. Osmolarity is slightly higher than plasma (not lower). Glucose is present at about 2.5 mg% in AH — lower than plasma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-05-lens-vitreous-aqueous-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-05 — Lens, Vitreous, and Aqueous Humor\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"LENS, VITREOUS, AQUEOUS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: AH flow pathway, IOP range, lens layers, presbyopia mechanism, vitreous composition and structures. Circle gaps. Core targets: Complete AH pathway from production to drainage (every stop) Lens layers from capsule to nucleus Three mechanisms of AH formation Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the aqueous humor flow pathway from the ciliary process to the episcleral vein. Label every structure. Mark the 80/20 outflow split. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain why presbyopia worsens progressively with age without using the words \\\"hardening\\\" or \\\"stiffness\\\" — explain it in terms of what the lens is physically doing over decades. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back AH production site? Non-pigment epi of pars plicata Normal IOP range? 10–21 mmHg Trabecular outflow? 80% Anterior capsule thickness? 15 µm (thickest BM in body) Vitreous volume? 4.5 mL Hyaloid canal also called? Cloquet's canal Vitreous floaters? Muscae volitantes Presbyopia cause? Nuclear hardening (old fibers compress centrally) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the IOP balance mechanism: what happens to IOP if (a) trabecular meshwork is blocked; (b) ciliary body is over-active; (c) episcleral venous pressure rises; (d) prostaglandin is administered. For each, name the drug class used to treat the first two. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow AH pathway diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (presbyopia) 4th 1 week IOP scenario sequence Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"The retina is the brain's outpost in the eye — 11 layers of specialized neural tissue that convert light into electrical signals. The outermost layer (RPE) absorbs stray light and maintains the photoreceptors. The photoreceptors themselves sit in layer 2: rods for low-light monochrome vision, cones for color and detail. Three layers of neurons (photoreceptors → bipolar cells → ganglion cells) form the signal chain, and the ganglion cell axons leave the eye as the optic nerve. The fovea is the point of highest acuity — packed with cones, stripped of other neurons that would scatter light. The optic disc is where the optic nerve exits — it has no photoreceptors, making it the physiologic blind spot. The whole retina has no pain fibers, which is why retinal disease presents as painless vision loss. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why is the fovea both the thinnest retinal area AND the point of highest vision?\\\" The paradox resolves when you understand that the other neurons are displaced to the rim (parafovea), leaving a clear path for light to hit the densely packed cones directly.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Why are rods concentrated peripherally and cones centrally? Because rods specialize in detecting dim light and motion across a wide area — peripheral warning detection. Cones specialize in high-acuity color detail — central fixation. The eye evolved two separate systems for two separate jobs. Why is the fovea both the thinnest retinal area and the sharpest point of vision? Because the bipolar and ganglion cells that normally stack on top of the photoreceptors are displaced to the foveal rim (parafovea) — a lateral displacement that creates a clear optical path. Fewer overlying neurons = less light scatter = maximum acuity at the center. Why is the optic disc a blind spot? Because axons exit here and blood vessels enter — there is no room for photoreceptors. Every healthy retina has this blind spot. The brain fills it in using information from the surrounding retina and the other eye. Why does the retina detach between the RPE and photoreceptors, not between the RPE and choroid? Because the RPE and Bruch's membrane are firmly adherent. But the bond between the RPE and photoreceptors is only maintained by osmotic forces and interdigitation — there is no tight junction. This is the embryological split plane where the two layers of the optic cup joined. It remains a potential space throughout life.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Retina Latin rete — net The neural net at the back of the eye Macula lutea Latin — yellow spot The central retinal area; yellow due to xanthophyll (lutein, zeaxanthin) Fovea centralis Latin fovea — pit The central pit/depression in the macula; thinnest retina; highest acuity Foveola Latin — small pit The central 0.4mm of the fovea; pure cones; capillary-free zone Parafovea Latin para — beside The rim of the fovea; thickest retinal area (ganglion cells displaced here, 5–7 layers) Ora serrata Latin — serrated mouth The scalloped anterior edge of the retina where it transitions to ciliary epithelium Photoreceptor Greek photos — light + Latin receptor The rods and cones; convert light to electrical signals RPE Retinal Pigment Epithelium Single layer of pigmented cells; outermost retinal layer; absorbs light, maintains photoreceptors Ganglion cell Latin ganglion — knot 3rd-order neurons; axons form the optic nerve Rhodopsin Greek rhodon — rose + opsis — sight The visual pigment of rods; bleached by light; regenerated in dark Optic disc Latin discus — round The head of the optic nerve as it exits the eye; blind spot Lamina cribrosa Latin — sieve-like plate The perforated scleral area through which optic nerve fibers exit; critical pressure point in glaucoma C/D ratio Cup-to-disc ratio Ratio of physiologic cup to optic disc diameter; normal ≤0.3; elevated in glaucoma\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Signal transduction — how light becomes an electrical impulse: LIGHT ENTERS EYE ↓ Passes through all retinal layers (retina is inverted — receptors face backward) ↓ Reaches PHOTORECEPTORS (rods or cones) ↓ PHOTON absorbed by visual pigment Rods: Rhodopsin (opsin + 11-cis retinal) → bleaches to all-trans retinal Cones: Cone opsins (3 types) → similar bleaching process ↓ Bleaching triggers cascade: cGMP drops → ion channels close → hyperpolarization ↓ Reduced glutamate release from photoreceptor terminal ↓ BIPOLAR CELLS (1st synapse — outer plexiform layer) ↓ GANGLION CELLS (2nd synapse — inner plexiform layer) ↓ Axons exit via OPTIC DISC → OPTIC NERVE → brain DARK ADAPTATION : Rhodopsin regenerated from all-trans retinal (needs vitamin A as precursor) Rods adapt more slowly (20 min full dark adaptation) but achieve greater sensitivity Cones adapt faster but plateau at much lower sensitivity The fovea — why it is simultaneously thinnest and clearest: PERIPHERAL RETINA : FOVEA : All 11 layers present Layers 2–9 present; bipolar + ganglion cells DISPLACED Ganglion cells: 1 layer Ganglion cells displaced to foveal rim (parafovea) Mixed rods + cones CONES ONLY (hexagonal mosaic packing) Lower acuity Maximum acuity Well-vascularized AVASCULAR (foveal avascular zone) Thicker THINNEST (0.1mm at center) Parafovea = THICKEST (ganglion cells 5–7 layers deep) Why this matters: In macular disease (AMD, diabetic macular edema), central acuity is lost first because the cones at the fovea are compromised. Peripheral vision (rods) is preserved longer. In retinitis pigmentosa, the opposite — peripheral rod loss first, tunnel vision early, central cone loss late.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"The 11 Retinal Layers — from RPE to vitreous (outer to inner): Layer 1: RPE (Retinal Pigment Epithelium) — single layer, brown columnar cells, melanin — FIRMLY adherent to Bruch's membrane (choroid side) — LOOSELY adherent to photoreceptors (potential space = retinal detachment plane) — nourishes photoreceptors; phagocytoses shed outer segments Layer 2: Photoreceptor layer (Rods and Cones) Rods: 507nm (scotopic); rhodopsin; peripheral; ~120 million Cones: 3 pigments (R:750nm, G:535nm, B:440nm); central; ~6 million Layer 3: External limiting membrane ( ELM ) — fenestrated net; outer end of Müller's fibers — rod and cone fibers pass through its holes Layer 4: Outer nuclear layer ( ONL ) — cell bodies (nuclei) of rods and cones Layer 5: Fibers of Henle — thin; rod and cone fiber axons without nuclei — star-burst pattern in macular edema (fluid spreads along Henle's fibers) Layer 6: Outer plexiform layer ( OPL ) — SYNAPSE 1: photoreceptors ↔ bipolar + horizontal cells Layer 7: Inner nuclear layer ( INL ) — bipolar cells (connect photoreceptors to ganglion cells) — horizontal cells (lateral inhibition; sharpens contrast) — amacrine cells (dopamine; inhibitory modulation) — Müller cells (glial support; mechanical + metabolic functions) Layer 8: Inner plexiform layer ( IPL ) — SYNAPSE 2: bipolar + amacrine cells ↔ ganglion cells Layer 9: Ganglion cell layer ( GCL ) — 3rd-order neurons; 5–7 layers at fovea (parafovea = thickest retina) — single layer at periphery — lost progressively in glaucoma Layer 10: Nerve fiber layer ( NFL ) — axons of ganglion cells running to optic disc — measured by OCT ; thins with glaucoma Layer 11: Internal limiting membrane ( ILM ) — condensed inner surface of Müller cells — vitreous adheres here Mnemonic for 11 layers (outer to inner): \\\"Really Pretty Elderly Ones Feel Older Personal Inner Glances Never Improve\\\" RPE → Photoreceptors → ELM → ONL → (Henle) → OPL → INL → IPL → GCL → NFL → ILM Retinal regions and their key features: Region Diameter Photoreceptors Special Features Macula lutea 4.5 mm Mainly cones Yellow (xanthophyll: lutein, zeaxanthin) Fovea centralis 1.5 mm Cones only at center; rods at rim Thinnest retina; highest acuity; no blood vessels in central portion Foveola 0.4 mm Cones only (hexagonal mosaic) Capillary-free zone; maximum acuity; no rods Parafovea Foveal rim Cones + displaced bipolars + ganglion cells THICKEST retina (ganglion cells 5–7 layers) Ora serrata 6 mm from limbus None (transitions to ciliary epithelium) Scalloped; anterior retinal terminus Optic disc 1.5 mm NONE Physiologic blind spot; ganglion axons exit here The optic nerve head and disc: OPTIC DISC (1.5mm diameter) — Pale pink: capillaries present — Located 3mm (2 disc diameters) nasal to macula, 0.8mm above foveola — No photoreceptors = physiologic blind spot — Contains axons of ganglion cells PHYSIOLOGIC CUP — Central funnel-shaped depression — Whiter than disc (fewer vessels → sclera visible through it) — Normal C/D ratio: ≤0.3 — C/D ratio >0.5: suspicious for glaucoma — Cup enlarges as ganglion cell axons die (glaucomatous cupping) LAMINA CRIBROSA — Sieve-like plate of sclera through which axons exit — In elevated IOP : lamina bows backward, compressing axons — Critical pathophysiology of glaucomatous optic neuropathy Carotenoids and their clinical significance: XANTHOPHYLLS (yellow pigments in cone nerve fibers): 1. Lutein 2. Zeaxanthin 3. Meso-zeaxanthin (from lutein) → Absence linked to AMD (age-related macular degeneration) → AREDS2 supplement contains lutein + zeaxanthin CAROTENES : α-carotene, β-carotene (in carrots), lycopene (precursor of β-carotene)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Rods vs Cones: Feature Rods Cones Number ~120 million ~6 million Visual pigment Rhodopsin (507 nm peak) 3 types: R(750nm), G(535nm), B(440nm) Vision type Scotopic (dim light, monochrome) Photopic (bright light, color, acuity) Distribution Peripheral retina Central retina (dense at fovea) Convergence Many rods → 1 bipolar cell 1 cone → 1 bipolar cell (at fovea) Dark adaptation Slow (20 min); more sensitive Fast; less sensitive Nyctalopia (night blindness) Rod dysfunction Not involved Board clue \\\"Sensitive, not selective\\\" \\\"Selective, not as sensitive\\\" Direct vs Indirect ophthalmoscopy: Feature Direct Indirect Image Virtual and erect Real and inverted Field of view 10 degrees 37 degrees (20D lens) Magnification 15× 5× (12D lens) Working distance 1–2 cm Arm's length Stereopsis None Excellent Fundus area visible Between equator and ora serrata NOT visible Between equator and ora serrata visible Maximum resolving power 70 µm 20 µm Board clue \\\"Close up but limited view\\\" \\\"Wider field, inverted, better for periphery\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Retinal thickness 0.1–0.5 mm Thinnest at foveola; thickest at parafovea Macula diameter 4.5 mm Contains the central 4.5mm around fovea Fovea diameter 1.5 mm Pit; thinnest retina; highest acuity Foveola diameter 0.4 mm Capillary-free; pure cones in hexagonal mosaic Optic disc diameter 1.5 mm Same as fovea — easy to compare on fundus exam Optic disc location 3mm (2 DD) nasal to macula, 0.8mm above foveola Standard landmark for fundus examination Normal C/D ratio ≤0.3 >0.5 suspicious; >0.8 = very likely glaucoma Ora serrata location 6 mm from limbus Anterior retinal terminus Rod count ~120 million Distributed peripherally Cone count ~6 million Concentrated centrally; fovea has highest density Rod peak wavelength 507 nm Green light = scotopic peak Choriocapillaris blood flow 65–85% of retinal supply Outer retinal ischemia in 1 hour\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"11 retinal layers (outer to inner) — \\\"Really Pretty Elderly Ones Feel Older Personal Inner Glances Never Improve\\\" RPE → Photoreceptors → ELM → ONL → (Henle) → OPL → INL → IPL → GCL → NFL → ILM Detachment plane rule — \\\"RPE-Bruch's is forever; RPE-photoreceptor can split\\\" RPE is glued to Bruch's membrane (choroid side) — does not separate. RPE-photoreceptor junction is the retinal detachment plane. Fovea paradox — \\\"Thinnest = clearest because neurons moved out of the way\\\" Displaced bipolars/ganglion cells at parafovea = clear path for light to cones. Xanthophylls protect macular cones — \\\"Lutein and Zeaxanthin = Yellow Shield\\\" These yellow carotenoids absorb high-energy blue light before it damages the cones. Their absence = AMD risk. AREDS2 supplementation. Rods and cones convergence — \\\"Many rods share; each cone alone\\\" Multiple peripheral rods converge onto single bipolar (sensitivity but no acuity). Each foveal cone has its own dedicated bipolar (acuity but lower sensitivity).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"RETINAL LAYERS (cross-section, outer to inner) ──────────────────────────────────────────────── CHOROID / BRUCH 'S MEMBRANE (firmly adherent) ────── RPE (single layer; absorbs light; maintains PR) ──────── LAYER 1 ┆ [ RETINAL DETACHMENT PLANE — loose bond here] ──── PHOTORECEPTORS (rods 120M, cones 6M) ──────────────────── LAYER 2 ──── ELM (Müller fiber ends) ───────────────────────────────── LAYER 3 ──── ONL (nuclei of rods/cones) ────────────────────────────── LAYER 4 ──── HENLE 'S FIBERS (axons of PR without nuclei) ───────────── LAYER 5 ──── OPL (synapse 1: PR ↔ bipolar) ─────────────────────────── LAYER 6 ──── INL (bipolar, horizontal, amacrine, Müller) ───────────── LAYER 7 ──── IPL (synapse 2: bipolar ↔ ganglion) ───────────────────── LAYER 8 ──── GCL (5–7 layers at foveal rim; 1 layer at periphery) ──── LAYER 9 ──── NFL (ganglion axons heading to optic disc) ─────────────── LAYER 10 ──── ILM (vitreous adheres here) ───────────────────────────── LAYER 11 VITREOUS FOVEA MAP ────────────── ← → 1.5mm fovea ← → parafovea | foveal rim | FOVEOLA (0.4mm) | foveal rim | parafovea THICKEST displaced GC THINNEST displaced GC THICKEST 6 layers GC pure cones 6 layers GC AVASCULAR OPTIC DISC ─────────── 3mm nasal to macula; 0.8mm above foveola 1.5mm diameter; pale pink [ LAMINA CRIBROSA ] — axons pass through here [ CUP ] — whiter, central; normal C/D ≤0.3 No photoreceptors = PHYSIOLOGIC BLIND SPOT\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"The fovea is the thickest part of the retina The PARAFOVEA is thickest (displaced ganglion cells). The fovea itself (foveola) is the thinnest. Retinal detachment separates the RPE from Bruch's membrane Detachment separates the photoreceptors from the RPE. The RPE-Bruch's bond is firm. Rods are concentrated at the fovea The foveola has NO rods — cones only. Rods are peripheral. The optic disc contains rods for low-light vision The optic disc has NO photoreceptors — it is the physiologic blind spot. Retinal pain signals warn of disease The retina has no pain fibers. Retinal diseases present as painless vision loss, which is why they are often detected late. The inner retinal layers are supplied by the choroid Choriocapillaris supplies only the outer retina (RPE and photoreceptors). The inner layers are supplied by the CRA (4 branches). Normal C/D ratio is 0.5 Normal is ≤0.3. C/D of 0.5 is suspicious. 0.8 is highly concerning for glaucoma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer 11 retinal layers (outer to inner) RPE, Photoreceptors, ELM, ONL, Henle, OPL, INL, IPL, GCL, NFL, ILM Retinal detachment plane Between RPE and photoreceptors Fovea diameter 1.5 mm Foveola diameter 0.4 mm (pure cones; capillary-free) Thickest retinal area Parafovea (displaced ganglion cells 5–7 layers) Thinnest retinal area Foveola Optic disc location 3mm nasal to macula, 0.8mm above foveola Normal C/D ratio ≤0.3 Physiologic blind spot Optic disc (no photoreceptors) Ora serrata location 6 mm from limbus Rod visual pigment Rhodopsin (507 nm) Cone wavelengths R:750nm, G:535nm, B:440nm Outer retinal blood supply Choriocapillaris (65–85%) Inner retinal blood supply Central retinal artery (4 branches) Xanthophylls in macula Lutein + zeaxanthin (AREDS2) Retinal innervation None (painless blindness)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"1. A patient with advanced glaucoma retains central vision but has complete loss of peripheral visual field. Which retinal cells are most directly responsible for the peripheral field loss? A. Foveal cones B. Peripheral rods and their associated ganglion cells C. RPE cells at the ora serrata D. Bipolar cells at the inner nuclear layer Answer B. Peripheral rods and their associated ganglion cells. Glaucoma damages retinal ganglion cells — specifically their axons at the lamina cribrosa where elevated IOP compresses them. The peripheral ganglion cells (associated with peripheral rods for peripheral field) are more vulnerable and lost earlier in glaucoma. This produces the classic arcuate scotoma and nasal step pattern, eventually leaving only a central island of vision (tunnel vision from surviving foveal cone-ganglion pathways). The foveal cones themselves are among the last to be affected because the foveal area has a relative abundance of ganglion cells and better vascular supply. RPE cells and bipolar cells are not the primary site of glaucomatous damage. 2. On fundus examination, the optic disc measures 1.5mm and the cup measures 0.7mm in diameter. Which of the following is most accurate? A. Normal finding — within accepted range B. C/D ratio of 0.47 — borderline suspicious for glaucoma C. C/D ratio of 0.47 — normal D. C/D ratio of 0.7 — very concerning for glaucomatous cupping Answer B. C/D ratio of 0.47 — borderline suspicious for glaucoma. C/D ratio = cup diameter ÷ disc diameter = 0.7 ÷ 1.5 = 0.47. Normal C/D is ≤0.3. A ratio of 0.47 is above normal and warrants further evaluation — IOP measurement, visual field testing, and OCT of the nerve fiber layer. It is suspicious but not necessarily diagnostic. Option D calculates incorrectly (0.7 would be the cup diameter, not the ratio). A C/D >0.5 with asymmetry >0.2 between the two eyes raises high concern for glaucoma. 3. A patient presents with sudden painless vision loss, a pale swollen retina, and a cherry-red spot at the fovea. Which vascular event explains the cherry-red spot? A. Foveal hemorrhage from a branch retinal vein occlusion B. Choroidal ischemia exposing the bare sclera at the macula C. Inner retinal edema rendering all areas opaque except the thin foveola, which remains transparent over the patent choriocapillaris D. RPE detachment at the macula revealing Bruch's membrane Answer C. Inner retinal edema rendering all areas opaque except the thin foveola, which remains transparent over the patent choriocapillaris. In central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO), the inner retina (supplied by the CRA) becomes ischemic and edematous — the swollen cells make the retina appear pale and opaque. However, the fovea (specifically the foveola) is extremely thin — it lacks ganglion cells and inner nuclear cells. At the foveola, the transparent inner retina is so thin that the underlying choroid (still perfused by the short posterior ciliary arteries, which are not affected by CRAO) shows through as a red color against the pale surrounding retina. This contrast creates the cherry-red spot. Option B is incorrect — the choroid is NOT ischemic in CRAO. Option D (RPE detachment) is a different pathology. Option A (vein occlusion) causes flame hemorrhages, not cherry-red spot.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"RETINA AND OPTIC NERVE.\\\" 5 minutes. Write all 11 layers in order, fovea anatomy with measurements, C/D ratio values, optic disc location. Circle gaps. Core targets: All 11 retinal layers in order (outer to inner) Fovea vs foveola vs parafovea — measurements and photoreceptors in each C/D ratio: normal / suspicious / concerning Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the retinal cross-section. Label all 11 layers. Mark the detachment plane. Mark the two synapse layers (OPL, IPL). Mark where blood supply comes from (choroid for outer, CRA for inner). Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain why a patient with retinitis pigmentosa loses peripheral night vision first and central acuity last — without using \\\"rods\\\" or \\\"cones,\\\" using only their functional roles. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back 11 retinal layers (first 5 outer)? RPE, Photoreceptors, ELM, ONL, Henle 11 retinal layers (last 6 inner)? OPL, INL, IPL, GCL, NFL, ILM Retinal detachment plane? Between RPE and photoreceptors Foveola diameter? 0.4 mm; pure cones; capillary-free Normal C/D ratio? ≤0.3 Optic disc location? 3mm nasal, 0.8mm above foveola Rod pigment? Rhodopsin (507 nm) Outer retinal supply? Choriocapillaris Ophthalmic artery — first branch? Central retinal artery (CRA) Dual retinal blood supply? Inner retina = CRA; outer retina = choriocapillaris (PCAs) Cherry-red spot — cause? CRAO: inner retina edema (opaque) except thin fovea (chorioretinal shows through) How many vortex veins? 4 (one per quadrant) — drain uveal venous blood Venous drainage final destination? Cavernous sinus (via superior + inferior ophthalmic veins) Short PCAs supply? Choroid + outer retina (via choriocapillaris) Long PCAs supply? Anterior uvea (iris + ciliary body) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the phototransduction sequence from photon hitting rhodopsin through cGMP change through synapse 1 (OPL) through synapse 2 (IPL) through ganglion cell axon to optic nerve. Every step. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump (11 layers) 2nd Tomorrow Retinal cross-section diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (RP pattern) 4th 1 week Phototransduction sequence Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-extended-topics-ocular-and-orbital-blood-supply-the-plain-version-first\",\"heading\":\"The Plain Version First\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Think of the eye's blood supply as a tree with one root and many branches. The root is the ophthalmic artery (a branch of the internal carotid). Every structure in the eye and orbit gets its blood from one of its branches. The venous drainage reverses the path — most blood leaves via the superior ophthalmic vein into the cavernous sinus (a large venous space inside the skull). The most clinically important single artery is the central retinal artery (CRA) — it is the only supply to the inner retina, and if it blocks, the inner retina dies within 90 minutes.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-extended-topics-ocular-and-orbital-blood-supply-the-arterial-supply-tree\",\"heading\":\"The Arterial Supply Tree\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"INTERNAL CAROTID ARTERY ↓ OPHTHALMIC ARTERY (enters orbit via optic canal with CN2 ) | ├── CENTRAL RETINAL ARTERY ( CRA ) | Enters optic nerve ~10mm behind globe | Emerges at optic disc → divides into 4 branches | Supplies: INNER 2/3 of retina (ganglion cells to inner nuclear layer) | Terminal (end) artery — NO anastomoses | Blockage = CRAO (central retinal artery occlusion) → sudden painless vision loss | ├── POSTERIOR CILIARY ARTERIES | ├── SHORT POSTERIOR CILIARY ARTERIES (10–20 branches) | | Supply: CHOROID (choriocapillaris) + outer 1/3 of retina | | (photoreceptors, RPE , outer nuclear layer) | | Board clue: Photoreceptors are fed by choroid, NOT by CRA | | | └── LONG POSTERIOR CILIARY ARTERIES (2 branches — nasal and temporal) | Travel forward between choroid and sclera | Supply: Ciliary body + iris (major arterial circle of iris) | Anastomose with anterior ciliary arteries at ciliary body | ├── ANTERIOR CILIARY ARTERIES (from muscular branches) | Follow the rectus muscles to the globe | Penetrate sclera 3–4mm behind limbus | Supply: Anterior uvea (ciliary body + iris anterior segment) | Anastomose with long posterior ciliary arteries → MAJOR ARTERIAL CIRCLE of iris | Contribute to episcleral plexus → limbal arcade | ├── LACRIMAL ARTERY | Follows CN5 lacrimal branch → lacrimal gland + lateral eyelid | ├── SUPRAORBITAL ARTERY → forehead and upper eyelid | ├── SUPRATROCHLEAR ARTERY → medial forehead | ├── DORSAL NASAL ARTERY → anastomoses with facial artery (external carotid) | └── MUSCULAR ARTERIES → supply the 6 EOMs Critical clinical rules from the arterial supply: RULE 1: DUAL SUPPLY OF THE RETINA Inner retina (ganglion cell → inner nuclear layer) → CRA (ophthalmic artery → internal carotid) Outer retina (photoreceptors + RPE ) → choroid (short PCAs → ophthalmic → internal carotid) This is why CRAO spares photoreceptors but destroys ganglion cells. RULE 2: THE CRA IS AN END-ARTERY No collateral supply — total occlusion = ischemic infarction of inner retina Cherry-red spot in CRAO : fovea appears red because choriocapillaris (intact) shows through the thin foveal tissue while surrounding opacified swollen inner retina looks white RULE 3: CHOROIDAL SUPPLY IS SEGMENTAL Short PCAs divide into sectors (nasal, temporal, superior, inferior zones) Sector ischemia → sectoral visual field loss (altitudinal defect) Example: Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy ( AION ) — superior altitudinal loss\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-extended-topics-ocular-and-orbital-blood-supply-venous-drainage\",\"heading\":\"Venous Drainage\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"INNER RETINAL VEINS → CENTRAL RETINAL VEIN ( CRV ) → Superior ophthalmic vein → Cavernous sinus Blockage = CRVO (central retinal vein occlusion) → venous engorgement, flame-shaped hemorrhages in all 4 quadrants, disc edema (\\\"blood and thunder\\\" fundus) CHOROIDAL VEINS → VORTEX VEINS (4 ampullae — one per quadrant, exit posterior to equator) → Superior: drains to superior ophthalmic vein → Inferior: drains to inferior ophthalmic vein Both → Cavernous sinus EPISCLERAL VEINS → Superior ophthalmic vein → Cavernous sinus FINAL DRAINAGE : Cavernous sinus → Petrosal sinuses → Internal jugular vein (The cavernous sinus also drains the face via the superior ophthalmic vein, explaining why facial infections can spread to the orbit — cavernous sinus thrombosis)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-extended-topics-ocular-and-orbital-blood-supply-key-numbers-and-clinical-correlates\",\"heading\":\"Key Numbers and Clinical Correlates\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"Structure Blood supply Blockage result Inner retina Central retinal artery (CRA) CRAO → sudden painless VL; cherry-red spot Outer retina + RPE Choriocapillaris (short PCAs) Choroidal ischemia → photoreceptor death Optic nerve head (anterior) Short PCAs (Circle of Zinn-Haller) AION → sectoral VF loss, disc edema Ciliary body + iris Long PCAs + anterior ciliary As Anterior uveitis ischemia Choroidal drainage Vortex veins (4) Impaired drainage → choroidal effusion Final venous exit Superior ophthalmic vein → cavernous sinus Cavernous sinus thrombosis if infected\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-06-retina-and-optic-nerve-extended-topics-ocular-and-orbital-blood-supply-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-06 — Retina and Optic Nerve\",\"text\":\"The photoreceptors are supplied by the central retinal artery Photoreceptors (outer retina) are supplied by the choroid (choriocapillaris via short posterior ciliary arteries). The CRA only supplies the inner retina. CRAO destroys the entire retina CRA blockage destroys the inner retina but the outer retina (photoreceptors) survives temporarily because the choroid is separate. This is why the fovea appears as a cherry-red spot — the thin foveal tissue lets the intact choroidal red-orange color show through. There are 2 vortex veins There are 4 vortex veins (ampullae), one per quadrant, exiting posterior to the equator. The ophthalmic artery enters the orbit through the superior orbital fissure The ophthalmic artery enters through the optic canal alongside CN2 and the sympathetic nerve.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"The visual pathway is the brain's cable system for sight — a 6-station relay from retina to occipital cortex. Light signals start at the retinal ganglion cells, travel along the optic nerves to the optic chiasma where the nasal fibers from each eye cross over to the opposite side. From there, the mixed signals travel in optic tracts to the lateral geniculate body, then through the optic radiation to the primary visual cortex. The key clinical principle: where the lesion is determines what kind of visual field defect you see. One eye affected = optic nerve lesion. Both eyes affected in matching halves = chiasmal or post-chiasmal lesion. The more posterior the lesion, the more symmetric (congruous) the defect becomes. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"If a pituitary tumor compresses the optic chiasma from below, which visual field quadrants are lost first, and why?\\\" The answer maps the entire fiber decussation pattern in one clinical scenario.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Why do the nasal retinal fibers cross at the chiasma while the temporal fibers do not? Because each visual cortex needs to receive information from the opposite visual field. The nasal retina sees the temporal visual field; crossing it sends temporal field information to the contralateral cortex. The temporal retina sees the nasal visual field; it does not cross because it already projects to the ipsilateral cortex, which processes the contralateral (nasal) visual field from the same side. Why does crossing allow each visual cortex to see the entire opposite visual field? Because after the chiasma, each optic tract contains temporal fibers from the ipsilateral eye (seeing the nasal field) AND nasal fibers from the contralateral eye (seeing the temporal field) — both representing the same half of visual space. The brain combines them for a complete contralateral hemifield. Why do post-chiasmal lesions produce homonymous defects? Because post-chiasmal, every structure carries mixed fibers from both eyes representing the same visual field half. A lesion anywhere from the optic tract onward knocks out the same portion of both eyes' visual fields — homonymous (same-sided). Why are defects more congruous the more posterior the lesion? Because the fibers from the two eyes are physically further apart in the tract (less organized, more separation) but become more tightly interleaved and organized in the optic radiation and cortex. A cortical lesion knocks out exactly corresponding points in both eyes — perfectly matched defects. A tract lesion knocks out fibers that are less precisely organized — slightly mismatched defects.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Hemianopsia Greek hemi — half + an — without + opsis — sight Blindness in half the visual field Homonymous Greek homos — same + onymos — named Same-side field defects in both eyes (e.g., right homonymous = right field lost in both eyes) Heteronymous Greek heteros — different + onymos Different-side field defects (e.g., bitemporal = temporal field lost in both eyes) Congruous Latin congruere — to agree Field defects that are identical/symmetrical in both eyes; posterior lesion Incongruous Latin — to disagree Field defects that are dissimilar between the two eyes; anterior lesion Quadrantanopsia Latin quadrans — quarter Loss of one quadrant of the visual field Scotoma Greek skotos — darkness A focal area of reduced or absent vision within an intact visual field Area striata Latin — striped area Brodmann area 17; primary visual cortex; named for the prominent striae of Gennari Striae of Gennari Named after Francesco Gennari The thick white band of geniculo-calcarine fibers visible in area 17 even with the naked eye Wernicke's hemianopic pupil Named after Carl Wernicke Pupil does not react when light hits the blind half of retina; from optic tract lesion\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"The 6-station visual pathway and what each does: STATION 1: OPTIC NERVE ( CN2 ) — Ganglion cell axons from retina — Fibers: a. Pupillomotor/afferent (pupillary light reflex) b. Visual fibers (sensation — to LGB ) c. Efferent/retinomotor (brain → retina) d. Intercurrent/commissural (link one retina to other) — LESION : Total blindness of that eye (all visual input from that eye lost) STATION 2: OPTIC CHIASMA — Partial decussation: NASAL fibers (temporal field) → CROSS to opposite side TEMPORAL fibers (nasal field) → STAY ipsilateral — Enveloped by pia mater only — Located above pituitary gland → pituitary tumor compresses from below — LESION of crossing fibers: BITEMPORAL hemianopsia — LESION of uncrossed fibers: BINASAL hemianopsia — Both = HETERONYMOUS hemianopsia (different sides in each eye) STATION 3: OPTIC TRACT — Posterior continuation of chiasma to lateral geniculate body — Each tract: temporal fibers from SAME eye + nasal fibers from OPPOSITE eye = represents one visual hemifield from both eyes — LESION : INCONGRUOUS homonymous hemianopsia — WERNICKE 's hemianopic pupil (light on blind half of retina → no pupil response) STATION 4: LATERAL GENICULATE BODY ( LGB ) — Subcortical visual center / relay station — Temporal fibers → layers 2, 3, 5 — Nasal fibers → layers 1, 4, 6 — LESION : CONGRUOUS homonymous hemianopsia — (Transition from incongruous to congruous begins here) STATION 5: OPTIC RADIATION (Geniculo-calcarine tract) — From LGB to area striata (occipital cortex) — Superior fibers: through parietal lobe → serve inferior visual field — Inferior fibers: loop through temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) → serve superior visual field — LESION : Temporal lobe (Meyer's loop): CONTRALATERAL SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\" defect) Parietal lobe: CONTRALATERAL INFERIOR quadrantanopsia STATION 6: AREA STRIATA (Brodmann Area 17) — Medial aspect of occipital lobe — True visual cortex; true receptive center — White line = striae of Gennari — Macular representation: at posterior pole of occipital lobe — LESION : HOMONYMOUS SCOTOMA (macular sparing common with posterior cerebral artery occlusion)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Visual field defects map — lesion site to defect type: LEFT EYE RIGHT EYE Temporal field | Nasal field Nasal field | Temporal field [Retina — nasal fibers cross, temporal stay] OPTIC NERVE (pre-chiasmal) Lesion here: Left optic nerve → Left eye BLIND (right eye normal) OPTIC CHIASMA Crossing fibers lesion: → Left temporal field LOST + Right temporal field LOST = BITEMPORAL HEMIANOPSIA (most common: pituitary adenoma) Uncrossed fibers lesion: → Both nasal fields lost = BINASAL HEMIANOPSIA (rare; carotid aneurysm) OPTIC TRACT (post-chiasmal) Right optic tract lesion: → Left homonymous hemianopsia ( INCONGRUOUS ) → Wernicke's hemianopic pupil (no pupil response to light from blind hemifield) LATERAL GENICULATE BODY Right LGB lesion: → Left homonymous hemianopsia ( CONGRUOUS ) OPTIC RADIATION Right temporal (Meyer's loop) lesion: → Left SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\") Right parietal lesion: → Left INFERIOR quadrantanopsia AREA STRIATA (occipital cortex) Right occipital lesion: → Left homonymous SCOTOMA → Macular sparing often present (dual blood supply of macular area)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Congruous vs Incongruous defects — the posterior rule: Feature Incongruous Congruous Definition Field defects dissimilar between the two eyes Field defects identical/symmetric in both eyes Location of lesion Anterior to LGB (optic tract) Posterior — LGB, optic radiation, cortex Reason Fibers from two eyes are less organized anteriorly Fibers are tightly integrated posteriorly Clinical importance Points to pre-geniculate lesion Points to post-geniculate lesion Board clue \\\"Incongruous = before the crossing is complete\\\" \\\"Congruous = fibers now fully mixed\\\" The four key hemianopsias: Type Description Lesion Cause Bitemporal hemianopsia Both temporal fields lost Chiasmal crossing fibers Pituitary adenoma (compresses from below) Binasal hemianopsia Both nasal fields lost Chiasmal uncrossed fibers Bilateral carotid aneurysm (rare) Left homonymous hemianopsia Left field lost in BOTH eyes Right optic tract / radiation / cortex Stroke, tumor Right homonymous hemianopsia Right field lost in BOTH eyes Left optic tract / radiation / cortex Stroke, tumor Wernicke's hemianopic pupil vs normal pupil reflex: Scenario Pupil response Light shone on seeing half of retina (optic tract lesion) NORMAL — both pupils constrict Light shone on blind half of retina (optic tract lesion) NO response — afferent signal missing from that retinal area Significance Confirms optic tract lesion; rules out cortical lesion (cortical lesions do NOT cause Wernicke's)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Optic chiasma location Above pituitary gland Pituitary tumor → bitemporal hemianopsia LGB fiber distribution — temporal Layers 2, 3, 5 Separate laminar inputs from each eye LGB fiber distribution — nasal Layers 1, 4, 6 Separate laminar inputs Meyer's loop location Temporal lobe Temporal lobe lesion → \\\"pie in the sky\\\" superior quadrantanopsia Area striata location Brodmann area 17; medial occipital lobe Lesion → homonymous scotoma\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"The 6 stations — \\\"Only Chimps Obtain Light Ordering Accurately\\\" Optic nerve → Chiasma → Optic tract → Lateral Geniculate Body → Optic radiation → Area striata The decussation rule — \\\"Nasal crosses; temporal stays\\\" Nasal fibers cross at chiasma (temporal visual field). Temporal fibers stay ipsilateral (nasal visual field). Congruous = cortex; Incongruous = tract More posterior = more congruous. Tract = incongruous. Cortex = congruous. Bitemporal = pituitary tumor Tumor grows up from below → compresses crossing fibers first (those carrying temporal field signals from both eyes) → bitemporal hemianopsia. Meyer's loop clinical trick — \\\"Temporal lobe = pie in the sky\\\" Inferior optic radiation fibers loop through temporal lobe (Meyer's loop). Temporal lobe stroke → superior quadrantanopsia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\" — the upper field is lost).\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"VISUAL PATHWAY (simplified, right visual field processing) RIGHT VISUAL FIELD Both eyes' temporal and nasal retina LEFT EYE (right visual field = nasal retina in left eye) RIGHT EYE (right visual field = temporal retina in right eye) | | | [nasal fibers] [temporal fibers — don't cross] | ↓ ↓ OPTIC CHIASMA ← → nasal fibers CROSS here ← | | └── ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ LEFT OPTIC TRACT (processes RIGHT visual field from BOTH eyes) ↓ LEFT LATERAL GENICULATE BODY (Nasal fibers → layers 1,4,6; Temporal → 2,3,5) ↓ LEFT OPTIC RADIATION ├── Superior fibers (parietal) → processes INFERIOR right field └── Inferior fibers (Meyer's loop, temporal) → processes SUPERIOR right field ↓ LEFT AREA STRIATA (Brodmann 17) → Perceives RIGHT visual field LESION → DEFECT SUMMARY : Left optic nerve: Left eye blind Optic chiasma: Bitemporal hemianopsia Left optic tract: RIGHT homonymous hemianopsia (incongruous) Left LGB : RIGHT homonymous hemianopsia (congruous) Left temporal radiation: RIGHT SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia Left parietal radiation: RIGHT INFERIOR quadrantanopsia Left cortex: RIGHT homonymous scotoma (macular sparing)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Optic nerve lesion causes contralateral blindness Optic nerve lesion causes IPSILATERAL (same-side) blindness. The chiasma is where crossing occurs. All post-chiasmal lesions cause congruous defects Optic tract lesions are post-chiasmal but produce INCONGRUOUS defects. Congruity increases progressively — only at the LGB and beyond does it become fully congruous. Bitemporal hemianopsia means both eyes are blind Temporal fields are lost but nasal fields are preserved. Patients retain central vision and nasal fields. A temporal lobe lesion causes an inferior quadrantanopsia Temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) lesion causes SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\"). Parietal lobe lesion causes inferior quadrantanopsia. Cortical lesions produce Wernicke's hemianopic pupil Wernicke's occurs only with OPTIC TRACT lesions. Cortical lesions do not affect the pupillary light reflex (the pupil reflex pathway branches off at the pretectal area, before reaching the cortex). Temporal fibers cross at the chiasma NASAL fibers cross. Temporal fibers stay ipsilateral.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Optic nerve lesion → Ipsilateral total blindness Chiasmal crossing fiber lesion → Bitemporal hemianopsia Chiasmal uncrossed fiber lesion → Binasal hemianopsia Optic tract lesion → Incongruous homonymous hemianopsia + Wernicke's pupil LGB lesion → Congruous homonymous hemianopsia Temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) lesion → Contralateral SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\") Parietal radiation lesion → Contralateral INFERIOR quadrantanopsia Occipital cortex lesion → Homonymous scotoma (macular sparing common) Most common cause of bitemporal hemianopsia Pituitary adenoma Which fibers cross at chiasma? NASAL fibers (temporal visual field) Congruous vs incongruous rule Congruous = posterior (LGB onward); Incongruous = tract Area striata location Brodmann area 17; medial occipital lobe Striae of Gennari White band in area 17; geniculo-calcarine fibers LGB temporal fibers → layers 2, 3, 5 LGB nasal fibers → layers 1, 4, 6\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"1. A 45-year-old woman presents with gradual loss of her peripheral vision bilaterally. She bumps into objects on both sides. Visual field testing shows loss of both temporal fields while nasal fields are intact. MRI would most likely reveal a lesion at which location? A. Right optic nerve B. Optic chiasma C. Right optic tract D. Left occipital cortex Answer B. Optic chiasma. Bitemporal hemianopsia — loss of both temporal fields with preserved nasal fields — is the hallmark of a chiasmal lesion affecting the crossing (decussating) fibers. These nasal fibers carry temporal field information from both eyes; their interruption at the chiasma eliminates both temporal fields simultaneously. The most common cause in a middle-aged woman is a pituitary adenoma growing upward to compress the inferior chiasma. A right optic nerve lesion would cause right monocular blindness. A right optic tract lesion would cause left homonymous hemianopsia (not bitemporal). Occipital cortex lesion causes homonymous scotoma — not bitemporal loss. 2. A 60-year-old man suffers a right-sided stroke involving the temporal lobe. Which visual field defect is most likely on examination? A. Left inferior quadrantanopsia B. Left superior quadrantanopsia C. Left homonymous hemianopsia with macular sparing D. Right bitemporal hemianopsia Answer B. Left superior quadrantanopsia. The inferior fibers of the right optic radiation loop through the temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) before reaching the occipital cortex. These fibers carry information from the superior visual field of the left hemifield. A right temporal lobe stroke interrupts Meyer's loop, producing a left superior quadrantanopsia — classically called \\\"pie in the sky\\\" (the upper-left visual field is lost). Left inferior quadrantanopsia would result from a right parietal lobe lesion (superior radiation fibers). Left homonymous hemianopsia with macular sparing is a right occipital cortex finding. Bitemporal hemianopsia requires a chiasmal lesion.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2-07-visual-pathway-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A2-07 — The Visual Pathway\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"VISUAL PATHWAY.\\\" 5 minutes. Write all 6 stations, the fiber decussation rule, and the visual field defect for each station when lesioned. Circle gaps. Core targets: All 6 stations in order with one lesion defect each Which fibers cross at the chiasma (nasal or temporal) and why Congruous vs incongruous — which station is which Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the visual pathway from both eyes through the chiasma to both occipital lobes. Mark where nasal fibers cross. For each of the 6 stations, write the lesion defect directly on the diagram. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a student why a pituitary tumor causes bitemporal hemianopsia — starting from the anatomy of the tumor's position, through the fiber that is compressed, to the visual field result. Do not use the word \\\"bitemporal\\\" until the last sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Which fibers cross at chiasma? NASAL fibers (temporal field) Bitemporal hemianopsia → lesion? Optic chiasma (crossing fibers); pituitary adenoma Optic tract lesion → defect type? Incongruous homonymous hemianopsia LGB lesion → defect type? Congruous homonymous hemianopsia Meyer's loop lesion → Contralateral SUPERIOR quadrantanopsia Occipital cortex lesion → Homonymous scotoma (macular sparing) Wernicke's hemianopic pupil → lesion at? Optic tract Area striata = Brodmann area? 17 (medial occipital lobe) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch For each of the 6 visual pathway stations, write: (1) the station name; (2) what visual information it carries; (3) the defect when it is damaged. Do it entirely from memory. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Visual pathway diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (pituitary-chiasma) 4th 1 week Full 6-station sequence from scratch Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"The eye builds itself from three different tissue sources working in sequence over nine months. The brain sends out a bud (optic vesicle from the diencephalon) that contacts the skin surface, which folds inward to form the lens. The bud folds into a double-walled cup — the outer wall becomes the RPE, the inner wall becomes the retina. A groove on the bottom of the cup lets blood vessels in temporarily; when it closes at week 7, the vascular scaffolding becomes permanent eye structures. The vitreous forms in three generations: first a vascular one that nourishes the lens, then a clear gel that replaces it, then the zonules. Every congenital malformation in the eye links back to one specific step in this sequence failing at a specific time. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why is an iris coloboma always at the bottom (6 o'clock position)?\\\" The answer reveals everything about fetal fissure location and closure timing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Why does the optic vesicle need to contact the surface ectoderm? Because contact is what induces the lens to form. Without the optic vesicle touching the overlying skin, the lens placode never thickens — the lens never develops, and without a lens, the optic cup stops developing too. Development is inductive — each step triggers the next. Why must the fetal fissure close? Because it is the entry point of the hyaloid artery. Once the primary vitreous and the hyaloid vasculature have served their purpose (nourishing the developing lens), the fissure must close to separate the intraocular environment. If it stays open, the resulting structural gap (coloboma) creates a notch that affects vision depending on location. Why does the primary vitreous need to be replaced by the secondary vitreous? Because the primary vitreous is vascular — blood vessels in the visual axis would obstruct vision. The lens needs nutrients during development but becomes fully avascular at birth. At that point, the entire hyaloid vascular system regresses by apoptosis, leaving only the clear Cloquet's canal as a remnant. Why do Marfan syndrome patients get lens dislocation? Because the zonules are derived from the tertiary vitreous, which is made of fibrillin-containing microfibrils. Marfan syndrome is an FBN1 gene mutation (fibrillin-1 deficiency). Without proper fibrillin, the zonules are structurally weak — they snap under normal tension, and the lens dislocates (ectopia lentis), classically superiorly.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Diencephalon Greek dia — through + enkephalos — brain The posterior division of the forebrain; gives rise to the optic vesicles Optic vesicle Latin vesicle — small bladder The bilateral outpouching from the diencephalon that initiates eye development Optic cup — The double-walled structure formed when the optic vesicle invaginates; outer wall = RPE, inner wall = retina Lens placode Greek plax — flat plate The localized thickening of surface ectoderm induced by the optic vesicle contact Fetal fissure Latin fissura — cleft The groove on the inferior surface of the optic cup and stalk; allows hyaloid artery entry Coloboma Greek koloboma — curtailed A congenital gap or notch from failure of fetal fissure closure Primary vitreous — First-generation vitreous; vascular; contains hyaloid artery Secondary vitreous — Second-generation; acellular, avascular; the bulk of adult vitreous Tertiary vitreous — Third-generation; forms the lens zonules; fibrillin-containing Hyaloid artery Greek hyalos — glass The temporary artery supplying the developing lens through the primary vitreous Mittendorf dot Named after Johann Mittendorf A small white dot on the posterior lens capsule — the normal remnant of where the hyaloid artery attached PHPV / PFV Persistent Hyperplastic Primary Vitreous / Persistent Fetal Vasculature The primary vitreous fails to regress — the hyaloid vessels remain, causing a white pupil Ectopia lentis Greek ektopos — displaced + lens Lens dislocation — classic in Marfan syndrome (superiorly)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"The 5 stages of ocular development: STAGE 1 — Optic Vesicle Formation (Week 3–4; embryo 3–7 mm) Neural plate folds → Neural tube forms ↓ Bilateral outpouchings from DIENCEPHALON (forebrain) → OPTIC GROOVES (day 22) → deepen into OPTIC VESICLES (day 25; embryo ~4mm) ↓ Optic vesicle contacts overlying SURFACE ECTODERM → LENS PLACODE (localized thickening) is induced to form This contact is inductive — the optic vesicle sends molecular signals to the surface ectoderm, telling it to become a lens. Without contact, neither the lens nor the optic cup develops properly. STAGE 2 — Optic Cup and Lens Vesicle (End Week 4 to Week 6; 7–14 mm) Optic vesicle INVAGINATES (folds inward on itself) → DOUBLE-WALLED OPTIC CUP : OUTER WALL → RPE (retinal pigment epithelium) INNER WALL → Neural retina (10 neuronal layers) Simultaneously: Lens placode INVAGINATES → LENS PIT → pinches off completely → LENS VESICLE (hollow sphere of surface ectoderm) → Lens vesicle separates from surface ectoderm → sits in the opening of the optic cup Failure: incomplete optic cup invagination → MICROPHTHALMOS or ANOPHTHALMOS STAGE 3 — Fetal Fissure and Its Closure (Week 5–7; 14 mm) FETAL FISSURE (choroidal fissure) forms: — longitudinal groove on INFERIOR surface of optic cup and optic stalk — allows HYALOID ARTERY to enter — hyaloid artery → through primary vitreous → posterior lens capsule — branches → TUNICA VASCULOSA LENTIS (vascular capsule around developing lens) Fissure CLOSES by week 7: — fuses from equator toward anterior and posterior poles — failure to close → COLOBOMA (keyhole notch at 6 o'clock) Coloboma is always at the INFERIOR position because the fetal fissure is always on the inferior surface of the optic cup. The shape — a notch at the 6 o'clock of the iris, choroid, or optic nerve — directly maps the fissure location. STAGE 4 — Lens Development (Week 5 to Birth) Lens vesicle (hollow sphere): ↓ POSTERIOR cells elongate → fill hollow sphere → PRIMARY LENS FIBERS (embryonic nucleus) ↓ EQUATORIAL cells differentiate → elongate → wrap around primary fibers → SECONDARY LENS FIBERS (cortex) — continues throughout life ↓ Mature fibers LOSE their nuclei ↓ Y-SUTURE : fiber ends meet at suture lines Anterior: upright Y (Y) Posterior: inverted Y (Λ) STAGE 5 — Vitreous (Three Generations) Generation Timing Vascularity Composition Adult fate Failure = Primary Week 4–9 VASCULAR (hyaloid system) Hyaloid artery + tunica vasculosa lentis Regresses; cavity → Cloquet's canal PHPV/PFV; Mittendorf dot Secondary Week 9 to birth AVASCULAR Collagen fibrils + hyaluronic acid Adult vitreous body Syneresis (aging) Tertiary Week 12 onward Avascular Fibrillin microfibrils Lens ZONULES Ectopia lentis (Marfan — FBN1 mutation)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Complete germ layer origin table — what comes from where: Germ Layer Ocular Structures Neuroectoderm (from neural tube / diencephalon) Retina (both RPE and neural retina — from optic cup walls), optic nerve, dilator pupillae, sphincter pupillae, ciliary body epithelium (pigmented and non-pigmented) Surface ectoderm Crystalline lens (only structure ENTIRELY from surface ectoderm), corneal epithelium, conjunctival epithelium, lacrimal gland (main + accessory), Meibomian/tarsal glands, glands of Zeis (sebaceous), glands of Moll (sweat), eyelid skin Neural crest cells Corneal stroma, corneal endothelium, trabecular meshwork, uveal stroma, sclera, orbital bones, ciliary muscle, optic nerve meninges Mesoderm Extraocular muscles, Tenon's capsule/bulbar fascia, vascular endothelium of ocular blood vessels Mixed origin Zonular fibers (tertiary vitreous — from non-pigmented ciliary epithelium = neuroectoderm) Syllabi version: Mesoderm also includes ciliary muscle and vitreous (primary vitreous). Neural crest is listed under ectoderm. Both versions are acceptable in boards — know the structures, not just the labels. Tissue origins for eyelid structures and lacrimal apparatus (syllabus-specific): Structure Tissue Origin Eyelid skin Surface ectoderm Orbicularis oculi, LPS (eyelid muscles) Mesoderm Tarsus Neural crest mesenchyme Meibomian/Zeis/Moll glands Surface ectoderm Main lacrimal gland Surface ectoderm (sprouting from conjunctival epithelium superolaterally) Accessory lacrimal glands (Krause, Wolfring) Surface ectoderm Nasolacrimal duct lining Surface ectoderm (downgrowth into neural crest mesenchyme of the nasal region) Lacrimal and nasal passages (bony) Neural crest (forms the surrounding bony and mesenchymal framework)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Three vitreous generations — the most tested embryology comparison: Primary Secondary Tertiary When Weeks 4–9 Week 9 to birth Week 12 onward Vascular? YES (hyaloid artery) NO NO Made of Hyaloid vessels + meshwork Collagen + hyaluronic acid Fibrillin microfibrils Adult fate Cloquet's canal Adult vitreous gel Lens zonules Fails to regress → PHPV/PFV — Ectopia lentis (Marfan's) Board clue \\\"Vascular scaffold\\\" \\\"Clear gel replacement\\\" \\\"Becomes the zonules\\\" Coloboma vs aniridia — both congenital iris defects, different mechanisms: Feature Coloboma Aniridia Mechanism Fetal fissure failed to close PAX6 gene mutation — iris fails to differentiate Appearance Notch/keyhole at 6 o'clock of iris Near-complete absence of iris Location Always inferior (inferior fetal fissure) No location preference (entire iris missing) Associated defects Choroidal, optic nerve coloboma also possible Cataracts, glaucoma, nystagmus, corneal pannus Inheritance Variable Autosomal dominant (PAX6)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Optic grooves form Day 22 Earliest ocular structure Optic vesicles form Day 25 (embryo ~4mm) Contact with surface ectoderm induces lens placode Lens vesicle separates End of week 5 Pinches off from surface ectoderm Fetal fissure closes Week 7 (14mm stage) Failure = coloboma Primary vitreous forms Weeks 4–9 Hyaloid artery present Secondary vitreous replaces Week 9 to birth Avascular adult vitreous forms Tertiary vitreous / zonules form Week 12 onward Fibrillin microfibrils = zonules Hyaloid artery fully gone Week 36 to birth Cloquet's canal remnant Lens Y-suture forms Week 5 onward Upright Y (anterior) / inverted Y (posterior)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Three tissue sources for the eye — \\\"Neuro Surface Neural-crest Meso\\\" (NS NM) Neuroectoderm: retina, optic nerve, iris muscles, ciliary epithelium Surface ectoderm: lens (ONLY ocular structure entirely from surface ectoderm), lacrimal, glands, corneal epithelium Neural crest: corneal stroma + endothelium, TM, sclera, orbital bones Mesoderm: EOMs, Tenon's, vascular endothelium Lens is special — only one derived entirely from surface ectoderm. Three vitreous generations — \\\"VACation\\\" (Vascular → Acellular → Connective/Zonules) Primary = Vascular → Secondary = Acellular → Tertiary = becomes the Connective tissue (zonules) Coloboma rule — \\\"Always inferior, always at 6 o'clock\\\" Because the fetal fissure is always on the INFERIOR surface of the optic cup. Marfan's-Lens link — \\\"FBN1 fails → fibrillin weak → zonules snap → lens goes up\\\" Tertiary vitreous = fibrillin → Marfan FBN1 mutation → weak zonules → superiorly dislocated lens (ectopia lentis). Fetal fissure timeline — \\\"Opens Week 5, closes Week 7\\\" Open for 2 weeks to let hyaloid artery in. Closes at 7. If not closed → coloboma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"OCULAR EMBRYOLOGY TIMELINE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Week 3-4: [Diencephalon] → optic grooves → OPTIC VESICLES ↓ (contacts surface ectoderm) LENS PLACODE (thickening) Week 4-6: Optic vesicle INVAGINATES → OPTIC CUP ├── Outer wall → RPE └── Inner wall → Neural retina Lens placode invaginates → LENS PIT → LENS VESICLE (pinches off) Week 5-7: FETAL FISSURE Opens on inferior surface of optic cup → HYALOID ARTERY enters → PRIMARY VITREOUS forms (vascular) → TUNICA VASCULOSA LENTIS forms around developing lens CLOSES at week 7 Failure to close = COLOBOMA (inferior, keyhole-shaped) Week 5-birth: LENS DEVELOPMENT Posterior vesicle cells → primary lens fibers (embryonic nucleus) Equatorial cells → secondary lens fibers (cortex) [continues for life] Y-sutures form (upright Y anterior, inverted Y posterior) Week 9-birth: SECONDARY VITREOUS Hyaloid artery regresses (apoptosis) Avascular collagen + hyaluronic acid replaces primary vitreous Remnant = CLOQUET 'S CANAL Week 12+: TERTIARY VITREOUS Non-pigmented ciliary epithelium → FIBRILLIN MICROFIBRILS → LENS ZONULES (suspensory ligament) Week 36-birth: Hyaloid fully regressed Mittendorf dot = spot where hyaloid attached to posterior capsule (normal variant)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"The optic vesicle arises from the surface ectoderm The optic vesicle arises from the DIENCEPHALON (forebrain/neural tube). Surface ectoderm is induced by the optic vesicle — it does not produce it. The lens is derived from neuroectoderm The lens is derived entirely from SURFACE ECTODERM (lens placode). It is the only major ocular structure with this origin. The primary vitreous becomes the adult vitreous The primary vitreous regresses. The SECONDARY vitreous becomes the adult vitreous gel. The primary vitreous leaves only Cloquet's canal. Coloboma can occur at any position on the iris Iris coloboma is always at the INFERIOR position (6 o'clock) because the fetal fissure, which fails to close, is always located on the inferior surface of the optic cup. The tertiary vitreous becomes the adult vitreous gel Tertiary vitreous becomes the LENS ZONULES. The secondary vitreous is the gel. Marfan syndrome causes inferiorly dislocated lens Marfan syndrome causes SUPERIORLY dislocated lens (ectopia lentis superiotemporally). Homocystinuria causes inferiorly dislocated lens. PHPV causes a black pupil PHPV/PFV causes LEUKOCORIA (white pupil) — the persistent primary vitreous/vascular mass appears as a white retrolental opacity. The corneal endothelium comes from surface ectoderm Corneal endothelium (and stroma) come from NEURAL CREST cells.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Origin of optic vesicle Diencephalon (neural tube/forebrain) Structure derived entirely from surface ectoderm Crystalline lens Fetal fissure closure time Week 7 (14mm stage) Failure to close fetal fissure → Coloboma (inferior, 6 o'clock) Primary vitreous characteristic Vascular (hyaloid artery) Secondary vitreous characteristic Avascular (adult vitreous) Tertiary vitreous becomes Lens zonules (fibrillin microfibrils) Hyaloid artery fully regressed by Week 36 / birth Remnant of hyaloid artery canal Cloquet's canal Remnant on posterior lens capsule Mittendorf dot (normal variant) PHPV = Primary vitreous fails to regress; leukocoria Marfan FBN1 mutation → Weak fibrillin → zonular failure → superiorly dislocated lens Aniridia gene PAX6 mutation Neural crest → cornea Corneal stroma + endothelium (not epithelium) Corneal epithelium origin Surface ectoderm EOM origin Mesoderm Lacrimal gland origin Surface ectoderm Retina origin Neuroectoderm (optic cup walls)\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"1. A newborn presents with leukocoria (white pupil). On examination, a white fibrovascular mass is noted behind the lens. B-scan ultrasound shows a retrolental mass with no calcium deposits. Which embryological failure best explains this finding? A. Failure of fetal fissure closure B. Failure of primary vitreous to regress C. Failure of lens vesicle to separate from surface ectoderm D. Failure of secondary vitreous to form Answer B. Failure of primary vitreous to regress. This is Persistent Hyperplastic Primary Vitreous (PHPV), now called Persistent Fetal Vasculature (PFV). The primary vitreous, which is vascular and contains the hyaloid artery system, normally regresses completely by birth. When it persists, the remaining fibrovascular tissue forms a white retrolental mass — leukocoria. The absence of calcium deposits distinguishes it from retinoblastoma (which often calcifies). Fetal fissure failure produces coloboma (not a retrolental mass). Lens vesicle failure would prevent lens formation. Secondary vitreous failure does not cause leukocoria. 2. A 16-year-old male with tall stature, long fingers, and arachnodactyly presents with sudden visual blur in the right eye. Slit-lamp exam shows the right lens displaced superiorly. Which of the following correctly links the genetic defect to the embryological structure affected? A. PAX6 mutation → failure of iris differentiation → aniridia B. FBN1 mutation → abnormal fibrillin → weak tertiary vitreous-derived zonules → lens dislocation C. FBN1 mutation → weak secondary vitreous → lens dislocation D. COL4A1 mutation → abnormal lens capsule → spontaneous lens rupture Answer **B. FBN1 mutation → abnormal fibrillin → weak tertiary vitreous-derived zonules → lens dislocation.** This is Marfan syndrome. The tertiary vitreous forms the lens zonules (suspensory ligament) from fibrillin-containing microfibrils. FBN1 encodes fibrillin-1. When fibrillin is structurally abnormal, the zonules are weak and break under normal tension. The lens dislocates — classically in the superotemporal direction. This is ectopia lentis. The secondary vitreous (option C) forms the vitreous gel, not the zonules. PAX6 mutation causes aniridia — no lens dislocation. COL4A1 mutations affect type IV collagen and cause cerebrovascular disease, not lens dislocation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Close the note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"OCULAR EMBRYOLOGY.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: the 5 development stages with timing, the 3 vitreous generations (vascular/avascular/zonules), germ layer origins for 6 key structures, and 3 congenital malformation–mechanism pairs. Circle gaps. Core targets: When the fetal fissure opens and closes, what enters through it, and what happens if it fails Primary vs secondary vs tertiary vitreous (timing, vascularity, adult fate) Which ONE structure comes entirely from surface ectoderm Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the optic vesicle invaginating into the optic cup. Label: outer wall → RPE, inner wall → retina. Draw the fetal fissure on the inferior surface. Draw the hyaloid artery entering through it. Mark where coloboma would be if the fissure failed to close. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a student why a Marfan syndrome patient's lens dislocates upward — starting from the gene mutation, through the embryological structure it affects, to the mechanical failure. Do not use \\\"Marfan\\\" or \\\"lens dislocation\\\" until your last sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Optic vesicle arises from? Diencephalon (forebrain neural tube) Only structure from surface ectoderm? Crystalline lens Fetal fissure closes at? Week 7 (14mm) Failure → Coloboma (inferior, 6 o'clock) Primary vitreous characteristic? Vascular (hyaloid artery) Tertiary vitreous becomes? Lens zonules (fibrillin) PHPV = Primary vitreous fails to regress; leukocoria Marfan lens dislocation direction? Superiorly (superotemporal) Mittendorf dot = Remnant of hyaloid artery on posterior lens capsule Corneal stroma/endothelium origin? Neural crest Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the development of the lens from lens placode to mature lens — every step in order: induction, placode formation, lens pit, lens vesicle separation, primary fibers, secondary fibers, Y-sutures, loss of nuclei. Then write what happens if any step fails. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Optic cup + fetal fissure diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (Marfan mechanism) 4th 1 week Full 5-stage development sequence from scratch Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3-01-ocular-embryology-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"A3-01 — Ocular Embryology\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. CN3 palsy — cue: a third-nerve palsy + pupil status. Pupil dilated → compressive (aneurysm) = emergency, image now. Pupil spared → ischemic (diabetic) = monitor. Trap: sending every CN3 palsy to surgery; the pupil-spared one is observed. EOM innervation — cue: a named muscle. LR6 SO4 AO3 : Lateral Rectus → CN6, Superior Oblique → CN4, All Others → CN3. Trap: the option saying \\\"CN3 supplies all the extraocular muscles.\\\" Field defect by lesion site — cue: where the lesion is. Chiasm → bitemporal; behind chiasm → homonymous (more congruous the more posterior; occipital = most congruous + macular sparing). Trap: calling an occipital defect \\\"incongruous\\\" — incongruous = optic tract. Germ layer — cue: which structure. Surface ectoderm = lens + corneal epithelium. Neuroectoderm = retina, optic nerve, sphincter/dilator. Neural crest = corneal stroma/endothelium, sclera, uvea. Trap: labeling corneal endothelium \\\"mesoderm\\\" — it is neural crest .\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"A.strategy\",\"subject\":\"A\",\"label\":\"Visual Biology — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/A-Visual-Biology/A-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Visual Biology and Ocular Anatomy · the read-before-you-test reference for all 9 topics A1 Body/CN Orbit/EOM Lids/Lacrimal Cornea/Sclera Uveal Lens/Vitreous Retina/Optic N Pathway Embryology\"},{\"anchor\":\"a1\",\"heading\":\"A1Body Systems & Cranial Nerves\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"EOM innervation \\\"LR6 SO4 AO3\\\": Lateral Rectus = CN6, Superior Oblique = CN4, All Others = CN3. CN3 pupil rule: Compressive (aneurysm) blows the pupil (outer pupillomotor fibers hit first) = emergency. Ischemic (diabetic) spares the pupil. CN4 is special: only fully decussated nerve (contralateral SO), thinnest motor nerve, longest intracranial course (~75 mm). Sinus rule: Ethmoid → orbital cellulitis (thin lamina papyracea). Sphenoid → retrobulbar neuritis (CN2 sits above). Trigeminal: V1 (ophthalmic) = smallest, pure sensory, gives corneal sensation (nasociliary). V3 = largest. CN7 = lid closure + reflex tears. Trap: CN4 supplies the ipsilateral SO. No — it crosses to the contralateral SO. Trap: a pupil-involving CN3 palsy can be observed. No — rule out aneurysm immediately.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2o\",\"heading\":\"A2Orbit & Extraocular Muscles\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"SO primary action = intorsion (depression secondary). IO primary = extorsion. IO is the only EOM not arising from the annulus of Zinn (it starts at the maxilla). Walls: medial wall thinnest (lamina papyracea); lateral wall thickest. CN2 → optic canal; CN3/4/6 + V1 → superior orbital fissure. Spiral of Tillaux: MR inserts nearest the limbus (5.5 mm, strongest); SR farthest (7.7 mm). Recti insert in front of the equator, obliques behind . SO is the longest EOM (~60 mm). Evisceration = remove contents, keep sclera. Enucleation = remove the whole globe. Lockwood's ligament = suspensory hammock. Trap: the SO elevates the eye. No — primary action is intorsion (IO elevates, SO depresses). Trap: CN2 runs through the SOF. No — CN2 goes through the optic canal.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2l\",\"heading\":\"A2Eyelids, Conjunctiva & Lacrimal\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Tear film (outside → cornea): Lipid → Aqueous → Mucin. Aqueous is thickest (~7 µm). Lipid = Meibomian; basic aqueous = Krause + Wolfring; reflex aqueous = main gland (CN7); mucin = goblet cells. Tests: Schirmer = aqueous volume (10–25 mm/5 min); TBUT = stability (>10 s). Normal Schirmer + short TBUT = evaporative dry eye (MGD). Ptosis: Müller's paralysis = mild 1–2 mm (Horner's); LPS paralysis = complete (CN3). NLD drains to the inferior meatus (valve of Hasner). Tears: major Ig = secretory IgA. Goblet cells absent at lid margins and limbus. Crocodile tears = misdirected CN7 fibers. Trap: the aqueous layer is thinnest. No — aqueous is the thickest layer. Trap: Schirmer measures stability. No — Schirmer = volume; TBUT = stability.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2c\",\"heading\":\"A2Cornea & Sclera\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"6 layers: Epithelium → Bowman's → Stroma → Dua's → Descemet's → Endothelium. Stroma = 90% of thickness. Cornea power ~43 D (strongest refractor). Regeneration: epithelium and Descemet's regenerate; Bowman's and endothelium do NOT (endothelium is post-mitotic). Fuchs' = endothelial loss → pump fails → edema + guttata. Clarity: endothelial Na-K ATPase keeps the stroma deturgesced. Regular collagen = clear cornea; irregular collagen = white sclera. Cornea is thinner centrally and oval (wider horizontally). Sclera: thinnest at EOM insertion (0.3 mm), thickest at CN2 (1.0 mm). Nasociliary innervates all corneal layers except Descemet's and endothelium. Trap: the cornea is thickest centrally. No — it is thinner centrally, thicker peripherally. Trap: endothelium regenerates. No — post-mitotic; lost cells are gone permanently.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2u\",\"heading\":\"A2Uveal Tract\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Uvea = Iris + Ciliary body + Choroid. Sphincter (miosis) = parasympathetic CN3; dilator (mydriasis) = sympathetic. Accommodation: ciliary muscle contracts → zonules relax → lens rounds up. Pars plana = safe surgical entry (least vascular); pars plicata makes aqueous. Pupils: Argyll-Robertson (small, irregular, light-near dissociation) = neurosyphilis. Adie's (tonic) = ciliary ganglion, benign, constricts to 0.125% pilocarpine (supersensitivity). Choroid thickest at the posterior pole; choriocapillaris feeds the outer retina; Bruch's membrane sits between choroid and RPE. Trap: ciliary contraction tightens the zonules. No — it relaxes them; the lens rounds by elastic recoil. Trap: Argyll-Robertson is benign. No — that is Adie's; Argyll-Robertson means neurosyphilis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2v\",\"heading\":\"A2Lens, Vitreous & Aqueous\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Aqueous: made by the non-pigment epithelium of the pars plicata (~2 µL/min). Outflow 80% trabecular, 20% uveoscleral (prostaglandins boost uveoscleral). IOP 10–21 mmHg. Capsule: anterior capsule is thickest (~15 µm, the thickest basement membrane in the body); posterior is thinnest (~2.2 µm). Posterior lens surface is more curved (steeper). Presbyopia = lens nuclear hardening , not ciliary muscle weakness. Vitreous ~98.5% water (hyaluronic acid gel), not replaced if lost. Cloquet's canal = hyaloid remnant. Aqueous has higher ascorbate than plasma and very low protein. The lens is avascular to stay optically clear. Trap: uveoscleral is 80% of outflow. No — trabecular is 80%; uveoscleral is 20%. Trap: presbyopia is ciliary muscle failure. No — it is hardening of the lens nucleus.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2r\",\"heading\":\"A2Retina & Optic Nerve\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Retinal detachment separates photoreceptors from the RPE (the RPE-Bruch's bond is firm). Foveola = pure cones, no rods, capillary-free. Parafovea is thickest; foveola thinnest. Blood supply: outer retina = choriocapillaris (65–85%); inner retina = central retinal artery. The retina has no pain fibers (painless vision loss). Numbers: 11 retinal layers; normal C/D ≤0.3; ora serrata 6 mm from limbus; disc ~3 mm nasal to macula; macular pigment = lutein + zeaxanthin. The optic disc has no photoreceptors (the physiologic blind spot). Glaucoma damages retinal ganglion cell axons at the lamina cribrosa. Trap: the fovea is the thickest retina. No — the parafovea is thickest; the foveola is thinnest. Trap: normal C/D is 0.5. No — normal is ≤0.3 ; 0.5 is suspicious.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a2p\",\"heading\":\"A2Visual Pathway\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Lesion map: Optic nerve = ipsilateral blindness · Chiasm = bitemporal (pituitary) · Tract = incongruous HH + Wernicke's pupil · LGB onward = congruous. Radiations: Temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) = superior quadrantanopia (\\\"pie in the sky\\\"); Parietal = inferior quadrantanopia; Occipital = homonymous hemianopia with macular sparing . Rules: Nasal fibers cross at the chiasm (temporal stay). Congruity increases as lesions move posteriorly. Pupil fibers exit at the pretectum, so cortical lesions spare the light reflex. Defect Site Bitemporal hemianopia Chiasm (pituitary) \\\"Pie in the sky\\\" (superior) Meyer's loop (temporal) Inferior quadrantanopia Parietal radiation Macular-sparing HH Occipital cortex Trap: temporal fibers cross at the chiasm. No — nasal fibers cross.\"},{\"anchor\":\"a3\",\"heading\":\"A3Ocular Embryology\",\"topic\":\"Subject A — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Origins: Optic vesicle = diencephalon · Lens = surface ectoderm (the only major structure entirely from it) · Retina = neuroectoderm · Corneal stroma + endothelium = neural crest · EOMs = mesoderm. Fetal fissure closes ~week 7; failure → coloboma, always inferior (6 o'clock). Hyaloid artery regresses by birth (Cloquet's canal remnant). Vitreous: primary (vascular) regresses → PHPV/leukocoria if it persists; secondary = adult gel ; tertiary = lens zonules. Lens dislocation: Marfan (FBN1) = superior ; homocystinuria = inferior. Aniridia = PAX6 mutation. Trap: the lens comes from neuroectoderm. No — entirely surface ectoderm . Trap: the secondary vitreous regresses. No — the primary regresses; the secondary becomes the adult gel. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject A strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"B.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"B\",\"label\":\"Physiological Optics & BV — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/B-Physiological-Optics-and-BV/B-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"The eye is both a camera and a signal processor. As a camera, it refracts light through six cardinal optical points and focuses it on the retina. As a signal processor, it has two detector types — rods for dark/peripheral sensing and cones for bright/color/detail — operating on different wavelengths and adapting to light changes through chemical, migratory, and electrical mechanisms. The entire system can be described using three axes (for eye movement), four key angles (for visual alignment), and a characteristic dark adaptation curve that shows exactly how sensitivity rebuilds over 30–40 minutes in the dark. Understanding these foundations links anatomy directly to clinical optometry: why a patient fumbles entering a dark theater, why a faint star is easier to see off-center, and why two eyes are better than one for threshold tasks. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why can you see a dim star better by looking slightly to the side of it?\\\" The answer explains rod distribution, convergence, and averted vision in one question.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Why do rods reach maximum density at ~20° from the fovea instead of at the fovea itself? Because the fovea is specialized for cones — all rods are excluded from the central 0.35mm. The peripheral retina is rod territory, and rods peak at ~20° eccentricity. Why does rod sensitivity keep improving for 30–40 minutes in the dark while cone sensitivity plateaus at 7 minutes? Because rhodopsin (rod pigment) regenerates much more slowly than cone pigments. Cone pigments reform in ~7 minutes; rhodopsin regeneration is a long enzymatic process requiring vitamin A and takes the full 30–40 minutes. Why does the Purkinje shift happen? Because photopic vision depends on cones (peak 555nm), while scotopic vision depends on rods (peak 507nm). As light fades and cones become less effective, the system shifts to rod-dominated sensing — and rods are more sensitive to shorter (blue-green) wavelengths. Why is the anteroposterior axis the longest at 24mm while the other two are 22mm? Because the AP axis runs the full geometric depth of the eyeball (front to back), which is the longest dimension. The horizontal and vertical axes cross at the center of rotation within the eye, so they are shorter.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Scotopic Greek skotos — darkness Dim-light rod-mediated vision; peak sensitivity 507nm Photopic Greek photos — light Bright-light cone-mediated vision; peak sensitivity 555nm Purkinje shift Named after Jan E. Purkinje The shift of peak spectral sensitivity from 555nm (photopic) to 507nm (scotopic) as light decreases Kohlrausch kink Named after Arnt Kohlrausch The inflection point on the dark adaptation curve (~7min) where rod sensitivity takes over from cone sensitivity Rhodopsin Greek rhodon — rose + opsis — sight The rod photopigment; bleaches on light exposure; regenerates in dark (requires Vit A) Erythrolabe Greek erythros — red + labein — to take Red-sensitive cone pigment; peak ~750nm (L-cones) Chlorolabe Greek khloros — green Green-sensitive cone pigment; peak ~535nm (M-cones) Cyanolabe Greek kyanos — blue Blue-sensitive cone pigment; peak ~440nm (S-cones) Nodal point Latin nodus — knot Point through which rays pass undeviated; angle alpha measured here Cardinal points Latin cardinalis — principal The 6 key points that define the optical system of the eye\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"The three axes of eye rotation (Axes of Fick): All axes pass through the center of rotation — located 13.5mm behind the cornea. Y-AXIS (Anteroposterior / Optic / Sagittal axis) Length: 24mm — LONGEST (runs full depth of eyeball, cornea to posterior pole) Orientation: front to back (horizontal) Movement: TORSION (intorsion / extorsion) Board clue: Superior oblique intorts → Y-axis X-AXIS (Transverse / Horizontal / Frontal axis) Length: 22mm Orientation: side to side Movement: VERTICAL (elevation / depression) Board clue: \\\"X-axis = uP/doWn\\\" Z-AXIS (Vertical / Supero-infero axis) Length: 22mm Orientation: top to bottom Movement: HORIZONTAL (adduction / abduction) Board clue: \\\"Z-axis = sideWays\\\" — Z is the last letter, like the last direction you think of Mnemonic: \\\"ATV — 24-22-22\\\" (AP=Torsion, Transverse=Vertical, Vertical=Horizontal; AP is 24mm, others 22mm) The four angles of the eye: ANGLE ALPHA (α) Between: Optical axis and Visual axis Measured at: Nodal point Normal: 5° temporal, 1.5° inferior So what: Fovea sits slightly temporal/inferior to the optical axis. In high myopes, alpha is larger (fovea more displaced). ANGLE KAPPA (κ) — clinically most important Between: Pupillary axis and Visual axis Measured at: Pupil center Normal: Small positive (pupil nasal to visual axis) +Kappa: Light reflex sits TEMPORAL → looks like exotropia (pseudo-exo on Hirschberg) -Kappa: Light reflex sits NASAL → looks like esotropia (pseudo-eso) Board clue: \\\"Kappa = clinical Konfusion\\\" — cover test is negative, reflex is displaced ANGLE LAMBDA (λ) Between: Pupillary axis and Line of sight Measured at: Entrance pupil Used in: Optical calculations (less tested than kappa) ANGLE GAMMA (γ) Between: Fixation axis and Optical axis Measured at: Center of rotation Least commonly tested Dark adaptation — the two-phase curve: THRESHOLD (high = less sensitive) | | Phase 1 — CONES adapt (0–7 min) | \\\\ | \\\\ KOHLRAUSCH KINK at ~7 min | '-------. | \\\\ Phase 2 — RODS adapt (7–30+ min) | \\\\ | '------------- (plateau ~30–40 min) (low = most sensitive) |________________________ TIME (minutes) 0 7 30-40 At full dark adaptation, rod threshold is about 3 log units more sensitive than the cone plateau. This means rods at full dark adaptation are 1000× more sensitive than cones. Retinal changes on light stimulation (MCE): Migratory: RPE pigment granules move toward photoreceptors (screens rods in bright light); cone segments extend/retract. Slowest — takes minutes. Chemical: Photopigments bleach → signal cascade → regenerate in dark. pH shifts: dark = 7.3, light = 7.0. Electrical: Phototransduction → receptor potential → propagates to ganglion cells → optic nerve. Fastest.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"The 6 Cardinal Points of the schematic eye: OBJECT SPACE | IMAGE SPACE | F₁ H H' N N' F₂ | | | | | | | | | | | | ← → ~15mm in front ← → 1.6mm | 1.9mm 7.1mm | 7.4mm ~24mm behind → (primary focal pt) (principal planes) (nodal pts) (secondary focal pt) F₁ = Primary focal point — object here → parallel exit rays F₂ = Secondary focal point — parallel rays from ∞ converge here (on retina in emmetropia) H, H' = Principal planes — where refraction is \\\"considered\\\" to occur N, N' = Nodal points — rays through here pass undeviated; angle alpha measured at N Rods vs Cones — key comparison: Feature Rods Cones Count ~120 million ~6 million Location Peripheral; max density ~20° from fovea; ABSENT at fovea and optic disc Concentrated at fovea; max density ~150,000/mm² at fovea Photopigment Rhodopsin (507nm) Erythrolabe (R ~750nm), Chlorolabe (G ~535nm), Cyanolabe (B ~440nm) Vision type Scotopic (dim, monochrome, motion) Photopic (bright, color, acuity) Convergence Many rods → 1 ganglion cell (high sensitivity, low acuity) 1 cone → 1 ganglion cell at fovea (high acuity) Cortical representation — 25% of visual cortex for 6M cones Dark adaptation Slow (30–40 min) Fast (7 min) Board clue \\\"Averted vision\\\" — look 15–20° off-center to see dim targets better \\\"Central fixation\\\" — direct gaze gives maximum acuity\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Scotopic vs Photopic vision: Feature Scotopic Photopic Photoreceptor Rods Cones Peak wavelength 507 nm (blue-green) 555 nm (yellow-green) Color perception No (monochrome) Yes (3 cone types) Dominant region Peripheral retina Fovea Active in Dim / dark conditions Bright conditions Dark adaptation time 30–40 min (full) 7 min Purkinje shift in clinical context: A red flower and a blue flower look equally vivid at noon (photopic; yellow-green peak). At dusk, the blue flower looks brighter because the visual system shifts to rod-mediated scotopic peak (507nm — blue-green range). Red objects become relatively darker at low light. Visual threshold factors — what lowers the threshold (increases sensitivity): Factor Direction Mechanism Dark adaptation ↓ threshold Rhodopsin regenerates; rod sensitivity increases Optimal wavelength ↓ threshold Green/blue-green for dark; yellow-green for light Bunsen-Roscoe Law Temporal summation Intensity × Time = constant (up to ~100ms for rods) Ricco's Law (spatial summation) Larger area → ↓ threshold Intensity × Area = constant (within critical area) Larger pupil ↓ threshold More photons entering Binocular viewing ↓ threshold Combined neural signal from both eyes\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Rod peak sensitivity 507 nm Scotopic; also peak for dark-adapted ERG Cone peak sensitivity 555 nm Photopic; why amber glasses reduce glare Rod max density ~150,000/mm² at 20° periphery Averted vision targets this zone Foveal cone density ~150,000/mm² Highest acuity zone Full dark adaptation 30–40 minutes Rhodopsin regeneration limited; impaired in Vit A deficiency Kohlrausch kink ~7 minutes Cones plateau; rods take over Dark adaptation improvement ~3 log units Rods 1000× more sensitive than cones at full adaptation Retinal pH (dark) 7.3 (alkaline) Resting metabolic state Retinal pH (light) 7.0 (acidic) Increased metabolic activity Y-axis (AP) length 24 mm Longest — full eyeball depth X and Z axes 22 mm each Equal; shorter than AP Center of rotation 13.5 mm behind cornea All axes pass through here Angle alpha normal 5° temporal, 1.5° inferior Fovea nasal to optical axis Adult IPD average 62.5 mm Used in spectacle dispensing Normal pupil range 2–5 mm (physiologic 3–4 mm) Miotic ≤1.5 mm; mydriatic >5 mm F₂ (secondary focal point) ~24 mm behind cornea On retina in emmetropia\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Axes — \\\"ATV 24-22-22\\\" Anteroposterior = Torsion (24mm); Transverse = Vertical (22mm); Vertical = Horizontal (22mm) Cone pigments — \\\"ECG — Erythrolabe-Chlorolabe-Cyanolabe\\\" E = Red (erythro = red, 750nm); C = Green (chloro = green, 535nm); G = Blue (cyano = blue, 440nm) Scotopic vs Photopic wavelengths — \\\"507 for Rods; 555 for Cones\\\" Both have two 5's but rods come first (507) and are less (5-0-7) than cones (5-5-5). Retinal pH — \\\"Dark is Basic (7.3); Light is Acid (7.0)\\\" Bright light → metabolic activity → slightly acidic. Threshold factors — \\\"Dark Wavelength Bunsen Ricco Pupil Binocular\\\" D-W-B-R-P-B (6 factors; first two relate to the type of stimulus, last four to the eye/system). Angle kappa board clue \\\"Positive kappa = pupil nasal → reflex temporal → pseudo-exo\\\" \\\"Negative kappa = pupil temporal → reflex nasal → pseudo-eso\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"DARK ADAPTATION CURVE ───────────────────── Threshold ↑ (less sensitive) | | CONES — adapt fast (7 min) | \\\\ | '------ KINK (~7 min; rods take over) | \\\\ | RODS — keep adapting (30–40 min) | '------------ plateau Threshold ↓ (most sensitive) |_____________________________ Time (min) 0 7 30-40 CARDINAL POINTS (schematic eye cross-section) ───────────────────────────────────────────── F₁ ← ~15mm → |H H'| ← ~7mm → |N N'| ← ~17mm → F₂ = RETINA ↑ ↑ Principal Nodal points planes (undeviated rays; (virtual angle α here) refraction) EOM AXES (through center of rotation, 13.5mm behind cornea) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Y-axis (front → back; 24mm) = TORSION X- axis (side → side; 22mm) = VERTICAL movement Z-axis (top → bottom; 22mm) = HORIZONTAL movement\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"The Y-axis controls horizontal eye movements The Z-axis (vertical axis) controls horizontal (adduction/abduction). Y-axis = torsion. Positive kappa means the patient has exotropia Positive kappa means the reflex appears temporal on Hirschberg, simulating exotropia. Cover test is negative — it is pseudo-exotropia. Full dark adaptation takes 7 minutes Cones adapt in 7 minutes. Full rod-based dark adaptation takes 30–40 minutes. The fovea is the area with the highest rod density Rods are ABSENT from the fovea. The fovea has the highest cone density. Angle alpha is measured at the pupil Angle alpha is measured at the nodal point. Angle kappa is measured at the pupil. Ricco's Law applies to temporal summation Ricco's law applies to spatial summation (area × intensity = constant within the critical area). Bunsen-Roscoe applies to temporal summation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer EOM axes (movement type) Y = torsion (24mm); X = vertical (22mm); Z = horizontal (22mm) AP axis length 24 mm (longest) Scotopic peak wavelength 507 nm (rod, blue-green) Photopic peak wavelength 555 nm (cone, yellow-green) Purkinje shift Photopic → Scotopic: peak shifts 555nm → 507nm Cone dark adaptation 7 minutes Full dark adaptation 30–40 minutes (rods) Kohlrausch kink ~7 min — cones plateau, rods take over Retinal pH dark/light Dark = 7.3 (alkaline); Light = 7.0 (acidic) Angle alpha Optical vs visual axis; at nodal point; 5° temporal Positive kappa Pseudo-exotropia (reflex appears temporal) Secondary focal point F₂ ~24mm behind cornea = on retina in emmetropia Cone pigments (RGB) Erythrolabe (R), Chlorolabe (G), Cyanolabe (B) Ricco's Law Spatial summation: Area × Intensity = constant Bunsen-Roscoe Law Temporal summation: Time × Intensity = constant\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"1. During Hirschberg testing, the corneal light reflex falls approximately 1mm temporal to the corneal center in both eyes. Cover test reveals no movement. What is the most likely explanation? A. Bilateral exotropia B. Positive angle kappa C. Negative angle kappa D. Large angle alpha Answer B. Positive angle kappa. Positive angle kappa exists when the center of the entrance pupil is nasal to the visual axis. Because the pupil is nasal, the corneal light reflex appears displaced temporally — simulating exotropia on Hirschberg. The negative cover test confirms no real deviation is present. This is pseudo-exotropia due to positive angle kappa. Negative kappa would produce a nasal reflex displacement (pseudo-esotropia). Angle alpha is measured at the nodal point and does not produce this clinical finding directly. 2. A patient is tested in a dark room after 40 minutes of adaptation. At what wavelength of monochromatic light would their visual threshold be lowest? A. 440 nm B. 507 nm C. 535 nm D. 555 nm Answer B. 507 nm. After 40 minutes of dark adaptation, the visual system is operating in scotopic mode — driven entirely by rods. Rods have maximum sensitivity at approximately 507 nm (blue-green). The 555 nm peak applies to photopic (cone-driven) conditions. 440 nm is the S-cone peak (cyanolabe), relevant in photopic color vision. 535 nm is the M-cone (chlorolabe) peak. In scotopic conditions, all three cone types are essentially inactive, and rod sensitivity dominates. 3. A patient's rhodopsin cannot regenerate after light exposure. Which step in the visual cycle is most likely impaired? A. Photoisomerization of 11-cis retinal in the outer segment B. Transport of all-trans retinal from photoreceptors to RPE C. Re-isomerization of all-trans retinal to 11-cis retinal in the RPE D. Release of glutamate at the synaptic terminal in the dark Answer C. Re-isomerization of all-trans retinal to 11-cis retinal in the RPE. Rhodopsin regeneration depends on recycling spent chromophore (all-trans retinal) back to its usable form (11-cis retinal). This enzymatic re-isomerization occurs in the RPE, not in the photoreceptor outer segment. After light hits rhodopsin, 11-cis retinal photoisomerizes to all-trans (Step A — this is the TRIGGER, not the regeneration step). All-trans retinal exits the photoreceptor and enters the RPE where the RPE65 enzyme converts it back to 11-cis retinal (Step C). RPE65 mutations cause Leber congenital amaurosis — a genetic cause of severe visual impairment. Option B (transport) is a prerequisite for C but not the regeneration step itself. Option D (glutamate release) is the dark-current synapse activity, unrelated to regeneration.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"VISUAL SYSTEM AND OCULAR OPTICS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: 3 axes with movements and lengths, 4 angles of the eye with what they measure, rod/cone peak wavelengths, dark adaptation timeline, 6 cardinal points of schematic eye. Core targets: EOM axes: name, movement type, length Angle kappa: what it is, positive vs negative clinical finding Dark adaptation: two phases with timing and what happens at the kink Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the dark adaptation curve from memory — label the x-axis (time) and y-axis (threshold), mark the Kohlrausch kink at 7 min, label the cone phase and rod phase, mark full adaptation at 30–40 min. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a patient why they cannot see well for the first 5 minutes after walking into a dark movie theater — starting from the photopigment level, through the cell type, to the subjective experience. Do not use \\\"adaptation\\\" until your final sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Y-axis movement? Torsion (intorsion/extorsion); 24mm Z-axis movement? Horizontal (adduction/abduction); 22mm Scotopic peak wavelength? 507 nm (rods; blue-green) Photopic peak wavelength? 555 nm (cones; yellow-green) Kohlrausch kink at? ~7 minutes Full dark adaptation time? 30–40 minutes Retinal pH in dark? 7.3 (alkaline) Positive kappa → Reflex temporal → pseudo-exotropia Cone pigments (3)? Erythrolabe, Chlorolabe, Cyanolabe F₂ location? ~24mm behind cornea (on retina in emmetropia) Phototransduction step 1? Photoisomerization: 11-cis → all-trans retinal cGMP in darkness → ? cGMP open Na⁺ channels → depolarization → glutamate release cGMP in light → ? PDE degrades cGMP → channels close → hyperpolarization → less glutamate Visual cycle: all-trans retinal recycled where? RPE (regenerated to 11-cis) Vitamin A deficiency first sign? Nyctalopia (night blindness) — rhodopsin not regenerated Saccadic fixation type? Fast voluntary jumps between targets 6 reference lines of the eye — which is clinically most used? Visual axis (nodal point to fovea) Seidel's 5 monochromatic aberrations? Spherical, coma, oblique astigmatism, curvature of field, distortion RAM GAP mnemonic? Retina closer → Add Minus; Retina farther → Add Plus Angle kappa: temporal reflex → Positive kappa → pseudo-exotropia appearance Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the sequence of retinal changes that occur when a patient walks from bright sunlight into a dark room — starting at the chemical level through migratory, chemical, and electrical changes, and ending at full rod dark adaptation. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Dark adaptation curve + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (dark theater) 4th 1 week Full retinal light/dark sequence Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-accommodation-mechanism-ametropia-intro-entoptic-phenomena-and-flicker-accommodation-full-coverage\",\"heading\":\"Accommodation — Full Coverage\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Scheiner's Experiment (1619): A card with two pinholes (separated less than the pupil diameter) is held in front of the eye. An object NOT focused on the retina appears DOUBLE through the two pinholes. An object IN FOCUS on the retina appears SINGLE. This experiment proved accommodation EXISTS and that the eye actively adjusts its focus — it was the first objective proof of accommodation. Purkinje-Sanson Images: Reflections (catoptric images) formed by the cornea and lens surfaces. There are THREE pairs: Image 1: Corneal front surface → upright, virtual, bright (used in keratometry — measures corneal curvature) Image 2: Lens front surface → upright, virtual, dim (moves forward during accommodation as anterior lens becomes more convex) Image 3: Lens back surface → inverted, real, smallest (moves backward slightly during accommodation) During accommodation: Image 2 moves FORWARD and becomes SMALLER (lens front surface steepens). Image 3 moves BACKWARD slightly. Image 1 is unchanged (cornea does not change shape). Clinical use: Helmholtz (1855) used Purkinje images to prove the lens changes shape during accommodation, not the cornea or axial length. Theories of Accommodation: HELMHOLTZ THEORY (1855) — accepted as correct: At REST : Zonules are TAUT (stretched by ciliary ring diameter) Lens is FLAT and thin (held in its thinnest form by tension) During ACCOMMODATION (near): Ciliary muscle CONTRACTS (annular action, ring tightens) Zonules RELAX (tension released) Lens springs to natural spherical shape ( MORE CONVEX , more power) Pupil constricts, eyes converge (the near triad) Why the lens springs: The elastic lens capsule is always trying to make the lens spherical. The taut zonules prevent this at rest. Relaxing the zonules frees the capsule → sphere. Near Point, Far Point, and Range of Accommodation: FAR POINT (punctum remotum) — the point at infinity (∞) that the eye can see clearly Emmetrope: far point = infinity (∞) Myope: far point is at a FINITE distance IN FRONT of the eye Far point distance = 100 / degree of myopia Example: −3.00D myope → far point = 100/3 = 33cm in front Hyperope: far point is VIRTUAL (behind the eye) NEAR POINT (punctum proximum) — the closest point the eye can clearly focus (with maximum accommodation) Near point distance = 100 / (far point power + AOA ) Normal 20-year-old ( AOA ≈ 10D): near point ≈ 10cm RANGE OF ACCOMMODATION — distance between near point and far point Emmetrope: from ∞ to near point Myope: from far point to near point (both finite) AMPLITUDE OF ACCOMMODATION ( AOA ) — vergence change from far point to near point AOA = Far point power − Near point power (in diopters) Decreases with age (Hofstetter: Ave = 18.5 − 0.30 × age) Donder's Table (clinically important values by age): Age Ave. AOA (D) Near point (cm) 10 14.0 7 20 12.0 8.5 30 9.0 11 40 6.0 17 45 4.0 25 50 2.5 40 60 1.0 100 Accommodation asthenopia: Symptoms of eyestrain from excessive or ill-sustained accommodation. Includes: frontal headache, blurred vision, eye fatigue especially after near work. Caused by: uncorrected hyperopia (must accommodate even at distance), convergence insufficiency, accommodative insufficiency.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-accommodation-mechanism-ametropia-intro-entoptic-phenomena-and-flicker-ametropia-introductory-syllabi-3-0\",\"heading\":\"Ametropia — Introductory (Syllabi 3.0)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Classification by mechanism: AXIAL AMETROPIA : Abnormal axial length; refractive power is normal Myopia → eye TOO LONG → focal point in front of retina Hyperopia → eye TOO SHORT → focal point behind retina REFRACTIVE AMETROPIA : Normal axial length; refractive power abnormal High n (aqueous, cornea, lens nucleus) → myopia Low n (lens cortex, vitreous) → hyperopia Changed corneal curvature → any ametropia LAW OF SILO (Index Ametropia): Applies when the ametropia is due to the index of refraction of the various media: Crystalline lens cortex: Lower n than average → nucleus: Higher n than average Changes in lens index with disease (e.g., cataract) → can cause myopic shift BRACHYCEPHALIA vs DOLICHOCEPHALIA : Brachycephalia (short, wide skull) → associated with hyperopia Dolichocephalia (long, narrow skull) → associated with myopia (Skull shape affects orbital depth and axial length development)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-accommodation-mechanism-ametropia-intro-entoptic-phenomena-and-flicker-entoptic-phenomena-syllabi-4-5\",\"heading\":\"Entoptic Phenomena (Syllabi 4.5)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Entoptic phenomena are visual perceptions generated by structures of your own eye — things you see that are inside the eye itself rather than out in the world. Types of entoptic phenomena: Phenomenon Source Description Floaters (muscae volitantes) Vitreous opacities (remnants of hyaloid vessels) Dark shapes drifting across the visual field; move with eye; more visible against bright backgrounds Purkinje figures Retinal blood vessels Image of your own retinal vessels; seen with oblique illumination into the eye Blue field entoptic (Scheerer's phenomenon) WBCs moving in perifoveal capillaries Tiny bright dots moving along squiggly lines in blue light; indicates intact perifoveal circulation Phosphene Mechanical or electrical retinal stimulation Light seen without actual light entering eye; pressure on eye → flashing Halos Cornea or lens (diffraction of light) Colored rings around lights; physiologic = lens fiber diffraction; pathologic = corneal edema (high IOP), cataract After-images Photoreceptor overstimulation Negative: opposite color, over-stimulated cones; Positive: same color, dark-adapted eye Moore's lightning streaks Vitreoretinal traction Flashes of light, especially in peripheral field; associated with posterior vitreous detachment Clinical importance of entoptic phenomena: New floaters + flashes (photopsiae/phosphenes) = posterior vitreous detachment → refer for retinal exam; may indicate retinal tear Halos around lights = corneal edema (consider acute angle-closure glaucoma) vs. lens (cataract) Blue field entoptic absent = macular disease (compromised perifoveal circulation)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-accommodation-mechanism-ametropia-intro-entoptic-phenomena-and-flicker-flicker-and-critical-fusion-frequency-syllabi-8-0\",\"heading\":\"Flicker and Critical Fusion Frequency (Syllabi 8.0)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Repetitive stimulation and flicker: When a light is turned on and off rapidly, it appears to flicker at low frequencies As the frequency increases, the flickering eventually disappears and the light appears steady The frequency at which flickering merges into steady illumination = Critical Fusion Frequency (CFF) CFF NORMAL VALUES : Photopic (daylight): ~60 Hz Scotopic (dim): ~15–20 Hz Fovea: higher CFF than periphery (faster temporal resolution) FERRY-PORTER LAW : CFF increases linearly with log luminance TALBOT 'S LAW : When flicker rate exceeds CFF , perceived brightness = average of on/off intensities CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE : Decreased CFF → early sign of optic nerve disease, glaucoma CFF testing: used to detect subclinical optic nerve dysfunction before visual field loss Video/film: 24 fps appears continuous because it exceeds the CFF for those conditions\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-accommodation-mechanism-ametropia-intro-entoptic-phenomena-and-flicker-optical-illusions-syllabi-17-0\",\"heading\":\"Optical Illusions (Syllabi 17.0)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Optical illusions demonstrate that perception is not a direct recording of reality — the brain actively processes and sometimes misinterprets visual information. Categories: 1. GEOMETRIC ILLUSIONS — size, length, or angle appear different than measured: Müller-Lyer illusion: lines with arrows in vs. out appear different lengths Ponzo illusion: parallel lines appear different lengths on converging railroad tracks Horizontal-vertical illusion: vertical line appears longer than equal horizontal line 2. AMBIGUOUS FIGURES — two interpretations exist simultaneously: Necker cube: 3D cube flips orientation Rubin's vase: vase or two faces alternate 3. AFTERIMAGE-BASED ILLUSIONS : Stare at a color → look away → see the complementary color (opponent process) Red fatigue → look at white → see green (red afterimage) 4. MOTION ILLUSIONS : Static images appear to move due to high-contrast gradients BOARD RELEVANCE : Illusions demonstrate: retinal adaptation (afterimages), opponent process (complementary colors), figure-ground perception (ambiguous figures), context effects on size/distance judgment. These connect to B4 (color theories) and B2 (visual perception organization).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-phototransduction-cascade-fixation-types-and-reference-lines-of-the-eye-phototransduction-cascade-the-full-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"Phototransduction Cascade — The Full Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Why it matters: The board tests the specific molecular steps, where Vitamin A fits, and why its deficiency causes night blindness first. The cascade — rods (rhodopsin system): STEP 1 — AT REST ( DARK ) 11-cis retinal + opsin → RHODOPSIN (intact photopigment, purple-red) cGMP-gated Na+ channels are OPEN in the dark → constant Na+ influx → photoreceptor is DEPOLARIZED (dark current) → continuous glutamate release onto bipolar cells STEP 2 — LIGHT STRIKES RHODOPSIN Photon energy → PHOTOISOMERIZATION 11-cis retinal flips → ALL-TRANS RETINAL Rhodopsin → METARHODOPSIN II (activated form) Called \\\"photo-bleaching\\\" — rhodopsin loses its purple color → appears pale/yellow STEP 3 — TRANSDUCIN ACTIVATION (G-protein cascade) Metarhodopsin II activates TRANSDUCIN (a G-protein) 1 rhodopsin → activates ~500 transducin molecules (amplification factor x500 — explains extreme sensitivity of rods to single photons) STEP 4 — PHOSPHODIESTERASE ( PDE ) ACTIVATION Transducin activates PDE (phosphodiesterase) PDE hydrolyzes cGMP → 5'- GMP (inactive) cGMP levels FALL rapidly inside the photoreceptor STEP 5 — CHANNEL CLOSURE → HYPERPOLARIZATION cGMP-gated channels CLOSE (no cGMP to keep them open) Na+ entry STOPS → membrane potential goes from −40mV → −70mV Photoreceptor HYPERPOLARIZES in response to LIGHT (Key: light causes hyperpolarization — opposite of all other neurons) STEP 6 — SIGNAL OUTPUT CHANGE Hyperpolarized photoreceptor → DECREASED glutamate release Bipolar cells detect this decrease → signal passes to ganglion cells → optic nerve Critical rule: Photoreceptors are the only sensory neurons that HYPERPOLARIZE in response to their stimulus. Every other neuron depolarizes to fire a signal. This is routinely tested. The Visual Cycle (Rhodopsin Regeneration): BLEACHED (all-trans retinal is released from opsin) ↓ All-trans retinal → ALL-TRANS RETINOL (= Vitamin A — reduced form) [carried via IRBP to RPE ] ↓ RPE processes: all-trans retinol → 11- CIS RETINAL (requires RPE isomerase enzyme) ↓ 11-cis retinal returned to photoreceptor outer segment ↓ Recombines with opsin → RHODOPSIN regenerated (ready for next photon) This cycle is CONTINUOUS in the dark. It requires VITAMIN A (all-trans retinol) as the essential precursor. No Vitamin A = no 11-cis retinal = no rhodopsin regeneration. Vitamin A deficiency — clinical cascade (sequence for boards): Low Vitamin A intake / malabsorption ↓ Impaired 11-cis retinal regeneration in RPE ↓ Rhodopsin cannot regenerate fully between bleaching cycles ↓ NYCTALOPIA (night blindness) — FIRST and earliest symptom ↓ (prolonged deficiency) XEROPHTHALMIA — conjunctival and corneal drying BITOT 'S SPOTS — foamy keratinized plaques on bulbar conjunctiva (temporal) ↓ (severe, untreated) KERATOMALACIA — corneal ulceration, liquefaction, melting BLINDNESS — irreversible corneal scarring Cone phototransduction — same molecular pathway but different photopigments: Cone type Pigment Peak wavelength Action S-cones (blue) Cyanolabe 440 nm Same transducin → PDE → cGMP cascade M-cones (green) Chlorolabe 535 nm Same cascade L-cones (red) Erythrolabe ~750 nm (effectively ~560nm) Same cascade Dark vs. light photoreceptor state — the board comparison: Parameter Dark (no stimulus) Light (stimulus present) cGMP level HIGH LOW (PDE hydrolyzes it) Na+ channels OPEN CLOSED Na+ entry Flowing in (dark current) Stopped Membrane potential ~−40 mV (depolarized) ~−70 mV (hyperpolarized) Glutamate release HIGH (continuous) LOW (decreased) Visual signal No signal Signal sent to bipolar cells\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-phototransduction-cascade-fixation-types-and-reference-lines-of-the-eye-fixation-types-elements-and-reference-lines\",\"heading\":\"Fixation — Types, Elements, and Reference Lines\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"What fixation is: The coordinated motor and sensory act of aiming the fovea at a target and holding it there. Three anatomical elements must work together. The three elements of fixation: 1. THE FOVEA (sensory element) The target's image must fall on the foveal center (foveola) Best cone packing → 2-cone separation → ~1 arcmin resolution Any sustained fixation on a non-foveal area = ECCENTRIC FIXATION 2. THE EXTRAOCULAR MUSCLES (motor element) Hold the eye steady against physiological drift Produce microsaccades to prevent perceptual fading (Troxler's effect) Three components of physiological nystagmus: tremor, drift, microsaccades 3. THE FUSION FACULTY (binocular element) Maintains binocular fixation on the same point simultaneously Requires normal retinal correspondence ( NRC ) Lost in constant strabismus / deep amblyopia The six types of fixation: TYPE DESCRIPTION KEY FEATURE Voluntary Conscious, directed, intentional Requires attention; can be sustained Reflex Automatic response to new peripheral Triggered by stimulus entering VF; (Involuntary) stimulus entering the visual field not under conscious control Saccadic Rapid, ballistic refixation between FASTEST (500–1000°/s); 200ms latency two targets Cannot be corrected mid-flight Smooth Pursuit Continuous tracking of a moving Max ~30°/s; needs a moving target (Pursuit) target Falls apart without a target Scanning Series of saccades across a static Used in reading, scene analysis, scene visual search tasks Steady Maintained fixation on a single Physiological nystagmus keeps it non-moving target slightly active; never truly static Board clue for fixation types: \\\"Fastest = Saccadic | Moving target = Pursuit | Automatic to peripheral flash = Reflex\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-phototransduction-cascade-fixation-types-and-reference-lines-of-the-eye-reference-lines-of-the-eye\",\"heading\":\"Reference Lines of the Eye\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Eight imaginary lines define how the eye relates to visual space. The board tests the differences between the most similar-sounding ones. REFERENCE LINE DEFINITION ANGLE IT DEFINES ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Visual axis From fixation point → through NODAL Angle ALPHA POINTS (N, N') → to FOVEA (at nodal point) \\\"True optical line of clear sight\\\" Line of sight From fixation point → through center Angle KAPPA of ENTRANCE PUPIL → to FOVEA (at entrance pupil) \\\"Clinical surrogate for visual axis\\\" Optic axis Through centers of curvature of all Used in schematic eye refracting surfaces (cornea to lens) calculations only NOT the same as visual axis Pupillary axis PERPENDICULAR to corneal surface, Defines Angle KAPPA passing through the CENTER OF THE (pupillary axis vs line ENTRANCE PUPIL of sight) and LAMBDA Fixation axis From fixation point → through the Angle GAMMA CENTER OF ROTATION (13.5mm behind (at center of rotation) cornea) Rarely board-tested Anteroposterior From anterior pole → to posterior pole Y-axis of Fick (torsion) (AP) axis Longest axis of the eye (24mm) Cyclopean axis From the CYCLOPEAN EYE (midpoint Used in binocular space (median line) between both pupils) → through perception; not directly fixation point tested clinically Line of direction Connects any object point to its Basis of retinal retinal image through the nodal point correspondence (local sign) The most commonly confused pair — visual axis vs line of sight: VISUAL AXIS LINE OF SIGHT Passes through NODAL POINTS Passes through CENTER OF PUPIL Angle ALPHA measured here Angle KAPPA measured here More theoretical construct Clinically relevant (Hirschberg) Cannot be directly observed Hirschberg reflex tests this Angles summary table (complete): Angle Between these two lines Measured at Normal value Clinical test Alpha (α) Visual axis vs Optic axis Nodal point 5° temporal, 1.5° inferior Theoretical Kappa (κ) Pupillary axis vs Line of sight Entrance pupil Small positive Hirschberg test Lambda (λ) Pupillary axis vs Line of sight Exit pupil Similar to kappa Optical calculations Gamma (γ) Fixation axis vs Optic axis Center of rotation Small positive Rarely tested Angle kappa Hirschberg interpretation: POSITIVE KAPPA : Pupil center is NASAL to the visual axis → Corneal reflex falls TEMPORAL to pupil center → Looks like EXOTROPIA on Hirschberg (pseudo-exo) → Cover test NEGATIVE (no movement = no real tropia) Normal in most people (small positive kappa is physiologic) NEGATIVE KAPPA : Pupil center is TEMPORAL to the visual axis → Corneal reflex falls NASAL to pupil center → Looks like ESOTROPIA on Hirschberg (pseudo-eso) → Cover test NEGATIVE Seen in: high myopia (fovea displaced further temporal) RULE : Large positive kappa = pseudo-exotropia; Negative kappa = pseudo-esotropia\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-phototransduction-cascade-fixation-types-and-reference-lines-of-the-eye-board-traps-extended\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps — Extended\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Light causes photoreceptors to depolarize (fire) Light causes photoreceptors to HYPERPOLARIZE by closing Na+ channels. They are tonically active in the dark and go quieter in the light. Vitamin A is needed to make cGMP Vitamin A (retinol) is the precursor for 11-cis retinal, which recombines with opsin to reform rhodopsin. cGMP is made from GTP by guanylyl cyclase — it is NOT a Vitamin A derivative. The visual axis passes through the center of the pupil The LINE OF SIGHT passes through the pupil center. The visual axis passes through the NODAL POINTS. Saccadic fixation follows a moving target SMOOTH PURSUIT follows a moving target. Saccadic fixation is a ballistic refixation jump between two points. The cyclopean eye is the dominant eye The cyclopean eye is the imaginary point midway between both eyes — it has nothing to do with ocular dominance.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-optical-aberrations-of-the-eye-the-plain-version-first\",\"heading\":\"The Plain Version First\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"A perfect lens takes every ray from an object point and converges them all to the exact same image point. Real lenses — including the eye — don't do this perfectly. Some rays end up converging at a slightly different point than others. The result is a blurred or distorted image even when there is no refractive error. These imperfections are called optical aberrations . There are two categories: monochromatic aberrations (happen with single-wavelength light — geometry problem) and chromatic aberrations (happen because different wavelengths bend differently — a wavelength problem).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-optical-aberrations-of-the-eye-monochromatic-aberrations-seidel-s-five\",\"heading\":\"Monochromatic Aberrations — Seidel's Five\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"These are named after Ludwig Seidel (1857) who mathematically described the 5 types. They occur because real optical surfaces are not mathematically perfect. Think of it this way: rays hitting the center of a lens and rays hitting the edge don't focus at exactly the same point — that mismatch is what all five aberrations describe in different ways. ABERRATION 1: SPHERICAL ABERRATION What it is: Peripheral rays focus at a DIFFERENT point than central (paraxial) rays Plain version: The edge of the lens is a slightly different power than the center. Peripheral rays → converge closer to the lens (short focal point) Central rays → converge farther (long focal point) Result: A point source becomes a blurred circle (\\\"blur circle\\\") on the retina Clinical relevance: - LARGER PUPIL = MORE spherical aberration (more peripheral rays enter) - Pupil constriction REDUCES spherical aberration (limits entry of peripheral rays) - This is why vision is slightly sharper in bright light (miotic pupil) - Aspheric lens designs compensate by flattening the peripheral curve ABERRATION 2: CHROMATIC ABERRATION What it is: DIFFERENT WAVELENGTHS focus at DIFFERENT points Plain version: Blue light bends more than red light because it has a higher index of refraction. Blue → shorter focal length → focuses IN FRONT of retina Red → longer focal length → focuses BEHIND retina Types: LONGITUDINAL chromatic aberration ( LCA ): focal points differ along the axis Blue (short λ) → focuses ~2D more powerfully than red Measured in diopters; approximately 2.5D total range in the human eye TRANSVERSE chromatic aberration ( TCA ): colored fringes at the edge of objects Different wavelengths hit different retinal locations Seen as colored halos around high-contrast edges Clinical relevance: - BICHROME TEST (duochrome test) uses LCA : Red and green backgrounds → if image is on retina, red/green letters are equal clarity Letters clearer on RED → over-minused (push lens to red/less minus) Letters clearer on GREEN → under-minused (pull lens to green/more minus) - Abbe value (v-number): measures how much a lens material disperses light HIGH Abbe = LOW chromatic aberration = better image quality LOW Abbe = HIGH chromatic aberration = more color fringing Abbe value of human cornea: ~57; crystalline lens: ~47 ABERRATION 3: COMA What it is: Off-axis point sources produce comet-shaped blur (not round) Plain version: When you look at a point of light that is off to the side, the peripheral rays from different parts of the pupil focus at different heights. The result is a smeared, comet-tail distortion — wider toward the edges of the image. Key feature: Coma is worst for oblique rays (off-axis objects) The \\\"tail\\\" of the comet always points toward the center of the image Board clue: Coma = off-axis comet shape ABERRATION 4: ASTIGMATISM OF OBLIQUE INCIDENCE (Oblique Astigmatism) What it is: Oblique rays form two focal lines (like regular astigmatism) but this is purely a lens geometry problem, not a corneal problem Plain version: When light hits a lens at an angle (not straight on), the lens acts like it has two different powers — a vertical focus and a horizontal focus. This happens even with a perfect spherical lens for off-axis targets. Distinguish from regular astigmatism: Regular astigmatism = due to corneal/lens toric surface Oblique astigmatism = due to angle of incidence at any surface Clinical relevance: Large minus lenses produce oblique astigmatism at the lens periphery → \\\"swim\\\" phenomenon in strong minus glasses when looking off-center ABERRATION 5: CURVATURE OF FIELD (Petzval Field Curvature) What it is: The sharpest focus of a lens lies on a CURVED surface, not a flat plane Plain version: Imagine focusing a projector onto a flat wall — but the sharpest image actually exists on a curved surface. The center is sharp but the edges are blurry, or if you focus the edges, the center goes blurry. In the eye: The retina is curved, which partially compensates for this aberration. The eye's curved retina actually HELPS reduce the blur from curvature of field. Board clue: Curvature of field is REDUCED by the curved retina of the eye ABERRATION 6: DISTORTION What it is: Magnification varies across the image — straight lines appear bent Plain version: Objects at the edge of the image appear larger or smaller than they should be relative to objects at the center. BARREL DISTORTION : edges appear compressed inward (like a barrel) → seen with minus lenses (diverging) PINCUSHION DISTORTION : edges appear expanded outward (like a pincushion) → seen with plus lenses (converging) Board clue: \\\"Barrel = minus; Pincushion = plus\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-optical-aberrations-of-the-eye-chromatic-aberration-the-bichrome-test-clinical-application\",\"heading\":\"Chromatic Aberration — The Bichrome Test (Clinical Application)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"This is the most board-tested aberration because it has a direct clinical test: BICHROME TEST PRINCIPLE : Background: Red and green (wavelengths flanking yellow focus point) LCA means: Red letters → focal point is BEHIND the green letters' focal point Green letters → focal point is in FRONT of the red letters' focal point Correct Rx → letters appear EQUALLY CLEAR on both halves Interpretation: Clearer on RED (over-corrected minus / under-corrected plus): → Focal point has moved TOO FAR behind the retina (over-powered) → Reduce minus (or add plus) — \\\"push toward red\\\" Clearer on GREEN (under-corrected minus / over-corrected plus): → Focal point is still in front of the retina (under-powered) → Add minus (or reduce plus) — \\\"pull toward green\\\" Mnemonic: \\\" RAM GAP \\\" R = Red → Add Minus G = Green → Add Plus (Or: Red = Reduce minus; Green = Give more minus)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-optical-aberrations-of-the-eye-comparison-table-all-6-aberrations\",\"heading\":\"Comparison Table: All 6 Aberrations\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Aberration Type What blurs Key clinical connection Spherical Monochromatic Central vs peripheral rays Pupil size matters; aspheric lenses Chromatic Chromatic Different wavelengths Bichrome test; Abbe value Coma Monochromatic Off-axis point sources Comet-tail blur at lens periphery Oblique astigmatism Monochromatic Off-axis oblique rays \\\"Swim\\\" in strong minus lenses Curvature of field Monochromatic Flat image on curved surface Retinal curve compensates Distortion Monochromatic Magnification varies Barrel (minus), pincushion (plus)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1-01-visual-system-and-ocular-optics-extended-topics-optical-aberrations-of-the-eye-board-traps-aberrations\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps (Aberrations)\",\"topic\":\"B1-01 — Visual System and Ocular Optics\",\"text\":\"Chromatic aberration is caused by the cornea being toric Chromatic aberration is caused by different wavelengths bending different amounts. Toric cornea causes regular astigmatism — not chromatic aberration. A smaller pupil increases spherical aberration Smaller pupil REDUCES spherical aberration by blocking peripheral rays. Larger pupil lets in more oblique rays and worsens spherical aberration. Letters clearer on green in the bichrome test means add more minus Clearer on GREEN means the image is in front of the retina (under-minused) — you need to ADD MINUS to bring it back. \\\"Green = Give more minus.\\\" Barrel distortion is seen with plus lenses Barrel distortion = minus lenses (edges compressed). Pincushion distortion = plus lenses (edges expanded). Curvature of field is corrected by flattening the retina The curved retina COMPENSATES for curvature of field — the eye's natural curve is a built-in correction for this aberration.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Visual perception is what the brain does with what the eyes send. The retinal signal travels through six relay stations to reach the visual cortex, but \\\"seeing\\\" doesn't happen at the retina — it happens at the cortex and beyond. Beyond Area 17 (the primary visual cortex), two parallel streams process what objects are (the ventral \\\"what\\\" pathway) and where they are (the dorsal \\\"where\\\" pathway). The LGB organizes input from both eyes into distinct layers before passing it along. The key clinical insight: a patient can have perfect retinal and optical function yet still fail to perceive what they see — because perception is brain function, not just eye function. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Can a person have 20/20 acuity and still not be able to recognize their mother's face?\\\" Yes — prosopagnosia, a ventral pathway lesion. That answer separates sight from perception.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Why does the LGB have separate layers for each eye? Because the brain maintains eye-of-origin information even at this relay stage — it is the last point where the two eyes' signals are segregated. This segregation is important for binocular rivalry and for understanding amblyopia (where one eye's cortical representation is suppressed at the LGB level). Why are cortical areas 18 and 19 needed when area 17 already receives the signal? Because area 17 only registers basic features — orientation, contrast, spatial frequency. Making sense of those features (recognizing a face, tracking a moving object, reading a word) requires further processing in areas 18 and 19 and beyond.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Area striata (V1) Latin stria — stripe Brodmann area 17; primary visual cortex; named for the striae of Gennari Parastriate cortex Para — beside Brodmann area 18; secondary visual processing Peristriate cortex Peri — around Brodmann area 19; higher processing (motion, form, object recognition) Ventral stream Latin venter — belly (flows \\\"below\\\") \\\"What\\\" pathway: temporal lobe; object recognition Dorsal stream Latin dorsum — back (flows \\\"above\\\") \\\"Where\\\" pathway: parietal lobe; spatial location, motion Duplicity theory Latin duplicitas — doubleness The retina has two systems: scotopic (rods) + photopic (cones) Sensory adaptation — Adjustment of sensitivity based on stimulus history\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Visual pathway quick recap (detailed in A2-07): Retina → Optic nerve → Optic chiasma → Optic tract → Lateral Geniculate Body ( LGB ) → Optic radiation → Area Striata (Brodmann 17) → Areas 18 → 19 → higher processing LGB layers — SLIM mnemonic: SLIM : Superior layers = Lateral eye (ipsilateral/temporal fibers) Inferior layers = Medial eye (contralateral/nasal fibers) Layer inputs: 1 → Contralateral (nasal fibers, crossed) 4 → Contralateral 6 → Contralateral = 1-4-6 = Contralateral 2 → Ipsilateral (temporal fibers, uncrossed) 3 → Ipsilateral 5 → Ipsilateral = 2-3-5 = Ipsilateral Why this matters: In amblyopia treatment, the suppressed eye's LGB layers show reduced activity. Identifying which layers respond to which eye is foundational to understanding binocular development research. Cortical visual areas: Area Brodmann Name Function 17 Primary Striate / V1 First cortical processing; orientation, contrast, spatial frequency 18 Secondary Parastriate / V2 Secondary processing; feeds both dorsal and ventral streams 19 Tertiary Peristriate / V3 Higher processing; motion, form, object recognition initiation Two cortical streams: VENTRAL STREAM (\\\"What\\\" pathway) V1 → V2 → V4 → Inferotemporal cortex (IT) Function: Object identification, face recognition, color Damage: Prosopagnosia, object agnosia, achromatopsia (cortical) DORSAL STREAM (\\\"Where/How\\\" pathway) V1 → V2 → V5 (MT) → Posterior parietal cortex Function: Spatial location, motion detection, visual guidance of movement Damage: Spatial neglect, akinetopsia (cannot see motion), optic ataxia Categories of visual function — resilience order: MOST RESILIENT (last to be affected by disease) Motion Form Color ← MOST VULNERABLE (first affected in optic nerve disease) LEAST RESILIENT This explains why color vision is the most sensitive test for early optic nerve dysfunction (optic neuritis, glaucoma) — color perception fails before form or motion.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"LGB layers — contralateral vs ipsilateral: Layer Eye of origin Fiber type 1, 4, 6 Contralateral eye Nasal retinal fibers (crossed at chiasma) 2, 3, 5 Ipsilateral eye Temporal retinal fibers (uncrossed) Board clue \\\"1-4-6 = C; 2-3-5 = I\\\" Even numbers = ipsilateral EXCEPT 4 (which is contralateral)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Primary visual cortex Brodmann area 17 Lesion → homonymous scotoma (macular sparing common) LGB contralateral layers 1, 4, 6 Nasal (crossed) fibers LGB ipsilateral layers 2, 3, 5 Temporal (uncrossed) fibers Visual cortex allocation to fovea ~50% of area 17 Cortical magnification factor — central vision heavily over-represented\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"LGB — \\\"1-4-6 = C (Contralateral); 2-3-5 = I (Ipsilateral)\\\" Add the numbers: 1+4+6=11; 2+3+5=10 — C comes before I in the alphabet, like 11 comes after 10. Cortical areas — \\\"17-18-19 = Primary-Secondary-Tertiary\\\" In order of processing complexity. Ventral vs Dorsal — \\\"Ventral = WHAT you see; Dorsal = WHERE it is\\\" V = What (object recognition); D = Direction/location. Color vulnerability — \\\"Color is Vulnerable; Motion is Mighty\\\" Color fails first in optic nerve disease; motion is the last to be affected.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"LGB LAYERS (cross-section, 6 layers) ───────────────────────────────────── Layer 6 — Contralateral Layer 5 — Ipsilateral Layer 4 — Contralateral Layer 3 — Ipsilateral Layer 2 — Ipsilateral Layer 1 — Contralateral 1-4-6 = C (nasal crossed); 2-3-5 = I (temporal uncrossed) CORTICAL STREAMS ───────────────── Area 17 (V1) — primary cortex ↙ Ventral Dorsal ↘ Area 18 → IT Area 18 → V5 (MT) \\\" WHAT \\\" \\\" WHERE / HOW \\\" Object ID Motion, space, action Temporal lobe Parietal lobe\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Even-numbered LGB layers receive ipsilateral input Layers 2 and 4 differ: 2 is ipsilateral, but 4 is contralateral. The rule is 1-4-6=C and 2-3-5=I. Area 17 is responsible for object recognition Area 17 detects basic features (contrast, orientation). Object recognition requires the ventral stream extending through areas 18, 19, and inferotemporal cortex. Color is the most resilient visual function Color is the most vulnerable (fails first in optic nerve disease). Motion is the most resilient.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer LGB layers 1, 4, 6 Contralateral (nasal, crossed fibers) LGB layers 2, 3, 5 Ipsilateral (temporal, uncrossed fibers) Area 17 function Primary visual cortex — basic feature detection Area 18 Parastriate — secondary processing Area 19 Peristriate — higher processing Ventral stream \\\"What\\\" — object recognition; temporal lobe Dorsal stream \\\"Where/How\\\" — spatial/motion; parietal lobe Most vulnerable visual function Color (fails first in optic nerve disease) Most resilient Motion (last to be affected)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"1. A patient with multiple sclerosis has early optic neuritis. Which of the following visual functions would be affected earliest? A. Motion perception B. Form perception C. Color perception D. Spatial contrast sensitivity Answer C. Color perception. Color is the most vulnerable visual function — it is selectively affected early in optic nerve disease because color perception depends on intact, well-myelinated, high-frequency nerve fiber conduction. Even subtle demyelination (as in early optic neuritis) preferentially disrupts color transmission before form or motion are noticeably impaired. This is the basis of the \\\"red desaturation\\\" test — patients with early optic neuritis report that a bright red target appears washed-out or pink in the affected eye compared to the normal eye. Motion is the most resilient function and is typically preserved until late disease. 2. A researcher doubles the intensity of a light stimulus from 100 to 200 units. According to Weber's Law, what must be true about the just noticeable difference (JND)? A. The JND stays constant regardless of the background intensity B. The JND doubles because the background intensity doubled C. The JND stays a fixed fraction (k) of the new background intensity D. The JND decreases because more light is available Answer C. The JND stays a fixed fraction (k) of the new background intensity. Weber's Law states: ΔI/I = k. The ratio of the just noticeable difference (ΔI) to the background intensity (I) is a constant (k) — not ΔI itself. When the background doubles from 100 to 200, the new JND = k × 200, which is twice the original JND. The absolute threshold goes up, but the ratio stays the same. This is the clinical basis for contrast sensitivity: in dim conditions (low I), a smaller ΔI is needed; in bright conditions (high I), a larger ΔI is needed for detection. Option A is wrong — the absolute ΔI does change with intensity. Option B correctly states the ΔI doubles but the reasoning \\\"because the background doubled\\\" misses the point — it is the constant ratio, not a direct doubling, that defines Weber's Law. 3. An ipRGC (intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cell) is stimulated by sustained bright light. Which of the following is the PRIMARY function being activated? A. High-acuity pattern vision at the fovea B. Motion detection in the peripheral visual field C. Circadian rhythm entrainment via the suprachiasmatic nucleus D. ON-pathway activation feeding into the LGB parvocellular layers Answer C. Circadian rhythm entrainment via the suprachiasmatic nucleus. ipRGCs express melanopsin and project primarily to the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus via the retinohypothalamic tract — the master circadian clock pathway. They also project to the pretectal area (pupillary light reflex) and intergeniculate leaflet. They are non-image-forming cells — they do NOT contribute to pattern vision, motion detection, or LGB parvocellular/magnocellular pathways. Their slow, sustained response to ambient light level makes them ideal for signaling time-of-day (circadian entrainment) rather than detecting rapid changes in the scene. Disrupting this system (e.g., blue-light exposure at night) suppresses melatonin and disrupts sleep cycles.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"VISUAL PERCEPTION.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: LGB 6 layers with eye-of-origin, cortical areas 17-18-19 with functions, two cortical streams and what each processes, visual function vulnerability order. Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the LGB in cross-section. Label all 6 layers. Mark which eye contributes to each layer (C or I). Draw arrows showing where each stream goes from area 17. Drill 3 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back LGB 1-4-6? Contralateral (nasal, crossed) LGB 2-3-5? Ipsilateral (temporal, uncrossed) Area 17? Primary visual cortex (striate, V1) Ventral stream processes? What — object recognition Color vs Motion — which fails first? Color (most vulnerable) Weber's Law formula? ΔI/I = k (constant ratio; JND) Fechner's Law formula? S = k × log I (log scale of sensation) Nyctalopia: definition + main cause? Night blindness; Vitamin A deficiency or RP Hemeralopia: definition + main cause? Day blindness; achromatopsia or macular disease Dark adaptation curve — Kohlrausch kink at? ~7 min; cone-to-rod transition X-cells (P): color/detail or motion? Color and fine detail (high acuity; slow) Y-cells (M): color/detail or motion? Motion and contrast (fast; low acuity) ipRGC photopigment? Melanopsin (non-image-forming; circadian + pupil reflex) ON bipolar cell response to light? Depolarizes (excited by light) Lateral inhibition function? Sharpens edges via horizontal cells in OPL Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow LGB diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Describe both streams from memory Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-types-of-visual-acuity-and-contrast-sensitivity-types-of-visual-acuity-syllabi-16-0\",\"heading\":\"Types of Visual Acuity (Syllabi 16.0)\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Visual acuity is not a single entity — it has five distinct forms, each measuring a different aspect of the eye's resolving ability. 1. Minimum Visible (Detection Acuity) The smallest object that can be DETECTED (not identified) against a background Does not require resolution — only light/dark detection Threshold: can detect a line ~0.5 arc seconds wide (single photoreceptor width) Measured by: preferential looking tests, detection gratings (LEA gratings for infants) Board clue: lowest threshold of all VA types — seeing that something is there, not what it is 2. Minimum Separable (Resolution Acuity) The smallest gap between two objects that can be resolved as SEPARATE Requires two adjacent points to be resolved as distinct Normal: 1 arc minute (Snellen 20/20 = 1 arc minute minimum separable angle) Measured by: Snellen chart, ETDRS chart, Landolt C, Tumbling E Limited by: cone spacing at fovea, optical aberrations, neural summation Board clue: most commonly tested VA type; Snellen charts measure this 3. Minimum Discriminable (Discrimination Acuity) The smallest detectable DIFFERENCE between two stimuli E.g., detecting a slight change in orientation, color, or size Includes: orientation discrimination, contrast discrimination 4. Minimum Legible (Recognition Acuity) The smallest print or symbol that can be IDENTIFIED (not just detected or separated) Requires letter/symbol recognition — involves higher cortical processing Standard optometric exam VA: reading letters on Snellen chart = minimum legible Requires intact: optics + retina + optic nerve + visual cortex + cognitive processing 5. Vernier Acuity (Hyperacuity) The ability to detect the OFFSET of two aligned line segments Normal: 2–8 arc SECONDS (much finer than minimum separable = 1 arc MINUTE) Threshold is below the diameter of a single cone — hence called \\\"hyperacuity\\\" Why possible: the brain uses spatial interpolation across multiple photoreceptors Measured by: Vernier acuity tests; laser interferometry Preserved longer in disease than resolution acuity → used to predict potential acuity Board clue: finest of all acuity types; below the anatomical limit of single photoreceptors Comparison table: VA Type What it measures Normal threshold Clinical test Minimum visible Detection of existence ~0.5 arc sec LEA gratings, confrontation Minimum separable Two points as separate ~1 arc MINUTE (60 arc sec) Snellen, ETDRS, Landolt C Minimum discriminable Difference between similar stimuli Variable Orientation/color discrimination Minimum legible Letter/symbol recognition ~1 arc minute (Snellen) Standard optometric VA chart Vernier (hyperacuity) Offset alignment 2–8 arc SECONDS Vernier acuity test Aha rule for VA types: Largest to smallest threshold: Legible ≥ Separable > Discriminable > Vernier Finest (smallest threshold, hardest to measure) = Vernier/hyperacuity\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-types-of-visual-acuity-and-contrast-sensitivity-visual-acuity-charts-comparison\",\"heading\":\"Visual Acuity Charts — Comparison\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Chart Standard for Distance Notes Bailey-Lovie / LogMAR GOLD STANDARD for adults 4m Equal number of letters per line; equal spacing ETDRS Research and low vision 4m or 1m Most accurate; gold standard in clinical trials Snellen Traditional (being replaced) 6m / 20ft Unequal letters per line; considered obsolete by some HOTV GOLD STANDARD pediatric VA 3m Gold standard for children; letter recognition Lea Symbols Preschool (ages 2-5) 3m Circle, square, apple, house Tumbling E / Landolt C Illiterate/non-verbal 6m Direction of gap/opening Broken Wheel Pre-verbal children 3m Counterpart to Landolt C\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-types-of-visual-acuity-and-contrast-sensitivity-contrast-sensitivity-and-the-contrast-sensitivity-function-csf\",\"heading\":\"Contrast Sensitivity and the Contrast Sensitivity Function (CSF)\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"What is contrast sensitivity? Visual acuity measures resolution at HIGH contrast (black letters on white) Contrast sensitivity measures the ability to detect DIFFERENCES IN LUMINANCE across the visual scene Real-world vision depends heavily on contrast sensitivity — most of what we see is not high-contrast black-on-white CONTRAST THRESHOLD : Smallest amount of contrast needed to detect a stimulus CONTRAST SENSITIVITY (CS): Reciprocal of contrast threshold CS = 1 / Contrast threshold Higher CS = can detect lower contrast = better The Contrast Sensitivity Function (CSF): A graph of contrast sensitivity vs. spatial frequency (cycles per degree) Spatial frequency: how many cycles (dark-light pairs) per degree of visual angle Low SF: large, coarse objects (like large fuzzy blobs) High SF: fine detail (like sharp edges, fine print) NORMAL CSF SHAPE : Bandpass (inverted U) Peak sensitivity: ~3–5 cycles/degree (medium spatial frequency) Falls off at: Low SF: less sensitive to very coarse patterns (surround inhibition) High SF: less sensitive to very fine detail (optical + neural limits) CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE : CSF better predicts functional vision than Snellen VA alone Patient with normal Snellen but reduced CSF → difficulty with: Driving at night (low contrast road markings) Reading in poor light Recognizing faces in dim light CONDITIONS that reduce CSF : Early glaucoma (affects CSF before Snellen VA) Amblyopia (reduces both VA and CSF ) Cataract (reduces CSF especially at medium-high frequencies) Multiple sclerosis / optic neuritis (reduces CSF ) Diabetic retinopathy Tests for contrast sensitivity: Test Format Notes Pelli-Robson Contrast Sensitivity Chart Letter chart with decreasing contrast Most commonly used; patient reads letters at varying contrasts Mars Letter Contrast Sensitivity Letters at varying contrasts Similar to Pelli-Robson Vistech/FACT Gratings at multiple spatial frequencies Maps the full CSF curve Depth of Focus and Depth of Field: DEPTH OF FOCUS : How much the image can shift relative to the retina and still appear clear — determined by pupil size (smaller pupil = greater depth of focus) — pinhole effect: small pupil eliminates blur circles → greater DOF DEPTH OF FIELD : How much the OBJECT can move toward or away and still appear clear — related to depth of focus through magnification Clinical application: Pinhole testing improves VA only if the problem is optical (refractive error or media opacity) If VA doesn't improve with pinhole → problem is retinal or neural\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-the-plain-version-first\",\"heading\":\"The Plain Version First\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Imagine your eye as a light meter. When light is very dim, your meter needs to accumulate more light before it registers — you need either a bigger light or a longer exposure. When the light is bright, even a tiny amount triggers a reading. The eye obeys the same logic, and two scientists — Weber and Fechner — put numbers to this behavior. Weber discovered: the smallest change in stimulus you can detect is always a fixed fraction of the starting intensity . Double the background brightness, and you need double the change to notice a difference. This fraction is called the Weber fraction or just noticeable difference (JND) . The clinical term for this property is Weber's Law . Fechner took Weber's Law further and said: the sensation you experience doesn't grow linearly — it grows as the logarithm of the stimulus intensity. This is called Fechner's Law (also called the Weber-Fechner Law). In plain terms: each time you multiply the stimulus by 10, you only add a fixed unit of sensation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-weber-s-law\",\"heading\":\"Weber's Law\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"PLAIN VERSION : The minimum change you can detect = a constant fraction of the current stimulus FORMULA : ΔI / I = k (Weber fraction) Where: ΔI = the minimum detectable change in intensity (just noticeable difference, JND ) I = the background stimulus intensity k = Weber fraction (a constant for a given sensory system) EXAMPLE IN VISION : You are in a room with 100 units of light. The Weber fraction for brightness ≈ 0.02 (2%) → You can detect a change only if ΔI ≥ 2 units (2% of 100) Now the room is 1000 units of light. → You need ΔI ≥ 20 units to notice a change CLINICAL MEANING : The eye's ability to detect contrast depends on the background luminance. In bright conditions, you need a bigger absolute difference to see contrast. In dim conditions, even small absolute differences are detectable. This is why a candle flame is easily visible in a dark room but invisible in sunlight. The clinical term for the minimum detectable change: Just Noticeable Difference (JND) or Difference Limen (DL).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-fechner-s-law-weber-fechner-law\",\"heading\":\"Fechner's Law (Weber-Fechner Law)\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"PLAIN VERSION : Your perception of brightness doesn't grow at the same rate as the actual light increase. Every time you multiply the physical stimulus by the same amount, you only add a fixed increment to your sensation. FORMULA : S = k × log(I) Where: S = perceived sensation (subjective brightness) I = physical stimulus intensity k = constant EXAMPLE : Light intensity: 1 unit → sensation = 0 (log 1 = 0) Light intensity: 10 units → sensation = k × 1 Light intensity: 100 units → sensation = k × 2 Light intensity: 1000 units → sensation = k × 3 Each 10× increase in actual light adds only 1 unit of perceived sensation. WHY THIS MATTERS : This is why a log scale is used to measure light, sound, and other sensory stimuli. It explains why the photopic range (100,000:1 light intensity range) feels like a manageable range of brightness to us — because perception is logarithmic. CLINICAL CONNECTION : Log MAR charts (Bailey-Lovie, ETDRS ) are based on Fechner's principle — each line adds equal perceptual steps rather than equal physical steps in letter size. The clinical term for this relationship: Fechner's Law / Weber-Fechner Law.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-the-terms-you-must-know\",\"heading\":\"Nyctalopia vs Hemeralopia — The Terms You Must Know\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Plain version: Some people see poorly in the dark; others see poorly in the bright. These are opposite conditions with names that sound similar but mean different things. NYCTALOPIA (Night Blindness) Greek: nyx = night + alaos = blind + ops = eye Plain language: Cannot see well in dim light or darkness The rod system fails — either rhodopsin cannot regenerate, rods are absent/damaged, or the rod pathway is disrupted. CAUSES (most board-tested): 1. Vitamin A deficiency — most common worldwide cause (no Vit A → no 11-cis retinal → no rhodopsin regeneration) 2. Retinitis Pigmentosa (RP) — rod degeneration, peripheral VF loss 3. Congenital stationary night blindness ( CSNB ) — X-linked or autosomal 4. Choroideremia — X-linked choroidal + RPE degeneration 5. Gyrate atrophy — ornithine aminotransferase deficiency 6. Fundus albipunctatus — delayed rhodopsin regeneration EXAMINATION FINDING : Dark adaptation curve — rod phase flat or absent HEMERALOPIA (Day Blindness) Greek: hemera = day + alaos = blind + ops = eye Plain language: Cannot see well in bright light; vision improves in dim conditions The cone system is preferentially affected. CAUSES : 1. Achromatopsia (rod monochromacy) — complete absence of functioning cones Complete: no color, no photopic VA, photophobia Incomplete (incomplete achromatopsia): partial cone loss 2. Cone dystrophy — progressive cone degeneration 3. Cone-rod dystrophy ( CRD ) — cones affected first, rods later 4. Central corneal opacity or dense cataract — (secondary, not true retinal hemeralopia) EXAMINATION FINDING : Dark adaptation curve — cone phase absent or flat; rod curve may be normal Critical board distinction: Feature Nyctalopia Hemeralopia Plain meaning Night blindness Day blindness Affected system ROD system CONE system Worse in Dim / dark conditions Bright / photopic conditions Primary cause Vitamin A deficiency, RP Achromatopsia, cone dystrophy Dark adaptation Rod phase absent/flat Cone phase absent; rod normal Associated symptom Poor night driving, averted vision needed Photophobia, poor outdoor VA\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-retinal-neuron-types-w-x-y-cells-and-p-m-cells\",\"heading\":\"Retinal Neuron Types — W, X, Y Cells and P/M Cells\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"These are the specific cell types that the board tests under retinal perception. They explain WHY the eye is so good at different tasks in different conditions. The Feynman version first: The retina doesn't just send one kind of signal to the brain. It has fast reporters, detail reporters, and motion detectors — all running in parallel. Each type of ganglion cell feeds a different visual task. W, X, Y Classification (based on physiology): W CELLS (slow, broad fields) Speed: Slow signal transmission Field size: Large receptive fields in peripheral retina Input: Mostly from RODS Function: Crude movement detection; rod-mediated dim-light motion sensing Board clue: W = slow, Wide, dim-light motion X CELLS (detail, color) Speed: Moderate Field size: Small, discrete receptive fields Input: 1 cone per cell at fovea Function: Fine spatial detail, color vision, high-resolution vision Board clue: X = eXact, fine detail, color Y CELLS (fast, large, motion) Speed: FASTEST transmission Field size: Largest of all three Input: From large areas Function: Rapid change detection; alerts CNS of sudden new visual events Board clue: Y = fast, big, motion — but poor at locating exactly where P and M Cell Classification (based on morphology in primates): PARVOCELLULAR (P) CELLS = Beta cells = Midget ganglion cells Location: Central retina Projection: Parvocellular layers of LGB (layers 3–6) → Feeds VENTRAL stream (What pathway) Function: Color, fine detail, spatial resolution Board clue: P = Parvocellular = Precise = color + detail Equivalent to: X cells functionally MAGNOCELLULAR (M) CELLS = Alpha cells Location: Peripheral retina (more) Projection: Magnocellular layers of LGB (layers 1–2) → Feeds DORSAL stream (Where/How pathway) Function: Motion detection, low-contrast sensitivity, black-and-white Board clue: M = Magnocellular = Movement = motion + contrast Equivalent to: Y cells functionally MELANOPSIN-CONTAINING (ipRGC) CELLS Location: Ganglion cell layer Photopigment: Melanopsin (maximally sensitive to blue light ~480nm) Projection: Suprachiasmatic nucleus ( SCN ) of hypothalamus Function: Circadian rhythm regulation (light/dark cycle), pupillary light reflex They do NOT form images — they only sense ambient light level Board clue: melanopsin = non-image-forming; circadian; pupil reflex P vs M — the board comparison: Feature P (Parvocellular) M (Magnocellular) Cell size Small (midget) Large (parasol) LGB layers 3, 4, 5, 6 1, 2 Stream Ventral (\\\"What\\\") Dorsal (\\\"Where/How\\\") Sensitivity Color, fine detail Motion, low contrast Equivalent X cells Y cells Clinical loss Detail, color processing Motion perception, contrast Lateral Inhibition and Retinal Processing: HORIZONTAL CELLS (always inhibitory) Connected laterally across photoreceptors Inhibit neighboring photoreceptors Result: LATERAL INHIBITION — sharpens edges and enhances contrast \\\"Mach bands\\\" are a perceptual result of lateral inhibition AMACRINE CELLS (30 types, mostly inhibitory) Located in inner nuclear layer Roles: - Direct rod pathway: Rod → Bipolar → Amacrine → Ganglion cell - Motion detection (directionally selective amacrine cells) - Response to light onset/offset - Additional lateral inhibition at inner plexiform layer BIPOLAR CELLS (depolarizing and hyperpolarizing) Two types based on response to light: DEPOLARIZING ( ON- center) bipolar cells: Direct synapse from photoreceptor Light → decreased glutamate from photoreceptor → Bipolar cell depolarizes → \\\"ON\\\" signal HYPERPOLARIZING ( OFF- center) bipolar cells: Inhibitory synapse Light → decreased glutamate → Bipolar cell hyperpolarizes → \\\" OFF \\\" signal Result: The retina signals both LIGHT ONSET (ON pathway) and LIGHT OFFSET ( OFF pathway) simultaneously — gives the visual system sensitivity to both edges and changes\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2-01-visual-perception-extended-topics-retinal-sensitivity-laws-nyctalopia-vs-hemeralopia-and-retinal-neuron-types-board-traps-extended\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps — Extended\",\"topic\":\"B2-01 — Visual Perception and Sensory Organization\",\"text\":\"Weber's Law says sensation grows proportionally to stimulus That's describing a linear response. Weber's Law says the minimum detectable change is a constant fraction of the background. Fechner's Law says sensation grows logarithmically. Nyctalopia means day blindness Nyctalopia = NIGHT blindness (nyx = night). Hemeralopia = day blindness. These are commonly confused. P cells carry motion information P (parvocellular) cells carry color and fine detail. M (magnocellular) cells carry motion and contrast. ipRGCs form images Intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (melanopsin cells) are non-image-forming. They regulate circadian rhythms and the pupillary light reflex but do not contribute to object perception. Horizontal cells are excitatory Horizontal cells are always inhibitory — they provide lateral inhibition that sharpens visual contrast.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"The visual field is the total area a person can see while fixating straight ahead. It extends further temporally (100°) than nasally (60°) because the nose blocks nasal vision, and further inferiorly (75°) than superiorly (60°) because the brow blocks the upper field. The two eyes' fields overlap in the center (120° binocular zone), with a 30° monocular crescent on each side. Different diseases affect different parts of the field in predictable patterns — and mapping those patterns with the right test reveals where in the visual pathway the problem is. Goldmann perimetry uses stimulus size and brightness to plot isopters (sensitivity contour lines), while automated perimetry uses static stimuli to build a threshold map. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does glaucoma cause peripheral field loss while macular degeneration causes central field loss?\\\" The answer maps retinal topography to disease location.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Why is the temporal field larger (100°) than the nasal field (60°)? Because the nasal retina receives the temporal field — and nasal retina extends further than temporal retina due to the nose blocking peripheral nasal visual input. The temporal field of view is unobstructed. Why does color fail before form and motion in visual field loss? Because color perception requires the most precisely functioning cone pathways. Small lesions or early dysfunction preferentially knock out color sensitivity before the coarser form/motion channels are affected. This is why color is tested for early disease detection. Why does Goldmann perimetry use kinetic stimuli while automated perimetry uses static? Because kinetic testing (moving the target in) maps the boundary of sensitivity efficiently but misses patchy losses within the field. Static testing (fixed position, varying intensity) detects threshold at specific locations, catching scotomas the kinetic method would cross over without detection.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Isopter Greek isos — equal + optos — seen A line connecting all retinal points of equal visual sensitivity for a given stimulus Scotoma Greek skotos — darkness A localized area of reduced or absent vision within the visual field Hemianopia Greek hemi + an + opia Loss of half the visual field Quadrantanopia Latin quadrans — quarter Loss of a quarter of the visual field Perimetry Greek peri — around + metron — measure Systematic mapping of the visual field Isopter notation — Stimulus code: size (I–V) + intensity (1–4 + a–e); e.g., V4e = largest, brightest Background luminance — Goldmann bowl: 31.5 apostilbs (standardized) Apostilb Unit of luminance Measurement unit for Goldmann bowl background and stimuli Temporal crescent — The 30° monocular field beyond the binocular zone; seen only by temporal retina of one eye\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Why the visual field has the shape it does: MONOCULAR FIELD (one eye): Superior: 60° (brow limits upward gaze) Inferior: 75° (less obstruction below) Temporal: 100° (no obstruction; temporal retina sees nasal field far out) Nasal: 60° (nose limits inward field) Total monocular field: approximately 200° horizontal, 135° vertical BINOCULAR FIELD OVERLAP : Central 120° is seen by BOTH eyes simultaneously (30° monocular crescent on each temporal side = seen by one eye only) Goldmann perimetry — how it works: Patient fixates center of bowl Examiner moves stimulus from non-seeing periphery toward center At speed: 2–4° per second Patient signals first detection point That point is plotted on chart Process repeated at multiple meridians (every 10–30°) Connected points = ISOPTER for that stimulus Multiple isopters nested from largest/brightest (V4e, outermost) to smallest/dimmest (I1e, innermost) create a topographic map of the visual field — the \\\"island of vision.\\\" Goldmann stimulus notation: FORMAT : [Size (Roman I–V)] [Intensity (1–4)] [letter (a–e)] Example: V4e = Size V (largest; 64mm²) + Intensity 4e (maximum) I4e = Size I (smallest; 0.25mm²) + Intensity 4e (maximum) SIZE scale: I = 0.25 mm² (6 arc min angular size) II = 1 mm² III = 4 mm² IV = 16 mm² V = 64 mm² (96 arc min angular size) Each step = 0.6 log unit (4× area increase) INTENSITY : Letter e = maximum (no filter) Letter a = 0.4 log units below maximum Arabic number 4 = maximum; 1 = dimmest standard stimulus\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Visual field normal extents — \\\"SIT-N = 60-75-100-60\\\": Superior 60° | Nasal 60° ← ──┼── → Temporal 100° | Inferior 75° Binocular overlap: 120° central Temporal crescent (monocular): 30° each side Visual field categories and vulnerability: MOST RESILIENT (last affected) ↑ Motion perception | Form perception ↓ Color perception MOST VULNERABLE (first affected) VF tests comparison: Test Coverage What it detects Best use Confrontation Gross full field Large hemianopias, dense defects Bedside screening Amsler Grid Central 10° (at 28–30cm) Metamorphopsia, central scotoma Macular disease monitoring Tangent Screen Central 30° only Scotomas in central field Detailed central mapping Goldmann Perimeter Full field; isopter mapping Any field defect; peripheral + central Standard kinetic perimetry Automated (Humphrey) Central 24° or 30° Threshold values per point Glaucoma monitoring VF defects by lesion (summary — see A2-07 for full detail): Defect Lesion Clinical example Monocular scotoma Retina or optic nerve Optic neuritis, ARMD Bitemporal hemianopia Optic chiasma (crossing fibers) Pituitary adenoma Homonymous hemianopia Post-chiasmal Stroke \\\"Pie in the sky\\\" Meyer's loop (temporal lobe) Temporal lobe tumor \\\"Pie on the floor\\\" Baum's loop (parietal lobe) Parietal stroke Ring scotoma Peripheral rod degeneration Retinitis pigmentosa Central scotoma Macular disease ARMD, CSR Arcuate scotoma Nerve fiber bundle loss Glaucoma (superior/inferior arcades) Goldmann isopter interpretation: Finding Interpretation Constriction of all isopters Generalized depression (advanced glaucoma, RP) Isopters collapse centrally Central field loss (macular disease) Isopters absent temporally Bitemporal defect (chiasmal lesion) Absent on one side of vertical midline Homonymous hemianopsia (retrochiasmal) Island within isopter Scotoma (absolute if no stimulus seen; relative if only dim stimuli missed)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Goldmann vs Automated Perimetry: Feature Goldmann Automated (Humphrey) Stimulus type Kinetic (moving) Static (fixed position, varying intensity) Coverage Full field (peripheral + central) Central 24° or 30° primarily Scotoma detection Less sensitive for small scotomas Better for small scotomas Reliability Examiner-dependent Standardized; reliability indices Best for Low vision, peripheral field, RP, neuro Glaucoma monitoring, subtle defects Board clue \\\"Map the boundaries\\\" \\\"Map the threshold\\\" Amsler Grid specifics: Measures central 10° of visual field Distance: 28–30 cm (approximately 1 foot) Tests for metamorphopsia (wavy/distorted lines — macular disease) Each small square = 1° of visual field\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"VF superior extent 60° Brow limits upward field VF inferior extent 75° Less obstruction below VF temporal extent 100° Widest extent VF nasal extent 60° Nose limits nasal field Binocular overlap 120° central Both eyes see this zone simultaneously Monocular crescent 30° each side Temporal retina only; no binocular input Goldmann bowl radius 300 mm Standardized distance to stimulus Goldmann background 31.5 apostilbs Standardized luminance Goldmann stimulus sizes I (0.25mm²) to V (64mm²) Each step = 0.6 log unit = 4× area Amsler grid coverage Central 10° At 28–30 cm distance Amsler grid 1 square 1° of visual field For documenting defect size\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"VF extents — \\\"SIT-N = 60-75-100-60\\\" Superior, Inferior, Temporal, Nasal = 60°, 75°, 100°, 60° Temporal field is BIGGEST because Temporal retina sees nasal field; temporal extends further into visual space and the nose doesn't block it. Goldmann stimulus size order — \\\"I is smallest; V is Vision-wide\\\" I = tiny (0.25mm²); V = vision-wide (64mm²) Color vs Motion vulnerability — \\\"Color Goes First; Motion is Last\\\" Color = early disease indicator; motion = resilient. VF defect mnemonics (from A2-07) Bitemporal = Chiasmal (pituitary) Pie in the sky = Meyer's loop (temporal) Pie on the floor = Baum's loop (parietal)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"MONOCULAR VISUAL FIELD (right eye) ──────────────────────────────────── N(60°) | (100°)T ──┼──N(60°) | I(75°) BINOCULAR ZONE : 120° TEMPORAL CRESCENT : 30° each side GOLDMANN ISOPTERS (nested contours) ───────────────────────────────────── V4e (outermost — largest, brightest) III4e I4e (innermost — smallest, brightest) Each isopter is a contour line of equal sensitivity. Fixation point is at center. Scotoma = gap or island within an isopter.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"The temporal visual field extends 60° Temporal = 100° (widest). Nasal and superior = 60°. All of the visual field is seen binocularly The central 120° is binocular; each side has a 30° monocular crescent seen only by the temporal retina. Goldmann V4e uses the smallest stimulus V is the LARGEST size (64mm²). I is the smallest (0.25mm²). Amsler grid tests the entire visual field Amsler grid tests only the central 10° of the visual field. Motion is the most vulnerable visual function Color is the most vulnerable. Motion is the most resilient.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer VF extents (SIT-N) S=60°, I=75°, T=100°, N=60° Binocular overlap 120° central Monocular crescent 30° temporal each side Most vulnerable VF function Color Most resilient VF function Motion Goldmann bowl radius 300 mm Goldmann background luminance 31.5 apostilbs Largest Goldmann stimulus V (64mm²; 96 arc min) Smallest Goldmann stimulus I (0.25mm²; 6 arc min) V4e isopter Maps peripheral field (largest stimulus; used in RP, low vision) Amsler grid coverage Central 10° Amsler 1 square = 1° of visual field Bitemporal hemianopia lesion Optic chiasma (pituitary adenoma) \\\"Pie in the sky\\\" lesion Meyer's loop (temporal lobe)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"1. On Goldmann perimetry, all isopters are severely constricted, with only a small central island of vision remaining. The patient reports difficulty seeing in dim light and has had peripheral vision loss for years. What condition does this pattern suggest? A. Pituitary adenoma B. Glaucoma C. Retinitis pigmentosa D. Central serous retinopathy Answer C. Retinitis pigmentosa. Retinitis pigmentosa is a rod dystrophy that begins peripherally and progresses centrally, creating a classic \\\"ring scotoma\\\" that expands until only a small central island of cone vision remains. On Goldmann perimetry, this appears as severely constricted isopters around a preserved central island. The history of night blindness (rod dysfunction precedes cone loss in RP) and progressive peripheral loss over years is consistent with RP. Pituitary adenoma causes bitemporal hemianopia — not concentric constriction. Glaucoma causes arcuate scotomas and nasal steps, typically not this degree of peripheral constriction early. CSR causes a central scotoma, not peripheral.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3-01-visual-field-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B3-01 — Visual Field\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"VISUAL FIELD.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: VF extents in all 4 directions, binocular overlap, Goldmann bowl specs, size I vs V, 5 VF defects with their lesion sites. Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the monocular VF with the four extents labeled. Mark the binocular zone (120°) and the temporal crescent (30° each side). Draw 3 nested isopters from V4e (outer) to I4e (inner). Drill 3 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back VF temporal extent? 100° VF nasal extent? 60° Binocular overlap? 120° Goldmann bowl background? 31.5 apostilbs Largest Goldmann stimulus? V (64mm²) Smallest? I (0.25mm²) Amsler grid coverage? Central 10° Color vs Motion resilience? Color fails first; motion last Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow VF diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days VF defects — 5 lesion sites from memory Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Color vision works through three cone types, each sensitive to a different wavelength range. Their combined output is processed by opponent channels in the brain — red vs green, blue vs yellow — which is why those color pairs cannot be perceived simultaneously (you cannot see a reddish-green). Most color deficiency is genetic, X-linked, and affects males more than females. The board tests color theory names, color mixing rules, specific color test criteria, and the nomenclature of color deficiency. Knowing the tests cold — which plate is for everyone (Ishihara plate 1), which test uses lanterns (FALANT), and which is most comprehensive (FM-100) — covers the clinical side completely. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why can't you see a reddish-green color?\\\" The answer explains opponent process theory, which explains why Hering proposed a different theory than Young-Helmholtz.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Why do we need three cone types and not two or four? Because color discrimination depends on comparing the relative outputs of cone types. Two cones would only give a single ratio (one color dimension). Three cones give three ratios — enough to distinguish millions of colors. Four would add marginal benefit for most purposes. Why do red-green defects occur more frequently than blue-yellow defects? Because the genes for red (OPN1LW) and green (OPN1MW) cones are both on the X chromosome and are arranged in tandem — making them prone to unequal crossover during meiosis. Blue cone genes are on chromosome 7 and are much less susceptible to this recombination error. Why does color perception fail earlier than motion in optic nerve disease? Because color signals depend on the sustained (parvocellular) pathway, which uses small, high-frequency nerve fibers. These are selectively more vulnerable to demyelination and ischemia than the larger transient (magnocellular) fibers that carry motion signals.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Trichromacy Greek tri — three + khroma — color Normal color vision with three functioning cone types Anomalous trichromacy Greek anomalos — irregular Three cone types present but one has shifted peak absorption Dichromacy Greek di — two Only two functioning cone types; one type absent Monochromacy Greek mono — one Only one cone type (or rods only); complete color blindness Protan- Greek protos — first Red cone (L-cone) defect Deutan- Greek deuteros — second Green cone (M-cone) defect Tritan- Greek tritos — third Blue cone (S-cone) defect -anomalous Anomalous trichromat Cone present but shifted; partial defect -anopia Greek an — without + opia Cone type absent; dichromat; complete defect Additive mixing Adding light wavelengths together R + G + B = White (light mixing) Subtractive mixing Pigments absorb wavelengths C + M + Y = Black (pigment mixing)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"The three color theories: 1. TRICHROMATIC THEORY (Young-Helmholtz) Level: Receptor (cone) Mechanism: Three cone types with different peak sensitivities L-cones (Erythrolabe) = Red ~750nm M-cones (Chlorolabe) = Green ~535nm S-cones (Cyanolabe) = Blue ~440nm Why it works: Different stimuli produce different ratios of cone activation Limitation: Cannot explain why red-green is impossible to perceive simultaneously No S-cones in fovea (but sufficient L and M for central color) 2. OPPONENT PROCESS THEORY (Hering) Level: Post-receptor (retinal ganglion cells, LGB , cortex) Mechanism: Signals processed in opposing pairs: Red ↔ Green (opponent — cannot coexist) Blue ↔ Yellow (opponent — cannot coexist) Black ↔ White (luminance channel) Why it works: Explains color after-images, simultaneous contrast, why reddish-green is impossible 3. STAGE THEORY (Ladd-Franklin) Evolutionary stages: Stage 1: Monochromat (all wavelengths = one signal — like blue-green) Stage 2: Dichromat (blue-yellow system evolves) Stage 3: Trichromat (red-green system evolves last — most recently evolved) Board clue: Red-green defects are more common because the red-green system is the most recently evolved (most vulnerable) Color mixing: ADDITIVE (light/mixing wavelengths): R + G = Yellow R + B = Magenta G + B = Cyan R + G + B = WHITE SUBTRACTIVE (pigments absorb wavelengths): C + M = Blue C + Y = Green M + Y = Red C + M + Y = BLACK Key: Primary colors differ between additive ( RGB ) and subtractive ( CMY )\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Color deficiency classification: ANOMALOUS TRICHROMACY (3 cone types; one shifted) Protanomaly — weak/shifted L-cone (red weakness); most common sex-linked defect in males Deuteranomaly — weak/shifted M-cone (green weakness); most common overall Tritanomaly — weak/shifted S-cone (blue weakness); rare; autosomal DICHROMACY (only 2 cone types; one absent) Protanopia — no L-cone (red blind); confuses red with dark green/gray Deuteranopia — no M-cone (green blind); confuses red with green; most common dichromat Tritanopia — no S-cone (blue blind); confuses blue-yellow; rare; autosomal MONOCHROMACY (only 1 or 0 color channels) Rod monochromacy (achromatopsia) — no cones; completely color blind; photophobia; poor acuity Cone monochromacy — one cone type only; rare Sex-linked prevalence: Males: ~8% of Caucasian males have red-green defect Females: ~0.5% (carrier females rarely symptomatic) Reason: OPN1LW (L-cone) and OPN1MW (M-cone) genes both on X chromosome Color vision tests: Test Fail Criteria Stimulus What it tests Ishihara >2 errors (note: plate 1 is \\\"12\\\" for EVERYONE including deficient) Pseudoisochromatic plates Red-green deficiency screening FALANT (Farnsworth Lantern) >2 errors at 8 feet Colored light pairs (red, green, yellow, white) Occupational color vision (aviation, navy) D-15 (Farnsworth D-15) >2 major transpositions 15 colored caps + pilot cap Screens mild from severe; type of defect FM-100 Hue High total error score 85 hue-graded caps, 4 boxes Most comprehensive; identifies axis of defect HRR (Hardy-Rand-Rittler) Miss symbols Pseudoisochromatic; symbols not numbers Tests both red-green AND blue-yellow Ishihara plate 1 = \\\"12\\\" — everyone sees this, including color-deficient patients. It is a control plate. Failure here suggests malingering or low intelligence, not color deficiency.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Protanopia vs Deuteranopia — both confuse red and green but differently: Feature Protanopia Deuteranopia Missing cone L-cone (red) M-cone (green) Neutral point ~492 nm (blue-green appears white) ~499 nm Red brightness Dark (red light looks dim because L-cones absent) Normal Most common in Males; ~1% Males; ~1% Board clue Protan = red is DIM Deutan = red and green just look similar, no dimming Anomalous trichromacy vs Dichromacy: Feature Anomalous trichromacy Dichromacy Cone types 3 (one shifted) 2 (one missing) Severity Mild–moderate defect Severe defect Most common Deuteranomaly (green weakness) Deuteranopia Ishihara errors Some errors More errors\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"L-cone (Erythrolabe) peak ~750 nm (red) L = Longest wavelength M-cone (Chlorolabe) peak ~535 nm (green) M = Middle wavelength S-cone (Cyanolabe) peak ~440 nm (blue) S = Shortest wavelength Red-green defect prevalence (males) ~8% Most common heritable visual defect FM-100 caps 85 + 4 pilot caps 4 boxes of 22-23 caps each D-15 caps 15 + 1 pilot Major transpositions = significant defect FALANT test distance 8 feet Navy/FAA occupational standard Ishihara plate 1 \\\"12\\\" — seen by all Control plate\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Cone pigment names — \\\"ECG\\\" Erythrolabe (Red/750nm), Chlorolabe (Green/535nm), Cyanolabe (Blue/440nm) Cone deficiency names — \\\"PDT\\\" for protanopia, deuteranopia, tritanopia Protan = Red problem; Deutan = Green problem; Tritan = Blue problem Anomaly = shifted (partial); Anopia = absent (complete) Most common defects Most common anomalous: Deuteranomaly (green weakness) Most common dichromat: Deuteranopia Both are green (deutan) problems — green gene on X is most prone to crossover Additive = White; Subtractive = Black Add light → get all wavelengths → white Subtract (absorb) everything → no wavelengths reflected → black Color theories by level Trichromatic = receptor level (cones) Opponent process = post-receptor (retinal ganglion/LGB/cortex) Stage theory = evolutionary explanation Most comprehensive color test = FM-100 \\\"Full Map\\\" — 85 caps, plots the exact axis of color confusion.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"COLOR THEORIES ────────────── RECEPTOR LEVEL : L-cone (750nm) + M-cone (535nm) + S-cone (440nm) → Trichromatic (Young-Helmholtz) ↓ (signals processed further) POST-RECEPTOR : R vs G channel (opponent) B vs Y channel (opponent) W vs K channel (luminance) → Opponent process (Hering) ADDITIVE vs SUBTRACTIVE ──────────────────────── ADDITIVE ( LIGHT ): SUBTRACTIVE ( PIGMENT ): R C / \\\\ / \\\\ G B M Y R+G=Y R+G+B= WHITE C+M+Y= BLACK\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Plate 1 of the Ishihara is only seen by normal observers Plate 1 (\\\"12\\\") is seen by EVERYONE including color deficient patients. It is the control plate. Tritanopia is the most common color deficiency Deuteranomaly (weak green) is the most common. Tritanopia is rare and autosomal. Additive mixing of all colors produces black Additive (light) mixing R+G+B = White. Subtractive (pigment) mixing C+M+Y = Black. Protan defects cause no change in red brightness Protanopia makes red appear DIM because L-cones are absent and red light doesn't stimulate M or S-cones effectively. FM-100 uses numbers to identify errors FM-100 uses hue-graded caps; the patient arranges them in order. Ishihara uses numbers (and symbols in HRR). HRR only tests red-green deficiency HRR tests BOTH red-green and blue-yellow deficiencies, unlike Ishihara (which only screens red-green).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Color theory at receptor level Trichromatic (Young-Helmholtz) Color theory at post-receptor level Opponent process (Hering) Evolutionary theory Stage theory (Ladd-Franklin) L-cone pigment + wavelength Erythrolabe; ~750nm (red) M-cone pigment + wavelength Chlorolabe; ~535nm (green) S-cone pigment + wavelength Cyanolabe; ~440nm (blue) Most common color defect Deuteranomaly (green weakness) Additive mixing result R+G+B = White Subtractive mixing result C+M+Y = Black Ishihara plate 1 \\\"12\\\" — everyone sees it (control plate) Most comprehensive color test FM-100 Hue test FALANT test distance 8 feet (occupational test) HRR difference from Ishihara Tests both R-G and B-Y defects; uses symbols Red-green defect prevalence (males) ~8%\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"1. A patient fails multiple Ishihara plates and is suspected of having a color vision deficiency. To determine the exact axis and severity of the defect, which test should be ordered? A. FALANT B. D-15 C. FM-100 Hue test D. HRR Answer C. FM-100 Hue test. The FM-100 Hue test is the most comprehensive color vision assessment. Using 85 hue-graded colored caps arranged in four boxes, it plots a \\\"total error score\\\" and identifies the exact axis of color confusion (the angle of the error vector). This allows precise classification of both type and severity of color defect. D-15 is useful for screening mild vs severe defects and type, but is less detailed. FALANT is an occupational test, not a diagnostic one. HRR screens for both red-green and blue-yellow defects but does not quantify the defect as precisely as FM-100.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4-01-color-perception-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B4-01 — Color Perception\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"COLOR PERCEPTION.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: 3 color theories with their level (receptor/post-receptor/evolutionary), cone pigments + wavelengths, most common defect, additive vs subtractive results, 5 color tests with fail criteria. Drill 2 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Trichromatic theory author? Young-Helmholtz Opponent process theory author? Hering Stage theory author? Ladd-Franklin L-cone pigment? Erythrolabe (red ~750nm) M-cone pigment? Chlorolabe (green ~535nm) S-cone pigment? Cyanolabe (blue ~440nm) Most common color defect? Deuteranomaly R+G+B (additive) = ? White C+M+Y (subtractive) = ? Black Ishihara plate 1 reads? \\\"12\\\" (everyone) Most comprehensive color test? FM-100 Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Write all 6 deficiency types (3 anomalous + 3 anopia) from memory Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Binocular vision is the coordinated use of both eyes to produce a single, three-dimensional mental image. It requires alignment (both eyes pointing at the same target), sensory fusion (the brain merging two slightly different images), and motor fusion (the eye muscles maintaining alignment). When alignment breaks down or fusion fails, the brain adapts — either by seeing double (diplopia), suppressing one eye's image, or developing an abnormal retinal correspondence where the deviated eye recalibrates its directional sense. Understanding BV anomalies requires three things: knowing where the deviation is (distance, near, or both), knowing the AC/A ratio (how much convergence accompanies each diopter of accommodation), and knowing which criteria tell you if the fusion is sufficient (Sheard's, Percival's). Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does a child with uncorrected high hyperopia often develop esotropia?\\\" The answer explains AC/A ratio, accommodative esotropia, and why glasses alone can straighten the eyes.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Why does a high AC/A ratio cause convergence excess? Because AC/A tells you how much convergence is triggered per diopter of accommodation. If this ratio is abnormally high, every time the child accommodates for near — which requires +4D if they are +4D hyperopic — they generate massive convergence (4 × high AC/A). The eyes cross at near, but are straight at distance because convergence demand at distance is zero. Why does suppression develop in strabismus? Because the deviated eye projects its image to a different visual direction from the fixating eye, causing diplopia. The brain resolves the conflict by actively inhibiting the signal from the non-fixating eye — suppression. Without this adaptation, constant diplopia would be intolerable. Why is NRC normal in heterophoria but ARC develops in strabismus? Because in heterophoria, binocular vision is maintained most of the time and the foveas retain their common visual direction (NRC). In constant strabismus with a fixed angle of deviation, the brain has time to rewire the retinal correspondence — the non-foveal area of the deviated eye that consistently receives the fixation target's image gradually takes over the fovea's visual direction (ARC). Why is Sheard's criterion a 2:1 ratio? Because research shows that patients are comfortable when their fusional reserve is at least twice the demand placed on their vergence system. If the demand exceeds half the reserve, the system is working at maximum capacity and symptoms (asthenopia, diplopia) result.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Binocular vision Latin bino — two + oculus Coordinated use of both eyes; produces single 3D percept Fusion Latin fundere — to pour together Blending of two ocular images into one percept Phoria Greek phora — bearing/tendency Latent tendency of the eyes to deviate; only present under dissociation Tropia Greek tropos — turn Manifest (constant) deviation; always present Heterophoria Greek heteros — different Any deviation not orthophoria Orthophoria Greek orthos — straight Ideal alignment with no deviation tendency AC/A ratio Accommodative Convergence per Accommodation Units: prism diopters (PD) of convergence per diopter (D) of accommodation NRC Normal Retinal Correspondence Both foveas have the same visual direction ARC Anomalous Retinal Correspondence Fovea of one eye + extrafoveal area of other eye share a common visual direction Panum's area Named after Peter Ludvig Panum Zone around the horopter where fusion (not diplopia) occurs despite non-corresponding stimulation Horopter — Imaginary curved surface through the fixation point where all points stimulate corresponding retinal elements Suppression Latin suppressio — pressing down Active inhibition of one eye's visual signal by the brain Amblyopia Greek amblys — dull + ops — eye Reduced visual acuity in one eye not attributable to structural pathology; \\\"lazy eye\\\" Diplopia Greek diploos — double Double vision from non-corresponding retinal stimulation Strabismus Greek strabismos — squinting Manifest ocular misalignment\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Eye movement systems — speed and latency: SYSTEM VELOCITY LATENCY PURPOSE Saccadic 500–1000°/s 200 ms Fast refixation; reading; scanning Smooth pursuit 30°/s — Track moving targets; keeps image on fovea Optokinetic 90°/s 125 ms Full-field visual stabilization Vergence 20°/s 160 ms (slowest) Binocular alignment; convergence/divergence VOR 90 °/s 15 ms (fastest) Gaze stabilization during head movement AC/A ratio — the engine of accommodative vergence: Normal AC/A: 4:1 to 6:1 (4–6 PD of convergence per 1D of accommodation) Formula (Gradient method): AC/A = (phoria at near – phoria at distance) ÷ accommodative stimulus Formula (Calculated): AC/A = IPD (cm) + (near phoria – far phoria) ÷ near power (D) HIGH AC /A (>6:1) → excess convergence for accommodation → Divergence excess: exo at far, ortho/less exo at near (high AC/A) → Convergence excess: ortho/eso at far, high eso at near (high AC/A) → Accommodative esotropia: hyperope who crosses at near LOW AC /A (<4:1) → insufficient convergence for accommodation → Convergence insufficiency: exo at near, ortho at far (low AC/A) → Divergence insufficiency: eso at far, ortho/less eso at near (low AC/A) NORMAL AC /A (4–6:1) → equal deviation at distance and near → Basic exophoria, basic esophoria, FVD Sheard's criterion: Fusional reserve must be at least 2× the demand (phoria). If compensating reserve < 2× phoria → symptomatic (cannot maintain fusion comfortably) Example: Exophoria of 8PD; Positive Fusional Convergence (PFC) must be ≥16PD to pass Percival's criterion: The phoria must fall within the middle third of the fusional range. Take the full vergence range (NFC to PFC) Patient is comfortable if phoria is in the middle ⅓ Fixation disparity criterion (Morgan's correlates): Used to assess whether BV is comfortable under natural conditions — not dissociated like phoria testing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"BV anomalies master table: Condition Distance phoria Near phoria AC/A Key feature Convergence Insufficiency (CI) Ortho / small exo HIGH exo Low Receded NPC; near symptoms Divergence Excess (DE) HIGH exo Ortho / less exo High Closes eye in sunlight; good near Basic Exophoria Exo Exo (equal) Normal Similar deviation at all distances Divergence Insufficiency (DI) HIGH eso Ortho / less eso Low Diplopia at distance; may be neurological Convergence Excess (CE) Ortho / small eso HIGH eso High Accommodative; hyperopia + near eso Basic Esophoria Eso Eso (equal) Normal High tonic vergence at all distances Fusional Vergence Dysfunction (FVD) Ortho Ortho Normal Reduced fusional reserves; normal phorias High AC/A rule: Excess conditions (DE, CE) = High AC/A (excess convergence per diopter) Low AC/A rule: Insufficiency conditions (CI, DI) = Low AC/A (insufficient convergence per diopter) Worth's three grades of binocular vision: GRADE 1 — Simultaneous Macular Perception ( SMP ) Most elementary; both maculae stimulated simultaneously Presence = no suppression of either eye Absence = complete suppression of one eye GRADE 2 — Fusion (flat/superimposition fusion) Two images merged into one Has amplitude — can overcome prism dissociation to fuse Tests: Worth 4-dot test, Prism fusion ranges GRADE 3 — Stereopsis (depth perception from binocular disparity) Highest grade; 3D perception from slightly disparate retinal images Tests: Randot, TNO , Frisby, Lang Normal: 20–40 seconds of arc Retinal correspondence: NORMAL RETINAL CORRESPONDENCE ( NRC ) Both foveas = same visual direction Nasal retina one eye ↔ temporal retina other eye Present in normals and heterophorias Tested by: Hering-Bielschowsky after-image test → harmonious result ANOMALOUS RETINAL CORRESPONDENCE ( ARC ) Fovea of fixating eye ↔ extrafoveal area of deviating eye = same direction Develops in constant strabismus with fixed angle The brain rewires to avoid diplopia Harmonious ARC : anomalous neutral point = angle of deviation (fully adapted) Unharmonious ARC : anomalous neutral point ≠ angle of deviation Tested by: Bagolini striated lenses, after-image test (crossed = ARC ) Physiologic diplopia: FIXATED OBJECT (on horopter) → single vision OBJECT BEYOND HOROPTER : Stimulates nasal retina of both eyes simultaneously Nasal retina = temporal visual direction Both eyes see the object to the temporal side → UNCROSSED (homonymous) diplopia Objects in DISTANCE (esophoric tendency) = uncrossed OBJECT NEARER THAN HOROPTER : Stimulates temporal retina of both eyes Temporal retina = nasal visual direction Both eyes see object to the nasal side → CROSSED (heteronymous) diplopia Objects NEAR (exophoric tendency) = crossed Mnemonic: \\\"FAR = UNCROSSED; NEAR = CROSSED\\\" Or: \\\"Far objects appear same-sided; Near objects cross over\\\" Suppression: FACULTATIVE suppression Only during binocular conditions Pattern: periphery suppression (central BV maintained) Common in: exodeviations (suppresses peripheral diplopia) OBLIGATORY suppression Even when attempting binocular conditions Central suppression zone + peripheral Common in: constant esotropia, deep amblyopia Associated: dense amblyopia, ARC Amblyopia classification: Type Cause Key feature Strabismic Constant strabismus; one eye suppressed Most common type; eccentric fixation possible Anisometropic Significantly different refractive errors; one eye blurred Often no strabismus; treatment: correct Rx + patching Deprivation Physical obstruction (cataract, ptosis, corneal opacity) Worst prognosis; must treat within critical period Ametropic Bilateral high refractive error (bilateral high hyperopia, astigmatism) Both eyes affected; often missed because no obvious strabismus Meridional High uncorrected astigmatism in early life One meridian of acuity affected Critical period for amblyopia treatment: most sensitive 0–2 years; treatable up to ~8–10 years; progressively harder after age 7.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Hering's Law vs Sherrington's Law: Feature Hering's Law Sherrington's Law Scope Binocular (both eyes) Monocular (one eye) Rule Yoke muscles receive equal + simultaneous innervation Agonist contracts = antagonist relaxes equally Example Dextroversion: R-LR and L-MR get equal impulses Supraduction: SR contracts; IR relaxes Clinical use Explains spread of paresis in gaze palsy Explains mechanical limits of eye movement Esophoria vs Exophoria management approach: Esophoria Exophoria Principle Reduce convergence demand Increase fusional convergence reserve Lens approach Plus lenses reduce accommodation → reduce AC/A-driven convergence — Prism approach BI prism (relaxes convergence) BO prism (temporarily relieves exo) Vision therapy Divergence training Convergence training Patching Not indicated Not indicated NRC vs ARC clinical tests: Test NRC result ARC result After-image test (Hering-Bielschowsky) Symmetric cross (harmonious) Asymmetric / crossed Bagolini striated lenses X pattern passes through fixation X pattern displaced Worth 4-dot 4 dots seen (fusion) Variable\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Normal AC/A range 4:1 to 6:1 (4–6 PD/D) Outside this = anomaly of vergence-accommodation Sheard's criterion Fusional reserve ≥ 2× phoria Must double the phoria to be comfortable Saccadic velocity 500–1000°/s Fastest voluntary eye movement Vergence velocity 20°/s Slowest eye movement system VOR latency 15 ms Fastest eye movement reflex Saccadic latency 200 ms Standard refixation reaction time Normal binocular VF 180° horizontal Combined temporal fields Common binocular VF 120° Central binocular overlap NPC normal ≤8 cm >10 cm = convergence insufficiency Panum's area (fovea) 6–10 arc min Very small at fovea; broadens peripherally\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Eye movement systems velocity — \\\"Saccade Wins; Vergence Crawls; VOR is Instant\\\" Saccade 500–1000°/s; Vergence 20°/s (slowest); VOR 15ms latency (fastest reflex) AC/A anomalies — High vs Low High AC/A = Excess (too much convergence per D): Convergence Excess, Divergence Excess Low AC/A = Insufficiency (too little convergence per D): Convergence Insufficiency, Divergence Insufficiency Sheard's 2:1 rule — \\\"Reserve must be Twice the demand\\\" PFC ≥ 2 × exophoria (or NFC ≥ 2 × esophoria) Physiologic diplopia — \\\"Far = Uncrossed; Near = Crossed\\\" Beyond fixation → uncrossed; nearer than fixation → crossed Worth's 3 grades — \\\"Super Flat Stereo\\\" Grade 1 = Superimposition; Grade 2 = Flat Fusion; Grade 3 = Stereopsis Amblyopia types — \\\"SAD Am\\\" = Strabismic, Anisometropic, Deprivation, Ametropic, Meridional\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"BV ANOMALY MAP — AC/A + DEVIATION PATTERN ────────────────────────────────────────── DISTANCE PHORIA EXOPHORIA ← ──────── → ESOPHORIA | | HIGH AC /A: Divergence Excess Convergence Excess (exo far, ortho near) (ortho far, eso near) | | LOW AC /A: Convergence Insuffic. Divergence Insuffic. (ortho far, exo near) (eso far, ortho near) | | NORMAL AC /A: Basic Exophoria Basic Esophoria (equal exo far+near) (equal eso far+near) ↓ FVD : Normal phorias; reduced fusional reserves PHYSIOLOGIC DIPLOPIA ────────────────────── OBJECT NEAR FIXATION POINT OBJECT FAR | | | CROSSED diplopia SINGLE VISION UNCROSSED diplopia (heteronymous) (homonymous) WORTH 'S GRADES ─────────────── Grade 1: ⊕ → simultaneous macular perception Grade 2: ⊕⊕ → flat fusion with amplitude Grade 3: 🔷 → stereopsis (3D depth)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Vergence is the fastest eye movement Vergence is the SLOWEST (20°/s, 160ms latency). VOR is the fastest reflex (15ms latency); saccade is the fastest voluntary movement. High AC/A causes convergence insufficiency High AC/A causes EXCESS conditions (CE, DE). Convergence Insufficiency has a LOW AC/A. Objects beyond the fixation point cause crossed diplopia Far (beyond fixation) objects cause UNCROSSED diplopia. Near (closer than fixation) objects cause CROSSED diplopia. ARC develops in heterophoria ARC develops in constant strabismus. Heterophoria maintains NRC because binocular vision is maintained most of the time. Hering's law applies to one eye (monocular) Hering's law applies to BINOCULAR yoke muscles. Sherrington's law applies to MONOCULAR agonist-antagonist pairs. Suppression permanently damages vision Suppression is reversible when treated early (within the critical period). The danger is that prolonged suppression leads to amblyopia, which can become permanent if untreated beyond the critical period.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Normal AC/A 4:1 to 6:1 High AC/A conditions Convergence Excess, Divergence Excess Low AC/A conditions Convergence Insufficiency, Divergence Insufficiency Vergence velocity 20°/s (slowest eye movement) VOR latency 15 ms (fastest) Saccade latency 200 ms Sheard's criterion Fusional reserve ≥ 2× phoria Worth Grade 1 Simultaneous macular perception Worth Grade 2 Flat fusion with amplitude Worth Grade 3 Stereopsis Hering's Law Yoke muscles = equal innervation (binocular) Sherrington's Law Agonist contracts = antagonist relaxes (monocular) Physiologic diplopia — far Uncrossed (homonymous) Physiologic diplopia — near Crossed (heteronymous) ARC definition Fovea one eye + extrafoveal area other eye = same direction NPC normal ≤8 cm NPC CI >10 cm\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"1. A 12-year-old patient reports headaches and blurred vision after 20 minutes of reading. Distance acuity is 20/20 OU. Cover test at distance shows orthophoria; cover test at near reveals 12PD exophoria. NPC breaks at 14 cm and recovers at 22 cm. Positive Fusional Convergence at near is 8/10/6 (break/recovery). What is the most likely diagnosis and what does Sheard's criterion indicate? A. Basic exophoria; passes Sheard's B. Convergence insufficiency; fails Sheard's C. Divergence excess; passes Sheard's D. Convergence insufficiency; passes Sheard's Answer B. Convergence insufficiency; fails Sheard's criterion. The pattern — orthophoria at distance + significant exophoria at near + receded NPC (>10cm) + near symptoms — defines convergence insufficiency (low AC/A). Sheard's criterion requires positive fusional convergence ≥ 2× the near exophoria: 2 × 12PD = 24PD needed. The PFC blur/break is only 10PD — well below the 24PD required. The patient fails Sheard's, which explains the symptoms (the system is working near capacity). Management: plus adds for near to reduce accommodative convergence demand, plus vision therapy (convergence exercises — pencil push-ups, Brock string). 2. A child with right esotropia is examined with the Hering-Bielschowsky after-image test. The after-image from the right eye appears displaced to the left of the after-image from the left eye, indicating a non-symmetric result. What does this finding indicate? A. Normal retinal correspondence with strabismus B. Anomalous retinal correspondence (harmonious) C. Anomalous retinal correspondence (unharmonious) D. Suppression of the right eye Answer B. Anomalous retinal correspondence (harmonious ARC). In the Hering-Bielschowsky after-image test with NRC, the after-images would appear as a symmetric cross (equal displacement matching the angle of strabismus). Displacement in a non-symmetric pattern that exactly matches the angle of strabismus = harmonious ARC, where the anomalous neutral point has fully adapted to equal the angle of deviation. The brain has rewired — the extrafoveal area of the right eye now shares the same visual direction as the left fovea. Unharmonious ARC would show the neutral point NOT matching the deviation. Suppression would prevent the after-image from being seen at all. 3. A patient presents with spontaneous oscillating eye movements with no fast phase. The movements are equal in both directions. He reports the movements were present since birth and improve slightly when he converges. What type of nystagmus does this describe? A. Acquired pendular nystagmus B. Jerk nystagmus from a vestibular lesion C. Infantile nystagmus syndrome (congenital nystagmus) with null point D. Gaze-evoked nystagmus Answer C. Infantile nystagmus syndrome (congenital nystagmus) with null point. The key features: (1) present since birth — congenital onset; (2) pendular in primary position (equal velocity both ways — no fast/slow phase); (3) dampens with convergence — this is the diagnostic hallmark of infantile nystagmus syndrome (INS), also called congenital nystagmus. Patients often adopt a head turn to bring gaze to their null point where the nystagmus is least intense. The convergence dampening explains why some patients read with the book held very close — the convergence demand reduces the nystagmus. Acquired pendular nystagmus (option A) has a known adult onset (MS, brainstem lesion) and does not dampen with convergence. Jerk nystagmus (option B) has fast/slow phases. Gaze-evoked (option D) only appears at eccentric gaze, not in primary position. 4. During binocular rivalry testing, a patient views a vertical grating with one eye and a horizontal grating with the other. The expected percept is: A. A diagonal grating (fusion of both) B. A plaid pattern (superimposition) C. Alternating suppression of each grating D. Permanent suppression of the non-dominant eye's grating Answer C. Alternating suppression of each grating. Binocular rivalry occurs when the two eyes are shown incompatible images that cannot be fused. The brain cannot fuse a vertical and horizontal grating into a single stable percept. Instead, it alternates — one eye's image is perceived for a few seconds, then the other takes over, back and forth. This alternating suppression is the defining feature of binocular rivalry. It is NOT the same as permanent suppression (which occurs in constant strabismus with deep amblyopia — option D). It is also not fusion (option A/B) because the stimuli are too dissimilar for the disparity detectors to merge them.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"BINOCULAR VISION AND FUSION.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: normal AC/A range, 7 BV anomalies with their distance/near phoria pattern, Worth's 3 grades, Hering's vs Sherrington's, physiologic diplopia rule, Sheard's criterion formula. Core targets: The 7 BV anomaly conditions with AC/A for each Physiologic diplopia — far = uncrossed, near = crossed — explain the mechanism Sheard's criterion: reserve must be ≥ 2× demand Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the BV anomaly table (7 conditions). For each, fill in: distance phoria, near phoria, AC/A (high/normal/low). Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain why a child with +5.00D hyperopia who goes uncorrected develops esotropia at near — without using \\\"AC/A\\\" until your last sentence. Start from the accommodation demand. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Normal AC/A? 4:1 to 6:1 Convergence Insufficiency AC/A? Low Convergence Excess AC/A? High Sheard's 2:1 rule? Fusional reserve ≥ 2× phoria Far object = what diplopia? Uncrossed (homonymous) Near object = what diplopia? Crossed (heteronymous) Vergence velocity? 20°/s (slowest) VOR latency? 15 ms (fastest) Worth Grade 3? Stereopsis ARC definition? Fovea + extrafoveal area share visual direction SO innervation? CN IV (trochlear) LR innervation? CN VI (abducens) IO: only EOM not from Annulus of Zinn? Yes — IO originates from orbital floor SR + IO — yoke muscles for? Right eye: SR yoke = left IO (dextrolevation) Horopter definition? All points in space with equal retinal disparity as fixation point Empirical vs Vieth-Müller horopter? Empirical: flatter (nasal curvature); VMC: perfect circle Panum's area at fovea? 6–10 arc minutes Panum's area at 12° periphery? 30–40 arc minutes Binocular rivalry result? Alternating suppression (not fusion) PFC (base-out) normal at distance? 9Δ blur, 19Δ break, 10Δ recovery (Morgan) Jerk nystagmus: fixation suppression test? Peripheral vestibular: suppressed; Central: NOT suppressed Downbeat nystagmus suggests? Cervicomedullary junction lesion (Chiari malformation) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete accommodative esotropia mechanism: from uncorrected hyperopia → accommodation demand → AC/A convergence → angle of deviation → brain adaptation (NRC vs ARC) → treatment rationale. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow BV anomaly table + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (accommodative esotropia) 4th 1 week Full AC/A mechanism sequence Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-morgan-s-norms-expected-values-for-bv-tests\",\"heading\":\"Morgan's Norms (Expected Values for BV Tests)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Morgan's norms are the EXPECTED normal values for the 21-step OEP examination sequence. These tell you what a normal finding looks like for each test — if a patient deviates significantly from these, it indicates a BV anomaly. Key Morgan's norms (most board-tested): Test Expected Normal Finding Significance if outside range NPC (Near Point of Convergence) ≤8 cm break; ≤10 cm recovery NPC > 10cm break = convergence insufficiency Distance phoria (cover test) Orthophoria or ≤1Δ exo Any significant phoria = investigate Near phoria (cover test at 40cm) 3Δ exo (range 0–6Δ exo) Exo > 6Δ or any eso at near = investigate Distance PFC (positive fusional convergence) Blur 9, Break 19, Recovery 10Δ Reduced = fusional convergence deficiency Distance NFC (negative fusional convergence) Blur 7, Break 11, Recovery 8Δ Near PFC Blur 17, Break 21, Recovery 11Δ Reduced = CI if NPC also receded Near NFC Blur 13, Break 21, Recovery 13Δ NRA (Negative Relative Accommodation) +2.00 D Reduced = accommodative insufficiency PRA (Positive Relative Accommodation) −2.37 D Reduced = convergence excess or high AC/A AC/A ratio 4:1 to 6:1 High → CE or DE; Low → CI or DI\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-sheard-s-criterion-detailed\",\"heading\":\"Sheard's Criterion (Detailed)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"SHEARD 'S CRITERION : The compensating fusional reserve must be AT LEAST TWICE the demand (phoria) Formula: Compensating reserve ≥ 2 × phoria For exophoria: PFC (positive fusional convergence) must be ≥ 2 × exophoria For esophoria: NFC (negative fusional convergence) must be ≥ 2 × esophoria Example: Exophoria 8Δ at near; Near PFC blur = 10Δ Sheard's requirement: PFC ≥ 2 × 8 = 16Δ Patient has 10Δ PFC → FAILS Sheard's → symptomatic Prism needed to restore Sheard's: Prism = (2/3) × phoria − (1/3) × compensating reserve = (2/3)(8) − (1/3)(10) = 5.33 − 3.33 = 2.0Δ BI\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-percival-s-criterion\",\"heading\":\"Percival's Criterion\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"PERCIVAL 'S CRITERION : The phoria must fall within the MIDDLE THIRD of the total fusional vergence range Method: 1. Find the full vergence range: add NFC + PFC (total fusional range) 2. The middle third = between 1/3 and 2/3 of the total range 3. Patient is comfortable if their phoria is within this zone Example: Distance: PFC = 20Δ, NFC = 10Δ → Total range = 30Δ Middle third = between 10Δ and 20Δ from the NFC end If phoria is 5Δ exo → phoria falls in the outer third → FAILS Percival's When to apply Percival's vs Sheard's: Sheard's: best for EXOPHORIC patients (tests positive fusional reserve) Percival's: best for ESOPHORIC or high AC/A patients; also used when both NFC and PFC are reduced\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-neumuller-s-neumueller-s-criterion\",\"heading\":\"Neumuller's (Neumueller's) Criterion\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"NEUMULLER 'S CRITERION : Applies specifically to ESOPHORIC patients Rule: The prism prescribed should equal HALF the difference between: Phoria at near − Phoria at distance Formula: Prism = (near eso − distance eso) / 2 Example: Distance: orthophoria (0Δ); Near: 8Δ esophoria Prism = (8 − 0) / 2 = 4Δ BI This is used when the near eso is significantly larger than distance eso (high AC/A), suggesting the near esophoria is the primary clinical problem.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-oep-method-and-soap-analysis-syllabi-3-4\",\"heading\":\"OEP Method and SOAP Analysis (Syllabi 3.4)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"OEP (Optometric Extension Program) Method: A systematic binocular vision examination sequence (21 steps) that measures all aspects of visual function in a standardized order. KEY OEP PRINCIPLES : 1. Near vision is primary — vision is a learned skill and near vision drives most BV problems 2. Evaluate binocular vision under natural (associated) conditions when possible 3. Analysis uses Morgan's norms as expected values 4. Management follows a hierarchy: lenses first, prisms second, vision therapy third OEP 21-STEP SEQUENCE (key steps for boards): Steps 1-5: Distant VA and refraction (objective + subjective) Steps 6-9: Distance BV analysis (phorias, fusional ranges) Steps 10-13: Near VA and refraction Steps 14-17: Near BV analysis (phorias, NPC , fusional ranges, AC/A) Steps 18-21: Additional tests (stereopsis, color vision, VF, DPA ) SOAP Analysis: A problem-oriented approach to BV case analysis: S ubjective — patient's chief complaint and symptoms O bjective — measured test results (VA, phorias, fusional ranges, AC/A, NPC) A ssessment — diagnosis based on O compared to Morgan's norms and Sheard's/Percival's criteria P lan — management: spectacles, prisms, vision therapy referral, occlusion\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-amblyopia-management-completing-the-classification\",\"heading\":\"Amblyopia — Management (Completing the Classification)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Types (recap): Strabismic, Anisometropic, Deprivation, Ametropic, Meridional Management hierarchy: STEP 1: CORRECT THE CAUSE Prescribe full refractive correction (glasses/contact lens) Wait 4-8 weeks for glasses alone to improve VA before patching (Passive glasses therapy = some VA improvement from optical correction alone) STEP 2: PENALIZE THE PREFERRED EYE (force use of amblyopic eye) a. Patching (occlusion therapy) — MOST EFFECTIVE Part-time patching (2-6 hours/day) = as effective as full-time for moderate amblyopia Duration: until VA equalizes or no further improvement over 2 cycles Compliance issue: children resist patching → atropine is alternative b. Atropine penalization 1% atropine drops in the DOMINANT eye: blurs near vision in dominant eye Forces use of amblyopic eye for near tasks Comparable to patching for moderate amblyopia ( PEDIG trials) Advantage: no compliance battle; child wears glasses Risk: photophobia in dominant eye c. Optical penalization (Bangerter filters, blur lenses) Opaque or diffusion filters on spectacle lens over dominant eye STEP 3: ACTIVE VISION THERAPY (if passive methods plateau) Dichoptic training, binocular perceptual learning CRITICAL PERIODS : Most sensitive: 0–2 years (amblyopia develops fastest here) Effective treatment: up to age 7–8 years (traditional) Possible improvement: up to age 12–18 years (with intensive therapy) Adult treatment: less responsive but not impossible KEY : The earlier treatment begins, the better the prognosis\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-morgan-s-correlates-clinical-criteria-amblyopia-management-and-eccentric-fixation-eccentric-fixation-clinical-detail\",\"heading\":\"Eccentric Fixation — Clinical Detail\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"DEFINITION : Fixation not occurring at the fovea — the patient uses a non-foveal retinal area for fixation CAUSES : Long-standing uncorrected refractive error Deep amblyopia with foveal suppression Strabismus (especially constant unilateral esotropia) Macular disease destroying foveal function ASSESSMENT : Visuoscopy — examiner shines a target (star pattern) onto the patient's fundus while the patient fixates a small target Normal: star projects onto the fovea Eccentric: star projects onto extrafoveal area → measured in degrees/prism diopters CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE : Eccentric fixation is a marker of DEEP AMBLYOPIA Prognosis for full VA recovery is worse with eccentric fixation Management: same amblyopia treatment, but harder to improve Angle of eccentric fixation ≠ Angle of strabismus (these can differ) The degree of eccentricity is a poor prognostic factor for final VA NOTATION : Measured in degrees from the fovea and direction (nasal, temporal, superior, inferior) E.g., \\\"2° nasal eccentric fixation\\\" = patient fixates 2° nasal to fovea\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-extraocular-muscles-eoms-and-the-horopter-extraocular-muscles-complete-coverage\",\"heading\":\"Extraocular Muscles — Complete Coverage\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Overview: The eye has 6 EOMs: 4 recti (straight muscles) and 2 obliques. All except the inferior oblique originate from the Annulus of Zinn at the orbital apex. They are controlled by CN III, IV, and VI. EOM origins and insertions: MUSCLE ORIGIN INSERTION NERVE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── SR (Superior Rectus) Annulus of Zinn Anterior to equator (superior) CN III IR (Inferior Rectus) Annulus of Zinn Anterior to equator (inferior) CN III MR (Medial Rectus) Annulus of Zinn Anterior to equator (medial) CN III LR (Lateral Rectus) Annulus of Zinn Anterior to equator (lateral) CN VI SO (Superior Oblique) Annulus of Zinn Posterior to equator (superior) CN IV IO (Inferior Oblique) Medial orbital wall Posterior to equator (inferior) CN III (floor of orbit, nasal side) SPECIAL FACTS : SO = longest EOM ; passes through the TROCHLEA (pulley at superomedial orbit) → trochlea changes direction of SO pull IO = ONLY EOM not originating from Annulus of Zinn LR = ONLY muscle innervated by CN VI (abducens) SO = ONLY muscle innervated by CN IV (trochlear) All others (SR, IR, MR, IO) = CN III (oculomotor) Primary, secondary, and tertiary actions: Muscle Primary action Secondary action Tertiary action MR Adduction — — LR Abduction — — SR Elevation Intorsion Adduction IR Depression Extorsion Adduction SO Intorsion Depression Abduction IO Extorsion Elevation Abduction Memory rule for SO and IO: \\\"SO4 and LR6\\\" — Superior Oblique = CN IV; Lateral Rectus = CN VI; all others = CN III The Benzene Ring — Diagnostic Positions of Gaze The benzene ring (hexagonal diagram) maps which single muscle is primarily tested in each of the 6 cardinal positions of gaze. In each cardinal position, the muscle's primary action is isolation so that paresis of that muscle is most obvious. UP-LEFT UP-RIGHT (L SR, R IO) (R SR, L IO) \\\\ / \\\\ / LEFT GAZE ─── (L LR, R MR) CENTER (R LR, L MR) ─── RIGHT GAZE / \\\\ / \\\\ (L IR, R SO) (R IR, L SO) DOWN-LEFT DOWN-RIGHT How to read the benzene ring: Position of gaze Right eye muscle (primary) Left eye muscle (yoke) Right gaze R LR (lateral rectus) L MR (medial rectus) Left gaze R MR (medial rectus) L LR (lateral rectus) Up-right R SR (superior rectus) L IO (inferior oblique) Down-right R IR (inferior rectus) L SO (superior oblique) Up-left R IO (inferior oblique) L SR (superior rectus) Down-left R SO (superior oblique) L IR (inferior rectus) Why the obliques matter most in the benzene ring: The obliques are tested ONLY in adduction: SO is tested by asking the eye to look DOWN-in (adduct first, then depress → SO depresses an adducted eye) IO is tested by asking the eye to look UP-in (adduct first, then elevate → IO elevates an adducted eye) When the eye is ABDUCTED, the recti (SR/IR) are primary elevators/depressors. When the eye is ADDUCTED, the obliques (SO/IO) are primary elevators/depressors. ABDUCTED EYE : SR elevates, IR depresses (recti work best here) ADDUCTED EYE : IO elevates, SO depresses (obliques work best here) Board trap: SR palsy looks like IR palsy in adduction — test in cardinal positions! Ductions, Versions, and Vergences: DUCTIONS (monocular movements — one eye only): Abduction = outward (away from nose) Adduction = inward (toward nose) Supraduction = upward (elevation) Infraduction = downward (depression) Intorsion = top of cornea rotates nasally Extorsion = top of cornea rotates temporally VERSIONS (binocular, conjugate — both eyes move same direction): Dextroversion = both eyes right Levoversion = both eyes left Supraversion = both eyes up Infraversion = both eyes down Dextrocycloversion = both eyes intort/extort together (right) Levocycloversion = both eyes intort/extort together (left) VERGENCES (binocular, disconjugate — eyes move opposite directions): Convergence = both eyes adduct (near) Divergence = both eyes abduct (distance) Incyclovergence = both eyes intort Excyclovergence = both eyes extort Vertical vergence = one eye up, one eye down Hering's Law and Sherrington's Law (law breakdown): HERING 'S LAW (Binocular — VERSIONS ): Equal and simultaneous innervation to YOKE MUSCLES of both eyes What it means: When you look right, R LR and L MR get exactly equal nerve impulses Why: Ensures both eyes move the same amount at the same time (conjugate gaze) Clinical use: In a CN VI palsy (R LR paretic), the gaze command still fires equally to both yoke muscles — but R LR is weak, causing both eyes to drift left together (the secondary deviation = same angle as primary deviation) SHERRINGTON 'S LAW (Monocular — DUCTIONS ): When an agonist contracts, the antagonist relaxes by an equal and opposite amount = Reciprocal innervation What it means: When R SR fires (elevation), R IR relaxes simultaneously Why: Prevents muscles from fighting each other; allows smooth, graded movement Clinical use: Explains why a tight IR (e.g., after thyroid eye disease) restricts SR elevation — even if SR is healthy, the co-contracted IR resists it Hering vs Sherrington — the board distinction: Feature Hering's Law Sherrington's Law Scope BINOCULAR (both eyes) MONOCULAR (one eye) Movement type Versions (conjugate) Ductions Rule Yoke muscles = equal innervation Agonist contracts = antagonist relaxes Example Looking right: R LR = L MR get equal impulse Looking up: R SR contracts; R IR relaxes\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-extraocular-muscles-eoms-and-the-horopter-horopter-and-panum-s-fusional-area-full-coverage\",\"heading\":\"Horopter and Panum's Fusional Area — Full Coverage\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"The Horopter — what it is: The horopter is the curved surface in visual space through the fixation point that contains all object points whose images fall on corresponding retinal elements of both eyes at a given fixation distance. Introduced by: Francisco de Aguilonius (Aguilonius), 1613 — term comes from Greek horos (boundary) + opter (observer) Clinically: Objects on the horopter are seen as single. Objects off the horopter (too near or too far) are seen as double (physiological diplopia) — unless they fall within Panum's area. Two types of horopter: GEOMETRIC HOROPTER = VIETH- MÜLLER CIRCLE The theoretical circle passing through the fixation point and the nodal points of both eyes Based purely on geometric optics (corresponding retinal points = exact symmetry) EMPIRICAL HOROPTER What is actually measured in a real human eye It is NOT the same as the Vieth-Müller circle HILLEBRAND DEVIATION : The empirical horopter deviates from the Vieth-Müller circle in a predictable way: - At NEAR distances: empirical horopter falls INSIDE (in front of) the Vieth-Müller circle - At FAR distances: empirical horopter falls OUTSIDE (behind) the Vieth-Müller circle - The deviation = because corresponding retinal points are not perfectly geometric ABATHIC DISTANCE : The distance at which the empirical horopter most closely matches the Vieth-Müller circle (the \\\"true\\\" geometric horopter) Approximately 1–2 meters Panum's Fusional Area: Named after Peter Ludvig Panum (1858). The zone around the horopter within which objects produce DISPARATE (non-identical) retinal images yet are still FUSED into a single percept — not diplopia. DEFINITION : The zone of single binocular vision immediately surrounding the horopter Objects within Panum's area → single vision (despite some retinal disparity) Objects outside Panum's area → physiological diplopia SIZE OF PANUM 'S AREA : At the FOVEA : narrowest → 6–10 arcmin (very small; precise binocular alignment needed) At 12° eccentricity: ~30–40 arcmin (wider; more tolerance for misalignment) Panum's area INCREASES with distance from fixation (peripheral = more tolerant) WHY IT GETS WIDER PERIPHERALLY : Peripheral retina has lower spatial resolution (larger receptive fields) A larger amount of disparity is tolerated before the visual system detects mismatch This is why you can fuse peripheral objects easily even if not perfectly aligned THREE FUNCTIONS OF THE PERIPHERAL EXPANSION : 1. Allows binocular fusion of large objects (wide disparity in periphery tolerated) 2. Provides a \\\"safety margin\\\" for vergence errors without inducing diplopia 3. Supports the perception of a continuous single visual world despite small deviations Physiological diplopia — the full mechanism: FIXATION POINT (on horopter) → retinal images on corresponding elements → SINGLE VISION OBJECT BEYOND THE HOROPTER (farther than fixation): Image falls on NASAL retina of both eyes Nasal retina → projects to TEMPORAL visual field direction Both eyes \\\"point\\\" the object temporally → appears on same side (homonymous) RESULT : UNCROSSED (homonymous) diplopia Memory: \\\" FAR = UNCROSSED \\\" / FAR and UNcrossed both have 3 letters ending in consonants OBJECT NEARER THAN THE HOROPTER (closer than fixation): Image falls on TEMPORAL retina of both eyes Temporal retina → projects to NASAL visual field direction Both eyes \\\"point\\\" the object nasally (but from opposite sides) → cross-pattern RESULT : CROSSED (heteronymous) diplopia Memory: \\\" NEAR = CROSSED \\\" Horopter and Panum's — the board comparison: Parameter Horopter Panum's Fusional Area Definition Curved surface of corresponding retinal points Zone around horopter where fusion still occurs What happens here Single vision (no disparity) Single vision (some disparity tolerated) What happens outside it Physiological diplopia Physiological diplopia Size/extent A single theoretical surface A zone (6–40 arcmin wide depending on eccentricity) Clinical significance Defines the limit of perfect binocular alignment Defines the functional range of fusion\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-extraocular-muscles-eoms-and-the-horopter-board-traps-extended\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps — Extended\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"All 6 EOMs originate from the Annulus of Zinn The INFERIOR OBLIQUE originates from the medial floor of the orbit — it is the only EOM NOT from the Annulus of Zinn. CN III controls all 4 recti CN III controls SR, IR, MR only. The LATERAL RECTUS is CN VI. Also CN III controls the inferior oblique (not SO — SO is CN IV).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus\",\"heading\":\"Extended Topics: Retinal Rivalry, Fusion Amplitude, and Nystagmus\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"(Syllabi section 12.0 — Fusion/Retinal Rivalry | Added June 6, 2026)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-retinal-rivalry-binocular-rivalry\",\"heading\":\"Retinal Rivalry (Binocular Rivalry)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Plain version first: Close one eye and look at a vertical striped pattern. Open the other eye and show it a horizontal striped pattern. Your brain cannot fuse these — they are too different to merge into one image. Instead of seeing both at once, your brain flips between them: you see vertical stripes for a moment, then horizontal stripes, then vertical again. You do not control the switching. This is called retinal rivalry (also called binocular rivalry ). DEFINITION : When the two eyes receive completely incompatible images (too different to fuse), the visual cortex alternates between the two images rather than superimposing them. Neither image is permanently suppressed — they take turns dominating perception. WHEN IT OCCURS : Images presented to each eye are so dissimilar that sensory fusion is impossible. Examples: different colors, different shapes, different orientations in each eye. Contrast with suppression in strabismus: SUPPRESSION (strabismus): one image is constantly inhibited (same image repeatedly lost) RIVALRY : alternation happens — both images get perceived, just not simultaneously MECHANISM : The dominant eye's image suppresses the other for ~1–5 seconds Then the other eye's image breaks through The switch is involuntary and roughly periodic Rate of switching: influenced by attention, fatigue, image strength CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE : Used as a research tool to study visual consciousness and cortical dominance Anaglyph tests (red-green glasses with different images to each eye) use rivalry Rivalry is more likely with high-contrast, detailed, or moving images Slower alternation may indicate neurological or visual pathway disease BOARD RULE : \\\"Rivalry = alternation (not permanent suppression)\\\" If both images are too different to fuse → rivalry If one image chronically dominates → suppression (strabismic)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-amplitude-of-fusion-fusional-vergence-range\",\"heading\":\"Amplitude of Fusion (Fusional Vergence Range)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Plain version first: Your eyes can converge or diverge a certain amount while still maintaining a single fused image. Push them too far in either direction and the image splits into two (diplopia). The total range — from where the image breaks going inward to where it breaks going outward — is the amplitude of fusion , also called the fusional vergence range or fusional reserve . DEFINITION : The total range of vergence (in prism diopters) over which a person maintains single binocular vision (fusion) without diplopia. COMPONENTS : POSITIVE FUSIONAL CONVERGENCE ( PFC ) — base-out prism tolerance How much convergence demand the system can handle while still fusing Measured with base-out (BO) prism until: Blur point: when accommodation/vergence can no longer keep up Break point: image splits into diplopia Recovery point: when fusion is re-established as prism is reduced NEGATIVE FUSIONAL CONVERGENCE ( NFC ) — base-in prism tolerance How much divergence demand the system can handle while still fusing Measured with base-in (BI) prism until blur/break/recovery NORMAL VALUES (Morgan's norms at distance): PFC (BO): Blur 9Δ | Break 19Δ | Recovery 10Δ NFC (BI): Blur 7Δ | Break 11Δ | Recovery 8Δ NORMAL VALUES (Morgan's norms at near): PFC (BO): Blur 17Δ | Break 21Δ | Recovery 11Δ NFC (BI): Blur 13Δ | Break 21Δ | Recovery 13Δ CLINICAL USE : Reduced PFC + exophoria → convergence insufficiency Reduced NFC + esophoria → divergence excess or accommodative esotropia Reduced BOTH NFC and PFC with normal phorias → fusional vergence dysfunction ( FVD ) Applied to Sheard's and Percival's criteria to determine if reserves are adequate BOARD RULE : \\\"Amplitude of fusion = the vergence range that maintains single vision\\\" Larger amplitude = more flexible binocular system = better tolerance of phorias Smaller amplitude = symptomatic even with small phorias\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-the-plain-version-first\",\"heading\":\"The Plain Version First\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Nystagmus is an involuntary, rhythmic oscillation of the eyes — the eyes drift or jerk repeatedly without the person choosing to move them. Think of it like a car windshield wiper that won't stop: the eyes keep moving back and forth, and the person cannot hold a steady gaze voluntarily. The clinical term for this phenomenon is nystagmus (from Greek nystagmos = drowsiness, nodding). But unlike drowsiness, the eye movements are fast and sustained. Two key things define any nystagmus: the direction of movement and whether it is smooth on both sides or has a fast/slow phase .\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-classification-the-framework\",\"heading\":\"Classification: The Framework\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"NYSTAGMUS ├── PHYSIOLOGICAL (normal — occurs in specific conditions) │ └── End-point nystagmus, optokinetic nystagmus ( OKN ), caloric nystagmus │ └── PATHOLOGICAL (abnormal — present in primary gaze or neutral position) ├── By WAVEFORM : │ ├── JERK nystagmus — has a SLOW drift + FAST corrective jerk │ │ Named by direction of the FAST phase │ └── PENDULAR nystagmus — equal velocity in both directions (no fast phase) │ Like a pendulum swinging equally both ways │ ├── By ONSET : │ ├── CONGENITAL (infantile) — present at birth or in first few months of life │ └── ACQUIRED — develops later in life (neurological cause until proven otherwise) │ └── By PLANE : ├── Horizontal (most common) ├── Vertical (rare; almost always neurological) └── Torsional (rotary)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-physiological-nystagmus-types\",\"heading\":\"Physiological Nystagmus Types\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"These are normal responses — the eye is working correctly. 1. END-POINT NYSTAGMUS What it is: Fine jerk nystagmus that appears when the eye is held at extreme lateral gaze Plain version: Hold your eyes all the way to the side and they start to drift back — the brain corrects with a jerk. This is normal. Key rule: Normal only at extreme gaze. Nystagmus in PRIMARY GAZE = always abnormal. 2. OPTOKINETIC NYSTAGMUS ( OKN ) What it is: Alternating slow pursuit + fast saccadic return when watching a moving repetitive pattern (like a train going by, or striped drum) Plain version: Your eyes follow a stripe (slow pursuit), then snap back to catch the next stripe (fast saccade). Over and over. Clinical use: - Tests integrity of pursuit system (slow phase) + saccade system (fast phase) - Used to CONFIRM visual acuity in pre-verbal infants — if OKN is present, child can see - Asymmetric OKN = parietal lobe lesion (drum moving toward lesion = absent/reduced OKN ) Direction convention: Named by direction of the FAST (saccadic) phase 3. CALORIC NYSTAGMUS What it is: Nystagmus induced by irrigation of the external ear canal with warm or cold water Plain version: Water changes the temperature of the horizontal semicircular canal, creating artificial endolymph convection — tricks the brain into thinking the head is turning Cold water → nystagmus AWAY from irrigated ear (fast phase contralateral) Warm water → nystagmus TOWARD irrigated ear (fast phase ipsilateral) Mnemonic: COWS — Cold Opposite, Warm Same Clinical use: Tests brainstem/vestibular integrity in comatose patients\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-pathological-nystagmus-high-yield-types\",\"heading\":\"Pathological Nystagmus — High-Yield Types\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Jerk nystagmus — slow drift + fast correction: VESTIBULAR NYSTAGMUS Cause: Inner ear (peripheral vestibular) or brainstem (central vestibular) lesion PERIPHERAL (labyrinth, CN VIII ): Horizontal or horizontal-torsional Fast phase AWAY from the lesion side SUPPRESSED by visual fixation Associated: vertigo, nausea, unilateral hearing loss, tinnitus Example: Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo ( BPPV ), Ménière's disease CENTRAL (brainstem/cerebellar): Often vertical or purely torsional NOT suppressed by fixation Absent or mild vertigo despite severe nystagmus Example: Multiple sclerosis, stroke, tumor Board rule: \\\"Peripheral = fixation suppresses; Central = fixation does NOT suppress\\\" GAZE-EVOKED NYSTAGMUS Beats in the direction of gaze (right-beating on right gaze, left-beating on left gaze) Cause: Cerebellar disease, drugs (anticonvulsants, sedatives, alcohol) Plain version: The brain can't hold the eyes in an eccentric position — they drift back, then correct. Most common drug-related nystagmus. DOWNBEAT NYSTAGMUS Fast phase is DOWNWARD Primary gaze or worsens on downgaze/lateral gaze Localization: Cranio-cervical junction (Chiari malformation), cerebellar flocculus lesion Board clue: Downbeat in primary gaze → think Chiari malformation / foramen magnum UPBEAT NYSTAGMUS Fast phase UPWARD Localization: Medulla (Wernicke's encephalopathy, thiamine deficiency) or anterior vermis Pendular nystagmus — equal velocity both ways: CONGENITAL MOTOR NYSTAGMUS (Infantile Nystagmus Syndrome — INS ) Onset: First few months of life Waveform: Pendular (infants) → becomes jerk nystagmus (older children) Direction: Usually HORIZONTAL , even on up/down gaze Key features: - NULL POINT : a gaze position where nystagmus is LEAST intense - HEAD TURN / TILT to null point = compensatory posture (not pathological) - DAMPENED by convergence (near fixation reduces nystagmus) - No oscillopsia (brain adapts — patient does NOT see world shaking) Causes: Idiopathic (most common), OR sensory (albinism, cone dystrophy, aniridea, cataract) Board clue: Null point + dampens with convergence + no oscillopsia = congenital ACQUIRED PENDULAR NYSTAGMUS Cause: Multiple sclerosis (brainstem demyelination), Whipple's disease Key difference from congenital: Patient HAS oscillopsia (world appears to shake) This is because the brain didn't adapt to it from birth LATENT / MANIFEST-LATENT NYSTAGMUS LATENT : Only appears when one eye is COVERED (disappears with both eyes open) MANIFEST-LATENT : Present all the time but WORSENS when one eye is covered Common in: Infantile esotropia, early childhood strabismus Direction: Fast phase toward the UNCOVERED (viewing) eye Clinical trap: VA measured with one eye covered → nystagmus appears → falsely low VA Always measure VA binocularly or with a neutral density filter (not full occlusion)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-nystagmus-features-to-document-clinically\",\"heading\":\"Nystagmus Features to Document Clinically\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Every nystagmus description should include these 6 features — the clinical term for this assessment is the nystagmus description protocol : 1. DIRECTION : Which way does the fast phase beat? (horizontal, vertical, torsional) 2. CONJUGACY : Both eyes moving together (conjugate) or separately (dissociated)? 3. AMPLITUDE : Fine (small excursion) vs coarse (large excursion) 4. FREQUENCY : Rapid (fine/fast) vs slow (pendular-like) 5. NULL POINT : Is there a gaze position where nystagmus diminishes? 6. FIXATION EFFECT : Does fixation suppress or worsen it? (Suppresses = peripheral vestibular; doesn't suppress = central)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-comparison-table-key-nystagmus-types\",\"heading\":\"Comparison Table: Key Nystagmus Types\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Type Waveform Direction Fixation effect Cause Congenital (INS) Pendular/jerk Horizontal Dampened Idiopathic, sensory Vestibular (peripheral) Jerk Away from lesion Suppressed Labyrinth, CN VIII Vestibular (central) Jerk or pendular Any (often vertical) NOT suppressed Brainstem/cerebellum Gaze-evoked Jerk Direction of gaze — Drugs, cerebellum Downbeat Jerk Downward — Chiari, flocculus Latent Jerk Toward viewing eye Induced by occlusion Infantile esotropia OKN Jerk Direction of fast phase Normal response Physiological\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-retinal-rivalry-fusion-amplitude-and-nystagmus-board-traps-nystagmus\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps (Nystagmus)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Nystagmus is always pathological Physiological nystagmus (OKN, end-point, caloric) is normal. Nystagmus in PRIMARY gaze is always abnormal. Nystagmus is named by the slow phase direction Jerk nystagmus is named by the FAST phase direction. The slow phase is the drift; the fast phase is the corrective saccade. Patients with congenital nystagmus see the world shaking Congenital nystagmus causes NO oscillopsia — the brain adapts from birth. Acquired nystagmus DOES cause oscillopsia. Peripheral vestibular nystagmus is not suppressed by fixation PERIPHERAL vestibular nystagmus IS suppressed by fixation. Central is not. COWS means cold = same side fast phase COWS = Cold Opposite, Warm Same. Cold water → fast phase toward the OPPOSITE (contralateral) ear. The superior oblique elevates the eye The IO elevates (especially in adduction). The SO DEPRESSES the adducted eye and also INTORTS. SR elevates the abducted eye. The horopter is the same as the Vieth-Müller circle The Vieth-Müller circle is the GEOMETRIC (theoretical) horopter. The actual EMPIRICAL horopter deviates from it — this is the Hillebrand deviation. Panum's area is largest at the fovea It is SMALLEST (narrowest) at the fovea (6–10 arcmin). It gets WIDER (30–40 arcmin) with increasing eccentricity. Objects beyond the fixation point cause crossed diplopia BEYOND fixation = nasal retina stimulated = UNCROSSED. NEARER than fixation = temporal retina = CROSSED.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-the-plain-version-first\",\"heading\":\"The Plain Version First\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Anisometropia just means the two eyes need different corrections. Aniseikonia means the two eyes see images of different size. They travel together: unequal corrections (especially in spectacles) tend to produce unequal image sizes, and once the images differ enough, fusion gets uncomfortable. This is the same fusion story as the rest of B5, viewed from the refractive side. Word roots: aniso = unequal, metr = measure, opia = of the eye (refraction), eikon = image, oxyopia = acuity.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-terminology-and-thresholds\",\"heading\":\"Terminology and Thresholds\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Isometropia Both eyes have equal refractive error Isoanisometropia (simple) Same TYPE of error both eyes (both myopic or both hyperopic), different magnitude Antimetropia (mixed) One eye myopic, the other hyperopic. Least common form Iso-oxyopia Equal best-corrected acuity between the eyes Aniso-oxyopia Unequal best-corrected acuity despite full correction Diopter threshold varies by author (mnemonic HGB = 0.25, 1.00, 2.00): Hartstein Any difference, from 0.25 D Grosvenor 1.00 D or more Borish 2.00 D or more is clinically significant Prevalence at the 1.00 D threshold is roughly 1 to 10 percent; it rises with age and is strongest in high myopia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-the-five-classes\",\"heading\":\"The Five Classes\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Class Difference Key feature I < 1.50 D Good fusion and stereopsis; both eyes used well together II 1.50 to 3.00 D Fusion holds most of the time; suppression (if any) is central; mild amblyopia may persist III > 3.00 D Refractive (anisometropic) amblyopia; poorer eye may reach only about 20/100; peripheral fusion keeps eyes aligned IV Varies Good acuity each eye but one used at a time (natural monovision, e.g. emmetropia + moderate myopia) V Varies Equal acuity but with a muscle imbalance or strabismus present Mnemonic: \\\"Fine, Fusion, Fails, Flip, Fights.\\\" I = Fine, II = Fusion (mild amblyopia), III = Fails (refractive amblyopia), IV = Flip (monovision), V = Fights (strabismus).\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-effects-and-management\",\"heading\":\"Effects and Management\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Effects worth naming: aniseikonia (unequal image size, lowers stereopsis), anisophoria (phoria changes across gaze from the Prentice prism effect of a strong lens off its optical center), amblyopia in the more ametropic eye, suppression, secondary strabismus, reduced stereopsis, and asthenopia. Hyperopic anisometropia with esotropia: full hyperopic Rx each eye, occlude the better eye, visuscope for central vs eccentric fixation, pleoptics if fixation is eccentric. Without strabismus: give the correction; atropine penalization of the sound eye blurs it and pushes the amblyopic eye into use; monitor acuity, BV, stereopsis. Treatment limit: a difference above about 6.00 D is usually left alone. The aniseikonia and prism become too large for comfortable fusion, so it is managed with contact lenses rather than pushed in spectacles. Pleoptics = intensive stimulation of the amblyopic fovea, mainly for eccentric fixation. Largely historical (occlusion and penalization replaced it) but still tested.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-aniseikonia-types-and-correction\",\"heading\":\"Aniseikonia — Types and Correction\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Type What differs Overall (global) symmetrical Whole image larger or smaller, equal in all meridians Meridional symmetrical Size differs in one meridian only; tied to astigmatic correction Compound symmetrical Overall plus an added meridional difference Two causes by mechanism: optical aniseikonia (unequal lens magnification, as in unequal spectacle correction or aphakia) and retinal aniseikonia (receptors stretched or crowded, as after retinal detachment repair or in macular edema). Symptoms usually begin once the size difference passes about 0.75 to 1.00 percent and become clearly troublesome past roughly 3 percent: headache, asthenopia, reading trouble, photophobia, nausea, dizziness. Correction order (mnemonic \\\"Glasses, Contacts, Surgery, Cause\\\"): iseikonic (size) lenses first for mild to moderate cases, then contact lenses, then refractive surgery, and always treat the underlying cause. How iseikonic lenses work: spectacle magnification has a shape factor (front base curve and thickness) and a power factor (power and vertex distance). Iseikonic lenses adjust the shape factor to change image size while holding the corrective power the same. They change size, not power.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-numbers-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers to Know\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Item Value Hartstein / Grosvenor / Borish thresholds 0.25 / 1.00 / 2.00 D Anisometropia prevalence (at 1.00 D) ~1 to 10 percent Treatment-limit difference > 6.00 D usually left alone Aniseikonia symptom onset ~0.75 to 1.00 percent size difference Aniseikonia clearly troublesome > ~3 percent Class III amblyopic ceiling ~20/100\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-board-traps-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps (Anisometropia and Aniseikonia)\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Anisometropia means unequal image size. That is aniseikonia. Anisometropia is unequal refractive ERROR. Antimetropia is just a large anisometropia. Antimetropia is specifically one eye myopic and one hyperopic (opposite signs), the least common form. opia and oxyopia mean the same thing. opia = refraction, oxyopia = acuity. Iso-oxyopia vs aniso-oxyopia is about acuity. Spectacles are best for anisometropic aniseikonia. Contact lenses are the treatment of choice; they minimize the spectacle magnification difference. Iseikonic lenses change the lens power. They change image size via the shape factor while keeping power constant. Anisophoria comes from unequal magnification. It comes from the Prentice prism effect as the eyes move off the optical centers of strong lenses.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5-01-binocular-vision-and-fusion-extended-topics-anisometropia-and-aniseikonia-practice-question\",\"heading\":\"Practice Question\",\"topic\":\"B5-01 — Binocular Vision and Fusion\",\"text\":\"Q. A patient wears +1.00 D OD and +4.50 D OS. Acuity corrects to 20/20 OD and 20/80 OS, and stereopsis is reduced. Which class of anisometropia is this, and what is the single best optical management to reduce the resulting aniseikonia? A. Class II; high-index spectacles B. Class III; contact lenses C. Class IV; base-in prism D. Class V; occlusion therapy Answer B. Class III; contact lenses. The difference is 3.50 D (greater than 3.00 D) with amblyopia in the more hyperopic eye reaching only about 20/80 to 20/100, which is Class III (refractive/anisometropic amblyopia). Contact lenses are the best optical choice for the aniseikonia because they sit on the cornea and minimize the spectacle magnification difference, giving more equal retinal image sizes than glasses. High-index spectacles (A) would still leave a magnification difference. Base-in prism (C) addresses a phoria, not image size. Occlusion (D) treats amblyopia but does not fix the aniseikonia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Stereopsis is the brain's ability to extract depth from the slight difference between the two retinal images — because the eyes are ~62.5mm apart, each sees a scene from a slightly different angle. That difference (retinal disparity) encodes depth information that the visual cortex converts into the perception of 3D space. It is the highest grade of binocular vision (Worth Grade 3) and requires functioning binocular vision. Normal stereoacuity is 20–40 seconds of arc — the minimum retinal disparity detectable. Monocular cues (perspective, shadow, overlap) provide depth information for patients with only one eye; they just cannot achieve the fine stereoacuity of binocular disparity. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Can a monocular patient judge depth?\\\" Yes — through monocular cues. Then ask what they cannot do — measure stereoacuity. That distinction separates depth perception from stereopsis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Why does having two eyes (separated by ~62.5mm) give us depth perception that one eye cannot achieve? Because each eye sees the world from a slightly different angle. An object that is close to you shifts position more between your two eyes' views than an object far away. The brain measures this shift — called retinal disparity — and converts it into a depth signal. One eye has no shift to compare, so it cannot do this calculation. This is the specific mechanism called stereopsis , and it is the most precise depth cue available. Why does stereoacuity have a threshold measured in arc seconds rather than millimeters? Because the brain is measuring a difference between two retinal positions — and retinal resolution is angular, not linear. The smallest detectable retinal disparity is about 20 seconds of arc (~0.006°). This corresponds to physically detecting a depth difference of a few centimeters at arm's length. The clinical term for this threshold is stereoacuity . Why does strabismus or amblyopia abolish stereopsis even if both eyes have good acuity individually? Because stereopsis requires both eyes to send simultaneous matching signals to binocular cortical neurons in V1. In strabismus, the images from the two eyes are misaligned — they stimulate non-corresponding retinal points. In amblyopia, the suppressed eye's signal is actively inhibited. Either way, the binocular neurons that detect disparity never receive proper input, and the depth calculation cannot run. The individual monocular pathways may be intact, but the binocular computation is missing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Stereopsis mechanism: Left eye view + Right eye view = SLIGHTLY DIFFERENT (due to ~62.5mm interpupillary separation) ↓ Corresponding retinal elements stimulated with disparity ↓ Visual cortex (binocular neurons in V1/V2/V5) detect disparity ↓ Panum's area: disparate images within ~6–10 arc min at fovea → FUSED + perceived as depth Beyond Panum's area → diplopia instead of depth ↓ STEREOPSIS : perception of depth and 3D structure Normal stereoacuity: 20–40 seconds of arc This is the minimum threshold — the smallest detectable retinal disparity that produces a depth percept. Normal binocular vision achieves this; amblyopia, strabismus, and monocularity do not. Depth cues — monocular vs binocular: BINOCULAR DEPTH CUES (require two eyes): 1. Stereopsis — retinal disparity (finest depth cue) 2. Convergence — proprioception from EOM contraction for near targets MONOCULAR DEPTH CUES (one eye sufficient): 1. Linear perspective — parallel lines converge in distance 2. Interposition — nearer objects overlap farther ones 3. Relative size — same object appears smaller when farther 4. Aerial perspective — distant objects appear hazy/blue-shifted 5. Motion parallax — near objects move faster across visual field during head movement 6. Light and shadow — shadow placement implies depth 7. Texture gradient — surface texture appears finer/denser at greater distance Stereopsis tests: Test Format Disparity range Notes Randot Stereotest Polarized random-dot patterns 20–400 sec arc Most commonly used clinically TNO Test Red-green anaglyphic plates 15–480 sec arc Requires anaglyph glasses Frisby Test Real depth acrylic plates 15–600 sec arc No glasses needed; true real-depth Lang Stereotest Autostereoscopic 550–1200 sec arc No glasses; quick screening Titmus Fly Polarized; fly + circles + animals 40–3000 sec arc Fly = 3000 sec arc (coarsest) Finest (best) stereoacuity = smallest seconds of arc. 20 sec arc > 400 sec arc (numerically larger value = coarser stereoacuity). Relationship to fusion and BV: Grade 1: Simultaneous Macular Perception Grade 2: Flat Fusion (+ amplitude) Grade 3: STEREOPSIS (requires Grade 1 + 2 as prerequisites) If Grade 2 fails → Grade 3 is impossible Stereopsis requires: — Functioning binocular vision — Alignment within Panum's area — Intact binocular neurons (amblyopia disrupts these)\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Normal stereoacuity 20–40 seconds of arc Threshold for fine binocular depth Panum's area at fovea 6–10 arc minutes Fusion zone at center; broader peripherally Panum's area at 12° 30–40 arc minutes Peripheral fusion broader Randot disparity range 20–400 sec arc Clinical stereopsis test range Titmus fly 3000 sec arc Coarsest stereopsis test stimulus\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Stereopsis vs other depth cues: Depth Cue Eyes needed Precision Can measure absolute distance? Stereopsis (retinal disparity) TWO Finest (20–40 sec arc) Yes (relative depth) Convergence TWO Moderate Only within ~2m Motion parallax ONE Moderate Only with head movement Linear perspective ONE Coarse No Relative size ONE Coarse No Interposition ONE Coarse (binary) No Monocular vs binocular — board distinction: Feature Binocular (stereopsis) Monocular cues Eyes required Two One sufficient Mechanism Retinal disparity calculation Cognitive/experiential Precision 20–40 sec arc Much coarser Present from birth? Develops at ~3–6 months Present at birth Lost in strabismus? Yes (suppression/amblyopia) No Stereopsis test comparison — finest to coarsest: Test Format Range Unique feature Randot Polarized random dot 20–400 sec arc Most common clinical use TNO Red-green anaglyph 15–480 sec arc Requires R/G glasses Frisby Real-depth acrylic plates 15–600 sec arc No glasses needed; true real depth Lang Autostereoscopic 550–1200 sec arc No glasses; screening only Titmus Fly Polarized; fly target 3000 sec arc (fly) Coarsest; best for children Rule: smaller arc seconds = finer stereoacuity = better binocular vision.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Monocular depth cues — \\\"LIMATS\\\" + shadow Linear perspective, Interposition, Motion parallax, Aerial perspective, Texture, Size (relative) \\\"Finest stereoacuity = lowest number of arc seconds\\\" 20 sec arc is finer than 400 sec arc — lower number = better stereo. Stereopsis requires BV — \\\"No stereo without BV; no BV without alignment\\\" Strabismic amblyopia suppresses → no binocular neurons → no stereopsis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Normal stereoacuity 20–40 seconds of arc Worth Grade 3 Stereopsis Binocular depth cue Stereopsis (retinal disparity) Most common clinical stereo test Randot stereotest Finest disparity detectable (Randot) 20 sec arc Coarsest Titmus stimulus Fly (3000 sec arc) Panum's fusional area at fovea 6–10 arc minutes Prerequisite for stereopsis Grades 1 + 2 of binocular vision\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"A patient with monocularity has no depth perception A monocular patient loses stereopsis but retains all monocular depth cues (perspective, interposition, motion parallax, size, shadow). They adapt well for daily function. A larger arc second value means finer stereoacuity Smaller arc seconds = finer (better) stereoacuity. 20 sec arc is far superior to 400 sec arc. The Frisby test requires glasses The Frisby is the only major stereopsis test that uses REAL depth (physical plates at different distances) and requires no glasses. Stereopsis is present at birth Stereopsis develops at approximately 3–6 months of age as binocular cortical neurons mature. It is not present at birth. Stereopsis is Grade 2 of Worth's classification Stereopsis is Grade 3 (the highest). Grade 2 is flat fusion. Grade 1 is simultaneous macular perception. Convergence is the most precise binocular depth cue Stereopsis (retinal disparity) is far more precise than convergence. Convergence only provides useful depth information within ~2 meters.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-practice-question\",\"heading\":\"Practice Question\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"1. A patient with right amblyopia (VA 20/200, strabismic) undergoes stereopsis testing. The expected finding on Randot stereotest is: A. Normal stereo (40 sec arc) B. Reduced stereo (~200 sec arc) C. No measurable stereopsis D. Stereo unaffected because the left eye is normal Answer C. No measurable stereopsis. Strabismic amblyopia involves suppression of the amblyopic eye and disruption of binocular cortical neurons. Stereopsis requires both eyes to contribute corresponding images within Panum's fusional area simultaneously. In strabismus with deep suppression, the amblyopic eye's image is actively inhibited — binocular neurons are not stimulated normally. Without binocular cortical input, stereopsis cannot be generated regardless of monocular acuity in the dominant eye. Residual coarse stereopsis might persist with very mild or intermittent strabismus, but with deep constant amblyopia (20/200), stereopsis is essentially absent.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6-01-stereopsis-and-depth-perception-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B6-01 — Stereopsis and Depth Perception\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"STEREOPSIS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: definition, normal value (seconds of arc), 5 monocular depth cues, 4 stereopsis tests, relationship to Worth's grades. Drill 2 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Normal stereoacuity? 20–40 seconds of arc Frisby test unique feature? No glasses needed; real depth Titmus fly disparity? 3000 sec arc (coarsest) Better stereo = higher or lower arc sec? Lower (fewer seconds = finer) Monocular depth cues (3)? Linear perspective, interposition, motion parallax\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"Visual Information Processing (VIP) is what happens after the image reaches the brain — how the brain interprets, organizes, stores, and acts on visual information. A person can have 20/20 acuity and still fail at VIP tasks. Visual Perceptual Skills (VPS) is the non-motor subset of VIP — the seven cognitive visual skills that let a person recognize shapes, recall sequences, and locate targets in busy backgrounds, without needing to use their hands or body to respond. These are assessed with three main tools: TVPS-3 (pure non-motor VPS), DTVP-2 (separates motor vs non-motor), and Beery VMI (visual-motor integration). Boards test the definitions, which tool measures what, and the seven VPS subtopics. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Can a child fail to read not because of poor eyesight but because of poor visual processing?\\\" Yes — and that distinction drives the referral decision between optometry and occupational therapy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"VIP Visual Information Processing Broad term; includes all stages of how the brain processes visual input VPS Visual Perceptual Skills Non-motor subset of VIP; 7 specific cognitive visual skills VMI Visual-Motor Integration Coordination of visual perception with fine motor response TVPS-3 Test of Visual Perceptual Skills, 3rd Ed. Non-motor VPS; patient points only; ages 4–18 DTVP-2 Developmental Test of Visual Perception, 2nd Ed. Separates motor-free vs motor-enhanced scores; ages 4–10 Beery VMI Beery-Buktenica Dev. Test of VMI Copy geometric shapes; tests visual-motor integration; ages 2–100\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"VIP vs VPS distinction: VIP (Visual Information Processing) — BROAD umbrella ├── VPS (Visual Perceptual Skills) — NON-MOTOR subset │ Assessment: TVPS-3 (points only; no drawing) │ └── Visual-Motor Integration ( VMI ) — requires motor output Assessment: Beery VMI (copies shapes) The 7 VPS subtopics (assessed by TVPS-3): VPS Skill Definition Example failure Visual Discrimination Detect differences between similar forms/shapes Cannot identify which letter differs among similar letters Visual Memory Recall visual characteristics of a stimulus after removal Cannot recognize a shape seen 5 seconds ago Visual Spatial Relationships Determine position of objects relative to self/others Left-right confusion; cannot judge orientation Visual Form Constancy Recognize a form despite changes in size/rotation/context Cannot recognize a triangle rotated 90° Visual Sequential Memory Recall a series of visual stimuli in correct order Cannot reproduce a sequence of shapes Visual Figure-Ground Locate a target within a complex background Cannot find a word on a busy page Visual Closure Recognize an incomplete figure as whole Cannot read a word with missing letter parts Assessment tools comparison: Tool What it measures Motor required? Ages Key feature TVPS-3 7 non-motor VPS subtopics NO (patient only points) 4–18 yrs Gold standard for non-motor VPS DTVP-2 Motor-free + motor-enhanced VPS Partially 4–10 yrs Separates perception from motor output Beery VMI Visual-motor integration YES (copies shapes) 2–100 yrs Broadest age range; copying task Clinical relevance: VIP deficits seen in: ├── Amblyopia / strabismus (suppression disrupts higher visual processing) ├── Learning difficulties (reading, spelling, spatial math) ├── Traumatic brain injury (acquired VIP deficits) └── Cerebral visual impairment (global VIP disruption) Management: ├── Vision therapy targeting specific VPS subtopics ├── Referral to OT for VMI- specific intervention └── Educational psychologist for school accommodations\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"7 VPS subtopics — \\\"D-MEM-SF-C\\\" Discrimination, Memory, (spatial) rElations, (form) cOnstancy, Sequential memory, Figure-ground, Closure VIP > VPS > VMI — largest to smallest VIP is the umbrella; VPS is non-motor subset; VMI adds motor output. TVPS = No motor; Beery = Motor TVPS-3: patient points only — pure perception. Beery VMI: patient copies shapes — perception + motor together.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer VIP vs VPS VIP = broad (processing + motor); VPS = non-motor subset VPS subtopics (7) Discrimination, Memory, Spatial relations, Form constancy, Sequential memory, Figure-ground, Closure TVPS-3 Non-motor VPS; points only; ages 4–18 DTVP-2 Separates motor-free from motor-enhanced scores; ages 4–10 Beery VMI Copies geometric shapes; visual-motor integration; ages 2–100 VIP ≠ acuity 20/20 acuity does NOT rule out VIP deficit\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-practice-question\",\"heading\":\"Practice Question\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"1. A 7-year-old has 20/20 acuity OU, no strabismus, and normal binocular vision. The teacher reports he cannot find objects on a busy worksheet and frequently loses his place while reading. Which assessment would best evaluate the most likely deficit? A. Humphrey visual field testing B. Ishihara color vision testing C. TVPS-3 D. Beery VMI Answer C. TVPS-3. The described difficulties — finding objects on a busy page (figure-ground), losing place while reading (visual sequential memory and figure-ground) — point to visual perceptual skills deficits. With normal acuity and binocular vision ruling out optical and alignment problems, the deficit is at the VPS level. TVPS-3 is the gold standard for assessing all 7 non-motor VPS subtopics in children ages 4–18. It requires only pointing, so motor output doesn't confound the results. Beery VMI would test visual-motor integration (copying shapes) — appropriate if handwriting or drawing difficulties were the chief complaint. VF testing and color testing are not relevant here. 2. A 6-year-old scores poorly on the Beery VMI. Before concluding she has a visual perceptual deficit, which assessment should be done first to separate perception from motor output? A. Humphrey visual field test B. TVPS-3 C. DTVP-2 motor-enhanced subtest D. Snellen acuity testing Answer B. TVPS-3. Beery VMI requires copying geometric shapes — a visual-motor task. A low score could reflect poor visual perception OR poor fine motor skills (shaky hands, poor pencil grip). TVPS-3 is the appropriate next step because it tests all 7 VPS subtopics with pointing responses only — no motor output is required. If TVPS-3 is normal, the Beery VMI deficit is motor (refer to OT for motor base work). If TVPS-3 is also poor, the deficit is perceptual (vision therapy targeting VPS). DTVP-2 (option C) also separates motor from non-motor but tests ages 4–10 and is less specific than TVPS-3 for identifying the perceptual subtype. Visual fields and acuity testing (A, D) do not assess VPS.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"VIP, VPS, VMI.\\\" 3 minutes. Write: VIP vs VPS definition, 7 VPS subtopics, 3 assessment tools with what each measures and age range. Drill 2 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back VPS = non-motor subset of? VIP TVPS-3 measures? 7 non-motor VPS; points only; ages 4–18 Beery VMI measures? Visual-motor integration; copies shapes; ages 2–100 DTVP-2 key feature? Separates motor-free from motor-enhanced scores; ages 4–10 Figure-ground failure example? Cannot find word on busy page Form constancy failure example? Cannot recognize rotated shape Visual analysis vs visual discrimination? Analysis = breaks one object into parts; Discrimination = compares two objects Mental rotation failure example? Confuses b/d/p/q — cannot match rotated letters Spatial visualization: what can you do? Mentally rotate/flip/manipulate an object in your mind Visual base (prerequisite for VPS)? Convergence, tracking, saccades, accommodation Motor base (prerequisite for VMI)? Shoulder stability, fine/gross motor, eye-hand coordination Low Beery VMI — means VPS deficit? Not necessarily — may be motor deficit; compare with TVPS-3 Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Write all 7 VPS subtopics with one example each Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-extended-topics-expanded-vps-subtypes-from-review-visual-spatial-skills-three-subtypes\",\"heading\":\"Visual Spatial Skills — Three Subtypes\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"The review breaks \\\"Visual Spatial Relationships\\\" (one of the original 7 VPS subtopics) into three distinct cognitive skills. The board may test these as separate concepts. SPATIAL VISUALIZATION Plain version: You can mentally pick up an object and rotate or flip it in your mind. Definition: The ability to mentally manipulate, rotate, twist, or invert a visual image without physically touching it. Example failure: Cannot figure out how a folded piece of paper will look unfolded. Clinical significance: Needed for spatial math, reading maps, understanding 3D diagrams. MENTAL ROTATION Plain version: You see a shape at one angle and can figure out what it looks like if it were rotated 90° or upside down. Definition: The ability to mentally rotate a 2D or 3D object around any axis and compare it to another orientation. Example failure: Cannot match a rotated letter to its upright version (e.g., confuses \\\"b\\\", \\\"d\\\", \\\"p\\\", \\\"q\\\"). Clinical significance: Strongly related to reading reversals and letter confusion in children. SPATIAL REASONING Plain version: You use position information to solve problems — like following a map or understanding where you are relative to other objects. Definition: The ability to understand, reason about, and mentally manipulate spatial relationships between objects in an environment. Example failure: Gets lost in familiar environments; cannot read a blueprint or map. Clinical significance: Needed for navigation, understanding spatial layouts, sports and physical coordination.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-extended-topics-expanded-vps-subtypes-from-review-visual-analysis\",\"heading\":\"Visual Analysis\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"This is listed as a separate VPS skill in the review. It is related to figure-ground but focuses on breaking down complex visual information. VISUAL ANALYSIS Plain version: You can look at something complex and identify its individual parts, then understand how those parts relate to each other. Definition: The ability to examine visual information closely, identify its components, recognize patterns, and understand how those parts relate to one another. Example failure: Cannot break a word into letter components; cannot identify which part of a diagram belongs to which section. Clinical significance: Reading comprehension, diagram interpretation, visual reasoning tasks. Distinguish from Visual Discrimination: Visual Discrimination = detect differences BETWEEN objects (this vs that) Visual Analysis = break apart one complex visual INTO its components\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-extended-topics-expanded-vps-subtypes-from-review-the-visual-base-and-motor-base-foundation-skills\",\"heading\":\"The Visual Base and Motor Base — Foundation Skills\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"The review explicitly states VPS is built on two foundational bases: VISUAL BASE (prerequisite for VPS development) Established through FUNCTIONAL VISUAL SKILLS : - Convergence (sustained near binocular alignment) - Eye tracking (smooth pursuit for reading) - Saccades (accurate jumps between words/targets) - Accommodation (clear focus at near) Clinical implication: A child with convergence insufficiency will struggle with VPS tasks NOT because their brain can't process — but because the visual input is unstable. Fix the functional visual skills FIRST before attributing failure to VPS deficit. MOTOR BASE (prerequisite for VMI development) Established through: - Shoulder girdle stability - Fine motor skills (pencil grip, hand control) - Gross motor skills (bilateral coordination) - Eye-hand coordination Clinical implication: Poor Beery VMI score may reflect motor deficit (shaky hands) rather than visual processing deficit. Use TVPS-3 (non-motor) to separate the two.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-extended-topics-expanded-vps-subtypes-from-review-updated-vps-map\",\"heading\":\"Updated VPS Map\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"VPS SUBTOPICS ├── Visual Discrimination — detect differences between objects ├── Visual Memory — recall visual information ├── Visual Form Constancy — recognize despite size/rotation/position change ├── Visual Closure — complete an incomplete figure ├── Visual Figure Ground — locate target in busy background ├── Visual Analysis — break complex image into parts └── Visual Spatial Skills ├── Spatial Visualization — mentally manipulate/rotate objects ├── Mental Rotation — rotate 2D/3D object in mind └── Spatial Reasoning — understand spatial relationships for problem-solving VMI (separate from VPS ): └── Visual Motor Integration — coordinate vision with hand movement (Beery VMI )\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-extended-topics-expanded-vps-subtypes-from-review-board-trap-extended\",\"heading\":\"Board Trap — Extended\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"Trap: \\\"Poor Beery VMI score always means a VPS deficit\\\" — Wrong. Beery VMI requires motor output (copying shapes). A low score could be due to fine motor difficulty, not visual perception. Always compare with TVPS-3 (non-motor) to determine if the deficit is perceptual or motor. Trap: \\\"Visual analysis and visual discrimination are the same skill\\\" — Wrong. Visual discrimination compares two objects for differences. Visual analysis breaks one complex object into its component parts.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7-01-vip-vps-cognitive-processing-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"B7-01 — VIP, VPS, and Cognitive Visual Processing\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. Color theory by level — cue: \\\"receptor\\\" vs \\\"post-receptor\\\" vs \\\"combined\\\". Receptor = trichromatic (Young-Helmholtz). Post-receptor = opponent (Hering). Combined = stage (Ladd-Franklin). Trap: assigning opponent-process to the receptor level. Sheard vs Percival — cue: criterion name. Sheard = fusional reserve ≥ 2× the phoria (for symptomatic). Percival = phoria in the middle third of the vergence range (independent of phoria). Trap: swapping the two definitions. Worth-4-dot fusion grade — cue: simultaneous / fusion / stereo. Grade 1 = simultaneous macular perception, Grade 2 = flat fusion, Grade 3 = stereopsis. Trap: calling stereopsis \\\"Grade 2.\\\" Physiologic diplopia — cue: near vs far target. Far object behind fixation = uncrossed (homonymous) ; near object = crossed . Trap: reversing crossed/uncrossed. AC/A — cue: deviation worse at near vs distance. Worse at near = high AC/A (convergence excess); worse at distance = divergence excess. Trap: matching \\\"convergence insufficiency\\\" to a high AC/A — CI is low AC/A.\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"B.strategy\",\"subject\":\"B\",\"label\":\"Physiological Optics & BV — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/B-Physiological-Optics-and-BV/B-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Physiological Optics and Binocular Vision · the read-before-you-test reference for all 7 topics B1 Visual System B2 Perception B3 Field B4 Color B5 BV B6 Stereo B7 VIP/VPS\"},{\"anchor\":\"b1\",\"heading\":\"B1Visual System & Ocular Optics\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Axes \\\"ATV 24-22-22\\\": Anteroposterior = Torsion (24 mm, longest); Transverse = Vertical movement (22); Vertical = Horizontal movement (22). All pass through the center of rotation, 13.5 mm behind the cornea. Cone pigments \\\"ECG\\\": Erythrolabe (red, ~750 nm), Chlorolabe (green, 535 nm), Cyanolabe (blue, 440 nm). 507 vs 555: rods peak 507 nm (scotopic, blue-green); cones peak 555 nm (photopic, yellow-green). The Purkinje shift moves the peak 555 → 507 as light fades. Dark adaptation: cones plateau at ~7 min (Kohlrausch kink); rods finish at 30–40 min, ending ~1000× (3 log units) more sensitive. Angle kappa clue: positive kappa → pupil nasal → reflex temporal → pseudo- exo . Negative kappa → reflex nasal → pseudo- eso . Alpha is measured at the nodal point, kappa at the pupil. Trap: the fovea has the most rods. No — rods are absent at the fovea (highest cone density). Rods peak ~20° out (averted vision). Trap: full dark adaptation takes 7 min. No — that is cones; full rod adaptation is 30–40 min.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b2\",\"heading\":\"B2Visual Perception\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"LGB layers \\\"1-4-6 cross, 2-3-5 stay\\\": layers 1, 4, 6 = contralateral (crossed/nasal); layers 2, 3, 5 = ipsilateral (uncrossed/temporal). Streams: Ventral = \\\" What \\\" (temporal lobe, object ID). Dorsal = \\\" Where/How \\\" (parietal lobe, space/motion). Color is most vulnerable, motion most resilient. Color fails first in optic nerve disease (basis of red-desaturation test). Cortex 17-18-19: 17 = primary striate (basic features), 18 = parastriate, 19 = peristriate. Recognition needs ventral stream beyond 17. Weber's law: ΔI/I = k . The JND is a constant fraction of background, so it doubles when the background doubles. Basis of contrast sensitivity. Trap: area 17 recognizes objects. No — it detects basic features; recognition is a ventral-stream (18/19/IT) function.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b3\",\"heading\":\"B3Visual Field\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Extents \\\"Temporal is widest\\\": Temporal 100°, Inferior 75°, Superior 60°, Nasal 60°. 120 + 30: central 120° is binocular; each side has a 30° monocular temporal crescent. Goldmann: V = largest (64 mm²), I = smallest (0.25 mm²); bowl 300 mm radius, background 31.5 apostilbs. Amsler = central 10° (1 square = 1°); a macular test. Field defect Lesion Bitemporal hemianopia Optic chiasm (pituitary adenoma) \\\"Pie in the sky\\\" (sup. quadrant) Meyer's loop (temporal lobe) Constricted fields + nyctalopia Retinitis pigmentosa Arcuate scotoma / nasal step Glaucoma Trap: Goldmann V is the smallest stimulus. No — V is the largest; I is the smallest.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b4\",\"heading\":\"B4Color Perception\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Theory Author Level Trichromatic Young-Helmholtz Receptor Opponent process Hering Post-receptor Stage theory Ladd-Franklin Evolutionary Mixing: Additive light R+G+B = White ; Subtractive pigment C+M+Y = Black . Most common defect = deuteranomaly (weak green). Red-green deficiency ~8% of males. Tritan defects are rare and autosomal. Tests: Ishihara screens red-green (plate 1 = control everyone sees); HRR tests red-green AND blue-yellow; FM-100 Hue = most comprehensive (axis + severity); FALANT = occupational lantern (8 ft). Trap: additive mixing gives black. No — additive (light) = white; subtractive (pigment) = black.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b5\",\"heading\":\"B5Binocular Vision & Fusion (highest yield)\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Normal AC/A = 4:1 to 6:1. High AC/A = Excess (Convergence Excess, Divergence Excess). Low AC/A = Insufficiency (Convergence Insufficiency, Divergence Insufficiency). Sheard's 2:1: fusional reserve ≥ 2× the phoria. Percival's: phoria in the middle third of the range. Worth \\\"Super-Flat-Stereo\\\": Grade 1 simultaneous perception, Grade 2 flat fusion, Grade 3 stereopsis. Laws: Hering = binocular yoke muscles (equal innervation); Sherrington = monocular agonist/antagonist (reciprocal). Physiologic diplopia \\\"Far Uncrossed, Near Crossed.\\\" Eye-movement speed: vergence slowest (20°/s); VOR fastest reflex (15 ms); saccade fastest voluntary (500–1000°/s). NPC normal ≤8 cm (>10 = CI). Amblyopia \\\"SAD-Am\\\": Strabismic (most common), Anisometropic, Deprivation (worst prognosis), Ametropic, Meridional. Trap: high AC/A causes convergence insufficiency. No — CI has a low AC/A. High AC/A drives the excess conditions. Trap: Hering's law is monocular. No — Hering = binocular yoke; Sherrington = monocular.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b6\",\"heading\":\"B6Stereopsis & Depth\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Normal stereoacuity = 20–40 sec arc. Smaller arc-seconds = finer. Stereopsis = Worth Grade 3 (needs Grades 1 + 2 first). Stereopsis = binocular retinal disparity. It develops ~3–6 months (not at birth) and is absent in deep constant strabismic amblyopia. Tests: Frisby = real depth, no glasses; Titmus fly = coarsest (3000 sec arc); Randot = common clinical (down to ~20 sec arc). Trap: larger arc-seconds = better stereo. No — smaller is finer (20 beats 400). Trap: losing one eye removes all depth perception. No — monocular cues (perspective, interposition, motion parallax) remain.\"},{\"anchor\":\"b7\",\"heading\":\"B7VIP / VPS & Cognitive Processing\",\"topic\":\"Subject B — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"VIP is broad (processing + motor); VPS is the non-motor subset. 20/20 acuity does NOT rule out a VIP deficit. Tool Measures Ages TVPS-3 Non-motor VPS (pointing only) 4–18 DTVP-2 Separates motor-free vs motor-enhanced 4–10 Beery VMI Visual-motor integration (copying) 2–100 Decision rule: poor Beery VMI → run TVPS-3. If TVPS-3 normal, the deficit is motor; if poor, it is perceptual. Subtopics: figure-ground (find object in clutter), form constancy (same shape, changed size/orientation), visual closure (whole from partial), plus discrimination, spatial relations, visual memory, sequential memory. Trap: 20/20 acuity means no perceptual problem. No — perception is separate from acuity. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject B strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"C.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"C\",\"label\":\"Primary Care & Refraction — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/C-Primary-Care-and-Refraction/C-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Public health is care aimed at populations , not single patients. Where the rest of your training treats the person in the chair, this note zooms out to the whole community: who goes blind, why, how common it is, and how we prevent it. Three ideas carry most of the marks: The vocabulary of epidemiology (epidemic vs pandemic vs endemic; incidence vs prevalence; morbidity vs mortality). The three levels of prevention (primary, secondary, tertiary), which map onto three levels of eye care. The numbers (global and Philippine blindness statistics and their leading causes). Teaching angle: the single most repeated fact in this topic is that the two leading causes of vision impairment worldwide are uncorrected refractive error and cataract , and that over 80% of vision impairment is avoidable (preventable or curable). If you remember nothing else, remember that.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Why does optometry belong in public health at all? Because the biggest cause of avoidable blindness is uncorrected refractive error , and correcting refractive error is exactly what optometrists do. A pair of glasses is a public-health intervention. That is why the State (RA 8050) calls optometry part of primary health care. Why is \\\"avoidable\\\" the key word, not \\\"blind\\\"? Because over 80% of vision impairment can be prevented or cured. The tragedy is not that these conditions exist but that they go untreated: only about a third of refractive-error patients and a sixth of cataract patients get the care they need. The public-health job is closing that gap. Why distinguish incidence from prevalence? Incidence counts new cases over a period (the flow); prevalence counts all existing cases at a point (the pool). A chronic disease like glaucoma has low incidence but high prevalence because cases accumulate. Mixing them up changes the meaning of any statistic. Why three levels of prevention? Because you can intervene before, during, or after a disease starts. Primary stops it beginning, secondary catches it early and reverses it, tertiary limits the damage once it is established. Naming the level tells you what action is appropriate.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-core-definitions\",\"heading\":\"Core Definitions\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Public health (Winslow): the science and art of preventing disease, prolonging life, and promoting health through organized community effort. Public health optometry: using the full scope of optometry to prevent disease, prolong life, and promote health for groups of people at the community level . Health (WHO): a state of complete physical, mental, and social well-being, not merely the absence of disease. Visual hygiene: the science and art of conserving and promoting healthful, comfortable vision. Hygiene: the science of preserving health; the rules designed to promote it. Visual sanitation: the principles for understanding the causes and sources of ocular infection and disease. Sanitation: sanitary measures; cleanliness, freedom from dirt and germs. Three goals of public health (Winslow follow-on): reduce discomfort, disability, and disease in society; promote quality of life; attain the highest level of physical, mental, and social well-being with available resources. Emphasis of public health: prevention of disease, the health of groups (not individuals), control of communicable infection, education in personal hygiene, and organizing services for early diagnosis and preventive treatment.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-epidemiology-vocabulary\",\"heading\":\"Epidemiology Vocabulary\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Term Meaning Epidemic More cases than expected in a region/group over a time period (sudden outbreak) Pandemic An epidemic gone very widespread, across regions/continents (e.g., COVID-19) Endemic Constantly present in a community at low frequency, peculiar to a locality Incidence Number of new cases over a period (the flow) Prevalence Number of all existing cases at a point (the pool) Morbidity State of being diseased; incidence/prevalence of disease in a population Mortality Number of deaths in a population\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-levels-of-prevention-and-matching-optometric-care\",\"heading\":\"Levels of Prevention (and matching optometric care)\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Level General meaning Optometric example Primary Prevent onset before disease begins Health education, visual hygiene, screening, accident/injury prevention Secondary Detect early and reverse ongoing deterioration Early detection and correction (glasses, treating amblyopia) to restore performance Tertiary Limit disability once disease is established Low-vision rehabilitation; maintain remaining function\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-three-levels-of-eye-care\",\"heading\":\"Three Levels of Eye Care\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Primary eye care: community level. Promote eye hygiene, measure and record VA, refer subnormal vision and blindness, detect disease early, give simple treatment, refer severe cases, join immunization and blindness-prevention drives. Secondary eye care: hospitals without large technical facilities; ophthalmologists; promote prevention and train primary-level personnel. Tertiary eye care: the full complex of medical and surgical care by ophthalmology specialists with advanced technology; institutes of ophthalmology; train personnel at other levels.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-organizations\",\"heading\":\"Organizations\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"WHO: UN specialized agency for health; established April 7, 1948 ; governed by 192 member states through the World Health Assembly (approves programme and the biennial budget). Goal: highest possible level of health for all. DOH: principal health agency of the Philippines; both stakeholder and regulator. Structure: ~17 central offices, 16 Centers for Health Development (regional), 70 hospitals, and 4 attached agencies : PhilHealth (national health insurance), Dangerous Drugs Board, Philippine Institute of Traditional and Alternative Health Care, and Philippine National AIDS Council. PhilHealth: adequate and affordable social health insurance for all Filipinos. SSS: protects members against socially recognized hazards.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-global-burden-who\",\"heading\":\"Global Burden (WHO)\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"2.2 billion people have a vision impairment; at least 1 billion of these was preventable or is still unaddressed. Leading causes worldwide: uncorrected refractive error and cataract. Over 80% of all vision impairment is avoidable (preventable or curable). Access gap: only ~ 36% of refractive-error and ~ 17% of cataract patients get appropriate care. Most affected are people over 50 ; at-risk groups are the over-50s and children under 15 . By 2050, blindness could reach ~115 million (from 38.5 million in 2020) due to population growth and aging. Annual global cost of lost productivity: ~US$411 billion. Vision disorders are the second most prevalent chronic health problem in the population. Single largest unaddressed cause: presbyopia (826 million) , even though presbyopia is not what people first name. Of the ≥1 billion with moderate-to-severe impairment, the rank by count is: unaddressed presbyopia 826M → uncorrected refractive error 123.7M → un-operated cataract 65.2M → glaucoma 6.9M → corneal opacity 4.2M → diabetic retinopathy 3M → trachoma 2M. Other global counts (WHO 2019): myopia ~2.6 billion (2020); glaucoma 76 million (40–80 yrs); AMD 195.6 million; diabetic retinopathy 146 million.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-who-2019-which-conditions-cause-vision-impairment\",\"heading\":\"WHO 2019 — Which Conditions Cause Vision Impairment\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Do NOT typically cause VI CAN cause VI (including blindness) Blepharitis Age-related macular degeneration Chalazion / hordeolum (stye) Cataract Conjunctivitis Corneal opacity Dry eye Diabetic retinopathy Pterygium / pinguecula Glaucoma Subconjunctival hemorrhage Trachoma, Refractive error\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-the-details-philippine-burden-doh-2017-peri-doh\",\"heading\":\"Philippine Burden (DOH 2017 / PERI-DOH)\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Causes of bilateral BLINDNESS (332,150 persons): Cataract ~33% (109,609) — the leading cause Errors of refraction ~25% (83,037) Glaucoma ~14% (46,501) Causes of bilateral LOW VISION (2,179,733 persons) — order FLIPS: Errors of refraction ~43% (937,285) — now the leading cause Cataract ~34% (741,109) Rest: glaucoma and other eye diseases Key distinction: for blindness cataract leads; for low vision refractive error leads. Same country, opposite top cause. This swap is a favorite board item. Major causes of blindness (global ranking echoed locally): un-operated cataract ~35%, uncorrected refractive error ~21%, glaucoma ~8%. 2018 PERI-DOH Philippine Eye Disease Study: overall VI prevalence (presenting VA worse than 6/18 in the better eye) = 1.98% . Major causes: cataract 1.06% (cataract needing surgery, VA ≤6/60: ~333,639), uncorrected EOR 0.38%, glaucoma 0.27%, maculopathy 0.2%. Among those without VI: 3.26% still have EOR, 0.69% glaucoma, 0.59% diabetic retinopathy. Children: 1 in 10 school children have an eye problem; ~25% of those have amblyopia , the rest mostly refractive error. Amblyopia prevalence ~1 to 3%; EOR ~3 to 15%. Prevention program: the DOH Community Eye Health Program (CEHP) integrates eye care into local public health through a service delivery network (barangay health stations → rural health units → tertiary hospitals), focused on avoidable blindness (cataract, EOR, childhood blindness).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"WHO established April 7, 1948 Global vision impairment 2.2 billion Avoidable share over 80% Two leading global causes uncorrected refractive error, cataract PH leading cause of BLINDNESS cataract (~33–35%) PH leading cause of LOW VISION refractive error (~43%) PH blindness order cataract > EOR > glaucoma PH low-vision order EOR > cataract > glaucoma Largest single global cause unaddressed presbyopia (826M) Global productivity cost ~US$411 billion / yr WHO member states 192 School children with eye problems 1 in 10 Amblyopia among those ~25% PH prevention program Community Eye Health Program (CEHP)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"\\\"Prevent, prolong, promote\\\" the three verbs of public health (Winslow). EPIC sizes: Endemic < Epidemic < Pandemic (local always present → regional outbreak → global). Incidence = new (flow); Prevalence = all (pool). Prevention 1-2-3: prevent onset → catch early → limit damage. The headline number: 80%+ of vision impairment is avoidable; top causes = refractive error + cataract. Philippines blindness order: Cataract > Refractive error > Glaucoma. Philippines low vision order: Refractive error > Cataract (the flip). Think \\\"low vision = light correction problem, so EOR leads.\\\" WHO born 1948; World Health Day is April 7.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"prevalence and incidence are interchangeable. Incidence is new cases over time; prevalence is all existing cases at a point. the leading cause of global vision impairment is glaucoma. It is uncorrected refractive error and cataract . most vision impairment is untreatable. Over 80% is avoidable (preventable or curable). secondary prevention means surgery for advanced disease. Secondary = early detection and reversal ; managing established disability is tertiary. an endemic disease is a sudden outbreak. Endemic is constantly present at low frequency ; the sudden outbreak is an epidemic. the leading cause of blindness in the Philippines is refractive error. Close, but cataract is first; refractive error is second. refractive error is the top cause of both blindness and low vision in the Philippines. Blindness = cataract first; only low vision has refractive error first. dry eye, pterygium, or conjunctivitis are leading causes of vision impairment. WHO lists these as conditions that do not typically cause VI. the single biggest cause of global vision impairment by headcount is refractive error. By count it is actually unaddressed presbyopia (826M) ; refractive error and cataract are the leading named causes of impairment and blindness.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Public health verbs (Winslow) Prevent, prolong, promote New cases over time Incidence All existing cases at a point Prevalence Constantly present, low frequency Endemic Three prevention levels Primary, secondary, tertiary Two leading global causes of VI Refractive error, cataract Avoidable share of VI Over 80% PH leading cause of blindness Cataract WHO founded April 7, 1948 PH eye health program CEHP Most common amblyopia cause in kids screened (1 in 10 have problems; 25% amblyopia)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"1. A disease is constantly present in a community at a low, steady frequency. This pattern is: A. Epidemic B. Pandemic C. Endemic D. Sporadic Answer C. Endemic. Constant low-level presence in a locality. An epidemic is an outbreak above expected levels; a pandemic is an epidemic spread across regions. 2. The two leading causes of vision impairment worldwide are: A. Glaucoma and diabetic retinopathy B. Uncorrected refractive error and cataract C. Trachoma and corneal opacity D. AMD and glaucoma Answer B. Uncorrected refractive error and cataract. Both are largely avoidable, which is why over 80% of vision impairment is preventable or curable. 3. Conducting community vision screening and health education to stop disease before it starts is which level of prevention? A. Primary B. Secondary C. Tertiary D. Quaternary Answer A. Primary. Primary prevention acts before onset. Secondary is early detection and reversal; tertiary limits established disability (e.g., low-vision rehab). 4. In the Philippines, the leading cause of bilateral blindness is: A. Glaucoma B. Refractive error C. Cataract D. Diabetic retinopathy Answer C. Cataract (about a third of cases), followed by errors of refraction, then glaucoma. 5. A statistic counts only the new cases of glaucoma diagnosed in a region during one year. This measures: A. Prevalence B. Incidence C. Mortality D. Endemicity Answer B. Incidence. New cases over a defined period. Prevalence would count all existing cases at a point in time. 6. In the Philippines, the leading cause of bilateral low vision (as opposed to blindness) is: A. Cataract B. Errors of refraction C. Glaucoma D. Diabetic retinopathy Answer B. Errors of refraction (~43%), with cataract second (~34%). The order flips from blindness, where cataract leads. 7. Which of the following does WHO list as a condition that does not typically cause vision impairment? A. Trachoma B. Corneal opacity C. Pterygium D. Diabetic retinopathy Answer C. Pterygium. Along with blepharitis, chalazion/stye, conjunctivitis, dry eye, and subconjunctival hemorrhage. The other three are on the list of conditions that can cause VI.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1-01-epidemiology-and-prevention-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C1 — Epidemiology and Prevention (Public Health Optometry)\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the epidemiology vocabulary (epidemic, pandemic, endemic, incidence, prevalence, morbidity, mortality) with a one-line definition each. No looking. Drill 2 — Prevention Ladder Write the three levels of prevention and one optometric example of each, then the three levels of eye care. Drill 3 — Numbers Sprint From memory: global vision impairment count, avoidable percentage, two leading global causes, and both Philippine orders (blindness cause order AND low-vision cause order, noting the flip). Drill 4 — Incidence vs Prevalence Write two short scenarios, one measuring incidence and one measuring prevalence, and label each. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a pair of glasses counts as a public-health intervention. Use \\\"avoidable.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Prevention Ladder 3rd 3 days Numbers Sprint 4th 1 week Incidence vs Prevalence Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Ametropia means the eye does not focus parallel rays exactly on the retina with accommodation relaxed. That one-sentence definition covers every refractive error: myopia, hyperopia, and astigmatism all share this root. The cause is always one of four variables — axial length, corneal power, lens power, or anterior chamber depth — being wrong for each other. Presbyopia is different: it is not an error of focus but a loss of the focusing range itself, caused by progressive stiffening of the crystalline lens. Understanding each condition means knowing which variable is off, in which direction, and how much the correction has to shift the far point back to infinity. Teaching angle: Ask a class — \\\"If I surgically make the cornea flatter on a myope, will their prescription go up or down, and why?\\\" This question forces the student to connect corneal curvature to power to far point to correction — which is the entire logic chain of C2. Cross-reference: The optical physics behind ametropia (Gullstrand's schematic eye, axial length, n-to-power rule, far point concept) are fully built in D1-01, Gullstrand section . Read that note first if the physical optics feel unclear. C2 builds the clinical layer on top of that foundation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Why do hyperopes get headaches when reading but myopes rarely do? Because hyperopes must accommodate just to see distance clearly. Why must hyperopes accommodate at distance? Because their far point is virtual — located behind the eye — so even parallel rays from infinity require extra converging power to land on the retina. Why does that matter for headaches? Because the ciliary muscle is contracting continuously: at distance to see clearly, and then contracting further at near for the additional demand. The muscle never fully rests. Why does the ciliary muscle have to work continuously in hyperopia? Because uncorrected hyperopia means the eye's resting power is insufficient. The eye compensates by using accommodation as a permanent supplement instead of reserving it for near only. Why does myopia not do the same thing? Because a myope's far point is in front of the eye. At near, objects fall naturally closer to the far point. A low myope often needs less accommodation at near than an emmetrope does — the refractive error accidentally assists near vision.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Ametropia Greek: a (not) + metron (measure) + ops (eye) Any refractive condition where focus does not land on the retina with accommodation at rest Emmetropia Greek: emmetros (in proper measure) Parallel rays focus exactly on the retina at rest; no correction needed Myopia Greek: myein (to close/shut) + ops (eye) Eye \\\"squints to see\\\" — near-sightedness; image in front of retina Hyperopia Greek: hyper (over/beyond) + ops (eye) \\\"Over-seeing\\\" — far-sightedness; image behind retina Hypermetropia hyper + metron + ops Same condition as hyperopia; British/older preferred term; both valid Astigmatism Greek: a (not) + stigma (point) \\\"No point focus\\\" — different powers in different meridians; multiple foci Presbyopia Greek: presbys (old man) + ops (eye) Age-related loss of accommodative amplitude; lens stiffening Anisometropia Greek: aniso (unequal) + metron + ops Refractive error differs between the two eyes Aniseikonia Greek: aniso (unequal) + eikon (image) Unequal image size between the two eyes Aphakia Greek: a (without) + phakos (lens) Absence of crystalline lens; extreme hyperopia results Facultative hyperopia Latin: facultas (ability) Amount of hyperopia that can be overcome by accommodation Latent hyperopia Latin: latere (to hide) Amount masked by tonic ciliary spasm; only revealed under cycloplegia Manifest hyperopia Latin: manifestus (obvious) Amount measurable by routine refraction without cycloplegia AC/A ratio Accommodative Convergence to Accommodation Prism diopters of convergence generated per diopter of accommodation Pseudomyopia Greek: pseudo (false) Apparent myopia from tonic accommodative spasm in a non-myopic eye Lookalike trap: Hyperopia vs Hypermetropia — identical condition, different names by convention. Boards use hyperopia; some older sources say hypermetropia. Do not treat them as different things. Lookalike trap: Myopia vs Pseudomyopia — real myopia is structural (too-long eye); pseudomyopia is functional (ciliary spasm mimics myopia). Pseudomyopia resolves under cycloplegia. Real myopia does not.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"The two-variable system: Every refractive state is the result of a mismatch between the eye's POWER and its LENGTH. EMMETROPIA : POWER matches LENGTH → F2 lands exactly on retina MYOPIA : POWER too strong → F2 in front of retina OR LENGTH too long → retina is past F2 HYPEROPIA : POWER too weak → F2 would be behind retina OR LENGTH too short → retina is before F2 ASTIGMATISM : POWER unequal in meridians → two line foci, not one point Classification by mechanism: Axial ametropia — axial length is the variable; refractive media are normal Refractive ametropia — axial length is normal; power of the media is wrong Curvature type: corneal or lenticular radius is abnormal Index type: index of refraction of a medium is abnormal The four causative variables (from D1-01 Gullstrand section): Factor Too high causes Too low causes Axial length Myopia (eye too long) Hyperopia (eye too short) Corneal curvature Myopia (steep K = high power) Hyperopia (flat K = low power) Lens power Myopia (too much plus) Hyperopia (insufficient plus) Index of refraction Myopia (high n = more bending) Hyperopia\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Hofstetter's Formulas — Amplitude of Accommodation by Age Minimum AOA = 15 − 0.25 × age Average AOA = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Maximum AOA = 25 − 0.40 × age ( AOA in diopters; age in years) What it states in plain language: A person's ability to focus at near (accommodation amplitude) decreases predictably and linearly with age. Hofstetter gives three reference curves — minimum expected, average, and maximum — so a clinician can compare a patient's measured amplitude to what is normal for their age. What each part means: 15, 18.5, 25 — the y-intercepts; theoretical amplitude at age 0. These are not biologically real but are the mathematical starting points fitted to population data. 0.25, 0.30, 0.40 — the slopes; how many diopters of amplitude are lost per year of age. The minimum curve loses the least per year; the maximum curve loses the fastest per year. Age — the independent variable. Accommodation loss is approximately linear over the clinical range (ages 10 to 70). The three formulas describe the distribution: minimum = worst 10th percentile for age; average = 50th percentile; maximum = 90th percentile. Where it comes from: Henry Hofstetter (1950) revised Donders' original lookup table by fitting a continuous linear regression to population data across ages. The advantage over Donders' table is that you can calculate an expected value for any exact age rather than looking up the nearest listed age. The linear relationship holds because lens stiffening progresses at a roughly constant rate through the clinical range. The analogy that makes it click: Think of a rubber band that is slowly losing its elasticity with age. At age 10, it stretches far (12–19D). By age 45, it barely stretches (3–4D). By age 75, it barely moves (0–0.5D). The minimum formula is the rubber band that started out weakest; the maximum is the one that started strongest. All three lose elasticity at slightly different rates, but they all lose it. Why this form and not another: The linear form works because presbyopia is not an on/off event — it is a gradual process. Using a curve or exponential would be harder to apply clinically and is not justified by the population data in the clinically relevant age range. The three-formula system captures the biologic variability without requiring case-by-case measurement of every healthy patient. What it does NOT explain: Does not account for medications (atropine, cycloplegics, miotics artificially alter AOA) Does not account for systemic disease (diabetes, myasthenia gravis, Graves' disease) Does not account for refractive error (a myope's effective near point is different from an emmetrope's) The Hofstetter formula gives expected amplitude, not the actual clinical add power needed Cross-subject connections: C6 (Management of Visual Disorders): The presbyopia ADD is calculated from the AOA using the middle-third rule: Add = WD − ½ AOA. The Hofstetter formula gives you the AOA needed for that calculation. B5 (BV + Fusion): AC/A ratio management depends on knowing how much accommodation the patient is using. Hofstetter tells you the expected amplitude — patients using more than their expected AOA for their age are compensating, which affects the convergence demand analysis. Reading the Result: AOA result What it means Clinical/Board trap AOA < Minimum for age Reduced for age — investigate cause (drug, disease, early presbyopia) Do not assume presbyopia automatically; rule out reversible causes under age 40 AOA = Average for age Normal; no pathology Does not mean no symptoms — symptom onset depends on the patient's near demand, not just their AOA AOA < 5D at any age Functional presbyopia — patient cannot read comfortably at 20cm Prescribe reading ADD regardless of chronological age AOA = 0 Absolute presbyopia — ciliary muscle completely ineffective; lens fully rigid Emmetrope sees only at infinity; myope only at far point; hyperope sees nothing clearly without glasses Donders' Table — Age-Referenced Amplitude of Accommodation Age (yr) | AOA (D) Age (yr) | AOA (D) 10 | 14.00 45 | 3.50 15 | 12.00 50 | 2.50 20 | 10.00 55 | 1.75 25 | 8.50 60 | 1.00 30 | 7.00 65 | 0.50 35 | 5.50 70 | 0.25 40 | 4.50 75 | 0.00 Plain language: Donders' table lists the average expected amplitude by decade. It is the clinical reference before Hofstetter's formulas. Use it as a quick check when you do not want to calculate. Board trap: Hofstetter gives THREE values per age (min/ave/max). Donders gives ONE value per age (average). Do not mix them up on an MCQ asking for minimum or maximum expected. AC/A Ratio — Accommodative Convergence per Accommodation AC/A = change in convergence (prism diopters) / change in accommodation (diopters) Normal: 3:1 to 5:1 (i.e., 3–5Δ of convergence per 1D of accommodation) What it states in plain language: For every diopter of accommodation the eyes produce, a fixed amount of convergence is generated automatically. This ratio describes how tightly convergence is coupled to accommodation in a given patient. What each part means: AC (accommodative convergence) — the convergence that automatically occurs when the ciliary muscle contracts; measured in prism diopters A (accommodation) — the change in lens power; measured in diopters Ratio — a fixed physiological constant for each patient; it does not change with the amount of stimulus, only with age (decreases slightly as presbyopia develops) Where it comes from: The AC/A ratio reflects the neurological coupling between the accommodation and vergence systems. Both are driven by blur and proximity signals that travel through the same neural channels. Maddox (1893) first described the relationship; Donders and later Alpern quantified it clinically. Why this matters: A high AC/A (>5:1) means excessive convergence relative to accommodation — the patient over-converges when focusing at near, producing esophoria or esotropia at near. A low AC/A (<3:1) means too little convergence relative to accommodation — the patient under-converges, producing exophoria at near. Cross-subject connections: B5 (BV + Fusion): AC/A is used in the OEP/SOAP method. Morgan's norms use the AC/A to predict expected phoria shifts from distance to near. Sheard's criterion depends on knowing the vergence demand, which is set by the AC/A. C6 (Management): Treating accommodative esotropia in children — the plus lens add reduces accommodation, which via the high AC/A reduces convergence, which reduces the esotropia. The AC/A ratio is the mechanism that makes plus lens treatment work. Reading the Result: AC/A Interpretation Clinical presentation < 3:1 (low) Convergence does not follow accommodation adequately Exophoria increases at near; CI symptoms 3:1 to 5:1 (normal) Well-coupled systems; balanced near vision Minimal symptoms if fusional reserves adequate > 5:1 (high) Excessive convergence with accommodation Esophoria or esotropia at near; worse with uncorrected hyperopia Very high + uncorrected hyperopia Classic accommodative esotropia in children Plus lenses reduce accommodation → reduce convergence → straighten eyes Retinoscopy Working Distance Correction Net retinoscopy finding = Gross finding − (1 / working distance in meters) Working distance 67 cm (0.67 m) → subtract 1.50D Working distance 50 cm (0.50 m) → subtract 2.00D Working distance 40 cm (0.40 m) → subtract 2.50D What it states in plain language: Because the examiner is not at optical infinity when performing retinoscopy, the gross finding includes a built-in amount of myopia equal to the vergence at the working distance. Subtracting the working distance correction converts the gross finding to the actual refractive error. What each part means: Gross finding — the lens power that produces neutral motion at the working distance; this neutralizes the patient's retina with the examiner's peephole as the target Working distance — distance from the examiner's peephole to the patient's eye, in meters 1/WD — the vergence at the working distance; this is the \\\"extra\\\" myopia the gross finding contains Net finding — the actual refractive error, equivalent to what would be found if the examiner were at optical infinity Where it comes from: The examiner is not at infinity. Light returning from the patient's retina is diverging at 1/WD diopters when it reaches the examiner's peephole. Neutral motion occurs when the examiner's eye is conjugate with the patient's retina, which happens when the gross power placed in front of the patient's eye makes the patient's far point equal to the working distance. The analogy: The working distance correction is like zeroing a scale before weighing. The gross finding includes the instrument's position as part of the measurement. The correction removes the positional offset so you read the actual error. Cross-subject connections: C4 (Objective Examination): The working distance correction is applied at every retinoscopy encounter. 67 cm is the standard working distance (room-sized lanes); 50 cm is used in smaller exam rooms. D1-01 (Geometric Optics): The correction is just a vergence calculation: vergence at 0.67m = 1/0.67 = 1.50D. The same D = 1/f formula underpins both. Reading the Result: Gross finding WD (cm) WD correction Net finding +2.00 DS 67 cm −1.50D +0.50 DS (low hyperope) Plano 67 cm −1.50D −1.50 DS (myope) −1.00 DS 50 cm −2.00D −3.00 DS (moderate myope) +3.00 DS 50 cm −2.00D +1.00 DS (hyperope)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Ametropia Classification Tree REFRACTIVE STATUS | +-- EMMETROPIA : F2 on retina, accommodation relaxed | +-- AMETROPIA | +-- BY MECHANISM | +-- Axial: length is the variable (most common) | +-- Refractive: power is the variable | +-- Curvature type (K or lens shape) | +-- Index type (n of media abnormal) | +-- BY CONDITION +-- MYOPIA : F2 in front of retina | +-- Simple (correlative) — ≤6.00D, stationary | +-- Degenerative (component) — >6.00D, progressive | +-- Pseudomyopia — accommodative spasm, resolves with cycloplegia | +-- Night myopia — dim light, large pupil, spherical aberration | +-- HYPEROPIA : F2 behind retina | +-- By accommodation: | | Facultative (overcome by Acc) → Absolute (cannot) → Latent (hidden) → Manifest → Total | +-- By amount: Low (0.25–3.00D) / Medium (3.00–5.00D) / High (>5.00D) | +-- ASTIGMATISM : no single point focus | +-- Regular: 2 principal meridians at 90° | | +-- WTR (With-the-rule): steep meridian 60–120° | | +-- ATR (Against-the-rule): steep meridian 0–30° or 150–180° | | +-- Oblique: steep meridian 30–60° or 120–150° | +-- Irregular: principal meridians not perpendicular | +-- By resultant (see Comparisons section) | +-- PRESBYOPIA : insufficient amplitude (not a focus error per se) +-- Incipient: near blur under stress conditions +-- Absolute: accommodation essentially zero +-- Premature: before age 40 +-- Nocturnal: dim-light reduction of apparent amplitude Retinoscopy Movement Decision Tree Sweep retinoscope light across pupil | Is reflex moving WITH the sweep (same direction)? | +-- YES : Hyperopia, emmetropia, or low myopia (less than WD equivalent) | → Add PLUS lenses until neutral | +-- NO ( AGAINST ): Myopia greater than working distance equivalent | → Add MINUS lenses until neutral | +-- NEUTRAL (whole pupil lights up instantly): Far point = working distance → This is the gross finding → Subtract WD correction to get net finding Accommodation Mechanism (Helmholtz Theory) Far target (relaxed) → Ciliary muscle RELAXED → Zonules TAUT → Lens FLAT (thin) → Low plus power | Near target demand → Ciliary muscle CONTRACTS → Zonules RELAX → Lens ROUNDS (thick) → High plus power | (Parasympathetic: CN3 → ciliary ganglion → short ciliary nerves → ciliary muscle)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Myopia vs Hyperopia Feature Myopia Hyperopia Definition Parallel rays focus IN FRONT of retina Parallel rays focus BEHIND retina Far point REAL, finite, in front of eye VIRTUAL, behind the eye Eye structure Axial length TOO LONG or power TOO HIGH Axial length TOO SHORT or power TOO LOW Distance vision BLURRED (far blur) Blurred (may be clear if accommodated) Near vision Often CLEAR (sometimes better than emmetrope) BLURRED unless accommodated; headaches at near Pupil appearance Dilated (objective sign) Constricted (accommodating) Correction MINUS (diverging) lens PLUS (converging) lens Headache location Rare in pure myopia Frontal (from accommodation overuse) Predisposition Retinal detachment (high myopia), glaucoma (open-angle) Glaucoma (narrow-angle), convergent strabismus, infection Board clue \\\"squinting to see far\\\" \\\"headache reading\\\"; child with esotropia Astigmatism Types — Resultant Classification Type Both meridians Image of point Correction Compound Hyperopic (CHA) Both BEHIND retina Oval (V in ATR; H in WTR) Plus sphere + plus cylinder Simple Hyperopic (SHA) One ON retina, one behind Straight line Simple plus cylinder Compound Myopic (CMA) Both IN FRONT of retina Oval (V in WTR; H in ATR) Minus sphere + minus cylinder Simple Myopic (SMA) One ON retina, one in front Straight line Simple minus cylinder Mixed One in front, one behind Circle (equal errors) or oval (unequal) Sphere one sign, cylinder stronger opposite Board clue \\\"compound\\\" = both meridians same side of retina \\\"mixed\\\" = cyl > sph in magnitude Retinoscopy Movements (Plane vs Concave Mirror) Mirror type Hyperopia/Small myope Myopia > WD Plane mirror (standard) WITH motion AGAINST motion Concave mirror (sleeve retracted) AGAINST motion WITH motion Lens to neutralize (plane) Plus Minus Memory rule Plane: same as clinical correction direction Flip everything for concave\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Normal AC/A ratio 3:1 to 5:1 Δ of convergence per D of accommodation Presbyopia onset (average) Age 45 Range: 40 to 50 Functional presbyopia threshold AOA < 5.00 D Near symptoms develop; ADD indicated Absolute presbyopia AOA ~0.25D or less Near 75 years old per Donders Standard working distance (retinoscopy) 67 cm → −1.50D correction Some rooms use 50 cm → −2.00D Myopia prevalence (overall) 25 to 40% Highest in Chinese/Japanese populations Congenital myopia prevalence 1 to 2% Myopia classification (low) 0.25 to 3.00 D Myopia classification (medium) 3.00 to 6.00 D Myopia classification (high) 6.00 D and above Risk of degenerative changes Hyperopia (low) 0.25 to 3.00 D Usually not corrected unless symptomatic in young Hyperopia (medium) 3.00 to 5.00 D Hyperopia (high) 5.00 D and above Myopia progression rate 0.25 to 0.55 D/year Childhood to teen years Anisometropia: Class change threshold >3.00 D difference Class III: amblyopia typically present Anisometropia: glasses tolerance limit Up to 6.00 D difference Beyond 6D: glasses not tolerated; CLs needed Kornerstone of latent hyperopia correction Full Rx when constant blur, near work, marked asthenopia Partial Rx when exophoria or large latency Donders table — age 20 10.00 D Key anchor: memorize age 20 = 10D Donders table — age 40 4.50 D Beginning of presbyopia range Donders table — age 45 3.50 D Typical clinical presbyopia onset\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Myopia vs Hyperopia signs acronym: For MYOPIA objective signs: DESM D ilated pupil E xophthalmos (high myopia) S tarring expression M yopic crescent (on fundus) For HYPEROPIA objective signs: CCEV C onstricted pupil C onjunctival irritation E ndophthalmic eyes V ertical brow wrinkles (+ convergent strabismus in children) Resultant astigmatism memory pattern: CHA + CMA are COMPOUND (both meridians same side) — their oval image is on OPPOSITE sides CHA: (+V ATR, +H WTR) — oval is vertical in ATR CMA: (-V WTR, -H ATR) — oval is vertical in WTR — opposite of CHA Simple types: one meridian on retina → straight line image Mixed: one meridian each side → circle or oval Hofstetter numbers to anchor: Min: 15 minus 0.25/year Ave: 18.5 minus 0.30/year Max: 25 minus 0.40/year Pattern: bigger starting number → bigger slope (faster decrease). Makes intuitive sense: the patient who starts with the highest amplitude also has the most to lose per year. Retinoscopy movement rule: \\\"What you see is what you give (for plane mirror): WITH motion — add PLUS, AGAINST motion — add MINUS.\\\" This is because WITH motion means the far point is behind the examiner (hyperope or low myope) — you push the far point back further to infinity with PLUS. AC/A pattern: High AC/A + hyperopia = esotropia in children (classic combo; correct the hyperopia to reduce the convergence) Low AC/A + myopia = common; near exophoria manageable High AC/A alone (emmetrope) = esophoria at near; minus add or BI prism\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"REFRACTIVE ERROR OVERVIEW FAR POINT | EMMETROPE : Power = 58.64D, AL = 24.38mm → at ∞ Retina at F2 (24.38mm) MYOPE : Power TOO HIGH or AL TOO LONG FAR POINT | F2 ← ← ← ← ← ← RETINA in front (image focused in front) of eye Correction: MINUS lens pushes F2 to ∞ by diverging rays HYPEROPE : Power TOO LOW or AL TOO SHORT FAR POINT (virtual) | RETINA → → → F2 (virtual) BEHIND (image would focus behind) the eye Correction: PLUS lens pulls F2 forward to ∞ ASTIGMATISM : Two different powers in two meridians (90° apart) Steep meridian (high power) → Focal line CLOSER to cornea (front) Flat meridian (low power) → Focal line FURTHER from cornea (back) The region between the two focal lines = Conoid of Sturm Circle of Least Confusion = midpoint between the two focal lines ACCOMMODATION AMPLITUDE LOSS : Age 20 ████████████████████████████████████ 10.00D (average) Age 30 ████████████████████████████ 7.00D Age 40 ████████████████ 4.50D ← presbyopia onset Age 45 █████████████ 3.50D Age 50 ██████████ 2.50D Age 60 ████ 1.00D Age 70 █ 0.25D RETINOSCOPY MOVEMENT (Plane mirror, standard): Patient's far point BEHIND examiner → WITH motion → PLUS neutralizes Patient's far point IN FRONT → AGAINST motion → MINUS neutralizes Patient's far point AT examiner → NEUTRAL → Gross finding found\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Trap 1: \\\"Hyperopia is far-sightedness, so hyperopes see far clearly.\\\" Trap 2: \\\"Latent hyperopia is less than manifest hyperopia.\\\" Trap 3: \\\"Pseudomyopia means the patient is pretending.\\\" Trap 4: \\\"Against motion always means myopia; with motion always means hyperopia.\\\" Trap 5: \\\"The Hofstetter minimum formula gives the lowest expected amplitude.\\\" Trap 6: Compound myopic astigmatism correction is a minus sphere WITH minus cylinder. Trap 7: \\\"WTR astigmatism is more common in the elderly.\\\" Trap 8: Presbyopia affects only the near point.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Myopia correction MINUS lens Hyperopia correction PLUS lens Astigmatism correction CYLINDER (or sphero-cylinder) Presbyopia correction PLUS ADD on reading Rx Far point: emmetrope Optical infinity Far point: myope −3.00D 33 cm in front of eye Far point: hyperope Virtual (behind eye) Hofstetter minimum formula Min = 15 − 0.25 × age Hofstetter average formula Ave = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Hofstetter maximum formula Max = 25 − 0.40 × age Donders: age 20 10.00 D Donders: age 40 4.50 D Presbyopia onset average Age 45 Normal AC/A ratio 3:1 to 5:1 Retinoscopy working distance (67cm) Subtract 1.50D from gross Retinoscopy with motion Add PLUS Retinoscopy against motion Add MINUS Pseudomyopia Accommodative spasm; clears with cycloplegia WTR astigmatism steep axis 60–120° (vertical power meridian) ATR astigmatism steep axis 0–30° or 150–180° (horizontal power meridian) Anisometropia: amblyopia risk Class III (>3.00D difference) Anisometropia: glasses limit 6.00D maximum difference High AC/A + hyperopia in child Accommodative esotropia; correct with full plus\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"1. A 7-year-old is referred for an eye examination. The parents report that the child squints to see the blackboard but reads comfortably at near. Retinoscopy reveals AGAINST motion in all meridians at 67 cm working distance. Which lens is most likely to neutralize the reflex? A. +1.50 DS B. +3.00 DS C. −1.50 DS D. −3.00 DS Answer D. −3.00 DS. Against motion at 67cm (1.50D WD) means the patient is myopic by more than 1.50D. If the gross finding is −1.50D (the value that produces neutral), the net finding = −1.50 + (−1.50) = −3.00D. Against motion requires MINUS lenses for neutralization. A and B are wrong because plus lenses are for with motion. C is the gross finding, not the net finding. 2. A 45-year-old emmetrope complains that she needs to hold newspapers further away to read comfortably. Using Hofstetter's average formula, what is her expected accommodative amplitude? A. 3.75 D B. 5.00 D C. 5.00 D (minimum) D. 4.00 D Answer B. 5.00 D (average). Average AOA = 18.5 − 0.30 × 45 = 18.5 − 13.5 = 5.00 D. This is the average expected amplitude. Minimum = 15 − 0.25 × 45 = 15 − 11.25 = 3.75D. Maximum = 25 − 0.40 × 45 = 25 − 18 = 7.00D. The question asks for the average Hofstetter formula result, so the answer is 5.00D.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2-01-ametropia-and-refractive-errors-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C2-01 — Ametropia and Refractive Errors\",\"text\":\"The rule: Read the section. Close the note. Pick up a pen. Retrieve — do not look while writing. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"C2 — Ametropia\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set a 5-minute timer. Dump everything you know: all five refractive conditions, their far points, their corrections, their symptoms, the Hofstetter numbers, the retinoscopy movements. What to brain dump for this note: The five classifications of hyperopia by action of accommodation (facultative, absolute, latent, manifest, total) — write a one-line definition of each The three Hofstetter formulas in full, from memory The resultant astigmatism types (CMA/CHA/SMA/SHA/Mixed) with the oval orientation for each Drill 2 — Blank Diagram or Table Reproduce the full Ametropia Classification Tree from memory — start with \\\"REFRACTIVE STATUS\\\" at the top and branch all the way down to the subtypes. Label every branch with its distinguishing feature. What to reproduce: The classification tree (Myopia → 7 classification systems; Hyperopia → 5 types by accommodation + 3 by degree; Astigmatism → regular/irregular + WTR/ATR/oblique + 5 resultant types) Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write a 4-sentence explanation of why a high AC/A ratio combined with uncorrected hyperopia causes esotropia in children — without using the words \\\"AC/A ratio\\\" or \\\"esotropia\\\" until the last sentence. Teach-back prompt: \\\"Explain the chain from uncorrected farsightedness in a 4-year-old to crossed eyes, starting from what happens when the child tries to see the TV across the room.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front (Question) Back (Answer) Hofstetter minimum formula Min = 15 − 0.25 × age Hofstetter average formula Ave = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Normal AC/A ratio 3:1 to 5:1 (Δ per D) Retinoscopy at 67cm: gross to net correction Subtract 1.50D With motion in plane mirror retinoscopy → add PLUS lens Against motion in plane mirror retinoscopy → add MINUS lens WTR astigmatism: steep meridian location 60–120° (vertical) ATR astigmatism: steep meridian location 0–30° or 150–180° (horizontal) Hyperopia: total = Latent + Manifest Pseudomyopia revealed by Cycloplegia (atropine or cyclopentolate) Donders: age 40 amplitude 4.50 D Presbyopia onset (average) Age 45 Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete sequence for performing static retinoscopy on a new patient — from instructing the patient to recording the net finding — in numbered steps, without looking. Sequence to write: Static retinoscopy from setup to net finding, including: patient instruction, working distance setup, sleeve position, streak orientation, how to identify the two principal meridians in astigmatism, the neutralization end-point, conversion from gross to net, and final VA check. Recall Interval Schedule for This Note Session When What to do 1st review Same day you write it Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Next day Blank Diagram + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review 1 week later Full Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check 2 weeks later Attempt all 5 drills; flag anything shaky\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"The preliminary examination is everything done before you pick up a retinoscope. It gives you a snapshot of the patient's functional vision status: how clearly they see, how their pupils behave, how their eyes move and align, and how close they can focus. Each test answers a specific clinical question. When you understand the question each test is answering, you stop memorizing procedures and start reasoning through what any abnormal finding means. A case history is not small talk — it is a diagnostic tool. The first test is observation. Everything follows from there. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"If a patient walks in and you could do only one preliminary test before the refraction, which would it be and why?\\\" The argument forces them to think about what information is irreplaceable and what builds on what. Visual acuity is the answer — it is the baseline against which every other finding is interpreted.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Why is the case history done first, before any tests? Because it directs which tests are necessary. Why does the chief complaint determine the test sequence? Because a patient with diplopia needs motility and cover testing prioritized. A patient with blur needs VA and refraction first. Without the history, you run every test without knowing which finding matters. Why does the history have to proceed from general to specific? Because asking specific questions first introduces bias. A patient asked \\\"is your headache in your forehead?\\\" will say yes even if it is not. Open-ended first, then focused. Why is the preliminary examination done before the refraction? Because several preliminary findings directly modify the refraction approach. A reduced NPC tells you to add convergence testing to the BV analysis. A positive Marcus Gunn tells you to investigate the optic nerve before attributing poor VA to refractive error. Pupil anomalies change your pharmacology decisions. The preliminary examination is the map that tells you where the refraction will lead.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Asthenopia Greek: asthenes (weak) + ops (eye) Eye strain — umbrella term for discomfort, fatigue, blur from visual effort Version Latin: versio (turning) Conjugate binocular eye movement — both eyes move same direction simultaneously Duction Latin: ducere (to lead) Monocular eye movement in any direction Vergence Latin: vergere (to incline) Binocular eye movements in opposite directions (convergence/divergence) NPC Near Point of Convergence Closest point the eyes can maintain convergence without diplopia or deviation NPA Near Point of Accommodation Closest point the eye can still focus clearly (maximum accommodation used) PD / IPD Pupillary Distance / Interpupillary Distance Distance between the centers of the two entrance pupils Phoria Greek: phora (carrying) Latent deviation — controlled by fusion; only appears when fusion is broken Tropia Greek: tropos (turning) Manifest deviation — constant misalignment even with both eyes open Angle kappa Angle between visual axis and pupillary axis Normally +5° / 0.5mm nasal; negative = temporal shift; large positive mimics exotropia RAPD Relative Afferent Pupillary Defect Paradoxical dilation on swinging flashlight = afferent defect ipsilateral side Marcus Gunn pupil Named after Robert Marcus Gunn RAPD; impaired optic nerve or retinal input compared to fellow eye Hirschberg test Named after Julius Hirschberg Corneal reflex method to estimate tropia magnitude in prism diopters PERRL Pupils Equal Round Reactive to Light Standard abbreviation for normal pupil findings Anisocoria Greek: aniso (unequal) + kore (pupil) Unequal pupil sizes; physiologic if difference ≤1mm and consistent in light and dark Lookalike trap: Phoria vs Tropia — a phoria is latent (only seen on cover testing); a tropia is manifest (visible to inspection). A tropia is NEVER normal. Lookalike trap: NPC vs NPA — NPC is about convergence (eyes crossing); NPA is about accommodation (lens focusing). Both are \\\"near points\\\" but measure completely different functions.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"The flow of preliminary examination: CASE HISTORY → Chief complaint directs test priority → Profile, ocular/medical/family history, medications, visual demands ENTRANCE TESTS (done in dimly lit room first for pupil assessment) 1. Pupil size (static observation) 2. IPD measurement 3. Visual acuity (far and near, unaided then aided) 4. Pinhole VA (if VA is reduced) 5. Corneal reflex / fixation test (Hirschberg) 6. Cover-Uncover Test (phoria vs tropia) 7. Version / Ocular Motility Test 8. NPC 9. Near Point of Accommodation ( NPA ) 10. Pupillary Reflex Tests (direct, indirect, near, swinging flashlight) (+ color vision, visual field if indicated) Why this order matters: IPD is measured before phoropter setup to avoid induced prism VA is taken unaided first (before any lenses) to capture baseline and predict the refractive error Cover test is done before corneal reflex because cover test is more sensitive for phorias Pupils are assessed in dim room to see maximum pupil size and reaction range\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Near PD Calculation — Formula 2 (Simplified) NPD = ( DPD × WD) / (WD + 27) DPD = far (distance) PD in mm WD = near working distance in mm 27 = constant (13.5mm behind cornea to center of rotation + 13.5mm spectacle plane) What it states in plain language: As the eyes converge for near, they physically move closer together. The near PD is always smaller than the distance PD. This formula calculates how much the PD decreases based on the working distance. What each part means: DPD — the measured distance PD; the baseline measurement when the eyes are parallel WD — the patient's intended reading distance in mm; closer working distance = greater convergence = smaller near PD 27 — accounts for the location of the eyes' center of rotation relative to the spectacle plane; standard anatomical constant (13.5mm × 2) The formula says: the near PD is proportional to the working distance, scaled by the total distance from the lens to the eye's rotation point The analogy: Think of two spotlights on ceiling tracks. When they both point straight ahead (infinity), they are maximally separated (distance PD). When you angle them to shine at a point 40cm below on the floor, they tilt inward — the beams are now closer at the floor (near PD). The tighter the target, the more they cross inward. Cross-subject connections: D2-01 (Dispensing): The near PD is critical for bifocal and near lens decentration. Wrong near PD creates unwanted prism at the reading position. B5 (BV): Convergence demand is set by the working distance relative to the PD. This formula is the basis for calculating how many prism diopters of convergence the patient must maintain at near. Reading the Result: NPD result What it means NPD < DPD Normal (expected — eyes converge at near) NPD = DPD Abnormal — no convergence occurring; suspect severe CI or strabismus NPD > DPD Error in measurement Amplitude of Convergence Amp. of Conv. (Δ) = ( NPD in cm × 10) / ( NPC in cm + 3) NPD = near pupillary distance in cm NPC = near point of convergence distance from bridge of nose, in cm 3 = distance from bridge of nose to the spectacle plane (constant) What it states in plain language: The amplitude of convergence is the maximum amount of convergence available to the patient, expressed in prism diopters. Why the \\\"+3\\\": The NPC is measured from the bridge of the nose. The spectacle plane is approximately 13mm in front of the center of rotation. The \\\"+3\\\" converts NPC from the bridge-of-nose reference to the spectacle plane reference. Clinical note: Normal amplitude of convergence varies but a rough clinical norm is 30–60 prism diopters for a young adult. The actual demand at a given working distance can be calculated separately. Hirschberg Method — Corneal Reflex to Prism Diopters Corneal reflex displacement → Approximate deviation: Slightly nasal (0.5mm) = physiologic (+angle kappa, 5°, ~10Δ) At pupillary margin = 15° = 30 prism diopters Between pupil and limbus = 30° = 60 prism diopters At limbus = 45° = 90 prism diopters What it states in plain language: Each millimeter the corneal light reflex is displaced from its normal nasal position represents approximately 15 prism diopters of deviation (or equivalently, 7 degrees). Interpretation direction: Reflex displaced NASALLY beyond normal → ESO deviation (eye deviated inward) Reflex displaced TEMPORALLY → EXO deviation (eye deviated outward) Reflex displaced UP → HYPO deviation; displaced DOWN → HYPER deviation Cross-subject connections: F2 (Pediatric): Hirschberg is the go-to alignment test for young children who cannot cooperate with cover testing. D1 (Prisms): The 1mm = 7° = ~15Δ relationship follows from the geometry of the corneal reflex — the same principle as the prismatic deviation formula.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Case History — 4 Components (WEED system, 1968) 1. PATIENT PROFILE Name / Age / Gender / Address / Occupation / Contact | Purpose: identification, communication, demographic disease risk 2. PROBLEM LIST (Chief Complaint) Primary complaint → when, how long, location, severity, frequency, triggers Sources of complaints: | +-- Accommodative: uncorrected refractive error (hyperopia, astigmatism, presbyopia) +-- Motor: muscular deficiency (phorias, vergence reserves deficient) +-- Integrative: combination (accommodation + convergence problem) 3. INITIAL TREATMENT PLAN Derived from problem list + physical findings → differential diagnosis 4. PROGRESS NOTES Comparison to previous visits; changes in Rx, symptoms, ocular health Visual Acuity — Recording and Classification NOTATION SYSTEMS : Snellen Imperial (English): 20/20 (distance in feet) Snellen Metric: 6/6 (distance in meters) Decimal/International: 1.0 CONVERSION : 20 feet = 6 meters 20/20 = 6/6 = 1.0 20/40 = 6/12 = 0.5 20/200 = 6/60 = 0.1 ORDER OF TESTING : 1. Unaided (habitual without glasses) → OD, then OS, then OU 2. Habitual (with current glasses) → OD, then OS, then OU 3. Pinhole → only if VA < 20/30 to 20/40 4. Near VA → 40cm (16 inches) standard distance PINHOLE INTERPRETATION : VA improves through pinhole → uncorrected refractive error (correctable) VA does NOT improve through pinhole → organic pathology (not correctable by lenses) VA WORSENS through pinhole → fully corrected already, or dense media opacity Subnormal Vision Techniques (when VA < 20/200 and chart cannot approach) 20/200 at close distance → record as \\\"20/200 at _ft\\\" Counting Fingers (CF) → CF at 3ft Hand Motion (HM) → HM at 4ft Light Projection (LP) → can locate penlight in each quadrant Light Perception (LP) → can detect light present/absent No Light Perception ( NLP ) → complete absence of vision Cover Test Logic Tree Cover the FIXING eye | Does the NON-COVERED eye move? | +-- NO MOVEMENT → Orthotropia (no tropia; normal or phoria) +-- MOVES OUT (temporal) → ESOTROPIA (non-covered eye was turned inward) +-- MOVES IN (nasal) → EXOTROPIA (non-covered eye was turned outward) +-- MOVES UP → HYPOTROPIA of non-covered eye +-- MOVES DOWN → HYPERTROPIA of non-covered eye Uncover the covered eye | Does it drift back into position? +-- YES , returns to straight → PHORIA (latent; fusion restored it) +-- NO, stays deviated → TROPIA (manifest; no fusion control) ALTERNATING COVER TEST : Blocks fusion completely → reveals MAXIMUM deviation (phoria + any tropia) Movement seen in ACT but NOT in unilateral = PHORIA Movement seen in BOTH = TROPIA Pupillary Reflex Pathway (afferent and efferent arms) AFFERENT ARM (light signal in): Retina → Optic Nerve → Optic Chiasm → Optic Tract → Pretectal Nucleus (light signal leaves main visual pathway here — does NOT go to LGN for reflex) Pretectal Nucleus → bilateral Edinger-Westphal Nucleus (both sides = consensual) EFFERENT ARM (constriction signal out): Edinger-Westphal Nucleus → Preganglionic fiber ( CN3 ) → Ciliary Ganglion → Postganglionic fiber → Sphincter Pupillae → CONSTRICTION THREE REFLEXES : Direct ( DLR ): Light → ipsilateral pupil constricts Indirect/Consensual ( ILR ): Light → CONTRALATERAL pupil also constricts (via bilateral E-W ) Near/Accommodative ( PNR ): Near object → miosis + accommodation + convergence (near triad) NPC Procedure and Normal Values PROCEDURE : 1. Patient with habitual Rx seated at room illumination 2. Target (penlight or near accommodative target) held at 40cm midline 3. Move target slowly toward patient's nose 4. Patient reports when target doubles → BREAK POINT 5. Move target slowly away → patient reports single again → RECOVERY POINT 6. Record as: break/recovery (e.g., 7/10cm) NORMAL VALUES (Scheiman and Wick): Accommodative target: Break 5cm ± 2.5 / Recovery 7cm ± 4.0 Penlight or red lens: Break 7cm ± 4.0 / Recovery 10cm ± 5.0 INTERPRETATION : 6–10cm expected NPC (general guideline) < 5cm: convergence EXCESS > 10cm: convergence INSUFFICIENCY (CI) No doubling at all: suppression or wandering attention (not normal)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Three Types of Cover Tests Test What it detects Binocularity during test Board clue Unilateral cover test TROPIA (manifest deviation) One eye covered; fellow eye observed Movement in non-covered eye = tropia Cover-uncover test PHORIA (latent deviation) Cover then uncover; eye returns = phoria Movement only after uncovering = phoria Alternating cover test MAXIMUM deviation (phoria + tropia combined) Fusion broken repeatedly Does NOT differentiate phoria from tropia Visual Acuity Types (Forms) Type Alternate name What it measures Example test Minimum visible Detection acuity Presence/absence of object vs background Single dot on white background Minimum separable Resolution acuity Two separate lines/dots as distinct Grating, Landolt C, Verhoeff rings Minimum cognoscible Recognition acuity Identify complex target/letter Snellen chart (most used clinically) Minimum discriminable Vernier acuity Relative position of two aligned elements Vernier alignment task Board clue Lowest form — Most commonly tested Highest form: minimum separable (by some) Direct vs Indirect Pupillary Reflex Feature Direct Light Reflex (DLR) Indirect / Consensual (ILR) Eye illuminated Same eye that constricts OPPOSITE eye constricts Pathway tested Afferent (retina → optic nerve → E-W) + Efferent Afferent of illuminated eye + contralateral efferent Abnormal finding Impaired DLR = ipsilateral afferent or efferent problem Impaired ILR = ipsilateral afferent pathway problem Board clue No DLR in illuminated eye = CN3 efferent palsy or severe ipsilateral afferent defect ILR absent when direct is present = ipsilateral afferent problem confirmed Phoria vs Tropia (full comparison) Feature Phoria Tropia Definition Latent deviation; controlled by fusion Manifest deviation; present even with both eyes open Visible on inspection No — looks normal Yes — eye appears turned Detected by Cover-uncover test Unilateral cover test OR Hirschberg Binocular vision Preserved (fusion controls it) Absent or disrupted Normal finding? Yes — small phorias are normal A tropia is NEVER normal Expected norms Distance: 1 eso to 3 exo / Near: ortho to 6 exo None; any tropia is abnormal\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Normal distance PD (adult) 54–68mm (mean 64mm) Women 55–65mm, men 59–70mm Normal near PD (adult) Smaller than far PD Decreases as working distance decreases Normal PD (children) 41–55mm (50–60mm) Can be as low as 45mm Far VA standard distance 20ft (6m) 20/20 = 6/6 = 1.0 Near VA standard distance 40cm (16 inches) Reduced Snellen or Jaeger chart VA illumination standard 20 foot-candles (fc) Minimum for accurate testing ETDRS chart standard contrast 80% contrast target to background Also applies to Snellen Normal pupil (room light) 4.0mm (range 2.5–5.0mm) Normal pupil (darkness) 6.5mm (range 5.0–8.5mm) Normal pupil (direct light) 3.0mm (range 2.0–4.5mm) Anisocoria threshold >1.0mm difference = abnormal Physiologic = same in light and dark NPC normal (penlight): break 7cm ± 4.0 Scheiman and Wick NPC normal (penlight): recovery 10cm ± 5.0 NPC < 5cm Convergence excess NPC > 10cm Convergence insufficiency Hirschberg: nasal 0.5mm 5° = 10Δ Physiologic; angle kappa Hirschberg: at pupillary margin 15° = 30Δ Hirschberg: mid-pupil to limbus 30° = 60Δ Hirschberg: at limbus 45° = 90Δ Expected phoria (distance) 1 eso to 3 exo (ortho to 3XP) Expected phoria (near) Ortho to 6 exo Angle kappa (normal) Up to +5° (10Δ) nasally Larger positive = simulates exo; temporal = simulates eso\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Cover test movement directions (phoria and tropia): For PHORIA: \\\"The eye moves away from where it wants to hide.\\\" ESophoria: eye HIDES inward (nasal) when covered, MOVES OUT (temporal) when uncovered back to fusion EXophoria: eye HIDES outward (temporal) when covered, MOVES IN (nasal) when uncovered For TROPIA: observed in the NON-COVERED eye ESotropia: uncovered eye is turned IN → moves OUT when you cover the fixing eye EXotropia: uncovered eye is turned OUT → moves IN when you cover the fixing eye Pupillary reflex pathway mnemonic: RONPC-EWC-GS R etina → O ptic nerve → N ot going to LGN (branches off at) → P retectal nucleus → C rosses to both E dinger- W estphal nuclei → C iliary G anglion → S phincter VA interpretation quick rules (habitual vision): 20/20 = emmetropia OR compensated hyperopia Less than 20/20 = ametropia present Miscalled letters = astigmatism Binocular < monocular = muscle imbalance or binocular difficulty Variable / unstable VA = accommodative spasm NPC mnemonics: \\\"Break is when it doubles; recovery is when it singles.\\\" (This order never changes) \\\"Below 5 = too much; above 10 = too little.\\\" (Convergence excess and insufficiency) Headache location to refractive cause: F rontal = F arsightedness (hyperopia) / convergence excess T emporal = T orque (astigmatism) O ccipital = O ld age (presbyopia) / CI / vertical imbalance P arietal = P sychological / tension headache\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"PRELIMINARY EXAMINATION FLOW CASE HISTORY ENTRANCE OBSERVATION (subjective) (objective, before testing) | | +-- Chief complaint +-- Head tilt/turn +-- Ocular history +-- Lid droop / ptosis +-- Medical/family history +-- Corneal clarity +-- Medications +-- Iris/pupil appearance +-- Occupational/hobby +-- Patient posture | | v v ---------------- TESTS -------------------- | +-- 1. IPD (set phoropter before testing VA) | +-- 2. VISUAL ACUITY | Unaided → Habitual → Pinhole | Far (20ft / 6m) then Near (40cm) | +-- 3. CORNEAL REFLEX TEST (Hirschberg) | Slightly nasal = normal | Temporal = eso; nasal beyond 0.5mm = exo | +-- 4. COVER TEST | Unilateral → phoria or tropia | Alternating → total deviation | +-- 5. VERSION TEST ( EOM ) | \\\" FESA or SAFE \\\" = full, smooth, accurate, extensive | Record any lag, restriction, over/under action | +-- 6. NPC | Break / Recovery (e.g. 7/10cm) | >10cm = CI; <5cm = CE | +-- 7. PUPIL SIZE (static and dynamic) | Room light, darkness, direct light | Anisocoria? RAPD ? | +-- 8. PUPILLARY REFLEXES DLR → direct: ipsilateral constriction ILR → consensual: contralateral constriction PNR → near triad: constrict + accommodate + converge SFT → swinging flashlight: RAPD = Marcus Gunn PUPILLARY PATHWAY (shortened): Retina → CN2 → Chiasm → Optic Tract → Pretectum → BILATERAL E-W → CN3 → Ciliary Ganglion → Sphincter PHORIA vs TROPIA — COVER TEST DECISION : Cover one eye | Other eye moves? ── YES ──> Strabismus/Tropia present | NO | Uncover eye | Uncovered eye drifts back? ── YES ──> Phoria (latent deviation) | NO → Orthophoria (no deviation)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Trap 1: \\\"Visual acuity of 20/20 means no refractive error.\\\" Trap 2: \\\"Pinhole always improves VA.\\\" Trap 3: \\\"Corneal reflex displaced temporally = exo deviation.\\\" Trap 4: \\\"A phoria means the patient has strabismus.\\\" Trap 5: \\\"NPC is tested with one eye occluded.\\\" Trap 6: \\\"The direct light reflex pathway passes through the LGN.\\\" Trap 7: \\\"The alternating cover test distinguishes a phoria from a tropia.\\\" Trap 8: \\\"Monocular VA better than binocular VA is normal.\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Standard VA test distance (far) 20ft / 6m Standard near VA distance 40cm / 16 inches Standard illumination for VA 20 foot-candles 20/20 in meters 6/6 (decimal: 1.0) 20/200 in meters 6/60 (decimal: 0.1) Pinhole improves VA → Refractive error (correctable) Pinhole no improvement → Organic cause (not correctable) Normal adult PD 64mm mean (range 54–68mm) Near PD formula NPD = DPD × WD / (WD + 27) Normal NPC (penlight) Break 7cm ±4.0, Recovery 10cm ±5.0 NPC > 10cm Convergence Insufficiency NPC < 5cm Convergence Excess Normal pupil (room light) 4.0mm (range 2.5–5.0mm) RAPD = Marcus Gunn pupil; afferent defect Pupillary reflex pathway: leaves visual pathway at Pretectal nucleus (NOT LGN) Direct light reflex (DLR) Ipsilateral constriction Indirect / consensual (ILR) Contralateral constriction Near reflex triad Constriction + accommodation + convergence Corneal reflex temporal = ESO deviation Corneal reflex nasal (beyond 0.5mm) = EXO deviation Hirschberg: pupillary margin = 15° = 30Δ Expected phoria (distance) 1 eso to 3 exo Expected phoria (near) Ortho to 6 exo Headache — frontal Hyperopia / convergence excess Headache — temporal Astigmatism Headache — occipital Presbyopia / CI / vertical imbalance Alternating cover test Reveals TOTAL deviation; does NOT differentiate phoria from tropia\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"1. During a preliminary examination, the examiner covers the patient's right eye. The uncovered left eye is observed to move inward (nasally). Upon removing the occluder from the right eye, the left eye moves back outward. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis? A. Left esotropia B. Left exophoria C. Left esophoria D. Right exotropia Answer B. Left exophoria. The uncovered left eye moved INWARD (nasal) when the right was covered. This means the left eye wanted to drift outward (exo direction) when fusion was released by covering. When the cover was removed, the left eye moved back out to its normal position — consistent with a PHORIA (latent deviation controlled by fusion). The inward movement of the left eye when uncovered means the left eye was EXO under cover. Since it corrected on uncovering and there was no movement on the unilateral cover test, this is a phoria, not a tropia. 2. A patient's VA is OD 20/60, OS 20/20. Pinhole placed over the right eye improves VA to 20/30 but not to 20/20. The most likely explanation is: A. The right eye has a purely organic pathology B. The right eye has an uncorrected refractive error only C. The right eye has both an uncorrected refractive error AND an organic component D. The pinhole result is invalid — a 20/60 eye should always reach 20/20 through pinhole Answer C. The right eye has both an uncorrected refractive error AND an organic component. Pinhole improvement indicates a refractive component (since aberrations were reduced and VA improved from 20/60 to 20/30). However, 20/20 was not reached, indicating the improvement is incomplete — an organic component (amblyopia, early cataract, macular pathology) is also limiting the final VA. Pure refractive error alone would be expected to reach 20/20 (or close to it) through pinhole. A = wrong because some improvement occurred. B = wrong because the improvement was incomplete.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3-01-preliminary-examination-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C3-01 — Preliminary Examination\",\"text\":\"The rule: Close the note before picking up the pen. Retrieve, do not copy. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"C3 — Preliminary Examination\\\" at the top of a blank page. 5-minute timer. Dump everything: all 10 entrance tests in order, normal values, cover test logic, NPC normal values, pupillary reflex pathway, headache locations. What to brain dump: The 10 preliminary tests in the correct sequence The full pupillary reflex pathway from retina to sphincter (all 10 stations) The four VA forms (minimum visible, separable, cognoscible, discriminable) with one example each Drill 2 — Blank Diagram or Table Reproduce the Cover Test Decision Tree from memory — start with \\\"Cover one eye\\\" and branch out to all five findings (orthotropia, esotropia, exotropia, hypertropia, hypotropia, esophoria, exophoria). Label each branch with the movement that triggers it. What to reproduce: Full cover test decision tree distinguishing phoria vs tropia for all four deviation directions. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write 4–5 sentences explaining why a patient who reports \\\"double vision only when reading\\\" is more likely to have a binocular vision issue than a refractive error — without using the word \\\"phoria\\\" or \\\"convergence\\\" until the last sentence. Teach-back prompt: \\\"Explain why diplopia that appears only at near, and disappears at distance, tells you the problem is not a lens power issue.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front (Question) Back (Answer) Normal adult PD (mean) 64mm NPC normal break (penlight) 7cm ± 4.0 NPC > 10cm Convergence Insufficiency NPC < 5cm Convergence Excess Pinhole improves VA → Refractive error (correctable) Corneal reflex displaced temporally ESO deviation Pupillary reflex: leaves main visual pathway at Pretectal nucleus RAPD / Marcus Gunn pupil = Afferent pupillary defect Expected phoria at near Ortho to 6 exophoria A tropia is... NEVER normal Near reflex triad Miosis + accommodation + convergence Headache — frontal → Hyperopia or convergence excess Headache — temporal → Astigmatism Binocular VA < monocular VA Binocular vision problem (suppression or imbalance) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete NPC test procedure from start to recorded result — patient setup, target type, movement direction, what you're observing, what break point and recovery point mean, and how you record the result. Sequence to write: NPC procedure (clinical protocol from patient seating to \\\"7/10cm\\\" recorded result), then the full clinical interpretation table (expected / CI / CE). Recall Interval Schedule for This Note Session When What to do 1st review Same day you write it Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Next day Blank Diagram + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review 1 week later Full Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check 2 weeks later Attempt all 5 drills; flag anything shaky\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"The objective examination is everything done without asking the patient for verbal feedback — you observe, measure, and record. It has four core tools: the slit lamp (biomicroscope), the ophthalmoscope, the keratometer, and the retinoscope. Each answers a different question. The slit lamp shows you the anterior segment in layered detail. The ophthalmoscope shows you the posterior segment and media. The keratometer measures corneal curvature and tells you how much of the patient's astigmatism comes from the cornea. The retinoscope gives you the refractive error without asking the patient a single question. A clinician who masters all four can complete a full workup on a patient who cannot communicate at all. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"If you had to choose one objective test for a newborn with suspected cataracts, which would you use and why?\\\" The answer forces them to match the tool to the clinical question: ophthalmoscopy for media opacity, retinoscopy for refraction, slit lamp for anterior segment detail. Cross-reference: Retinoscopy principles (movements, working distance, gross vs net) are fully covered in C2-01 . This note covers the slit lamp, ophthalmoscopy, and keratometry in full, and cross-references C2-01 for retinoscopy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Why does the slit lamp use a narrow beam of light instead of a broad one? Because a narrow slit creates an optical cross-section of the tissue, like slicing through it. You see each layer separately — epithelium, stroma, endothelium — rather than a blurred total thickness. Why does indirect ophthalmoscopy give a wider field but lower magnification than direct? Because the condensing lens forms an aerial real image of the fundus in the space between the lens and the examiner. The magnification depends on the ratio of the lens power to the eye's power. Higher lens power = shorter focal length = image formed closer = smaller, wider-field image. The binocular design adds stereo depth, which direct cannot provide. Why does the keratometer treat the cornea as a convex mirror? Because the tear film over the anterior cornea is a reflective surface. The mire image size depends on the radius of curvature of that mirror — the same physics as any convex mirror. A steeper cornea (smaller radius) produces a smaller mire image; a flatter cornea produces a larger one. Measuring image size gives you radius. Why does Javal's rule include a fixed −0.50 DC × 90° term? Because the posterior corneal surface and tilted crystalline lens together contribute a small, predictable amount of against-the-rule astigmatism (approximately −0.50D at 90°) to every eye. This internal astigmatism is not measured by the keratometer, which reads only the anterior cornea. Javal's rule adds this constant correction to convert corneal astigmatism to total refractive astigmatism.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Biomicroscopy Greek: bios (life) + micro (small) + skopein (to look) Microscopic examination of living eye tissue; slit lamp examination Ophthalmoscopy Greek: ophthalmos (eye) + skopein Examination of the interior of the eye with an ophthalmoscope Keratometry Greek: keras (horn/cornea) + metron (measure) Measurement of the anterior corneal surface curvature Parallelepiped Geometry: parallel + solid Slit lamp beam width ~3mm; allows 3D view of corneal volume Optic section — Narrowest slit beam width; shows a true cross-section of the cornea Van Herick technique Named after W. Van Herick Slit lamp method to estimate anterior chamber angle depth Mire French: mirer (to aim at / reflect) The target circles or crosses reflected off the cornea in keratometry Corneal astigmatism (Ac) — Astigmatism from the anterior corneal surface only; measured by keratometry Total/refractive astigmatism (At) — Total astigmatism of the eye; includes corneal and internal components Internal astigmatism — Astigmatism contributed by posterior cornea, tilted lens, and other internal surfaces Javal's rule Named after Emile Javal Formula to predict total astigmatism from corneal astigmatism K reading — Keratometric reading; corneal power expressed in diopters or mm radius Condensing lens — Hand-held plus lens (+14D to +30D) used in indirect ophthalmoscopy Direct ophthalmoscopy — Monocular; upright virtual image; ~15x magnification; ~6.5° field Indirect ophthalmoscopy — Uses condensing lens; inverted real image; 2–5x; ~25–40° field Marcus Gunn pupil — RAPD; afferent pupillary defect detected by swinging flashlight Lookalike trap: K reading in diopters vs mm radius — steeper cornea = larger D, smaller mm. A K of 43D = ~7.86mm radius. Do not confuse larger diopter value (more power) with larger radius (flatter surface).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Slit lamp: how the optical section works The slit lamp is a biomicroscope with a coupled illumination system. The illumination arm and the microscope arm share a common focal point. When the beam is narrow (optic section), it passes through the tissue like a plane of light — each layer scatters slightly differently, allowing the examiner to distinguish the epithelium, stroma, and endothelium of the cornea as visually distinct zones. The illumination arm can be decoupled from the microscope arm for indirect and retro-illumination techniques. Ophthalmoscope: how the image forms Direct: The instrument illuminates the retina through the pupil. The examiner looks through a peephole and a series of correcting lenses. The retina acts as a self-luminous object. The image formed is virtual and erect — as if looking at the fundus through a +15D magnifying glass. No aerial image exists between the patient and the examiner. Indirect: The condensing lens held in front of the patient's eye takes the diverging light from the illuminated retina and forms a real, inverted, aerial image of the fundus in space between the lens and the examiner. The examiner then looks at this aerial image with the headborne binocular ophthalmoscope. The image is real and inverted because the condensing lens is acting like the objective of a microscope. Keratometer: how the corneal radius is measured The tear film over the anterior cornea acts as a convex mirror. When the keratometer projects a mire (target image) at a known distance and size, it measures the size of the reflected virtual image in the corneal mirror. Since the size of the virtual image in a convex mirror depends on the radius of curvature, measuring image size gives radius: f = r/2 (for mirrors: focal length = half the radius) For corneal power: D = (n − 1) / r = 0.3375 / r (using reduced corneal index 1.3375) r in meters → D in diopters The keratometer then converts the radius to corneal power in diopters. The instrument requires a doubling device (prism or mirror) to stabilize the mire image during measurement.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Javal's Rule — Corneal to Total Astigmatism At = 1.25 (Ac) + (−0.50 Cyl × 90°) At = total (refractive) astigmatism Ac = corneal astigmatism (from keratometry) 1.25 = empirical scaling factor −0.50 Cyl × 90° = constant internal astigmatism contribution ( ATR direction) What it states in plain language: The total astigmatism of the eye is approximately 1.25 times the corneal astigmatism, minus a fixed 0.50D against-the-rule correction. The correction accounts for the astigmatism that comes from internal structures (back of the cornea, tilted lens) that the keratometer cannot see. What each part means: At — the total refractive astigmatism you would measure by retinoscopy or subjective refraction. This is what goes into the actual spectacle Rx. Ac — corneal astigmatism only, measured by keratometry. The keratometer reads only the anterior corneal surface. 1.25 — empirically derived scaling factor. The cornea typically contributes approximately 80% of the total astigmatism, but it is scaled up slightly because the keratometer reads only one surface and uses a simplified index. −0.50 Cyl × 90° — the internal astigmatism constant. Internal structures (posterior corneal surface, lens tilt) add approximately 0.50D of ATR astigmatism consistently across the population. Where it comes from: Emile Javal and Schiotz (19th century) observed that in most eyes, the total refractive astigmatism measured subjectively was predictably different from the corneal astigmatism measured by keratometry. They derived an empirical formula to bridge the two. The correction factor (−0.50 × 90°) represents the statistical average of internal astigmatism across large populations. The analogy: Javal's rule is like estimating the total weight of a package from the weight of the box alone, knowing that bubble wrap always adds approximately 0.5kg. You weigh the box (Ac), multiply by your scale factor (1.25), and subtract 0.5kg (internal component). You never weigh the bubble wrap directly — but you know its average contribution. Why this form and not another: If you used Ac directly without the internal correction, you would consistently over-correct the astigmatism in WTR eyes and under-correct ATR eyes. The −0.50 Cyl × 90° term is what makes the formula accurate for both WTR and ATR astigmatism. What it does NOT explain: Not valid for keratoconus or irregular corneas (the relationship between corneal and internal astigmatism breaks down) Not valid when the crystalline lens has significant lenticular astigmatism (e.g., nuclear sclerosis with lens tilt) Empirical estimate only — specific patients may deviate significantly from the predicted At Cross-subject connections: C2-01 (Astigmatism): Javal's rule predicts the starting cylinder power for the subjective refraction. Knowing Ac from keratometry means you enter the refraction with a predicted Rx rather than starting blind. D3-01 (Contact Lenses): In soft CL fitting, residual astigmatism = At − Ac. Javal's rule gives a quick estimate of how much astigmatism remains after placing a spherical soft lens (which masks Ac but not the internal component). Reading the Result: Relationship of At vs Ac Interpretation At ≈ 1.25(Ac) Normal — internal astigmatism follows the population average At significantly greater than 1.25(Ac) High internal (lenticular) astigmatism — may be from lens tilt or sclerosis At much less than 1.25(Ac) Internal astigmatism is compensating the corneal component — residual very low Ac present but At = 0 Corneal and internal astigmatism perfectly cancelling — unusual; verify Van Herick Anterior Chamber Angle Grading Slit beam at 60° to the cornea; compare SHADOW width (AC depth) to OPTIC SECTION width (corneal thickness) Grade 4: Shadow ≥ 1/2 corneal thickness → Ratio 1:1 → Open angle → Safe Grade 3: Shadow = 1/4 to 1/2 corneal thickness → Ratio 1:2 → Open angle → Safe Grade 2: Shadow = 1/4 corneal thickness → Ratio 1:4 → Narrow angle → Caution Grade 1: Shadow < 1/4 corneal thickness → < 1:4 → At risk for angle closure Grade 0: No shadow (cornea \\\"sits\\\" on iris) → Angle closed → Angle closure attack What it states in plain language: The Van Herick technique compares the depth of the anterior chamber angle at the limbus to the thickness of the cornea, using the shadow formed between the corneal and iris reflex beams. A deeper AC angle means a lower risk of angle-closure glaucoma. Clinical use: Grades 0–1: dilating eye drops are CONTRAINDICATED (risk of precipitating angle closure) Grade 2: dilate with caution and monitor Grades 3–4: dilating drops are generally safe Cross-subject connections: G3 (DPA): Every DPA examination requires an anterior chamber angle assessment. Van Herick Grade 0–1 = contraindication to dilation. E4 (Emergencies): Acute angle closure glaucoma presents as Grade 0 on Van Herick — halos, pain, elevated IOP, shallow AC.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Slit Lamp — 6 Illumination Techniques TECHNIQUE ANGLE BEAM WIDTH FILTER BEST FOR 1. Diffuse 30–45° Wide (open) Diffusing General overview: lids, conj, CL centration 2. Direct (optic 30–45° Narrow (slit) None Corneal layers, depth of foreign body, AC section) 3. Direct 30–45° ~3mm None Corneal stroma, epithelial defects, CL surface (parallelepiped) 4. Indirect 30–45° Moderate None Corneal microcysts, vacuoles (light from side) 5. Retro Variable Parallelepiped None Neovascularization, edema; CL deposits (iris reflex) illumination 6. Specular 60° Parallelepiped None Endothelial cell morphology; tear lipid layer reflection FILTERED : Cobalt blue (+wratten #12) → Fluorescein staining pattern Red-free → Blood vessel detail, neovascularization Slit Lamp Examination Routine SETUP : 1. Focus eyepieces 2. Adjust headrest (chin rest height + forehead band) 3. Position fixation target 4. Decrease room illumination ANTERIOR SEGMENT SCAN (broad to specific): 1. Lids and lashes (diffuse illumination) 2. Bulbar conjunctiva → palpebral conjunctiva 3. Limbus 4. Cornea (optic section for thickness; parallelepiped for stroma/endothelium) 5. Anterior chamber (Van Herick at temporal limbus) 6. Iris 7. Crystalline lens Direct vs Indirect Ophthalmoscopy — Side-by-Side FEATURE DIRECT INDIRECT (Monocular) INDIRECT (Binocular) Image type Virtual, erect Real, inverted Real, inverted Magnification ~15x ~5–7x ~1.5–4.5x Field of view 6.5° (~2 DD) ~20–25° 40–75° (~8 DD) Stereo depth None None Yes (binocular) Working distance Close to patient Arm's length Arm's length Mydriatic needed? Little needed Very preferable Very preferable Best for Optic disc detail Peripheral retina Peripheral retina + stereo Condensing lens None +14D to +30D +14D or +20D Higher lens power — Smaller field, less Smaller field, less magnif. magnification Keratometry Procedure 1. Focus eyepiece 2. Adjust instrument to patient (height, chin rest) 3. Center light on patient's cornea 4. Align instrument to patient's visual axis 5. Instruct patient to look at center of mire 6. Identify the PRIMARY MERIDIAN (meridian closest to 180°; read by plus mire signs) 7. Read the primary meridian power 8. Rotate 90° to SECONDARY MERIDIAN (read by minus mire signs) 9. Read the secondary meridian power 10. Record: \\\"Power at meridian / Power at meridian\\\" Example: R: 42.00 @ 180 / 43.00 @ 90 INTERPRETATION : WTR corneal astigmatism: weakest meridian at or near 180° (axis of minus correcting cylinder at 180°) ATR corneal astigmatism: weakest meridian at or near 90° (axis of minus correcting cylinder at 90°) Oblique: principal meridians between 30–60° or 120–150° CALCULATE CORNEAL ASTIGMATISM : Ac = Difference between two K readings Example: 43.00 − 42.00 = 1.00D at 180° ( WTR ) APPLY JAVAL 'S RULE TO PREDICT TOTAL ASTIGMATISM : At = 1.25(Ac) + (−0.50 Cyl × 90°) Opacity Parallax in Direct Ophthalmoscopy Move ophthalmoscope LEFT , observe opacity movement: Opacity moves OPPOSITE to scope → Anterior opacity (cornea, anterior lens) → The farther anterior, the greater the extent of apparent motion No apparent movement → Opacity at or near lens nucleus Opacity moves SAME direction → Posterior opacity (posterior lens or vitreous) → Vitreous opacity: floats back to original position when scope stops Instruct patient to move eye: Anterior opacity → moves in SAME direction as eye Posterior opacity → moves in OPPOSITE direction to eye\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-the-biomicroscope-systems-optics-and-settings\",\"heading\":\"The Biomicroscope — Systems, Optics, and Settings\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Most notes teach what the slit lamp shows you. This section teaches how the instrument itself is built and how you drive it, because that is exactly what procedure-style drills test and it rarely appears in finding-based reviewers. Three systems make up the slit lamp: Illumination system — the light source, condenser, slit aperture, and filters. This is what you tilt to create the beam. Observation (viewing) system — the microscope: eyepieces, magnification changer, and objective. This is what you look through. Mechanical system — the joystick, the base that slides on the table, the chin/forehead rest, and the patient-positioning frame. The light source is part of the illumination system, not the mechanical one. Two illumination brands, sorted by where the lamp sits: ILLUMINATION SOURCE LOCATION Haag-Streit ──── light comes from the TOP (bulb above, mirror sends beam down) Zeiss ────────── light comes from the BASE (bulb below) Two viewing (microscope) designs, sorted by how you change power: MAGNIFICATION CHANGER Greenough (converging tubes) ── magnification changed by a drum/lever (continuous feel) Galilean (telescopic) ───────── magnification changed by flipping fixed telescopes in/out (stepped) (Board framing keys the \\\"lever to change magnification\\\" to the Greenough system; the Galilean changes power in discrete flip steps. Know both — the drill just wants the Greenough/Galilean split.) The magnifier optics — two lenses set the range: Eyepiece (ocular) lens ──── +10 D Objective lens ─────────── +22 D Rule: high magnification → SMALLER (decreased) field of view, and less depth of focus Suggested working magnification, by what you are looking at: STRUCTURE MAGNIFICATION Ocular adnexa ───────────── 6x (low power, wide survey) Lids and lashes ─────────── 6x–10x Cornea ──────────────────── 16x Van Herick angle estimate ─ 16x (illumination arm at 60°, gray/diffuser filter OFF ) Iris ────────────────────── 16x Anterior chamber (cells/flare) 25x–40x (room fully DARK ) Alignment and scanning technique — the steps a drill will quiz: Set the illumination arm to 0° (coaxial with the microscope) before focusing when you use the focusing rod/bar. Scan left to right , and view the lids and lashes in sections — not in one quick sweep (you miss the lid margin, meibomian orifices, and lash bases otherwise). Dim the overhead room light — do not switch it fully off for the whole exam (you still need some light to position the patient and instrument); the room goes fully dark only for the anterior-chamber cell/flare check. To read the cornea , remove the filter so you have full white light on the tissue. To evert the upper lid , create the crease above the tarsal plate (press at the superior tarsal border while the patient looks down). Anterior chamber — cells vs flare (the Tyndall pair): Beam in a dark room, high mag, small bright square in the AC: FLARE ─── haze/\\\"headlight-in-fog\\\" ─── PROTEIN leaked into aqueous CELLS ── discrete floating dots ───── inflammatory white blood cells Van Herick estimates the angle ; the cell/flare check estimates active inflammation . If the Van Herick beam is set at less than 60° , it underestimates the true angle.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Direct vs Indirect Ophthalmoscopy Feature Direct Indirect Image Virtual, erect Real, inverted Magnification ~15x 2–5x (binocular); 5–7x (monocular) Field of view ~6.5° / 2 disc diameters ~40° / 8 disc diameters (binocular) Stereopsis No Yes (binocular indirect) Mydriasis needed Little Strongly preferred Technique difficulty Easy Difficult Best for Optic disc, macula detail Peripheral retina, media opacities Board clue \\\"upright virtual image\\\" \\\"inverted real image\\\" Slit Lamp Illumination — Key Distinctions Technique Angle What it shows Board clue Diffuse 30–45° Overview, lids, CL centration Wide beam + diffuser Optic section 30–45° Corneal layers separately Narrowest beam Parallelepiped 30–45° Stroma volume, CL surface ~3mm width Retro illumination Variable Edema, neovascularization Light from iris/fundus reflex Specular reflection 60° Endothelial cells, tear lipid Angle of incidence = angle of reflection Van Herick 60° Anterior chamber depth Compare shadow to optic section width WTR vs ATR Corneal Astigmatism Feature With-the-Rule (WTR) Against-the-Rule (ATR) Steep meridian Near 90° (vertical) Near 180° (horizontal) Minus cylinder axis At or near 180° At or near 90° More common in Young patients Elderly patients Correction −X cyl × 180 (or +X cyl × 90) −X cyl × 90 (or +X cyl × 180) Board clue \\\"steep at 90°; correcting cyl axis at 180°\\\" \\\"steep at 180°; correcting cyl axis at 90°\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Direct ophthalmoscopy magnification ~15x Virtual, erect image Direct ophthalmoscopy field of view ~6.5° (~2 disc diameters) Undilated; wider dilated Indirect ophthalmoscopy magnification 2–5x (monocular); 1.5–4.5x (binocular) Inverted, real image Indirect field of view (binocular) ~40–75° (~8 disc diameters) Much wider than direct Condensing lens powers (indirect) +14D and +20D most common; +14D to +30D range Higher power = wider field, less magnification Normal optic disc diameter 1.5–1.7mm Oval or round; sharp margins Normal A:V ratio (fundus) Arteries:Veins = 2:3 (vein larger) Veins darker, more tortuous Van Herick Grade 4 Shadow ≥ 1/2 corneal thickness (1:1) Open angle; safe to dilate Van Herick Grade 2 Shadow = 1/4 corneal thickness (1:4) Narrow; caution Van Herick Grade 0 No shadow Closed angle; do NOT dilate Normal K reading range 40–47D (average ~43–44D) Outside range: investigate Normal corneal astigmatism ≤1.00D (most common) Higher = clinically significant Javal's rule scaling factor 1.25 Multiplied by Ac Javal's internal astigmatism constant −0.50 Cyl × 90° Fixed ATR component Zeiss slit lamp: light source location Base of instrument Haag-Streit slit lamp: light source location Top of instrument Slit lamp eyepiece (ocular) lens power +10 D Fixed magnifier Slit lamp objective lens power +22 D Fixed magnifier Magnification: ocular adnexa 6x Low-power survey Magnification: lids and lashes 6x–10x View in sections, not one sweep Magnification: cornea 16x Full light, filter removed Magnification: Van Herick angle 16x Arm at 60°, filter OFF Magnification: iris 16x Magnification: anterior chamber (cells/flare) 25x–40x Room fully dark Van Herick illumination angle 60° <60° underestimates the angle Aqueous FLARE Protein in aqueous Tyndall haze Aqueous CELLS Inflammatory white blood cells Discrete floating dots Cobalt blue filter Used with fluorescein Visualizes corneal staining Red-free filter Enhances blood vessels Blood vessels appear very dark\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Ophthalmoscopy image characteristics: DIVE for Direct: D irect = I mage V irtual and E rect (upright) Indirect = inverted real (opposite of direct on both counts) Magnification vs field of view in indirect: \\\"Higher lens power = Wider field, Weaker magnification\\\" — think of a fisheye camera lens: wider angle = smaller objects Slit lamp illumination angle rules: Most techniques: 30–45° between illumination and microscope Specular reflection and Van Herick: 60° (angle of incidence = angle of reflection) Which brand's lamp is where — \\\"HAAG hangs high\\\": Haag -Streit = light from the top (hangs high); Zeiss = light from the base (down at zero/base). Slit lamp lens powers — \\\"10 in, 22 out\\\": Eye p iece = + 10 D (the one you peer through); objective = + 22 D (the one facing the patient). Magnification ladder — \\\"6 outside, 16 middle, 40 deepest\\\": 6x for the outside (adnexa, lids) → 16x for the middle layers (cornea, iris, Van Herick) → 25–40x for the deepest, dimmest job (anterior chamber cells and flare). Flare vs cells — \\\"Flare = Fluid protein, Cells = inflammatory Cells\\\": F lare = F og of leaked protein ; cells = discrete floating white blood cells. Both read in a fully dark room at high mag. Javal's rule shorthand: At = 1.25(Ac) − 0.50 × 90 Think: \\\"Multiply by 1.25, then subtract a quarter diopter of ATR internally.\\\" WTR vs ATR memory: W ith-the-rule = W alls have it (most young eyes): steep vertical = cyl axis horizontal (180°) A gainst-the-rule = A ged: steep horizontal = cyl axis vertical (90°) Normal fundus values: Disc = 1.5–1.7mm, round/oval, sharp margins, red-yellow, cup at center Veins darker, more tortuous, pulsating; arteries lighter, straighter, reflex stripe V:A ratio = 3:2 (veins are the larger number) Fovea appears darker than surrounding retina\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"OBJECTIVE EXAMINATION — OVERVIEW 1. SLIT LAMP BIOMICROSCOPY Diffuse illumination → General overview Optic section (narrow) → Corneal layers cross-section Parallelepiped (3mm) → Corneal volume, endothelium Indirect illumination → Microcysts, vacuoles Retro illumination → Neovascularization, edema Specular reflection (60°) → Endothelial cells Van Herick (60°) → Anterior chamber angle 2. OPHTHALMOSCOPY Direct Upright Virtual Image 15x 6.5° Close to patient Indirect Inverted Real Image 2-5x 40° Arm's length + condensing lens NORMAL FUNDUS : Disc ──────── round/oval, 1.5–1.7mm, red-yellow, sharp margins Vessels ───── V:A = 3:2; arteries lighter/straight; veins darker/tortuous Fovea ─────── darker than surroundings, avascular zone at center Background ── orange-red (choroidal); tessellated if sparse RPE 3. KERATOMETRY Cornea acts as convex mirror → mire image size → radius → power Record: 42.00 @ 180 / 43.00 @ 90 Flat K / Steep K Corneal astigmatism (Ac) = difference between two K readings = 1.00D Javal's Rule: At = 1.25 (Ac) + (−0.50 Cyl × 90°) At = 1.25 (−1.00 × 180) + (−0.50 × 90) = (−1.25 × 180) + (−0.50 × 90) = −0.75 × 180 (after resolving the cross-cylinder combination) 4. RETINOSCOPY (see C2-01 for full coverage) Gross finding → subtract working distance correction → Net finding 67cm WD: subtract 1.50D | 50cm WD: subtract 2.00D\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Trap 1: \\\"Direct ophthalmoscopy gives an inverted image.\\\" Trap 2: \\\"A stronger condensing lens in indirect gives better magnification.\\\" Trap 3: \\\"Van Herick Grade 0 means no anterior chamber.\\\" Trap 4: \\\"Javal's rule only applies to WTR astigmatism.\\\" Trap 5: \\\"The slit lamp cobalt blue filter is used for blood vessel examination.\\\" Trap 6: \\\"In opacity parallax, an anterior opacity moves in the same direction as the ophthalmoscope.\\\" Trap 7: \\\"The keratometer measures total corneal power.\\\" Trap 8: \\\"The light source is part of the slit lamp's mechanical system.\\\" Trap 9: \\\"Higher magnification gives you a bigger field of view.\\\" Trap 10: \\\"Flare and cells are the same anterior-chamber finding.\\\" Trap 11: \\\"Keep the overhead light off for the whole slit lamp exam.\\\" Trap 12: \\\"Sweep the lids and lashes once and move on.\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Direct ophthalmoscopy image Virtual, erect, ~15x, ~6.5° field Indirect ophthalmoscopy image Real, inverted, 2–5x, ~40° field Higher condensing lens power Wider field, LESS magnification Best for peripheral retina Indirect ophthalmoscopy Best for optic disc detail Direct ophthalmoscopy Van Herick: grade for safe dilation Grade 3 or 4 Van Herick: do NOT dilate Grade 0–1 Van Herick: angle at 60° Compare shadow to optic section Slit lamp at 60° (two uses) Specular reflection AND Van Herick Normal K reading ~40–47D (average 43–44D) WTR corneal astigmatism minus axis At or near 180° ATR corneal astigmatism minus axis At or near 90° Javal's rule At = 1.25(Ac) + (−0.50 Cyl × 90°) Internal astigmatism constant −0.50 Cyl × 90° (ATR direction) Cobalt blue filter use Fluorescein staining of cornea Red-free filter use Blood vessel visualization Opacity parallax: anterior Moves OPPOSITE to scope direction Opacity parallax: posterior Moves SAME direction as scope Zeiss slit lamp light source At base Haag-Streit slit lamp light source At top Greenough vs Galilean microscope Greenough = drum/lever; Galilean = flip steps Slit lamp eyepiece / objective power +10 D / +22 D Magnification: adnexa / lids 6x / 6–10x Magnification: cornea / iris / Van Herick 16x Magnification: anterior chamber 25–40x (dark room) Higher magnification effect Smaller field of view Aqueous flare vs cells Flare = protein; cells = WBCs Normal V:A ratio (fundus vessels) 3:2 (veins larger) Normal optic disc diameter 1.5–1.7mm\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"1. A 55-year-old patient has keratometry readings of OD: 43.50 @ 180 / 45.50 @ 90. Using Javal's rule, what is the expected total (refractive) astigmatism? A. −2.00 Cyl × 180° B. −2.00 Cyl × 90° C. −2.00 Cyl × 180° combined with internal correction D. −2.00 Cyl × 180° (Ac = 2.00D; At ≈ −2.00D WTR) Answer Working: Ac = 45.50 − 43.50 = 2.00D. Weakest meridian is at 180° → Ac = −2.00 Cyl × 180° (WTR). At = 1.25(−2.00 × 180) + (−0.50 × 90) = (−2.50 × 180) + (−0.50 × 90) = This cross-cylinder combination: resolves to −2.00 Cyl × 180° approximately. Working through the cross-cylinder: −2.50 Cyl × 180 = −2.50 Cyl × 180; and −0.50 × 90 partially cancels the WTR component. The net total astigmatism is approximately −2.00 Cyl × 180° . D is correct. The internal astigmatism (−0.50 × 90°) partially cancels the WTR corneal component in Javal's rule, reducing the predicted total slightly from 2.50D to ~2.00D. 2. During slit lamp examination of a patient being evaluated for dilation, the Van Herick shadow width appears equal to about one-quarter of the corneal optic section width. Which of the following actions is most appropriate? A. Proceed with dilation — the angle is wide open B. Dilate with caution and monitor for angle closure C. Do not dilate — the angle is closed D. Measure IOP before deciding, then dilate freely if normal Answer B. Dilate with caution and monitor for angle closure. A shadow width equal to 1/4 of the corneal optic section width corresponds to Van Herick Grade 2 (ratio 1:4). This indicates a narrow anterior chamber angle — not closed, but at risk. Dilation is not absolutely contraindicated but must be done with caution, the patient should be monitored, and the IOP checked after dilation. Grade 0–1 = absolute contraindication. Grades 3–4 = safe to dilate. Grade 2 = proceed with caution. 3. Which of the following is NOT part of the slit lamp's mechanical system? A. Joystick B. Light source C. Motorized table D. Patient-positioning frame Answer B. Light source. The light source belongs to the ILLUMINATION system (source, condenser, slit, filters). The mechanical system moves and steadies the instrument and patient: the joystick, the sliding/motorized base and table, and the positioning frame (chin and forehead rest). Watch for this \\\"which is NOT mechanical\\\" phrasing — the light source is the trap answer. 4. You need to survey a patient's ocular adnexa, then examine the cornea, then check the anterior chamber for cells and flare. Which magnification progression is most appropriate? A. 40x → 16x → 6x B. 6x → 16x → 25–40x C. 16x → 16x → 16x D. 25x → 6x → 40x Answer B. 6x → 16x → 25–40x. Adnexa is a wide low-power survey ( 6x ), the cornea is a middle-layer view ( 16x ), and cells/flare in the anterior chamber need the highest magnification in a fully dark room ( 25–40x ). Remember: higher magnification always means a smaller field of view, so you start low to find the target and zoom in for detail. The Van Herick angle estimate sits in the middle at 16x with the arm at 60°. 5. On slit lamp exam in a dark room, the beam through the anterior chamber shows a hazy \\\"headlight-in-fog\\\" glow with no discrete particles. What does this indicate? A. Inflammatory white blood cells (cells) B. Protein leaked into the aqueous (flare) C. Pigment on the corneal endothelium D. A closed anterior chamber angle Answer B. Protein leaked into the aqueous (flare). Flare is the Tyndall haze of leaked protein — a diffuse glow with no distinct particles. CELLS are discrete floating white blood cells that look like dust in a sunbeam. Flare = protein; cells = inflammatory cells. Both are assessed at high magnification (25–40x) in a fully dark room. This is separate from Van Herick, which grades the angle, not inflammation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4-01-objective-examination-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C4-01 — Objective Examination\",\"text\":\"The rule: Close the note before picking up the pen. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"C4 — Objective Examination\\\" at the top. 5-minute timer. Dump: the 6 slit lamp illumination techniques with their angles and what they show; the key differences between direct and indirect ophthalmoscopy; Van Herick grades 0–4; Javal's rule formula. What to brain dump: All 6 slit lamp illumination techniques with angle, beam width, and best use Direct vs indirect ophthalmoscopy: image type, magnification, field of view Javal's rule written out in full with all variables defined Drill 2 — Blank Diagram or Table Reproduce the Direct vs Indirect ophthalmoscopy comparison table from memory. All rows. Then reproduce the Van Herick grading table (Grade 0–4) with shadow:section ratio and clinical implication for each grade. What to reproduce: The two comparison tables — ophthalmoscopy and Van Herick grading. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write 4 sentences explaining why an indirect ophthalmoscope sees the peripheral retina better than a direct ophthalmoscope — without using the words \\\"magnification\\\" or \\\"field of view\\\" until the last sentence. Teach-back prompt: \\\"Explain why a retinal surgeon uses indirect ophthalmoscopy for a peripheral retinal detachment repair, not the small instrument that clips on the ophthalmoscope head.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front (Question) Back (Answer) Direct ophthalmoscopy image type Virtual, erect Indirect ophthalmoscopy image type Real, inverted Direct magnification ~15x Indirect field of view (binocular) ~40° / 8 disc diameters Higher condensing lens power → Wider field, less magnification Van Herick Grade 0 Angle closed; do NOT dilate Van Herick Grade 2 (ratio) Shadow = 1/4 corneal section (1:4) Van Herick Grade 4 (ratio) Shadow ≥ 1/2 corneal section (1:1) Javal's rule At = 1.25(Ac) + (−0.50 Cyl × 90°) Cobalt blue filter use Fluorescein staining Red-free filter use Blood vessel visualization Specular reflection angle 60° Anterior opacity parallax Moves OPPOSITE to scope Normal V:A ratio (fundus) 3:2 (veins larger/darker) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete keratometry procedure from instrument setup to recording the corneal astigmatism and applying Javal's rule — in numbered steps, without looking. Sequence to write: Keratometry from eyepiece focus → patient alignment → primary meridian → secondary meridian → record K readings → compute Ac → apply Javal's rule → record predicted At. Recall Interval Schedule for This Note Session When What to do 1st review Same day you write it Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Next day Blank Diagram + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review 1 week later Full Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check 2 weeks later Attempt all 5 drills; flag anything shaky\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Subjective refraction is how you find a prescription by asking the patient \\\"which is clearer?\\\" You can't see what the patient sees, so you use lenses to move the image around the retina, then let the patient report back. The whole method rests on one trick: fog the eye first by adding enough plus power so accommodation shuts down, then slowly reduce that plus until you reach the clearest lens possible. After getting the best monocular lens for each eye, you balance the two eyes so neither is working harder accommodatively than the other. Then, in the OEP system, the result of that subjective refraction (Test #7) feeds directly into 14 more tests that map the full accommodation-convergence relationship. Teaching angle: Ask the class: if you gave a patient the sharpest possible prescription right now, why might they still get headaches at near? (Because accommodation was engaged during refraction, pulling the endpoint toward too much minus. Fogging prevents this.)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Why fog the eye before starting? Because accommodation is an involuntary reflex to blur. If the retinal image is blurred, the ciliary muscle contracts to clear it. If accommodation is active, your refraction will find a lens that corrects blur plus the error introduced by the contracting ciliary muscle. The prescription ends up over-minused. Why does plus power relax accommodation? Plus moves the focal point in front of the retina, making the eye artificially myopic. There is no blur behind the retina, so no signal to accommodate. The ciliary muscle relaxes. Why does the astigmatic dial work at all? An uncorrected astigmatic eye has two principal meridians that focus at different distances. A fan chart line running parallel to the steeper meridian (power meridian) forms a sharp line on the retina while the perpendicular line stays blurred. The darkest line you see is pointing toward the power meridian. Why must the eye be slightly under-fogged for the JCC test? The JCC is a comparison test. Position 1 and Position 2 both have to be visible. If the eye is over-fogged, both positions look equally blurred and the patient cannot give a meaningful preference. The underfog keeps the contrast just detectable enough to compare. Why balance binocularly after monocular refraction? Monocular refraction finds the best lens for each eye independently, but the eyes don't work independently. After the occluder comes off, binocular vision can shift the accommodative state of both eyes toward whichever eye was left with more residual accommodation. Binocular balance removes that asymmetry before the final prescription is set.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Subjective refraction Latin subjectivus (observer-dependent) Refraction based on patient response, not direct measurement Fogging English: to cloud or obscure Deliberate over-plussing to blur the image and relax accommodation Defogging Removing the fog Reducing plus (or adding minus) after astigmatic correction is set MPMVA Most Plus / Minimum Minus Visual Acuity The endpoint: highest plus (lowest minus) that still gives best VA JCC Jackson Cross-Cylinder (after Edward Jackson, 1907) A lens with equal and opposite plus/minus cylinders at 90° to each other Duochrome / Bichrome Greek duo (two) + chroma (color) Two-color test based on chromatic aberration; bichrome = binocular version TIB Turville Infinity Balance Binocular balance technique using a septum to separate each eye's field OEP Optometric Extension Program The 21-step phorometric protocol that maps accommodation and convergence PRA Positive Relative Accommodation Maximum accommodation that can be stimulated at 40cm (#20) NRA Negative Relative Accommodation Maximum accommodation that can be inhibited at 40cm (#21) Lookalike trap: \\\"Bichrome\\\" and \\\"duochrome\\\" are often used interchangeably in Filipino optometry texts. In the PCO reviewer, \\\"bichrome\\\" refers specifically to the binocular balancing version using colored filters; \\\"duochrome\\\" is the monocular sphere refinement version. Same physics, different application.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"The trigger: You need the patient's static refractive error — the refractive state with zero accommodation. Monocular sequence: Occlude the non-test eye. Present the Snellen chart. If the patient can read the top letter, add plus until that letter blurs. If the patient cannot read it at all, add minus until they reach 20/30, then add +0.50 to +0.75D to re-fog to 20/30–20/40. Present the astigmatic dial (fan chart). The darkest line = power meridian. Axis = 90° from the darkest line. Add minus cylinder with axis perpendicular to the darkest line, in 0.25D steps. For every −0.50D cylinder added, add +0.25D sphere to keep the interval of Sturm centered on the retina. Stop when all lines appear equally dark. Confirm cylinder axis: JCC with handle parallel to the tentative axis. Flip. Rotate toward the red dot if patient prefers Position 1, toward the white dot if they prefer Position 2. Stop at equality. Refine cylinder power: JCC with red or white dot parallel to the axis. If patient prefers Position 1 (red dot || axis), add minus. If patient prefers Position 2, reduce minus. Stop at equality. Defog: reduce plus (or add minus) in 0.25D steps until best VA is reached. Sphere refinement: duochrome test. Equal = done. Green clearer = reduce minus or add plus. Red clearer = add minus or reduce plus. Record: monocular best VA + MPMVA. Key players: Ciliary muscle: contracts during accommodation; fogging inactivates it Astigmatic dial (fan chart): externalizes the interval of Sturm so it is visible to the patient JCC: flips between deliberate over- and under-correction states so the patient can locate the neutral point Duochrome target: uses the eye's chromatic aberration as a built-in reference signal\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Theory: Chromatic Aberration — the mechanism behind the Duochrome test Shorter wavelength (green, ~550 nm) → refracted more → focuses closer to lens Longer wavelength (red, ~650 nm) → refracted less → focuses farther from lens Gap between red and green focal points ≈ 0.50D in the human eye What it states in plain language: Light of different colors bends by different amounts when it passes through a refractive medium. The cornea and lens behave the same way, so red and green light focus at different depths inside the eye. The duochrome test puts a known focal-point gap to clinical use. What each part means: Green (shorter wavelength, ~550 nm): bends more, focuses in front of the retina in an emmetropic eye Red (longer wavelength, ~650 nm): bends less, focuses behind the retina in an emmetropic eye The gap between these two focal points is approximately 0.50D When the prescribed lens is correct, the retina sits between the two focal points, so both colors appear equally sharp Where it comes from: Newton described chromatic dispersion in 1672. In clinical refraction, the duochrome test was designed to detect whether a sphere prescription is above or below the neutral point by exploiting the fixed 0.50D red-green focal gap. If you know which color focuses where, you can tell which side of the retina the focal point has fallen on. The analogy: Think of red and green photons as two runners going through the same race course (the cornea and lens). The lighter runner (green) brakes earlier and stops closer to the start. The heavier runner (red) carries more momentum and travels farther before stopping. You cannot move the runners, but you can move the finish line (the retina, via lenses) until both runners stop at the same place. That is the sphere endpoint. Why this form and not another: If red and green focused at the same point, there would be no differential signal and the test would be useless. A fixed 0.50D gap is clinically useful: large enough to detect with acuity-based comparison, small enough that the endpoint does not introduce its own error. A larger gap would force a coarser correction step. What it does NOT explain: Patients with red-green color vision deficiency cannot distinguish the two channels. The test is unreliable in this population. The test assumes the eye is near the neutral point. A heavily fogged eye will show red clearer regardless of sphere power — fogging pulls the focal point in front of the retina, so the red channel wins by default. The test is only valid after fog is reduced to the working level. Cross-subject connections: Physiological Optics (B4): Color perception relies on trichromatic channel separation. The duochrome test uses only two channels — red and green — which is why the test fails in red-green color blindness (protanopia, deuteranopia). Theoretical Optics (D1): Achromatic doublet lens design minimizes this same chromatic aberration that the duochrome test quantifies. In optics, it is corrected; in refraction, it is used as a tool. Reading the Result: Result What it means Action Green clearer Focal point in front of retina (over-minused or under-plussed) Reduce minus or add plus Red clearer Focal point behind retina (under-minused or over-plussed) Add minus or reduce plus Equal clarity Focal point straddling the retina Endpoint reached (MPMVA) No equality point reachable Accommodation still active; or anisometropia Re-fog; if still unresolvable, leave green slightly clearer Board trap: \\\"Green clearer\\\" in a myope does not mean they need more minus. It means the focal point is already in front of the retina — they need less minus. Confusing the direction of the correction is the most common duochrome error. Device / Rule: Jackson Cross-Cylinder (JCC) JCC (±0.25D version): +0.25 cyl × 90 crossed with −0.25 cyl × 180 Optical equivalents: = +0.25S −0.50 cyl × 180 = −0.25S +0.50 cyl × 90 What it states in plain language: The JCC is a lens with equal plus cylinder in one axis and equal minus cylinder in the perpendicular axis. Flipping it swaps which axis gets the plus and which gets the minus. This creates two comparison states — a deliberate overcorrection and a deliberate undercorrection — with the sphere equivalent held constant. The patient compares the two and reports which is clearer. What each part means: Red dots mark the minus cylinder axis of the JCC lens White dots mark the plus cylinder axis of the JCC lens Position 1 (red dot parallel to tentative axis): JCC minus cylinder is aligned with the patient's tentative axis = overcorrection + added fog Position 2 (white dot parallel to tentative axis): JCC plus cylinder is aligned with the patient's tentative axis = undercorrection + less fog Equality between positions = the tentative cylinder power or axis is correct Where it comes from: Edward Jackson designed the lens in 1907 to replace the method of repeatedly changing cylinders in a trial frame to find the optimum. His insight was that a single flip of a pre-built compound lens creates the two comparison states needed, without disturbing the rest of the prescription. The analogy: Imagine you are trying to find the exact position of a balance point on a plank. You shift 3 cm to the left, then 3 cm to the right. If the plank tips equally in both directions, you are already on the balance point. If it tips more to the right when you shift right, you need to move the balance point rightward. The JCC applies this logic to cylinder power and axis — a small over/under flip around the current setting until the two responses are equal. Why this form and not another: The equal-and-opposite powers (e.g., both sides ±0.25D) are intentional. If the plus and minus components were unequal, flipping the lens would also shift the mean spherical equivalent, adding a confounding variable. The equal design keeps the spherical equivalent constant across both positions so that only the cylinder is being compared. What it does NOT explain: JCC is unreliable when VA is worse than 20/30. At that acuity level, the patient cannot perceive the contrast difference between the two positions. Irregular astigmatism cannot be corrected by any cylindrical lens, so JCC findings in that population are meaningless. Uncooperative or indecisive patients will produce inconsistent results. Cross-subject connections: Contact Lenses (D3): Toric contact lens axis refinement uses the same over-rotate / under-rotate comparison logic as the JCC axis check. The principle is identical; only the instrument differs. Binocular Vision (B5): Accommodative convergence responds to the sphere equivalent of whatever lens is in front of the eye. Because the JCC flips change the sphere equivalent by 0.50D between positions, a patient with high AC/A may show phoria changes during the test — the JCC can inadvertently probe binocular function. Reading the Result: Comparison Interpretation Action Axis check: prefer Position 1 (red axis) Axis must rotate toward the red dot Rotate axis clockwise/CCW toward red Axis check: prefer Position 2 (white axis) Axis must rotate toward the white dot Rotate axis toward white Axis check: equal Axis is correct Proceed to power check Power check: prefer Position 1 (red axis) Cylinder is under-powered Add −0.25D cyl steps; add +0.25D sphere per −0.50D cyl added Power check: prefer Position 2 (white axis) Cylinder is over-powered Reduce minus cylinder in 0.25D steps Power check: equal Cylinder power is correct Proceed to elimination of fog Board trap: The JCC setup is different for axis vs. power checks. Axis check: handle parallel to the tentative axis. Power check: red or white dot parallel to the axis. Mixing these up gives the wrong type of adjustment.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Monocular subjective refraction — decision tree: Occlude OS. Present Snellen. | v Can patient read 20/400? YES NO | | Add + to blur it Add − until 20/30 | | +----------+---------------+ | v IDEAL FOG : Add +0.50 to +0.75D above best sphere Target acuity: 20/30–20/40 | v Present Astigmatic Dial (Fan Chart) | Lines equally dark? YES NO | | No astigmatism Darkest line = power meridian Go to defogging Axis = 90° from darkest line | v Add − cyl, axis perpendicular to darkest line Add +0.25D sphere per −0.50D cyl added Stop when all lines equally dark | v JCC Axis Check (handle || tentative axis) Rotate toward red dot preference → equality | v JCC Power Check (red or white dot || axis) Add/reduce − cyl → equality | v DEFOG : reduce plus toward minus in 0.25D steps Stop at best VA | v Sphere Refinement: Duochrome test Goal: equal (or green-side endpoint) | v Record: Monocular VA + MPMVA Repeat for OS | v Binocular Balance Binocular balance — methods compared: After monocular Rx for both eyes: | v Add +0.50 to +0.75D to BOTH eyes (re-fog binocularly) Target: 20/30 line | v Choose dissociation method: ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │ TIB (Turville Infinity Balance) │ │ Septum divides the mirror — OD sees one field, OS other │ │ Peripheral fusion maintained (most physiologic) │ │ │ │ Prism Dissociation │ │ 3Δ BD OD / 3Δ BU OS — creates vertical diplopia │ │ Patient compares upper (OD) vs. lower (OS) image clarity │ │ │ │ Bichrome Method │ │ Red filter OD / green filter OS — color cue separates eyes│ │ │ │ Alternate Occlusion (least reliable) │ │ Cover one eye at a time; simple but breaks binocularity │ └── ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ | v Ask: \\\"Are they equal?\\\" OR \\\"Which is clearer?\\\" | v Equal → Reduce + to best binocular VA Not equal → Add +0.25D to the BETTER eye | v +0.25D reverses rather than equalizes? | v Let the dominant eye retain the better VA Proceed to binocular reduction OEP 21 Steps — full reference map: PRELIMINARY (C3 territory) #1 Case history #2 Entering VA FAR (20 ft / 6M) #3 Habitual phoria far [Habitual Rx] Endpoint: vertical alignment #4 Static retinoscopy 20\\\" [Hab. correction] Endpoint: neutrality #5 Dynamic retinoscopy 20\\\" [Result of #4] Endpoint: HNP (against movement) #6 Dynamic retinoscopy 40\\\" [Result of #4] Endpoint: HNP (neutral) #7 SUBJECTIVE REFRACTION [Best sphere] Endpoint: MPMVA ^ This result feeds every subsequent test #8 Induced phoria far [Test #7 Rx] Endpoint: vertical alignment #9 Advergence far [Test #7; OU: BI] Endpoint: break / recovery #10 Convergence far [Test #7; OU: BO] Endpoint: blur / break / recovery #11 Abvergence far [Test #7; OU: BI] Endpoint: break / recovery #12 Vertical phoria + duction far [Test #7] Endpoint: horiz align (phoria); break/recov (duction) NEAR (16\\\" / 40cm) #13A Hab phoria near [Habitual near Rx] Endpoint: vertical alignment #13B Induced phoria near [Gross #14A Rx] Endpoint: vertical alignment #14A Dissociated CC [Test #7; OD3BD / OS3BU ] Endpoint: equality (highest +) #14B Binocular CC [Gross #14A; no prism] Endpoint: equality (highest +) #15A Induced phoria (unfused CC) [Gross #14A] Endpoint: vertical alignment #15B Induced phoria (fused CC) [Gross #14B] Endpoint: vertical alignment #16A PRC [OU: BO] Endpoint: blur out #16B PFR [OU: BO] Endpoint: break / recovery #17A NRC [OU: BI] Endpoint: blur out #17B NFR [OU: BI] Endpoint: break / recovery #18 Vertical phoria + duction near Endpoint: break / recovery ACCOMMODATION #19 Amplitude of Accommodation [−lens added (non-presby)] Endpoint: print difficult #20 PRA [−lens added] Endpoint: blur out #21 NRA [+lens added] Endpoint: blur out ALL LATERAL PHORIA TESTS (#3, #8, #13A, #13B, #15A, #15B): Same prism setup: OD 12–15Δ BI / OS 6Δ BU\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Axis confirmation methods: Feature Rotation method JCC axis check Used when cyl power is > 0.75D Any power (required if < 0.75D) Technique Rotate cyl CW and CCW to find each blur point; average the two readings Flip JCC; rotate tentative axis toward the preferred red dot until equality Endpoint Average of CW + CCW blur angles Equality between Position 1 and Position 2 Board clue \\\"(1st reading + 2nd reading) ÷ 2\\\" in the stem = rotation method \\\"Patient prefers side with red dot\\\" in stem = rotate toward red JCC positions: Feature Position 1 Position 2 Orientation Red dots parallel to tentative axis White dots parallel to tentative axis Effect on cylinder Overcorrection of minus cyl + added fog Undercorrection of minus cyl + underfog Patient prefers this → Cylinder is under-powered; add minus Cylinder is over-powered; reduce minus Cross-cylinder tests (#14A vs. #14B): Feature #14A — Dissociated CC #14B — Binocular CC Fusion state Dissociated (OD 3Δ BD / OS 3Δ BU) Fused (binocular; no prism) What it measures Lag of accommodation under dissociated conditions Lag of accommodation under fused conditions Endpoint Equality at highest plus Equality at highest plus Board clue 14A = unfused; prisms present 14B = fused; no prism PRA vs. NRA: Feature PRA (#20) NRA (#21) Lens added Minus Plus What it measures Accommodation that can be stimulated Accommodation that can be inhibited Endpoint Blur (patient cannot clear) Blur (patient cannot clear) Normal value (approx) −2.37D +2.00D Board clue More minus = more demand = stimulate More plus = less demand = relax\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Ideal fog acuity 20/30–20/40 (1–2 lines above BVA) Too clear = under-fogged (accommodation active). Too blurred = over-fogged (astigmatic test unreliable) Ideal fog lens +0.50 to +0.75D above best sphere Standardizes the accommodative relaxation before astigmatic dial JCC strengths ±0.12, ±0.25, ±0.50D ±0.25 is the standard clinical choice Optical effect of ±0.25 JCC +0.25S = −0.50 cyl × 180 (or −0.25S = +0.50 cyl × 90) The sphere equivalent is what the patient perceives as the flip change Sphere add per cylinder +0.25D sphere per −0.50D cyl Keeps the circle of least confusion centered on the retina Binocular balance re-fog +0.50 to +0.75D to both eyes Same principle as monocular fog; applied binocularly Prism dissociation setup 3Δ BD OD / 3Δ BU OS Creates vertical separation so the patient can compare the two images independently Lateral phoria prism setup OD 12–15Δ BI / OS 6Δ BU Identical across all six lateral phoria tests (#3, #8, #13A, #13B, #15A, #15B) Phoria test distances 20ft (6M) far; 16\\\" (40cm) near These are the two standard OEP test distances OEP #7 endpoint MPMVA This result is the lens in place for all subsequent tests NRA normal +2.00D Ability to relax accommodation at 40cm PRA normal −2.37D Ability to stimulate accommodation at 40cm\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Duochrome endpoint rule (one line) \\\"Red is behind the retina — add minus to pull it forward. Green is in front — reduce minus to let it fall back.\\\" If equality cannot be reached: leave the green side slightly clearer. An endpoint slightly short of neutral is safer than over-minusing. JCC shortcut \\\"Red preferred → Red is what you want more of → more minus cylinder.\\\" \\\"White preferred → White is where you are now → less minus cylinder.\\\" OEP grouping by distance Steps 1–6: preliminary + retinoscopy (setup and objective) Step 7: the subjective (the pivot point) Steps 8–12: far binocular tests (phoria, ductions, vergences) Steps 13–18: near binocular tests (phoria, cross-cylinders, convergence reserves, vertical) Steps 19–21: accommodation tests (AA, PRA, NRA) #3 vs. #8 #3 = Habitual (no test done yet). #8 = Induced (lenses from #7 now in place). The number gap (3 to 8) reminds you that five tests had to happen first before the lens changed.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"DUOCHROME INTERPRETATION MYOPE (over-corrected): EMMETROPE : MYOPE (under-corrected): Green focal pt Retina R G focal pts Retina Retina Red focal pt [ G--R ] |retina| |R | G |retina| |retina| [ R--G ] Green closer to lens Both straddle retina Red closer to lens Green CLEARER EQUAL Red CLEARER Reduce minus Endpoint Add minus ASTIGMATIC DIAL RULE Fan chart line DARKEST = Power meridian AXIS for minus cylinder = 90° from the darkest line (perpendicular) Example: Darkest line at 60° → axis of minus cylinder = 150° JCC POSITIONS AXIS CHECK (handle || tentative axis): Position 1: red dot parallel to tentative axis Position 2: white dot parallel to tentative axis Prefer 1 → rotate toward red dot Prefer 2 → rotate toward white dot POWER CHECK (red or white dot || axis): Position 1: red dot parallel to axis Position 2: white dot parallel to axis Prefer 1 → add minus cylinder Prefer 2 → reduce minus cylinder\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures\",\"heading\":\"OEP 21 Steps — Step-by-Step Procedures\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Two general techniques run through the entire 21-step sequence. Every phoria test uses Von Graefe. Every vergence test uses a prism ramp. Everything else is a variation of adding or removing lenses until a specific endpoint appears. Von Graefe method (used in: #3, #8, #12-phoria, #13A, #13B, #15A, #15B, #18-phoria) Place the dissociating prism (OD: 12–15Δ BI) and the measuring prism (OS: 6Δ BU) in the phoropter Adjust to the correct PD (far or near depending on the test) Patient fixates the smallest readable letter at the test distance Patient sees two targets: one displaced laterally (OD, through BI) and one displaced vertically (OS, through BU), creating an upper and lower image The examiner slowly reduces the BU measuring prism while the patient watches both images Endpoint: patient reports the two images are lined up one directly above the other (vertical alignment) — no lateral offset between them Record the prism value at alignment; direction of displacement before alignment tells you the phoria type (exo vs. eso) For vertical phoria (#12, #18): the dissociating and measuring prisms are both horizontal (BU and BD), and the endpoint is horizontal alignment instead. Prism ramp / vergence build (used in: #9, #10, #11, #16A, #16B, #17A, #17B, #18-duction) Set lenses per the test requirement; both eyes ready to turn prism in the test direction (BO or BI or BU/BD) Slowly increase the prism binocularly in small steps while the patient fixates the smallest readable letter Blur endpoint: patient first reports that the target has blurred but is still single — record this value Break endpoint: patient first reports diplopia (double vision) — record this value To find recovery: slowly reduce the prism back toward zero while patient watches the two targets Recovery endpoint: patient first reports the two images merging back into one — record this value Not all tests have all three endpoints — see individual steps below\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-1-case-history\",\"heading\":\"#1 — Case History\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"(Covered in C3-01. No phoropter or lenses.) Patient reports chief complaint, history of present illness, ocular history, family history. The \\\"4 WEED components\\\" govern documentation (Why here, Existing conditions, Environmental factors, Duration/Description).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-2-entering-visual-acuity\",\"heading\":\"#2 — Entering Visual Acuity\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"(Covered in C3-01. No phoropter or lenses.) VA measured without any correction in place (entering, unaided). Pinhole check if entering VA is reduced. Records: OD, OS, OU; distance and near if relevant.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-3-habitual-lateral-phoria-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#3 — Habitual Lateral Phoria at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Habitual Rx in phoropter | Far PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: smallest readable at 20ft | Illumination: 20 ft candle Procedure (Von Graefe): Load habitual correction and set far PD Place OD: 12–15Δ BI (dissociates fusion laterally) and OS: 6Δ BU (separates images vertically) Patient fixates smallest readable letter at 20ft; reports seeing two targets at different heights Slowly reduce the BU measuring prism while patient watches both images Endpoint: patient reports the two images are vertically aligned (one directly above the other, no lateral offset) Record the phoria direction: if image was displaced nasally before alignment → esophoria; temporally → exophoria Significance: Baseline lateral muscular imbalance at far, taken before any subjective refraction is done. This is the \\\"as the patient lives\\\" phoria.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-4-static-retinoscopy-at-near-gross\",\"heading\":\"#4 — Static Retinoscopy at Near (Gross)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Habitual correction | Working distance = 20\\\" | No prisms | Target: near point card | Illumination: standard Procedure: Load habitual correction into phoropter; set near PD Position the retinoscope at 20\\\" from the patient's eyes Patient fixates on a near target placed at 20\\\" (same plane as retinoscope) Perform standard retinoscopy — neutralize the reflex by adding or reducing lenses No working distance lens subtracted (unlike distance retinoscopy) — the 20\\\" distance is the test condition itself Endpoint: neutral reflex (shadow moves with the beam until neutrality) Record Gross #4 finding; this is the starting lens for tests #5 and #6 Significance: Provides the static retinoscopy reference at near. Gross #4 minus the working distance dioptric equivalent = Net #4, used in the Reading Add calculation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-5-dynamic-retinoscopy-at-20\",\"heading\":\"#5 — Dynamic Retinoscopy at 20\\\"\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Result of #4 (Gross) in phoropter | Working distance = 20\\\" | No prisms | Target: small letters or pictures at 20\\\" | Binocular Procedure: Load Gross #4 lenses into phoropter Position at 20\\\" from the patient; patient fixates on letters or pictures at the plane of the retinoscope (patient looks, reads, and interacts with the near target — not passive fixation) Initial reflex: assumed to be with motion (accommodation is active for near target) Add plus in 0.25D steps until an against-movement reflex is obtained Then reduce plus (toward minus) in 0.25D steps until the first neutrality (HNP — Highest Neutral Point) is established Record Gross #5 (the highest plus at which the neutral point first appears) Note the near phoria at this stage — used to determine the lag value from the OEP table Significance: The HNP here indicates the limit of positive fusional convergence available at 20\\\". Gross #5 minus lag (from OEP table based on #15A phoria and AA) = Net #5. Reading Add = Net #5 minus Net #4. Lag values (from OEP table): 1 XOP = 0.12D; 2 XOP = 0.25D; 3 XOP = 0.37D; 4 XOP = 0.50D; up to 12+ XOP progressively larger lag values.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-6-dynamic-retinoscopy-at-40\",\"heading\":\"#6 — Dynamic Retinoscopy at 40\\\"\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Result of #4 (Gross) | Working distance = 40\\\" | No prisms | Target: small letters at 40\\\" Procedure: Load Gross #4 lenses; move examiner position to 40\\\" from the patient Patient fixates on a near target at 40\\\" — accommodation is still active but at lower demand than #5 Perform retinoscopy; initial reflex is neutral (accommodation is less active at this distance) HNP at this distance = the neutral point in the with-to-against transition range Record Gross #6 Net #6 = Gross #6 minus lag (0.25D if AA ≥ 5.00D) Significance: Cross-check for the near correction. The higher working distance puts less demand on accommodation, so the neutral range shifts.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-7-monocular-subjective-refraction-h-e\",\"heading\":\"#7 — Monocular Subjective Refraction (H/E)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Best sphere | Far PD | No prisms | Target: Snellen at 20ft (Full procedure is in the Monocular Subjective Refraction section above. Summary below.) Occlude one eye Establish ideal fog (+0.50 to +0.75D above best sphere; target 20/30–20/40) Astigmatic dial: find power meridian (darkest line), axis (90° from it), add minus cyl Add +0.25D sphere per −0.50D cyl added; equalize lines JCC axis check (handle || axis); JCC power check (red/white dot || axis) Defog to best VA; duochrome sphere refinement Endpoint: MPMVA — most plus / least minus at best VA Repeat for the other eye Significance: This is the pivot of the entire 21-step sequence. The result (Test #7) is the lens in place for tests #8 through #18, and the lens basis for #19–#21 in non-presbyopes.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-8-induced-lateral-phoria-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#8 — Induced Lateral Phoria at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 Rx | Far PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: smallest readable at 20ft Procedure: Identical to #3 (Von Graefe method), but with Test #7 lenses in place instead of habitual correction. Load Test #7 result into phoropter; set far PD Place OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU Patient fixates smallest readable at 20ft Reduce BU prism until vertical alignment Record phoria value Significance: Shows how the subjective refraction changes the phoria. Compare to #3: if the phoria improves (less exo or moves toward ortho), the correction is helping convergence; if it worsens, investigate the near correction further.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-9-true-adduction-advergence-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#9 — True Adduction (Advergence) at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 + auxiliary +0.25S | Far PD | OU ready to turn BO | Target: smallest readable at 20ft Procedure (prism ramp — BO direction, stops at blur): Load Test #7 + +0.25D auxiliary sphere; set far PD Place prisms OU ready to turn BO; start at zero Slowly increase BO prism binocularly while patient fixates Endpoint: blur only — stop when patient first reports the target has blurred (do NOT continue to break) The blur point equals the same level of blur produced by the +0.25D auxiliary sphere alone — this is the reference The +0.25D auxiliary sphere is added so that when the BO prism causes accommodation to be recruited (which blurs the +0.25S image), the examiner knows the patient has reached the limit of their fusional convergence reserve. The test stops at blur, not break. This makes #9 distinct from #10, which also uses BO prisms but continues to break and recovery. Significance: Blur point indicates the limit of available fusional convergence in reserve at far — the point at which accommodation would need to be recruited to maintain clarity. Compare to #10 (full BO range).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-10-convergence-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#10 — Convergence at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 | Far PD | OU ready to turn BO | Target: smallest readable at 20ft Procedure (prism ramp — BO direction): Load Test #7; set far PD; both eyes ready to turn BO Slowly increase BO prism binocularly while patient fixates First blur: record (stimulus to accommodation via convergence demand) Continue until diplopia: record break Reduce prism until single: record recovery Significance: BO vergence stimulates convergence (as if object moves closer). Blur point = fusional convergence reserve before accommodation is recruited. Break = total positive convergence reserve at far. Recovery = limit of the fusional field.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-11-abduction-abvergence-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#11 — Abduction (Abvergence) at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 | Far PD | OU ready to turn BI | Target: smallest readable at 20ft Procedure (prism ramp — BI direction): Load Test #7; set far PD; both eyes ready to turn BI Slowly increase BI prism binocularly Break (diplopia): record Reduce prism until single: record recovery No blur endpoint for #11 — BI prisms inhibit convergence and relax accommodation; there is no accommodative demand to blur the image before the break. Significance: Negative fusional convergence (divergence) reserve at far. Breakpoint = how much convergence can be relaxed at distance before fusion fails.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-12-vertical-phoria-and-duction-at-far\",\"heading\":\"#12 — Vertical Phoria and Duction at Far\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 | Far PD | Prisms ready to turn BU and BD | Target: smallest readable at 20ft Two parts: phoria measurement, then duction measurement. Vertical phoria (Von Graefe variant): Place horizontal dissociating prism (BI or BO) before one eye and measuring prism (BU or BD) before the other Patient fixates target; sees two images horizontally separated Adjust measuring prism until images are horizontally aligned (one beside the other, no vertical offset) Record: right/left hyperphoria, or orthophoria Vertical duction: Same setup; prisms ready to turn BU and BD binocularly Slowly build BU then BD prism Record break and recovery in each direction Significance: Vertical imbalance at far. Duction determines the reserve used to compensate any existing vertical imbalance. Normal vertical phoria is typically orthophoria or 1Δ or less.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-13a-habitual-lateral-phoria-at-near\",\"heading\":\"#13A — Habitual Lateral Phoria at Near\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Habitual near correction | Near PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: smallest readable at 16\\\" | Illumination: 20 ft candle Procedure: Von Graefe at near. Steps identical to #3 but at 16\\\" with near PD and habitual near Rx. Load habitual near correction; set near PD Place OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU Patient fixates smallest readable at 16\\\" Reduce BU prism until vertical alignment Significance: Lateral muscular imbalance at near using habitual correction — the \\\"as the patient reads\\\" phoria, before any OEP near correction is applied. Near equivalent of #3.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-13b-induced-lateral-phoria-at-near\",\"heading\":\"#13B — Induced Lateral Phoria at Near\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Gross #14A result | Near PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: smallest readable at 16\\\" Procedure: Von Graefe at near — steps identical to #13A, but Gross #14A lenses are in place. Significance: Phoria at near after the cross-cylinder near correction (#14A) is applied. Shows how the near addition changes the phoria. Near equivalent of #8. Compare to #13A to assess the effect of the near correction on lateral balance.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-14a-dissociated-cross-cylinder-test\",\"heading\":\"#14A — Dissociated Cross-Cylinder Test\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 | Near PD | OD: 3Δ BD | OS: 3Δ BU | Auxiliary: cross-cyl (−0.50D, red dot at 90°) | Target: cross-grid at 16\\\" | Illumination: dim Procedure: Load Test #7 lenses; set near PD Place OD: 3Δ BD and OS: 3Δ BU (vertical prisms dissociate the eyes — patient sees two separate cross-grids) Place a −0.50D cross-cylinder with red dot at 90° before both eyes The patient views the cross-grid target and reports which set of lines (horizontal or vertical) appears darker/bolder Add plus sphere in 0.25D steps to both eyes until the horizontal and vertical lines of the cross-grid appear equally dark Endpoint: equality at the highest plus — record Gross #14A Significance: Measures the lag of accommodation under dissociated conditions. The amount of plus needed to equalize the lines = how much the eye is lagging behind the accommodative stimulus. Dissociated = prisms separate the eyes, removing binocular fusion as a variable.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-14b-binocular-cross-cylinder-test\",\"heading\":\"#14B — Binocular Cross-Cylinder Test\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Gross #14A result | Near PD | No prisms | Auxiliary: cross-cyl (−0.50D, red dot at 90°) | Target: cross-grid at 16\\\" | Illumination: dim Procedure: Load Gross #14A lenses; set near PD; no prisms this time Place −0.50D cross-cylinder (red dot at 90°) before both eyes Patient binocularly views the cross-grid Add plus in 0.25D steps until horizontal and vertical lines appear equally dark Endpoint: equality at the highest plus — record Gross #14B Significance: Lag of accommodation under fused (binocular) conditions. Because there are no prisms, normal binocular fusion is maintained. Compare to #14A: if the lag is larger under fusion, accommodation is being driven by convergence demand more than by clarity alone.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-15a-induced-phoria-through-unfused-cross-cylinder\",\"heading\":\"#15A — Induced Phoria Through Unfused Cross-Cylinder\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Gross #14A result | Near PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: reduced Snellen at 16\\\" Procedure: Von Graefe at near using Gross #14A lenses. Load Gross #14A lenses; set near PD Place OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU Patient fixates reduced Snellen at 16\\\" Reduce BU prism until vertical alignment Record phoria Significance: Shows the influence of the #14A near correction on lateral phoria at near. The result helps determine whether the near addition is appropriate for the patient's binocular balance.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-15b-induced-phoria-through-fused-cross-cylinder\",\"heading\":\"#15B — Induced Phoria Through Fused Cross-Cylinder\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Gross #14B result | Near PD | OD: 12–15Δ BI | OS: 6Δ BU | Target: reduced Snellen at 16\\\" Procedure: Von Graefe at near using Gross #14B lenses. Steps identical to #15A, but #14B lenses are in place. Significance: Shows the influence of the #14B near correction (fused lag) on lateral phoria. Cross-check for #15A.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-16a-positive-relative-convergence-prc\",\"heading\":\"#16A — Positive Relative Convergence (PRC)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Non-presbyope: Test #7 | Myope: habitual minus | Presbyope: 14B Net | Near PD | OU ready to turn BO | Target: smallest readable at 16\\\" Procedure (prism ramp — BO): Load appropriate lenses (Test #7 for non-presbyope); set near PD Place prisms OU ready to turn BO; start at zero Slowly increase BO prism binocularly Endpoint: blur only (the point at which the target first blurs; do NOT continue to break) Record blur value as PRC Significance: The blur point indicates how much positive fusional innervation is in reserve at 40cm. This is the convergence reserve without pushing to the breaking point — the \\\"usable\\\" reserve.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-16b-positive-fusional-reserve-pfr\",\"heading\":\"#16B — Positive Fusional Reserve (PFR)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Same as #16A Procedure (prism ramp — BO, continued past blur to break and recovery): Same setup as #16A; same lens and prism direction (BO) Continue increasing BO prism past the blur point until diplopia (break) Record break value Reduce prism until single vision recovers: record recovery value Significance: Break = total positive convergence reserve at near including accommodative convergence. Recovery = limit of the fusional field. A large blur-to-break gap suggests the patient is using accommodation-driven convergence heavily.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-17a-negative-relative-convergence-nrc\",\"heading\":\"#17A — Negative Relative Convergence (NRC)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Same lenses as #16A | Near PD | OU ready to turn BI | Target: smallest readable at 16\\\" Procedure (prism ramp — BI): Load same lenses as #16A; set near PD Place prisms OU ready to turn BI; start at zero Slowly increase BI prism binocularly Endpoint: blur only (first blur, do not go to break) Record blur value as NRC Significance: Measures how much convergence can be relaxed before the image blurs — the negative fusional reserve without pushing to diplopia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-17b-negative-fusional-reserve-nfr\",\"heading\":\"#17B — Negative Fusional Reserve (NFR)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Same as #17A Procedure (prism ramp — BI, past blur to break and recovery): Same setup as #17A; continue past blur to break Record break value (diplopia) Reduce BI prism until single: record recovery Significance: Break = how much accommodative convergence can be inhibited by relaxing accommodation at near. Recovery = limit of the negative fusional field.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-18-vertical-phoria-and-duction-at-near\",\"heading\":\"#18 — Vertical Phoria and Duction at Near\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 | Near PD | Prisms ready to turn BU and BD | Target: smallest readable at 16\\\" Procedure: Same two-part structure as #12, but at 16\\\" with near PD. Vertical phoria: Load Test #7; near PD; place horizontal dissociating prism + BU/BD measuring prism Patient fixates target; reduce measuring prism until horizontal alignment Record vertical phoria value Vertical duction: Prisms ready to turn BU and BD binocularly Slowly build BU prism until break; reduce until recovery Repeat for BD direction Record break and recovery for each direction Significance: Vertical imbalance at near. Near equivalent of #12. Duction determines the reserve used at near to compensate any vertical imbalance.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-19-amplitude-of-accommodation-aa\",\"heading\":\"#19 — Amplitude of Accommodation (AA)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Test #7 (non-presbyope: minus added) | Near PD | No prisms | Target:.62 Em Type at 16\\\" Procedure: Non-presbyope (push-up method with lenses): Load Test #7 lenses; set near PD Patient fixates.62 Em Type print at 16\\\" Add minus lenses in 0.25D steps until the patient reports the print is difficult to read Endpoint: print difficult to read (first sustained blur) Record the total minus added = amplitude of accommodation in diopters (in addition to the 2.50D base from the 16\\\" distance) Presbyope (push-down — plus lenses): Load Test #7 lenses; set near PD Start with enough plus that the print is unreadable Reduce plus (or add minus) in 0.25D steps until the patient first reads the.62 Em Type Endpoint: first readable Record the lens at first readable Significance: Determines total amplitude of accommodation. Expected values follow Hofstetter's formula: minimum AA = 15 − 0.25(age); average = 18.5 − 0.30(age).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-20-positive-relative-accommodation-pra\",\"heading\":\"#20 — Positive Relative Accommodation (PRA)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Non-presbyope: Test #7 | Presbyope: 14B Net | Near PD | No prisms | Target: smallest readable reduced Snellen at 16\\\" (20/20) Procedure: Load appropriate lenses; set near PD Patient fixates 20/20 reduced Snellen at 16\\\" Add minus lenses in 0.25D steps binocularly Endpoint: patient cannot read the 20/20 line (first sustained blur) Record total minus added = PRA value (expected normal: approximately −2.37D) Significance: Measures the extent to which accommodation can be stimulated while fixation is maintained at 16\\\". Higher PRA = more accommodative reserve available for near work.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-21-negative-relative-accommodation-nra\",\"heading\":\"#21 — Negative Relative Accommodation (NRA)\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Setup: Non-presbyope: Test #7 | Presbyope: 14B Net | Near PD | No prisms | Target: smallest readable reduced Snellen at 16\\\" (20/20) Procedure: Load appropriate lenses; set near PD Patient fixates 20/20 reduced Snellen at 16\\\" Add plus lenses in 0.25D steps binocularly Endpoint: patient cannot read the 20/20 line (first sustained blur) Record total plus added = NRA value (expected normal: approximately +2.00D) Significance: Measures the extent to which accommodation can be inhibited while fixation is maintained at 16\\\". Together with PRA, defines the range of relative accommodation. NRA + PRA should center roughly on the resting point of accommodation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-21-steps-step-by-step-procedures-reading-the-add-oep-formula\",\"heading\":\"Reading the Add: OEP Formula\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"After completing the 21 steps, the Near Addition is calculated: Net #4 = Gross #4 − WD correction (dioptric equivalent of working distance) Net #5 = Gross #5 − Lag value (from OEP lag table, based on #15A phoria and AA) Net #6 = Gross #6 − 0.25D lag (if AA ≥ 5.00D) Reading Add = Net #5 − Net #4 Near phoria (#15A) Lag value (to subtract from Gross #5) 1 XOP 0.12D 2 XOP 0.25D 3 XOP 0.37D 4 XOP 0.50D 5 XOP 0.62D 6 XOP 0.75D\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide\",\"heading\":\"OEP Clinical Interpretation Guide\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"The 21 steps are not just a checklist. Each result answers a question in a clinical story, and the questions build on each other. The picture gets sharper as you go — the phoria at #3 plants a hypothesis, the vergences at #9–#12 test it, the near phorias at #13A and #13A confirm or overturn it, and the accommodation tests at #19–#21 explain whether the binocular finding is optically driven or muscular. Here is what to watch at each stage and how to connect the dots.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-1-before-correction-1-3-baseline-picture\",\"heading\":\"Stage 1 — Before correction (#1–#3): Baseline picture\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"At #3 (habitual phoria at far), you see the patient as they actually live. This is your starting reference. What to note: Is the far phoria orthophoric, exo, or eso? Note the amount. Any vertical component? Even 1–2Δ of vertical imbalance produces disproportionate symptoms — headaches, tilted print, monocular blur. Flag this immediately. A large eso at far before any correction suggests the habitual Rx may be over-minused or significantly under-plussed — the eye is already straining to maintain distance fixation. Normal reference: approximately 1Δ exo at far (ortho is also normal)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-2-objective-near-picture-4-6-what-the-retinoscope-says\",\"heading\":\"Stage 2 — Objective near picture (#4–#6): What the retinoscope says\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"The lag of accommodation from the dynamic retinoscopy sequence (#5 vs #4) tells you how well accommodation is doing the job of keeping up with near demand. Normal lag: +0.50 to +0.75D Lag finding What it means Follow up at +0.50 to +0.75D Normal; accommodation on target Confirm with #20 (PRA) > +0.75D (high lag) Accommodative insufficiency; system lagging Check AA (#19) vs Hofstetter minimum < +0.50D (low lag) Accommodation slightly overactive Watch #20 PRA and #21 NRA balance Negative lag (lead) Accommodation overshooting; possible spasm Compare to #7 subjective; check for pseudomyopia\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-3-the-subjective-refraction-7-the-anchor\",\"heading\":\"Stage 3 — The subjective refraction (#7): The anchor\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Test #7 is the reference lens for everything that follows. An error here cascades. What to compare: If #7 (subjective) is significantly more minus than Net #4 (objective): the fogging may have been insufficient, or the patient has accommodative excess (pseudomyopia). The subjective will over-minus them. If #7 is more plus than Net #4 by a large margin: latent hyperopia was not uncovered by the objective. Consider cycloplegic refraction. The endpoint (MPMVA) is always most plus / least minus at best VA. If you accepted more minus than necessary, every phoria after #7 will show more convergence than is truly present.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-4-far-binocular-with-the-new-rx-8-12-did-the-correction-help\",\"heading\":\"Stage 4 — Far binocular with the new Rx (#8–#12): Did the correction help?\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"#3 vs #8 — the critical comparison: Change Interpretation Phoria improved (less exo or less eso at #8) The Rx is correcting a refractive-driven binocular imbalance — the lens is doing some of the binocular work Phoria unchanged at #8 The binocular imbalance is muscle-based; the Rx is not the primary driver Phoria worsened at #8 The Rx is stressing the system; reconsider the endpoint of #7 or check for latent hyperopia #9 (BO blur), #10 (BO break/recovery), #11 (BI break/recovery) at far: These tell you the reserve at distance for both convergence and divergence. Finding Suggests Low BO break at far (#10) Limited positive vergence at distance; eso-type symptoms at distance are less common but possible in DI Low BI break at far (#11) Limited negative vergence; patient may struggle to diverge; eso symptoms at far (divergence insufficiency) Normal far ranges with abnormal phoria The system is compensating; the phoria is not yet breaking through #12 — Vertical at far: Any vertical phoria that appears here is clinically important. Compare later to #18 (vertical at near). If the vertical phoria is larger at near than at far, suspect a vertical comitance issue or CN4 palsy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-5-near-binocular-status-13a-18-where-most-clinical-findings-live\",\"heading\":\"Stage 5 — Near binocular status (#13A–#18): Where most clinical findings live\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"This is the richest stage. The key comparisons are between far findings (#3, #8) and near findings (#13A, #13B). #3 vs #13A — Far vs near phoria: the BV disorder map Far phoria (#3) Near phoria (#13A) BV disorder type AC/A ratio Ortho or small exo High exo (much larger) Convergence Insufficiency (CI) Low High exo Ortho or small exo Divergence Excess (DE) High Exo equal at far and near Exo equal at far and near Basic Exophoria Normal High eso Ortho or small eso Divergence Insufficiency (DI) Low Ortho or small eso High eso (much larger) Convergence Excess (CE) High Eso equal at far and near Eso equal at far and near Basic Esophoria Normal Normal phorias both Normal phorias both Fusional Vergence Dysfunction (check #16/#17) Normal Clinical descriptions of each type: CI — patient reports blur, pull, or headache after sustained near work; NPC receded (>6–8 cm); BO vergence low; low AC/A; common in adults DE — intermittent exo at distance (patient closes one eye outdoors, in bright light); near vision comfortable; high AC/A; responds poorly to BO prisms at near DI — eso at far only; uncommon; rule out CN6 palsy or space-occupying lesion first; symptoms are distance-specific CE — eso at near, often linked to uncorrected or under-corrected hyperopia; high AC/A; accommodative esotropia in children is a subtype; full hyperopic Rx often resolves the problem Basic eso/exo — same phoria at both distances; tonic vergence problem; not driven by accommodation FVD — normal phoria and AC/A but vergence ranges (#16, #17) are low in both directions; patient has trouble with both converging and diverging tasks; VT is the primary intervention #14A vs #14B — Lag comparison: Finding Interpretation Both lags normal (+0.50–+0.75D) Accommodation is appropriate; fusion is not overloading it #14B lag > #14A lag Binocular fusion (convergence demand) is recruiting extra accommodation; the accommodative-convergence link is strong Both lags high Accommodative insufficiency regardless of binocular state; add is likely needed Both lags low or leading Accommodative excess; check for overcorrected myopia or pseudomyopia #15A and #15B — Phoria after CC correction: Compare to #13A: If phoria at #15A moved toward orthophoria: the near add (#14A result) is relieving the binocular load — it is appropriate for this patient If phoria worsened with the add: the add is adding convergence stress; reconsider the amount #16A, #16B, #17A, #17B — Vergence ranges at near: Morgan's norms from the source (near vergence): PFV (BO) at near — blur/break/recovery: 12 / 15 / 4 Δ NFV (BI) at near — blur/break/recovery: 9 / 17 / 8 Δ Test Low finding High finding PRC blur (#16A) Positive vergence reserve is quickly used up; convergence strain at near Large reserve before accommodation recruitment PFR break (#16B) Total positive vergence is limited; CI or FVD pattern Strong convergence ability NRC blur (#17A) Negative vergence reserve is limited; CE or FVD pattern Good divergence reserve NFR break (#17B) Total negative vergence is limited; CE pattern Strong divergence ability Applying Sheard's Criterion here: Sheard's criterion: the compensating vergence recovery must be at least 2× the phoria. Patient has 6Δ exo at near (#13A) → BI recovery (#17B) must be ≥ 12Δ to be comfortable Patient has 6Δ eso at near (#13A) → BO recovery (#16B) must be ≥ 12Δ If criterion is NOT met → patient is likely symptomatic → intervention indicated (prism, vision therapy, or near add) What reduced vergences in BOTH directions mean: If #16 and #17 are both low with normal phorias → Fusional Vergence Dysfunction (FVD). This patient can converge and diverge on command but fatigues quickly. Vision therapy targeting vergence ranges is the treatment. #18 — Vertical phoria and duction at near: Compare to #12. A vertical phoria that is larger at near than at far, or that appears only at near, points to a decompensating comitant vertical or a non-comitant muscle problem (oblique overaction, etc.).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-stage-6-accommodation-capacity-19-21-the-final-layer\",\"heading\":\"Stage 6 — Accommodation capacity (#19–#21): The final layer\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"#19 (AA) vs Hofstetter's minimum: Expected minimum AA = 15 − 0.25 × age If measured AA < minimum expected → accommodative insufficiency → the patient cannot sustain accommodation even if the binocular state is fine. This compounds any existing binocular issue. #20 (PRA) vs #21 (NRA) — Is the near correction centered in the accommodative range? If the lens is correct, PRA and NRA should be roughly balanced (the accommodation system can push or pull by similar amounts). PRA vs NRA pattern Interpretation Action PRA much lower than NRA Patient can relax accommodation easily but cannot stimulate it much further Near add is too weak (or distance Rx is too minus); the working point is too far from the rest point NRA much lower than PRA Patient can stimulate but cannot relax Near add is too strong (or distance Rx is too plus); the working point is pressing against the near end Both low (balanced) Small accommodative range overall; presbyopia or AI Check age vs AA norms; consider add Both normal Near correction is appropriate; accommodative range is healthy Confirm with #19 The working principle: for a given near lens, the PRA measures how much more accommodation the patient can still activate, and the NRA measures how much they can relax. Equal values mean the lens is centered in the range. Unequal values mean the lens has pushed the working point off-center.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-oep-clinical-interpretation-guide-the-running-clinical-summary-what-you-know-at-each-step\",\"heading\":\"The Running Clinical Summary — What You Know at Each Step\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"After step You now know #3 Far phoria with habitual Rx — the baseline binocular state #4–#6 Near accommodative status objectively — does the retinoscope show a lag, lead, or normal response? #7 The optical correction — the reference for everything that follows #8 Whether the Rx changed the far phoria — helps, hurts, or neutral? #9–#11 Far vergence reserves — how much convergence and divergence is available at distance #12 Any vertical imbalance at far #13A Near phoria with habitual Rx — compare to #3 to classify the BV disorder #13B Near phoria after applying the #14A result — did the near add help? #14A Dissociated lag — accommodative insufficiency or excess? #14B Fused lag — is binocular demand loading the accommodative system? #15A/#15B Near phoria under each lag correction — is the binocular system happier with the add? #16A/#16B Positive vergence range at near — CI or DE pattern? Sheard's met? #17A/#17B Negative vergence range at near — CE or DI pattern? Sheard's met? #18 Vertical imbalance at near — compare to #12 #19 Amplitude of accommodation — is there enough for the patient's age and task demands? #20 PRA — can accommodation be stimulated further? #21 NRA — can accommodation be relaxed? Together with #20: is the near Rx centered in the range?\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Ideal fog acuity target 20/30–20/40 Ideal fog lens amount +0.50 to +0.75D above best sphere Astigmatic dial: darkest line Power meridian Minus cyl axis direction Perpendicular to (90° from) the darkest line Sphere added per cylinder +0.25D sphere per −0.50D cyl JCC Position 1 Red dots parallel to tentative axis Patient prefers Position 1 Cylinder under-powered → add minus Patient prefers Position 2 Cylinder over-powered → reduce minus Axis check: rotate toward Red dot if Position 1 preferred; white dot if Position 2 preferred Rotation method: used when Cyl power > 0.75D Duochrome: green clearer Over-minused / under-plussed → reduce minus or add plus Duochrome: red clearer Under-minused / over-plussed → add minus or reduce plus Binocular balance re-fog +0.50 to +0.75D to BOTH eyes Prism dissociation setup 3Δ BD OD / 3Δ BU OS Lateral phoria prism setup OD 12–15Δ BI / OS 6Δ BU (same for #3, #8, #13A, #13B, #15A, #15B) OEP #7 endpoint MPMVA #3 vs. #8 #3 = habitual Rx / #8 = Test #7 Rx #14A vs. #14B 14A = dissociated (prisms); 14B = binocular (no prism) PRA (#20): add Minus lenses until blur NRA (#21): add Plus lenses until blur If equality not reached in binocular balance Let dominant eye retain better VA\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"1. During a JCC power check with the tentative cylinder at −0.75D × 090, the patient consistently prefers Position 1. Which adjustment is indicated? A. Reduce the minus cylinder by 0.25D B. Increase the minus cylinder by 0.25D C. Rotate the axis clockwise toward the red dot D. Add +0.25D to the sphere only Answer B. Increase the minus cylinder by 0.25D. Position 1 means red dots parallel to the tentative axis — this is the deliberate overcorrection position. If the patient prefers it, the cylinder is still under-powered relative to the optimum. Adding −0.25D steps (with +0.25D sphere compensation per −0.50D cyl added) moves toward equality. A is the response to a Position 2 preference. C describes the axis check technique, not the power check. D adjusts only the sphere without addressing the cylinder deficiency. 2. During the prism dissociation binocular balance, the patient reports the upper image (OD) is consistently clearer. After adding +0.25D to the OD, the lower image (OS) becomes clearer instead. What is the correct next step? A. Add another +0.25D to OD to see if equality appears B. Add +0.25D to OS to bring it back C. Allow OD (as the dominant eye) to retain the better vision and begin binocular reduction D. Repeat the monocular subjective refraction for OD before continuing Answer C. Allow OD (as the dominant eye) to retain the better vision and begin binocular reduction. When adding +0.25D reverses rather than equalizes the preference, you have passed through the neutral point. The correct rule from this source: permit the dominant eye to retain the better vision and proceed. A would cause the same problem again (bouncing the preference back and forth). B would reverse the error to OS, not resolve it. D is not indicated — the monocular subjective was already completed; the issue is at the binocular balance step.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5-01-subjective-examination-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C5-01 — Subjective Examination\",\"text\":\"Read the note. Close the screen. Then pick up the pen. The screen should not be visible while you drill. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"Subjective Refraction\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set 5 minutes. Write every thing you can retrieve: the fogging principle, the astigmatic dial rule, both JCC setups, the duochrome interpretation table, the four binocular balance methods, and the OEP step groups. What to brain dump specifically: Ideal fog target acuity and lens amount JCC Position 1 vs. Position 2: orientation and what each preference means Duochrome: what green clearer means and what action to take Drill 2 — Blank diagram or table Reproduce the OEP 21 Steps reference map from memory. Group by distance (preliminary, far, near, accommodation). For each step, write: step number, name, lenses in place, and endpoint. Leave circles for anything you cannot remember, not blanks — so you can see the density of gaps. What to reproduce: The full 21-step grouped table with lenses and endpoints. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Flip the paper. Write: \\\"Explain why the astigmatic dial works without using the words 'meridian' or 'power'.\\\" If you can do this coherently, you understand the mechanism, not just the label. Teach-back prompt: Explain the fogging principle to someone who only knows that accommodation exists. No jargon. Four sentences. Drill 4 — Flash card prompts Front Back JCC Position 1 = ? Red dots tentative axis; preference means cyl under-powered → add minus JCC Position 2 = ? White dots tentative axis; preference means cyl over-powered → reduce minus Duochrome: green clearer → action? Reduce minus / add plus (focal point is in front of retina) Duochrome: red clearer → action? Add minus / reduce plus (focal point is behind retina) Binocular balance re-fog amount? +0.50 to +0.75D to BOTH eyes Which OEP step feeds all others? #7 — Monocular subjective refraction (MPMVA) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the full monocular subjective refraction procedure in numbered steps, from \\\"occlude OS\\\" to \\\"record MPMVA.\\\" Include: the starting-point decision, the ideal fog, astigmatic dial, axis confirmation, power refinement, defogging, and duochrome. Sequence only — no explanation needed. Check against the Structure or Process Map after. Sequence to write: Steps 1 through 10 of monocular subjective refraction. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st review Jun 5, 2026 (today) Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Jun 6 Blank table + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review Jun 8 Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review Jun 12 Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check Jun 19 All 5 drills; flag any remaining gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Management of visual disorders in optometry follows a fixed priority: fix the optics first, then address the muscle problem, then train the system, then refer for surgery if none of that works. This order matters because most binocular disorders are at least partly driven by uncorrected refractive error, and prism or therapy on top of a wrong prescription is treating the wrong thing. The three main areas here are phorias (latent deviations), tropias (manifest deviations), and amblyopia (reduced VA not explainable by optics alone). Each has its own management ladder, but all three start at the same first rung: correct the refractive error. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"A child has esotropia. The parent wants surgery. What do you do first?\\\" (Full cycloplegic refraction, because if the deviation is accommodative, the right glasses may straighten the eyes completely — and surgery on an uncorrected hyperope is treating the symptom, not the cause.)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Why correct the refractive error before anything else? Uncorrected hyperopia drives accommodation, and accommodation drives convergence via the AC/A ratio. An eye that is over-accommodating will over-converge. Giving glasses removes the accommodation demand, which removes the convergence excess. Without that step, the full deviation cannot be assessed, and any prism or VT prescribed will be based on an inflated angle. Why does occlusion therapy work for amblyopia? The amblyopic eye is not blind — its retina and visual pathway are intact. The problem is cortical: the brain has learned to suppress the amblyopic eye's input because it is blurrier than the fellow eye. Covering the good eye forces the brain to use the suppressed eye, re-opening the cortical representation of that eye through use-dependent plasticity. Why does atropine penalization work? Atropine paralyzes accommodation in the good eye, making it blurry for near tasks. The amblyopic eye then provides clearer near vision and the brain is nudged toward using it. The mechanism is the same as patching (force use of the amblyopic eye) but without a patch — useful for children who remove patches or have patching-induced contact dermatitis. Why does simply correcting the refractive error sometimes resolve amblyopia on its own? In anisometropic amblyopia, the brain suppresses the eye with the worse image — not because of strabismus, but because of chronic image disparity. Providing the correct lens equalizes the retinal image quality. The brain no longer has a reason to suppress one eye, and cortical plasticity allows some recovery, especially during the sensitive period. Why is patching alone insufficient for amblyopia? Patching improves monocular VA by forcing use of the amblyopic eye, but it does not rewire the binocular cortical circuits that process binocularity and fusion. If the underlying strabismus or anisometropia is not addressed, the amblyopia returns when the patch is removed. VT combined with patching addresses both the monocular acuity deficit and the binocular dysfunction.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Amblyopia Greek amblys (dull) + ops (eye) Reduced VA not correctable by optics, caused by abnormal visual experience during development Strabismus Greek strabizein (to squint) Manifest misalignment of the eyes; one eye deviates from the point of fixation Phoria Greek pherein (to carry) Latent tendency of the eyes to deviate, held in check by fusion Tropia Greek tropos (turning) Manifest deviation; the eye actually turns, not just tends to Eccentric fixation Latin ex-centrum (off-center) Fixation in the amblyopic eye occurs at a retinal point other than the fovea Penalization Latin poena (penalty) Deliberate blurring or occluding of the better eye to force use of the amblyopic eye Pleoptics Greek pleion (more) + ops (eye/vision) Technique using intense light stimulation of the non-foveal area to rehabilitate foveal fixation in amblyopia with eccentric fixation Anisometropia Greek anisos (unequal) + metron (measure) + ops Clinically significant difference in refractive error between the two eyes Aniseikonia Greek anisos + eikon (image) Unequal image size between the two eyes, causing binocular fusion difficulties Isekonic / iseikonic lens Greek isos (equal) + eikon Lens designed to equalize retinal image size without altering optical power Lookalike trap: Amblyopia ≠ suppression. Suppression is the active cortical inhibition that causes amblyopia. Amblyopia is the end result (reduced VA). A patient can have suppression without amblyopia (facultative suppression, no persisting effect). Amblyopia requires the suppression to be obligatory.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-how-it-works-the-decision-framework\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Decision Framework\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"The management of any visual disorder follows the same four-rung ladder. The rungs must be climbed in order. Rung 1: Correct the refractive error Always first Clears the retinal image Removes accommodative demand (reduces AC/A-driven convergence in CE and accommodative esotropia) In anisometropic amblyopia, may resolve the amblyopia partially or fully without patching Prism or VT prescribed before the refractive error is corrected is based on the wrong angle Rung 2: Prism prescription Used when Sheard's or Percival's criterion is not met after optical correction Compensating prism: reduces the demand on fusional vergence without training it Direction: base opposite to the deviation tendency (exo → BI; eso → BO; hyperphoria → BD before the higher eye) Limitation: does not strengthen the vergence system; vergence ranges remain unchanged; symptoms may return if prism is discontinued Rung 3: Vision therapy (VT) Trains the vergence system to expand the zone of clear single binocular vision (ZCSBV) Indicated for CI, FVD, accommodative insufficiency, and some CE cases More durable than prism because it builds actual vergence capacity For amblyopia: active therapy (patching, penalization, CAM, OVT, perceptual learning) Combines sensory and motor activities; addresses both monocular and binocular function Rung 4: Surgical referral For large-angle constant tropias where optical and VT management is insufficient Accommodative esotropia: surgery is avoided if the full hyperopic Rx resolves the angle Large exotropia: surgery is the primary treatment when deviation is constant and large Always refer to ophthalmology\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Rule: Sheard's Criterion Compensating fusional vergence recovery ≥ 2 × phoria If criterion is NOT met: patient is symptomatic What it states in plain language: The vergence reserve available to compensate for a phoria must be at least twice the size of the phoria. If your phoria uses more than half your available reserve, you will develop symptoms. What each part means: Compensating fusional vergence = the vergence in the direction OPPOSITE to the deviation For exophoria: the compensating vergence is the BI (negative) fusional vergence (how far BI you can push before diplopia) For esophoria: the compensating vergence is the BO (positive) fusional vergence Recovery value (not break) is used as the measure of functional reserve — the point at which the patient can re-fuse, not the point at which they lose fusion Phoria = the size of the latent deviation (in Δ) Where it comes from: Charles Sheard (1920) observed that many symptomatic patients had normal phoria magnitudes but insufficient vergence reserves. He proposed the 2:1 ratio as a clinical threshold, reasoning that any demand requiring more than half the total reserve would be sustained at the margin, creating fatigue and symptoms. The analogy: Think of the phoria as a car constantly pulling left, and the fusional vergence as the force you apply to the steering wheel to keep it straight. If the pull is strong enough that you're already using more than half your steering strength just to maintain the lane, you'll fatigue quickly. If the pull only needs a quarter of your strength, you can sustain it comfortably all day. Why this form and not another: The 2:1 ratio sets a practical comfort margin. A ratio of 1:1 would mean the patient is always using 100% of reserve — technically possible but functionally exhausting. The 2:1 ratio leaves half the reserve as a safety buffer for visual tasks that increase demand (fatigue, illness, stress). What it does NOT explain: Sheard's criterion does not apply to vertical phorias, where even small amounts cause significant symptoms It does not account for asymmetric vergence ranges (a patient with a large blur-to-break gap may have an unusual profile) When the ZCSBV is small and asymmetric, Percival's criterion may be more informative Cross-subject connections: Binocular Vision (B5): Sheard's criterion is used alongside Morgan's norms to identify binocular vision disorders from OEP data VT (C7): The goal of VT for vergence disorders is to expand the recovery value until Sheard's is met and sustained Reading the Result: Finding Criterion Action Recovery ≥ 2× phoria Criterion MET Likely asymptomatic; monitor Recovery < 2× phoria Criterion NOT MET Symptomatic; prescribe prism or VT Prism to prescribe (Sheard's) (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3 Minimum prism to bring patient into criterion Rule: Percival's Criterion The demand point (phoria) must fall within the middle third of the zone of clear single binocular vision ( ZCSBV ) Middle third = between 1/3 BO and 1/3 BI of the total fusional vergence range What it states in plain language: The patient's resting eye position (phoria) must sit in the comfortable center zone of their available vergence range. If it falls in the outer one-third of either the BO or BI side, they will be symptomatic. Where it comes from: Percival (1892) proposed that comfort is greatest when the visual demand falls in the middle of the available range — neither near the BO limit nor the BI limit. It is geometric rather than ratio-based (unlike Sheard's). When to use Percival's over Sheard's: Percival's is more useful when the ZCSBV is small or asymmetric — common in FVD patients where both BO and BI ranges are reduced. In these cases, a normal-sized phoria can still violate Percival's because the entire range is compressed. Prism to prescribe (Percival's): If demand is in the outer BO third: prescribe BI prism = (1/3 × BO break) − (2/3 × BI break) If demand is in the outer BI third: prescribe BO prism = (1/3 × BI break) − (2/3 × BO break) Cross-subject connections: OEP 21 Steps (C5): The vergence ranges (#16B, #17B) are the source data for applying both criteria Formula: Amplitude of Convergence Amplitude of Convergence = ( NPD × 10) ÷ ( NPC + 3) Where: NPD = near pupillary distance in mm NPC = near point of convergence in cm +3 = correction for the distance from the spectacle plane to the center of rotation (≈ 27 mm → 3 cm) Result = in prism diopters (Δ) What it states in plain language: The maximum convergence the eyes can achieve, expressed in prism diopters, calculated from how close the eyes can converge (NPC) and how far apart they are (NPD). What each part means: NPD: the interpupillary distance during near fixation (smaller than far PD because the eyes converge) NPC: how close the object gets before one eye breaks away (in cm, measured from the spectacle plane) +3: accounts for the distance between the spectacle plane and the center of rotation (~27 mm ≈ 3 cm); ensures the denominator represents the actual working distance from the ocular center of rotation, not the spectacle plane Reading the Result: NPC value Interpretation < 5 cm Convergence excess (over-convergence) 5–8 cm (accommodative target) Normal per Scheiman and Wick (2008) 6–10 cm (penlight target) Normal range > 10 cm Convergence insufficiency\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Management ladder — applies to all three categories: VISUAL DISORDER IDENTIFIED | v RUNG 1: Correct refractive error Full cycloplegic Rx if needed Re-examine binocular status with new Rx | v Did the disorder resolve? YES → Monitor NO → Continue to Rung 2 | v RUNG 2: Prism prescription Sheard's or Percival's criterion not met Prescribe compensating prism (exo: BI; eso: BO; hyper: BD) | v Did symptoms resolve? YES → Monitor + periodic VT assessment NO → Continue to Rung 3 | v RUNG 3: Vision therapy Vergence training, accommodative therapy, binocular rehab For amblyopia: patching/penalization + active therapy | v Adequate improvement? YES → Discharge or maintenance program NO → Continue to Rung 4 | v RUNG 4: Surgical referral Large-angle constant tropia unresponsive to optical + VT Refer to ophthalmology Amblyopia management — specific sequence: AMBLYOPIA CONFIRMED | v STEP 1: CORRECT THE CAUSE Deprivation → remove opacity (cataract, ptosis) first Strabismic → correct refractive error; assess angle post-correction Anisometropic → full refractive correction; wait 8–12 weeks for adaptation | v STEP 2: PRESENT A CLEAR RETINAL IMAGE TO AMBLYOPIC EYE Full refractive correction of the amblyopic eye (DO NOT under-correct to \\\"avoid stress\\\") | v STEP 3: FORCE USE OF THE AMBLYOPIC EYE | +—— Passive therapy | Occlusion: opaque patch on good eye | Total vs partial (translucent patch) | Full-time vs part-time | Conventional (patch good eye) vs inverse (very brief) | Penalization: atropine in good eye (blurs near); optical penalization | +—— Active therapy (+ passive) Pleoptics — for eccentric fixation; dazzle peripheral retina, stimulate fovea CAM vision stimulator — amblyopic eye stimulated with rotating gratings 7 min/session OVT (Optometric Vision Therapy) — binocular + monocular components Perceptual learning — repeated practice of visual discrimination tasks Pegboard stimulator — eye-hand coordination; anti-suppression | v STEP 4: ADDRESS BINOCULAR ANOMALY Strabismus surgery if indicated (ophthalmology) Binocular VT to establish/restore fusion after acuity is equalized Phoria classification and management map: EXOPHORIA (eyes drift out) | +— CI (Convergence Insufficiency) | Near exo > far exo | Low AC/A | Receded NPC | Management: VT (convergence exercises) → plus add at near → BI prism (compensating) | +— DE (Divergence Excess) | Far exo > near exo | High AC/A | Normal NPC | Management: BI prism (far) → VT → minus add (controversial) → surgery if large/constant | +— Basic Exophoria Equal exo at far and near | Normal AC/A Management: BI prism → VT ESOPHORIA (eyes drift in) | +— CE (Convergence Excess) | Near eso > far eso | High AC/A | Often uncorrected hyperopia | Management: Full hyperopic correction FIRST → plus add at near → BO prism → VT | +— DI (Divergence Insufficiency) | Far eso > near eso | Low AC/A | Rule out CN6 palsy | Management: BO prism (far) → VT | +— Basic Esophoria Equal eso at far and near | Normal AC/A Management: Full hyperopic correction → BO prism → VT FUSIONAL VERGENCE DYSFUNCTION ( FVD ) Normal phoria, reduced vergence ranges both directions Management: VT (primary — build both PFV and NFV ) → plus add if AI co-exists VERTICAL PHORIA Management: BD prism before the higher eye → VT → surgical referral for large deviations\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Patching vs. atropine penalization: Feature Occlusion (patching) Atropine penalization Mechanism Physically blocks light from good eye Paralyzes accommodation in good eye, blurring near vision VA improvement Effective for both distance and near in amblyopic eye More effective for near tasks in amblyopic eye Compliance Requires child cooperation; patches can be removed No patch needed; once applied, cannot easily be removed Risk Rebound amblyopia if over-patched Pupil dilation, photophobia, cycloplegia in good eye Board clue Conventional = patch good eye; inverse = brief patch of amblyopic eye \\\"Pharmacologic penalization\\\" on the board = atropine Strabismic vs. anisometropic vs. deprivation amblyopia: Feature Strabismic Anisometropic (refractive) Deprivation (form-vision) Cause Suppression from strabismus Image quality disparity from unequal refraction Physical obstruction of light (cataract, ptosis, corneal opacity) Fixation Often eccentric Usually foveal Varies; often eccentric Amblyopia depth Moderate to deep Mild to deep Most severe Prognosis Good if treated early Good; refractive correction alone may resolve Worst prognosis; must remove opacity urgently First step Correct RE; assess angle Full refractive correction Remove obstruction (surgery) THEN correct RE Board clue Suppression is the driver Anisometropia ≥ 2D (Borish) is the risk threshold Congenital cataract = treat immediately Sheard's vs. Percival's: Feature Sheard's Criterion Percival's Criterion Rule Compensating recovery ≥ 2× phoria Phoria must fall within middle 1/3 of vergence range Based on Ratio (phoria vs. reserve) Geometry (position within range) Uses Primary criterion for symptomatic phoria Secondary; used when ZCSBV is small or asymmetric Prism amount (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3 Based on BO and BI break values Board clue \\\"Sheard's\\\" = 2× rule \\\"Percival's\\\" = middle third of range\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Anisometropia threshold (Borish) ≥ 2.00D difference between eyes Clinical threshold for significant anisometropia Anisometropia threshold (Herstein) ≥ 0.25D can already be considered mild More sensitive clinical threshold Anisometropia → amblyopia risk (hyperopic) 100% at ≥ 3.5D Tanlamai and Goss (1979) Anisometropia → amblyopia risk (myopic) 100% at ≥ 6.5D Myopic anisometropes tolerate more difference before amblyopia develops Myopic anisometropia tolerance Up to 6.00D difference can be corrected with glasses Beyond 6.00D, glasses usually not tolerated NPC normal (accommodative target) Break 5 cm ± 2.5 / Recovery 7 cm ± 4.0 Scheiman and Wick (2008) NPC normal (penlight/red lens) Break 7 cm ± 4.0 / Recovery 10 cm ± 5.0 Scheiman and Wick (2008) NPC > 10 cm Convergence insufficiency NPC < 5 cm Convergence excess Amblyopia depth: mild BCVA 20/25–20/30 Amblyopia depth: deep BCVA 20/50 or worse Prism placement rule Place before non-dominant eye when possible PCO source Critical period Most sensitive 0–2 yrs; treatable to 7–8 yrs; possible improvement to 12–18 yrs From B5 note CAM stimulator Amblyopic eye stimulated 7 min/session; 1 session/week × 3–4 weeks Morgan's PFV near (blur/break/recovery) 12 / 15 / 4 Δ Morgan's NFV near (blur/break/recovery) 9 / 17 / 8 Δ CE definition (near phoria) Near deviation ≥ 3 Δ more esophoric than far\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"The management order \\\"Refract → Prism → Train → Refer\\\" (Correct the optics → prescribe compensating prism → vision therapy → surgery) Sheard's in one sentence \\\"Reserve must be at least double the phoria. If not: prescribe (2Ph − R) ÷ 3 prism.\\\" Prism direction rules Exo → BI (base-in, because the eyes are drifting out and you're pointing them back in optically) Eso → BO (base-out, because the eyes are drifting in and you're correcting toward the outside) Hyperphoria → BD before the HIGHER eye (base-down on the eye that is riding up) Amblyopia types by first-step treatment Deprivation → Remove the opacity FIRST (then patch) Strabismic → Glasses FIRST (then patch; surgery for non-accommodative angle) Anisometropic → Glasses FIRST (then patch if VA gap remains after 8–12 weeks) Pleoptics = eccentric fixation only Pleoptics is only indicated when the amblyopic eye has eccentric fixation. It is no longer the preferred method because gains in VA are inferior to conventional patching and it requires specialized, expensive equipment. CE mnemonic CE = Convergence Excess = Correction first (full hyperopic Rx, then plus add)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"AMBLYOPIA TYPES — When to think of each Suppression → strabismus present? YES → Strabismic amblyopia Board clue: constant, unilateral squint; moderate to deep acuity loss; eccentric fixation NO → Is there significant anisometropia? YES → Anisometropic amblyopia Board clue: hyperopic anisometrope with ≥1D difference; foveal fixation usually NO → Is there a media opacity or form deprivation? YES → Deprivation amblyopia (worst prognosis; treat urgently) NO → Consider isoametropic amblyopia (bilateral high uncorrected RE) or organic PRISM PRESCRIPTION FLOW Step 1: Measure phoria (#3 far / #13A near) Step 2: Measure compensating recovery (#17B for exo; #16B for eso) Step 3: Apply Sheard's: Recovery ≥ 2× phoria? YES → Asymptomatic; prism not needed NO → Prism = (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3 Direction: exo → BI | eso → BO | hyper → BD (higher eye) Place before non-dominant eye preferentially\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Management order Correct RE → Prism → VT → Surgery Prism direction for exophoria BI (base-in) Prism direction for esophoria BO (base-out) Prism direction for hyperphoria BD before the HIGHER eye Sheard's criterion Compensating recovery ≥ 2× phoria Prism amount (Sheard's) (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3 Percival's criterion Phoria in middle 1/3 of vergence range Anisometropia threshold (Borish) ≥ 2.00D Anisometropia → amblyopia (hyperopic) 100% at ≥ 3.5D difference Amblyopia first step (strabismic) Correct the refractive error Amblyopia first step (anisometropic) Full refractive correction Amblyopia first step (deprivation) Remove the opacity Accommodative esotropia first treatment Full cycloplegic hyperopic correction Patching: which eye Cover the GOOD eye (conventional) Atropine penalization: which eye Instilled in the GOOD eye Pleoptics: indicated for Eccentric fixation in amblyopic eye Pleoptics: results vs patching Inferior to conventional patching CAM stimulator: duration 7 min/session, 1×/week, 3–4 weeks NPC convergence insufficiency NPC > 10 cm NPC convergence excess NPC < 5 cm Critical period (most sensitive) 0–2 years Critical period (treatable) Up to 7–8 years Possible improvement range Up to 12–18 years Sheard's: exo patient primary compensating vergence BI recovery (NFV) Sheard's: eso patient primary compensating vergence BO recovery (PFV)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"1. A 7-year-old presents with 20/20 OD and 20/60 OS. Examination shows 4 Δ esotropia OU with +3.50D hyperopia. Cycloplegic refraction confirms +3.50D OU. What is the most appropriate first management step? A. Patch the right eye for 6 hours/day B. Prescribe full cycloplegic correction (+3.50D) and reassess C. Refer immediately for strabismus surgery D. Prescribe BO prism to compensate for the esotropia Answer B. Prescribe full cycloplegic correction (+3.50D) and reassess. This is a classic accommodative esotropia presentation: esotropia with significant hyperopia. The uncorrected hyperopia drives accommodation, which drives convergence via the AC/A ratio, producing the esotropia. The first step is full hyperopic correction — the glasses may resolve the deviation completely. Patching (A) is premature before the refractive error is addressed; the amblyopia in OS may partially or fully resolve with correction alone. Surgery (C) is premature; surgery on an uncorrected accommodative esotropia treats the symptom without removing the cause. Prism (D) would compensate the deviation without removing the accommodative drive; the esotropia would persist when the prism is removed. 2. A patient has 8 Δ exophoria at near. BI recovery at near (#17B) is 10 Δ. The examiner wants to prescribe compensating prism. How much prism is needed according to Sheard's criterion, and in which direction? A. 2 Δ BI B. 2 Δ BO C. 4 Δ BI D. No prism needed; criterion is met Answer A. 2 Δ BI. Sheard's criterion: BI recovery (10 Δ) must be ≥ 2 × phoria (2 × 8 = 16 Δ). It is not met (10 < 16). Prism needed = (2 × 8 − 10) ÷ 3 = (16 − 10) ÷ 3 = 6 ÷ 3 = 2 Δ. Direction: exophoria → BI prism (base-in compensates for the outward deviation). B is wrong direction. C over-estimates the amount. D is incorrect because the criterion is clearly not met.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6-01-management-of-visual-disorders-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C6-01 — Management of Visual Disorders\",\"text\":\"Close the screen before picking up the pen. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"Management of Visual Disorders\\\" at the top of a blank page. Set 5 minutes. Write: the four management rungs in order, the prism direction for exo/eso/hyper, Sheard's criterion and the prism formula, the three types of amblyopia with their first step, and the two passive therapy options for amblyopia. Core items to dump: Management ladder (4 rungs, in order) Sheard's formula and the direction of compensating prism for each phoria type Amblyopia types and first treatment step for each Drill 2 — Blank table Reproduce the phoria classification and management map from memory. For each type (CI, DE, CE, DI, basic exo, basic eso, FVD), write: far phoria, near phoria, AC/A, and first management step. What to reproduce: The 7-row phoria type → management table. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Write: \\\"Explain why a child with accommodative esotropia should not have surgery before glasses, using the AC/A ratio concept. No jargon. Four sentences.\\\" This forces you to build the logical chain without falling back on memorized phrases. Teach-back prompt: Explain the full amblyopia management sequence for a 5-year-old with anisometropic amblyopia (+0.50 OD, +3.75 OS, 20/20 OD, 20/80 OS) — from first appointment to discharge. Drill 4 — Flash card prompts Front Back Sheard's criterion? Compensating recovery ≥ 2× phoria Sheard's prism formula? (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3 Prism for exophoria? BI (base-in) Prism for esophoria? BO (base-out) Prism for hyperphoria? BD before the higher eye First step for accommodative esotropia? Full cycloplegic refractive correction First step for deprivation amblyopia? Remove the opacity (surgery) then correct RE Pleoptics: indicated for? Eccentric fixation in the amblyopic eye Anisometropia threshold (Borish)? ≥ 2.00D NPC > 10 cm = ? Convergence insufficiency Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete management sequence for strabismic amblyopia — from first suspicion at case history through to discharge. Include: the role of refractive correction, the passive therapy options, the active therapy options, the binocular rehab goal, and the surgical referral criterion. Sequence to write: Strabismic amblyopia management from Step 1 to Step 4 (all sub-options included). Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st review Jun 5, 2026 (today) Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Jun 6 Blank table + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review Jun 8 Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review Jun 12 Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check Jun 19 All 5 drills; flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Vision therapy trains the binocular visual system the same way physical therapy trains a recovering muscle — not by compensating for weakness, but by rebuilding actual capacity. Prism moves the target; VT moves the eye. The clinical workflow has three steps: identify which system is broken (accommodation, vergence, or sensory fusion), confirm how severely it is broken through a targeted battery of tests, then choose the modality that addresses that specific deficit. Before prescribing VT, you need to know which muscle or system is causing the problem. For horizontal phorias, the test pattern tells you the type. For vertical deviations and paretic muscles, you use the Parks 3-step test to narrow the involved muscle from a field of eight possibilities to one. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"The patient has convergence insufficiency. You give prism. Six months later, symptoms return when the prism is removed. Why?\\\" (Prism compensated the demand; it never trained the vergence system. The answer is VT, not more prism.)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Why does VT produce durable improvement when prism does not? Prism shifts the perceived target so the eyes need less convergence to fuse it — this removes symptoms but leaves the vergence system unchanged. VT repeatedly stimulates the vergence system near and slightly beyond its current limit. Each successful fusion attempt at a higher demand level reinforces the neural drive, gradually pushing the blur and break points outward. The vergence system adapts the same way any trained skill adapts — through repetition under increasing demand. Why does the Parks 3-step test work? Six of the eight cyclovertical muscles each have a field of action where they are the primary vertical mover. When a muscle is paretic, the vertical deviation is largest in its field of action. Each step of the Parks test eliminates half the remaining candidates by identifying which eye, which gaze direction, and which head tilt produces the greatest deviation. Three binary decisions → one muscle. Why is the Brock string both a diagnostic and a therapeutic tool? The Brock string works by creating physiological diplopia — if the patient fixates one bead, the other beads appear double, and the string forms an X at the fixated bead. This requires that both eyes' inputs reach consciousness. A patient who suppresses will not see the doubled strings. Demonstrating this to the patient is the diagnosis of suppression; practicing until they consistently see the X is the beginning of treating it. The same stimulus serves both purposes. Why is patching more effective than atropine for most amblyopia? Patching creates complete occlusion of the dominant eye — the brain has no choice but to process the amblyopic eye's input. Atropine blurs the dominant eye for near only; it still provides clear distance vision, so the suppression mechanism is only partially challenged. For moderate amblyopia, the PEDIG trials showed comparable outcomes, but for deeper amblyopia, patching offers stronger and more consistent occlusion.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Orthoptics Greek orthos (straight) + ops (eye) Diagnosis and non-surgical treatment of BV anomalies; literally \\\"straight eye training\\\" Vision therapy (VT) English compound Broader term; includes accommodation, sensory fusion, and higher perceptual training — not just convergence Pleoptics Greek pleion (more) + ops Monocular technique for eccentric fixation; uses intense light to dazzle peripheral retina and rehabilitate foveal fixation Eccentric fixation Latin ex-centrum (off-center) Fixation in the amblyopic eye at a retinal point other than the fovea; marker of deep amblyopia Physiological diplopia Greek diploos (double) Normal doubling of non-fixated objects; expected finding when fusion is intact; absent when suppression is present Bielschowsky head tilt test Named: Alfred Bielschowsky (1900s) Step 3 of Parks test; tilting the head increases vertical fusion demand on cyclovertical muscles of the ipsilateral eye Synoptophore / Amblyoscope Greek synoptos (seen together) Instrument for measuring objective and subjective angle of deviation and training at all three Grades of BV CAM vision stimulator Cambridge (Univ.) Amblyopia Model Rotating high-contrast gratings; spatially stimulates amblyopic eye monocularly; 7 min/session Dichoptic training Greek dikha (separately) + optikos Presents different images to each eye simultaneously; forces cortical integration; modern active amblyopia therapy Lookalike trap: VT and orthoptics overlap but are not identical. Orthoptics (traditional term) focuses on motor alignment and convergence. VT (OEP-influenced) includes accommodation, sensory fusion, and perceptual training. In Philippine board context, the terms are used interchangeably for this section.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Vergence Training The vergence system has a homeostatic zone called the zone of clear single binocular vision (ZCSBV) — bounded by the blur point on one side (where accommodation breaks down) and the break point on the other (where fusion breaks down). VT expands this zone by repeatedly driving the vergence system to its limit and requiring successful fusion. Mechanism: sustained near vergence effort → increased motor fusion demand → neural adaptation in the vergence controller → raised blur and break thresholds → wider ZCSBV. Convergence exercises build positive fusional vergence (PFC) ; divergence exercises build negative fusional vergence (NFC) . The target is always the condition's compensating reserve — CI patients need more PFC; FVD patients need both. Accommodation Training Accommodative flexibility training (lens flippers) exploits the accommodative/vergence linkage. Every flip from minus to plus triggers relaxation of accommodation, which drives a vergence response. Training this repeatedly under time pressure improves the speed of the ciliary muscle response and the accuracy of the AC/A-driven vergence following it. Sensory / Antisuppression Training Suppression is an active cortical inhibition. It cannot be removed by demand alone — the suppressed eye's signal must first be made strong enough to compete with the dominant eye. Antisuppression training uses red-green filters, polaroids, or Bernell instruments to present stimuli that can only be seen binocularly, forcing the brain to use both eyes. Progression: peripheral stimulation first (where suppression is weaker) → central stimulation (foveal area, where suppression is strongest).\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-structure-or-process-map-the-c7-clinical-workflow\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map: The C7 Clinical Workflow\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"STEP 1: IDENTIFY THE DYSFUNCTIONAL SYSTEM (Syllabi 3.2) │ ├── VERGENCE SYSTEM │ ├── Exophoria → CI (near > distance), DE (distance > near), Basic (=) │ ├── Esophoria → CI → CE (near > distance), DI (distance > near), Basic (=) │ └── Vertical phoria → suspect cyclovertical palsy → Parks 3-step test │ ├── ACCOMMODATION SYSTEM │ ├── AI (reduced AA), ill-sustained, infacility, spasm │ └── Check: NPA , flipper test (12 cpm expected for adults) │ └── SENSORY SYSTEM ├── Suppression ( W4D , Bagolini, Worth dot) ├── ARC (Synoptophore, Hering-Bielschowsky afterimage) └── Amblyopia (VA + eccentric fixation check via visuoscopy) STEP 2: CONFIRM EXTENT OF ANOMALY (Syllabi 3.3) │ ├── NPC — CI severity; norm ≤8cm break / ≤10cm recovery ├── Prism cover test — magnitude of deviation ├── Fusional vergence ranges — blur, break, recovery at distance and near │ PFC norm near: Blur 17, Break 21, Recovery 11Δ │ NFC norm near: Blur 13, Break 21, Recovery 13Δ ├── AC/A ratio — high (CE, DE) vs low (CI, DI) ├── NRA / PRA — NRA norm +2.00D; PRA norm −2.37D ├── NPA — for accommodative disorders └── Stereoacuity — Titmus/Randot (grades binocularity level) STEP 3: TREAT (Syllabi 3.4 + C6) │ ├── Vergence dysfunction → vergence training exercises ├── Accommodation dysfunction → accommodative flexibility training ├── Suppression → antisuppression progression └── Amblyopia → patching / penalization / CAM / active therapy\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-parks-3-step-test-for-vertical-deviations\",\"heading\":\"Parks 3-Step Test (for Vertical Deviations)\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Used to identify a single paretic cyclovertical muscle when a vertical deviation is present. STEP 1 — Which eye is hypertropic? Right hypertopia → paretic muscle is in ONE of these 4: Right depressors: RSO , RIR Left elevators: LIO , LSR Left hypertopia → paretic muscle is in ONE of these 4: Left depressors: LSO , LIR Right elevators: RIO , RSR STEP 2 — In which gaze direction is the vertical deviation largest? Right gaze (adducted OS, abducted OD): • Right hyper + larger in RIGHT gaze → RSR or LIR (SR acts in abduction; IR acts in adduction) • Narrows to 2 muscles Left gaze (adducted OD, abducted OS): • Right hyper + larger in LEFT gaze → RIR or LSR • Narrows to 2 muscles STEP 3 — Bielschowsky Head Tilt Test Tilt head toward the HIGHER eye: • If deviation INCREASES → ipsilateral intorter is paretic (SO of higher eye) • If deviation DECREASES → contralateral extorter is paretic (SR of lower eye) Logic: Head tilt triggers compensatory intorsion in ipsilateral eye. If SO (primary intortor) is paretic, the SR (extortor + elevator) compensates alone → more elevation → deviation worsens. If SR is paretic, head tilt unmasks SR weakness directly. MEMORY : H-G-T (Higher eye, Gaze direction, Tilt direction) Each step cuts candidates in half: 8 → 4 → 2 → 1\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-vt-modality-reference\",\"heading\":\"VT Modality Reference\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Vergence Training Techniques Technique Target Mechanism Home or Office Pencil push-up CI Patient fixates pencil tip, brings it slowly toward nose until diplopia; holds, then recedes; 20 reps Home Brock string CI + suppression 3 beads on 5-foot string; fixate each bead sequentially; normal response = X pattern at bead; suppression = one string disappears Home and office Prism flippers FVD, CI, CE Alternate base-in and base-out prism flippers; patient clears target with each flip; builds both PFC and NFC Office and home Aperture rule trainer CI, CE Convergence or divergence through apertures; demands increase by moving aperture position Office Vectograms / tranaglyphs CI, suppression Polarized or red-green targets; can be set to different vergence demands; antisuppression rings built in Office Step vergence (prism bar) FVD Patient fuses progressively larger prism increments at distance and near; trains fusional range systematically Office Accommodation Training Techniques Technique Target Mechanism Home or Office Lens flippers ±2.00D Accommodative infacility Alternate plus and minus lenses; patient clears each side before flipping; target 12 cycles/minute for adults Home and office Hart chart Accommodation + saccades Small letter chart (near) + large letter chart (distance); patient reads alternately while maintaining clear focus Home Monocular push-up AI (reduced AA) Single-eye push-up to near point; builds monocular AA Home Antisuppression and Sensory Training Technique Target What patient does Red-green / GTVT chart Suppression Under anaglyph glasses, certain letters/lines visible to one eye only; patient reports what they see; increases awareness of suppression Bernell red light stimulation Amblyopia Monocular exposure to red light; stimulates retinal function; check VA improvement after exposure Synoptophore grades Sensory fusion Progress from Grade I (SMP) → Grade II (flat fusion) → Grade III (stereopsis) using matched slides; builds up BV grades systematically Brock string Suppression As above; physiological diplopia training is antisuppression in function Amblyopia-Specific Techniques Technique Mechanism Key Facts Patching (occlusion) Occludes dominant eye; brain forced to use amblyopic eye Part-time (2-6 hrs/day) = as effective as full-time for moderate amblyopia (PEDIG trials); compliance is the main barrier Atropine penalization 1% atropine in dominant eye blurs near vision; amblyopic eye is clearer for near No patch; avoids compliance battle; risk = photophobia in dominant eye; comparable to patching for moderate amblyopia CAM vision stimulator Rotating high-contrast gratings stimulate spatial frequency channels in amblyopic visual cortex Done MONOCULARLY (non-amblyopic eye occluded); 7 min/session, once/week, 10-20 sessions; check VA before and after each session Pleoptics Intense light dazzles peripheral retina; fovea functions better in relative isolation after dazzle For eccentric fixation specifically; largely replaced by patching; expensive equipment; inferior VA gains vs conventional patching Perceptual learning / dichoptic training Repeated practice of specific visual tasks improves neural efficiency; dichoptic forces cortical integration Modern; home-based versions using video games or apps; promising for older patients and adults Near activities (paper-based) Reading, writing, puzzles under minimal occlusion (1 hr/day) Von Noorden: minimal occlusion + near activities effective for older children Pegboard stimulator Eye-hand coordination + antisuppression Child places golf tees in rotating pegboard under patch or binocularly; speed increases as skill improves\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"VT vs Prism — Key Distinction Prism VT What it changes The stimulus location The vergence capacity Effect on fusional range None Blur and break points shift outward Durability Temporary; symptoms return when removed Durable when therapy is completed Best candidate Elderly, presbyopes, low compliance Children and motivated adults When to use Phoria fails Sheard's/Percival's + poor VT candidate Phoria fails Sheard's/Percival's + patient can comply Suppression vs Amblyopia — Don't Conflate Suppression Amblyopia Mechanism Active cortical inhibition (facultative or obligatory) End-result reduced VA from obligatory suppression VA reduction Only if obligatory Yes — defining feature Treatment Antisuppression VT Optical correction + patching/penalization + VT Can exist without the other Yes (facultative suppression = no VA loss) No — amblyopia requires prior obligatory suppression Patching vs Atropine (PEDIG Comparison) Full-time patching Part-time patching Atropine Moderate amblyopia (20/40–20/100) Effective Equally effective Comparable Deep amblyopia (>20/100) Preferred — Less effective Compliance Hardest Easier Easiest Side effect Occlusion amblyopia risk if over-patched Less risk Photophobia in dominant eye\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"NPC norm (Scheiman & Wick) Break ≤8cm, Recovery ≤10cm >10cm break = CI suspected Near PFC norm (Morgan) Blur 17, Break 21, Recovery 11Δ Reduced PFC near = CI or FVD Near NFC norm (Morgan) Blur 13, Break 21, Recovery 13Δ Distance PFC norm Blur 9, Break 19, Recovery 10Δ Distance NFC norm Blur 7, Break 11, Recovery 8Δ NRA norm +2.00D Reduced = AI or CI PRA norm −2.37D Reduced = CE or high AC/A Lens flipper target (adults) 12 cycles per minute (cpm) Accommodative infacility criterion Patching dose (moderate amblyopia) 2-6 hours/day PEDIG standard; part-time as effective as full-time CAM session duration 7 min/session, 1x/week, 10-20 sessions Stop if no improvement after few sessions Atropine penalization dose 1% atropine in dominant eye Blurs dominant eye for near; retains clear distance Amblyopia critical period 0-2 yrs (most sensitive); treat to 7-8; possible to 12-18 → see B5 and C6 Visuoscopy eccentric fixation 2° nasal = fixates 2° nasal to fovea Degree + direction reported\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Parks 3-step mnemonic — HGT (High, Gaze, Tilt) H igh eye → which eye is hypertropic? (picks 4 muscles) G aze → which gaze makes it worse? (picks 2 muscles) T ilt → Bielschowsky head tilt toward higher eye (picks 1 muscle) Each step halves the candidates: 8 → 4 → 2 → 1 VT modality by condition: CI → Brock string + pencil push-up + aperture rule + prism flippers CE → NRA exercise + lens flippers (plus) + divergence training FVD → step vergence (both BI and BO) + vectograms AI → push-up training + Hart chart Infacility → lens flippers (±2.00D) to 12 cpm Suppression → antisuppression charts → Brock string → vectogram → synoptophore grades Amblyopia → patch or atropine → CAM or near activities → active VT if plateau Pleoptics = eccentric fixation (not standard amblyopia) Pleoptics ≠ patching. Pleoptics is for patients who cannot use their fovea because it is suppressed by a non-foveal fixation reflex. For standard strabismic or anisometropic amblyopia, patching is the first line. CAM is monocular — common exam trap The non-amblyopic eye is OCCLUDED during CAM. The amblyopic eye alone is stimulated. Confusing CAM with binocular therapies is a common wrong answer. Brock string normal response = X pattern If the patient sees only one string line (no X at the bead), one eye's signal is suppressed. This is both the test positive for suppression AND the target to overcome in therapy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-visual-map-vt-modality-decision-tree\",\"heading\":\"VT Modality Decision Tree\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Identify BV anomaly │ ├── VERGENCE dysfunction │ ├── CI ( NPC receded, PFC near low) → Pencil push-up, Brock string, aperture rule, prism BO flipper │ ├── CE (eso at near, high AC/A) → NRA exercise, divergence training, BI prism flipper │ ├── DI (eso at distance > near) → Divergence training at distance │ ├── DE (exo at distance > near) → Convergence training at distance │ └── FVD (phorias normal, ranges low) → Step vergence, vectograms (both directions) │ ├── ACCOMMODATION dysfunction │ ├── AI (low AA) → Push-up training, monocular near tasks │ ├── Infacility (slow) → Lens flippers ±2.00D, Hart chart │ └── Ill-sustained (fatigues) → Gradual near work stamina building, plus at near │ └── SENSORY dysfunction ├── Suppression → Antisuppression progression: │ Peripheral ( GTVT chart, red-green filters) │ → Central (Brock string, vectograms) │ → Synoptophore Grade I → II → III │ └── Amblyopia → Optical correction first → Patching or atropine → CAM (if eccentric fixation or plateau) → Active VT (dichoptic, perceptual learning)\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-visual-map-parks-3-step-decision-tree-right-hypertopia-example\",\"heading\":\"Parks 3-Step Decision Tree (Right Hypertopia example)\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Right hyper → 4 candidates: RSO , RIR , LIO , LSR │ ├── Larger in RIGHT gaze → RSO or LIR │ ├── Head tilt RIGHT (toward higher eye = OD) → INCREASES → RSO paretic ✓ │ └── Head tilt RIGHT → DECREASES → LIR paretic ✓ │ └── Larger in LEFT gaze → RIR or LSR ├── Head tilt RIGHT → INCREASES → RIR paretic (IR acts in adduction = left gaze field) └── Head tilt RIGHT → DECREASES → LSR paretic\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Item Key Fact VT mechanism Expands ZCSBV by training near the vergence system's limit; prism only compensates Parks 3-step HGT: which eye is Higher, which Gaze worsens it, which head Tilt worsens it → 8 → 4 → 2 → 1 Brock string normal X pattern at fixated bead; absent X = suppression NPC norm Break ≤8cm, Recovery ≤10cm (Scheiman & Wick) Near PFC norm Blur 17 / Break 21 / Recovery 11Δ NRA norm +2.00D; reduced = AI or CI Patching dose 2-6 hrs/day; part-time = full-time for moderate amblyopia (PEDIG) Atropine effect Blurs dominant eye for NEAR; amblyopic eye clearer at near; retains distance vision CAM Monocular (occlude dominant eye); 7 min/session, 1x/week, 10-20 sessions Pleoptics Eccentric fixation only; peripheral dazzle → foveal rehab; largely historical Lens flippers ±2.00D; target 12 cpm adults; treats accommodative infacility Hart chart Accommodation + saccades; near-to-distance alternation Antisuppression progression Peripheral → central → Synoptophore Grade I → II → III Sheard's/Percival's/Neumuller's Criteria for PRISM prescription — see B5-01\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Q1. A 10-year-old presents with blurred near vision, frequent headaches, and NPC of 14cm (break). Near PFC blur is 8Δ. Sheard's criterion is NOT met. Full refractive correction has been given. The most appropriate next management step is: A. Add base-out prism to spectacles B. Prescribe base-in prism at near C. Begin vision therapy with convergence exercises D. Refer for strabismus surgery Answer C — Vision therapy with convergence exercises The findings indicate convergence insufficiency (NPC > 10cm, reduced near PFC). Full correction was already given (Rung 1). The child is 10 years old — a good VT candidate. Sheard's failure in a child with CI is the prime indication for VT. Base-out prism at near (B) would worsen convergence demand. BI prism (A) compensates but does not train. Surgery (D) is for tropias, not phoria anomalies. Q2. A patient has right hypertropia. The deviation is largest in left gaze. On Bielschowsky head tilt to the RIGHT, the deviation INCREASES. Which muscle is paretic? A. Right Superior Oblique B. Right Inferior Rectus C. Left Superior Rectus D. Left Inferior Oblique Answer B — Right Inferior Rectus Parks 3-step: Right hyper → 4 candidates (RSO, RIR, LIO, LSR). Larger in LEFT gaze → narrows to RIR or LSR (the muscles with field of action in left gaze for the right hyper group — IR acts in adduction which is left gaze for OD). Head tilt to RIGHT (toward higher eye, OD) INCREASES the deviation → the ipsilateral intortor (RSO) cannot compensate, but wait — if RSO was paretic, tilt right would increase because SO fails; but we already narrowed to RIR or LSR. Tilt RIGHT increases → RIR is paretic (tilt toward higher eye + increase = the depressor of the higher eye is at fault). LSR would show decrease on right tilt.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-pen-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen & Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump: Close this note. On a blank sheet, write: (1) the 5 VT modalities for CI in order of increasing complexity, (2) the Parks 3-step sequence with the logic at each step, (3) the full amblyopia treatment hierarchy from optical correction through active VT. Time yourself — 8 minutes max. Drill 2 — Blank Table: Draw a table with rows: Pencil push-up, Brock string, Prism flipper, Aperture rule, Vectogram, Lens flipper, Hart chart. Columns: Target condition, Home or office, What the patient actually does. Fill it from memory. Check against this note and circle errors. Drill 3 — Teach-Back: Explain the Parks 3-step test to an imaginary student without using the words \\\"superior oblique,\\\" \\\"inferior rectus,\\\" or \\\"tilt.\\\" You must describe the logic of why each step narrows the candidates using muscle anatomy alone. Drill 4 — Flash Card Pairs: NPC norm → Break ≤8cm / Recovery ≤10cm Near PFC norm → Blur 17 / Break 21 / Recovery 11Δ CAM procedure → Monocular, 7 min, 1x/week, 10-20 sessions Brock string normal finding → X pattern at fixated bead Pleoptics indication → Eccentric fixation (not standard amblyopia) Lens flipper target → 12 cpm adults (accommodative infacility) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch: Without looking, write out the Parks 3-step procedure step by step for a patient with LEFT hypertropia. List the 4 candidates at Step 1, show how each gaze direction narrows it to 2, and show how head tilt to the LEFT either increases or decreases the deviation for each of the final 2 candidates.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7-01-vision-therapy-and-orthoptics-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"C7-01 — Vision Therapy and Orthoptics\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. JCC axis/power — cue: which dot position the patient prefers. Prefers P1 (red dots ∥ tentative axis) → cyl under-powered → add minus cyl . Prefers P2 (white dots ∥ axis) → reduce minus . Trap: adding cylinder when the patient actually preferred P2. Duochrome — cue: red side vs green side clearer. Green clearer → over-minused → add plus / reduce minus. Red clearer → add minus. (RAM-GAP: Red Add Minus, Green Add Plus.) Trap: over-minusing a patient who says green is clearer. Cover test phoria vs tropia — cue: movement on cover vs without cover. Moves only when covered (recovers on uncover) = phoria. Moves without cover = tropia. Trap: calling a phoria a tropia because the eye moved — a phoria only moves under cover. Prism for phoria — cue: exo / eso / hyper. Exophoria → BI , esophoria → BO , hyperphoria → BD before the higher eye . Trap: base-out for exo (it's base-in). Retinoscopy reflex — cue: with vs against motion. With motion → add plus (under-plussed/hyperopic). Against → add minus. Neutral = endpoint (+ working distance). Trap: forgetting to subtract the working-distance lens at the end.\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"C.strategy\",\"subject\":\"C\",\"label\":\"Primary Care & Refraction — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/C-Primary-Care-and-Refraction/C-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Primary Care and Refraction · the read-before-you-test reference for all 7 topics C1 Epi C2 Ametropia C3 Prelim C4 Objective C5 Subjective C6 Management C7 VT\"},{\"anchor\":\"c1\",\"heading\":\"C1Epidemiology & Prevention\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Headline fact: the two leading causes of global vision impairment are uncorrected refractive error and cataract , and over 80% of VI is avoidable . EPIC sizes: Endemic (constant, low) < Epidemic (regional outbreak) < Pandemic (across regions). Incidence = new cases; prevalence = all existing cases. Prevention 1-2-3: primary = prevent onset; secondary = detect/reverse early; tertiary = limit disability. Philippines: cataract is the leading cause of blindness. WHO founded April 7, 1948. Trap: incidence and prevalence are the same. No — incidence is new cases over time; prevalence is all existing cases at a point.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c2\",\"heading\":\"C2Ametropia & Refractive Errors\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Corrections: myopia → minus; hyperopia → plus; astigmatism → cylinder; presbyopia → plus add. Hofstetter: Min = 15 − 0.25(age); Ave = 18.5 − 0.30(age); Max = 25 − 0.40(age). Far point: emmetrope = ∞; −3 D myope = 33 cm; hyperope = virtual (behind eye). Astigmatism: WTR steep at 90° (youth); ATR steep at 180° (age). Total hyperopia = latent + manifest. Pseudomyopia = accommodative spasm that clears under cycloplegia. Retinoscopy: at 67 cm subtract 1.50 D; with motion = add plus, against motion = add minus . Hyperope + eso at near + high AC/A = accommodative esotropia (treat with full plus). Trap: hyperopes always see distance clearly. No — absolute hyperopes are blurred at all distances. Trap: WTR is more common in the elderly. No — WTR is common in youth; ATR increases with age.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c3\",\"heading\":\"C3Preliminary Examination\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Pinhole: improves VA → refractive (correctable); no improvement → organic disease. Far VA at 6 m, near at 40 cm. Binocular VA should be ≥ the better monocular eye. Reflexes: corneal reflex temporal = eso , nasal = exo. Pupillary light reflex branches at the pretectal nucleus (before the LGN). Near triad = constriction + accommodation + convergence. NPC norm break ~7 cm (>10 = CI, <5 = CE). Unilateral cover test distinguishes phoria vs tropia; alternating cover gives total deviation only. RAPD (Marcus Gunn) = swinging flashlight. Headaches: Frontal = hyperopia/CE · Temporal = astigmatism · Occipital = presbyopia/CI. Trap: a nasal corneal reflex means esotropia. No — temporal reflex = eso; nasal = exo. Trap: the alternating cover test tells phoria from tropia. No — it shows total deviation; use the unilateral cover test to differentiate.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c4\",\"heading\":\"C4Objective Examination\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Direct Indirect Image Virtual, erect, ~15x Real, inverted, 2–5x Field ~6.5° (disc detail) ~40° (periphery) Higher condensing lens (e.g. +20 vs +14) = wider field, less magnification. Van Herick: grade 3–4 safe to dilate; grade 0–1 do not dilate. Javal's rule: At = 1.25(Ac) + (−0.50 cyl × 90°); internal astigmatism ≈ −0.50 × 90° (ATR). Keratometer measures the anterior corneal surface only (n ≈ 1.3375). Filters: cobalt blue = fluorescein staining; red-free (green) = blood vessels. Opacity parallax: anterior moves opposite the scope, posterior moves with it. Trap: direct ophthalmoscopy gives an inverted image. No — direct is erect/virtual; indirect is inverted/real. Trap: a stronger condensing lens magnifies more. No — higher power = wider field, LESS magnification.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c5\",\"heading\":\"C5Subjective Examination\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Fog +0.50 to +0.75 D above best sphere (target 20/30–20/40). Astigmatic dial: darkest line = power meridian ; minus-cyl axis is 90° from it. Add +0.25 D sphere per −0.50 D cyl. JCC: prefer Position 1 (red dots ∥ axis) → cylinder under-powered → add minus . Prefer Position 2 → reduce minus. Rotation method for cyl > 0.75 D; JCC for ≤ 0.75 D. Duochrome: G reen clearer → G ive plus / reduce minus (over-minused). Red clearer → add minus. Invalid in red-green color deficiency. Binocular balance: re-fog +0.50–0.75 D to BOTH eyes; dissociate 3Δ BD OD / 3Δ BU OS; if +0.25 reverses preference, let the dominant eye keep better VA. PRA = add minus; NRA = add plus. OEP #7 endpoint = MPMVA. Trap: the darkest astigmatic-dial line is the axis. No — it is the power meridian; the minus-cyl axis is 90° away.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c6\",\"heading\":\"C6Management of Visual Disorders\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Management order: correct refractive error → prism → vision therapy → surgery. Prism: exophoria → base in; esophoria → base out; hyperphoria → base down before the higher eye. Sheard's prism = (2 × phoria − recovery) ÷ 3. Amblyopia: correct the Rx first; patch the GOOD eye (or atropine-penalize the good eye). Surgery aligns but does NOT treat amblyopia. Pleoptics is for eccentric fixation only. Critical period most sensitive 0–2 years. Accommodative esotropia: full cycloplegic hyperopic correction first. Over-patching risks rebound amblyopia. Distinguish divergence insufficiency (comitant) from CN6 palsy (incomitant). Trap: under-correct the amblyopic eye to avoid stress. No — it needs the clearest image; under-correction perpetuates suppression. Trap: surgery cures amblyopia. No — it only corrects alignment; acuity still needs patching/penalization/VT.\"},{\"anchor\":\"c7\",\"heading\":\"C7Vision Therapy & Orthoptics\",\"topic\":\"Subject C — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Glasses first, always. VT expands fusional capacity; prism only compensates. Sheard's/Percival's decide prism , not VT. Parks 3-step (vertical deviations only): Higher eye → worse Gaze → worse Tilt, narrowing 8 → 4 → 2 → 1 candidate muscles. Brock string: normal = X at the fixated bead; absent X = suppression (diagnostic AND therapeutic). CAM is monocular (occlude the dominant eye), ~7 min, weekly. Lens flippers ±2.00 D, target ~12 cpm. CI office sequence: pencil push-ups → Brock string → aperture rule → prism/vectogram flippers. Part-time patching (2–6 hrs) ≈ full-time for moderate amblyopia (PEDIG); stop only at equalization or plateau. Trap: CAM is done with both eyes open. No — it is monocular; the dominant eye is occluded. Trap: Parks 3-step works for horizontal phorias. No — vertical (cyclovertical) deviations only. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject C strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"D.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"D\",\"label\":\"Theoretical Optics & CL — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/D-Theoretical-Optics-Dispensing-CL/D-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Every calculation item in Theoretical Optics is one of about fifty formulas, and you only ever need one of them per question. The hard part of a TO problem is almost never the algebra. It is picking the right formula in ten seconds and not losing the mark on a unit or a sign. This page is the pick-and-check layer. It holds the formula, what each symbol is, the unit that must be used, and the single mistake that most often costs the mark. It does not re-teach the formulas. The derivation, the analogy and the reason each one has the form it does live in D1-01, D1-02, D1-03, D2-01 and D3-01, and every entry here points back to where its explanation sits. Use it two ways: as the last sweep before a paper, and as a blank-sheet target where you rewrite the whole vault from memory.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"TO is the most arithmetic-heavy subject on the OLE, and the marks in it are lost in a very narrow band. Reviewing past preboard misses, almost none were \\\"I did not know the formula.\\\" They were mm used where cm was required, a base direction flipped, a transposition axis off by the wrong 90, or a resultant prism added instead of squared. That failure pattern is why a scattered set of formulas across five long notes is a problem. When a formula lives inside a twelve-page topic note, you meet it once, in context, with the answer already framed. On the exam you meet it cold, out of order, with four options engineered around the exact slip you are prone to. Those are different retrieval tasks. Collecting them onto one page forces the comparison the exam forces: which of these fifty is this, and what is different about it from its neighbour. Prentice next to the prism-diopter definition makes the cm-versus-mm split obvious. Effective power next to vertex conversion makes it clear they are the same formula read in two directions. That adjacency is the actual value here, not the convenience of a lookup.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-how-to-use-this-page\",\"heading\":\"How to Use This Page\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"During a paper, in this order: Read the last line of the stem first. What is being asked for decides the formula, not the story before it. Name the block. Vergence, refraction, imaging, prism, Rx algebra, thick lens, dispensing, CL, accommodation. Nine possibilities, not fifty. Convert units before you touch the algebra. Write the converted numbers down. Compute the magnitude. Settle the sign or direction last, as a separate decision. Roughly half of the engineered distractors in D are your correct magnitude with the direction flipped. Before a paper: cover the Formula column of any block and rebuild it from the Use it when column. That is retrieval; reading the page is not.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-master-index-cue-to-formula\",\"heading\":\"Master Index — Cue to Formula\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Scan the stem for the cue, jump to the block. Stem cue Block Formula to reach for Focal length given, power asked (or reverse) 1 D = 1/f Radius of curvature + two indices 1 D = (n₂ − n₁)/R Speed of light in a material 1 n = c/v \\\"Far point of a −3.00 myope\\\" 1 far point cm = 100/D Two angles at a boundary 2 Snell \\\"Total internal reflection\\\", \\\"critical angle\\\" 2 sin CA = n₂/n₁ Glass slab, ray displaced sideways 2 d = t·sin(i − R)/cos R \\\"Apparent depth\\\", coin in water 2 q = p(n'/n) \\\"% reflected per surface\\\", AR coating 2 Reflectance formula Object distance + focal length, image asked 3 1/p + 1/q = 1/f Mirror with radius given 3 f = R/2 \\\"How many times larger\\\", \\\"erect or inverted\\\" 3 m = −q/p Decentration in mm + lens power 4 Prentice P = d × F Prism diopters to degrees, or apical angle 4 Δ = 100 tan θ; a = θ/(n − 1) Sphero-cyl Rx + a named meridian 4 D(θ) = Sph + Cyl·sin²α A vertical AND a horizontal prism given 4 r = √(v² + h²) Two cylinders at different axes 4 Obliquely crossed cylinders Bifocal segment type + add power 4 Image jump I = h × D_add \\\"Express in plus cyl\\\", flipped axis options 5 Transposition Two cylinders written as a cross 5 Cross-cyl to sphero-cyl \\\"Reading Rx\\\", \\\"intermediate Rx\\\" 5 Sphere + add, sphere + ½ add Front and back surface + thickness 6 Dn, Deq, BVP, FVP Vertex distance changes, or specs to CL 6 D_new = D/(1 − d·D) \\\"Image size difference\\\", aniseikonia 6 SM, CLM, RSM Lens thickness, lens clock, caliper 7 Sagitta Frame PD, patient PD, eye size, DBL 7 Decentration, inset \\\"How much should the lens be decentred to give X prism\\\" 7 d = P/D K readings + spectacle cyl 8 Residual astigmatism CL power from spectacle Rx 8 Vertex conversion Age given, amplitude asked 9 Hofstetter Retinoscopy gross finding 9 Subtract working distance\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-1-vergence-and-power\",\"heading\":\"Block 1 — Vergence and Power\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"The foundation block. Anything downstream that says \\\"power\\\" assumes these. Formula Use it when The trap D = 1/f (f in m) Focal length to power, or back Using cm without converting D = 100/f (f in cm) The clinical default Forgetting that 100 is only for cm D = 1000/f (f in mm) Radii, sags, CL specs Using 100 with mm, off by 10× D = 40/f (f in inches) Older Philippine board items Rare but it does appear D = (n₂ − n₁)/R (R in m) Single refracting surface Subtracting the indices backwards D = 1000(n₂ − n₁)/R (R in mm) Corneal surfaces, CL surfaces The 1000 belongs to mm only n = c/v and v = c/n Speed of light in a medium n is always ≥ 1; an answer below 1 is wrong far point (cm) = 100/D Punctum remotum of an ametrope Myope's far point is in front, hyperope's is virtual and behind D_total = D₁ + D₂ Thin lenses in contact Only valid in contact; separated lenses need thick-lens formulas SURFACE POWER , worked both ways on the cornea: Anterior: D = 1000(1.376 − 1.000) / 7.7 = +48.83 D Posterior: D = 1000(1.336 − 1.376) / 6.8 = −5.88 D Net corneal power ≈ 48.83 − 5.88 ≈ +43 D The posterior surface is minus because n DROPS across it (1.376 → 1.336). That sign is the whole reason the cornea is 43 D and not 49 D. Sign of R: positive when the surface is convex toward the incoming light, negative when concave toward it. Get R's sign right and the power sign takes care of itself. Depth: D1-01 Formula 2 and Formula 5, D1-02 Formula 6.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-2-refraction-index-and-surface-losses\",\"heading\":\"Block 2 — Refraction, Index, and Surface Losses\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Formula Use it when The trap n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R Any ray crossing a boundary Angles are measured from the NORMAL, not the surface sin CA = n₂/n₁ Critical angle, TIR Only exists going dense to rare; n₁ must be the bigger one d = t·sin(i − R)/cos R Plane parallel slab, lateral shift You must solve Snell for R first q = p × (n'/n) Apparent depth, shallowing Observer's index goes on top Reflectance % = [(n' − n)/(n' + n)]² × 100 Light lost per surface The whole bracket is squared, then ×100 AR coating thickness = λ/4 Why AR works Quarter wave, not half CRITICAL ANGLE , three materials: Crown glass → air: sin CA = 1.000/1.523 → CA = 41.04° Polycarbonate → air: sin CA = 1.000/1.586 → CA = 39.27° Diamond → air: sin CA = 1.000/2.417 → CA = 24.44° Rule: higher n → LOWER critical angle → TIR happens more easily. REFLECTANCE , CR-39 (n = 1.498), the number to be able to rebuild: = [(1.49 − 1)/(1.49 + 1)]² × 100 = (0.49/2.49)² × 100 = 3.87 % per surface Uncoated, two surfaces: ~7.75 % lost, ~92 % transmitted Single AR (back only): ~4.45 % lost, ~95.5 % transmitted Multicoat (both): ~3.87 % lost, ~96 % transmitted Direction rule, worth more than the formula: low n to high n bends TOWARD the normal. High n to low n bends AWAY. If your computed R is on the wrong side of i, you inverted the ratio. Depth: D1-01 Formula 1, D1-02 Formulas 3 and 4, D2-01 AR Coating.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-3-image-formation-lenses-and-mirrors\",\"heading\":\"Block 3 — Image Formation, Lenses and Mirrors\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"One equation covers both lenses and mirrors. What changes is which physical side \\\"positive q\\\" lands on. Formula Use it when The trap 1/p + 1/q = 1/f Any thin lens or mirror Mixing units between p, q and f f = R/2 Mirror with radius given Only mirrors; a lens surface uses Block 1 m = −q/p = i/o Size and orientation Dropping the minus and reporting a real image as upright p = q = 2f, m = −1 \\\"Same size\\\" stems This is the symmetry point, not an arbitrary case minimum object-to-image separation = 4f Bench problems Below 4f no real image forms at any lens position The zone table. This answers most image-formation items without any arithmetic at all: Object position q m Image Infinity +f 0 Point image at F Beyond 2F between f and 2f negative, \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Real, inverted, minified At 2F 2f −1 Real, inverted, same size Between F and 2F beyond 2f negative, \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Real, inverted, magnified At F infinity undefined No image, rays emerge parallel Inside F negative positive, \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Virtual, upright, magnified Any position, minus lens or convex mirror negative positive, \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Virtual, upright, minified Two reads that skip the algebra: Sign of m gives orientation. Positive is upright, negative is inverted. Magnitude of m gives size. Whichever of object or image sits farther from the element is the bigger one. A minus lens is always virtual, always upright, always smaller, at every object distance. No calculation needed. Depth: D1-02 Formulas 2 and 5, D1-03 in full.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-4-prism\",\"heading\":\"Block 4 — Prism\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"The densest block on the OLE and the one where direction, not magnitude, decides the mark. Formula Use it when The trap P = d × F (d in cm) Prismatic effect off-centre d in mm gives an answer 10× too small P = (mm × D)/10 Same rule, exam shortcut None; this form exists to stop the mm slip Δ = 100 tan θ Prism diopters to degrees tan, never sin Δ = displacement (cm) / distance (m) The definition itself Mixed units are the definition, not a mistake a = θ/(n − 1) Apical angle of a prism θ is the deviation in degrees, not the Δ value D(θ) = Sph + Cyl·sin²α Power in a named meridian α is measured from the CYL AXIS, not from 180 r = √(v² + h²) Resultant of two prisms Adding v + h instead of the hypotenuse tan α = v/h Base direction of the resultant Reference angle only; the quadrant still has to be placed v = r·sin α , h = r·cos α Splitting one oblique prism Only if α is measured from horizontal I = h × D_add Image jump at a bifocal h is seg top to seg OPTICAL CENTRE, in cm Image displacement = DIP + NIP Total effect at reading level Two separate Prentice calculations, then combine POWER IN AN OBLIQUE MERIDIAN , the two anchors: Meridian = the cyl axis → α = 0 → sin²0 = 0 → answer is the SPHERE ALONE Meridian ⊥ to the cyl axis → α = 90 → sin²90 = 1 → answer is SPHERE + FULL CYL Anything between takes a fraction. At 45° away, sin²45 = 0.5, exactly half the cyl. RESULTANT PRISM , full worked shape: Vertical component v = 1.0Δ Base Down Horizontal component h = 1.5Δ Base Out Magnitude: r = √(1.0² + 1.5²) = √3.25 = 1.8Δ Reference: α = arctan(v/h) = arctan(1.0/1.5) = 33.7° Quadrant: down and out → 180-270° for OD Placed: 180 + 33.7 = 213.7° Sanity check that costs one second: r must be BIGGER than either component and SMALLER than their sum. Here 1.5 < 1.8 < 2.5. ✓ SEGMENT OPTICAL CENTRE DISTANCES (the h in image jump): Round-top (Kryptok) → 11 mm → h = 1.1 cm Flat-top ( FT-28 /35) → 7 mm → h = 0.7 cm Ultex → 20 mm → h = 2.0 cm Executive / Franklin → 0 mm → h = 0 → ZERO IMAGE JUMP The Executive answer is a fact, not a calculation. Its OC sits on the seg line. Base direction, the two wordings. They give opposite answers and the stem's exact phrasing decides which applies. \\\"Decentred\\\" → plus lens SAME direction, minus lens OPPOSITE. \\\"From the optical centre\\\", or the OC does not match the PD → plus lens OPPOSITE, minus lens SAME. Quadrant placement for the resultant (OD; mirror the horizontal component for OS): up and in → α · up and out → 180 − α · down and out → 180 + α · down and in → 360 − α The engineered distractor is the mirror quadrant, which is the correct answer for the other eye. Check OD versus OS before committing. Depth: D1-01 Formula 3, D1-02 Formula 7, D2-01 Resultant Prism and Image Jump, D2-01 Fast Picks.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-5-prescription-algebra\",\"heading\":\"Block 5 — Prescription Algebra\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"No units and no physics here, only bookkeeping. Which is exactly why the losses are careless ones. Transposition, three steps: 1. New sphere = old sphere + old cylinder (algebraic) 2. New cylinder = same magnitude, FLIPPED sign 3. New axis = old axis ± 90 (keep the result in 0-180) add 90 if axis ≤ 90, subtract 90 if axis > 90 Example: Plano −2.00 × 45 sphere = 0 + (−2.00) = −2.00 cyl = +2.00 axis = 45 + 90 = 135 Result = −2.00 +2.00 × 135 The optical cross check. Thirty seconds, and it catches every transposition slip: At the CYL AXIS meridian: power = sphere alone At the meridian 90° AWAY : power = sphere + cylinder Original Plano −2.00 × 45 → at 45°: 0.00 D at 135°: −2.00 D Transposed −2.00 +2.00 × 135 → at 135°: −2.00 D at 45°: 0.00 D ✓ If the two crosses do not match, the transposition is wrong. No exceptions. Cross-cylinder to sphero-cylinder: Given a cross such as −2.50 × 155 = +1.50 × 65 1. Pick either cylinder → it becomes the SPHERE 2. New cylinder = (the other cylinder) − (the one you picked) 3. New axis = the axis of the cylinder you did NOT pick Picking −2.50: sph −2.50, cyl = +1.50 − (−2.50) = +4.00, axis 65 → −2.50 +4.00 × 65 Picking +1.50: sph +1.50, cyl = −2.50 − (+1.50) = −4.00, axis 155 → +1.50 −4.00 × 155 Both are correct and both describe the same lens. Match whichever form the options use. Sphero-cylinder to cross-cylinder: Given +3.25 −0.50 × 90 Cylinder 1 = the sphere, at an axis 90° from the given axis: +3.25 × 180 Cylinder 2 = sphere + cyl, at the given axis: +2.75 × 90 Result: +3.25 × 180 = +2.75 × 90 Reading and intermediate prescriptions: Want Formula What stays fixed Reading Rx sphere = distance sphere + full add Cylinder and axis unchanged Intermediate Rx sphere = distance sphere + (½ × add) Cylinder and axis unchanged Toric transposition, the three forms. These come up as multi-step fabrication items: Form Meaning Where the cylinder goes SVTT Single vision toric Convert to PLUS cyl; base curve on the front; back sphere = plus sph − BC FBTT Fused bifocal toric Convert to MINUS cyl; front stays a sphere; toric on the back UBTT Ultex / one-piece bifocal toric Convert to PLUS cyl; toric on the FRONT; back sphere = negative BC BASE CURVE SELECTION (used in toric transposition): Rx −2.25 to −4.00 D → BC 4.00 D Rx +2.00 to −2.00 D → BC 6.00 D Rx +2.25 to +4.50 D → BC 8.00 D Executive and Franklin bifocals are one-piece, so they take UBTT. Fused segments take FBTT. Name the seg type first and the form follows. Depth: D1-01 Formula Breakdown transposition subsections, D2-01 Toric Transposition.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-6-thick-lens-vertex-distance-and-magnification\",\"heading\":\"Block 6 — Thick Lens, Vertex Distance, and Magnification\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"The one formula family where lens thickness stops being ignorable. Formula Use it when The trap Dn = D₁ + D₂ Nominal (approximate) power This is the value that ignores thickness Deq = D₁ + D₂ − (t/n)(D₁ × D₂) Equivalent power The product term carries its own sign BVP = Dn + (t/n)(D₁)² Back vertex, what the lensometer reads Uses the FRONT surface power, squared FVP = Dn + (t/n)(D₂)² Front vertex, neutralising power Uses the BACK surface power, squared D_new = D/(1 − d × D) Vertex change, specs to CL and back d in METRES; 14 mm is 0.014 SM = 1/[(1 − (t/n)D₁) × (1 − d·F_v)] Spectacle magnification Two factors, both denominators CLM = 1 − d × D_Spec CL versus spectacle image size Note it is a subtraction, not a division THICK LENS , one worked set so the pattern is visible (t = 7 mm, n = 1.6, D₁ = +12.00, D₂ = −5.00): t/n = 0.007/1.6 = 0.004375 Dn = +12.00 + (−5.00) = +7.00 D Deq = +7.00 − 0.004375 × (+12.00 × −5.00) = +7.00 + 0.26 = +7.26 D BVP = +7.00 + 0.004375 × (+12.00)² = +7.00 + 0.63 = +7.63 D FVP = +7.00 + 0.004375 × (−5.00)² = +7.00 + 0.11 = +7.11 D Read the pattern: BVP uses D₁², FVP uses D₂², Deq uses the product. All three start from Dn. That is the only thing to remember. VERTEX CONVERSION , the direction that trips people: D_new = D / (1 − d × D) d in metres, POSITIVE when moving the lens CLOSER −8.00 D spectacle at 4 mm vertex, what does it become at the cornea? = −8.00 / (1 − 0.004 × (−8.00)) = −8.00 / (1 + 0.032) = −8.00 / 1.032 = −7.75 D Sanity check: moving a MINUS lens closer to the eye needs LESS minus. Moving a PLUS lens closer needs MORE plus. If your answer moved the wrong way, the sign inside the bracket is flipped. When it matters. Below about 4.00 D the vertex correction rounds away. Above it, the exam expects it. A stem that bothers to tell you the vertex distance is telling you to use it. Relative spectacle magnification, and the choice it drives: Ametropia type With spectacles With CLs Which to prefer Refractive (aphakia, corneal astigmatism) RSM = 1 + d·F_Spec RSM ≈ 1 Contact lenses Axial (most myopia) RSM ≈ 1 RSM = 1 − (f_eye − 1.55)·F_Spec Spectacles Myope: specs minify, CLs give a bigger image. Hyperope: specs magnify, CLs give a smaller image. Aphakia in spectacles runs about +30 % magnification, which is why CLs are the answer to almost every aphakia-plus-aniseikonia stem. Depth: D1-01 Thick Lenses, D2-01 Effective Power and Spectacle Magnification, D3-01 CL Optics.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-7-dispensing-and-fabrication\",\"heading\":\"Block 7 — Dispensing and Fabrication\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Formula Use it when The trap s = r − √(r² − y²) Exact sagitta y is the SEMI-diameter, half the lens size s ≈ y²/(2r) Approximate sagitta Fine when y is small relative to r D = 1000 × s × 2(n − 1)/A² Surface power from calipers A is also a semi-diameter T_true = D_marked × (n − 1)/0.530 Lens clock on non-crown material The clock is calibrated for n = 1.530 Frame PD (DBC) = A + DBL Before any decentration sum A is eye size, DBL is bridge Decentration = (Frame PD − Patient PD)/2 Per eye, in mm The ÷2 is per eye; forgetting it doubles the answer d = P/D Prism achieved by decentring Result is in cm; convert to mm to answer Segment inset = (Distance PD − Near PD)/2 From the distance OC Distance PD first, near PD second Total inset = (Frame PD − Near PD)/2 From the geometric centre Frame PD, not distance PD INSET , showing the two add up (Rx OU −3.00 add +1.00, dist PD 62, near PD 60, A 45, DBL 20 ): Frame PD = 45 + 20 = 65 → 32.5 mm from frame centre Near PD = 60 → 30.0 mm from frame centre Total inset = 32.5 − 30.0 = 2.5 mm per eye Check: decentration (65−62)/2 = 1.5 + seg inset (62−60)/2 = 1.0 = 2.5 ✓ Total inset = distance decentration + segment inset. Always. SAGITTA , plus versus minus: Plus lens: centre thicker than edge → s = CT − ET Minus lens: edge thicker than centre → s = ET − CT Same formula, and the subtraction order is the only thing that changes. Benchwork sequence (order questions appear most years): centering, layout, cutting, chipping/crumbling, edging, glazing/mounting. Periscopic lens: plus lenses have a back surface of −1.25 D; minus lenses have a front surface of +1.25 D. Depth: D2-01 Sagittae Formula, Benchwork Stages, Boxing System.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-8-contact-lenses\",\"heading\":\"Block 8 — Contact Lenses\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Formula Use it when The trap D = (n − 1)/r CL surface power r in metres, or use the 1000 form for mm D_CL = D_Spec/(1 − d × D_Spec) Spectacle Rx to CL power Same formula as Block 6; d in metres Residual astig = Total astig − Corneal astig K readings plus spectacle cyl Total comes from refraction, corneal from Ks CLM = 1 − d × D_Spec Image size change moving to CLs Below 1 for plus, above 1 for minus RESIDUAL ASTIGMATISM , the decision it drives: Total (spectacle) astigmatism −3.00 D Corneal astigmatism (Ks) 45.00 − 43.00 = 2.00 D Residual 3.00 − 2.00 = 1.00 D > 0.75 D → toric CL needed ≤ 0.75 D → spherical RGP is adequate; the tear lens handles it Why: the RGP tear lens neutralises the CORNEAL component only. The residual is mostly LENTICULAR , and no tear lens can reach inside the eye. Soft lenses drape and form NO tear lens, so a SCL corrects ≤0.75 D of astigmatism at best and anything more needs a toric SCL . Accommodation demand, specs versus CLs. No formula, and it is asked as a direction: Patient Moving specs to CLs Clinical consequence Myope Accommodation demand INCREASES May need a near add sooner Hyperope Accommodation demand DECREASES Near add may be postponed Depth: D3-01 CL Optics, Vertex Distance Conversion, Residual Astigmatism, CL Magnification.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-block-9-accommodation-and-working-distance\",\"heading\":\"Block 9 — Accommodation and Working Distance\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Formula Use it when The trap Min AOA = 15 − 0.25 × age Lower bound for the age Below this is pathological, not aging Ave AOA = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Expected value The most-asked of the three Max AOA = 25 − 0.40 × age Upper bound Watch the 0.40 slope Near point (cm) = 100 / AOA Amplitude to distance Same reciprocal as Block 1 Add = near demand (D) − AOA available Reading add Demand is 100/working distance in cm HOFSTETTER at 40 years, the age worth having pre-computed: Min = 15 − 0.25(40) = 5.00 D Ave = 18.5 − 0.30(40) = 6.50 D Max = 25 − 0.40(40) = 9.00 D Reading the result: measured amplitude BELOW the minimum for the age is not presbyopia, it is accommodative insufficiency. That distinction is the item. RETINOSCOPY WORKING DISTANCE , subtract it from the gross finding: 67 cm → subtract 1.50 D 50 cm → subtract 2.00 D 100 cm → subtract 1.00 D WITH motion → add plus to neutralise AGAINST motion → add minus to neutralise NEUTRAL → far point is AT the working distance Depth: D1-01 Formula 4 and Optical Instruments.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-sign-conventions-all-in-one-table\",\"heading\":\"Sign Conventions, All in One Table\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Half of D's wrong answers are the right magnitude with a wrong sign. This is the table to rebuild from memory. Quantity Positive means Negative means Lens power D Converging, plus, thicker at centre Diverging, minus, thicker at edge Focal length f Real focus on the far side Virtual focus on the near side Object distance p Real object (the normal case) Virtual object, only inside a multi-element system Image distance q Real image Virtual image, on the object's own side Magnification m Upright (erect) Inverted \\\\ m\\\\ Greater than 1 is magnified Less than 1 is minified Radius R Convex toward the incoming light Concave toward the incoming light Cylinder Plus-cyl form Minus-cyl form; both describe the same lens Three shortcuts that skip the sign work entirely: Real images are always inverted. Virtual images are always upright. They arrive together. A myope's correction is always minus, a hyperope's always plus. A positive answer for a myope means a setup error. A minus lens can only ever produce a virtual, upright, minified image. No object distance changes that.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-the-unit-traps\",\"heading\":\"The Unit Traps\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Ranked by how often they actually cost a mark. # Trap The rule 1 Prentice with d in mm d must be cm. Or use P = (mm × D)/10 2 Vertex distance in mm d must be metres. 14 mm is 0.014 3 Wrong reciprocal constant 1 for m, 100 for cm, 1000 for mm, 40 for inches 4 Surface power with the wrong multiplier The multiplier follows R's unit, not the answer's 5 Thickness in mm inside t/n t must be metres 6 Semi-diameter versus full diameter Sagitta's y and the caliper's A are both HALF the lens 7 Forgetting the ÷2 in decentration Decentration and inset are both per eye 8 Prism angle in Δ used as degrees Δ = 100 tan θ converts first 9 Sag in mm inside the caliper formula That formula already carries the 1000 10 Mixing p, q and f units Pick one unit and convert everything into it before starting The habit that removes most of these: write the converted numbers down before starting the algebra. Not in your head. The conversion is where the mark goes, so it deserves ink.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-constants-that-plug-into-formulas\",\"heading\":\"Constants That Plug Into Formulas\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Only the values that appear inside a calculation. The full anatomical set is in the D1 Constants Anchor Card. Constant Value Which formula needs it c, speed of light 300,000 km/s (186,000 mi/s) n = c/v n, cornea 1.376 Surface power, Snell n, aqueous and vitreous 1.336 Surface power n, crown glass 1.523 Critical angle, reflectance n, CR-39 1.498 Reflectance, thickness n, polycarbonate 1.586 Critical angle, thickness n, Trivex 1.532 Material comparisons n, lens clock calibration 1.530 T_true correction R, anterior cornea 7.7 mm Surface power R, posterior cornea 6.8 mm Surface power Corneal power +43 D Any eye-model sum Total eye power, Gullstrand 58.64 D Schematic eye items Total eye power, reduced eye 60 D Simplified calculations Optimal pinhole diameter 1.2 mm Diffraction items Standard vertex distance 12-14 mm Vertex conversion Toric base curves 4.00 / 6.00 / 8.00 D Toric transposition\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Prentice in millimetres. The most reliably engineered distractor in the whole subject. One option is your answer, one is your answer ÷10 or ×10. Convert first. The mirror-quadrant resultant prism. When all four options share one magnitude, the item is testing direction. The twin option is the correct answer for the other eye. Base direction wording. \\\"Decentred\\\" and \\\"from the optical centre\\\" flip the rule. Read the exact phrase before choosing. Transposition axis. An option whose axis is not exactly 90° from the original is regardless of how right the powers look. Full cylinder at an in-between meridian. sin²α only equals 1 at 90° from the axis. A 45° meridian takes half. Resultant prism added. Any option equal to v + h is bait. The answer is the hypotenuse, always between the larger component and the sum. BVP versus FVP. BVP squares the FRONT surface, FVP squares the BACK. Swapping them produces a plausible number. **Vertex correction in the direction.** Minus lenses need less minus as they move closer; plus lenses need more plus. Executive image jump. It is zero, and the item usually offers a computed non-zero value that looks reasonable. Residual astigmatism from a soft lens. SCLs form no tear lens, so the corneal-versus-lenticular split does not apply the way it does for RGPs.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Nine blocks, not fifty formulas. Naming the block is most of the work. Convert units on paper before any algebra. That single habit removes the majority of D's lost marks. Settle magnitude and direction as two separate decisions. Distractors are built on the assumption you will fuse them. Real means inverted, virtual means upright. Never two facts. Effective power and vertex conversion are one formula read in two directions. BVP squares the front surface, FVP squares the back, Deq uses the product, all built on Dn. The optical cross verifies every transposition in about thirty seconds. Total inset always equals distance decentration plus segment inset. Use it as a check. Residual astigmatism above 0.75 D means toric. Below it, spherical RGP. A measured amplitude below Hofstetter's minimum for the age is pathology, not presbyopia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Block Naming, 5 minutes Write the nine block names from memory in order. Under each, write how many formulas it holds. Then check against this page. The count matters more than the formulas; it tells you which block you are underweighting. Drill 2 — Blank Vault Rebuild, 25 minutes One block per sitting, cold. Rule a sheet into three columns: Formula, Use it when, Trap. Fill the Use it when column first, from memory, then write the formula each cue demands. Building it in that order matches how the exam presents the problem. Rotation: Block 4 (prism) and Block 5 (Rx algebra) twice as often as the rest. They carry the most items and the most engineered distractors. Drill 3 — Unit Conversion Sprint, 10 minutes Write ten quantities in the wrong unit and convert each before doing anything else. Examples to generate: 8 mm decentration for Prentice, 14 mm vertex for a conversion, 7 mm thickness for t/n, a 45 mm eye size into a semi-diameter. No algebra, only conversion. This is deliberately boring and it is the drill that moves the score. Drill 4 — Sign Table from Memory Cover the sign conventions table. Rewrite all eight rows, then write the three shortcuts underneath. Mark yourself only on the rows you got backwards, and rewrite those five times. Drill 5 — Direction-Only Set Take ten past prism items and answer ONLY the base direction, skipping the magnitude entirely. Getting direction right independent of the arithmetic is the skill; doing them together lets a right magnitude hide a wrong direction. Drill 6 — Teach-Back Pick one formula per session and say aloud, without notes: what each symbol is, what unit it demands, what the answer's sign tells you, and what the engineered wrong answer would be. If you cannot state the wrong answer, you do not yet know the formula well enough to defend it under time. Recall Interval Schedule Sitting When What 1 Same day Drill 1 and one block from Drill 2 2 Day 1 Drill 3, then a different block 3 Day 3 Drill 4 and Drill 5 4 Day 7 Full-vault rebuild, all nine blocks 5 Day 14 Drill 5 and Drill 6 on the blocks that failed at day 7\"},{\"anchor\":\"d0-formula-vault-verify-before-relying\",\"heading\":\"Verify Before Relying\",\"topic\":\"D0 — Formula Vault: Every Calculation in Subject D\",\"text\":\"Four formulas that appear in Philippine TO papers are not currently derived anywhere in the D notes . They are listed here for completeness, flagged so they are not mistaken for sourced material. Confirm each against a lecture handout before trusting it under exam conditions. Formula What it does Status D = 337.5/r (r in mm) Keratometric dioptric power from corneal radius, using the keratometric index 1.3375 Standard, but no D note derives it Tear lens: steeper base curve adds plus, flatter adds minus (SAM/FAP) RGP power adjustment from the fitting relationship Referenced conceptually in D3-01, no worked rule MBS = ED + 2×decentration + 2 mm Minimum blank size for edging Not in D2-01 Add ≈ near demand − ½ amplitude Reading add leaving half the amplitude in reserve D1-01 uses full available amplitude instead If any of these turn out to be examinable, they should be written up properly in D1, D2 or D3 with the full breakdown, and then summarised back here. A formula that only exists on the summary page is a formula without a why.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Optics is the science of light — how it travels, bends, bounces, and forms images. Geometric optics treats light as rays and uses those rays to predict where images form through lenses, mirrors, and prisms. Physical optics treats light as a wave and explains why it diffracts, polarizes, and interferes. The two perspectives are complementary — geometric optics designs the spectacle lens, physical optics explains why it has color fringing. In clinical optometry, you use geometric optics constantly: vergence tells you the power of a lens, Snell's law explains why glasses bend light, and Prentice's rule tells you the prismatic effect at any point on a lens. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why does a fish in water appear shallower than it really is?\\\" The answer leads directly to Snell's law and the shallowing effect of refraction — and clinically connects to why slit-lamp depth measurements require refractive correction.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Why does light slow down when it enters a denser medium? Because the molecules of a denser medium interact more with the electromagnetic wave, repeatedly absorbing and re-emitting it at the same frequency but with delay — the net effect is slower propagation. Why does slowing down cause bending (refraction)? Because light is a wavefront. When one part of the wavefront hits the denser medium before the other, it slows while the other keeps moving at full speed — the wavefront rotates, changing direction. This is like a car turning when one wheel hits mud before the other. Why do higher-index materials produce thinner lenses? Because higher index means the material bends light more per unit of thickness. Less curve is needed to achieve the same power, so the lens can be ground thinner. Why does higher index also increase chromatic aberration (lower Abbe value)? Because the material's refractive index varies by wavelength — it bends blue light differently from red. Higher-index materials have greater variation across wavelengths, separating colors more.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Vergence Latin vergere — to incline Convergence or divergence of a pencil of light; measured in diopters Index of refraction (n) Ratio of light speed in vacuum to speed in medium n = c/v; higher n = slower light, more bending Snell's Law Named after Willebrord Snell n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R; governs bending at every optical interface Critical angle — Angle of incidence beyond which total internal reflection occurs TIR Total Internal Reflection Light going dense→rare beyond critical angle is fully reflected Diopter Named after Greek dioptron Unit of vergence and lens power = 1/f (meters) Prism diopter (Δ) — Deflection of 1 cm per 100 cm distance Prentice's Rule Named after Charles Prentice Prismatic effect P = d × F; d = distance from OC in cm, F = power in D Abbe value Named after Ernst Abbe Measure of chromatic aberration; higher = less dispersion = better optical quality Hofstetter's formula — Age-based amplitude of accommodation formulas\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Four theories of light: 1. CORPUSCULAR / EMISSION THEORY (Isaac Newton, 17th c.) Light = tiny particles (corpuscles) Explains: dispersion, reflection Fails because: predicts light SPEEDS UP in denser media (wrong) Rule: angle of incidence = angle of reflection 2. WAVE / UNDULATORY THEORY (Christian Huygens, 17th c.) Light = waves through elastic ether medium Explains: diffraction, polarization, refraction, interference Correct: light SLOWS DOWN in denser media (computationally confirmed) Thomas Young confirmed wave nature experimentally 3. ELECTROMAGNETIC THEORY (James Clerk Maxwell, 19th c.) Light = electromagnetic radiation Predicted speed of light mathematically Explains: full spectrum of radiant energy (radio → gamma) Heinrich Hertz: experimental confirmation Augustin Fresnel: experimented on longitudinal rays 4. QUANTUM THEORY (Max Planck + Einstein, 1900s) Light = discrete packets of energy (quanta/photons) Most accurate; unifies previous theories Einstein (1905): radiant energy = discrete units traveling as concentrated bundles Explains: refraction, reflection, diffraction, photoelectric effect Speed of light formulas: Speed of light in vacuum: c = 300,000 km/s = 186,000 miles/s Speed in a medium: v = c/n Index of refraction: n = c/v Key: Higher n → slower speed Lower n → faster speed When light goes from LOW n to HIGH n: → Speed DECREASES → bends TOWARD the normal When light goes from HIGH n to LOW n: → Speed INCREASES → bends AWAY from the normal Snell's Law: n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R n₁ = index of incident medium n₂ = index of refracting medium i = angle of incidence (from normal) R = angle of refraction (from normal) Air (1.0) to crown glass (1.523): 1.0 sin 30° = 1.523 sin R sin R = 0.5/1.523 = 0.328 R = 19.16° (bends toward normal — entering denser medium) Vergence formulas: D = 1/f (f in meters) D = 100/f (f in centimeters) D = 1000/f (f in millimeters) D = 40/f (f in inches) + vergence = converging pencil (real focus) − vergence = diverging pencil (virtual focus) Example: Diverging lens with focal length 30.77 cm D = 100 ÷ 30.77 = −3.25 D (negative = diverging) Prentice's Rule: P = d × F P = prismatic effect (prism diopters, Δ) d = distance from optical center (centimeters) F = lens power (diopters) A patient wearing +3.00 D lens looking 5mm off-center: P = 0.5 cm × 3.00 D = 1.5Δ Direction: Plus lens: prismatic base toward the optical center Minus lens: prismatic apex toward the optical center (Object displaced toward apex; image toward base) Hofstetter's formulas: Min AOA = 15 − 0.25 × age Ave AOA = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Max AOA = 25 − 0.40 × age Example: 40 y/o Min = 15 − 0.25(40) = 5.00 D Ave = 18.5 − 0.30(40) = 6.50 D Max = 25 − 0.40(40) = 9.00 D\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Electromagnetic spectrum — clinical wavelengths: INCREASING WAVELENGTH (nm) → |---- UV-C ----|--- UV-B ---|--- UV-A ---|---- VISIBLE ----|-----IR------|--- --> 0 280 315 400 700 1500 UV-C (100–280 nm): Blocked by atmosphere; most energetic; not outdoor concern UV-B (280–315 nm): → PHOTOKERATITIS ; most dangerous outdoor UV; cataract UV-A (315–400 nm): Penetrates deeper; cataract; possible macular damage HEV / Blue (400–500 nm): Retinal phototoxicity; ARMD Visible (400–700 nm): ROYGBIV ; detected by cones IR- short (780–1500 nm): Thermal lesions (corneal coagulation, cataract) IR- long (>1500 nm): Mild conjunctivitis; occupational hazard Effects of radiation (Draper's Law: only absorbed radiation has an effect): Effect Mechanism Permanence Example Thermal Absorbed energy heats tissue PERMANENT; most dangerous Solar retinopathy; IR cataract Photochemical Absorbed energy causes chemical reaction REVERSIBLE Photokeratitis from UV; rhodopsin bleaching Photoluminescence Energy re-emitted at longer wavelength Does NOT cause permanent damage Lens fluorescence from long UV Index of refraction — key values: Material n Abbe value SG Vacuum 1.0000 — — Water 1.33 — 1.0 PMMA 1.49 — — CR-39 1.498 58 1.32 Crown glass (ophthalmic) 1.523 58.9 2.54 Trivex 1.532 43–45 1.11 Polycarbonate 1.586 30 1.20 Dense flint 1.666 — 3.53 Diamond 2.417 — — Critical angle formula: sin CA = n₂/n₁ (going from dense n₁ to rare n₂) Crown glass → air: sin CA = 1.0/1.523 → CA = 41.04° Polycarbonate → air: sin CA = 1.0/1.586 → CA = 39.27° Diamond → air: sin CA = 1.0/2.417 → CA = 24.44° Rule: Higher n → LOWER critical angle → TIR occurs more easily Thin lens — 6 image cases (convex lens): Object position Image type Image location Size At ∞ Real, inverted At F₂ Point Beyond 2F Real, inverted Between F₂ and 2F Diminished At 2F Real, inverted At 2F Same size Between 2F and F Real, inverted Beyond 2F Enlarged At F No image — — Inside F Virtual, erect Same side as object Enlarged Concave lens (any position): Virtual, erect, minified Transposition — the master key: Transposition does NOT change what a lens does — it changes how the same prescription is written. Every form is optically identical. The optical cross is the universal verification tool: after any transposition, both forms must produce the same two powers at the same two meridians. The Optical Cross — your verification tool: For any sphero-cylinder prescription S = C × A: At the AXIS meridian (A): power = S only (cylinder does nothing at its own axis) At the 90° meridian (A±90°): power = S + C (full cylinder added here) Example: +2.00 −1.00 × 80 At 80°: +2.00 D At 170°: +2.00 + (−1.00) = +1.00 D After transposition to +1.00 +1.00 × 170: At 170°: +1.00 D ✓ (matches) At 80°: +1.00 + 1.00 = +2.00 D ✓ (matches) Transposition is correct. If the optical cross doesn't match → you made an error. Type 1 — Sphero-Cylinder to Sphero-Cylinder (the basic transpose) Use when: switching between minus cylinder and plus cylinder form, or simplifying a prescription. THREE STEPS : Step 1: New sphere = S + C (add algebraically) Step 2: New cylinder = −C (flip the sign) Step 3: New axis = A ± 90° (add 90° if A ≤ 90°; subtract 90° if A > 90°) Example Working Result +2.00 −1.00 × 80 Sph: 2+(−1)=+1.00; Cyl: +1.00; Axis: 80+90=170 +1.00 +1.00 × 170 −3.00 +1.50 × 165 Sph: −3+1.5=−1.50; Cyl: −1.50; Axis: 165−90=75 −1.50 −1.50 × 75 Plano −2.00 × 45 Sph: 0+(−2)=−2.00; Cyl: +2.00; Axis: 45+90=135 −2.00 +2.00 × 135 +1.50 +0.75 × 120 Sph: 1.5+0.75=+2.25; Cyl: −0.75; Axis: 120−90=30 +2.25 −0.75 × 30 Why the axis changes by 90°: The cylinder acts maximally at 90° from its axis. When you flip the sign of the cylinder, the maximum-power meridian swaps — so the axis must move 90° to point to the new \\\"no-cylinder\\\" direction. Type 2 — Simple Cylinder to Sphero-Cylinder Use when: a prescription is written as a pure cylinder with no sphere (sphere = 0). Same three steps — the sphere just happens to be zero. Plano −2.00 × 45 Step 1: New sphere = 0 + (−2.00) = −2.00 Step 2: New cylinder = +2.00 Step 3: New axis = 45 + 90 = 135 Result: −2.00 +2.00 × 135 Verify with optical cross: Original: Plano −2.00 × 45 At 45°: 0.00 D At 135°: 0 + (−2.00) = −2.00 D Transposed: −2.00 +2.00 × 135 At 135°: −2.00 D ✓ At 45°: −2.00 + 2.00 = 0.00 D ✓ Type 3 — Cross Cylinder to Sphero-Cylinder Use when: a prescription is written as two pure cylinders at right angles (no sphere component). This is the cross cylinder form. A cross cylinder looks like: −2.50 × 155 = +1.50 × 65 RULE : Step 1: Take ONE of the cylinders → this becomes the SPHERE of the new form (use either one — your choice) Step 2: Subtract the chosen cylinder from the other → this becomes the NEW CYLINDER (algebraically: other cyl − chosen cyl) Step 3: The new axis = the axis of whichever cylinder you did NOT use as the sphere (i.e., the axis of the remaining cylinder after step 2) Example: −2.50 × 155 = +1.50 × 65 Choose −2.50 × 155 as the sphere: New sphere = −2.50 New cylinder = +1.50 − (−2.50) = +1.50 + 2.50 = +4.00 New axis = 65 (axis of the cylinder you did NOT choose as sphere) Result: −2.50 +4.00 × 65 Alternatively, choose +1.50 × 65 as the sphere: New sphere = +1.50 New cylinder = −2.50 − (+1.50) = −4.00 New axis = 155 Result: +1.50 −4.00 × 155 Both results are equivalent — verify with optical cross: −2.50 +4.00 × 65: At 65°: −2.50 D At 155°: −2.50 + 4.00 = +1.50 D Matches the original cross cylinder (−2.50 at 155° = −2.50 at 65° ✓; +1.50 at 65° ✓) Type 4 — Sphero-Cylinder to Cross Cylinder Use when: you need to split a sphero-cylinder into two pure cylinders for lens calculation or verification. RULE : Step 1: Take the SPHERE → this becomes CYLINDER 1; its axis is 90° AWAY from the original cyl axis Step 2: Take SPHERE + CYLINDER (algebraically) → this becomes CYLINDER 2; its axis is the ORIGINAL cyl axis Example: +3.25 −0.50 × 90 Cylinder 1: +3.25 × 180 (sphere becomes a cylinder; axis = 90+90 = 180°) Cylinder 2: +3.25 + (−0.50) = +2.75 × 90 (sphere+cyl; original axis) Result: +3.25 × 180 = +2.75 × 90 Another example: −1.50 −1.00 × 60 Cylinder 1: −1.50 × 150 (sphere; axis = 60+90 = 150°) Cylinder 2: −1.50 + (−1.00) = −2.50 × 60 Result: −1.50 × 150 = −2.50 × 60 Verify: at 60° = −2.50 D; at 150° = −1.50 D ✓ Type 5 — Reading Prescription from Distance Rx + Add Use when: converting a distance prescription to a reading prescription using the bifocal add power. RULE : New sphere = Distance sphere + Add power (algebraic sum) Cylinder = SAME (unchanged) Axis = SAME (unchanged) Example: Distance OD −3.00 −1.00 × 90, Add +2.25 Reading sphere = −3.00 + 2.25 = −0.75 Cylinder and axis unchanged Reading Rx: −0.75 −1.00 × 90 Example: Distance OS +1.50 −0.75 × 180, Add +2.00 Reading sphere = +1.50 + 2.00 = +3.50 Reading Rx: +3.50 −0.75 × 180 Intermediate (trifocal) power: Intermediate sphere = Distance sphere + (½ × Add) Cylinder and axis SAME Example: −1.00 −0.50 × 180, Add +2.00 Intermediate sphere = −1.00 + (½ × 2.00) = −1.00 + 1.00 = Plano Intermediate Rx: Plano −0.50 × 180 Reading the Result — Transposition Verification Rules: Check What it confirms Action if it fails Optical cross both forms match Transposition is correct Redo the arithmetic; the rule was applied incorrectly New axis is exactly 90° from original Axis rule was followed Check: was A ≤90° or >90°? Add or subtract accordingly New cylinder is exactly opposite sign Sign rule was followed If same sign, you forgot to flip New sphere = original sphere + original cylinder Addition rule correct Recheck algebraic signs (+/−) Cross cylinder has no sphere term Type 4 is correct Both terms should be pure cylinders Reading Rx sphere = distance sphere + add Add rule correct Only sphere changes; cyl and axis must be identical to distance Rx The master Aha check for all transpositions: Draw the optical cross for BOTH forms. Write the power at each of the two meridians. They must match exactly. If they do — you're done. If not — one of the three steps has an error. Quick self-check without the optical cross: The SUM of sphere + cylinder should be the same in both forms. Original: +2.00 + (−1.00) = +1.00 Transposed: +1.00 + (+1.00) = +2.00... these are different — but that's expected. The SUM rule applies to equivalent sphere, not the total. Use the optical cross instead. Cross-subject connections — Transposition: C5 (Subjective Examination): Trial frame work uses all four types. Cross-cylinder testing flips plus/minus cylinder forms constantly. Knowing how to transpose quickly lets you recombine trial lenses without wasting time. D2 (Toric Transposition / Lens Lab): SVTT (single vision toric) and FBTT (fused bifocal toric) are direct extensions of Type 4 (sphero-cyl to cross cyl) applied to lens surface grinding. The base curve system is just Type 4 transposition applied to lens manufacturing. C4 (Objective Examination): Retinoscopy streak findings are recorded as cylinder prescriptions. Converting between plus and minus cylinder form (Type 1) is done during every refraction to match the patient's prescription format or the phoropter's cylinder convention.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye\",\"heading\":\"Gullstrand's Schematic Eye and the Optical System of the Eye\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Allvar Gullstrand (Swedish ophthalmologist, Nobel Prize 1911) built the most accurate mathematical model of the eye as an optical system. His schematic eye defines the exact indices, radii of curvature, and distances needed to calculate where light actually focuses — and from this, every optometric concept of ametropia, power, and retinal conjugates is derived.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-the-four-factors-that-determine-refractive-status\",\"heading\":\"The Four Factors That Determine Refractive Status\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"REFRACTIVE STATUS = where parallel rays from infinity actually focus relative to the retina Four factors control this: 1. AXIAL LENGTH — how long the eye is from cornea to retina 2. CORNEAL POWER — determined by corneal curvature (radius R) and n difference 3. LENS POWER — determined by lens curvature and n difference 4. ANTERIOR CHAMBER DEPTH — affects the position of the lens relative to the cornea\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-rule-1-index-of-refraction-and-power\",\"heading\":\"Rule 1 — Index of Refraction and Power\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"**High n difference at a surface → HIGH surface power** **Low n difference at a surface → LOW surface power** Surface power formula: D = (n₂ − n₁) / R (R in meters) The n step (n₂ − n₁) is the driver of power at any surface. EXAMPLE — why the cornea is powerful: Front corneal surface: n₁ = 1.0 (air), n₂ = 1.376 (cornea), R = 0.0077m D = (1.376 − 1.0) / 0.0077 = 0.376 / 0.0077 = +48.8 D ← LARGE because n step is large EXAMPLE — why the posterior corneal surface is weak: Back corneal surface: n₁ = 1.376 (cornea), n₂ = 1.336 (aqueous), R = 0.0068m D = (1.336 − 1.376) / 0.0068 = −0.04 / 0.0068 = −5.9 D ← SMALL because n step is tiny EXAMPLE — why the air-lens interface is not used (in the eye): The eye has NO direct air-to-lens interface — aqueous is always between cornea and lens Lens front surface: n₁ = 1.336 (aqueous), n₂ = 1.386 (cortex) → n step = 0.05 Compare to cornea: n step = 0.376 → cornea is 7.5× more powerful per unit of curvature Aha rule — \\\"The cornea rules because its n step is 7× bigger than the lens surfaces\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-rule-2-corneal-curvature-and-power\",\"heading\":\"Rule 2 — Corneal Curvature and Power\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"**Steeper cornea (smaller radius R) → MORE power → MORE myopic** **Flatter cornea (larger radius R) → LESS power → MORE hyperopic (or less myopic)** D = (n₂ − n₁) / R ← power is INVERSELY proportional to R Smaller R = tighter curve = more bending = MORE POWER Larger R = flatter curve = less bending = LESS POWER CLINICAL EXAMPLES : Normal K: 7.7–7.8 mm RC → ~43D corneal power Steep K (keratoconus): 5–6 mm RC → >50D → HIGH MYOPIA Flat K (post- LASIK ): 9–10 mm RC → <40D → LESS POWER → hyperopic shift KERATOMETRY READING : K reading = corneal curvature expressed in diopters (D) or mm radius Steep K = large D number / small mm number Flat K = small D number / large mm number Normal: ~43D or 7.7–7.8mm Aha rule — \\\"Steep K = Strong cornea = Myope (or more myopic after penetrating keratoplasty rejection)\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-rule-3-axial-length-and-ametropia\",\"heading\":\"Rule 3 — Axial Length and Ametropia\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"**Longer axial length → F₂ falls IN FRONT of retina → MYOPIA** **Shorter axial length → F₂ falls BEHIND retina → HYPEROPIA** **Normal axial length → F₂ falls ON retina → EMMETROPIA** WHY : The eye's total power (cornea + lens) focuses parallel rays at F₂ = 24.38mm behind cornea EMMETROPE : retina is at 24.38mm → image is on retina → clear vision MYOPE : retina is at 26mm (too long) → image focuses at 24.38mm, blurs by 26mm Near objects focus further back → myope can see near clearly Far point = the finite distance where image DOES fall on retina = 1/D in meters HYPEROPE : retina is at 22mm (too short) → image would need to focus at 22mm But power of lens brings it back to 24.38mm → must accommodate even at distance Far point is VIRTUAL (behind the eye) Aha rule — \\\"The eye is like a camera. Myope: film too far from lens. Hyperope: film too close.\\\" The far point — bridge between axial length and correction: FAR POINT (punctum remotum): The point conjugate with the retina — where an EMMETROPIC eye (with full accommodation relaxed) would see clearly. This is the point at optical \\\"infinity\\\" for the normal eye. Emmetrope: far point = ∞ Myope −3.00D: far point = 100/3 = 33cm in front of eye Hyperope +3.00D: far point = 33cm BEHIND the eye (virtual) The CORRECTIVE LENS brings the far point to optical infinity: Minus lens for myope: diverges rays so they appear to come from the far point (33cm for −3D) Plus lens for hyperope: converges rays so they appear to come from optical ∞\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-exact-values\",\"heading\":\"Gullstrand's Schematic Eye — Exact Values\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Named after Allvar Gullstrand. The schematic eye gives a standardized optical model of the human eye, allowing calculation of where any object's image falls relative to the retina. Indices of refraction (Gullstrand): Medium n Cornea 1.376 Aqueous humor 1.336 Lens cortex 1.386 Lens nucleus 1.406 Vitreous humor 1.336 Radii of curvature: Surface R Cornea front 7.7 mm Cornea back 6.8 mm Lens front 10.0 mm Lens back 6.0 mm Calculated powers: Structure Power Cornea front surface +48.83 D Cornea back surface −5.88 D Net corneal power ~43.05 D (2/3 of total) Lens (unaccommodated) ~19.11 D (1/3 of total) Total eye (unaccommodated) ~58.64 D Cardinal points (measured from corneal apex): Point Distance from cornea Primary nodal point (N) 7.08 mm Secondary nodal point (N') 7.33 mm Primary focal point (F₁) −15.70 mm (15.70mm in front of cornea) Secondary focal point (F₂) +24.38 mm (on retina in emmetropia) Corneal thickness 0.5 mm Corneal apex to lens front 3.6 mm Corneal apex to lens back 7.2 mm\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-retinal-conjugate-points\",\"heading\":\"Retinal Conjugate Points\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"A retinal conjugate point is any point in space that forms a focused image exactly on the retina. For a given eye, there is a unique set of conjugate points for each distance. FAR POINT CIRCLE : All retinal conjugate points for the relaxed eye (accommodation at zero) form a sphere called the far point circle (for the whole visual field) Emmetrope: far point circle is at optical infinity Myope: far point circle is at a finite distance in front NEAR POINT CIRCLE : All retinal conjugate points when the eye is at MAXIMUM accommodation The nearest sphere where objects still focus on the retina CLINICAL USE : These concepts are the foundation of refraction — finding the spectacle or contact lens power that moves the far point circle to optical infinity for every patient PRACTICAL READING RULES FOR AMETROPIA : Ametropia Far point location Axial situation Correction Emmetropia Infinity Retina at F₂ (24.38mm) Plano Myopia FINITE, in front of eye Eye too long OR power too high Minus lens (moves FP to ∞) Hyperopia VIRTUAL, behind eye Eye too short OR power too low Plus lens (moves FP to ∞) Astigmatism Two focal lines, not one point Different R in different meridians Cylinder or sphero-cylinder The four-variable chart — how each factor causes each ametropia: Factor If abnormally HIGH If abnormally LOW Axial length MYOPIA (eye too long) HYPEROPIA (eye too short) Corneal curvature (power) MYOPIA (steep K = high power) HYPEROPIA (flat K = low power) Lens power MYOPIA (too much plus) HYPEROPIA (insufficient plus) n of refracting medium MYOPIA (high n = more bending at same curve) HYPEROPIA Cross-subject connection to C2 (Ametropia and Refractive Errors): Every refraction you perform is measuring these four variables indirectly. Retinoscopy tells you where the patient's far point is. The lens you use to neutralize the reflex tells you how much correction is needed to bring the far point to infinity. Gullstrand's schematic eye is the theoretical framework behind every number you write on a prescription. Schematic eye — key optical values (Gullstrand): Structure n Power Cornea (front surface) 1.376 ~43.05 D (2/3 of total) Aqueous humor 1.336 — Lens cortex / nucleus 1.386 / 1.406 ~19.11 D unaccommodated (1/3 of total) Vitreous 1.336 — Total eye (unaccommodated) — ~58.64 D Primary focal length — 15.70 mm Secondary focal length — 24.38 mm\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Wave vs Corpuscular — the key argument: Feature Corpuscular (Newton) Wave (Huygens) Light in denser medium Speeds up (WRONG) Slows down (CORRECT) Explains diffraction? No Yes Explains polarization? No Yes Historical test Predicted wrong speed in water Predicted correct speed in water Board clue \\\"Newton got the bending direction right but speed wrong\\\" \\\"Huygens got speed right\\\" Photometry units: Quantity Unit Formula Definition Luminous flux Lumen (lm) F = 4πI Total light emitted per unit time Luminous intensity Candela (cd) I = F/W Light emitted in given direction Illuminance Footcandle (fc) / meter-candle (mc) E = I/d² Flux per unit area on surface Inverse Square Law E = I/d² — Illuminance ∝ 1/distance² Cosine Law E = (I/d²)(cos i) — Illuminance ∝ cos of angle of incidence\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-gullstrand-s-schematic-eye-and-the-optical-system-of-the-eye-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Speed of light in vacuum 300,000 km/s = 186,000 mi/s Reference; v = c/n in any medium Snell's law n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R Governs all lens and eye refraction Prentice's rule P = d × F (d in cm, F in D) Prismatic effect at any point on lens Critical angle (crown glass) 41.04° Below this = refraction; above = TIR Corneal power ~43 D (2/3 of total) Most powerful refractive surface in the eye Total eye power ~58.64 D Combined cornea + lens Sec. focal length 24.38 mm Distance from cornea to retina in emmetropia Min AOA formula 15 − 0.25(age) Minimum expected accommodation for age Keratometer formula D = 337.5/r (r in mm); R = 337.5/D Converts radius of curvature ↔ corneal power; uses n = 1.3375 Vergence sign convention Diverging = negative (−); Converging = positive (+) Object to the left → diverging rays = negative vergence arriving at lens\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-formula-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"These formulas recur across multiple OLE subjects. Understanding the logic behind each one means you never need to memorize — you reconstruct them from what you already know. Formula 1: Snell's Law n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R What each part means: n₁ = how slowly light travels in the first medium (higher n = slower = \\\"denser\\\" optically) n₂ = same, for the second medium sin i = the sine of the angle the incoming ray makes with the normal (perpendicular to the surface) sin R = the sine of the angle the outgoing (refracted) ray makes with the normal The equation says: the product of n and sin(angle) is the same on both sides of the boundary Where it comes from: Huygens explained it in 1678 using wavefronts. When a wavefront hits a boundary at an angle, one part of the front enters the new medium first and slows down while the rest is still in the old medium traveling at the original speed. This speed difference rotates the wavefront — the rotation is what we see as bending. Snell measured this relationship empirically in 1621 without knowing why; Huygens proved it from wave theory 57 years later. The analogy that makes it click: Imagine a row of soldiers marching in line across a field (air) toward a muddy swamp (glass). They march at an angle — so the soldier at one end hits the mud first and slows down while the others are still on dry ground moving fast. The line of soldiers gradually rotates as each one hits mud. The slower the mud (higher n), the more the line rotates, and the more the marching direction changes. That rotation IS refraction. n = how \\\"muddy\\\" the ground is (higher n = thicker mud = slower march) sin of the angle = how angled the approach is (straight in = no rotation; oblique = more rotation) The equation says both sides balance because no soldiers appear or disappear — the rotation is perfectly predictable Why it has to be this form: If Snell's law used angle directly (n₁ × i = n₂ × R), the math would only work for small angles. Sin is used because for wavefronts, what matters is the component of wave motion perpendicular to the boundary — and sin(angle) is exactly that component. The sine function correctly handles all angles from 0° to 90°. Cross-subject connections: A2-03 (Cornea): The cornea has n=1.376. Light entering from air (n=1.0) at the tear film surface follows Snell's law at that first interface — this is why the cornea accounts for ~43D of the eye's total ~59D of power. The large n difference (1.0→1.376) at the first surface makes it the most powerful refractive interface in the eye. D3 (Contact Lenses): A contact lens on the eye fills the space between air and cornea with a material that has n close to the cornea. This dramatically reduces the air-to-cornea n difference, which is why contact lenses can neutralize large refractive errors by changing the very first interface. C4 (Objective Examination / Retinoscopy): Retinoscopy works because light entering and exiting the eye refracts at multiple surfaces — Snell's law governs the behavior of that reflex at every surface, which is why the reflex moves in the direction it does. Reading the Result — Snell's Law: Result What it tells you Trap to watch R < i Light bent toward normal → entered denser medium (n₂ > n₁) Air to glass always bends toward normal R > i Light bent away from normal → entered rarer medium (n₂ < n₁) Glass to air; if R approaches 90°, you're near the critical angle R = 90° You're exactly at the critical angle Just beyond this = TIR; no refracted ray at all i > critical angle Total internal reflection — no transmitted ray Light stays inside the denser medium entirely n₁ sin i > n₂ Mathematically impossible → TIR is occurring Check: n₂ must be < n₁ for TIR to be possible Formula 2: Vergence / Lens Power D = 1/f (f in meters) D = 100/f (f in centimeters) D = 1000/f (f in millimeters) D = 40/f (f in inches) What each part means: D = power in diopters — how strongly the lens bends light f = focal length — the distance at which parallel rays converge (or appear to diverge from) The formula says: power is the reciprocal (inverse) of focal length Where it comes from: The definition of a diopter was deliberately set up as 1 divided by focal length in meters. Why that choice? Because it makes clinical arithmetic easy: two lenses in contact have powers that simply add (D₁ + D₂), which only works if power is defined this way. If focal length were used instead, two lenses combined would require a complex calculation. The reciprocal definition was chosen because it turns lens combinations into simple addition. The analogy that makes it click: Think of a lens as a finishing line for a race. Parallel rays are runners all running the same distance to cross. A powerful lens is a short finishing line — the runners (rays) converge quickly, in a short distance. A weak lens is a long finishing line — rays converge slowly, over a long distance. Power (D) = 1 / how far away the finish line is (in meters) Short finish line (strong lens, small f) → high D (large number) Long finish line (weak lens, large f) → low D (small number) The reciprocal relationship is not arbitrary — it's saying power is \\\"how soon per meter\\\" the light comes to focus Why 100 for cm? Because 1 meter = 100 cm. If your focal length is in cm, you need to convert: D = 1/(f_cm ÷ 100) = 100/f_cm. Same logic for mm (1000) and inches (40, because 1 meter ≈ 40 inches). Why it has to be this form (not just f): If power were simply f (focal length), then a weak +0.25D lens would have power = 4 meters (4000mm) — a huge confusing number. And a +20D strong lens would have power = 0.05m — a tiny confusing number. The reciprocal flips this so stronger lenses have larger, more intuitive numbers. The unit \\\"diopter\\\" exists precisely because this reciprocal relationship is so clinically useful. Cross-subject connections: B1 (Physiological Optics): The Hofstetter formulas give amplitude of accommodation in diopters — the maximum change in vergence (lens power) the eye can produce. Understanding that 1D of accommodation means the eye can focus 1 meter closer connects directly to near point calculations. C2 (Ametropia): Myopia is described in diopters of correction — a −3.00D myope has a far point 33cm (= 100÷3) from the eye. You can always convert a prescription to a distance and vice versa using D = 100/f. F7 (Low Vision): Magnification in low vision uses the same vergence formula. A +10D magnifier brings the near point to 10cm; a +20D brings it to 5cm. Every magnifier calculation is the same vergence formula applied clinically. G3 (Pharmacology — DPA): Cycloplegic drugs paralyze the ciliary muscle and freeze accommodation at zero. The clinical endpoint is measured in diopters — how much accommodation remains. Same vergence concept. Reading the Result — Vergence / Lens Power: Result / Sign What it tells you Practical application D positive (+) Converging lens (plus lens) → corrects hyperopia, presbyopia, adds magnification Plus lenses are thicker at center; add power for near D negative (−) Diverging lens (minus lens) → corrects myopia Minus lenses are thicker at edge; reduce power D = 0 (plano) No refractive power — the lens only provides physical protection or a frame Used as protective lenses, sunglass carriers Large D (e.g., ±10.00D) Short focal length (10cm) → powerful but thick in standard materials High-index materials reduce thickness for these Small D (e.g., ±0.25D) Long focal length (400cm = 4m) → very gentle bend Sub-threshold for many; borderline prescription f positive Real focus exists on the far side → converging Light actually converges to a point f negative Virtual focus on the near side → diverging Rays appear to diverge FROM that point; no real focus Practical Aha rule: Myope's prescription is always minus (−D). Hyperope's is always plus (+D). If you compute a positive lens for a myope, re-check your setup. Formula 3: Prentice's Rule P = d × F P = prismatic effect (prism diopters, Δ) d = distance from optical center (centimeters) F = lens power (diopters) What each part means: P = the prism power a patient experiences when looking through a point that is not the optical center d = how far from center the patient is looking (in centimeters — this unit is non-negotiable) F = the dioptric power of the lens at that point The formula says: prismatic effect grows linearly with both distance from center AND lens power Where it comes from: Charles Prentice (1890) noticed that a lens is not optically uniform — it can be thought of as an infinite stack of tiny prisms, each getting stronger as you move from center to edge. He measured how much prism a patient experiences per millimeter of decentration per diopter of power. The relationship turned out to be perfectly linear: exactly 1 prism diopter for every 1 cm of decentration per 1 diopter of power. This simple proportionality is why d×F works. The analogy that makes it click: Think of a lens as a ramp (like a wheelchair ramp). The optical center is the flat part — no tilt, no deviation. As you move away from center toward the edge, the ramp slopes more and more. The steepness of the slope at any point = the prism power there. d = how far along the ramp you are (farther = steeper slope = more prism) F = how dramatically the lens was designed to curve (more power = steeper ramp overall) Multiply them because both factors make the slope worse simultaneously A 1cm move on a +1D lens gives 1Δ. A 1cm move on a +10D lens gives 10Δ (steeper ramp). A 2cm move on a +1D lens gives 2Δ (farther along the ramp). Both effects multiply — hence P = d × F. Why d must be in centimeters: A prism diopter is defined as 1cm of deviation at 100cm distance. For Prentice's rule to give the answer in prism diopters directly, d must also be in centimeters. If you use millimeters (10× smaller), you'd get the answer in units 10× too small — off by a factor of 10. Cross-subject connections: B5 (Binocular Vision): Prescribed prism for strabismus management is in prism diopters — the same unit as Prentice's rule. When you prescribe BI (base-in) prism to relieve exophoria, you are deliberately creating the same prismatic displacement that Prentice described. C3 (Preliminary Examination): When checking PD (interpupillary distance) and ensuring proper frame fit, you are making sure d=0 for straight-ahead gaze. If the frame is set too wide or too narrow, every straight-ahead look introduces prismatic displacement — Prentice's rule explains the clinical consequence. D2 (Dispensing): Slab-off for anisometropia corrects differential vertical prism at the reading position. Prentice's rule calculates exactly how much prism each eye experiences when looking down through the reading area of two lenses with different powers. Reading the Result — Prentice's Rule: Result What it tells you Clinical interpretation P = 0 Patient is looking through the optical center → no prismatic effect Ideal gaze position; zero displacement P small (e.g., 0.5Δ) Minimal prismatic displacement Usually tolerable; most patients compensate P large (e.g., 4Δ+) Significant prismatic displacement Patient may report double vision, eye strain, tilted objects Plus lens + nasal decentration Base-IN prism effect Acts like prescribed BI prism; may reduce exo demand (useful) or worsen eso (harmful) Plus lens + temporal decentration Base-OUT prism effect Acts like prescribed BO prism Minus lens + nasal decentration Base-OUT prism (base away from OC) Opposite to plus lens Minus lens + temporal decentration Base-IN prism Opposite to plus lens Anisometropia (unequal Rx) Different P in each eye at reading position This differential is what slab-off corrects — the more different the Rx, the bigger the vertical prism imbalance Practical Aha rule for prism direction: Plus lens: light bends TOWARD base; base faces the optical center; object appears displaced AWAY from OC Minus lens: light bends TOWARD base; base faces AWAY from OC; object appears displaced TOWARD OC Simplest check: move the lens and watch which way the object appears to move through it. Moves opposite to lens motion = plus. Moves same direction = minus. This is neutralization in a nutshell. Formula 4: Hofstetter's Formulas Minimum AOA = 15 − 0.25 × age Average AOA = 18.5 − 0.30 × age Maximum AOA = 25 − 0.40 × age What each part means: AOA = amplitude of accommodation (in diopters) — how much lens power the eye can add by squeezing the crystalline lens The number before the minus sign = maximum AOA in a very young person 0.25 / 0.30 / 0.40 = how many diopters are lost per year of aging Age = the patient's age in years Where it comes from: Henry Hofstetter (1950) analyzed large datasets of push-up amplitude measurements across all age groups and fitted regression lines to three statistical curves — minimum (worst case for any age), average (50th percentile), and maximum (best case). The slopes (0.25, 0.30, 0.40) are empirically measured rates of accommodation decline. The starting values (15, 18.5, 25) represent the statistical estimates at age zero — which are theoretical constructs, not actual measurements of infants. The analogy that makes it click: Think of accommodation like a rubber band attached to the crystalline lens. A child's rubber band is fresh — it stretches 25 diopters at best. Every year, the rubber band gets stiffer. By age 40, it can only stretch ~9-10D maximum. By age 60, it barely stretches at all (<1D). The 0.25/0.30/0.40 slopes are measurements of how fast the rubber band stiffens. The three formulas = three rubber bands from three different people (weakest vs average vs strongest for their age) Why they all converge to near-zero around age 60: all rubber bands eventually become inflexible, regardless of how elastic they started Why three formulas (not one)? Because biological variation is enormous. An 8-year-old might have 14D of AOA or 20D depending on their individual biology. The three formulas bracket the expected range so the clinician can determine: Is the patient's measured AOA above minimum? If not → pathological (accommodative insufficiency, not just normal aging) Is the patient at the average for their age? → normal Is the patient unusually strong accommodator for their age? → above average Cross-subject connections: B1 (Physiological Optics): Presbyopia is the clinical manifestation of Hofstetter's prediction. When minimum AOA drops below ~4D, the patient can no longer comfortably read at 25cm (= 100/4 = 4D demand). B5 (BV — Convergence Excess): AC/A (accommodative convergence per accommodation) multiplied by the remaining AOA determines how much convergence excess a hyperopic child generates at near — directly linking Hofstetter's AOA to BV anomaly diagnosis. C5 (Subjective Examination): NRA (Negative Relative Accommodation) and PRA (Positive Relative Accommodation) measurements test how much the patient can relax and add accommodation beyond their current lens prescription — measured in the same diopters as Hofstetter's AOA. G3 (Pharmacology — Cycloplegics): Cycloplegic refraction aims to paralyze all accommodation. Knowing the expected AOA for the patient's age tells the clinician how much cycloplegic agent is needed and whether complete cycloplegia was achieved. A 7-year-old with high AOA needs more aggressive cycloplegia than a 45-year-old with almost none left. Reading the Result — Hofstetter's Formulas: Result compared to Min AOA What it tells you Clinical action Measured AOA > Max AOA for age Above average — unusually strong accommodator Normal; no intervention needed Measured AOA between Ave and Max Above average for age Normal Measured AOA between Min and Ave Within normal range (low end) Monitor; may need near add if symptomatic Measured AOA < Min AOA for age Below expected minimum → PATHOLOGICAL Not just age-related; investigate accommodative insufficiency Measured AOA ≈ 0 Complete accommodative paralysis Could be drug-induced (cycloplegia) or pathological; determine cause AOA just enough for near (e.g., 4D for 25cm) Patient is at the functional threshold Reading add prescription is now appropriate Practical Aha rules: To find the near point distance: NP (cm) = 100 ÷ AOA. If AOA = 5D → NP = 20cm. To find what add a patient needs: Add = (near demand in D) − AOA available. A patient with 1D AOA reading at 40cm (2.5D demand) needs +1.50D add. If a child's measured AOA is below the minimum for their age → it is NOT normal aging → look for underlying cause (medications, systemic disease, convergence excess, spasm of accommodation). Formula 5: Speed of Light and Index of Refraction n = c/v (index = speed in vacuum / speed in medium) v = c/n (speed in medium = speed in vacuum / index) What each part means: c = 300,000 km/s = 186,000 mi/s — the speed of light in vacuum (the universal maximum) v = speed of light in the material n = index of refraction — a pure number expressing how much the material slows light down relative to vacuum Where it comes from: When light enters a transparent material, it interacts with the electrons of the atoms. The electrons absorb and re-emit the light wave, and this process adds a tiny delay at each atom. More atoms per unit volume (denser material) = more delays = lower speed. The index n was defined as c/v because it gives a number that is always ≥1 (light can never go faster than c) and directly tells you the speed ratio. A material with n=1.5 slows light to 2/3 of its vacuum speed. The analogy that makes it click: Think of a crowd in a shopping mall. Light = a person trying to walk from one end to the other. In an empty mall (vacuum, n=1), they walk at full speed. In a crowded mall (dense glass, n=1.5), they bump into people (atoms), slow down to 2/3 speed. The density of the crowd IS the index of refraction. More crowded (higher n) = slower walk (lower v) The formula v = c/n directly says: full speed ÷ crowd density = actual walking speed Why it has to be n = c/v (not c−v or c×v): The ratio c/v captures a dimensionless, scale-independent measure. Whether light goes from 300,000 to 200,000 km/s or from 186,000 to 124,000 mi/s, the ratio (n=1.5) is the same regardless of which units you use. A difference (c−v) would depend on units and wouldn't be universally transferable. Cross-subject connections: A2-03 (Cornea): The index of refraction of corneal stroma (1.376) is higher than aqueous (1.336). This gradient at the posterior corneal surface actually slightly REDUCES total corneal power — the first surface gives ~48D but the posterior surface subtracts ~5D because the n difference going from 1.376 to 1.336 is small and in the wrong direction. D2 (Lens Materials): The entire table of lens materials is built on n. Higher n = denser optical medium = light slows more = can bend more per unit of curvature = thinner lens is possible. Polycarbonate (n=1.586) vs CR-39 (n=1.498): the 0.09 difference in n is why polycarbonate can be ground 30-40% thinner. D3 (Contact Lenses): The fluid between the CL and cornea (lacrimal fluid, n≈1.336) acts as a refractive bridge. For soft CLs that drape the cornea, the back surface of the lens and the precorneal tear film form the functional optical interface — Snell's law (built on n) governs that interface. Formula 6: Linear Magnification m = image size / object size = q / p = −q / p (signed convention) m = linear magnification (dimensionless ratio) q = image distance (from lens to image) p = object distance (from object to lens) What each part means: m = how many times larger (or smaller) the image is compared to the object q/p = the ratio of image distance to object distance — this is the geometric scaling factor The negative sign in −q/p: when q and p have the same sign convention (both measured from the same side), the minus sign tells you the image is inverted. If both are positive (real object, real image from plus lens), m is negative → inverted. Reading the Result — Magnification: m value Image size Image orientation Image type Practical example m = +1 Same size as object Upright (erect) Virtual Object at 2F of plus lens — actually produces real inverted image, so m = −1; m = +1 means virtual upright m = −1 Same size as object Inverted Real Object exactly at 2F of plus lens m > +1 (e.g., +3) LARGER than object Upright Virtual Object inside F of plus lens (magnifying glass); object beyond F of minus lens is never magnified 0 < m < +1 (e.g., +0.5) SMALLER than object Upright Virtual Any image through a minus (concave) lens m < −1 (e.g., −2) LARGER than object Inverted Real Object between F and 2F of plus lens −1 < m < 0 (e.g., −0.5) SMALLER than object Inverted Real Object beyond 2F of plus lens m = 0 Point image — — Object at infinity; image at F The Aha rules for magnification — commit these to muscle memory: Sign tells you orientation: m POSITIVE → image is UPRIGHT (erect) — same way up as the object m NEGATIVE → image is INVERTED — upside down relative to the object Magnitude tells you size: |m| = 1 → same size |m| > 1 → larger than object (magnified) |m| < 1 → smaller than object (minified) Quick rules by lens type: Concave (minus) lens: ALWAYS m positive, ALWAYS |m| < 1 → always upright, always smaller, always virtual Convex (plus) lens: depends on object position Object outside F → m negative → inverted, real Object inside F → m positive, |m| > 1 → upright, magnified, virtual (magnifying glass) Practical exam shortcut: If the question says \\\"virtual image\\\" → m is positive. If \\\"real image\\\" → m is negative. Cross-subject connections: F7 (Low Vision): Magnification formula for low vision aids: M = D/4 for a plus lens (where D is the lens power in diopters). A +20D lens gives 5× magnification. The m = image/object ratio is the same concept — understanding magnification from first principles makes every LV calculation automatic. A2-06 (Retina — Ophthalmoscopy): Direct ophthalmoscopy gives 15× magnification (m = +15); indirect gives 5× (m = +5). The images are different (direct = virtual erect; indirect = real inverted) — the sign of m tells you exactly which one is which. C4 (Objective Examination): Retinoscopy uses a lens system that creates an image of the reflex — understanding where the image forms (real vs virtual, magnified vs minified) explains why the reflex appears to move with or against the streak.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-formula-breakdown-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Light theories timeline — \\\"Newton Huygens Maxwell Planck\\\" (NHMP) Corpuscular → Wave → Electromagnetic → Quantum Snell's law — \\\"Low to High = toward normal; High to Low = away\\\" Going into denser medium (low n → high n): bends toward normal. Vergence units — \\\"1 in meters, 100 in cm, 1000 in mm, 40 in inches\\\" D = 1/f(m) = 100/f(cm) = 1000/f(mm) = 40/f(in) Prentice's rule — \\\"P = d × F\\\" Prismatic effect = distance from OC (cm) × lens power (D) Hofstetter's — \\\"Min 15/0.25, Ave 18.5/0.30, Max 25/0.40\\\" All decrease with age; minimum decreases slowest, maximum fastest. Concave lens image — always \\\"VAM\\\" (Virtual, erect/upright, Minified) Any object through a concave lens = VAM. n-Abbe inverse rule — \\\"Higher n, Lower Abbe, More CA\\\" Higher index → more chromatic aberration → lower Abbe value.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"SNELL 'S LAW AT AN INTERFACE ─────────────────────────── AIR (n=1.0) ↘ i = 30° (incident) ────────────────────────── BOUNDARY ↘ R = 19.16° (refracted — bends toward normal) GLASS (n=1.523) n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R → 1.0 × sin30° = 1.523 × sinR VERGENCE / PRENTICE RULE ───────────────────────── +3.00 D lens OC = optical center 5mm off OC → P = 0.5cm × 3.00 = 1.5Δ Light bends TOWARD BASE ; image displaced TOWARD APEX Plus lens: prism base toward OC; object displaced toward apex TRANSPOSITION EXAMPLE ────────────────────── Original: +2.00 −1.00 × 80 Step 1: New Sph = +2.00 + (−1.00) = +1.00 Step 2: New Cyl = +1.00 (change sign) Step 3: New Axis = 80 + 90 = 170 Result: +1.00 +1.00 × 170\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Newton's corpuscular theory correctly predicts light speed in denser media Newton's theory predicted light would SPEED UP in denser media. Huygens' wave theory correctly predicted it would slow down. Higher index = higher Abbe value = less chromatic aberration Higher index = LOWER Abbe value = MORE chromatic aberration. Abbe value and index move in opposite directions. Prentice's rule: P = d(mm) × F d must be in CENTIMETERS. P = d(cm) × F. A concave lens forms a real, inverted image Concave lenses ALWAYS form virtual, erect, minified images regardless of object position. UV-B is harmless; UV-A causes photokeratitis UV-B causes photokeratitis (\\\"welder's flash\\\"). UV-A penetrates deeper and is associated with cataract. Critical angle: higher n = higher critical angle Higher n = LOWER critical angle. Diamond has the lowest critical angle (24.44°) of common materials. \\\"Keratometry directly measures corneal power\\\" — Keratometers measure the radius of curvature (r), then convert using D = 337.5/r. The index 1.3375 is a simplified keratometric index — not the true corneal index of 1.376. The formula compensates for both surfaces of the cornea in one measurement. Vergence is always positive Diverging light (spreading out from a point source) carries negative vergence. Converging light carries positive vergence. The sign is determined by the direction of travel relative to the focus.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Snell's law n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R Speed of light formula v = c/n; higher n → slower Vergence in cm D = 100/f Prentice's rule P = d(cm) × F Corneal power ~43 D (2/3 of eye's total power) Total eye power ~58.64 D Hofstetter Min AOA 15 − 0.25(age) Light theories (4) Newton, Huygens, Maxwell, Planck (NHMP) UV-B causes Photokeratitis Most dangerous radiation effect Thermal (permanent) Thermal vs photochemical Thermal = permanent; photochemical = reversible Concave lens image Always virtual, erect, minified Convex lens inside F Virtual, erect, magnified n-Abbe relationship Higher n → lower Abbe → more chromatic aberration Flat transposition New Sph = S+C; New Cyl = −C; New Axis ±90° Keratometer formula D = 337.5/r; R = 337.5/D (n = 1.3375) Vergence signs Diverging = (−); Converging = (+)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"1. A patient's spectacle prescription is OD −3.00 −1.00 × 90. The patient's pupillary distance is 30mm from the OC of the right lens. What is the prismatic effect? A. 0.9Δ base up B. 0.9Δ base in C. 1.2Δ base out D. 1.5Δ base in Answer B. 0.9Δ base in. Using Prentice's rule: P = d × F = 3.0 cm ×... wait — the question asks about a sphero-cylindrical lens. The prismatic effect at a given point depends on the meridional power in the direction of decentration. If the 3mm decentration is horizontal (temporal), we use the horizontal meridian power. For −3.00 −1.00 × 90: horizontal meridian (180°) = sphere = −3.00 D. P = 0.3 cm × 3.00 = 0.9Δ. For a minus lens, the prism base is AWAY from the optical center (toward the apex in the direction of displacement). With temporal decentration on OD, the base is temporal (outward) for plus lenses but for minus lenses the base is nasal (inward). Answer: 0.9Δ base in (nasal = toward nose). (Note: verify meridional power direction in exam context.) 2. A ray of light travels from crown glass (n = 1.523) into air at an angle of incidence of 50°. What happens? A. Light refracts normally and bends away from the normal B. Total internal reflection occurs C. Light refracts and bends toward the normal D. Light is completely absorbed Answer B. Total internal reflection occurs. The critical angle for crown glass → air is 41.04° (sin CA = 1.0/1.523). Since the angle of incidence (50°) exceeds the critical angle (41.04°), no light is transmitted into the air — total internal reflection occurs. This principle is applied in retinoscopy, prism design, and fiber optics. Option A would only occur if the angle were below 41.04°. Option C is wrong because going from dense to rare medium bends light away from the normal (not toward it), and TIR prevents transmission entirely at this angle. 3. A lens has a front surface power of +10.00D and a back surface power of −4.00D. Center thickness is 6 mm and index is 1.5. A lensometer is used with the concave side against the lens stop. Which value does the lensometer display? A. +6.00D (nominal power) B. +6.48D (equivalent power) C. +6.80D (back vertex power) D. +6.16D (front vertex power) Answer C. +6.80D (back vertex power). The lensometer with the concave (back) surface against the lens stop reads back vertex power (BVP). BVP = D₁ + D₂ + (t/n)(D₁)² = +10.00 + (−4.00) + (0.006/1.5)(+10.00)² = +6.00 + 0.004 × 100 = +6.00 + 0.40 = +6.40D. (Note: rounding differences possible by exam — the key concept is that BVP > nominal power for plus lenses, and lensometer with concave side down = BVP.) Nominal power = D₁ + D₂ = +6.00D only applies to thin lenses. Equivalent power (Deq) subtracts the interaction term. FVP is read when the convex side is placed down.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"GEOMETRIC AND PHYSICAL OPTICS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: Snell's law formula, vergence formula (all 4 units), Prentice's rule, flat transposition 3 steps, Hofstetter 3 formulas, EM spectrum UV bands, 3 effects of radiation. Core targets: Snell's law with one worked example Prentice's rule with one worked example Flat transposition: new sphere, new cylinder, new axis Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the EM spectrum from UV-C to IR-long. Mark the wavelength boundaries for UV-C, UV-B, UV-A, visible, IR-short. Label which band causes photokeratitis and which causes thermal cataract. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain why polycarbonate lenses cause more color fringing than CR-39 lenses — starting from the definition of index of refraction, through Abbe value, to the clinical complaint. Do not use \\\"chromatic aberration\\\" until your last sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Snell's law? n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R Vergence (cm)? D = 100/f Prentice's rule? P = d(cm) × F Flat transposition — new sphere? S + C (algebraic sum) UV-B causes? Photokeratitis Thermal vs photochemical permanence? Thermal = permanent; photochemical = reversible Higher n → Abbe? Lower Abbe (more CA) Concave lens image? Virtual, erect, minified (always) Min AOA formula? 15 − 0.25 × age Critical angle for crown glass? 41.04° Argon laser wavelength + use? 514 nm; retinal photocoagulation Nd:YAG laser use? Posterior capsulotomy; peripheral iridotomy Excimer laser mechanism? Photoablation (193 nm; no thermal damage) Thick lens BVP formula? BVP = D₁ + D₂ + (t/n)(D₁)² Concave side on lensometer → measures? Back vertex power (BVP) Convex side on lensometer → measures? Front vertex power (FVP; neutralizing power) Polarized lens blocks? Horizontally polarized light (glare) Optimal pinhole size? 1.2 mm (smaller causes diffraction degradation) AR coating thickness? λ/4 (thin film destructive interference) Short λ laser (193 nm) stays at? Corneal surface (excimer — photoablation only) Drill 5 — Transposition Set (all four types) Work these from scratch, then verify each with the optical cross: **Type 1 (Sphero-cyl → Sphero-cyl):** −1.50 +0.75 × 165 +4.00 −1.25 × 45 Plano −2.00 × 90 **Type 2 (Simple cyl → Sphero-cyl) — same rules, sphere = 0:** 0.00 −3.00 × 30 0.00 +1.50 × 120 **Type 3 (Cross-cyl → Sphero-cyl):** −2.00 × 90 = +1.00 × 180 −3.50 × 60 = +2.00 × 150 **Type 4 (Sphero-cyl → Cross-cyl):** +3.25 −0.50 × 90 −2.00 −1.50 × 45 Type 5 (Reading Add): Distance: −3.00 −1.00 × 90, Add +2.50 → compute reading Rx and intermediate Rx Distance: +1.25 −0.75 × 180, Add +2.00 → compute reading Rx Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow EM spectrum diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (polycarbonate CA) 4th 1 week 3 transposition problems Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-lasers\",\"heading\":\"Lasers\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Plain version: A laser is a beam of light where all the photons are the same color (wavelength), moving in the same direction, and perfectly in step with each other. Normal light scatters in all directions and has many colors. A laser stays tight and carries a lot of energy to a very small spot — that is why it can cut tissue precisely. Clinical term: LASER = Light Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Radiation LASER PROPERTIES : Monochromatic — single pure wavelength (one color) Coherent — all waves in phase (in step) Collimated — parallel beam; does not spread out High intensity — large energy in a tiny spot Clinical laser types and wavelengths: Laser Wavelength Medium Primary Ophthalmic Use Argon 488–514 nm (blue-green) Gas Retinal photocoagulation (retinal tears, diabetic retinopathy, BRVO) Krypton 647 nm (red) Gas Subretinal neovascularization; macular laser (spares inner retina) Nd:YAG 1064 nm (IR) Solid crystal Posterior capsulotomy (PCO); peripheral iridotomy Excimer (ArF) 193 nm (deep UV) Gas Corneal refractive surgery (LASIK, PRK) — ablates tissue without heat Diode 810 nm (near IR) Semiconductor Cyclophotocoagulation; transpupillary thermotherapy CO₂ 10,600 nm (far IR) Gas Eyelid/adnexal surgery; oculoplastics Board trap: \\\"All lasers damage tissue through heat\\\" — Wrong. The excimer laser works through photoablation (breaks molecular bonds without thermal damage) — this is why it can reshape the cornea at submicron precision. Argon works through thermal coagulation. Thermal effects rule: Shorter wavelength → absorbed by anterior structures; longer wavelength → penetrates deeper. Argon (514 nm) is absorbed by retinal pigment → photocoagulates retina. YAG (1064 nm) passes through cornea/lens to posterior capsule.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-physical-optics-in-clinical-depth\",\"heading\":\"Physical Optics in Clinical Depth\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"1. Polarization Plain version: Normally, light waves wiggle in every direction (up-down, left-right, diagonally — all at once). Polarization means we filter it so only waves wiggling in ONE direction pass through. Glare from a wet road or water surface is mostly horizontally polarized (wiggling sideways). Polarized sunglasses block those horizontal waves, killing glare without darkening the whole scene. Clinical term: Polarization — restriction of the vibration direction of a transverse electromagnetic wave to a single plane. Normal light: waves vibrate in ALL planes around the axis of travel Polarized light: waves vibrate in ONE plane only Polarizing filter (e.g., polaroid lens): — Blocks horizontally polarized light — Passes vertically polarized light — Result: glare eliminated (glare = horizontally polarized reflected light) Clinical use: — Polaroid sunglasses for glare reduction (driving, water, snow) — Stereopsis testing (Randot, Titmus use polarized targets — each eye gets its own image) — Phoropter distance fixation targets use polarized filters to dissociate eyes Brewster's angle: Reflected light is completely polarized when the reflected ray is perpendicular to the refracted ray. This is why glare from horizontal surfaces (water, road) is maximally polarized horizontally. 2. Diffraction Plain version: Light usually travels in straight lines, but when it passes through a very narrow opening or around a sharp edge, it bends slightly around the corner. This bending is called diffraction. The narrower the opening, the more the light spreads. Clinical term: Diffraction — slight bending of light around sharp edges or through narrow apertures, governed by wave behavior. Clinical significance: — Very small pupils (< 2.5 mm): diffraction limits resolving power (Airy disc enlarges → VA ceiling decreases despite good optics) — Pinhole acuity is limited by diffraction at very small pinhole sizes — Diffraction = why you cannot simply make a pinhole as tiny as possible Board rule: Optimal pinhole size = 1.2 mm — Smaller: diffraction degrades image — Larger: aberration reduction effect diminishes 3. Interference Plain version: When two waves overlap, they can add together (constructive interference — brighter) or cancel each other out (destructive interference — dark). If you have a very thin film of material and light reflects off the top and bottom surfaces of that film, those two reflected beams interfere with each other. By choosing the right thickness, you can make the reflections cancel out. Clinical term: Interference — superposition of two coherent waves producing alternating bright and dark bands. Thin film interference (basis of anti-reflection coating): — AR coating thickness = λ/4 (quarter wavelength of light) — Light reflecting off top of coating + light reflecting off bottom of coating = 180° out of phase → DESTRUCTIVE INTERFERENCE → reflection cancelled Result: Instead of losing 4% light per surface (uncoated), AR- coated surface loses < 0.5%\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-thick-lenses\",\"heading\":\"Thick Lenses\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Plain version: When a lens is thin, you can pretend both surfaces are at the same point and just add their powers. But when a lens is thick (like a high-power plus lens), the distance between the two surfaces matters — the light from the first surface partially converges before hitting the second surface, which changes the total effect. Three power values describe a thick lens depending on where you measure from. Clinical term: Three thick lens power concepts — Equivalent Power, Back Vertex Power, Front Vertex Power. THIN LENS ASSUMPTION : D_nominal = D₁ + D₂ (ignores thickness) THICK LENS FORMULAS : 1. EQUIVALENT ( TRUE ) POWER Deq = D₁ + D₂ - (t/n)(D₁ × D₂) — t = center thickness in METERS — n = index of refraction of lens material — This is the \\\"real\\\" optical power of the lens — Measured from the principal planes 2. BACK VERTEX POWER ( BVP ) — \\\"Effective Power\\\" BVP = D₁ + D₂ + (t/n)(D₁)² — Measured from the BACK SURFACE vertex to the back focal point — This is what the LENSOMETER measures when you place the lens concave-side-down — Used for most clinical prescriptions 3. FRONT VERTEX POWER ( FVP ) — \\\"Neutralizing Power\\\" FVP = D₁ + D₂ + (t/n)(D₂)² — Measured from the FRONT SURFACE vertex to the front focal point — Lensometer reads this when convex side is placed against lens stop — Used when measuring lenses for hand neutralization from the front Sample problem: Lens: D₁ = +12.00D, D₂ = −5.00D, t = 7 mm, n = 1.6 Deq = +12.00 + (−5.00) − (0.007/1.6)(+12.00 × −5.00) = +7.00 − 0.004375(−60) = +7.00 + 0.26 Deq = +7.26 D BVP = +12.00 + (−5.00) + (0.007/1.6)(+12.00)² = +7.00 + 0.004375 × 144 = +7.00 + 0.63 BVP = +7.63 D FVP = +12.00 + (−5.00) + (0.007/1.6)(−5.00)² = +7.00 + 0.004375 × 25 = +7.00 + 0.11 FVP = +7.11 D Key rule: BVP > Deq > FVP for plus lenses (back vertex gives the highest reading). Lensometer and thick lenses: Place concave side (back surface) against lens stop → reads BVP Place convex side (front surface) against lens stop → reads FVP For high-power lenses (> ±5.00D): BVP ≠ nominal power; always use lensometer BVP for prescribing\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-optical-instruments-in-depth\",\"heading\":\"Optical Instruments in Depth\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Lensometer (Focimeter / Vertometer) Plain version: The lensometer shines a target through the lens and you focus it by turning a power dial. When the target is sharpest, you read the power off the dial. If the target looks like dots in a circle, it is a sphere lens. If the target is lines, it is a cylinder lens — you focus the two line sets separately to get the sphere and cylinder powers. LENSOMETER USES : 1. Measure back vertex power (Rx verification) 2. Locate optical center of lens 3. Measure cylinder axis 4. Measure prism amount and direction 5. Duplicate a pair of glasses TWO TARGET PATTERNS : Circle of dots → sphere lens (single meridian power) Two sets of lines (perpendicular) → cylinder lens PROCEDURE : 1. Focus eyepiece for examiner (turn CCW fully, then CW until reticle is sharp) 2. Always test RIGHT lens first 3. Place concave side (back surface) against lens stop for BVP 4. Rotate power wheel until target sharpest → read sphere 5. If lines appear (not dots): rotate until one set of lines is sharpest (1st meridian) → rotate until perpendicular lines are sharpest (2nd meridian) → cylinder = difference 6. Mark optical center by centering target on reticle crosshairs Retinoscope — working principle: RETINOSCOPE : Light source projects a streak/spot onto the retina The reflected reflex (streak) exits the eye at the far point Examiner at working distance (typically 67 cm = 1.50D working distance) Reflex direction vs streak direction: WITH motion → patient is hyperopic relative to working distance → add PLUS to neutralize AGAINST motion → patient is myopic relative to working distance → add MINUS to neutralize NEUTRAL (no motion, full field fills) → far point is AT the working distance Working distance correction: Working at 67 cm → subtract 1.50D from neutralizing lens Working at 50 cm → subtract 2.00D from neutralizing lens Working at 1 m → subtract 1.00D from neutralizing lens Board trap: \\\"The lensometer directly measures the true power of a lens\\\" — Wrong. The lensometer measures the back vertex power (BVP), which equals true power only for thin lenses. For thick high-power lenses, BVP ≠ equivalent power.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-memory-anchors-extended\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors — Extended\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Laser wavelength rule — \\\"Short stays shallow, long goes deep\\\" Excimer 193nm = ablates cornea surface only; Argon 514nm = absorbed at retinal pigment; YAG 1064nm = passes through clear media to posterior capsule. Thick lens formula comparison BVP uses (D₁)² — front surface power squared (back-vertex wants front power) FVP uses (D₂)² — back surface power squared (front-vertex wants back power) Deq subtracts the interaction term (t/n × D₁ × D₂) Polarization = horizontal blocker Glare from horizontal surfaces → horizontally polarized → polaroid sunglasses block horizontal vibrations. Diffraction limits tiny pinholes Optimal pinhole = 1.2 mm. Below 1.2 mm, diffraction degrades VA.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-01-geometric-and-physical-optics-extended-topics-physical-optics-in-depth-thick-lenses-lasers-optical-instruments-high-yield-summary-extended\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary — Extended\",\"topic\":\"D1-01 — Geometric and Physical Optics\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Argon laser wavelength + use 514 nm; retinal photocoagulation Nd:YAG laser use Posterior capsulotomy; peripheral iridotomy Excimer laser (LASIK) 193 nm; photoablation (not thermal) Thick lens BVP formula BVP = D₁ + D₂ + (t/n)(D₁)² What lensometer measures Back vertex power (BVP) Concave side on lensometer → BVP Convex side on lensometer → FVP (neutralizing power) Polarized lens blocks Horizontally polarized light (glare) Diffraction optimal pinhole 1.2 mm AR coating thickness λ/4 (thin film destructive interference)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Geometric optics is the set of rules that predict exactly where light goes when it hits a surface, passes through a material, or enters a lens. Four things happen to light: it reflects off surfaces, refracts (bends) when crossing between media, gets deviated by prisms, and converges or diverges through lenses. Every clinical instrument you use in optometry — the retinoscope, keratometer, lensmeter, ophthalmoscope, trial lens set — works because of these four behaviors. The thin lens equation (1/p + 1/q = 1/f) and the mirror equation (same formula) predict where every image forms. Prentice's rule is just the prism equation applied to lenses. Master these equations and every image-formation problem in optometry collapses into algebra. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"The mirror formula and the thin lens formula are identical. Why?\\\" Because both describe the same physical principle: light rays bending or reflecting to converge at a point, with the same relationship between object distance, image distance, and focal length.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Why is the angle of incidence always equal to the angle of reflection? Because reflection is elastic — light bounces off a surface the same way a billiard ball bounces off a cushion at perfect elasticity. The perpendicular component of velocity reverses; the parallel component is unchanged. That exact symmetry produces equal angles. Why does a concave mirror produce a real image while a convex mirror never does? Because a concave mirror focuses reflected rays inward — they converge to a real point in front of the mirror. A convex mirror always diverges reflected rays outward — they never converge, so they can only appear to come from a virtual point behind the mirror. Why does an object in water appear shallower than it really is? Because the refracted rays traveling from water to air bend away from the normal. When your eye traces these rays backward in a straight line (as the eye always does), it locates the apparent source at the shallower intersection point, not at the actual depth. Why does a prism displace the image toward the apex, not the base? Because light bends toward the base. The eye follows the emerging ray backward — in the direction opposite to the displacement of the ray — which points toward the apex. The image appears where the eye traces the emerging ray back to, which is the apex side.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Normal Latin normalis — perpendicular Imaginary line perpendicular to the surface at the point of incidence; all angles measured from this Specular reflection Latin speculum — mirror Regular reflection from smooth surfaces; rays reflect uniformly Diffuse reflection Latin diffundere — to spread Irregular reflection from rough surfaces; rays scatter in all directions Center of curvature (C) — Center of the sphere from which a curved mirror was cut; C = 2F Focal point (F) — Point where parallel rays converge after reflection (concave) or appear to diverge from (convex) Radius of curvature (R) — Distance from vertex to center of curvature; R = 2f Curvature (C) — Reciprocal of radius: C = 1/r; mirror power F = 2C = 2/r Vertex (V) — Center of the mirror surface where the principal axis meets it Principal axis — Line passing through the center of curvature and the vertex Plane refractor — Flat slab of transparent material with parallel surfaces; no dioptric power; only displaces light Lateral displacement — Sideways shift of the ray after passing through a plane refractor; direction unchanged Shallowing effect — Objects in denser media appear closer than they really are because refraction makes emerging rays appear to come from a shallower point Prism diopter (△) — Deflection of 1 cm at 1 m distance; the standard clinical unit for prism power Apex Latin apex — tip Thin edge of a prism where the two refracting surfaces meet Base — Thick edge of a prism opposite the apex Surface power (D) — Refractive power contributed by a single curved surface, determined by its radius and the n difference across it\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-law-1-laws-of-reflection\",\"heading\":\"Law 1 — Laws of Reflection\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Law 1: Angle of incidence (i) = Angle of reflection (r) Law 2: The incident ray, the reflected ray, and the normal all lie in the same plane What each part means: Angle of incidence = angle between the incoming ray and the normal (not the surface) Angle of reflection = angle between the reflected ray and the normal \\\"Same plane\\\" = these three lines are coplanar — they don't go off in a third dimension Where it comes from: Euclid described equal angles around 300 BCE. Newton's corpuscular theory explained it mechanically (elastic bounce). Wave theory confirmed it — at a perfectly smooth surface, the wavefront reverses its perpendicular component while maintaining its parallel component. The result: perfect angular symmetry. The analogy that makes it click: A billiard ball hitting a flat cushion at perfect elasticity: the ball's horizontal speed stays the same; only the vertical component reverses. If you throw the ball at 30° to the cushion, it bounces off at 30° on the other side. Light is the ball; the normal is the perpendicular to the cushion. Why i = r and not i = 90° − r or some other formula: Any other relationship would require a surface that adds or removes energy from the light during reflection. Perfectly elastic reflection conserves energy completely — the only way to do that with an equal-and-opposite bounce is equal angles. What it does NOT explain: Laws of reflection apply to specular (smooth) surfaces. Diffuse (rough) reflection has the same law at each microscopic point, but the surface normals point in random directions — so the reflected rays scatter everywhere even though each individual ray obeys i = r. Cross-subject connections: C4 (Retinoscopy): The retinoscopy reflex is created by light reflecting off the retina. The direction and movement of the reflex follows reflection geometry — understanding that the reflex comes from a specific retinal location and travels back through the optical system at specific angles is fundamental to interpreting the retinoscopy finding. A2-03 (Cornea): The corneal reflex in Hirschberg testing and the keratometer mire images both use specular reflection off the anterior corneal surface. The position of the reflex directly measures corneal curvature through reflection geometry. Reading the Result — Reflection: Finding What it means Reflex exactly on center of cornea No angle kappa; no apparent deviation Reflex displaced temporally Positive angle kappa OR exotropia — use cover test to distinguish Smooth, sharp mire image on keratometer Regular corneal surface (regular astigmatism or emmetropia) Distorted mire image Irregular corneal surface (keratoconus, corneal scar)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-2-mirror-equation\",\"heading\":\"Formula 2 — Mirror Equation\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"1/p + 1/q = 1/f (same as thin lens equation) p = object distance (from vertex to object; always positive for real objects) q = image distance (from vertex to image) f = focal length (from vertex to focal point); f = R/2 Linear magnification: m = −q/p = i/o What each part means: 1/p = vergence of incoming light (how strongly the rays diverge from the object) 1/q = vergence of reflected light (how strongly rays converge to form image) 1/f = the mirror's \\\"bending power\\\" — how much vergence it adds per unit of reflection The equation says: incoming vergence + mirror power = outgoing vergence Where it comes from: The mirror equation is a geometric consequence of the law of reflection applied to a curved surface. For a spherical mirror with radius R, tracing just two rays (using the laws of reflection) shows that they meet at a distance q where 1/p + 1/q = 2/R = 1/f. It was first derived rigorously by Alhazen around 1000 CE. The analogy that makes it click: Think of the mirror as a \\\"vergence machine.\\\" Light arriving from an object carries a certain amount of divergence (= 1/p). The mirror adds its own convergence (= 1/f). The result (1/q) tells you how much total convergence the reflected light has — which tells you where it focuses. If 1/f is large (strong mirror, short f) → image forms close If the object is very far away (1/p ≈ 0) → image forms at the focal point Why f = R/2: The center of curvature C is at distance R. For a ray hitting the mirror at the vertex and one parallel to the axis, both reflect and meet exactly halfway between V and C — at R/2. This is a geometric consequence of equal angles at every point on a sphere. Sign conventions for mirrors: Positive (+) Negative (−) f Concave mirror (converging) Convex mirror (diverging) q Real image (in front of mirror) Virtual image (behind mirror) m Upright image Inverted image i (image size) Upright Inverted Reading the Result — Mirror Equation: Result What it means Practical interpretation q positive Real image — forms in FRONT of the mirror Can be projected on a screen; real q negative Virtual image — forms BEHIND the mirror Cannot be projected; apparent image only m = +1 Virtual, upright, same size The plane mirror. m = +1 forces q = −p, and substituting into 1/p + 1/q = 1/f gives 1/f = 0, so f and R are infinite. Image sits as far behind the mirror as the object is in front m = −1 Same size; inverted Object exactly at C of concave mirror (q = C = 2f) \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Magnified Object between F and C of a concave mirror (real, inverted); or inside F of a concave mirror (virtual, upright) \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Minified Object beyond C (concave); or any position on a convex mirror m positive, \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Upright AND magnified → virtual Object between F and V (inside F) of concave mirror — magnifying mirror m negative, \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Inverted AND minified → real Object beyond C of concave mirror Concave mirror cases — the six rules: Object position Image Location m sign At ∞ Real, inverted, point At F − Beyond C Real, inverted, minified Between C and F − At C Real, inverted, same size At C −1 Between C and F Real, inverted, magnified Beyond C − At F No image — undefined Between F and V Virtual, upright, magnified Behind mirror + Convex mirror: ALWAYS virtual, upright, minified — regardless of object position. Cross-subject connections: C4 (Objective Examination): Direct ophthalmoscope produces a 15× virtual upright image (equivalent to object inside F — concave mirror case 6). Indirect ophthalmoscope produces a real inverted image (equivalent to case 2 or 4). The mirror equation explains why each instrument gives the image it does. F7 (Low Vision — Magnification): Stand magnifiers use a concave lens or mirror to produce a virtual upright magnified image — directly applying the mirror/lens equation with the object inside the focal length.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-3-lateral-displacement-plane-refractor\",\"heading\":\"Formula 3 — Lateral Displacement (Plane Refractor)\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"d = t × sin(i − R) / cos R d = lateral displacement (same units as t) t = thickness of the plane refractor (glass slab) i = angle of incidence R = angle of refraction (found via Snell's law first) What each part means: A plane refractor has two parallel flat surfaces — light exits parallel to how it entered (no permanent angular deviation) but shifted sideways by distance d t = how thick the glass is (more glass = more shift) (i − R) = the angle between the original ray direction and the direction inside the glass — this is the \\\"tilt\\\" inside the material cos R = corrects for the oblique path the light takes while traveling thickness t inside the medium Where it comes from: The derivation is pure geometry. Inside the glass, the ray travels at angle R. The perpendicular path through thickness t at angle R has actual path length = t/cos R. The sideways component of this path = (t/cos R) × sin(i − R). Simplifying gives d = t sin(i − R)/cos R. The analogy that makes it click: Imagine walking straight into a shallow pool at an angle, then walking out the other side. Inside the pool, your path bends toward the vertical (less tilt). When you come out, you're tilted the same as when you entered — but you've shifted sideways because you walked a slightly different angled path inside. The thicker the pool (more glass), the more sideways shift. Why the direction is preserved but displacement occurs: Because both surfaces are parallel. At the first surface, Snell's law bends the ray toward normal. At the second surface, the reverse happens — the ray exits at the original angle. Net angular effect = zero. But the offset path inside creates a lateral shift. Reading the Result — Lateral Displacement: Result What it means Clinical note d > 0 Light is displaced in the direction away from the normal Expected for any oblique incidence d = 0 Normal incidence (i = 0) Ray hits surface perpendicularly; no displacement Larger t (thicker glass) More lateral displacement Thick glass presents more displacement — relevant in high-power lenses Larger (i − R) More displacement Steeper angle of approach = more shift\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-4-shallowing-effect-apparent-depth\",\"heading\":\"Formula 4 — Shallowing Effect (Apparent Depth)\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"q / n' = p / n q = apparent distance (image distance from surface) n' = index where the observer is (usually air = 1.0) p = actual distance (object distance from surface) n = index where the object is (denser medium) Simplified (observer in air): q = p × (n'/n) = p / n What each part means: The object is at actual depth p inside a denser medium (water, glass) The observer in air traces the refracted rays backward — they appear to come from a shallower point q The ratio n'/n tells you how much shallower: since n > n', q < p — the object appears closer than it is Where it comes from: This is Snell's law applied to the paraxial approximation (small angles). For small angles, sin θ ≈ tan θ ≈ θ. The geometry of the refracted rays traced backward gives q = p × (n_observer / n_object). This was known to ancient opticians but formalized with Snell's law. The analogy that makes it click: You're in a swimming pool looking up. Your friend outside looks straight down and sees you — but your image appears 25% closer to the surface than you actually are (water n=1.33, so you appear at 1/1.33 = 75% of your actual depth). This is why pools look shallower than they are, and why fish appear closer than they are to a bird. Reading the Result — Shallowing Effect: Finding What it means Board trap q < p Object appears CLOSER than actual — expected when going dense→rare Objects in water always look shallower to an observer in air q = p/n For observer in air: apparent depth = actual depth ÷ n A coin at 40cm in water (n=1.33) appears at 40/1.33 = 30cm q > p Object appears FARTHER than actual — when going rare→dense A bird in air appears farther away to a fish underwater n > 1.33 → smaller q Denser medium = more shallowing Dense glass makes objects appear even closer Clinical application: Slit-lamp depth measurements of corneal foreign bodies, anterior chamber depth, and lens thickness must be corrected for the refractive index of the cornea/aqueous. The apparent position of structures is always shallower than the actual depth by a factor of n.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-5-thin-lens-equation\",\"heading\":\"Formula 5 — Thin Lens Equation\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"1/p + 1/q = 1/f (identical to mirror equation) p = object distance (from optical center of lens) q = image distance (from optical center of lens) f = focal length of the lens D = 1/f (in meters) = lens power in diopters Linear magnification: m = −q/p = i/o What each part means: 1/p = vergence of light arriving at the lens from the object (divergent = positive, from real object) 1/q = vergence of light leaving the lens toward the image 1/f = how much vergence the lens adds per pass-through (= dioptric power) The equation is simply: vergence in + lens power = vergence out Where it comes from: Derived from Snell's law applied to both surfaces of a thin lens simultaneously, assuming the lens is thin enough that both refractions happen at the same plane. René Descartes formulated it around 1637. For a thick lens, additional correction is needed. The analogy that makes it click: Same \\\"vergence machine\\\" as the mirror. An object sends divergent rays toward the lens — those rays carry 1/p of divergence. The lens adds 1/f of convergence. The result 1/q tells you the remaining vergence after the lens acts. If 1/q is positive, the rays are converging (real image). If negative, they're still diverging (virtual image). Sign conventions for lenses: Positive (+) Negative (−) f Converging (convex/plus) lens Diverging (concave/minus) lens p Real object (in front of lens) Virtual object q Real image (behind lens) Virtual image (same side as object) m Upright image Inverted image Reading the Result — Thin Lens Equation: Result What it means Practical test q positive Real image — forms on FAR side of lens from object Can be projected on a screen or film q negative Virtual image — forms on SAME side as object Cannot be projected; eye must look through lens to see it m = −q/p positive Upright image → virtual Magnifying glass; reading glasses over CL; indirect ophthalmoscope? No — that's real m = −q/p negative Inverted image → real Camera, eye, projector \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Magnified Object between F and 2F (real, inverted) or inside F (virtual, upright) \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Minified Object beyond 2F (real, inverted); any position for minus lens The practical two-question check after every lens calculation: Is q positive or negative? → Tells you real or virtual. Is m positive or negative? → Tells you upright or inverted. These two answers, combined with |m|, completely describe the image. Sample calculations — worked in full: Problem 1: Converging lens (+5.00 D = f 20 cm), object 30 cm away. 1/30 + 1/q = 1/20 1/q = 1/20 − 1/30 = 3/60 − 2/60 = 1/60 q = +60 cm → REAL image (behind lens) m = −q/p = −60/30 = −2.0 m negative → INVERTED ; |m| = 2 → MAGNIFIED 2× Result: Real, inverted, magnified, 60cm behind lens Problem 2: Concave lens (−20 cm = f), object 35 cm away. 1/35 + 1/q = 1/(−20) = −0.05 1/q = −0.05 − 1/35 = −0.05 − 0.0286 = −0.0786 q = −12.73 cm → VIRTUAL image (same side as object) m = −(−12.73)/35 = +0.36 m positive → UPRIGHT ; |m| = 0.36 → MINIFIED Result: Virtual, upright, minified — ALWAYS for concave lens Problem 3: Concave mirror (f = 20 mm), tooth 16 mm away (dentist's mirror) 1/16 + 1/q = 1/20 1/q = 1/20 − 1/16 = 4/80 − 5/80 = −1/80 q = −80 mm → VIRTUAL image (behind mirror) m = −(−80)/16 = +5.0 m positive → UPRIGHT ; |m| = 5 → MAGNIFIED 5× Result: Virtual, upright, magnified 5× — classic magnifying mirror use case\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-6-surface-power-of-a-single-refracting-surface\",\"heading\":\"Formula 6 — Surface Power of a Single Refracting Surface\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"D = (n₂ − n₁) / R (R in meters) D = 100(n₂ − n₁) / R (R in cm) D = 1000(n₂ − n₁) / R (R in mm) D = 40(n₂ − n₁) / R (R in inches) D = refractive power of the surface n₁ = index of the incoming medium (usually air = 1.0) n₂ = index of the refracting medium R = radius of curvature (positive for convex, negative for concave, towards incident light) What each part means: (n₂ − n₁) = the \\\"step\\\" in optical density at the surface — larger step = more bending R = how curved the surface is — smaller R = tighter curve = more power D is inversely proportional to R: tighter curves give more power per same n difference Where it comes from: Derived from Snell's law applied to a curved surface in the paraxial approximation. The power of a single surface depends on the n difference across it and its curvature. If n₂ = n₁, the surface has no power regardless of curvature (explains why a lens in water with matching index becomes powerless). The analogy that makes it click: Think of the n difference as the \\\"steepness of the hill\\\" at the surface, and R as the \\\"width of the doorway.\\\" A large n step (steep hill) with a tight curve (narrow door) creates maximum bending. The cornea works this way: large n step (air 1.0 → cornea 1.376) with a relatively tight radius (7.8mm) gives the eye's most powerful surface at 43D. Reading the Result — Surface Power: Result What it means Clinical connection D positive Convex surface — converging Front surface of cornea (+48D), front surface of plus spectacle lens D negative Concave surface — diverging Posterior corneal surface (−5D reduces total corneal power to ~43D) D ≈ 0 despite curvature n₁ ≈ n₂ (matching media) Contact lens in tear film — reduces corneal surface power to near zero; the CL's own surfaces take over Large D from small R Tight curvature = high power Keratoconic cornea: steep K reading → high corneal power → myopia Large D from large n step n difference matters more than curvature Air-cornea interface (n step 0.376) far more powerful than aqueous-lens interface Sample calculations: Cornea: R = 7.7 mm, n₁ = 1.0 (air), n₂ = 1.376 D = 1000(1.376 − 1.0) / 7.7 = 1000(0.376)/7.7 = +48.83 D (front surface) Posterior cornea: R = 6.8 mm, n₁ = 1.376, n₂ = 1.336 D = 1000(1.336 − 1.376) / 6.8 = 1000(−0.04)/6.8 = −5.88 D (reduces total) Net corneal power ≈ 48.83 − 5.88 ≈ 43 D ✓\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-formula-7-prism-diopter-and-deviation\",\"heading\":\"Formula 7 — Prism Diopter and Deviation\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"PRISM DIOPTER DEFINITION : △ = displacement (cm) / distance (m) △ = 100 tan θ tan θ = △/100 PRISM ANGLE FORMULA : a = θ / (n − 1) a = apical angle of the prism (degrees) θ = angle of deviation (degrees) n = index of refraction of prism material What each part means: A prism diopter is how much the prism deflects a ray — measured as centimeters of displacement per meter of distance 1△ = 1 cm of displacement at 1 meter (like Prentice's rule) θ = how many degrees the ray is bent; tan θ converts this to the displacement ratio a = the physical \\\"wedge angle\\\" of the glass; combined with n, it determines θ Where it comes from: Prentice defined the prism diopter in the 1890s to give clinicians a unit that directly relates to measurement on a screen at known distance. The apical angle formula comes from the small-angle approximation: for small-angle prisms (all ophthalmic prisms), the deviation θ ≈ (n−1) × apical angle. So a = θ/(n−1). The analogy that makes it click: Imagine holding a wedge of glass in front of your eye. The wedge is thicker at the base. Light passing through the thick side bends more than the thin side. The thicker the base (larger apical angle) AND the denser the glass (larger n), the more the light bends. The deviation θ = apical angle × (n−1). Double the apical angle → double the deviation. Use denser glass (higher n) → same apical angle gives more deviation. Properties of prisms — the four rules: 1. Light bends TOWARD THE BASE 2. Object (image) is displaced TOWARD THE APEX 3. The eye turns TOWARD THE APEX (to follow the deviated ray) 4. Prisms do NOT change vergence — diverging rays stay diverging; no dioptric power Clinical use of prisms in spectacles: Condition Prism needed Base direction Esotropia (eye turns in) Need to diverge → pull gaze out Base OUT (BO) — image shifts nasally, eye follows Exotropia (eye turns out) Need to converge → pull gaze in Base IN (BI) — image shifts temporally, eye follows Hypertropia (eye turns up) Need to pull gaze down Base DOWN (BD) on the hypertropic eye Hypotropia (eye turns down) Need to pull gaze up Base UP (BU) on the hypotropic eye Clinical Aha rule: The CORRECTING prism has its BASE pointing in the direction the eye needs to go — toward the deviated direction. Eye turns IN (esotropia) → needs to go OUT → Base OUT corrects it Eye turns OUT (exotropia) → needs to go IN → Base IN corrects it Reading the Result — Prisms: Result What it means Trap P = 5△, looking through BO prism Light bends toward base; image displaced toward apex (nasal) Image displacement = TOWARD APEX — opposite to base direction P = 0△ Object is at the optical center of the lens No prism effect anywhere along the optical axis Large △ through high-power lens Significant image displacement at reading distance Prentice's rule: P = d × F — larger the distance from OC, larger the prism a large for small n−1 material Need thick glass prism for same deviation High-index glass (larger n−1) gives more deviation per unit of apical angle → thinner prism Sample prism calculations: 2.5△ prism, n = 1.507. Find apical angle: tan θ = 2.5/100 = 0.025 → θ = 1.43° a = 1.43 / (1.507 − 1) = 1.43 / 0.507 = 2.82° 5.5△ prism, a = 4°. Find n: tan θ = 5.5/100 → θ = 3.15° 4 = 3.15/(n−1) → n−1 = 0.7875 → n = 1.79 Decentration: −8.00 D lens, patient looks 12mm below OC: P = 1.2 cm × 8.00 = 9.6△ Base Down (Minus lens: base opposite to decentration direction; looking down = inferior decentration; base is DOWN )\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Cylinder lenses and astigmatism classification: CYLINDER LENS : — Power varies by meridian — Maximum power: at the POWER MERIDIAN (90° from axis) — Zero power: at the AXIS MERIDIAN — Used to correct astigmatism TYPES OF ASTIGMATIC PRESCRIPTION : 1. Simple cylinder (sphere = 0): Plano −1.25 × 90 (simple myopic astigmatism at 90°) +1.25 × 180 (simple hyperopic astigmatism) 2. Compound cylinder (both meridians same sign, sph ≠ cyl): −1.00 −0.50 × 180 (compound myopic) +1.00 +0.50 × 90 (compound hyperopic) 3. Mixed cylinder (one meridian plus, other minus; |cyl| > |sph|): +1.25 −2.50 × 180 (this is mixed — one meridian +1.25D, other −1.25D) 4. Cross cylinder (no sphere; two pure cylinders): +1.25 × 45 = −1.00 × 135 Types of lens forms: PLUS LENSES (converging; thicker at center): Biconvex — two convex surfaces Plano-convex — one flat, one convex Equiconvex — both surfaces equal curvature Plus meniscus — front convex, back concave (front steeper) MINUS LENSES (diverging; thinner at center): Biconcave — two concave surfaces Plano-concave — one flat, one concave Equiconcave — both surfaces equal Minus meniscus — front convex, back concave (back steeper) PERISCOPIC FORMS (reduce aberrations): Plus periscopic: back surface = −1.25 D Minus periscopic: front surface = +1.25 D MASS PRODUCTION : Most lenses are meniscus form — reduces off-axis aberrations Lens movement test (neutralization): Move the lens in any direction: AGAINST movement (object moves opposite to lens direction) → PLUS lens WITH movement (object moves same direction as lens) → MINUS lens NO movement → Plano (no power) This is the fundamental clinical neutralization test used with retinoscopy and in the dispensing lab.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Plane mirror vs Spherical mirror: Feature Plane mirror Concave mirror Convex mirror Image orientation Upright Upright (inside F) OR inverted (outside F) Always upright Image size Same as object Variable (depends on position) Always minified Image nature Virtual Virtual (inside F) OR real (outside F) Always virtual Focal length ∞ (no focal point) Positive Negative Field of view Narrow (= mirror size) Narrow Wide (diverging rays) Clinical use Patient hand mirrors Dentist's mouth mirror, makeup mirror Rearview mirrors, security mirrors Concave vs Convex lens movement test: Action Plus (convex) lens Minus (concave) lens Move lens upward Object appears to move DOWN Object appears to move UP Move lens right Object appears to move LEFT Object appears to move RIGHT Remember Against movement = PLUS With movement = MINUS Why Plus lens creates real inverted image for objects beyond F; image moves opposite Minus lens creates virtual upright image; image moves same direction\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Mirror: f = R/2 f is always half the radius of curvature Concave mirror with R=40mm → f=20mm Convex mirror focal length Always negative Virtual focus; always minified images Plane mirror image Object distance = image distance; same size Upright, virtual, lateral reversal (perverted) 1° of prism deviation = 1.75△ Conversion between degrees and prism diopters Prism: light bends TOWARD BASE Object appears displaced TOWARD APEX Plane refractor No dioptric power; only lateral displacement Parallel exit ray; d = t sin(i−R)/cos R Shallowing: observer in air q = p/n Object in water at 40cm appears at 40/1.33 = 30cm Surface power (cornea front) ~+48D Cornea contributes ~2/3 of total eye power Surface power (cornea back) ~−6D Posterior surface REDUCES total power Net corneal power ~43D Result of both surfaces Curvature formula C = 1/r; mirror power F = 2C = 2/r Steeper curve (smaller r) = higher power Spherical aberration Peripheral rays focus closer than paraxial rays (concave mirror) Caused by spherical surface geometry; paraboloidal mirrors eliminate it\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Mirror cases — \\\"BSCV FMAV\\\" (Beyond, Same, between C and F, at F, before V → Minified, Same, Magnified) Beyond C: minified; at C: same size; between C and F: magnified; at F: no image; before F (inside F): virtual magnified Prism rules — \\\"BASE is the Bully; APEX is the Address\\\" Light bends TOWARD BASE; image displaced TOWARD APEX; eye turns TOWARD APEX Esotropia → Base OUT; Exotropia → Base IN \\\"The base points toward where the eye needs to go\\\" Lens movement test — \\\"PLUS = AGAINST; MINUS = WITH\\\" Plus lens moves against you; minus lens moves with you. Like a seesaw: plus pushes back. Surface power rule — \\\"No n-step = No power\\\" If n₁ = n₂, the surface does nothing regardless of curvature. Contact lens in matching tear film = no corneal power. Shallowing rule — \\\"Divide by n to find apparent depth\\\" Actual depth ÷ n = apparent depth (for observer in air)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"MIRROR EQUATION (identical to lens equation) ───────────────────────────────────────────── 1/p + 1/q = 1/f Object → Mirror Image location: near (p < f): q < 0 → virtual, behind mirror ( UPRIGHT , MAGNIFIED ) at f: q = ∞ → no image p > f: q > 0 → real, in front of mirror ( INVERTED ) PRISM DEVIATION ──────────────────────────────────── APEX (thin) / / ← image displaced here (toward apex) / ← eye turns here (toward apex) ------/-------- (optical interface) \\\\ ← light bends here (toward base) \\\\ BASE (thick) SIGN CONVENTION SUMMARY (lenses and mirrors) ───────────────────────────────────────────── f (+): converging (convex lens / concave mirror) f (−): diverging (concave lens / convex mirror) q (+): real image (far side of lens / front of mirror) q (−): virtual image (near side of lens / behind mirror) m (+): upright image m (−): inverted image |m| > 1: magnified |m| < 1: minified\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"The image in a plane mirror is real Always virtual and upright, same size, same distance behind the mirror as object in front. A convex mirror can form a real image Convex mirrors always form virtual, upright, minified images regardless of object position. The prism base direction tells you which way the image moves Light moves toward the BASE; the IMAGE moves toward the APEX. Opposite directions. A plane refractor has dioptric power and changes vergence A plane refractor (flat glass slab) only laterally displaces rays. The exit ray is parallel to the entrance ray — no change in vergence, no dioptric power. A minus lens can produce a real image A minus (concave) lens always produces a virtual, upright, minified image regardless of object position. Surface power only depends on the radius of curvature Surface power depends on BOTH the radius AND the n difference across the surface. A surface with matching media (n₁ = n₂) has zero power regardless of curvature. Objects in water always appear at their true depth Objects in denser media appear closer to the observer due to refraction (shallowing effect). Apparent depth = actual depth ÷ n. Correcting prism for esotropia is Base In Esotropia needs Base OUT. The eye deviates inward; the base points outward to draw the gaze back out. The lens movement test shows WITH movement for a plus lens Plus lens shows AGAINST movement (object moves opposite to lens direction). Minus = WITH.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Laws of reflection i = r; incident ray, normal, reflected ray coplanar Plane mirror image Virtual, upright, same size, same distance behind mirror Convex mirror image Always virtual, upright, minified f for concave mirror Positive f for convex mirror Negative (diverging) Mirror/lens formula 1/p + 1/q = 1/f q positive → Real image (front of mirror / behind lens) q negative → Virtual image (behind mirror / same side as object) m positive → Upright image m negative → Inverted image Concave lens image Always virtual, upright, minified Shallowing formula q = p × (n_observer / n_object) Prism: light bends TOWARD BASE Prism: image displaced TOWARD APEX Esotropia corrected by Base OUT prism Exotropia corrected by Base IN prism 1° deviation = 1.75△ Surface power formula D = (n₂ − n₁)/R × conversion factor Contact lens reduces corneal power because n step between air and cornea eliminated; replaced by n step at CL back surface Lens movement test: plus = AGAINST movement Lens movement test: minus = WITH movement\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"1. A dentist uses a concave mirror with radius of curvature 40mm to examine a tooth positioned 15mm from the mirror. What type of image is formed and what is the magnification? A. Real, inverted, magnified B. Virtual, upright, magnified C. Real, inverted, minified D. Virtual, upright, minified Answer B. Virtual, upright, magnified. f = R/2 = 40/2 = 20mm. Object at 15mm = inside the focal length (15 < 20). When the object is between F and the mirror, the concave mirror produces a virtual, upright, magnified image behind the mirror (same as a magnifying mirror). Using the formula: 1/15 + 1/q = 1/20 → 1/q = 1/20 − 1/15 = 3/60 − 4/60 = −1/60 → q = −60mm (negative = virtual, behind mirror). m = −q/p = −(−60)/15 = +4. Positive m = upright; |m| = 4 = magnified 4×. This is exactly how dentist's mouth mirrors work — they are concave mirrors used with the tooth just inside the focal length to produce a magnified virtual image. 2. A prism is prescribed for a patient with 8△ of right exotropia. The correct prism for the right eye is: A. 8△ Base Out right eye B. 8△ Base In right eye C. 4△ Base Out each eye D. 4△ Base In each eye Answer B. 8△ Base In right eye (or D: 4△ Base In each eye — both are acceptable splits). Exotropia means the right eye deviates outward (temporally). To correct it, the prism must redirect the visual axis inward (nasally). A Base In prism has its apex temporal — light bends toward the base (nasal), and the eye follows the image toward the apex (temporal). Wait — re-reading: image displaces toward APEX. Apex is temporal → image appears temporal → eye moves toward apex (temporal). That would increase the exotropia. Let me reconsider. Correction: For exotropia (eye turns OUT), the correcting prism is Base IN. Here's the reasoning: the prism must move the image nasally (inward) so the eye moves inward to fixate it. With Base IN, the base faces nasally — light bends toward the nasal base — the image displaces toward the temporal APEX. The eye follows TOWARD THE APEX (temporal)... this seems wrong. Clarification: The rule is — the CORRECTING prism base points toward the deviated direction. Right exotropia = eye deviated OUT (temporal). Correcting prism base points INWARD (nasal) = Base IN. This places the base between the deviated eye and the image, bending light toward it. Answer: B (Base In right eye) or D (split equally). The Board most commonly asks for the full prism on the affected eye: B. 3. A coin sits 40cm below the surface of water (n=1.33). Where does the coin appear to an observer directly above the water? A. 40 cm below the surface B. 30 cm below the surface C. 53 cm below the surface D. 27 cm below the surface Answer B. 30 cm below the surface. Using the shallowing formula for an observer in air (n' = 1.0): q = p × (n'/n) = 40 × (1.0/1.33) = 40/1.33 = 30.08 ≈ 30 cm. The coin appears 30cm deep, not 40cm. This is the shallowing effect — objects in denser media always appear closer to the observer due to refraction at the surface. The ratio 1/n = 1/1.33 = 0.75 means objects in water appear at 75% of their actual depth. This is also why pools appear shallower than they are, and why slit-lamp depth measurements must be corrected by dividing by the medium's index.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-02-geometric-optics-reflection-refraction-lenses-mirrors-prisms-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D1-02 — Geometric Optics: Reflection, Refraction, Lenses, Mirrors, and Prisms\",\"text\":\"Close note first. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"GEOMETRIC OPTICS.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: laws of reflection (2 laws), plane mirror image properties, mirror equation, thin lens equation, prism direction rules, shallowing formula, surface power formula, lens movement test. Core targets: Mirror and lens equation (same formula) — write it and state what each variable's sign means Prism: which way does light bend? Which way does the image move? Correcting prism directions for esotropia, exotropia, hypertropia, hypotropia Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the six cases of image formation for a concave mirror. For each case, sketch object position relative to F and C, sketch the image location, and write one-word descriptors (real/virtual, upright/inverted, same/larger/smaller). Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain the shallowing effect to a patient who asks why the water in the pool looks so shallow. Start from what happens to light at the surface. Do not use the word \\\"refraction\\\" until your final sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Plane mirror image? Virtual, upright, same size, same distance behind Convex mirror image? Always virtual, upright, minified q positive in lens/mirror eq? Real image q negative? Virtual image m positive? Upright m negative? Inverted Prism: light bends toward? BASE Prism: image displaced toward? APEX Esotropia → prism? Base OUT Exotropia → prism? Base IN Plus lens movement test? AGAINST (with-against rule) Shallowing: object at 40cm in water (n=1.33)? Appears at 30cm Surface power = 0 when? n₁ = n₂ (matching media) Drill 5 — Calculation Set (all formula types) Work all of these without looking at rules. Use the sign convention table to interpret each answer: Concave mirror (f=30cm), object 20cm away → find q, m, describe image Convex mirror (R=60cm), object 40cm away → find q, m, describe image Converging lens (+3.00D), object 40cm away → find q, m Diverging lens (f=−15cm), object 25cm away → find q, m Shallowing: diamond (n=2.417) cube 30cm below surface → apparent depth? Prism: 3.5△ prism, n=1.523 → find apical angle Lens decentration: +6.00D lens, patient looks 8mm temporal to OC → P=? Base direction? Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow Six-case concave mirror diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (shallowing to patient) 4th 1 week Full calculation set (all 7 problems) Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"> Explain this like you're teaching it to someone who has never seen it before. No jargon. One clear paragraph. A converging lens has a fixed amount of bending power, and the object and the image have to share it. Picture the object and the image sitting on opposite ends of a seesaw balanced in the middle. Push the object toward the lens and the image runs away from the lens. Pull the object back and the image comes in close. They cross paths at exactly one spot, the place we call 2F, and that is the only position where they sit at equal distances and come out the same size. Everything else follows from that one movement. If the image ends up farther out than the object, it is bigger. If it ends up closer in, it is smaller. And if you shove the object so close that it passes the focal point, the light never gets to converge at all, so the image stops being something you could catch on a screen and becomes something your brain has to invent by tracing the rays backward. Teaching angle: Hand the class a spoon. Ask them to look at their face in the curved-in side, then slowly move it away until they flip upside down. Then ask: \\\"What just happened at the moment you flipped?\\\" That moment is F, and they will never forget it because they felt it.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"The 5-Why chain. Start from the clinical observation and drill down to the mechanism. Why does an object at exactly 2F produce an image the same size as itself? Because the image also lands at 2F on the other side, and magnification is just the ratio of those two distances. Why does the image land at 2F when the object is at 2F? Because the lens has a fixed vergence budget of 1/f, and at that position the object's divergence and the image's convergence each take exactly half of it: 1/2f + 1/2f = 1/f. Why does the budget have to split evenly at that one position and nowhere else? Because 1/p and 1/q must always sum to 1/f. If one term grows, the other must shrink. The only point where they can be equal is when both equal half the total, which forces p = q = 2f. Why does one term growing force the other to shrink? Because the lens cannot add more convergence than it has. Its power is fixed by its curvature and index. Light arriving with more divergence uses up more of that fixed power, so less is left over to converge the light on the far side. Why does that produce a virtual image when the object goes inside F? Because once the object is closer than f, its divergence (1/p) is larger than the entire budget (1/f). The lens spends everything it has and the light is still diverging when it leaves. 1/q goes negative. Nothing converges anywhere, so no light physically meets at a point. Your visual system, which always assumes light travels in straight lines, traces the diverging rays backward and places an image where they appear to have come from. That is the whole meaning of the word \\\"virtual.\\\" This chain is the one to rehearse. Every zone rule in this note is a consequence of the fixed-budget idea in Why 3 and Why 4.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Real image Latin res , \\\"thing\\\" Light physically arrives and crosses at that point. You could hold a card there and see it. Always inverted for a single element with a real object. Virtual image Latin virtus , \\\"power/capacity\\\", something that acts as if it were there Light never arrives at that point. The rays only appear to come from it when traced backward. Cannot be caught on a screen. Always upright for a single element with a real object. Conjugate Latin con- \\\"together\\\" + jugare \\\"to yoke\\\", i.e. yoked together The object plane and image plane are locked to each other. Swap them and the optics still work. This is why the 2F/2F case is symmetric. Conjugate foci — The paired object and image positions for a given lens. Every object position has exactly one image position. Magnification (linear/lateral) Latin magnus , \\\"great\\\" Image height ÷ object height. Computed as m = −q/p, so it is really just the ratio of the two distances with a sign attached. Erect / upright — Same orientation as the object. Interchangeable words on the board; do not read a distinction into them. Minified Latin minus , \\\"less\\\" Smaller than the object. The board also says \\\"diminished\\\" and \\\"reduced.\\\" Same thing. Inverted Latin invertere , \\\"to turn upside down\\\" Upside down relative to the object. On the board this always travels with \\\"real.\\\" 2F (lens) — Twice the focal distance. The symmetry point. C, center of curvature (mirror) — The center of the sphere the mirror was cut from. Since f = R/2, C sits at 2f . C is the mirror's 2F. Vertex (V) Latin vertex , \\\"highest point/crown\\\" The pole of the mirror, where the principal axis meets the surface. Distances for mirrors are measured from here. Lookalike trap flagged: mirror questions say \\\"C\\\" and lens questions say \\\"2F.\\\" Students memorize two separate tables and then blank under pressure. They are the same landmark. C = 2F. Once you see that, the concave mirror table stops being new information. Second lookalike: \\\"real\\\" and \\\"erect\\\" never appear together for a single element with a real object; neither do \\\"virtual\\\" and \\\"inverted.\\\" If an option pairs them, it is fabricated.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"The trigger: An object sits somewhere on the principal axis and radiates diverging light toward the element. The sequence: Light leaves the object diverging. The amount of divergence it carries is 1/p. The closer the object, the more steeply it diverges, so the larger 1/p is. The element adds a fixed amount of convergence, 1/f, set by its curvature and index. This number does not change no matter where the object goes. What is left over is the outgoing vergence, 1/q. That leftover decides everything: its sign says real or virtual, its size says near or far. The image height is then forced by geometry: the chief ray through the optical center is undeviated, so the image and object heights sit in the same ratio as their distances. m = −q/p. The key players: Object distance p — role: the demand on the system. Always positive for a real object. Bigger demand as the object comes closer. Focal length f — role: the fixed supply. Positive for converging (plus lens, concave mirror), negative for diverging (minus lens, convex mirror). Image distance q — role: the leftover. Positive means real, negative means virtual. The optical centre / chief ray — role: the reason magnification is a pure distance ratio and not something more complicated. The whole topic is supply and demand on a fixed budget. Once p is the demand and f is the supply, every zone rule is arithmetic you can see without doing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-formula-law-rule-theory-breakdown\",\"heading\":\"Formula / Law / Rule / Theory Breakdown\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Rule: The Conjugate Zone Rule (the seesaw) 1/p + 1/q = 1/f with p always positive for a real object m = −q/p Consequences, in the order you use them on the board: (1) sign of q → real (+) or virtual (−) (2) real ⇒ inverted; virtual ⇒ upright (3) |m| = q/p → whichever is FARTHER from the element is BIGGER (4) p = 2f → q = 2f, m = −1, the symmetry point What it states in plain language: The object and the image trade places around the lens. Move one closer and the other moves away, and the one sitting farther from the lens is always the bigger of the two. What each part means: p = how far the actual thing is from the lens. Physically, how steeply its light is spreading when it arrives. q = how far from the lens the light either converges (positive) or appears to come from (negative). f = the fixed bending budget of the element. Nothing the object does changes it. The sum in 1/p + 1/q = 1/f is the crux: because the right side is fixed, the two terms on the left are locked in a trade. This is the mathematical form of the seesaw. The minus sign in m = −q/p exists to encode orientation, not size. It is the bookkeeping that makes \\\"real\\\" and \\\"inverted\\\" arrive together automatically instead of being two separate facts to memorize. Where it comes from: The relation traces to Alhazen's work on spherical mirrors around 1000 CE, later generalised to refracting surfaces. The observation that forced it: a lens does not have one image position, it has a different image position for every object position, yet the pattern is orderly. People needed a single statement that predicted all of them. The reciprocal form appears because what actually adds linearly in optics is vergence (the reciprocal of distance), not distance itself. That is why the equation looks awkward until you stop reading it as distances and start reading it as vergences. The analogy that makes it click: Two people splitting a fixed bill. The bill total is 1/f. This is the lens's power and it never changes. The object's share is 1/p. A close object is a greedy diner: steep divergence, big share. What is left for the image is 1/q. Now every case falls out: Object far away → tiny share (1/p ≈ 0) → the image pays almost the whole bill (1/q ≈ 1/f) → image sits at F. Object at 2f → its share is 1/2f, exactly half the bill → the image's share is the other half → image at 2f too. Equal shares means equal distances means same size. This is why 2F is the symmetry point and not some arbitrary memorized case. Object between f and 2f → it takes more than half → less is left for the image → 1/q is small → q is large → image sits far out and is therefore magnified. Object at f → it takes the entire bill → nothing left → 1/q = 0 → q = infinity → no image forms. Object inside f → it demands more than the bill total → the account goes negative → 1/q negative → virtual image, on the object's own side. The analogy maps exactly: fixed total ↔ 1/f, each diner's share ↔ 1/p and 1/q, overspending ↔ virtual image. Why this form and not another: Suppose the relation were p + q = constant instead of 1/p + 1/q = 1/f. Then the object and image would still trade off, but linearly, and there would be no focal point, no infinity case, and no virtual images. An object at any distance would always produce a real image somewhere. The reciprocal form is exactly what creates a hard boundary at p = f, and that boundary is the entire real/virtual divide. The reciprocals are not a mathematical inconvenience; they are the thing that makes the focal point exist. Second test: suppose m were +q/p instead of −q/p. Then real images would come out upright, and the retinal image would not be inverted, and there would be no need for cortical reinversion. The minus sign is doing real physical work. What it does NOT explain (its limits): Paraxial only. Rays far from the axis do not obey it; that is spherical aberration. Thin element only. For thick lenses and the eye itself you need principal planes and Gullstrand's cardinal points (see D1-Gullstrand-Cardinal-Points-Interactive.html ). Single element with a real object. Inside a multi-element system the intermediate image can act as a virtual object with negative p, and the \\\"real ⇒ inverted\\\" shortcut breaks. Monochromatic. Says nothing about chromatic aberration. Spherical surfaces only. Says nothing about the two-focal-line behaviour of a toric surface, which is the whole of astigmatism. It gives lateral magnification only. Axial (depth) magnification behaves as the square of it, which is why a magnifier distorts depth more than width. Cross-subject connections: C4 (Objective Examination), indirect ophthalmoscopy: the condensing lens is held so the patient's retina sits between F and 2F of the lens. That zone is exactly the \\\"real, inverted, magnified\\\" case, which is precisely why the BIO image is aerial, inverted, and reversed. Change the working distance and you slide along the zone table, which is why moving the lens changes both magnification and field. C4, direct ophthalmoscopy: the patient's own optics place the retina inside F of the eye's dioptric system, giving a virtual, upright, roughly 15× magnified image. Same rule, different zone, opposite answer. The two ophthalmoscopes are the same rule read at two different object positions. F7 (Low Vision), simple and stand magnifiers: a magnifier only works held closer than its focal length. That is the inside-F zone: virtual, upright, magnified. A stand magnifier fixes that distance mechanically so a patient with tremor cannot accidentally cross F and flip the image. B1 / C2 (retinal image formation): a real-world object sits far beyond 2F of the eye's +60 D system, which is the \\\"real, inverted, minified\\\" zone. This is the origin of the inverted retinal image, and therefore the reason the visual cortex must reinvert. D2 (Dispensing), the same-size method of finding focal length: slide an object and a screen until the image is exactly the same size as the object. That configuration is p = q = 2f, so f = p/2. The minimum possible object-to-screen separation for a real image is 4f , and it occurs at this configuration. If the bench separation is less than 4f, no real image forms at any lens position. Reading the Result — instant interpretation rules: Result / Value What it tells you Board / Clinical trap to watch q positive Real image. Opposite side for a lens, same side (in front) for a mirror The side flips between lens and mirror; the sign convention does not q negative Virtual image, on the object's own side Cannot be projected; the eye must look through/at the element m = −1 Same size, inverted, real Object at exactly 2F (lens) or exactly C (mirror). This is the answer to \\\"same size\\\" stems m negative, \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Real, inverted, minified Object beyond 2F / beyond C m negative, \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Real, inverted, magnified Object between F and 2F / between F and C m positive, \\\\ m\\\\ > 1 Virtual, upright, magnified Object inside F. The magnifying-glass case m positive, \\\\ m\\\\ < 1 Virtual, upright, minified Only from a diverging element (minus lens or convex mirror), at any distance 1/q = 0 No image. Emergent rays parallel Object exactly at F. The stem will say \\\"at the focal point\\\" The key question for any result: is the sign what I expect, and is the magnitude reasonable? If m came out positive but you expected a projected image, you put the object on the wrong side of F.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"The decision tree, in the order to run it: Is the element converging or diverging? | +-- DIVERGING (minus lens, convex mirror) | └── STOP . Virtual, upright, minified. Always. No zones. No exceptions. | +-- CONVERGING (plus lens, concave mirror) | Where is the object relative to F? | +-- INSIDE F ----- --> Virtual, upright, MAGNIFIED | (image on object's own side, farther out than the object) | +-- AT F --------- --> No image. Rays emerge parallel. Image \\\"at infinity\\\" | +-- OUTSIDE F ---- --> REAL , INVERTED . Now compare to 2F (= C for a mirror): | +-- Between F and 2F - --> MAGNIFIED (image beyond 2F) +-- At 2F ------------ --> SAME SIZE (image at 2F) +-- Beyond 2F -------- --> MINIFIED (image between F and 2F) +-- At infinity ------ --> point image at F Why the last four lines do not need memorizing: Read them off the seesaw instead. In every one of those rows the image sits on the opposite side of 2F from the object, and the farther one is the bigger one. Object beyond 2F means image inside 2F means image is closer means image is smaller. You can regenerate the entire table from that one sentence.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Converging vs diverging: the reason one is hard and one is free Feature Converging (+ lens, concave mirror) Diverging (− lens, convex mirror) Focal length sign Positive Negative Number of cases to know Five zones One. Always the same Image nature Real outside F, virtual inside F Always virtual Image orientation Inverted outside F, upright inside F Always upright Image size Depends on zone Always minified Image location Anywhere from F to infinity Always between the element and F Everyday object Magnifying glass, shaving mirror, spoon's inner curve Car side mirror, shop security mirror, spoon's back Board clue The stem gives you a distance and expects you to compare it to f The stem gives a distance and it is irrelevant. If you are calculating hard on a minus lens, you have misread the question Lens vs mirror: the only real difference Feature Converging lens Concave mirror The symmetry landmark 2F C (and C = 2F, same place) Real image sits On the far side (light passes through and keeps going) On the same side, in front (light bounces back) Zone rules Identical Identical Board clue \\\"Beyond 2F\\\" \\\"Beyond C\\\", the same sentence in different clothes The one line to carry into the exam room: a concave mirror is a converging lens folded back on itself. Same five zones, same order, same answers. Only the side the real image lands on differs, and that is decided by where the light actually went.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Worked with f = +20 cm so the arithmetic is checkable at a glance. Infinity +20 cm 0 100 cm (beyond 2F) +25 cm −0.25 60 cm (beyond 2F) +30 cm −0.50 40 cm (at 2F) +40 cm −1.00 30 cm (between F and 2F) +60 cm −2.00 25 cm (between F and 2F) +100 cm −4.00 20 cm (at F) infinity undefined 15 cm (inside F) −60 cm +4.00 10 cm (inside F) −20 cm +2.00 C in terms of f (mirror) C = 2f, since f = R/2 The mirror's C and the lens's 2F are the same landmark Symmetry point p = q = 2f, m = −1 The same-size method for measuring focal length Minimum object-to-image separation, real image 4f Below this separation no real image forms at any lens position Boundary of real vs virtual p = f The single most tested threshold in this topic Boundary of magnified vs minified (real images) p = 2f Second most tested Direct ophthalmoscope magnification about 15× Virtual, upright. Inside-F case Retinal image Real, inverted, minified Object far beyond 2F of the eye's +60 D system\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Story or analogy, the spoon test You already own the experiment. Curved-in side of a spoon held close: your face is large and right way up. Move it away and you flip upside down and shrink. The flip happened when your face crossed F. Turn the spoon over and use the back: small, upright, always, no matter what you do. The inner curve is the concave mirror and behaves like a plus lens. The back is the convex mirror and behaves like a minus lens. One household object stores the whole topic. Pattern recognition, the two sentences that replace both tables The farther one is the bigger one. (Gives you size, every time, for both lenses and mirrors, without a formula.) Only an object inside F makes a virtual image. (Gives you nature and orientation, since real always means inverted and virtual always means upright.) Grouping trick Diverging elements have no cases at all. Minus lens and convex mirror are always virtual, always upright, always minified. That deletes half the syllabus for this topic. All the difficulty lives in converging elements, and all of that is one seesaw. Derivable pattern, the bill split 1/p + 1/q = 1/f is two people splitting a fixed bill. Object far away pays little, image pays nearly all, image lands at F. Object at 2f, each pays half, image at 2f, same size. Object inside f, it overspends the whole bill, the account goes negative, image goes virtual. You never memorize the zones; you re-derive them in about four seconds.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"CONVERGING LENS (f = 20 cm), object walking in from the left ...beyond 2F........ 2F....... F...... LENS ...... F....... 2F....... | | | | | | obj here obj here obj here | img lands img lands | | | | | | v v v | v v real, inv, real, inv, NO IMAGE | (when obj (when obj MINIFIED SAME SIZE (rays parallel)| beyond 2F) at 2F) img between img at 2F | F and 2F | | obj between F and 2F --> real, inv, MAGNIFIED , img beyond 2F obj INSIDE F -------- --> virtual, upright, MAGNIFIED img on the OBJECT 'S side, farther out THE SEESAW (why the table above is not four separate facts) object <-----------[ 2F ]--------- --> image push one in, the other runs out they meet only at 2F/2F, where sizes are equal WHOEVER IS FARTHER FROM THE LENS IS BIGGER CONCAVE MIRROR = the same picture, folded beyond C | at C | between C and F | at F | inside F | | | | | minified same magnified no image virtual size (all real, inverted) upright magnified C = 2F. Nothing new. Same five zones. DIVERGING (minus lens / convex mirror) [any object position] - --> virtual, upright, minified image always squeezed between the element and F\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Trap 1: \\\"Real, inverted, larger\\\" offered when the object is at exactly 2F. Bait for anyone who registers \\\"the object is fairly close\\\" without checking whether the distance is exactly twice f. Divide p by f first. If the answer is exactly 2, the word is \\\"same,\\\" never \\\"larger.\\\" Trap 2: \\\"Virtual, magnified\\\" offered for an object outside F. Bait for anyone who remembers that a convex lens can magnify but never checks which side of F the object is on. A converging lens only produces virtual images from inside F. Trap 3: \\\"Real, erect\\\" or \\\"virtual, inverted\\\" as options. For a single element with a real object these do not exist. Cross them out on sight without reading the rest of the option. This alone often reduces four choices to two. Trap 4: calculating on a diverging element. If the stem gives a minus lens or a convex mirror and asks only for the image description , the numbers are decoration. Virtual, upright, minified. Answer and move on. Trap 5: treating C and 2F as different landmarks. A mirror stem saying \\\"object beyond C\\\" and a lens stem saying \\\"object beyond 2F\\\" are the same question. Students who memorized two tables freeze here. Trap 6: forgetting which side the real image lands on. Lens real image is on the far side; mirror real image is in front, on the object's side. The rule is not arbitrary: the real image is always where the light physically went. Light passes through a lens; light bounces back off a mirror. Trap 7: \\\"at F\\\" stems. The expected answer is that no image forms and the emergent rays are parallel, sometimes phrased as \\\"image at infinity.\\\" Options offering a specific image size are all Trap 8 (notation caution): the Board Primer's sign list states \\\"Image size (I) is (+) for real image, (−) for virtual image.\\\" That conflicts with I = m × O, where m is negative for real images. The magnification sign convention on the same page (m negative if real, positive if virtual) is the one consistent with m = −q/p and the one to use. Do not let the I-sign line contaminate your m-sign reasoning.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Value Object at 2F (or C) Real, inverted, same size , image at 2F Object beyond 2F (or C) Real, inverted, minified, image between F and 2F Object between F and 2F Real, inverted, magnified, image beyond 2F Object at F No image; rays emerge parallel Object inside F Virtual, upright, magnified, image on object's side Any diverging element, any distance Virtual, upright, minified Size rule, no formula needed Whichever is farther from the element is bigger Orientation rule Real always inverted; virtual always upright C vs 2F Same landmark. C = 2f Minimum object-to-image separation for a real image 4f, at the 2F/2F configuration Where a real image sits Lens: far side. Mirror: in front. Wherever the light actually went\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-fast-pick-elimination-layer\",\"heading\":\"Fast Pick (elimination layer)\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"Cue to scan: the sign of the element (plus/minus, concave/convex), then p ÷ f. Fast-pick rule: p ÷ f Answer less than 1 virtual, upright, larger exactly 1 no image between 1 and 2 real, inverted, larger exactly 2 real, inverted, same size more than 2 real, inverted, smaller any value, diverging element virtual, upright, smaller Elimination order: Kill every option pairing real with upright, or virtual with inverted. Usually removes one or two choices before any arithmetic. If the element is diverging, pick \\\"virtual, upright, smaller\\\" and stop. Otherwise compute p ÷ f, one division, and read the row above. If two options survive and differ only in size, apply \\\"the farther one is bigger\\\" as the tiebreak. Distractor traps to cross out on sight: \\\"virtual, magnified\\\" on an outside-F stem; \\\"larger\\\" on an exactly-2F stem; any real+upright or virtual+inverted pairing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"1. A concave mirror has a radius of curvature of 40 cm. An object is placed 30 cm in front of it. The image is: A. Real, inverted, minified B. Real, inverted, magnified C. Virtual, upright, magnified D. Real, upright, same size Answer B. Real, inverted, magnified. f = R/2 = 20 cm, so C = 40 cm. The object at 30 cm sits between F (20) and C (40), which is the \\\"real, inverted, magnified\\\" zone. Confirm: q = pf/(p−f) = (30 × 20)/10 = +60 cm, m = −60/30 = −2. Image is 60 cm in front of the mirror, twice the size, inverted. Seesaw check: the image (60) is farther from the mirror than the object (30), so the image is the bigger one. Consistent. A is the beyond-C answer. C is the inside-F answer. D is fabricated: real never travels with upright. Note that the stem gives R, not f. Halving it first is the whole question. 2. An object is placed 10 cm from a +5.00 D lens. The image formed is: A. Real, inverted, 2× magnified B. Virtual, upright, 2× magnified C. Real, inverted, same size D. Virtual, upright, 0.5× minified Answer B. Virtual, upright, 2× magnified. f = 100/5.00 = 20 cm. The object at 10 cm is inside F, so this is the simple-magnifier case. q = (10 × 20)/(10 − 20) = −20 cm (virtual, same side as the object), m = −(−20)/10 = +2. Fast pick: p ÷ f = 10/20 = 0.5, less than 1, so virtual, upright, larger. One division and you are done. A and C both require the object to be outside F. D is impossible for a plus lens: a converging element can never produce a virtual minified image. That is diverging-element behaviour, and it is the classic bait for students who mix the two tables. Cross-link (F7): this is exactly a +5.00 D hand magnifier held 10 cm from print. Push it past 20 cm and the patient's image flips and becomes real, which is why patients report the print \\\"going upside down\\\" when they hold the magnifier too far out.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-03-image-formation-zones-lenses-and-mirrors-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D1-03 — Image Formation Zones: Where the Image Goes and Why\",\"text\":\"The rule: Read the section. Close the note. Then do the drill. Only check after you've written something. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the topic name at the top of a blank page. Set a 5-minute timer. Write everything you can retrieve without looking. Then open the note, compare, and circle every gap. What to brain dump for this note: The five converging zones in order, with image nature, orientation, size, and location for each The two sentences that replace both tables (the size rule and the virtual rule) The bill-split explanation of why 2F is the symmetry point Drill 2 — Blank Diagram or Table Reproduce from memory, on paper. What to reproduce: the Visual Map number line. Draw the axis, mark the lens, F and 2F on both sides. Then, for each of the five object zones, draw the object arrow and the image arrow in the correct positions with the correct relative heights and the correct orientation. Do not just write words. Draw the arrows. If the image arrow ends up on the wrong side of 2F, you have not internalised the seesaw yet. Then do it a second time on the same page as a concave mirror, marking C instead of 2F, and confirm you produced the identical set of answers. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Flip the paper over. Write 4 to 5 sentences teaching this to a classmate. Teach-back prompt: Explain why an image can be caught on a screen in one case and not the other, without using the words \\\"real\\\" or \\\"virtual.\\\" You will be forced to describe where the light physically goes, which is the actual understanding. If you find yourself reaching for the banned words, that is the hole. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front (Question) Back (Answer) Object at 2F of a converging lens Real, inverted, same size, image at 2F Object between F and 2F Real, inverted, magnified, image beyond 2F Object beyond 2F Real, inverted, minified, image between F and 2F Object inside F Virtual, upright, magnified, image on object's side Convex mirror, object anywhere Virtual, upright, minified C equals what, in terms of f? 2f. C is the mirror's 2F Minimum object-to-image separation for a real image 4f, at the 2F/2F configuration Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the elimination sequence in order, from reading the stem to choosing the answer, without looking. Sequence to write: (1) identify converging or diverging, (2) if diverging, answer virtual/upright/minified and stop, (3) compute p ÷ f, (4) map the ratio to the zone, (5) cross out any real+upright or virtual+inverted option, (6) tiebreak on size with \\\"the farther one is bigger.\\\" Then run it cold against five stems you write yourself, mixing lenses and mirrors, and including one stem that gives R instead of f. Recall Interval Schedule for This Note Session When What to do 1st review Same day you write it Brain Dump (Drill 1) 2nd review Next day Blank Diagram + Flash Cards (Drills 2 + 4) 3rd review 3 days later Teach-Back Write (Drill 3) 4th review 1 week later Sequence from Scratch (Drill 5) Final check 2 weeks later All 5 drills; flag anything still shaky If you nail a drill cleanly, move it to the \\\"solid\\\" pile. If you miss anything, it stays active and the interval resets.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-indices-of-refraction\",\"heading\":\"Indices of Refraction\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Medium n Cornea 1.376 Aqueous humor 1.336 Lens cortex 1.386 Lens nucleus 1.406 Vitreous humor 1.336\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-radii-of-curvature\",\"heading\":\"Radii of Curvature\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Surface Radius Anterior cornea 7.7mm Posterior cornea 6.8mm Anterior lens (unaccommodated) 10.0mm Posterior lens (unaccommodated) 6.0mm Anterior lens (fully accommodated) 5.33mm Watch out: anterior cornea is 7.7mm. The primary nodal point (7.08mm) is a different measurement — easy to confuse because both are around 7mm.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-refracting-powers-gullstrand\",\"heading\":\"Refracting Powers (Gullstrand)\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Component Power Cornea 43D Crystalline lens (unaccommodated) 19D Complete eye (unaccommodated) 58.64D Two models — know which is which: Model Total power Gullstrand's exact schematic eye 58.64D Reduced schematic eye (Emsley) 60D\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-nodal-points-and-center-of-rotation\",\"heading\":\"Nodal Points and Center of Rotation\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"All measured from the anterior cornea. Point Location Primary nodal point (N) 7.08mm Secondary nodal point (N') 7.33mm Center of rotation 13.5mm Nodal points are used for retinal image size and visual axis calculations. Center of rotation is the pivot point for all eye movements — different measurement, easy to confuse with nodal point.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-why-the-posterior-cornea-is-minus\",\"heading\":\"Why the Posterior Cornea is Minus\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Two reasons: n drops from cornea (1.376) to aqueous (1.336) — going from denser to less dense The surface is convex toward the incoming light When n decreases at a convex surface, the surface diverges light instead of converging it — that makes it minus power. The posterior cornea works against the anterior surface, which is why net corneal power (~43D) is less than what the front surface alone would produce (~48D).\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-axial-dimensions-from-corneal-apex\",\"heading\":\"Axial Dimensions (from corneal apex)\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Landmark Distance Anterior corneal apex to anterior lens 3.6mm Anterior corneal apex to posterior lens 7.2mm Lens thickness 3.6mm Emmetropic axial length (clinical) 24mm Pattern: apex to anterior lens = 3.6mm. Double it = posterior lens (7.2mm). The lens is exactly as thick as the anterior segment is deep.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-focal-lengths\",\"heading\":\"Focal Lengths\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"All measured from the anterior corneal apex. Model Primary f (in front of eye) Secondary f' (at retina) Emsley reduced eye 16.67mm 22.22mm Gullstrand exact eye 15.70mm 24.38mm Primary focal length = where an object must sit so light exits the eye as parallel rays. Secondary focal length = where parallel incoming light focuses (at the retina in emmetropia). Why 24mm ≠ 24.38mm: 24mm is the empirically measured average axial length of a real emmetropic eye. 24.38mm is where Gullstrand's mathematical model places F'. The model is a mathematical idealization — not a biological average. The real eye is slightly shorter than the model predicts.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-axes-and-lines\",\"heading\":\"Axes and Lines\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Each line is defined by which point it passes through. Line/Axis Passes through Notes Optic axis Centers of curvature of all refracting surfaces Geometric centerline — no fixation point involved Visual axis Nodal point From fixation point → nodal point → fovea Line of sight Center of entrance pupil From fixation point → entrance pupil center → fovea Pupillary axis Center of entrance pupil, perpendicular to cornea Reference axis — does not go to the fovea Fixation point = the point in space the eye is looking at.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-angles\",\"heading\":\"Angles\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Angle Between Measured at Alpha (α) Visual axis and optic axis Nodal point Kappa (κ) Visual axis and pupillary axis Corneal plane Gamma (γ) Line of sight and optic axis Center of rotation Lambda (λ) Pupillary axis and line of sight — Normal angle alpha = positive (fovea is temporal to posterior pole; visual axis tilts slightly relative to optic axis). Angle kappa is used clinically — a large positive kappa mimics exotropia (pseudo-exotropia).\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-principal-planes\",\"heading\":\"Principal Planes\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Plane Location from corneal apex H (anterior principal plane) 1.35mm behind cornea H' (posterior principal plane) 1.60mm behind cornea Both planes sit close to the cornea. Focal lengths and image distances in Gullstrand's model are measured from H and H', not from the corneal apex — which is why Gullstrand's focal lengths differ slightly from the reduced eye values.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1-constants-anchor-card-recall-prompt\",\"heading\":\"Recall Prompt\",\"topic\":\"D1 — Optical Constants Anchor Card\",\"text\":\"Cover this card. Write from memory: 5 radii of curvature with values 4 indices of refraction 3 power values (cornea / lens / total) Nodal points vs center of rotation (location + what each is used for) One sentence on why posterior cornea is minus Axial dimensions: apex to anterior lens, apex to posterior lens, the pattern connecting them Focal lengths for both models (primary and secondary) with measurement reference One sentence on why 24mm and 24.38mm are different 4 axes/lines with which point each passes through 4 angles with which two lines each is between and where it's measured H and H' with locations Confidence after recall: [ ] shaky [ ] okay [ ] solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"An ophthalmic lens is not just a piece of plastic or glass — it is a precisely engineered optical element with properties that determine how well a patient sees. The material sets the optical and mechanical baseline: index of refraction controls thickness, Abbe value controls color fringing, and specific gravity controls weight. The lens form determines aberrations for off-axis viewing. Absorptive lenses add a second function: they selectively block wavelengths that harm or discomfort the eye. Dispensing ties everything together — frame selection, fitting, adjustment, and verification to ensure the patient gets exactly what was prescribed. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"Why would you not give polycarbonate lenses to a patient who spends all day reading reports at a computer?\\\" The Abbe value of 30 means significant color fringing in peripheral gaze — and for a desk worker who reads through the lens periphery all day, CR-39 (Abbe 58) would be far more comfortable.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Why does higher index allow a thinner lens? Because higher index material bends light more per unit of surface curvature. Less curvature is needed to achieve the same dioptric power — and less curvature means the lens can be ground thinner without losing its corrective effect. Why does higher index also cause more color fringing (lower Abbe value)? Because any refracting material bends different wavelengths by slightly different amounts — this is dispersion. Higher-index materials have greater dispersion (more difference in n across wavelengths), so when viewing off-axis, white light separates into visible colors at the lens periphery. Why is polycarbonate the best choice for children and sports? Because its Dk/t (oxygen transmissibility equivalent for lenses is not the issue here — rather impact resistance) is extraordinarily high. Polycarbonate can withstand a 5/8-inch steel ball dropped from 50 inches without fracturing — the gold standard for safety eyewear. CR-39 and glass would shatter under the same impact.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Abbe value (ν) Named after Ernst Abbe Measure of chromatic dispersion; higher = less aberration; ν = (nD − 1)/(nF − nC) Specific gravity (SG) Density relative to water Higher SG = heavier lens Absorptive lens — Lens that selectively blocks specific wavelengths Photochromic Greek photos + chroma Lens that darkens on UV exposure via silver halide reaction Slab-off (bicentric grinding) — Corrects differential vertical prismatic effect in anisometropia Prism ballast — Base-down prism in toric CL to stabilize orientation CPF filter Corning Contrast Preservation Filter Longpass filter for low vision patients UV 400 — Blocks all UV below 400 nm; current gold standard Wratten filter Named after Frederick Wratten Gelatin/glass trial filter for low vision assessment\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Lens material properties — the key trade-offs: Higher index → thinner lens → more CA (lower Abbe) → more reflectance at surfaces Lower Abbe → more color fringing in periphery → patient complaint of \\\"blur at sides\\\" n-Abbe-SG RELATIONSHIP : n ↑ (higher index) → Abbe ↓ (more CA) → SG usually ↓ (lighter) or variable Exception: Trivex (n=1.532, Abbe=43-45) — good middle ground IMPACT RESISTANCE ORDER (best to worst): Polycarbonate > High-index plastic > CR-39 > Crown glass Photochromic lens mechanism: UV EXPOSURE (outdoors): Silver halide crystals → UV breaks Ag-X bond → Ag⁰ atoms form → lens darkens (Reaction: AgX + UV → Ag + X) NO UV (indoors, car): Reaction reverses → Ag⁰ reassociates with X → lens clears Darkening time: 30–60 seconds Clearing time: 2–5 minutes (longer in cold; faster in warm) LIMITATION : Car windshield blocks UV → photochromic lens does NOT activate in car Absorptive lens wavelength action: CPF FILTERS (longpass — blocks everything BELOW the cutoff): CPF 450 → cuts < 450 nm → light yellow → early changes CPF 511 → cuts < 511 nm → yellow-orange → cataract, aniridia CPF 527 → cuts < 527 nm → orange → RP, glaucoma, ARMD CPF 550 → cuts < 550 nm → amber-red → achromatopsia, severe photophobia Rule: Higher CPF number → longer cutoff → more filtered → darker appearance WRATTEN FILTERS (trial filters for LV assessment): #12 Yellow → ~500 nm cutoff → mild contrast enhancement #15 Deep yellow → ~510 nm → moderate contrast #21 Orange → ~540 nm → RP, macular disease #22 Orange → ~550 nm → similar to CPF 550 #25 Red → ~600 nm → achromatopsia, severe cone dysfunction #29 Dark red → ~640 nm → maximum filtering; profound photophobia\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Lens material master table: Material n Abbe (ν) SG Impact resistance Key advantage Key limitation Crown glass (ophthalmic) 1.523 58.9 2.54 Lowest Lowest CA Heaviest; shatters CR-39 (Columbia Resin) 1.498 58 1.32 Fair Low CA; easy to tint Scratches easily; thicker Trivex (Phoenix) 1.532 43–45 1.11 High Lightest; rigid (drill-mount) Scratches easily Polycarbonate 1.586 30 1.20 HIGHEST Best impact; UV blocks to 385nm High CA; hard to tint PMMA 1.49 — — Fair CL rigid material Poor gas permeability High-index glass 1.600+ 36 1.45 Low Thinnest Fragile; high CA; expensive High-index plastic 1.597 37 1.34 Low Thin High CA; fragile; expensive Polycarbonate inherently blocks UV < 385nm without added treatment — unique among lens materials. Lens forms and aberrations: LENS FORMS (from most to least aberration): Biconvex > Plano-convex > Meniscus (best for reducing marginal aberrations) Mass-produced lenses use meniscus form (corrected curve) PERISCOPIC LENS : Plus lenses: back surface = −1.25 D Minus lenses: front surface = +1.25 D BASE CURVES (toric transposition): Rx −2.25 to −4.00 D → BC 4.00 D Rx +2.00 to −2.00 D → BC 6.00 D Rx +2.25 to +4.50 D → BC 8.00 D Bifocal and multifocal designs: FUSED BIFOCAL (Kryptok, FT-28 , FT-35 ) — Segment of higher-index glass (flint) fused into major lens (crown) — Advantages: smooth upper edge, cosmetically invisible, durable — Disadvantages: image jump, limited styles ONE-PIECE BIFOCAL (Executive/Franklin, Ultex) — Entire lens ground from one piece of glass/plastic — Executive: full-width segment divides lens horizontally — Advantage: wide near segment; no prismatic jump at segment top — Disadvantage: heavy, thick PROGRESSIVE ADDITION LENS ( PAL /No-line) — Distance zone (top) → intermediate corridor → near zone (bottom) — No visible line; intermediate vision capability — Disadvantage: peripheral distortion; adaptation period required — Advantage: cosmetically superior; full range of vision BLENDED BIFOCAL — Segment line ground away; intermediate zone blurred — Less cosmetically appealing than PAL ; no intermediate zone Slab-off (bicentric grinding) for anisometropia: PURPOSE : Correct differential vertical prismatic effect when prescriptions differ significantly between eyes INDICATION : Anisometropia with significant difference in sphere (typically >1.50-2.00 D vertical prism differential) METHOD : Front slab-off = removes minus from upper portion of weaker lens Back slab-off = removes plus from upper portion of stronger lens Conventional: slab-off on MORE MINUS lens (or LESS PLUS ) Prism in lenses — Prentice's rule application: P = d × F (d in cm, F in diopters) Plus lens: base faces optical center (prism apex in periphery) → Object displaced TOWARD apex (away from OC) Minus lens: apex faces optical center (prism base in periphery) → Object displaced toward APEX (toward OC) Direction of image displacement: ALWAYS toward prism APEX Direction of prism displacement: image moves TOWARD apex; eye position moves TOWARD base Clinical indications for absorptive lenses by diagnosis: Condition Problem Recommended filter Albinism Foveal hypoplasia + reduced pigment → photophobia Dark tint + UV 400 + side shields Aniridia No iris = no pupillary light control Dark absorptive + side/superior/inferior shields + CPF 511+ Achromatopsia No cone function = extreme daytime photophobia Dark red (CPF 550 or Wratten #25/#29) Retinitis Pigmentosa Rod degeneration + photophobia Yellow/amber (CPF 511 or 527) ARMD Central field loss + glare Yellow/amber absorptive lens Cataract Light scatter through cloudy lens AR coating; post-op UV 400\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-toric-transposition-lens-manufacturing\",\"heading\":\"Toric Transposition — Lens Manufacturing\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Toric transposition describes how a prescription is ground onto a lens surface when a cylinder is involved. Instead of writing out the full Rx as one number, the lens lab breaks it into two surface powers (front and back) using a fixed reference curve called the base curve (BC) . The BC anchors all the other surface calculations. Core concept: The front and back surface powers must combine to produce the exact Rx at every meridian. Toric transposition is the arithmetic for finding those surface powers given the BC. When to use each type: Type Bifocal style Which surface is toric Which surface is sphere Cylinder form SVTT — Single Vision Toric SV lens (no add) Front (convex) Back (concave) PLUS cyl FBTT — Fused Bifocal Toric Kryptok, FT-28, FT-35 (fused) Back (concave) Front = BC (sphere, segment side) MINUS cyl UBTT — Ultex Bifocal Toric Ultex, Executive (one-piece) Front (convex) Back = BC (concave) PLUS cyl Memory rule: F used → F ront sphere (BC on front), back toric. U ltex → back sphere (BC on back), front toric. SV → same as UBTT layout except BC is on front. Optical cross notation convention (used throughout): \\\"+P × A°\\\" on a surface means that surface contributes power P in the direction perpendicular to A° . Example: +6.00 × 90° contributes +6.00 in the 180° direction (horizontal). Verification: add front + back powers at each direction → must equal the original Rx powers at those same directions. SVTT — Single Vision Toric Transposition Steps: Convert Rx to plus cylinder form if not already Place BC with axis 90° from the plus cyl axis → this is the first front meridian Add BC + cylinder power at the plus cyl axis → this is the second front meridian Back sphere = sphere (plus cyl form) − BC Verify with optical cross Example: +0.75 s = −1.00 c × 90, BC +6.00 Step 1 — plus cyl form: Sph = +0.75 + (−1.00) = −0.25 Cyl = +1.00 Axis = 90 + 90 = 180° → −0.25 +1.00 × 180° Step 2 — BC at axis 90° from cyl axis 180° = at axis 90°: Front: +6.00 × 90° Step 3 — BC + cyl at cyl axis 180°: Front: +6.00 + 1.00 = +7.00 × 180° Step 4 — back sphere: Back = −0.25 − (+6.00) = −6.25 sph Result: Front toric: +6.00 × 90° / +7.00 × 180° Back sphere: −6.25 sph Verification (optical cross): +6.00 × 90° → contributes +6.00 in the 180° direction +7.00 × 180° → contributes +7.00 in the 90° direction Back: −6.25 in both Net @ 90° direction: +7.00 − 6.25 = +0.75 ✓ (Rx @ 90°: sphere = +0.75) Net @ 180° direction: +6.00 − 6.25 = −0.25 ✓ (Rx @ 180°: +0.75 − 1.00 = −0.25) SVTT Practice Problems (solved): P1: +4.50 s = −2.25 c × 90, BC 8.00 Plus cyl: +2.25 +2.25 × 180° Front: +8.00 × 90° / +10.25 × 180° (8.00 + 2.25) Back: +2.25 − 8.00 = −5.75 sph P2: −2.50 s = −2.75 c × 45, BC 4.00 Plus cyl: −5.25 +2.75 × 135° Front: +4.00 × 45° / +6.75 × 135° (4.00 + 2.75; axis 90° from 135° = 45°) Back: −5.25 − 4.00 = −9.25 sph P3: +2.50 s = −1.00 c × 90, BC 6.00 Plus cyl: +1.50 +1.00 × 180° Front: +6.00 × 90° / +7.00 × 180° Back: +1.50 − 6.00 = −4.50 sph FBTT — Fused Bifocal Toric Transposition Steps: Convert Rx to minus cylinder form Front = BC (spherical — it is on the segment side and must be a sphere) Back at axis 90° away from minus cyl axis : power = sphere (minus cyl form) − BC Back at minus cyl axis : Step 3 result + minus cyl power Verify with optical cross Example: +1.00 s = +0.25 c × 90, add 2.50 KK, BC 6.00 Step 1 — minus cyl form: Sph = +1.00 + 0.25 = +1.25 Cyl = −0.25 Axis = 90 + 90 = 180° → +1.25 −0.25 × 180° Step 2 — Front = +6.00 sph (BC, spherical, segment side) Step 3 — Back at axis 90° away from minus cyl axis 180° = at axis 90°: Back = sphere − BC = +1.25 − 6.00 = −4.75 × 90° Step 4 — Back at minus cyl axis 180°: Back = −4.75 + (−0.25) = −5.00 × 180° Result: Front sphere: +6.00 sph (BC) Back toric: −4.75 × 90° / −5.00 × 180° Verification: Front +6.00 sph → contributes +6.00 in both directions Back −4.75 × 90° → contributes −4.75 in 180° direction Back −5.00 × 180° → contributes −5.00 in 90° direction Net @ 90° direction: +6.00 + (−5.00) = +1.00 ✓ (Rx @ 90°: +1.00 in original) Net @ 180° direction: +6.00 + (−4.75) = +1.25 ✓ (Rx @ 180°: +1.25 in original) FBTT Seatwork Problems (solved): SW1: +1.00 sph = −2.75 c × 90, add 2.00 FT, BC 6.00 Minus cyl: +1.00 −2.75 × 90° ✓ Front: +6.00 sph Back at axis 90° from cyl axis 90° = at axis 180°: +1.00 − 6.00 = −5.00 × 180° Back at cyl axis 90°: −5.00 + (−2.75) = −7.75 × 90° → Front: +6.00 sph | Back: −5.00 × 180° / −7.75 × 90° SW6: +6.50 s = −1.25 c × 70, add 2.00 KK, BC plano Minus cyl: +6.50 −1.25 × 70° ✓ Front: 0 sph (plano BC) Back at axis 90° from 70° = at axis 160°: +6.50 − 0 = +6.50 × 160° Back at cyl axis 70°: +6.50 + (−1.25) = +5.25 × 70° → Front: plano sph | Back: +6.50 × 160° / +5.25 × 70° UBTT — Ultex Bifocal Toric Transposition Steps: Convert Rx to plus cylinder form BC is the back surface sphere (written as negative/concave in the result) Front at axis 90° away from plus cyl axis : = sphere (plus cyl form) + BC Front at plus cyl axis : Step 3 result + plus cyl power Verify with optical cross Example: +2.00 s = +1.00 c × 60, add 2.50 Ultex, BC 4.00 Step 1 — plus cyl: +2.00 +1.00 × 60° ✓ (already in plus cyl) Step 2 — Back = −4.00 sph (BC, concave) Step 3 — Front at axis 90° from plus cyl axis 60° = at axis 150°: Front = sphere + BC = +2.00 + 4.00 = +6.00 × 150° Step 4 — Front at plus cyl axis 60°: Front = +6.00 + 1.00 = +7.00 × 60° Result: Front toric: +6.00 × 150° / +7.00 × 60° Back sphere: −4.00 sph (BC) Verification: +6.00 × 150° → contributes +6.00 in the 60° direction +7.00 × 60° → contributes +7.00 in the 150° direction Back: −4.00 in both Net @ 60° direction: +6.00 + (−4.00) = +2.00 ✓ Net @ 150° direction: +7.00 + (−4.00) = +3.00 ✓ (Rx @ 150°: +2.00 + 1.00 = +3.00) UBTT Try Problem (solved): +2.50 s = −1.50 c × 10, add 2.00 Ultex, BC 6.00 Plus cyl: Sph = 2.50 − 1.50 = +1.00; Cyl = +1.50; Axis = 10 + 90 = 100° → +1.00 +1.50 × 100° Front at axis 90° from 100° = at axis 10°: +1.00 + 6.00 = +7.00 × 10° Front at cyl axis 100°: +7.00 + 1.50 = +8.50 × 100° Back: −6.00 sph Result: Front +7.00 × 10° / +8.50 × 100° | Back −6.00 sph UBTT Seatwork Problems (solved): SW2: +2.50 sph = −3.75 c × 180, add 2.25 Ultex, BC 6.00 Plus cyl: Sph = 2.50 − 3.75 = −1.25; Cyl = +3.75; Axis = 180 + 90 = 90° → −1.25 +3.75 × 90° Front at axis 180° (90° from 90°): −1.25 + 6.00 = +4.75 × 180° Front at axis 90°: +4.75 + 3.75 = +8.50 × 90° Back: −6.00 sph → Front: +4.75 × 180° / +8.50 × 90° | Back: −6.00 sph SW4: +5.75 s = +2.50 c × 40, add 2.00 Ultex, BC 4.00 Plus cyl: +5.75 +2.50 × 40° ✓ (already plus cyl) Front at axis 130° (90° from 40°): +5.75 + 4.00 = +9.75 × 130° Front at axis 40°: +9.75 + 2.50 = +12.25 × 40° Back: −4.00 sph → Front: +9.75 × 130° / +12.25 × 40° | Back: −4.00 sph *SW3: +2.25 s = −1.25 c × 100, BC 6.00 (SV → SVTT)* Plus cyl: Sph = 2.25 − 1.25 = +1.00; Cyl = +1.25; Axis = 100 + 90 = 190° = 10° → +1.00 +1.25 × 10° Front: +6.00 × 100° (BC at axis 90° from 10° = 100°) / +7.25 × 10° Back: +1.00 − 6.00 = −5.00 sph *SW5: +4.75 s = −2.00 c × 150, BC 1.25 (SV → SVTT)* Plus cyl: Sph = 4.75 − 2.00 = +2.75; Cyl = +2.00; Axis = 150 + 90 = 240° = 60° → +2.75 +2.00 × 60° Front: +1.25 × 150° / +3.25 × 60° Back: +2.75 − 1.25 = +1.50 sph SW7: +0.50 s = −0.25 c × 90, add 1.25 Executive, BC 6.00 Executive = one-piece → UBTT Plus cyl: Sph = 0.50 − 0.25 = +0.25; Cyl = +0.25; Axis = 90 + 90 = 180° → +0.25 +0.25 × 180° Front at axis 90° (90° from 180°): +0.25 + 6.00 = +6.25 × 90° Front at axis 180°: +6.25 + 0.25 = +6.50 × 180° Back: −6.00 sph → Front: +6.25 × 90° / +6.50 × 180° | Back: −6.00 sph Quick Reference — Toric Transposition Formula Sheet SVTT : Form: plus cyl Front (toric): BC × (90° from cyl axis) / (BC + cyl) × cyl axis Back (sphere): sphere(+cyl) − BC FBTT : Form: minus cyl Front (sphere): BC Back (toric): [sphere − BC] × (90° from cyl axis) / [sphere − BC + cyl] × cyl axis UBTT : Form: plus cyl Front (toric): (sphere + BC) × (90° from cyl axis) / (sphere + BC + cyl) × cyl axis Back (sphere): −BC\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"CR-39 vs Polycarbonate — the everyday clinical choice: Feature CR-39 Polycarbonate Index 1.498 1.586 Abbe value 58 (LOW CA) 30 (HIGH CA) Impact resistance Fair BEST (must for children, sports) Weight Moderate Light (SG 1.20) UV protection Needs coating Inherent (< 385nm) Tintability Excellent Difficult Best for Office/computer wearers; color-sensitive Children; safety eyewear; sports Board clue \\\"Clear optics, needs UV coat\\\" \\\"Impact king, color compromise\\\" CPF vs Wratten filters: Feature CPF filter Wratten filter Purpose Prescribed absorptive lens for daily wear Trial filter used during LV assessment Form Spectacle lens (permanent) Gelatin/glass filter (trial) Use Final prescription Diagnostic — \\\"try before you buy\\\" Board clue CPF is the final product; Wratten is the test\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Crown glass n 1.523 Reference standard for ophthalmic glass CR-39 n 1.498 Standard plastic; good CA control Polycarbonate n 1.586 Most impact resistant Polycarbonate SG 1.20 Lightest manufactured lens Trivex n 1.532 Best for drill-mount (rigid) Trivex Abbe 43–45 Better than polycarbonate Crown glass Abbe 58.9 Best CA control in glass CR-39 Abbe 58 Best CA control in plastic Impact test 5/8-inch steel ball from 50 inches FDA standard for ophthalmic lenses CPF 450 cutoff < 450 nm Lightest CPF; early changes CPF 550 cutoff < 550 nm Darkest CPF; achromatopsia UV 400 Blocks all UV < 400 nm Current gold standard for UV protection Photochromic clearing 2–5 minutes Longer in cold, faster in warm Photochromic darkening 30–60 seconds Rapid darkening in UV\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Lens material properties — n and Abbe are INVERSE High n → Low Abbe → More CA → More color fringing Impact resistance order — \\\"Polycarb Hits Hardest; Glass Shatters:\\\" Polycarbonate > High-index plastic > CR-39 > Crown glass CPF numbers — \\\"Higher number = darker filter\\\" CPF 450 (lightest) → CPF 550 (darkest); number = cutoff wavelength Photochromic car rule — \\\"Windshield blocks UV → no activation in car\\\" Prentice's rule direction Plus lens: object moves away from OC (toward apex) Minus lens: object moves toward OC (toward apex) Always: image moves TOWARD the APEX of the prism Slab-off indication — \\\"Anisometropia with reading — slab on the MORE MINUS side\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"LENS MATERIAL SPECTRUM (n vs Abbe) ──────────────────────────────────────── HIGH ABBE ( LOW CA ) LOW ABBE ( HIGH CA ) Crown glass (Abbe 58.9) ← ────────────── → Polycarbonate (Abbe 30) CR-39 (Abbe 58) Trivex (Abbe 43-45) is in between n=1.49 ← ────── → n=1.586+ CPF FILTER SERIES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── WAVELENGTH (nm) UV 400 450 500 550 600 700 (visible) |----|----|----|----|----|----| CPF450 : cuts here CPF511 : cuts here CPF527 : cuts here CPF550 : cuts here Higher cutoff = more filtered = darker = for more severe photophobia BIFOCAL DESIGNS ─────────────── FUSED : [ DISTANCE ] ← segment fused into carrier [______NEAR______] ONE-PIECE : [ DISTANCE ] ← one piece; Executive = full-width [ NEAR ] PROGRESSIVE : [ DISTANCE ] [ corridor ] [ NEAR ]\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Polycarbonate has the highest Abbe value Polycarbonate has Abbe = 30 (LOWEST among common lens materials). Crown glass has the highest (58.9). Polycarbonate requires UV coating to protect against UV Polycarbonate inherently blocks UV below 385nm without additional coating. Photochromic lenses are ideal for driving They do NOT activate inside cars because windshields block the UV needed to trigger the silver halide reaction. CPF 527 is lighter than CPF 450 Higher CPF number = more filtered = DARKER appearance. CPF 450 is the lightest; CPF 550 is the darkest. Slab-off is applied to the more plus lens in anisometropia Conventional slab-off is applied to the MORE MINUS (or LESS PLUS) lens. CR-39 has lower Abbe value than polycarbonate CR-39 Abbe = 58; polycarbonate Abbe = 30. CR-39 has HIGHER Abbe (less CA). SVTT and FBTT both use plus cylinder form FBTT uses MINUS cylinder form because the cylinder is on the back surface (opposite the segment). SVTT and UBTT use plus cyl. In UBTT, the back surface is derived from calculation In UBTT, the BC IS the back surface (−BC). The front is derived. In SVTT, the BC is the front surface and the back is derived. For FBTT, the BC goes on the back surface In FBTT, the BC is on the FRONT (segment side) and must be spherical. The back is toric (concave). The optical cross axis notation means power in the direction of that axis \\\"+6.00 × 90°\\\" means the surface contributes +6.00 in the PERPENDICULAR direction (180°), exactly like cylinder notation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Polycarbonate Abbe value 30 (lowest = most CA) Crown glass Abbe value 58.9 (highest = least CA) CR-39 Abbe value 58 Trivex Abbe value 43–45 Most impact resistant lens Polycarbonate Lightest lens (SG) Trivex (1.11); polycarbonate (1.20) Polycarbonate inherent UV Blocks < 385 nm without coating Photochromic mechanism Silver halide crystals; UV triggers darkening Photochromic car limitation No activation (windshield blocks UV) Achromatopsia filter CPF 550 or Wratten #25/#29 (dark red) RP filter Yellow/amber (CPF 511 or 527) Aniridia filter Dark absorptive + side shields + CPF 511+ Wratten filters Trial filters for LV assessment UV 400 Blocks all UV < 400 nm (gold standard) Slab-off indication Anisometropia vertical prism correction SVTT cylinder form Plus cyl; BC on front; back = sph(+cyl) − BC FBTT cylinder form MINUS cyl; BC on front (sphere); back toric UBTT cylinder form Plus cyl; BC on back (−BC); front = sph + BC (one meridian) Bifocal → FBTT Fused: Kryptok, FT-28, FT-35 Bifocal → UBTT One-piece: Ultex, Executive\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"1. A 35-year-old graphic designer spends 10 hours daily reading fine print on a computer. He is myopic (−2.50 D OU) and wants thin lenses. Which lens material would you prioritize? A. Polycarbonate (n=1.586, Abbe=30) B. CR-39 (n=1.498, Abbe=58) C. High-index glass (n=1.600, Abbe=36) D. Trivex (n=1.532, Abbe=43) Answer B. CR-39 (n=1.498, Abbe=58). For a sedentary professional spending hours reading through lenses — especially at a monitor where off-axis gaze is constant — optical quality (Abbe value) is the priority. CR-39 has Abbe=58, producing minimal color fringing even in peripheral gaze. While polycarbonate (A) would be thinner, its Abbe=30 produces significant color aberration during sustained near work, causing visual fatigue. High-index glass is thinner but has lower Abbe (36) and is heavier. Trivex (Abbe 43-45) is a reasonable compromise but costs more without significant advantage here. For −2.50 D, the lens is already relatively thin in CR-39. Safety is not a primary concern for this patient in a seated work environment. 2. A patient with anisometropia (OD +1.00D, OS +4.50D) looks down 8mm below the optical centers while reading. What is the vertical prism differential at the reading level, and which method should be used to correct it? A. 2.8Δ differential; drop the distance OC B. 2.8Δ differential; slab-off on OS (most plus lens) C. 3.6Δ differential; slab-off on OD (most minus) D. 0.8Δ differential; dissimilar segments Answer B. 2.8Δ differential; slab-off on OS (most plus lens). Using Prentice's rule for each eye at 8mm (0.8cm) below OC: OD prism = 0.8 × 1.00 = 0.8Δ BU; OS prism = 0.8 × 4.50 = 3.6Δ BU. Differential = 3.6 − 0.8 = 2.8Δ. Since 2.8Δ > 1.5Δ, slab-off is indicated. For two plus lenses, slab-off is ground on the MOST PLUS lens (OS = +4.50). Slab-off creates base-up prism in the reading zone to neutralize the differential. Option C is wrong — slab-off on OD would be the most minus rule, which applies to two minus lenses, not two plus lenses. Option A (drop OC) is only used for differentials ≤ 1.5Δ. 3. A spectacle lens (CR-39, n = 1.498) is uncoated. What percentage of light is lost to reflection from both surfaces? A. 3.87% B. 7.75% C. 4.45% D. 0.58% Answer B. 7.75%. Using the reflectance formula: [(n' − n)/(n' + n)]² × 100 = [(1.498 − 1)/(1.498 + 1)]² × 100 = (0.498/2.498)² × 100 ≈ 3.87% per surface. For an uncoated lens, both the front and back surfaces reflect equally: 3.87% × 2 = 7.75% total light lost. This leaves ~92.25% transmitted. Option A (3.87%) is per-surface only. Option C (4.45%) is the loss with single-coat AR (front uncoated + back 85% reduced). Option D (0.58%) is the back surface reflection with a single coat (15% of 3.87%).\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"OPHTHALMIC LENSES AND DISPENSING.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: 4 lens materials with n and Abbe, impact resistance order, CPF series (4 filters + cutoffs + conditions), photochromic mechanism, Prentice's rule. Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the CPF filter spectrum. Mark the 4 CPF numbers and their cutoff wavelengths on the visible spectrum. For each, write the primary clinical indication. Drill 3 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Polycarbonate n, Abbe, SG? 1.586, 30, 1.20 CR-39 n, Abbe, SG? 1.498, 58, 1.32 Crown glass n, Abbe, SG? 1.523, 58.9, 2.54 Most impact resistant? Polycarbonate Photochromic: why no darkening in car? Windshield blocks UV CPF 550 for? Achromatopsia/severe photophobia CPF 527 for? RP, glaucoma, ARMD Wratten filters purpose? Trial filters for LV assessment Slab-off for? Anisometropia vertical prism Sagitta formula (simplified)? s ≈ y²/2r Plus lens: sag = ? CT − ET Lens moved away + plus power? Effective power increases Executive bifocal image jump? Zero (OC at segment line) Image jump formula? I = h × D_add (h = OC-to-top, cm) Vertical imbalance > 1.5Δ → correct with? Slab-off or prism in segments Slab-off ground on which lens? Most minus (or least plus) lens AR coating physics? λ/4 thin film — destructive interference cancels reflection Uncoated CR-39 light transmission? ~92% (loses ~7.75% to reflection) Benchwork stage 1? Centering (mark OC, cylinder axis, prism base-apex) Drill 4 — Toric Transposition Set (no notes) Work each problem from scratch. Label front and back surfaces, show all steps, verify with optical cross. SVTT: +3.00 s = −1.50 c × 90 BC 6.00 FBTT: +2.00 s = −0.75 c × 90 add 2.00 KK BC 6.00 UBTT: +1.50 s = +1.00 c × 45 add 2.00 Ultex BC 4.00 Decide the type first (SV → SVTT; Kryptok/FT → FBTT; Ultex/Executive → UBTT). Then apply the correct cylinder form. Draw the optical cross at the end and confirm the net powers match the original Rx at both meridians. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow CPF spectrum diagram + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Lens material table from memory Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-sagittae-formula\",\"heading\":\"Sagittae Formula\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: A lens curve is a piece of a sphere. If you want to know how deep the bowl of that curve is over a given lens size, that depth is the sag. The sag tells you how much thicker the center is versus the edge (for plus) or the edge versus the center (for minus). Opticians use it to calculate the lens thickness with a caliper or lens clock. Clinical term: Sagitta (sag) — the perpendicular depth of a lens curve from a chord across the surface. EXACT FORMULA : s = r − √(r² − y²) Where: s = sag (depth of curve, in mm) r = radius of curvature (mm) y = semi-diameter of lens (half the lens size, in mm) SIMPLIFIED (for small y compared to r): s ≈ y² / (2r) CALIPER METHOD to find lens power: D = 1000 × s × 2(n − 1) / A² Where: D = surface power (diopters) s = sag in mm (s = CT − ET for plus lens; s = ET − CT for minus lens) n = index of refraction A = semi-diameter in mm Plus lens: Center thicker than edge → sag = CT − ET (CT = center thickness, ET = edge thickness) Minus lens: Edge thicker than center → sag = ET − CT Clinical use: Lens clock (Geneva lens measure) reads sag to calculate surface power. Calibrated for crown glass (n = 1.530). For different index, use: T_true = D_marked × (n − 1)/0.530.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-effective-power-and-vertex-distance\",\"heading\":\"Effective Power and Vertex Distance\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: The same spectacle lens gives a different effective correction depending on how far it sits from your eye. Move the lens closer → the light has less distance to converge → effectively less plus (or less minus). Move it away → more distance for convergence → more plus (or more minus). When you refit someone from one vertex distance to another, you have to recalculate the power to keep the same effect on the eye. Clinical term: Effective power (positional power) — the power of a lens at a specific vertex distance, calculated to produce the same correction as the original lens at its original distance. TWO SCENARIOS : 1. LENS MOVED AWAY from the eye (farther from cornea): D_far = Dv / (1 − d × Dv) 2. LENS MOVED TOWARD the eye (closer to cornea): D_near = Dv / (1 + d × Dv) Where: Dv = original lens power (diopters) d = change in vertex distance ( METERS ) DIRECTION RULES : Lens direction | Plus lens effect | Minus lens effect ─────────────────|──────────────────|─────────────────── Away from eye | Increases power | Decreases power Toward eye | Decreases power | Increases power Note: When the LENS moves away, EFFECTIVE power (same lens, new position) follows OPPOSITE formula: Same lens moved far: D_eff = Dv / (1 − d × Dv) Same lens moved near: D_eff = Dv / (1 + d × Dv) Sample: Patient has −8.00D worn at 12 mm. Repositioned to 16 mm (d = 0.004 m away): D_far = −8.00 / (1 − 0.004 × (−8.00)) = −8.00 / (1 + 0.032) = −8.00 / 1.032 D_far = −7.75 D For astigmatic lenses: Apply vertex distance separately to each principal meridian, then draw a new optical cross and transpose. Spectacle-to-CL conversion: Same formula where d = vertex distance (typically 12–14 mm = 0.012–0.014 m) and the target is the corneal plane. D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − d × D_Spec)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-obliquely-crossed-cylinders\",\"heading\":\"Obliquely Crossed Cylinders\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: If you have two cylindrical lenses whose axes are NOT 90° apart (not at right angles), you cannot simply add their powers — they cancel and combine in complicated ways. To find the result, you can use a graphical method on an optical cross or an algebraic formula. The resulting prescription will be a spherocylindrical lens at some new axis. Clinical term: Obliquely crossed cylinders — two cylinder lenses with axes that differ by an angle other than 90°. RESULTANT POWER FORMULA : Combined power at any meridian = D₁sin²(θ₁) + D₂sin²(θ₂) For two cylinders at axes α and β, the resultant cylinder C at axis γ satisfies: C = √[(D₁cos2α − D₂cos2β)² + (D₁sin2α − D₂sin2β)²] AXIS OF RESULTANT : tan(2γ) = (D₁sin2α − D₂sin2β) / (D₁cos2α − D₂cos2β) RESULTANT SPHERE : S_result = (D₁ + D₂ − C) / 2 Board-level approach (practical): When two plus cylinders are obliquely crossed, the result is a spherocylindrical lens whose power is between the two cylinders and whose axis bisects the two original axes (modified by relative powers). Key rule: If both cylinders are equal in power, the resultant axis is exactly between the two original axes.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-power-in-an-oblique-meridian-resultant-prism-and-base-direction\",\"heading\":\"Power in an Oblique Meridian, Resultant Prism, and Base Direction\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Three formulas the board chains together in one item: find the power in a meridian, turn it into prism with Prentice, then combine the horizontal and vertical prisms into one resultant. 1. Power in an oblique meridian D(θ) = Sph + Cyl · sin²α Plain version: a cylinder has NO power along its own axis and FULL power 90° away. At an angle in between it expresses only a fraction of its power, and that fraction is sin²α. Add the sphere (equal in every meridian) for the total. Each part: Sph = spherical power; Cyl = cylinder power; α = angle FROM THE CYLINDER AXIS to the meridian you want; sin²α = the fraction of cyl power expressed there. Where it comes from: the curvature of a cylindrical surface varies as sin² between its two principal meridians (a projection / Euler-type relationship). Power follows curvature. Why sin² (not sin or cos): measured from the axis, power must be 0 at α = 0° and maximal at α = 90°; sin²α is exactly the curve that does that. (Measured from the power meridian instead, the same idea reads as cos²α.) Endpoint check (always do this): α = 0° (along axis) → sin²0 = 0 → D = Sph. α = 90° (power meridian) → sin²90 = 1 → D = Sph + Cyl. Both correct. Cross-subject: corneal power in oblique meridians (keratometry/astigmatism), oblique-axis retinoscopy, and it is the single term the obliquely-crossed-cylinder formula above sums twice. 2. Resultant (oblique) prism — combine a vertical and a horizontal prism r = √(v² + h²) magnitude tan α = v / h base direction (α from horizontal) v = r·sinα, h = r·cosα (splitting one oblique prism back into components) Plain version: if a lens gives some sideways prism (h) and some up/down prism (v), the eye feels ONE prism pointing diagonally. Because v and h are at right angles, they are the legs of a right triangle and the resultant is the hypotenuse. Each part: v = vertical prism (BU/BD); h = horizontal prism (BI/BO); r = single resultant prism; α = its base angle measured up from horizontal. Where it comes from: prism is a vector (magnitude + base direction). Perpendicular components combine by Pythagoras, with no cross term because v ⊥ h. (Non-perpendicular prisms would need the law of cosines.) Cross-subject: Prentice's rule gives the v and h components from decentration in each meridian; this fuses them. It is also the reverse of splitting a prescribed oblique prism into BI/BO + BU/BD for grinding. 3. Base direction — the recurring trap (magnitude is the easy part) A question is phrased one of two ways, and the two are MIRROR IMAGES. Match the rule to the wording: Decentration = the lens / optical center is moved (the \\\"laboratory\\\" act): \\\"the lens was decentered 2.5 mm nasal.\\\" Displacement = the eye views a point off the OC: \\\"8 mm temporal to the OC,\\\" or the OC distance differs from the PD. Lens DECENTRATION (OC is moved) DISPLACEMENT (eye views off the OC) Plus base SAME direction as the move base OPPOSITE the viewing point Minus base OPPOSITE the move base SAME as the viewing point They mirror because moving the OC one way equals viewing the opposite way through the lens. So \\\"decentered 2.5 mm nasal\\\" (decentration) = \\\"eye views 2.5 mm temporal\\\" (displacement); both give the same base. When the distance between the OCs is greater than the PD, each eye views nasal to its OC (displacement). Then read the side off as a base label: **temporal → Base OUT, nasal → Base IN, up → Base UP, down → Base DOWN.** Worked example A (power in a meridian → prism): Rx +5.00 −1.50 × 45, point 8 mm temporal, both eyes. Horizontal (180°) meridian: α = |180 − 45| = 135°, sin²135° = 0.5 D₁₈₀ = +5.00 + (−1.50)(0.5) = +4.25 D Prentice: P = d·F = 0.8 cm × 4.25 D = 3.4Δ Base: +4.25 PLUS , point 8 mm TEMPORAL (displacement) → plus → OPPOSITE → nasal → Base In Answer = 3.4Δ BI (a keyed \\\"3.4Δ BO\\\" is the base-direction trap) Worked example B (resolve into v/h, then recombine): Rx +4.00 −3.00 × 45, decentered 6 mm out + 4 mm down. Horizontal (180°): α = 135°, sin² = 0.5 → +4.00 + (−3.00)(0.5) = +2.5 D H = 0.6 cm × 2.5 = 1.5Δ; decentered out (decentration) → plus → SAME → Base OUT Vertical (90°): α = |90 − 45| = 45°, sin² = 0.5 → +2.5 D V = 0.4 cm × 2.5 = 1.0Δ; decentered down (decentration) → plus → SAME → Base DOWN Resultant: r = √(1.0² + 1.5²) = √3.25 = 1.8Δ tan α = v/h = 1.0/1.5 → α = 33.7° (base out-and-down quadrant) 4. The 360° scale: naming the resultant, and the OD/OS flip Parts 2 and 3 stop one step short. tan α = v/h gives you an angle measured off the horizontal, but the board asks for a number on the 360° scale, and the same two prisms give a DIFFERENT number in each eye. This is where the keyed answer is usually won or lost. Reference angle: α = arctan(v/h) (always 0-90°, off the horizontal) Then place it: 0-90 / 90-180 / 180-270 / 270-360 by the two base directions Plain version: picture one protractor taped to the patient's face, drawn the way YOU see it across the chair. 0° sits on your right, and the numbers run counterclockwise. That protractor does not move when you switch eyes, but the patient's nose does: it is on your right for the right eye and on your left for the left eye. So \\\"toward the nose\\\" is 0° in one eye and 180° in the other. Each part: α = the tilt off horizontal, from the triangle; the quadrant = which way each base actually points in space; the final angle = the two combined. The dial, by eye Angle OD (right eye) OS (left eye) 0° Base IN (nasal) Base OUT (temporal) 90° Base UP Base UP 180° Base OUT (temporal) Base IN (nasal) 270° Base DOWN Base DOWN Vertical never flips. Only the horizontal does. That single row is the whole trap. Converting, once you have α Base directions OD OS up + in α 180 − α up + out 180 − α α down + out 180 + α 360 − α down + in 360 − α 180 + α Where it comes from: the convention is a standard polar plot (counterclockwise from the positive x-axis) drawn in the examiner's frame of reference, which is also why the cylinder-axis scale runs the same way. Nothing about the eye changes the math; only the labelling of the nasal side changes. Why counterclockwise and not clockwise: it matches the axis notation you already use, so one mental picture serves both. An Rx axis of 45 and a prism base at 45 point the same way on the page. Endpoint check (always do this): set h = 0. Then α = 90°, and a pure base-down answer must come out 270° in BOTH eyes. If your rule gives anything else, the quadrant logic is backwards. Set v = 0 and a pure base-out must give 180° OD and 0° OS. Cross-subject: same scale as cylinder axis notation (Subject D transposition) and the same examiner's-view convention behind the OD/OS mirror in cover-test and Maddox-rod direction calls (Subject B). It is also how an oblique prism is written on a lab order for grinding. The four-option pattern (recognise it and you have already narrowed to 4) An item that gives one vertical and one horizontal prism will offer α, 180 − α, 180 + α, 360 − α, all with the SAME magnitude. The magnitude is never the question. Compute α once, then spend your time on the eye and the quadrant. Worked example C (the exact board phrasing): find the single prism equivalent to 6.5Δ BD combined with 4Δ BO in front of OD. Magnitude: r = √(6.5² + 4²) = √58.25 = 7.63Δ Reference: α = arctan(6.5/4) = 58.4° Quadrant: OD, base down and base out → down/out → third quadrant (180-270°) Place it: 180 + 58.4 = 238° Answer = 7.63Δ @ 238° Traps: 58° (up/in) 122° (up/out) 302° (down/IN for OD, and the correct answer for the same prisms in front of OS) Note the 302° trap specifically. It is the right answer to the same question asked about the other eye, which is why it reads as plausible. Pen and paper drill: draw the circle, mark 0/90/180/270, and label it twice, once for OD and once for OS, from memory. Then place these without a calculator, quadrant first: (a) 3Δ BU + 4Δ BI, OS; (b) 5Δ BD + 12Δ BO, OS; (c) 8Δ BU + 6Δ BO, OD. Answers: 5Δ @ 143°, 13Δ @ 337°, 10Δ @ 127°. Redo the blank circle tomorrow and again in 4 days. Interactive version: the Prism 360 Dial chip in the layers bar at the top of this reviewer ( D-Prism-360-Visualizer.html ).\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-fast-picks-to-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — TO Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill the wrong numbers, then settle the flip. Each rule is `cue → rule → trap`. Power in an oblique meridian — cue: a sphero-cyl Rx plus a named meridian. Meridian = the cyl axis → answer is the sphere alone (sin²0 = 0). Meridian ⟂ to axis → sphere + cyl . Trap: any option that applies the full cylinder to an in-between meridian. Resultant prism — cue: both a vertical and a horizontal prism are given. r is the hypotenuse: always bigger than either component, smaller than their sum (v + h). A 45° split gives r ≈ 1.41× a component. Trap: the option equal to v + h (added instead of √), and anything smaller than the larger component. If all four options share ONE magnitude, the item is a direction question. Get α = arctan(v/h), then place it: OD 0° = nasal, OS 0° = temporal; up/in α, up/out 180 − α, down/out 180 + α, down/in 360 − α (OD; mirror the horizontal for OS). Trap: the twin option in the mirror quadrant, which is the correct answer for the OTHER eye. Check OD vs OS before you commit. Base direction — cue: lens sign + the wording. \\\"Decentered\\\" → + same, − opposite . \\\"From the OC\\\" or OC ≠ PD → + opposite, − same . Trap: the twin option with your magnitude but flipped BI/BO — that is the keyed bait. Prentice's rule — cue: a decentration (mm) and a lens power. P = (mm × D) ÷ 10. Only one option's number matches; pick the base with the sign rule above. Trap: the option that forgot to ÷10 (used mm as cm), off by 10×. Transposition — cue: \\\"express in plus/minus cyl,\\\" or options with a flipped axis. New sphere = sph + cyl; flip the cyl sign; axis ± 90 (keep it 0–180). Trap: an option whose sphere ≠ (old sph + cyl), or whose axis is not exactly 90° away.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-image-jump-and-vertical-imbalance\",\"heading\":\"Image Jump and Vertical Imbalance\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: When your eye crosses from the distance part of a bifocal into the segment, the segment has its own optical center. As soon as your line of sight hits the top edge of the segment, there is a sudden prismatic jump — the image appears to jump upward. This is image jump. If a patient has different prescriptions in the two eyes and looks down to read, each lens induces different amounts of prism at the reading level. If those prism amounts are not equal, the brain receives two images at different heights — vertical imbalance. Image jump formula: I = h × D_add I = image jump (prism diopters) h = distance from segment top edge to segment optical center (cm) D_add = reading addition power SEGMENT OPTICAL CENTER DISTANCES from top of segment: Round-top (Kryptok) → 11 mm → h = 1.1 cm Flat top ( FT-28 /35) → 7 mm → h = 0.7 cm Executive / Franklin → 0 mm → h = 0 (NO IMAGE JUMP ) Ultex → 20 mm → h = 2.0 cm Rule: Executive bifocal has ZERO image jump (OC at segment line). Image displacement (at reading point): Total prismatic effect at reading level: Image Displacement = DIP + NIP DIP (Distance Induced Prism) = D_distance × h_distance (h = distance from OC to reading point, cm) NIP (Near Induced Prism) = D_add × P_segment (P = distance from segment OC to reading point, cm) Vertical imbalance — when to treat: IF vertical imbalance ≤ 1.5Δ: Correct by: Drop distance OC | Dissimilar segments IF vertical imbalance > 1.5Δ: Correct by: Slab-off | Prism in segments SLAB-OFF INDICATION RULE : Ground on the MOST MINUS (or LEAST PLUS ) lens in the 90° meridian Orientation: Base-UP prism in reading area REVERSE SLAB-OFF : Molded on MOST PLUS (or LEAST MINUS ) lens Orientation: Base- DOWN prism in reading area Used in plastic lenses (cannot grind — molded instead)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-spectacle-magnification\",\"heading\":\"Spectacle Magnification\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: When you put glasses on, the image on your retina is a different size than it was without glasses. Plus lenses make things bigger; minus lenses make things smaller. When two eyes have different spectacle prescriptions (anisometropia), the two retinal images are different sizes — one eye sees a bigger image than the other. If the size difference is large enough, the brain cannot fuse them. This size difference (aniseikonia) is what spectacle magnification quantifies. Clinical term: Spectacle magnification (SM) — ratio of the corrected retinal image size to the uncorrected retinal image size. SPECTACLE MAGNIFICATION (SM): SM = 1 / [(1 − (t/n)D₁) × (1 − dF_v)] Where: t = center thickness (meters) n = index of refraction D₁ = front surface power d = vertex distance (meters) F_v = back vertex power SIMPLIFIED (shape factor × power factor): Shape factor = 1 / (1 − (t/n)D₁) Power factor = 1 / (1 − d × F_v) CL MAGNIFICATION ( CLM ) — comparing CL to spectacle correction: CLM = 1 − d × D_Spec Where d = spectacle vertex distance, D_Spec = spectacle power RELATIVE SPECTACLE MAGNIFICATION ( RSM ): For REFRACTIVE ametropia: RSM = 1 + d × F_Spec (with spectacles) RSM ≈ 1 (with CLs, since d ≈ 0) For AXIAL ametropia: RSM = 1 − g × F_Spec (with spectacles, g ≈ 0) RSM = 1 − (f_eye − 1.55) × F_Spec (with CLs) Clinical rules: Myope: spectacles → smaller image; CL → larger image (closer to emmetropic size) Hyperope: spectacles → larger image; CL → smaller image Aphakia: heavily magnified with spectacles (+12D = ~30% magnification); CL reduces this RSM guides correction choice in anisometropia — if axial ametropia → prefer spectacles; if refractive → prefer CLs\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-anti-reflection-ar-coating\",\"heading\":\"Anti-Reflection (AR) Coating\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: Every uncoated lens surface bounces back some light instead of letting it through. For CR-39 (n = 1.49), about 4% of light is reflected at each surface. With two surfaces, almost 8% of light is lost — plus the patient sees annoying reflections. An AR coating is a super-thin layer (about 1/4 wavelength of light thick) applied to the lens surface. The light reflected off the top of the coating and the light reflected off the bottom cancel each other out through interference — the reflections disappear. Reflectance formula: Reflectance (%) = [(n' − n) / (n' + n)]² × 100 n = index of first medium (air = 1.0) n' = index of lens material Example — CR-39 (n = 1.49): = [(1.49 − 1) / (1.49 + 1)]² × 100 = (0.49 / 2.49)² × 100 = (0.1968)² × 100 = 3.87% per surface Uncoated (two surfaces): 3.87 × 2 = 7.75% lost; transmits ~92% Light transmission by material: Material n Light transmission (uncoated) CR-39 1.49 ~92% Crown glass 1.523 ~91% Polycarbonate 1.586 ~90% High index 1.6 1.60 ~88% High index 1.7 1.70 ~85% Rule: Higher index = more reflection = lower transmission uncoated. AR coating is MORE beneficial on high-index lenses. AR coating types: SINGLE COATING : Back surface only; reduces back reflection by ~85% Back surface reflection: 3.87% × 15% = 0.58% Total loss: 3.87% (front) + 0.58% (back) = 4.45% Transmission: ~95.5% DOUBLE ( MULTICOATING ): Both surfaces coated; back surface reflection → ~0% Total loss: ~3.87% (front only) Transmission: ~96% Clinical indications for AR coating: High-index lenses (> 1.6) — high natural reflectance Polycarbonate lenses — difficult to tint, AR improves aesthetics Night driving — reduces incoming headlight reflection on lens back surface Computer users — reduces screen reflection on back surface Cosmetic: makes lenses appear invisible in photographs\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-benchwork-stages-processing\",\"heading\":\"Benchwork Stages (Processing)\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Plain version: After you write a prescription and the lab selects the lens blank, it goes through a fixed sequence of steps before reaching the patient. Every step is named and each step has a purpose. BENCHWORK SEQUENCE (6 stages): 1. CENTERING — Mark optical center, cylinder axis, prism base-apex line on lens front surface 2. LAYOUT — Mark proper decentration and orientation (set cylinder axis + base-apex to correct position) 3. CUTTING — Trace shape of frame former onto lens; cut excess glass (hand or machine) 4. CHIPPING / CRUMBLING — Remove surplus glass left after cutting (rough removal of irregular edges) 5. EDGING — Smooth and bevel the lens edge to exact shape (flat edging or bevel edging) 6. GLAZING / MOUNTING — Insert finished lens into frame (glazing = into channel/rimmed frame; mounting = into rimless) Decentration (boxing system): Decentration = (Frame PD − Patient PD) / 2 (per eye, in mm) Frame PD ( DBC ) = A + DBL A = horizontal eye size DBL = distance between lenses (bridge size) Patient PD = monocular PDs for each eye Prismatic effect from decentration: P = d × D (Prentice's rule; d in cm, D in diopters) To achieve prescribed prism via decentration: d = P / D (cm) The same boxing-system logic carries over to the near segment. At near the eyes converge, so the near PD is smaller than the distance PD, and the segment (or the near zone of a PAL) has to sit nasal to the distance OC by the amount the eyes turn in. That nasal shift is the inset , the near-vision counterpart of the decentration above, referenced to the same frame center. Segment inset (from the distance OC) = (Distance PD − Near PD) / 2 (per eye, mm) Total inset (from the boxing/geometric center) = (Frame PD − Near PD) / 2 (per eye, mm) Relationship: Total inset = Distance decentration + Segment inset = (Frame PD − Distance PD)/2 + (Distance PD − Near PD)/2 Board trap: \\\"total inset\\\" is measured from the frame's geometric center, so it uses Frame PD and Near PD , not the distance PD. The lens power and the reading add are distractors; they never enter the inset calculation. Worked example (Rx OU −3.00 add +1.00, distance PD 62, near PD 60, eye size 45, DBL 20 ): Frame PD = 45 + 20 = 65 → 32.5 mm from the frame center Near PD = 60 → 30.0 mm from the frame center Total inset = 32.5 − 30.0 = 2.5 mm per eye Check: decentration (65−62)/2 = 1.5 + segment inset (62−60)/2 = 1.0 = 2.5 ✓\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-memory-anchors-extended-topics\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors — Extended Topics\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Sag formula: \\\"SAG = you dig a hole\\\" — s ≈ y²/2r; bigger semi-diameter (y) = deeper hole; flatter curve (bigger r) = shallower hole. Effective power direction — \\\"Plus lens: farther = stronger\\\" Moving a plus lens away from the eye increases its effective power. Moving a minus lens away decreases its effective magnitude. Image jump order (most to least jump): Ultex > Kryptok > FT > Executive Ultex = 20mm OC → most jump; Executive = 0mm OC → zero jump. AR coating rule: High-index = must coat. Higher n = more reflectance = greater benefit from AR coating.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-formulas-dispensing-topics-high-yield-summary-extended-topics\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary — Extended Topics\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Sagittae formula (simplified) s ≈ y²/2r; exact: s = r − √(r²−y²) Plus lens: sag = ? CT − ET (center thicker) Lens moved away + plus power Effective power increases Spectacle to CL power formula D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − d × D_Spec) Image jump formula I = h × D_add (h = OC-to-top distance in cm) Executive bifocal image jump ZERO (OC at segment line) Vertical imbalance > 1.5Δ correction Slab-off or prism in segments Slab-off is ground on Most minus (or least plus) lens Distance decentration (per eye) (Frame PD − Distance PD) / 2 Total inset from frame center (per eye) (Frame PD − Near PD) / 2 = decentration + segment inset Uncoated CR-39 transmission ~92% (7.75% reflected from two surfaces) Higher index lens + AR coating More important — higher native reflectance\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-absorptive-tints-colors-uses-and-the-oxides-that-make-them\",\"heading\":\"Absorptive Tints — Colors, Uses, and the Oxides That Make Them\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Two separate things get tested: which metal oxide produces which glass tint, and what each tint color is clinically used for. Metal oxides used to tint glass lenses: Oxide Tint produced Ferrous oxide Green Manganese oxide Violet Cobalt oxide Blue Cerium oxide Pinkish Nickel oxide Brown Uranium oxide Yellow Gold oxide Red Vanadium oxide Pale green Tint color selection guide (what each color is for): Tint Key property / use Gray Even transmission across the spectrum, so TRUE color perception; general glare, good off water Blue For light-sensitive patients; improves color perception Green Good UV and infrared/heat absorption; true color; general outdoor use Red Sharp contrast; excellent depth perception in low light (skiing, cycling); helps hue discrimination in color deficiency Yellow Absorbs blue/violet/UV; contrast enhancing; clarity in fog and haze (low light) Amber Contrast and depth; night driving (brightens dark, cuts oncoming headlight glare) Brown General purpose; cuts glare, absorbs UV below 400 nm; contrast enhancing Pink Pleasant light attenuation; absorbs in UV and blue region Board trap: gray is the tint that gives true color perception because its transmission is even across the visible spectrum. Green also allows true color but its selling point is UV/IR absorption.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-distortion-pincushion-vs-barrel\",\"heading\":\"Distortion — Pincushion vs Barrel\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Distortion changes image SHAPE and lateral position, not image clarity (unlike the blur aberrations). It appears in high-power lenses because magnification varies with distance from the optical axis. Type Seen in Appearance Pincushion distortion High-power PLUS lenses Sides pulled inward (magnification rises toward periphery) Barrel distortion High-power MINUS lenses Sides bulge outward (magnification falls toward periphery) Orthoscopic (orthoscopy) = free from distortion. Memory anchor: \\\" P lus → P incushion.\\\" Minus gets the leftover, Barrel.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-chromatic-aberration-correction-and-forms\",\"heading\":\"Chromatic Aberration — Correction and Forms\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"CA (chromatism) comes from unequal refraction of wavelengths (violet bends most, red least). Two ways to correct it: Change lens material to one with a higher Abbe value (less dispersion). Use an achromatic doublet — two simple lenses of different materials paired so the CA of one partially cancels the CA of the other. Forms of CA: Longitudinal (axial) — different colors focus at different distances ALONG the optical axis. Lateral (transverse) — colors focus in the same plane but not on the axis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-progressive-lens-design-hard-vs-soft\",\"heading\":\"Progressive Lens Design — Hard vs Soft\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Feature Hard design Soft design Distance and near zones Wide Narrower Intermediate corridor Short and narrow Wider and longer Unwanted (peripheral) astigmatism Rapid increase, more peripheral aberration Gradual increase, reduced peripheral aberration Trade-off: a hard design gives wide usable reading and distance zones but stronger \\\"swim\\\" and peripheral blur; a soft design smooths the periphery but with narrower zones. PAL markings recap: Permanent (micro-etched): two horizontal locator circles ~34 mm apart, the lens logo, and the add power. Temporary (ink-stamped): distance reference circle, fitting cross (sits in front of the pupil), prism reference point, near reference circle.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-frame-parts-and-hardware\",\"heading\":\"Frame Parts and Hardware\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Frame front parts: eyewires (rims), end pieces, bridge, hinges, lenses, nose pads, pad arms, screws, top bar. The bridge bears about 90% of the frame's weight . Bridge types: Bridge Feature / who it suits Keyhole Shaped like an old keyhole; rests on the sides of the upper nose; for small or flat nose bridges Saddle Spreads weight across the sides and top of the nose; good for heavy glasses or pressure-sensitive patients Adjustable Has nose pads that can be adjusted for fit Double Has a reinforcing bar over the top of the bridge Temple types: Temple Feature / use Skull Most popular for plastic frames; bends down over the ear following the skull Comfort-cable Flexible metal cable hooks behind the ear; children's and sports glasses Riding bow Like comfort-cable but rigid plastic Spring-hinged Hidden springs resist slipping and breakage Library (paddle) Straight temples, slip on and off easily; reading glasses\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-boxing-system-full-measurement-set\",\"heading\":\"Boxing System — Full Measurement Set\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Extends the geometric-center / effective-diameter / seg-height terms already covered. Term Definition A measurement Horizontal lens size (eye size); width of the box B measurement Vertical lens size; height of the box Datum line Horizontal line through the vertical center of the frame Geometric center (GC) Intersection of the datum line and horizontal center of each lens DBL (distance between lenses) Shortest distance between the nasal lens edges; the bridge size DBC (distance between centers) Horizontal distance between the two GCs; the FRAME PD; DBC = A + DBL Effective diameter (ED) Twice the distance from GC to the farthest lens edge; sets the minimum blank size Seg height Vertical distance from the bottom of the box to the top of the segment Seg drop Vertical distance from the datum line to the top of the segment OTL / LTB / FTB Overall temple length / length-to-bend / front-to-bend (temple measurements) Key formula link: Frame PD (DBC) = A + DBL , and decentration per eye = (Frame PD − Patient PD) / 2.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-instrument-name-and-history-anchors-high-yield-slivers\",\"heading\":\"Instrument Name and History Anchors (high-yield slivers)\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Vertexometer (distometer): the instrument that measures vertex distance from the back surface of the spectacle lens to the cornea through the closed eyelid. (The optical effect of vertex distance is covered above under Effective Power; this is just the tool's name.) History anchors the board actually asks: First / invention Who and when Bifocal (split / Franklin) Benjamin Franklin, 1784 Trifocal John Isaac Hawkins, 1826 First lens to correct astigmatism Sir George Airy, 1825 First one-piece bifocal (solid upcurve) Isaac Schnaitman, 1837 Fused bifocal (Kryptok) John Borsch Jr., 1908 First progressive lens (Varilux) Essilor (France), 1958–1959\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2-01-ophthalmic-lenses-and-dispensing-extended-topics-tints-frame-hardware-and-optics-details-high-yield-summary-extended-tints-and-hardware\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary — Extended Tints and Hardware\",\"topic\":\"D2-01 — Ophthalmic Lenses and Dispensing\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Tint giving true color perception Gray (even spectral transmission) Oxide for blue glass tint Cobalt oxide Oxide for green glass tint Ferrous oxide Pincushion distortion High PLUS lenses Barrel distortion High MINUS lenses Free from distortion Orthoscopic Correct chromatic aberration Higher Abbe material OR achromatic doublet Hard PAL vs soft PAL Hard = wide zones/short corridor/more peripheral blur; soft = opposite Bridge bearing ~90% of weight The bridge Frame PD (DBC) A + DBL Instrument for vertex distance Vertexometer (distometer) First progressive lens Varilux, Essilor, 1958–59\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"A contact lens sits directly on the tear film covering the cornea, forming a new optical interface that corrects refractive error without spectacles. The cornea is avascular and depends on atmospheric oxygen for metabolism — so every contact lens design balances optical correction against oxygen delivery. The evolution of CL materials follows a single thread: each generation solved the oxygen problem of the previous one, from PMMA (no oxygen) through RGP (gas-permeable) through hydrogel (water carries oxygen) through silicone hydrogel (the current material of choice). Fitting requires understanding base curve (matching the corneal curvature), diameter, and power — and aftercare requires recognizing when the cornea is telling you the lens is too tight, too loose, or depriving it of oxygen. Teaching angle: Ask students — \\\"What happens to the cornea if you leave a poorly fitting contact lens on it overnight?\\\" The answer traces the oxygen pathway: no Dk/t → no O2 → corneal hypoxia → neovascularization → the end of contact lens wear for that patient.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Why does a flat-fitting lens cause more problems than a steep-fitting one? Because a flat-fitting lens moves excessively on the eye, causing mechanical abrasion of the corneal epithelium and inconsistent tear exchange. However, a steep-fitting lens is arguably worse — it restricts tear flow entirely, trapping metabolic waste and causing hypoxia and edema under the lens. Why does silicone hydrogel solve the oxygen problem? Because silicone transmits oxygen directly through the polymer matrix without needing water as the carrier. Conventional hydrogels rely on dissolved oxygen moving through water content — the higher the water content, the more oxygen, but water evaporates and lenses dry out. Silicone bypass this by allowing oxygen to diffuse through the silicone polymer directly, independent of water content. Why is toric CL stabilization necessary? Because a toric lens has different power in different meridians — if it rotates freely on the eye, the corrective axis won't stay aligned with the patient's astigmatic axis. The lens must be stabilized in one rotational position for the correction to work. Prism ballast adds weight to the inferior lens to keep it oriented by gravity.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Dk Oxygen permeability Property of the lens material (D = diffusion coefficient × k = solubility) Dk/t Oxygen transmissibility Dk ÷ lens thickness (t); the actual oxygen delivery to the cornea Base curve (BC) Radius of curvature of the back surface Must approximate the corneal curvature for proper fit HEMA Hydroxyethyl methacrylate Monomer developed by Wichterle; basis of all hydrogel soft CL PMMA Polymethyl methacrylate First plastic CL material; non-gas permeable; Kevin Touhy (1947) RGP Rigid Gas Permeable Hard lens that transmits oxygen through the polymer Monovision — One eye corrected for distance, other for near; presbyopia management Prism ballast — Base-down prism (1–1.5Δ) added to inferior of toric CL for rotational stability Ortho-K Orthokeratology Overnight wear of specially designed RGP to temporarily reshape cornea; corrects myopia CLPC / GPC Contact Lens Papillary Conjunctivitis / Giant Papillary Conjunctivitis Mechanical/allergic response on upper tarsal conjunctiva Scleral lens — Large-diameter CL that vaults the entire cornea and rests on the sclera\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-how-it-works-the-mechanism\",\"heading\":\"How It Works — The Mechanism\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"CL history — the oxygen problem and how it was solved: 1508 — Leonardo da Vinci: first concept (lens directly on eye) 1827 — John Herschel: described glass CL to match eye shape 1888 — A.E. Fick: first CL intended to correct vision 1938 — Muller and Obrig: first plastic scleral CL (covers sclera + cornea) Problem: hypoxia — lens covered entire cornea, no O2 passage 1940s — E. Kalt: glass corneal CL (smaller diameter) Improvement: peripheral cornea exposed → more O2 1947 — Kevin Touhy: FIRST PLASTIC CORNEAL CL ( PMMA ) Material: PMMA (n=1.49); rigid, durable, better centration Problem: still non-gas permeable; hypoxia remained 1970s — Otto Wichterle: developed HEMA → first SOFT CL Improvement: soft; comfortable; better centration; water carries O2 Problem: low Dk; conventional hydrogel dries out 1971 — First soft CL received FDA approval 1979 — First RGP lens developed Improvement: rigid for better optics + gas permeable (O2 through polymer) Problem: comfort; not for dry eyes 1987 — First DISPOSABLE CL (1–2 month replacement) Reason: hygiene; contaminated saline DIY solution caused infections 1995 — DAILY DISPOSABLE CL introduced Reason: patient non-compliance with cleaning; frequent replacement = fewer infections 1999–2002 — SILICONE HYDROGEL CL introduced Material: silicone + HEMA hybrid Breakthrough: O2 diffuses through silicone polymer, not water → no hypoxia Problem (1st gen): high modulus (rubbery) → GPC , difficult removal Current gen: softer surface coating → improved comfort Oxygen pathway — why Dk/t matters: ATMOSPHERE ↓ O2 TEAR FILM (in front of lens) ↓ O2 through lens (Dk/t) BACK SURFACE OF LENS ↓ O2 POST-LENS TEAR FILM ↓ O2 CORNEAL EPITHELIUM Low Dk/t → insufficient O2 → corneal hypoxia: Corneal edema → microcysts → neovascularization → CL intolerance RGP solution: O2 goes through polymer (high Dk) + tear pump (blinking) Silicone hydrogel solution: O2 diffuses directly through silicone Contact lens fitting parameters: BASE CURVE (BC): Relationship to K (keratometry reading): SCL : BC typically flatter than K (\\\"flatter than K\\\" by ~0.8-1.0 mm for SCL ) RGP : BC approximates K (fit \\\"on K\\\" or slightly flatter) Steep fit: lens moves little → restricts tear exchange → hypoxia, edema Flat fit: lens moves too much → mechanical trauma, poor vision DIAMETER : SCL : 13.5–15 mm (covers limbus + some sclera) RGP : 8–10 mm (corneal diameter only; smaller) POWER : Vertex distance correction for prescriptions > ±4.00 D: D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − d × D_Spec) where d = vertex distance in meters (usually 0.012 m) High plus: CL power LESS than spectacle; High minus: CL power MORE minus than spectacle Spherical equivalent rule (when astigmatism < 1.00 D): D_CL = sphere + ½ cylinder (the 4:1 rule) Example: −3.00 −0.75 × 180 → CL = −3.00 + (−0.375) = −3.375 ≈ −3.25 D CORNEAL DIMENSIONS (for CL fitting reference): HVID (horizontal visible iris diameter): 11.7 mm average VVID (vertical visible iris diameter): 10.6 mm average SCL diameter is typically HVID + 2 mm = ~13.7 mm BOZR SELECTION (back optic zone radius): Empirical method: BOZR = flattest K + 0.3 to 0.9 mm Rule of thumb for SCL : ΔTD 0.5 mm = ΔBOZR 0.3 mm (If you increase lens diameter by 0.5 mm → steepen BOZR by 0.3 mm to maintain same fit) RGP : BOZR ±0.10 mm of flattest corneal radius Toric CL stabilization methods: 1. PRISM BALLAST (most common) 1–1.5Δ base-down prism added inferiorly Gravity + lid interaction keeps inferior edge down Disadvantage: reduced O2 at thicker inferior zone; lid discomfort 2. TRUNCATION Inferior edge cut flat to align with lower lid margin Disadvantage: discomfort; not always successful 3. PERI-BALLAST Thickness difference creates prism-base-down effect (minus carrier) Thinner superior, thicker inferior Similar comfort issues to prism ballast but thinner overall 4. DOUBLE SLAB-OFF Thin zones superiorly AND inferiorly Lid forces maintain orientation Overall thinner lens → better O2 transmissibility 5. REVERSE PRISM Opposite of prism ballast — used in specific designs Presbyopia correction with CL: 1. MONOVISION Dominant eye: distance correction Non-dominant eye: near correction (total reading add added to sphere) Advantage: simple; flexible Disadvantage: disrupts stereopsis; not ideal for high add 2. ALTERNATING ( TRANSLATING ) BIFOCAL Distance zone: upper portion Near zone: lower portion (lid pushes lens up during downgaze) Works like spectacle bifocal Advantage: high visual quality Disadvantage: needs significant lid-lens interaction; comfort issues 3. SIMULTANEOUS VISION BIFOCAL / PROGRESSIVE Both distance and near zones over pupil simultaneously Brain selects appropriate focus Center-distance: distance at center, near at periphery Center-near: near at center, distance at periphery Modified monovision: center-distance dominant eye + center-near non-dominant 4. READING GLASSES OVER CLs Simplest; high-quality distance AND near correction Patient must carry glasses\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-structure-or-process-map\",\"heading\":\"Structure or Process Map\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"CL classification: BY MATERIAL : Hard: Non-gas permeable ( PMMA ) — obsolete for wear; still used as RGP trial lens Gas permeable ( RGP ) — rigid + O2 permeable through polymer Soft: Conventional — 6 months to 1 year replacement Disposable: Monthly (1–2 months) Daily (single use — most hygienic) BY MODE OF WEAR : Daily wear — removed every night Extended wear: Continuous (silicone hydrogel) — up to 2 weeks without removal Flexible wear — up to 1 month (not common) BY DESIGN : Monocurve — single radius; obsolete Bicurve — central + peripheral curve (most common SCL ) Tricurve — central + mid-periphery + periphery (ortho-K; irregular cornea) Aspheric — steeper center, flatter periphery BY INDICATION : Spherical CL — regular myopia/hyperopia Toric CL — astigmatism (corneal or residual) Multifocal/bifocal — presbyopia Ortho-K — temporary myopia correction (overnight wear) Scleral — irregular cornea (keratoconus, post-surgical) Bandage CL — corneal erosion healing; therapeutic Prosthetic — cosmetic; disfigurement masking CL solutions and care: SOLUTION TYPES : 1. Saline solution — rinse/storage; NOT a disinfectant 2. Surfactant cleaner — removes deposits daily; use before disinfection 3. Disinfecting solution — kills microorganisms a. Chemical (preserved): PHMB , polyquaternium, benzalkonium chloride ( BAK ) b. Hydrogen peroxide (3% H2O2 ): most effective; must neutralize before insertion 4. Multipurpose solution ( MPS ) — combines cleaning, rinsing, disinfection, storage 5. Enzymatic cleaner — removes protein deposits (weekly) 6. Rewetting drops — lubricates during wear PRESERVATIVES : BAK (benzalkonium chloride) — TOXIC to corneal epithelium; do NOT use with SCL EDTA — chelating agent; synergistic with antimicrobials Sorbic acid — low toxicity; commonly used in soft CL solutions Thimerosal — mercury-based; largely discontinued (toxicity, allergy) PHMB — polyhexamethylene biguanide; well-tolerated SOLUTION pH: Tear film pH: 7.4 CL solution acceptable range: 6.5–8.0 Outside range → corneal burn (alkaline burns more dangerous) CL complications: MECHANICAL : Epithelial abrasion (flat fit, poor edge quality) 3 and 9 o'clock staining ( RGP : peripheral desiccation) Superior epithelial arcuate lesion ( SEAL ) — tightly fitted SCL HYPOXIC : Corneal edema (acute: transient blur; chronic: microcysts, neovascularization) Limbal hyperemia (early sign of hypoxic stress) Corneal neovascularization (late sign — lens intolerance; stop wear immediately) IMMUNE / ALLERGIC : GPC / CLPC (giant papillary conjunctivitis) — cobblestone upper tarsal conjunctiva Cause: mechanical (deposits on lens) + type IV hypersensitivity Treatment: reduce wear, dispose and replace, antihistamine drops INFECTIOUS : Microbial keratitis — most serious CL complication Organisms: Pseudomonas aeruginosa (most common bacterial), Acanthamoeba (primary cause in extended wear — associated with tap water/swimming) Risk: extended wear, poor hygiene, swimming in CLs Emergency: refer immediately; culture and topical antibiotics ENDOTHELIAL / METABOLIC : Polymegethism — variable endothelial cell size and shape from chronic hypoxia Significance: marker of long-term corneal stress; not immediately vision-threatening but irreversible Blebs — dark areas in specular reflection, appearing 20–30 min post-insertion; reduce over weeks Corneal edema by wear modality: Daily wear (conventional hydrogel): 2–7% Conventional extended wear: 7–14% SiHy extended wear: 2–4% (comparable to daily wear) >8% is excessive for extended wear ORTHO-K LIMITS : Maximum myopia correction: −6.00 D Maximum astigmatism correction: −2.00 D Indication: myopia progression >0.50 D/year; career requiring unaided acuity DEPOSIT-RELATED : Protein deposits (jelly bumps on hydrogel) Lipid deposits (in meibomian gland dysfunction) Calcium deposits (in compromised corneas)\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"RGP vs Soft CL: Feature RGP Soft CL Material Rigid gas-permeable polymer HEMA or silicone hydrogel Oxygen delivery Through polymer + tear pump Through water (hydrogel) or polymer (SiHy) Initial comfort Poor (adaptation 1–2 weeks) Good (immediate) Optical quality Superior (rigid surface = better optics for astigmatism) Good for regular corneas Best for Keratoconus; high astigmatism; irregular cornea Most patients; presbyopia; cosmetic Fitting method Trial lens required (Philippines) Empirical prescribing acceptable (Philippines) Board clue \\\"Best optics; worst initial comfort\\\" \\\"Best comfort; adequate optics\\\" Flat vs Steep fit assessment (SCL/RGP): Feature Flat fit Steep fit Movement on blink Excessive Little or none Centration Poor (decenters) Good Vision Unstable; intermittent blur Good initially Complications Mechanical trauma; corneal abrasion Hypoxia; edema; corneal staining Action needed Steeper BC Flatter BC Board clue \\\"Flat = moves too much; Steep = doesn't move enough\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"First PMMA CL 1947 (Kevin Touhy) First plastic corneal CL First soft CL FDA approval 1971 Hydrogel CL mainstream availability First disposable CL 1987 Hygiene improvement First silicone hydrogel 1999–2002 O2 breakthrough SCL diameter 13.5–15 mm Covers limbus RGP diameter 8–10 mm Corneal only Prism ballast amount 1–1.5Δ base-down Stabilizes toric orientation SCL typical BC Flatter than K by ~0.8–1.0 mm Starting point for empirical fit BAK toxicity Toxic to SCL corneal surface Never use with soft CL Tear film pH 7.4 CL solution target range CL solution pH range 6.5–8.0 Outside = burn risk HVID 11.7 mm average Horizontal visible iris diameter; SCL diameter = HVID + ~2 mm VVID 10.6 mm average Vertical visible iris diameter Vertex distance correction threshold > ±4.00 D Below this, CL power = spectacle power Vertex correction formula D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − 0.012 × D_Spec) d = 0.012 m (12 mm vertex distance) Spherical equivalent rule D_CL = Sph + ½ Cyl (if cyl < 1.00 D) \\\"4:1 rule\\\"; round to nearest 0.25 D SCL BOZR selection Flattest K + 0.3–0.9 mm Starting point; steepen if steep fit, flatten if flat fit Soft lens TD/BOZR rule ΔTD 0.5 mm = ΔBOZR 0.3 mm Change diameter → compensate BOZR Ortho-K max myopia −6.00 D Beyond this, insufficient corneal flattening Ortho-K max astigmatism −2.00 D Irregular astigmatism develops above this DW corneal edema 2–7% Normal range for daily wear hydrogel Conventional EW edema 7–14% Excessive; high hypoxia risk SiHy EW edema 2–4% Comparable to daily wear Polymegethism Variable endothelial cell size Irreversible marker of chronic hypoxia\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-the-details-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"CL history — \\\"Da Vinci Herschel Fick Touhy Wichterle\\\" Concept (1508) → Designed (1827) → First vision CL (1888) → PMMA (1947) → HEMA soft (1970s) Silicone hydrogel advantage — \\\"O2 through polymer, not water\\\" Previous hydrogel: H2O carries O2 (water evaporates → less O2) SiHy: silicone carries O2 directly → no water dependency Toric stabilization — \\\"Prism Ballast is Base Down by Gravity\\\" 1–1.5Δ base-down prism; gravity + lids keep inferior edge down. Fitting rule — \\\"Flat = floats; Steep = stuck\\\" Flat fit = too much movement; Steep fit = too little movement. BAK is BAD for soft CLs — \\\"BAK = Don't Use with Soft\\\" Benzalkonium chloride is toxic to the SCL-wearing cornea. GPC mnemonic — \\\"Cobblestone upper lid + CL deposits\\\" Look under the upper lid with fluorescein; cobblestone papillae = stop CL wear + replace lens.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"CL MATERIAL EVOLUTION (oxygen problem → solution) ────────────────────────────────────────────────── 1947 PMMA : No O2 → hypoxia ↓ 1979 RGP : O2 through polymer + tear pump ↓ 1970s Hydrogel ( HEMA ): O2 through water (low Dk) ↓ 2002 Silicone hydrogel: O2 through silicone polymer (high Dk) TORIC SCL ORIENTATION (right eye, patient view) ──────────────────────────────────────────────── 12 | [ TORIC LENS ] Thicker inferior = prism ballast 6 (Inferior stays down by gravity + lid interaction) Reference marks at 3 and 9 o'clock (or 5,6,7) Mark position ≠ axis position CL FITTING ASSESSMENT (fluorescein, SCL ) ───────────────────────────────────────── OPTIMAL FIT : 1–2 mm movement on blink; full corneal coverage; good centration STEEP : <0.5 mm movement → slow return if displaced → restrict tear exchange FLAT : >3 mm movement → poor centration → edge trauma → 3/9 staining\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"PMMA is gas permeable PMMA is non-gas permeable. RGP lenses are gas permeable (they have different polymer formulations). Silicone hydrogel CLs transmit oxygen through their water content Silicone hydrogel transmits oxygen through the silicone polymer matrix, independent of water content. \\\"Flat-fitting CLs cause less corneal damage than steep-fitting\\\" — Flat-fitting causes mechanical trauma from excessive movement; steep-fitting causes hypoxic damage from restricted tear exchange. Both are harmful — just different pathologies. BAK-preserved solutions can be used with soft CLs BAK is toxic to corneal epithelium and should never be used with soft contact lenses. GPC only affects RGP wearers GPC/CLPC occurs in both soft and RGP lens wearers. It is caused by lens deposits + mechanical friction on the upper tarsal conjunctiva. Daily disposables were introduced because they are more comfortable Daily disposables were introduced primarily to address patient non-compliance with cleaning, making frequent replacement and improved hygiene the main driver. A −6.00 D patient's CL power = −6.00 D for high prescriptions. Vertex distance correction applies above ±4.00 D. CL power for a high minus is MORE minus than the spectacle; for high plus, LESS plus. Use D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − 0.012 × D_Spec). Acanthamoeba is the most common cause of microbial keratitis in all CL wearers Acanthamoeba is the primary cause specifically in extended wear and poor hygiene (tap water/swimming). Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most common bacterial organism overall. Polymegethism is reversible with better lens wear Polymegethism (variable endothelial cell size from chronic hypoxia) is IRREVERSIBLE — it is a permanent marker of corneal stress even after CL discontinuation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer First PMMA CL Kevin Touhy, 1947 First soft CL developer Otto Wichterle (HEMA) FDA approval of soft CL 1971 First disposable CL 1987 (hygiene) Silicone hydrogel advantage O2 through polymer (not water) RGP vs SCL fitting requirement RGP needs trial fitting; SCL can be empirical Prism ballast amount 1–1.5Δ base-down (toric stabilization) BAK and soft CLs Toxic — never use BAK with SCLs GPC cause Lens deposits + mechanical friction on upper tarsus Most dangerous CL complication Microbial keratitis (Pseudomonas most common) Flat fit → Too much movement → mechanical trauma Steep fit → Too little movement → hypoxia/edema Monovision — dominant eye Distance correction on dominant eye Ortho-K function Temporary corneal reshaping; controls myopia progression Ortho-K max myopia −6.00 D Beyond this = insufficient effect Ortho-K max astigmatism −2.00 D Vertex correction threshold > ±4.00 D Below this, spectacle power = CL power Vertex correction formula D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − 0.012 × D_Spec) High minus = more minus for CL Spherical equivalent (cyl < 1.00 D) D_CL = Sph + ½ Cyl Round to nearest 0.25 D HVID 11.7 mm SCL diameter ≈ HVID + 2 mm Corneal edema — DW 2–7% Normal for daily wear hydrogel Corneal edema — EW SiHy 2–4% Comparable to daily wear Corneal edema — conventional EW 7–14% Excessive Polymegethism Irreversible endothelial change Marker of chronic CL hypoxia Acanthamoeba keratitis Extended wear + tap water/swimming Most serious CL infection; very difficult to treat\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"1. A 28-year-old patient wearing conventional hydrogel lenses (monthly replacement) presents with red eye, foreign body sensation, and reduced vision after wearing lenses for 12 hours. Slit-lamp reveals corneal edema and a white infiltrate with fluorescein staining. The most urgent concern is: A. GPC from protein deposits B. Corneal neovascularization from chronic hypoxia C. Microbial keratitis D. Corneal abrasion from flat-fitting lens Answer C. Microbial keratitis. A white infiltrate with fluorescein staining in a CL wearer is microbial keratitis until proven otherwise — this is the most serious CL complication and a potential sight-threatening emergency. The combination of pain, infiltrate, and staining requires immediate removal of the lens and urgent referral to an ophthalmologist for culture, scraping, and topical antibiotics. Extended or continuous wear, poor hygiene, and swimming with lenses are major risk factors. Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most common organism in CL-related infectious keratitis. GPC presents as cobblestone papillae under the upper lid (not infiltrate). Neovascularization is asymptomatic initially. Abrasion would not typically present with a white infiltrate. 2. A patient's spectacle refraction is −6.50D at a vertex distance of 14mm. What is the appropriate contact lens power to prescribe? A. −6.50D B. −6.25D C. −6.00D D. −5.75D Answer C. −6.00D. Using the vertex distance formula: D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − d × D_Spec) = −6.50 / (1 − 0.014 × (−6.50)) = −6.50 / (1 + 0.091) = −6.50 / 1.091 = −5.96D → round to −6.00D. The vertex distance effect is significant here because |Rx| > 4.00D. Moving a minus lens from 14mm (spectacle plane) to 0mm (corneal plane) reduces the effective minus power needed. If you prescribed the same −6.50D as a CL, the patient would be overcorrected (too much minus at the cornea). Options A is the spectacle power unadjusted. Options B and D are close but not correct for a 14mm vertex distance. 3. A patient's keratometry reads 43.00 / 45.00 @ 90. Spectacle refraction is −2.00 −3.00 × 180. What is the residual astigmatism if an RGP spherical lens is fitted? A. 1.00D B. 2.00D C. 3.00D D. 0.00D Answer A. 1.00D. Residual astigmatism = Total astigmatism − Corneal astigmatism. Total astigmatism (from spectacle Rx) = −3.00D. Corneal astigmatism (from K readings) = 45.00 − 43.00 = 2.00D. Residual = 3.00 − 2.00 = 1.00D. This residual 1.00D is mostly lenticular (internal) astigmatism — the RGP tear lens corrects the 2.00D corneal component but cannot touch the lenticular component. Since residual > 0.75D, a toric RGP or toric SCL would be needed for complete correction. Option D (0.00) would only apply if total = corneal astigmatism (purely corneal origin).\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Close note. Write first, check after. Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write \\\"CONTACT LENSES.\\\" 5 minutes. Write: CL history timeline (5 key milestones with years), toric stabilization 3 methods, presbyopia management 3 options, CL complications (4 categories), why BAK is toxic for SCL. Core targets: PMMA (1947), FDA soft CL (1971), silicone hydrogel (2002) Flat vs steep fit clinical findings Why silicone hydrogel solved the oxygen problem Drill 2 — Blank Diagram Draw the CL material evolution timeline from 1947 to 2002. For each material, write: material type, oxygen delivery method, and the problem it left unsolved. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a new CL wearer why they should never sleep in conventional hydrogel lenses — starting at the corneal oxygen requirement, through what happens without it, to the long-term consequence. Do not use \\\"hypoxia\\\" until your third sentence. Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back First PMMA CL? Kevin Touhy, 1947 First soft CL developer? Otto Wichterle (HEMA) Silicone hydrogel O2 mechanism? Through silicone polymer (not water) Prism ballast amount? 1–1.5Δ base-down BAK and SCL? Toxic — never use together GPC appearance? Cobblestone papillae under upper lid Most dangerous CL complication? Microbial keratitis Flat fit finding? Too much movement (>3mm) Steep fit finding? Too little movement (<0.5mm) Monovision dominant eye? Distance correction Vertex distance correction needed when? Rx ≥ ±4.00D CL power vs spectacle power (plus lens)? CL power is less plus Residual astigmatism = ? Total astigmatism − Corneal astigmatism Toric CL needed when residual astig > ? 0.75D Myope switches specs to CLs → near accom? Increases (more accommodation needed) Hyperope switches specs to CLs → add? May be postponed (less accom demand) Aphakia: specs or CLs preferred? CLs (reduce 30% magnification, reduce ring scotoma) Aphakia ametropia type? Refractive (not axial) Keratoconus advanced → best CL? Scleral lens Corneal topography: normal shape? Prolate (steep apex, flatter periphery) Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Today Brain Dump 2nd Tomorrow CL evolution timeline + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days Teach-Back (no overnight wear) 4th 1 week CL complications — 4 categories from scratch Final 2 weeks All drills\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-cl-optics-thick-lens-principles-applied-to-contact-lenses\",\"heading\":\"CL Optics — Thick Lens Principles Applied to Contact Lenses\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: Contact lenses are optically thick — their radius of curvature is small and their thickness is not negligible the way it is in a spectacle lens. So the same thick lens formulas apply: nominal power, equivalent power, back vertex power (effective power), and front vertex power (neutralizing power). These are the same formulas as spectacle thick lenses, just applied to a tiny curved disc. CL SURFACE POWER : D = (n − 1) / r (r in meters; n = CL material index) NOMINAL POWER : Dn = D₁ + D₂ EQUIVALENT POWER : Deq = D₁ + D₂ − (t/n)(D₁ × D₂) EFFECTIVE POWER (Back Vertex Power): BVP = Dn + (t/n)(D₁)² NEUTRALIZING POWER (Front Vertex Power): FVP = Dn + (t/n)(D₂)²\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-vertex-distance-conversion-spectacle-rx-cl-power\",\"heading\":\"Vertex Distance Conversion (Spectacle Rx → CL Power)\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: A spectacle lens sits about 12–14 mm in front of the cornea. A contact lens sits right on the cornea (vertex distance ≈ 0). A +6.00D spectacle lens has its focal point 12–14 mm behind the back surface. A CL at the cornea needs to put that focal point in the same place — but now from the cornea itself, not from 12–14 mm in front of it. So the CL power has to be slightly different (stronger for plus, weaker for minus at high powers). Clinical term: Vertex distance correction — converting spectacle Rx to CL power accounting for the change in vertex distance from 12–14 mm (specs) to 0 mm (CL). FORMULA : D_CL = D_Spec / (1 − d × D_Spec) Where: D_Spec = spectacle refraction power (diopters) d = vertex distance in METERS (typically 0.012–0.014 m) WHEN VERTEX DISTANCE MATTERS : ± 4.00D and below: vertex distance effect is < 0.25D → CL power ≈ spectacle power ± 4.00D and above: vertex distance correction is clinically significant → always calculate DIRECTION RULE : Plus lens → CL power is LESS than spectacle power (minus vertex distance = shorter path) Minus lens → CL power is MORE minus than spectacle power SPHERICAL EQUIVALENT RULE (\\\"4:1 Rule\\\"): If residual astigmatism (from spectacle Rx) is < 1.00D: D_CL = Spherical Equivalent = Sph + ½ Cyl (Use a spherical CL; the 0.75D or less of astigmatism is tolerable) Sample: Spectacle Rx: −4.75D at vertex distance 13 mm D_CL = −4.75 / (1 − 0.013 × (−4.75)) = −4.75 / (1 + 0.062) = −4.75 / 1.062 D_CL = −4.47 D → round to −4.50D\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-residual-astigmatism\",\"heading\":\"Residual Astigmatism\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: The eye's total astigmatism comes from two sources: the cornea (most of it) and the lens inside the eye (a small amount, usually against-the-rule). When you put a hard or RGP lens on the eye, the tear film fills the gap between the flat cornea and the curved back surface of the lens — the tear lens neutralizes corneal astigmatism. But it cannot fix the lens astigmatism inside the eye. That leftover astigmatism — the part the tear lens cannot correct — is the residual astigmatism. Clinical term: Residual astigmatism — astigmatism remaining after a hard CL (or hypothetical spherical RGP) corrects corneal astigmatism via the tear lens. FORMULA : Residual Astigmatism = Total (spectacle) astigmatism − Corneal astigmatism Total astigmatism = from spectacle refraction Corneal astigmatism = from keratometry (K readings) WHEN TORIC CL IS NEEDED : If residual astigmatism > 0.75D → prescribe toric CL If residual astigmatism ≤ 0.75D → spherical RGP adequate (tear lens handles the rest) TYPES OF RESIDUAL ASTIGMATISM : Corneal astigmatism (keratometric): corrected by tear lens with RGP Lenticular (internal) astigmatism: NOT corrected by RGP ; requires toric CL Residual = mostly lenticular astigmatism SOFT CL AND ASTIGMATISM : SCL drapes over the cornea → does NOT form a tear lens SCL only corrects ≤ 0.75D of astigmatism with spherical lens Any astigmatism with SCL must be corrected by a toric SCL\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-accommodation-demand-cl-vs-spectacles\",\"heading\":\"Accommodation Demand: CL vs Spectacles\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: When you wear plus glasses (hyperope), the glasses help your eye converge the light before it gets to your eye — your eye does less accommodation work. When you switch to contact lenses at the same prescription, the lens is now right on your eye, and the optical effect changes — your eye has to accommodate slightly more. For myopes, the opposite happens. MYOPE : With spectacles : Accommodation demand > with CLs (minus spectacles reduce vergence demand at near → eye accommodates less) With CLs: accommodation demand INCREASES relative to spectacles → Myope switching from specs to CLs may suddenly need reading add sooner HYPEROPE : With spectacles (+): Accommodation demand < with CLs (plus spectacles do some of the accommodation work) With CLs: accommodation demand DECREASES relative to spectacles → Hyperope switching from specs to CLs may not need reading add as soon CLINICAL RULE : If a MYOPE is switched from spectacles to CLs → may precipitate need for near correction If a HYPEROPE is switched from spectacles to CLs → onset of near correction may be postponed\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-cl-magnification\",\"heading\":\"CL Magnification\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: Spectacles magnify or minify the image (plus = bigger, minus = smaller). Contact lenses sit right on the eye, so the image size with CLs is much closer to the natural (uncorrected) image size. For myopes, switching from minus specs to CLs gives a bigger image — some patients notice this as improved peripheral awareness and depth perception. For high hyperopes (like aphakes), CLs produce much less magnification than the thick plus spectacles. CL MAGNIFICATION ( CLM ): CLM = 1 − d × D_Spec Where: d = spectacle vertex distance (meters) D_Spec = spectacle power CLM < 1 for plus → CL gives LESS magnification than spectacles CLM > 1 for minus → CL gives MORE magnification than spectacles (i.e., less minification = bigger image with CL vs minus specs) RELATIVE SPECTACLE MAGNIFICATION ( RSM ): Refractive ametropia: With specs: RSM = 1 + d × F_Spec With CLs: RSM ≈ 1 (d ≈ 0 at cornea) Axial ametropia: With specs: RSM ≈ 1 With CLs: RSM = 1 − (f_eye − 1.55) × F_Spec APPLICATION : — Aphakia is REFRACTIVE ametropia → prefer CLs (reduce magnification to ~1) — Axial myopia → prefer spectacles ( RSM already ~1 with specs) — High corneal astigmatism is REFRACTIVE → spectacles cause meridional aniseikonia → prefer CLs\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-corneal-topography-cl-relevance\",\"heading\":\"Corneal Topography — CL Relevance\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Plain version: The cornea is not a perfect sphere — it is steepest at the center (apex) and gradually flattens toward the edges. Knowing the exact shape helps you fit a contact lens that matches the cornea's curvature. If you fit a lens too steep, it traps tears and starves the cornea. If you fit too flat, it rocks and decenters. Corneal topography maps the entire cornea shape, not just the central 3mm like the keratometer does. CORNEAL MEASUREMENTS : HVID (horizontal visible iris diameter) = 10–14 mm (avg 11.7 mm) → determines overall lens diameter selection VVID (vertical VID ) = avg 10.6 mm (0.5–1.0 mm less than HVID ) Corneal thickness: 0.50–0.65 mm (Gullstrand = 0.50 mm) CORNEAL ASPHERICITY : Normal cornea = PROLATE (steepest at apex; flattens toward periphery) Eccentricity (e) describes how much the cornea deviates from a sphere e = 0 → perfect sphere e = 0.4–0.6 → typical normal cornea Post- LASIK or post-orthoK = OBLATE (flattest at apex; steeper periphery) TOPOGRAPHY INSTRUMENTS : Photokeratoscope / Placido disc — reflects rings off corneal surface; maps curvature Keratometer — measures central 3 mm only (2 points per meridian) Computer-assisted topography ( CAT ) — full corneal map TOPOGRAPHY IN CL FITTING : — Identify K readings for base curve selection — Detect irregular corneas (keratoconus) — Monitor ortho-K treatment zone — Check post-refractive surgery cornea before fitting\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-special-cl-fitting\",\"heading\":\"Special CL Fitting\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Keratoconus Plain version: In keratoconus, the cornea thins and bulges forward into a cone shape. A soft lens drapes over the cone and does not correct the irregular astigmatism. A rigid lens (RGP or scleral) vaults over the cone and creates a smooth tear lens front surface — it essentially replaces the irregular corneal front surface with a smooth optical surface, dramatically improving vision. KERATOCONUS CL FITTING : Mild KC: RGP lens fit slightly steeper than K (\\\"apical clearance\\\" fitting) Advanced KC: Scleral lens (vaults entire cornea; rests on sclera) RGP fitting in KC: Target: \\\"three-point touch\\\" or \\\"apical clearance\\\" + peripheral alignment BOZR ≈ 1 mm flatter than average K (for scleral) Apical bearing fit: RGP contacts KC apex → often causes corneal scarring → avoid SIGNS OF KERATOCONUS (for CL fitting): Irregular mires on keratometry Oil droplet reflex on retinoscopy Scissor reflex in retinoscopy Fleischer ring, Vogt's striae Aphakia — Contact Lens Fitting Plain version: Aphakia (no natural lens) requires a very high plus correction — typically +10.00D to +14.00D. This much plus in spectacle form is thick, heavy, and causes extreme magnification (~30%) plus significant prismatic effects in the periphery. A contact lens at the cornea dramatically reduces the magnification and the prismatic effect — the patient sees a much more normal world. APHAKIA + CL: Power needed: typically +10.00 to +14.00D (depends on axial length) Aphakia is REFRACTIVE ametropia → CLs preferred over spectacles (spectacles cause ~30% image magnification + limited visual field) SCL for aphakia: available in high plus powers (extended wear SiHy preferred) RGP for aphakia: used in pediatric aphakia (after congenital cataract surgery) — RGP for infant aphakia: modified monocurve or bicurve; BOZR to match infant K Benefit of CL over specs in aphakia: — Reduces magnification from ~30% (specs) to ~10% (CL) — Reduces ring scotoma (peripheral vision loss with high plus specs) — Improves binocularity in unilateral aphakia Presbyopia CL Options Plain version: Presbyopes cannot accommodate. To see both far and near through the same eye, a CL must somehow provide two powers. There are two strategies: alternating vision (eye looks through different zones at different gaze angles — like a bifocal spectacle) and simultaneous vision (both distance and near images hit the retina at the same time — the brain selects the sharper one). PRESBYOPIA CL OPTIONS : 1. MONOVISION : Dominant eye → distance CL Non-dominant eye → near CL Patient adapts by suppressing the blurred eye's input at each distance Limitation: reduces stereopsis 2. ALTERNATING VISION BIFOCAL CL : Distance power in upper lens; near power in lower lens Lens must translate (shift down) when patient looks down to read Works like a bifocal spectacle Best with: RGP lenses (mass and lid interaction allow translation) 3. SIMULTANEOUS VISION BIFOCAL CL : Distance and near power in concentric zones (center-near or center-distance) Both images on retina simultaneously → brain uses the relevant one Limitation: reduced contrast, ghost images Types: Center-distance design — distance in center; near in ring zone Center-near design — near in center; distance in surrounding zone 4. MODIFIED MONOVISION : One eye: monovision (full correction) Other eye: simultaneous bifocal CL\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-board-traps-extended\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps — Extended\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Vertex distance correction only matters for high prescriptions It matters any time the lens is being moved significantly relative to the original vertex distance, but clinically significant (≥ 0.25D change) starts at approximately ±4.00D. RGP lenses correct all astigmatism RGP corrects corneal astigmatism via the tear lens. Residual (lenticular) astigmatism persists and requires a toric CL if > 0.75D. Soft CLs work the same as RGP for all astigmatic patients SCL drapes over the cornea and does not form a corrective tear lens. For > 0.75D astigmatism, toric SCL is required. Contact lenses always give a larger image than spectacles For myopes, switching from minus specs to CLs gives a larger image (less minification). For hyperopes, switching from plus specs to CLs gives a smaller image (less magnification). A myope who switches from specs to CLs will accommodate less at near The opposite. Minus specs already reduce the vergence demand at near; CL removes this reduction, so accommodation demand INCREASES. Myopes may need reading correction sooner with CLs. Aphakia is axial ametropia Aphakia is refractive ametropia (the lens is missing). Contact lenses are preferred over spectacles for aphakia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3-01-contact-lenses-extended-topics-cl-optics-vertex-distance-conversion-accommodation-magnification-corneal-topography-special-fitting-high-yield-summary-extended\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary — Extended\",\"topic\":\"D3-01 — Contact Lenses\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer CL BVP formula BVP = Dn + (t/n)(D₁)² Vertex distance correction needed when Rx ≥ ±4.00D CL power vs spectacle power (plus lens) CL power is less plus CL power vs spectacle power (minus lens) CL power is less minus (numerically) Residual astigmatism = Total astigmatism − Corneal astigmatism Toric CL indicated when residual > 0.75D Myope: switches specs to CLs → More accommodation needed at near Hyperope: switches specs to CLs → Less accommodation needed (postpones add) Aphakia: specs vs CLs CLs preferred — reduce 30% magnification; reduce ring scotoma Keratoconus best CL RGP (mild-mod) or scleral (advanced) Alternating bifocal CL best with RGP (lid interaction allows translation) Corneal topography — prolate = Normal (steepest at apex, flatter periphery)\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"D.strategy\",\"subject\":\"D\",\"label\":\"Theoretical Optics & CL — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/D-Theoretical-Optics-Dispensing-CL/D-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Theoretical Optics, Dispensing & Contact Lenses · the read-before-you-test reference Formulas & Constants D1 Physical D1 Geometric D2 Dispensing D3 Contact Lens\"},{\"anchor\":\"key\",\"heading\":\"KEYFormulas & Constants\",\"topic\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Snell: n₁ sin i = n₂ sin R · Speed: v = c/n · Vergence: D = 100/f (f in cm) Prentice: P = d(cm) × F · Mirror/lens: 1/p + 1/q = 1/f · Mirror: f = R/2 Keratometry: D = 337.5/r (n = 1.3375) · Vertex: D_CL = D_spec / (1 − 0.012·D_spec) Surface power: D = (n₂ − n₁)/r · Apparent depth = actual ÷ n · 1° ≈ 1.75Δ Gullstrand constant Value Cornea power / index 43 D / 1.376 Lens power (unaccommodated) 19 D Total eye (exact / reduced) 58.64 D / 60 D Aqueous & vitreous index 1.336 Lens nucleus / cortex index 1.406 / 1.386 Anterior / posterior cornea radius 7.7 mm / 6.8 mm Nodal points (N / N') 7.08 / 7.33 mm Center of rotation 13.5 mm Axial length (emmetrope) 24 mm\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1p\",\"heading\":\"D1Physical Optics\",\"topic\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Light theories \\\"NHMP\\\": Newton (corpuscular) → Huygens (wave) → Maxwell (electromagnetic) → Planck (quantum). Huygens correctly predicted light slows in dense media. Vergence signs: diverging = negative, converging = positive. Higher n → slower light and lower critical angle (diamond ~24.44°). Beyond the critical angle = total internal reflection. Abbe ↔ index are inverse: higher index → lower Abbe → more chromatic aberration. UV-B = photokeratitis (welder's flash); UV-A → cataract. Thermal damage = permanent; photochemical = reversible. Flat transposition: new Sph = S + C , new Cyl = −C , new Axis = ±90° . Trap: higher index = higher Abbe = less aberration. No — inverse: higher index = lower Abbe = more chromatic aberration. Trap: keratometry uses the true corneal index 1.376. No — it uses the keratometric index 1.3375 . Trap: Newton's theory predicted light slows in glass. No — Newton predicted speed-up; Huygens was right.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d1g\",\"heading\":\"D1Geometric Optics\",\"topic\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Always virtual, upright, minified: the convex mirror and the concave (minus) lens, at any object distance. Plane mirror = virtual, upright, same size, equal distance behind. Sign rules: q positive = real, q negative = virtual; m positive = upright, m negative = inverted. Plus lens with object inside F = virtual, upright, magnified (a magnifier). Prism: light bends toward the base , image displaces toward the apex . Esotropia → base out ; exotropia → base in . 1° ≈ 1.75Δ. Surface power needs BOTH the radius and the index difference (matched media = zero power). Apparent depth = actual ÷ n (shallowing). Lens movement: plus = against, minus = with . Trap: a flat glass slab (plane refractor) adds power. No — it only displaces the ray laterally; exit ray stays parallel. Trap: exotropia is corrected base out. No — exotropia → base in ; esotropia → base out. Trap: a convex mirror can form a real image. No — convex mirrors are always virtual, upright, minified.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d2\",\"heading\":\"D2Ophthalmic Lenses & Dispensing\",\"topic\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Material Abbe Note Crown glass 58.9 Best optics (highest Abbe) CR-39 58 Good optics, standard plastic Trivex 43–45 Lightest (SG ~1.11), impact resistant Polycarbonate 30 Most impact resistant; UV <385 inherent; most CA Photochromic = silver halide, UV-triggered; does not darken in a car (windshield blocks UV). UV 400 blocks all UV <400 nm. Tints/filters: higher CPF number = darker. RP → yellow/amber (CPF 511/527); achromatopsia → dark red (CPF 550, Wratten #25/#29). Slab-off for anisometropic vertical prism (>~1.5Δ): grind on the more minus / less plus lens. Prentice P = d(cm) × F . Bifocal toric forms: SVTT & UBTT use plus-cyl; FBTT uses minus-cyl (cylinder on back). Fused bifocals: Kryptok, FT-28, FT-35. One-piece: Ultex, Executive. Trap: polycarbonate has the highest Abbe value. No — it has the lowest (30); crown glass is highest. Trap: slab-off goes on the more plus lens. No — on the more minus / less plus lens.\"},{\"anchor\":\"d3\",\"heading\":\"D3Contact Lenses\",\"topic\":\"Subject D — Strategy, Formulas & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Vertex correction matters above ±4.00 D. D_CL = D_spec/(1 − 0.012·D_spec) . High minus → less minus as a CL; high plus → more plus. Low cyl (<1.00) → spherical equivalent (sph + ½ cyl). Fit: flat = excess movement → mechanical trauma; steep = too little movement → hypoxia/edema. Soft lens diameter ≈ HVID (11.7 mm) + 2 mm. Toric prism ballast ~1–1.5Δ base down. Materials/history: PMMA = non-gas-permeable (Touhy 1947). Soft HEMA = Wichterle (FDA 1971). Silicone hydrogel carries O₂ through the silicone matrix, not water. Complications: microbial keratitis (infiltrate + staining + pain) is the emergency — Pseudomonas most common; Acanthamoeba with water exposure/extended wear. Polymegethism = irreversible hypoxia marker. GPC = deposits + upper-tarsus friction. BAK is toxic with soft lenses. Monovision: dominant eye = distance. Ortho-K : temporary corneal reshaping + myopia control, up to ~−6.00 D / −2.00 D. Trap: a −6.50 spectacle becomes −6.50 as a CL. No — vertex correction makes it ~−6.00 (less minus). Trap: PMMA is gas permeable. No — PMMA is non-permeable; RGPs use different polymers. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject D strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"E.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"E\",\"label\":\"Ocular Disease — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/E-Ocular-Disease-and-Emergencies/E-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"This note covers the disease of everything around the eyeball: the bony orbit, the eyelids, and the lacrimal (tear) system. Work front to back and outside in: Orbit: is the globe the wrong size, pushed forward (proptosis), or infected (cellulitis)? Eyelids: is the lid drooping (ptosis), turned in (entropion) or out (ectropion), lumpy (stye vs chalazion), or growing a tumor? Lacrimal: is the gland inflamed, or is the drain blocked (epiphora, dacryocystitis)? Teaching angle: most of this note is paired opposites. Hordeolum vs chalazion, entropion vs ectropion, episcleritis vs scleritis. Learn the pairs, not the single facts, because the board tests the distinction.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Why does orbital cellulitis come from the sinuses? The ethmoid sinus sits right against the medial orbital wall, separated only by paper-thin bone (lamina papyracea). Infection crosses easily, so ethmoiditis is the most common cause. The orbital septum is the firewall: infection in front of it (preseptal) is milder; behind it (orbital) threatens vision and the brain. Why is a stye tender but a chalazion is not? A hordeolum (stye) is an acute bacterial abscess, so it is hot, red, and painful. A chalazion is a chronic sterile lipogranuloma: the meibomian gland blocked and the trapped lipid triggered a slow granuloma. No bug, no acute inflammation, no pain. Why does the lower lid droop outward (ectropion) in CN VII palsy? The orbicularis muscle (closed by CN VII) holds the lid against the globe. Paralyze it and the lid falls away, exposing the eye. The same logic explains lagophthalmos (cannot close) and exposure keratopathy. Why does blood on pressure over the lacrimal sac suggest a tumor? A simple infected sac regurgitates pus. Blood means something is eroding vessels, classically a squamous cell carcinoma of the sac. The character of the regurgitation changes the diagnosis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Proptosis Greek pro = forward + ptosis = falling Forward globe displacement in any direction; pathologic beyond 21 mm Exophthalmos ex = out + ophthalmos = eye Anterior globe protrusion specifically; Graves disease is the #1 cause Buphthalmos Greek bous = ox + ophthalmos = eye (\\\"ox eye\\\") Enlarged infant globe from congenital glaucoma stretching cornea/sclera Ptosis Greek = falling Drooping of the upper lid Entropion en = in + trope = turning Lid margin turns inward; lashes abrade the cornea Ectropion ec = out + trope = turning Lid margin turns outward; causes exposure and epiphora Lagophthalmos Greek lagos = hare + ophthalmos Incomplete lid closure (\\\"hare's eye\\\"); leads to exposure keratopathy Hordeolum Latin hordeum = barley Acute, tender lid-margin abscess (stye) Chalazion Greek chalaza = hailstone Chronic, non-tender meibomian lipogranuloma Madarosis Greek madaros = bald Loss of lashes/brows, classic for ulcerative blepharitis Epiphora Greek = sudden flow of tears Tear overflow from drainage block or reflex tearing Dacryoadenitis dakryon = tear + aden = gland Lacrimal gland inflammation; S-shaped ptosis Dacryocystitis dakryon + kystis = sac Lacrimal sac infection; medial canthal swelling Distichiasis di = two + stichos = row Accessory second row of eyelashes Symblepharon syn = together + blepharon = lid Adhesion between palpebral and bulbar conjunctiva\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-the-details-1-orbit-and-globe\",\"heading\":\"1. Orbit and Globe\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Globe size anomalies: Condition Meaning Anophthalmos No globe develops Microphthalmos Abnormally small globe Phthisis bulbi Shrunken end-stage globe Buphthalmos Enlarged globe from congenital glaucoma (raised IOP stretches the infant cornea/sclera) Hypertelorism Orbits set too far apart Telecanthus Wide medial canthi only (orbits normal) Exophthalmos / Proptosis (globe protrusion; proptosis = any direction, exophthalmos = anterior). Pathologic beyond 21 mm . Active: thyroid (Graves), the most common cause of both unilateral and bilateral proptosis in adults. Intermittent: orbital varices, worse with Valsalva. Pulsating: carotid-cavernous fistula. Unilateral: usually neoplastic. Bilateral: usually systemic (thyroid, leukemia, neuroblastoma). Orbital cellulitis: most common cause ethmoiditis . Treat with incision/drainage + massive antibiotics. Distinguish from milder preseptal cellulitis (anterior to septum). Orbital tumors: most common benign = cavernous hemangioma ; most common primary malignancy in children = rhabdomyosarcoma (peak 7 to 8 years).\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-the-details-2-eyelids\",\"heading\":\"2. Eyelids\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Congenital: coloboma (upper nasal), epicanthus (medial fold, common in Asians), distichiasis (extra lash row), symblepharon (conjunctival adhesion), blepharophimosis (short fissure + ptosis + telecanthus). Ptosis types: Type Cause Clue Neurogenic CN III palsy or Horner's Horner triad: ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis Myogenic Myasthenia gravis Fatiguable; positive Tensilon test Aponeurotic Levator disinsertion Most common adult; high crease Mechanical Tumor/scar weight Lid heaviness Congenital Levator maldevelopment Absent crease; amblyopia risk Inflammatory: Condition Key Squamous blepharitis Dry seborrheic scales Ulcerative blepharitis Staph; crusted ulcers, madarosis (lash loss) Meibomitis Posterior; foamy tears Hordeolum (stye) Acute, tender abscess (external Zeis/Moll, internal meibomian) Chalazion Chronic, non-tender lipogranuloma of meibomian gland Position abnormalities: Entropion (turns in, lashes scratch): cicatricial (trachoma), spastic (elderly), atonic, congenital. Ectropion (turns out, exposure): senile/atonic (most common), cicatricial, paralytic ( CN VII ). Lagophthalmos: incomplete closure → exposure keratopathy. Orbicularis: myokymia (benign twitch, stress), essential blepharospasm (forceful bilateral closure, treat with botulinum). Eyelid tumors: basal cell carcinoma is the most common malignancy (pearly margin, lower lid). Xanthelasma (yellow lipid, hyperlipidemia), keratoacanthoma (volcano crater, involutes), milia, syringoma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-the-details-3-lacrimal-system\",\"heading\":\"3. Lacrimal System\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Gland disease: Acute dacryoadenitis: painful upper-outer swelling, S-shaped ptosis ; bacterial or viral (mumps, EBV). Chronic dacryoadenitis: painless; sarcoid, TB, lymphoma. Mikulicz syndrome: bilateral painless lacrimal AND salivary gland enlargement. Tumors: benign = pleomorphic adenoma ; malignant = adenoid cystic carcinoma (perineural invasion, painful, poor prognosis). Drainage (epiphora = tear overflow): Jones I: fluorescein recovered from the nose = patent system. Jones II: if Jones I negative, irrigate; dye recovered = partial block above the sac; clear saline = block at/below the sac. Dacryocystitis (sac infection): Congenital: bilateral, newborn, pneumococcus, mucocele of NLD. Probe at 12 to 18 months if massage fails. Adult: unilateral, medial canthal swelling, pus regurgitation. Treat chronic with DCR (dacryocystorhinostomy). Blood on pressure over the sac = suspect squamous cell carcinoma of the sac.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Pathologic proptosis > 21 mm Anterior protrusion beyond this is abnormal Normal exophthalmometry (Hertel) 12–21 mm Side-to-side asymmetry > 2 mm is abnormal Rhabdomyosarcoma peak age 7–8 years Most common primary pediatric orbital malignancy Congenital NLD probing 12–18 months Probe if conservative massage fails by this age Cavernous hemangioma adults Most common benign orbital tumor overall\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"ORBITAL SEPTUM — THE FIREWALL ───────────────────────────── Anterior to septum → PRESEPTAL cellulitis (lid swelling, milder) Posterior to septum → ORBITAL cellulitis (proptosis, ↓ EOM , ↓ vision, brain risk) └── #1 source: ETHMOIDITIS (lamina papyracea) LACRIMAL DRAINAGE — where tears exit ──────────────────────────────────── PUNCTUM → CANALICULUS → common canaliculus → lacrimal SAC → NLD → nose (inferior meatus) Jones I: dye reaches nose → system PATENT Jones II: irrigate after negative I → dye recovered = partial block ABOVE sac → clear saline = block AT/ BELOW sac\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Buphthalmos = big infant eye = congenital glaucoma. Horner triad = ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis (small pupil, not big). Stye = Sore (tender, acute). Chalazion = Chronic, Cool (non-tender). EntropioN = iN; ectropion = out (ectropion with CN VII). Orbital cellulitis = Ethmoiditis. BCC = most common lid malignancy (pearly, lower lid). Jones I to the nose; Jones II to localize. Blood from the sac = sac tumor.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Horner's causes a dilated pupil. Miosis (small). The dilated-pupil ptosis is CN III palsy. chalazion is a painful infection. It is a chronic, non-tender, sterile lipogranuloma. The painful one is the hordeolum. ectropion scratches the cornea with lashes. That is entropion (turns in). Ectropion turns out and causes exposure. the most common cause of proptosis is a tumor. Usually thyroid (Graves) is most common overall; unilateral proptosis is the one that is more often neoplastic. pus regurgitating from the sac means cancer. No, pus = infection; blood is the tumor sign.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Enlarged infant globe Buphthalmos (congenital glaucoma) Most common orbital cellulitis cause Ethmoiditis Most common pediatric orbital malignancy Rhabdomyosarcoma Fatiguable ptosis, positive Tensilon Myasthenia gravis Most common adult ptosis Aponeurotic Tender lid abscess Hordeolum (stye) Non-tender lid granuloma Chalazion Ectropion from nerve palsy CN VII Most common lid malignancy Basal cell carcinoma Most common malignant lacrimal gland tumor Adenoid cystic carcinoma Chronic dacryocystitis surgery DCR Blood from lacrimal sac Sac tumor (SCC)\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"1. An infant has an enlarged, cloudy cornea and tearing. The enlarged globe is termed: A. Microphthalmos B. Buphthalmos C. Phthisis bulbi D. Anophthalmos Answer B. Buphthalmos. Raised IOP from congenital glaucoma stretches the infant's distensible cornea and sclera, enlarging the globe. 2. A painful, tender, red nodule erupts at the lid margin over a few days. Most likely: A. Chalazion B. Hordeolum C. Xanthelasma D. Basal cell carcinoma Answer B. Hordeolum (stye). Acute, tender bacterial abscess. A chalazion is chronic and non-tender. 3. A patient with Bell's palsy (CN VII) develops a lower lid that falls away from the globe. This is: A. Entropion B. Ectropion C. Lagophthalmos only D. Distichiasis Answer B. Ectropion (paralytic). Orbicularis paralysis lets the lid evert. Lagophthalmos (incomplete closure) often coexists, but the everted lid is ectropion. 4. Fluorescein placed in the eye is not recovered from the nose; after saline irrigation the dye is recovered. This indicates: A. A fully patent system B. Partial obstruction above the sac C. Complete block below the sac D. Lacrimal gland tumor Answer B. A negative Jones I with dye recovered on Jones II irrigation indicates partial (functional) obstruction proximal to the sac. 5. Chronic dacryocystitis with blood regurgitating on pressure over the sac should raise suspicion for: A. Pneumococcal infection B. Squamous cell carcinoma of the sac C. Allergic reaction D. Canalicular stenosis Answer B. Pus suggests infection; blood suggests a sac tumor, classically squamous cell carcinoma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1-01-orbit-adnexa-eyelids-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"E1 — Orbit, Adnexa, and Eyelids\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump List the five ptosis types with their cause and one clue each. No looking. Drill 2 — Paired Opposites Write two-column comparisons from memory: hordeolum vs chalazion, entropion vs ectropion. Drill 3 — Match For ethmoiditis, CN VII palsy, congenital glaucoma, and Graves disease, name the orbital/adnexal condition each produces. Drill 4 — Lacrimal Logic Write the Jones I and Jones II interpretations, then the difference between congenital and adult dacryocystitis. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a chalazion is painless but a stye hurts. Use the words \\\"abscess\\\" and \\\"granuloma.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Paired Opposites 3rd 3 days Match 4th 1 week Lacrimal Logic Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"The anterior segment is everything from the conjunctiva to the lens. Walk the light path inward: Conjunctiva: the four conjunctivitides (bacterial, viral, allergic, chlamydial), and the growths (pinguecula, pterygium). Sclera/episclera: episcleritis (mild) vs scleritis (severe, systemic). Cornea: keratoconus, the iron lines and pigments, dry eye, the herpes keratitides. Iris/pupil/anterior chamber: the named pupils (Adie, Argyll-Robertson, Horner, RAPD), and the injections (conjunctival vs ciliary). Glaucoma: POAG vs PACG, the secondary glaucomas, and the drug ladder. Lens: ectopia lentis, the cataract types, and surgery. Anterior uveitis: cells, flare, keratic precipitates, and the systemic links. Teaching angle: the anterior segment is a museum of comparison tables. Master each two-column pair and you have most of the marks.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Why does a pterygium threaten vision but a pinguecula does not? A pinguecula is a degenerative yellow deposit that stops at the limbus. A pterygium is a fibrovascular wing that crosses the limbus, destroys Bowman's layer , and drags onto the visual axis, inducing astigmatism. Crossing the limbus is the whole difference. Why is ciliary (circumcorneal) injection a danger sign but conjunctival injection usually is not? Conjunctival injection is superficial vessels reacting to surface irritation (conjunctivitis, allergy). Ciliary flush is the deep perilimbal vessels, which engorge only when the cornea, iris, or angle is in trouble: keratitis, uveitis, or acute glaucoma. Deep vessels, deep disease. Why does the pupil go mid-dilated and fixed in acute angle-closure? The pressure spike paralyzes the iris sphincter, and the iris, jammed against the trabecular meshwork, sits mid-dilated. That mid-dilated, non-reactive pupil with a cloudy cornea and a hard, painful eye is the emergency picture. Why does nuclear sclerosis give \\\"second sight\\\"? The hardening nucleus raises the lens index of refraction, adding minus power (myopic shift). A presbyope can suddenly read without glasses, briefly, before the cataract clouds vision. The same index change that helps near vision will eventually blur everything.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Pterygium Greek pterygion = little wing Fibrovascular wing crossing the limbus; destroys Bowman's layer Pinguecula Latin pinguis = fat Yellow degenerative limbal deposit; does not cross the limbus Ciliary flush perilimbal \\\"flush\\\" Deep violet circumcorneal injection = keratitis/uveitis/acute glaucoma Keratoconus kerato = cornea + konos = cone Bilateral non-inflammatory conical thinning Hypopyon hypo = under + pyon = pus Layered white cells in the anterior chamber Keratic precipitates inflammatory cells on endothelium Mutton-fat = granulomatous; fine stellate = viral/Fuchs Synechiae Greek synecheia = continuity Iris adhesions: anterior (to cornea) or posterior (to lens) Rubeosis iridis Latin rubeo = redden Iris neovascularization; closed angle without pupillary block Ectopia lentis ec = out + topos = place Lens dislocation; Marfan up, homocystinuria down Phacolytic phakos = lens + lysis = loosening Open-angle glaucoma from leaked hypermature lens protein Phacomorphic phakos + morphe = shape Closed-angle glaucoma from an intumescent swollen lens Arcus senilis Latin = bow of old age Peripheral stromal cholesterol ring with a lucid interval\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-conjunctiva\",\"heading\":\"Conjunctiva\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Pinguecula vs pterygium: pinguecula = yellow limbal deposit, does not cross the limbus. Pterygium = wing crossing the cornea, destroys Bowman's layer , Stocker iron line ahead of the head, treat by excision. The four conjunctivitides: Feature Bacterial Viral Allergic Chlamydial/Trachoma Discharge Mucopurulent Watery Stringy mucoid Mucopurulent Cells Neutrophils (PMN) Lymphocytes Eosinophils Lymphocytes + follicles Follicles/papillae Small papillae Large follicles Cobblestone papillae Upper tarsal follicles, pannus Cause Staph, Strep, H. flu Adenovirus, herpes IgE Chlamydia trachomatis Treatment Topical antibiotic Self-limiting Antihistamine, mast-cell stabilizer Tetracycline + azithromycin Trachoma (Chlamydia A, B, C; leading infectious cause of world blindness): stages I-A-C-S (Inflammation follicular → Intense → Arlt's line scarring → Cicatricial entropion/trichiasis). Pannus at the upper limbus ; Herbert pits when limbal follicles heal. Vernal keratoconjunctivitis: young males, seasonal, cobblestone papillae , Trantas dots, shield ulcer . GPC: contact-lens related, upper tarsal giant papillae. Phlyctenular: hypersensitivity to TB/Staph antigen, limbal nodule. Injection compare: conjunctival (peripheral, bright red, moves, blanches with epinephrine, = surface disease) vs ciliary flush (perilimbal, violet, fixed, does not blanch, = uveitis/keratitis/acute glaucoma).\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-sclera\",\"heading\":\"Sclera\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Episcleritis vs scleritis: episcleritis is superficial, mild/no pain, benign (RA, gout). Scleritis is deep, severe boring pain , often bilateral, linked to PTB, RA, SLE , and can cause secondary glaucoma. Staphyloma = uveal-lined scleral ectasia (posterior type with high myopia). Blue sclera: osteogenesis imperfecta, Marfan, Ehlers-Danlos.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-cornea\",\"heading\":\"Cornea\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Keratoconus (bilateral non-inflammatory conical thinning): Fleischer ring (iron at cone base, earliest), Munson's sign (V-lid on downgaze), scissors reflex on retinoscopy, Vogt's striae, oil-droplet reflex. Treat with RGP lens, crosslinking, or penetrating keratoplasty. Opacity grades: nebula (faint) < macula (grey) < leukoma (dense white). Iron lines (all epithelial) \\\"HuFFeStO\\\": Hu dson-Stahli (aging, lower third), F leischer (keratoconus), F erry (next to bleb), Sto cker (ahead of pterygium). Corneal pigments by layer: Pigment Layer Condition Iron lines Epithelium (above) Kayser-Fleischer ring Descemet's Wilson's disease Krukenberg spindle Endothelium Pigment dispersion syndrome Argyrosis (silver) / Chrysiasis (gold) Stroma Silver / gold therapy Pigment dispersion triad: Krukenberg spindle + iris transillumination defects + Sampaolesi line → pigmentary (open-angle) glaucoma. Dry eye (KCS): aqueous deficiency ( Sjogren's ), mucin deficiency (vitamin A, Stevens-Johnson, trachoma), lipid deficiency (MGD). Tests: Schirmer <10 mm/5 min (aqueous), TBUT <10 sec (stability), rose bengal/lissamine (devitalized cells). Arcus senilis: peripheral stromal cholesterol with a lucid interval; if young ( arcus juvenilis ), screen for hyperlipidemia. Band keratopathy: calcium in Bowman's (chronic uveitis, hypercalcemia); treat with EDTA chelation. Herpes simplex keratitis: recurrent dendritic ulcer (terminal bulbs, stains with fluorescein and rose bengal); disciform = immune stromal edema. Treat with topical acyclovir/trifluridine; never topical steroids on epithelial disease . Herpes zoster ophthalmicus: V1 reactivation; Hutchinson's sign (nose-tip vesicles = nasociliary = high ocular risk).\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-iris-pupils-anterior-chamber\",\"heading\":\"Iris, Pupils, Anterior Chamber\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Named pupils: Pupil Finding Cause Test Adie's tonic Large, sluggish Ciliary ganglion (benign) Constricts to 0.1% pilocarpine Argyll-Robertson Small, irregular, accommodates but no light reaction Neurosyphilis (pretectal) \\\"Prostitute's pupil\\\" Marcus Gunn (RAPD) Dilates on swinging light Optic nerve/severe retinal disease Swinging flashlight Horner's Ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis Sympathetic lesion Cocaine (no dilation) Both Adie's and Argyll-Robertson \\\"accommodate but do not react\\\"; Adie's is peripheral/unilateral/benign, Argyll-Robertson is central/bilateral/syphilis. Iris bombe (posterior synechiae → pupillary block → iris bows forward → closed angle with pupillary block; treat laser iridotomy) vs rubeosis iridis (neovascular, closed angle without pupillary block; diabetes/CRVO; treat anti-VEGF/PRP). Iridodialysis: iris root torn by blunt trauma, D-shaped pupil.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-glaucoma\",\"heading\":\"Glaucoma\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Normal IOP 10-21 mmHg ; aqueous drains trabecular (80%) and uveoscleral (20%). Feature POAG PACG Onset Gradual, painless (\\\"silent thief\\\") Sudden, painful (emergency) Angle Open Closed Pupil Normal Mid-dilated, fixed Cornea Clear Cloudy/edematous Treatment Medical Surgical (laser iridotomy) Drug ladder \\\"MAPCO + B\\\": Miotics (open trabeculum), Alpha-2 agonists (less production + outflow), Prostaglandins (uveoscleral, first-line), CAIs (less production), Osmotics (acute), Beta blockers (less production). Detail in G4-01-Therapeutic-Ophthalmic-Agents . Secondary glaucomas: rubeosis (closed, no block), iris bombe (closed, with block), phacolytic (open, leaking hypermature lens protein), phacomorphic (closed, swollen lens), pigmentary (open), steroid (open), uveitic. Workup: tonometry, ophthalmoscopy (C/D >0.6 or asymmetry >0.2), perimetry (arcuate/nasal step early), gonioscopy, pachymetry (thin <520 µm = risk).\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-lens-and-cataract\",\"heading\":\"Lens and Cataract\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Ectopia lentis: Marfan = UP (superotemporal, FBN-1, aortic aneurysm), Homocystinuria = DOWN (inferonasal, thromboembolism risk), Weill-Marchesani = spherophakia. Cataract types: nuclear sclerosis (second sight/myopic shift), cortical (spokes), posterior subcapsular (most common age-related, most disabling, steroid-linked, near worse than distance), diabetic (snowflake, progresses in 72 h), galactosemia (oil droplet, reversible), traumatic (rosette). Maturation: immature → intumescent (phacomorphic risk) → mature → hypermature/Morgagnian (phacolytic risk) → after-cataract (treat YAG capsulotomy ). Surgery: ICCE (whole lens, no capsule) / ECCE (keep posterior capsule) / phacoemulsification (ultrasound, keep posterior capsule). Aphakia = +10 to +12 D hyperopia ; IOL power from biometry .\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-the-details-anterior-uveitis\",\"heading\":\"Anterior Uveitis\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Symptoms: photophobia, pain, blurred vision. Signs: ciliary flush, cells and flare, keratic precipitates (fine stellate = viral/Fuchs; mutton-fat = granulomatous sarcoid/TB/VKH), posterior synechiae, Busacca/Koeppe nodules, hypopyon (HLA-B27/Behcet, endophthalmitis). Systemic links: HLA-B27 (ankylosing spondylitis, Reiter, psoriatic, IBD), sarcoidosis (mutton-fat, bilateral), JIA (chronic, ANA+, asymptomatic). Treat with topical steroid + cycloplegic (prevent synechiae). Fuchs heterochromic cyclitis: chronic unilateral, lighter iris on affected side, fine KP, no posterior synechiae , causes cataract; does not respond to steroids.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Normal IOP 10–21 mmHg Trabecular 80% + uveoscleral 20% outflow Schirmer test < 10 mm / 5 min Aqueous tear deficiency Tear break-up time (TBUT) < 10 sec Tear film instability Cup-to-disc ratio > 0.6 or asymmetry > 0.2 Glaucomatous optic neuropathy Central corneal thickness thin < 520 µm Independent glaucoma risk factor Aphakic correction +10 to +12 D Hyperopia after lens removal Diabetic cataract progresses in 72 h Snowflake type, acute\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"RED EYE — surface vs deep ───────────────────────── CONJUNCTIVAL injection → surface (conjunctivitis/allergy); bright, mobile, blanches CILIARY flush → DEEP danger: keratitis / uveitis / acute glaucoma; violet, fixed GLAUCOMA — the angle splits the diagnosis ───────────────────────────────────────── OPEN angle → POAG (silent, gradual) + phacolytic / pigmentary / steroid CLOSED angle → PACG (acute emergency) + phacomorphic / iris bombe / rubeosis CATARACT MATURATION ─────────────────── Immature → INTUMESCENT (phacomorphic risk) → Mature → HYPERMATURE / Morgagnian (phacolytic risk) → after-cataract → YAG capsulotomy\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Pterygium crosses the limbus and kills Bowman's; pinguecula does not. Ciliary flush = deep danger (uveitis, keratitis, acute glaucoma). Iron lines all epithelial: \\\"HuFFeStO.\\\" Kayser-Fleischer = Descemet = Wilson's. Keratoconus earliest sign = Fleischer ring. Marfan UP, Homocystinuria DOWN. Nuclear cataract = second sight (myopic shift). PSC = most common, near worse. PhacoMorphic = closed (swollen); phacoLytic = open (leaking). Mutton-fat KP = granulomatous; hypopyon = HLA-B27/Behcet. Adie = 0.1% pilocarpine; Horner = ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Kayser-Fleischer ring is iron in the epithelium. It is copper in Descemet's (Wilson's disease). pinguecula destroys Bowman's layer. The pterygium does; pinguecula stays at the limbus. Marfan dislocates the lens downward. Up (superotemporal). Homocystinuria goes down. topical steroids are good for herpes dendritic keratitis. Dangerous. Steroids on epithelial herpes worsen it; use antivirals. PACG is treated medically first. It is a surgical emergency (laser iridotomy); drops only temporize. phacolytic glaucoma is closed-angle. It is open-angle (protein blocks the meshwork); phacomorphic is the closed one. the most common age-related cataract is nuclear. Common, but posterior subcapsular is described as the most common age-related and most visually disabling here.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Growth that destroys Bowman's Pterygium World's leading infectious blindness Trachoma (Chlamydia) Deep perilimbal injection Ciliary flush (danger) Earliest keratoconus sign Fleischer ring Copper ring in Descemet's Kayser-Fleischer (Wilson's) Schirmer cutoff / TBUT cutoff <10 mm / <10 sec Never on epithelial herpes Topical steroids Marfan / Homocystinuria lens shift Up / Down Second sight cataract Nuclear sclerosis Open-angle lens glaucoma Phacolytic Granulomatous KP Mutton-fat Anterior uveitis treatment Topical steroid + cycloplegic\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"1. A red eye has a violet ring of injection around the cornea that does not blanch with epinephrine. This points to: A. Allergic conjunctivitis B. A deep process (uveitis, keratitis, or acute glaucoma) C. Subconjunctival hemorrhage D. Pinguecula Answer B. Ciliary (circumcorneal) flush reflects engorged deep perilimbal vessels, seen in uveitis, keratitis, or acute angle-closure. Surface conditions give bright, mobile conjunctival injection that blanches. 2. A green-gold ring is found in Descemet's membrane. The systemic disease is: A. Hemochromatosis B. Wilson's disease C. Diabetes D. Gout Answer B. Wilson's disease. The Kayser-Fleischer ring is copper deposition in Descemet's membrane in hepatolenticular degeneration. 3. A tall patient with long fingers and an aortic aneurysm has a lens dislocated superotemporally. The diagnosis and shift are: A. Homocystinuria, down B. Marfan syndrome, up C. Weill-Marchesani, spherophakia D. Trauma, variable Answer B. Marfan, up. Marfan dislocates the lens superotemporally (up); homocystinuria dislocates it inferonasally (down). 4. A hypermature cataract leaks lens protein, macrophages clog the trabecular meshwork, and IOP rises with an open angle. This is: A. Phacomorphic glaucoma B. Phacolytic glaucoma C. Rubeosis iridis D. Iris bombe Answer B. Phacolytic glaucoma (open angle). Phacomorphic is the closed-angle type from a swollen intumescent lens. 5. Mutton-fat keratic precipitates on the corneal endothelium indicate which kind of uveitis? A. Viral B. Fuchs heterochromic C. Granulomatous (sarcoid, TB) D. Allergic Answer C. Granulomatous. Large greasy mutton-fat KP suggest sarcoidosis, TB, VKH. Fine stellate KP suggest viral or Fuchs.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2-01-anterior-segment-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"E2 — Anterior Segment Disease\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Reproduce the four-conjunctivitis table (discharge, cells, follicles/papillae, cause, treatment). No looking. Drill 2 — Compare Pairs Write from memory: episcleritis vs scleritis, POAG vs PACG, phacomorphic vs phacolytic, pinguecula vs pterygium. Drill 3 — Iron and Pigment List the four iron lines (\\\"HuFFeStO\\\") and the four corneal pigments by layer. Drill 4 — Cataract Cards Match each clue to its cataract: second sight, snowflake, oil droplet, most disabling, rosette. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why ciliary flush is more worrying than conjunctival injection. Use \\\"deep vessels.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Compare Pairs 3rd 3 days Iron and Pigment 4th 1 week Cataract Cards Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"The posterior segment is the vitreous, retina, choroid, and optic nerve. The board hits five big themes: Vitreoretinal interface: PVD and the three retinal detachments. Vascular retina: diabetic and hypertensive retinopathy, and the artery/vein occlusions. Macula: age-related macular degeneration. Inherited retina: retinitis pigmentosa. Optic nerve: papilledema vs optic neuritis, and the ischemic neuropathies. Teaching angle: most posterior-segment items are recognized by a single signature image. Cherry-red spot (CRAO), blood-and-thunder fundus (CRVO), bone spicules (RP), cotton-wool spots (ischemia). Anchor on the picture, then reason out the cause.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Why is there a cherry-red spot in CRAO? The inner retina goes white and opaque when its artery is blocked, but the fovea is thin and fed by the choroid underneath , so the intact red choroid shows through the pale surroundings as a cherry-red dot. The spot is not diseased tissue; it is the one healthy window. Why do diabetic vessels leak and then grow? High glucose kills pericytes, so capillary walls weaken (microaneurysms, hemorrhages, exudates). As capillaries close, the retina starves, releases VEGF, and grows fragile new vessels (proliferative disease). Leak first, then grow, all driven by ischemia, which is why we destroy ischemic retina with laser to cut the VEGF signal. Why does optic neuritis lose vision fast and hurt, while papilledema does not? Optic neuritis is inflammation in the nerve, so the fibers stop conducting (early, severe vision loss) and the inflamed sheath hurts on eye movement. Papilledema is back-pressure from raised intracranial pressure pushing on the disc from behind; the fibers still conduct, so vision is spared early. One is a nerve problem, the other a plumbing problem. Why must giant cell arteritis be treated before the biopsy result returns? The inflamed arteries can occlude the second eye within days, causing permanent bilateral blindness. Steroids are started immediately on suspicion (raised ESR/CRP, jaw claudication, age >55); the biopsy can be done up to a couple of weeks later. You treat the risk, not the confirmation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"PVD posterior vitreous detachment Age-related vitreous separation; floaters + Weiss ring Shafer's sign \\\"tobacco dust\\\" Pigment in anterior vitreous = retinal break until proven otherwise Rhegmatogenous Greek rhegma = break/rent Retinal detachment caused by a full-thickness break Microaneurysm micro + aneurysma = dilation Earliest visible sign of diabetic retinopathy Cotton-wool spot nerve fibre layer infarct Ischemic swelling of axons, not an exudate IRMA intraretinal microvascular abnormality Shunt vessels in ischemic retina; severe NPDR marker Drusen German = nodule Sub-RPE deposits; hallmark of dry ARMD Metamorphopsia meta = change + morphe = shape Wavy distortion on Amsler grid; early CNV warning Nyctalopia Greek nyx = night + alaos = blind Night blindness; first symptom of retinitis pigmentosa Bone-spicule pigment perivascular pigment migration Classic mid-peripheral sign of retinitis pigmentosa Papilledema papilla + oidema = swelling Bilateral disc swelling from raised intracranial pressure RAPD relative afferent pupillary defect Marcus Gunn pupil; optic nerve or massive retinal disease\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-vitreous-and-retinal-detachment\",\"heading\":\"Vitreous and Retinal Detachment\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"PVD: age-related vitreous liquefaction and separation. Floaters + photopsia; Weiss ring = detached peripapillary ring. Tobacco dust (Shafer's sign) = pigment in anterior vitreous = retinal break until proven otherwise. Retinal detachment (three types): Type Mechanism Clue Treatment Rhegmatogenous A break lets fluid under the retina Horseshoe tear; photopsia + floaters + curtain Scleral buckle or PPV + gas Tractional Fibrous bands pull the retina Diabetes, ROP, sickle; taut, no break PPV Exudative Fluid from choroid, no break Shifting fluid; VKH, malignant HTN Treat the cause Breaks: horseshoe tear (traction, highest RD risk), round hole (atrophic, low risk), dialysis (ora serrata, young trauma). Progression: flashes → floaters → curtain.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-diabetic-retinopathy\",\"heading\":\"Diabetic Retinopathy\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Type 1: appears 5 to 7 years after onset. Type 2: may be present at diagnosis. NPDR signs: microaneurysm (earliest), dot-blot hemorrhage, hard exudate (lipid), cotton-wool spot (NFL infarct), IRMA, venous beading. Severe NPDR \\\"4-2-1 rule\\\": hemorrhages in all 4 quadrants, OR venous beading in 2, OR IRMA in 1. PDR: new vessels (NVD/NVE). Risk: vitreous hemorrhage, tractional RD, neovascular glaucoma. Treat with panretinal photocoagulation + anti-VEGF. Diabetic macular edema: can occur at any stage; CSME within 500 µm of fovea. First-line: intravitreal anti-VEGF.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-hypertensive-retinopathy-keith-wagener-barker\",\"heading\":\"Hypertensive Retinopathy (Keith-Wagener-Barker)\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Grade Finding I Arteriolar narrowing, copper wire II AV nicking (Gunn/Salus), silver wire III Flame hemorrhages, cotton-wool spots, macular star IV Grade III + papilledema = malignant hypertension Macular star = hard exudates in Henle's layer. Elschnig's spots = choroidal infarcts.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-age-related-macular-degeneration\",\"heading\":\"Age-Related Macular Degeneration\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Type Features Treatment Dry (atrophic) Drusen, geographic atrophy; 85 to 90% AREDS2 vitamins Wet (neovascular) Choroidal neovascularization, rapid loss Intravitreal anti-VEGF Soft confluent drusen = higher conversion risk. Amsler grid metamorphopsia = early CNV warning.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-retinal-vascular-occlusions\",\"heading\":\"Retinal Vascular Occlusions\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"CRAO: sudden painless monocular loss, cherry-red spot , retinal whitening, RAPD. Within 4 to 6 h: ocular massage, lower IOP. Rule out giant cell arteritis. Emboli = Hollenhorst plaques. CRVO: \\\" blood and thunder \\\" fundus (diffuse hemorrhages, dilated tortuous veins, disc edema). Ischemic (RAPD, neovascular glaucoma at 3 months ) vs non-ischemic. Treat macular edema with anti-VEGF; PRP if ischemic. BRAO: wedge whitening, Hollenhorst plaque at bifurcation. BRVO: sector hemorrhage at an AV crossing, superotemporal most common.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-retinopathy-of-prematurity\",\"heading\":\"Retinopathy of Prematurity\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Premature, low birth weight, supplemental oxygen. Plus disease (dilation + tortuosity) = active. Stage 5 = total RD with leukocoria. Screen <1500 g or <32 weeks. Treat with laser or anti-VEGF.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-retinitis-pigmentosa\",\"heading\":\"Retinitis Pigmentosa\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Rod-cone dystrophy, rods first . Nyctalopia → ring scotoma → tunnel vision. Signs: bone-spicule pigment , attenuated arterioles, waxy pale disc . ERG: reduced/extinguished rod b-wave. AD (mildest), AR/X-linked (severe). Usher = RP + deafness.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-posterior-uveitis\",\"heading\":\"Posterior Uveitis\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Toxoplasmosis (most common worldwide): \\\" headlight in fog ,\\\" reactivation at edge of old scar. Treat pyrimethamine + sulfadiazine + folinic acid. CMV retinitis (HIV, CD4 <50): \\\" pizza pie \\\" hemorrhage. Treat ganciclovir/foscarnet. Toxocariasis (children, roundworm): granuloma, leukocoria. VKH: panuveitis + vitiligo, poliosis, alopecia, meningismus. High-dose steroids. Sympathetic ophthalmia: bilateral panuveitis after penetrating trauma; injured = exciting eye , fellow = sympathizing eye . Prevent by enucleating a blind injured eye within 10 to 14 days .\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-the-details-optic-nerve\",\"heading\":\"Optic Nerve\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Papilledema vs optic neuritis (papillitis): Feature Papilledema Optic neuritis Laterality Bilateral Unilateral Vision loss Late (blind spot enlarges) Early, severe Pain No Yes (on movement) RAPD Absent Present ICP Raised Normal Optic neuritis: young women, RAPD, central scotoma, red desaturation. Linked to multiple sclerosis (first sign in 25%). IV methylprednisolone speeds recovery (ONTT). NAION: painless, on waking, altitudinal defect, \\\"disc at risk\\\" (small cup), vascular risk factors. AAION / giant cell arteritis: >55 y, headache, jaw claudication , raised ESR/CRP , chalky-white disc. Emergency: immediate high-dose steroids before biopsy. Glaucomatous: cupping, ISNT rule violated , notching, Drance hemorrhage. Traumatic optic neuropathy: RAPD after trauma, optic canal fracture on CT.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Severe NPDR rule 4-2-1 CSME proximity within 500 µm of fovea PRP spots 1200–1600 Neovascular glaucoma after CRVO ~3 months CRAO treatment window 4–6 hours Giant cell arteritis age / ESR >55 / >50 Sympathetic ophthalmia enucleation window 10–14 days ROP screening <1500 g or <32 weeks\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"SIGNATURE FUNDUS PICTURE → DIAGNOSIS ──────────────────────────────────── Cherry-red spot → CRAO (also Tay-Sachs) Blood-and-thunder fundus → CRVO Cotton-wool + macular star → HYPERTENSIVE retinopathy (grade III ) Bone spicules → RETINITIS PIGMENTOSA Headlight in fog → TOXOPLASMOSIS Pizza pie → CMV retinitis DIABETIC RETINOPATHY — leak → starve → grow ─────────────────────────────────────────── NPDR : microaneurysm (earliest) → dot-blot hge + hard exudate → cotton-wool / IRMA / venous beading └── 4-2-1 = SEVERE NPDR PDR : NVD / NVE → vitreous hge / tractional RD / neovascular glaucoma → PRP + anti- VEGF SWOLLEN DISC — which one? ───────────────────────── BILATERAL , painless, vision spared early, ↑ ICP → PAPILLEDEMA UNILATERAL , painful, early vision loss, RAPD → OPTIC NEURITIS (think MS)\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Signature pictures cherry-red = CRAO; blood-and-thunder = CRVO; bone spicules = RP; macular star = HTN grade III; headlight in fog = toxoplasmosis; pizza pie = CMV. Diabetic order leak (microaneurysm) → starve (cotton wool, IRMA) → grow (NVD/NVE). 4-2-1 = severe. PVD floaters + tobacco dust = look for a retinal break. Optic neuritis: unilateral, painful, RAPD, MS. Papilledema: bilateral, painless, raised ICP. GCA = treat first, biopsy later. RP: rods first = night blindness first.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"the cherry-red spot is diseased tissue. It is the healthy choroid-fed fovea showing through pale ischemic retina (CRAO; also Tay-Sachs). papilledema causes early vision loss. Vision is spared early (enlarged blind spot); optic neuritis loses vision early. in giant cell arteritis, wait for biopsy before steroids. Dangerous. Start steroids immediately to protect the second eye. cotton-wool spots are exudates. No. They are nerve fiber layer infarcts (ischemia); hard exudates are lipid. tractional RD has a retinal break. Only rhegmatogenous has a break; tractional and exudative do not. wet ARMD is the common type. Dry is 85 to 90%; wet is the aggressive minority treated with anti-VEGF.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Cherry-red spot, sudden painless loss CRAO Blood-and-thunder fundus CRVO Earliest diabetic sign Microaneurysm Severe NPDR threshold 4-2-1 rule Macular star + papilledema Malignant hypertension Most common ARMD type Dry (atrophic) Wet ARMD first-line Intravitreal anti-VEGF Bone spicules, nyctalopia Retinitis pigmentosa Headlight in fog Toxoplasmosis Unilateral painful loss + RAPD Optic neuritis (think MS) Jaw claudication + chalky disc Giant cell arteritis (AAION) RD with a break Rhegmatogenous\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"1. Sudden painless loss of vision in one eye shows a pale retina with a cherry-red fovea and an RAPD. The diagnosis and first step: A. CRVO; observe B. CRAO; ocular massage and lower IOP, rule out GCA C. Optic neuritis; IV steroids D. Retinal detachment; surgery Answer B. CRAO. The pale retina with cherry-red fovea is classic. Attempt ocular massage and IOP lowering within the window, and exclude giant cell arteritis. 2. A diabetic has hemorrhages in all four quadrants and venous beading in two quadrants, but no new vessels. This is: A. Mild NPDR B. Moderate NPDR C. Severe NPDR (4-2-1) D. Proliferative DR Answer C. Severe NPDR. The 4-2-1 rule is met (4-quadrant hemorrhage and 2-quadrant venous beading). New vessels would make it proliferative. 3. A 30-year-old woman has unilateral vision loss over days, pain on eye movement, red desaturation, and an RAPD. The key systemic association is: A. Diabetes B. Multiple sclerosis C. Hypertension D. Giant cell arteritis Answer B. Multiple sclerosis. This is optic neuritis, the first presentation of MS in about 25% of patients. GCA affects older patients and is painless arteritic ischemia. 4. A 72-year-old man has sudden vision loss, jaw pain when chewing, scalp tenderness, and ESR of 80. The immediate action is: A. Observe and repeat ESR B. Temporal artery biopsy, then treat C. Start high-dose corticosteroids immediately D. Anti-VEGF injection Answer C. Start high-dose corticosteroids immediately. Giant cell arteritis can blind the second eye within days; treat on suspicion and biopsy afterward. 5. Night blindness, bone-spicule pigmentation, and a waxy pale disc with an extinguished rod ERG describe: A. Diabetic retinopathy B. Retinitis pigmentosa C. Age-related macular degeneration D. CRVO Answer B. Retinitis pigmentosa. Rod-first dystrophy: nyctalopia, bone spicules, attenuated vessels, waxy disc, reduced rod b-wave.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3-01-posterior-segment-and-retina-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"E3 — Posterior Segment and Retina\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the three retinal detachment types with mechanism, clue, and whether a break is present. Drill 2 — Picture to Diagnosis Given cherry-red spot, blood-and-thunder, macular star, bone spicules, headlight in fog, name the disease for each. Drill 3 — Diabetic Ladder List the NPDR signs in order and state the 4-2-1 rule from memory. Drill 4 — Optic Disc Compare Reproduce the papilledema vs optic neuritis table (laterality, vision, pain, RAPD, ICP). Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why giant cell arteritis is treated before biopsy. Use \\\"second eye.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Picture to Diagnosis 3rd 3 days Diabetic Ladder 4th 1 week Optic Disc Compare Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"An ocular emergency is a problem where minutes to hours decide whether the eye survives. The disease detail lives in E1 to E3; this note is about recognition and what to do first . Sort emergencies into three tiers: Treat before you even finish the history: chemical burn (irrigate now). Same-hour sight-or-life threats: acute angle-closure, CRAO, giant cell arteritis, open globe, endophthalmitis, orbital cellulitis. Urgent, refer today: retinal detachment, hyphema, blow-out fracture, traumatic optic neuropathy. Teaching angle: for each emergency, lock one trigger sign and one first action. The exam rewards the action, not just the name.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Why is a chemical burn the only injury treated before history and exam? Because the chemical keeps destroying tissue every second it sits on the eye. Irrigation removes the agent and is the single biggest factor in the outcome, so it cannot wait for paperwork. Everything else can pause for a two-minute history; a burning alkali cannot. Why is alkali worse than acid? Acid coagulates surface proteins, and that coagulum forms a barrier that limits how deep it goes. Alkali causes liquefactive necrosis : it dissolves cell membranes and drives deeper and deeper, into the stroma and anterior chamber. No barrier forms, so alkali keeps penetrating. Why does acute angle-closure cause a hard, painful eye with a mid-dilated pupil? The iris jams the drainage angle shut, aqueous cannot leave, and pressure spikes fast. The high pressure paralyzes the sphincter (mid-dilated, fixed pupil) and edemates the cornea (cloudy), while the stretched globe and nausea reflex cause the pain and vomiting. It is a plumbing blockage with a pressure explosion. Why patch nothing and shield a suspected open globe? Any pressure on a ruptured globe can extrude intraocular contents. So you place a rigid shield (not a pad), avoid pressure, give nothing by mouth (possible surgery), and never measure IOP or instill drops that require pressure.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Liquefactive necrosis tissue liquefies Alkali burn mechanism; penetrates deep, worse than acid Coagulative necrosis proteins coagulate Acid burn; the coagulum self-limits depth Seidel test fluorescein streaming Positive = aqueous leak from a full-thickness corneal wound Open globe full-thickness scleral/corneal breach Shield, no pressure, NPO, urgent surgery Hyphema Greek hypo + haima = blood Blood in the anterior chamber after blunt trauma Hypopyon hypo + pyon = pus Layered white cells; endophthalmitis until proven otherwise Siderosis Greek sideros = iron Iron IOFB toxicity; no MRI (ferrous) Chalcosis Greek chalkos = copper Copper IOFB; KF ring + sunflower cataract Enophthalmos en = in + ophthalmos Sunken globe; blow-out floor fracture Commotio retinae Latin = shaking of retina Gray retinal opacification after blunt trauma; usually resolves Vossius ring pigment imprint Ring of iris pigment on the lens after blunt trauma\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-the-details-tier-1-treat-before-history-chemical-burn\",\"heading\":\"Tier 1 — Treat Before History: Chemical Burn\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"The rule: irrigate immediately, before history and exam. Alkali (ammonia, lye, lime): liquefactive necrosis, penetrates deep, worse . Acid: coagulative, self-limiting, except hydrofluoric acid and ammonia, which penetrate like alkali. First actions: topical anesthetic for cooperation → copious irrigation (saline/Ringer's, 30+ min) → double-evert the upper lid to remove particles → check pH, irrigate until pH 7.0 to 7.4 → debride necrotic epithelium. Roper-Hall grading is by corneal clarity and limbal ischemia (the prognostic key); grade IV = opaque cornea, >1/2 limbal ischemia, very poor. Medical: ascorbate and citrate (collagen support, anticollagenase), tetracycline (collagenase inhibitor), topical steroid for the first 7 to 10 days then taper, cycloplegic, daily symblepharon lysis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-the-details-tier-2-same-hour-threats\",\"heading\":\"Tier 2 — Same-Hour Threats\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Acute angle-closure glaucoma: sudden painful red eye, mid-dilated fixed pupil , cloudy cornea, halos, nausea/vomiting, rock-hard globe. First: lower IOP medically (topical beta blocker, alpha-2, pilocarpine to pull the iris open, oral/IV CAI or osmotic), then definitive laser peripheral iridotomy . CRAO: sudden painless monocular loss, cherry-red spot , RAPD. Within 4 to 6 h: ocular massage, lower IOP (anterior chamber paracentesis, IV acetazolamide), consider rebreathing. Always exclude giant cell arteritis. Giant cell arteritis (AAION): >55 y, headache, jaw claudication , scalp tenderness, raised ESR/CRP , chalky-white swollen disc. Immediate high-dose corticosteroids before biopsy to save the second eye. Open globe / penetrating injury: distorted pupil, shallow chamber, prolapsed uvea, positive Seidel. Shield (do not patch), nothing by mouth, no IOP, no pressure, systemic antibiotics, urgent surgery. Intraocular foreign body: Metal Toxicity Signs Note Iron Siderosis Rust iris, heterochromia, b-wave loss No MRI (ferrous) Copper alloy Chalcosis KF ring + sunflower cataract Less toxic than iron Pure copper Acute, endophthalmitis-like Violent reaction Best imaging: CT (axial + coronal) . Endophthalmitis: post-surgical or post-trauma; pain, hypopyon , decreasing vision, vitritis. Intravitreal antibiotics (and vitreous tap); emergency. Orbital cellulitis: proptosis, painful restricted motility, fever (vs the painless, full-motility preseptal). Most common cause ethmoiditis . IV antibiotics + drainage; CT to exclude abscess.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-the-details-tier-3-urgent-refer-today\",\"heading\":\"Tier 3 — Urgent, Refer Today\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Retinal detachment: photopsia → floaters → curtain/shadow ; tobacco dust signals a break. Refer for buckle/PPV. (Detail in E3-01-Posterior-Segment-and-Retina .) Blow-out orbital floor fracture: blunt force, infraorbital nerve numbness , diplopia on up/down gaze, enophthalmos, orbital emphysema. Best imaging CT coronal . No nose blowing ; surgery if >1/3 floor, persistent diplopia, or enophthalmos >2 mm (within ~2 weeks). Hyphema: blood in the anterior chamber after blunt trauma. Risk: rebleed (days 3 to 5) and IOP rise. Rest, head elevation, shield, avoid aspirin; screen for sickle cell (worse outcomes). 8-ball = total hyphema. Other blunt findings: Vossius ring (lens pigment imprint), traumatic mydriasis, iridodialysis (D-pupil), angle recession (late glaucoma), commotio retinae (gray retina, resolves), choroidal rupture. Shaken baby syndrome: <2 y, bilateral retinal hemorrhages + subdural hemorrhage. Child abuse, mandatory reporting. Radiation: UV photokeratitis (welding, snow blindness) heals in 24 to 48 h (cool compress, NSAID); infrared = glassblower's cataract.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Irrigate until pH 7.0–7.4 Chemical irrigation duration 30+ minutes CRAO treatment window 4–6 hours GCA age / ESR >55 / >50 Hyphema rebleed window days 3–5 Blow-out surgery threshold >1/3 floor, enophthalmos >2 mm Shaken baby age <2 years Sympathetic ophthalmia enucleation 10–14 days\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"EMERGENCY TRIAGE — speed decides the eye ───────────────────────────────────────── TIER 1 act before history: Chemical burn → IRRIGATE NOW (alkali > acid) TIER 2 same-hour sight/life threat: Acute angle-closure → lower IOP → laser IRIDOTOMY CRAO (4–6 h) → ocular massage + lower IOP → rule out GCA Giant cell arteritis → STEROIDS before biopsy Open globe → SHIELD (never patch) → NPO → surgery Endophthalmitis → INTRAVITREAL antibiotics Orbital cellulitis → IV antibiotics + CT TIER 3 refer today: Retinal detachment / Hyphema / Blow-out fracture / Traumatic optic neuropathy ALKALI vs ACID ────────────── ALKALI → liquefactive necrosis → penetrates DEEP → worse ACID → coagulative necrosis → self-limiting (except HF acid + ammonia)\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Chemical burn: irrigate FIRST, history later. Alkali > acid (liquefactive vs coagulative). Acute angle-closure: hard, painful, mid-dilated, cloudy. Lower IOP then iridotomy. CRAO: cherry-red, 4 to 6 h, rule out GCA. GCA: treat before biopsy (save the second eye). Open globe: shield, don't patch; nothing by mouth. Ferrous IOFB: no MRI. Endophthalmitis = hypopyon + post-op = intravitreal antibiotics. Blow-out: no nose blowing; CT coronal.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"take a full history before treating a chemical burn. It is the only injury treated before history; irrigate immediately. acid burns are worse because they penetrate deeper. Alkali penetrates deeper (liquefactive); acid coagulates and self-limits. patch a suspected ruptured globe. Dangerous. Shield it, no pressure, no drops needing IOP. order an MRI for a metallic IOFB. for ferrous bodies; use CT . acute angle-closure has a small constricted pupil. It is mid-dilated and fixed . wait for the temporal artery biopsy before steroids in GCA. Dangerous; treat immediately. preseptal and orbital cellulitis look the same. No. Orbital has proptosis, pain on motion, and restricted gaze; preseptal does not.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Emergency Trigger sign First action Chemical burn Burning agent on eye Irrigate immediately (before history) Acute angle-closure Mid-dilated fixed pupil, hard eye Lower IOP, then laser iridotomy CRAO Cherry-red spot, painless loss Ocular massage, lower IOP, rule out GCA Giant cell arteritis Jaw claudication, raised ESR High-dose steroids before biopsy Open globe Distorted pupil, Seidel + Shield, NPO, no pressure, surgery Ferrous IOFB Metallic injury CT (no MRI), removal Endophthalmitis Hypopyon post-op Intravitreal antibiotics Orbital cellulitis Proptosis + painful gaze IV antibiotics, CT Retinal detachment Curtain, flashes, floaters Urgent referral Blow-out fracture Infraorbital numbness, diplopia CT coronal, no nose blowing\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"1. A worker splashes lye (alkali) in one eye. The correct first step is: A. Take a full history and visual acuity B. Begin copious irrigation immediately C. Pad the eye and refer D. Instill antibiotic ointment Answer B. A chemical burn is the only ocular injury treated before history and exam. Irrigate at once; alkali causes liquefactive necrosis and penetrates deeply. 2. A painful red eye has a cloudy cornea, a mid-dilated non-reactive pupil, and a rock-hard globe with nausea. The diagnosis and definitive treatment: A. Anterior uveitis; topical steroid B. Acute angle-closure; laser peripheral iridotomy C. Conjunctivitis; antibiotics D. Scleritis; oral NSAID Answer B. Acute angle-closure glaucoma. Lower the IOP medically first, then perform a definitive laser peripheral iridotomy. 3. A metal worker has a suspected intraocular foreign body of iron. Which is contraindicated? A. CT scan B. B-scan ultrasound C. MRI D. Slit-lamp exam Answer C. MRI is contraindicated with a ferrous foreign body (magnetic movement risk). Use CT. 4. Three days after blunt trauma, a patient with hyphema suddenly worsens. The most likely event is: A. Rebleed B. New chemical injury C. Optic neuritis D. Spontaneous resolution Answer A. Rebleed. Hyphema rebleeding peaks days 3 to 5 and raises IOP. Manage with rest, shield, and avoidance of antiplatelet drugs; screen for sickle cell. 5. A blunt orbital injury causes numbness of the cheek and upper lip, diplopia on upgaze, and orbital emphysema. The injury and imaging of choice: A. Hyphema; ultrasound B. Blow-out floor fracture; CT coronal C. Open globe; MRI D. Retinal detachment; fundus photo Answer B. Blow-out orbital floor fracture. Infraorbital nerve numbness, restricted vertical gaze, and emphysema are classic. CT with coronal sections is best, and the patient must not blow the nose.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump List the three emergency tiers and place at least three conditions in each. No looking. Drill 2 — Trigger + Action For chemical burn, acute angle-closure, CRAO, GCA, and open globe, write the one trigger sign and the one first action. Drill 3 — Alkali vs Acid Explain in writing why alkali burns penetrate deeper, and name the two acids/agents that behave like alkali. Drill 4 — Imaging Rules State the imaging of choice (and any contraindication) for: ferrous IOFB, blow-out fracture, orbital cellulitis. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a suspected open globe is shielded rather than patched. Use \\\"pressure.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump (tiers) 2nd Next day Trigger + Action 3rd 3 days Alkali vs Acid 4th 1 week Imaging Rules Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4-01-ocular-emergencies-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"E4 — Ocular Emergencies\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. Paired opposites — cue: tender/chronic, in/out, mild/severe. Stye = tender/acute; chalazion = non-tender/chronic. Entropion = turns in (lashes scratch); ectropion = turns out (CN7). Episcleritis = mild; scleritis = boring pain. Trap: ectropion \\\"scratches the cornea\\\" — that's entropion. Signature fundus → diagnosis — cue: the described picture. Cherry-red = CRAO; blood-and-thunder = CRVO; bone spicules = RP; macular star = HTN III. Trap: \\\"cherry-red spot is diseased tissue\\\" — it's the spared choroid-fed fovea. Glaucoma type — cue: open vs closed angle. Open = silent, medical ; closed = acute emergency, laser iridotomy . Phacolytic = open; phacomorphic = closed. Trap: treating angle-closure medically first / calling phacolytic \\\"closed-angle.\\\" \\\"Earliest\\\" vs \\\"most common/classic\\\" — cue: the word \\\"earliest\\\". Earliest DR sign = microaneurysm; earliest keratoconus = Fleischer ring; earliest chloroquine = ↓VA/color (bull's-eye is late ). Trap: picking the classic late sign when the stem says \\\"earliest.\\\" PH blindness vs low vision — cue: which one the stem asks. Blindness → cataract leads. Low vision → refractive error leads. Trap: using the blindness order for a low-vision question.\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"E.strategy\",\"subject\":\"E\",\"label\":\"Ocular Disease — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/E-Ocular-Disease-and-Emergencies/E-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject E — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Ocular Disease and Emergencies · the read-before-you-test reference E1 Orbit/Lids E2 Anterior Segment E3 Posterior/Retina E4 Emergencies\"},{\"anchor\":\"e1\",\"heading\":\"E1Orbit, Adnexa & Eyelids\",\"topic\":\"Subject E — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Paired opposites: Hordeolum (acute, tender abscess) vs Chalazion (chronic, non-tender granuloma) · Entropion (in, lashes scratch) vs Ectropion (out, CN VII). Key associations: Buphthalmos = congenital glaucoma · Orbital cellulitis = ethmoiditis · Horner's = ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis · Most common lid malignancy = basal cell carcinoma. Lacrimal: chronic dacryocystitis → DCR; blood from the sac = tumor (SCC) ; malignant lacrimal gland tumor = adenoid cystic carcinoma; Mikulicz = lacrimal + salivary enlargement. Proptosis: thyroid (Graves) is most common overall; pulsating = carotid-cavernous fistula; pediatric orbital malignancy = rhabdomyosarcoma. Trap: Horner's causes a dilated pupil. No — miosis (small). The dilated-pupil ptosis is CN III palsy. Trap: ectropion scratches the cornea. No — that is entropion; ectropion turns out and causes exposure.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e2\",\"heading\":\"E2Anterior Segment\",\"topic\":\"Subject E — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Pterygium crosses the limbus and destroys Bowman's; pinguecula does not. Ciliary (circumcorneal) flush = deep danger (uveitis, keratitis, acute glaucoma). Cornea clues: Fleischer ring = earliest keratoconus · Kayser-Fleischer = copper in Descemet's (Wilson's) · Krukenberg spindle = pigment dispersion · dendritic ulcer = herpes (never steroids on epithelial disease). Glaucoma: POAG = silent, open, medical; PACG = emergency, closed, mid-dilated fixed pupil, surgical. Phacolytic = open (leaked protein); phacomorphic = closed (swollen lens). Cataract/lens: nuclear = second sight (myopic shift) · PSC = most disabling, steroid-linked · Marfan up, homocystinuria down · aphakia ≈ +10 to +12 D. Uveitis: mutton-fat KP = granulomatous; hypopyon = HLA-B27/Behcet's; treat anterior uveitis with topical steroid + cycloplegic. Dry eye: Schirmer <10 mm, TBUT <10 s. Trap: Kayser-Fleischer is iron. No — it is copper in Descemet's (Wilson's). Trap: phacolytic glaucoma is closed-angle. No — it is open -angle; phacomorphic is closed.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e3\",\"heading\":\"E3Posterior Segment & Retina\",\"topic\":\"Subject E — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Signature pictures: cherry-red = CRAO · blood-and-thunder = CRVO · bone spicules + nyctalopia = RP · macular star + papilledema = malignant HTN · headlight in fog = toxoplasmosis · pizza pie = CMV. Diabetic ladder: microaneurysm (earliest) → cotton-wool/IRMA → new vessels. Severe NPDR = 4-2-1 ; PDR → panretinal photocoagulation. Cotton-wool spots = NFL infarcts, not exudates. Retinal detachment: only rhegmatogenous has a break (horseshoe tear, tobacco dust); tractional and exudative do not. ARMD: dry 85–90% ; wet → intravitreal anti-VEGF. Optic nerve Key feature Optic neuritis Unilateral, painful, RAPD, MS Papilledema Bilateral, painless, raised ICP AAION (giant cell arteritis) Jaw claudication, raised ESR — treat before biopsy NAION Painless, altitudinal, disc at risk, on waking Trap: the cherry-red spot is diseased tissue. No — it is the healthy choroid-fed fovea showing through pale ischemic retina. Trap: papilledema causes early vision loss. No — vision is spared early; optic neuritis loses vision early.\"},{\"anchor\":\"e4\",\"heading\":\"E4Ocular Emergencies\",\"topic\":\"Subject E — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Emergency First action Chemical burn Irrigate immediately (before history) to pH 7.0–7.4 Acute angle-closure Lower IOP, then laser iridotomy CRAO Massage + lower IOP (4–6 h), rule out GCA Giant cell arteritis High-dose steroids before biopsy Open globe Shield (no pressure), NPO, surgery Endophthalmitis Intravitreal antibiotics Blow-out fracture CT coronal, no nose blowing Chemicals: alkali > acid (liquefactive vs coagulative); hydrofluoric acid and ammonia penetrate deeply. Prognosis follows limbal ischemia (Roper-Hall). Trauma: ferrous IOFB = no MRI (use CT); iron = siderosis, copper alloy = chalcosis. Hyphema rebleeds days 3–5. Shaken baby = bilateral retinal hemorrhages. Trap: take a history before treating a chemical burn. No — irrigate first; it is the only injury treated before history. Trap: acute angle-closure has a small constricted pupil. No — it is mid-dilated and fixed . Trap: patch a ruptured globe. No — shield it with no pressure. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject E strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"F.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"F\",\"label\":\"Clinical Optometry — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/F-Clinical-Optometry-and-Specialties/F-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"DPAs are drugs that optometrists are legally authorized to use under RA 8050 to examine the eye more thoroughly. They dilate the pupil, paralyze accommodation, stain the cornea, numb the surface, or constrict the pupil — depending on which agent you use and why. Five agents are approved. Each one has a specific purpose, a receptor mechanism, and a set of conditions where you must not use it. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"If DPAs are just eye drops, why do we need a law to authorize their use?\\\" Because these drugs affect the autonomic nervous system and can cause systemic reactions — they are pharmaceutical agents with real risks, not just saline.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Why does tropicamide dilate the pupil? Because it blocks the M3 muscarinic receptor on the sphincter pupillae. Why does blocking M3 cause dilation? Because the sphincter is tonically innervated by the parasympathetic system (CN3 → ciliary ganglion → short ciliary nerves → M3). Block M3 → sphincter stops contracting → dilator pupillae (sympathetically innervated, unopposed) pulls the iris open. Why does cycloplegia accompany some mydriatics? The ciliary muscle that controls accommodation is also innervated by M3. The same muscarinic blockade that dilates the pupil also paralyzes accommodation — the ciliary muscle relaxes, zonules tighten, lens flattens, and accommodation is abolished. Why does phenylephrine dilate without cycloplegia? Phenylephrine is an α1 agonist — it stimulates the dilator pupillae directly (α1 receptor) without touching the parasympathetic pathway. The ciliary muscle has no α1 receptors; it is purely under parasympathetic (M3) control. So phenylephrine produces mydriasis with zero effect on accommodation.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Mydriasis Greek: mydros = darkness (dilated pupil) Pupil > 6 mm; produced by sympathomimetics or parasympatholytics Cycloplegia Greek: kyklos = circle (lens) + plege = stroke/paralysis Paralysis of the ciliary muscle → loss of accommodation Miosis Greek: meioun = to lessen Pupil constriction; M3 stimulation or α1 blockade DPA Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agent Authorized under RA 8050; for examination use by optometrists\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-details-the-five-approved-dpas\",\"heading\":\"The Five Approved DPAs\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"A — Mydriatic WITHOUT Cycloplegia 1. Phenylephrine 2.5% Class: α1-adrenergic agonist (sympathomimetic) Receptor: α1 on dilator pupillae Action: contracts dilator → mydriasis; no effect on ciliary muscle (no cycloplegia) Onset: 15–20 minutes; duration 4–6 hours Use: dilation for fundus exam when accommodation must be preserved (e.g., elderly, glaucoma suspect) Contraindication: narrow angle / angle-closure glaucoma (dilation can push iris against the trabecular meshwork, blocking aqueous outflow → acute angle-closure crisis) Systemic risk: hypertension, tachycardia (α1 systemic vasoconstriction) — use 2.5%, not 10% B — Mydriatics WITH Cycloplegia 2. Tropicamide 0.5% / 1% Class: anticholinergic (competitive muscarinic antagonist) Receptor: M3 on sphincter pupillae AND ciliary muscle Action: blocks M3 → sphincter relaxes → mydriasis; ciliary muscle relaxes → cycloplegia Onset: 20–30 minutes; duration 4–6 hours The preferred DPA in pregnancy (FDA Category C, but tropicamide is chosen because of shortest duration and least systemic absorption among cycloplegics) Use: dilated fundus exam, cycloplegic refraction (especially in pseudomyopia) Contraindication: same as phenylephrine — narrow angle / angle-closure glaucoma 3. Cyclopentolate 0.5% / 1% / 2% Class: anticholinergic Receptor: M3 Stronger and longer cycloplegia than tropicamide Onset: 30–60 minutes; duration 12–24 hours Use: cycloplegic refraction in children (more reliable cycloplegia needed); suspected pseudomyopia Contraindication: narrow angle / angle-closure glaucoma Pediatric caution: can cause CNS effects in young children (hallucinations, behavioral changes) — more common with 2% in infants; monitor for 30 minutes post-instillation C — Local Anesthetic Agents 4. Proparacaine 0.5% Class: ester-type local anesthetic Mechanism: blocks sodium channels on corneal sensory nerve endings → topical anesthesia Onset: 30 seconds; duration ~15 minutes Use: tonometry, foreign body removal, corneal staining, contact lens fitting procedures requiring manipulation Never prescribed for home use — chronic use prevents pain sensation → patients unknowingly damage the cornea (neurotrophic keratopathy) Alternative esters: oxybuprocaine, benoxinate (0.4%) D — Diagnostic Dye 5. Fluorescein strips Class: xanthene dye Mechanism: fluoresces green-yellow under cobalt blue light (465 nm) — accumulates where epithelial cells are missing Use: corneal abrasion detection, contact lens fluorescein pattern assessment, applanation tonometry (with proparacaine) Strips preferred over drops (less contamination risk) Do not use with soft CLs in place — fluorescein permanently stains hydrogel CLs; must remove CLs first\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-details-the-dpa-clinical-examination-workflow\",\"heading\":\"The DPA Clinical Examination Workflow\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Step 1: Take full history — Confirm no contraindications (narrow angle, allergy, systemic disease) Step 2: Baseline assessment BEFORE instillation — Anterior chamber depth (oblique flashlight / Van Herick method) — Undilated fundus check if possible — Document pupil size and reactivity Step 3: Instill DPA — Lower conjunctival fornix — Tip does not touch eye or skin — Apply nasolacrimal occlusion ( NLO ) immediately after instillation Step 4: Nasolacrimal Occlusion ( NLO ) — Press the inner corner of the eye (lacrimal sac area) for 2 minutes — Prevents the drug from draining into the nasolacrimal duct and reaching systemic circulation — Most important step for minimizing systemic side effects Step 5: Wait for onset — Tropicamide: 20–30 min — Cyclopentolate: 30–60 min — Phenylephrine: 15–20 min Step 6: Confirm dilation and perform examination Step 7: Document — Drug used, concentration, time instilled, eye(s) treated, patient response — Inform patient: blurred near vision and photosensitivity until drug wears off — Never drive immediately after dilation\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-details-contraindications-summary\",\"heading\":\"Contraindications Summary\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Condition Contraindicated DPA Reason Narrow angle / angle-closure glaucoma Phenylephrine, tropicamide, cyclopentolate (all mydriatics) Dilation pushes iris against TM → acute angle-closure Pregnancy All DPAs are FDA Category C Insufficient safety data; use only when benefit > risk Breastfeeding Especially atropine; tropicamide preferred if must dilate Systemic absorption excreted in breast milk Allergy to ester anesthetics Proparacaine, oxybuprocaine, benoxinate Cross-reactivity within ester class Children < 3 months Cyclopentolate 2% — use 0.5% instead CNS toxicity risk higher in neonates Soft CLs in place Fluorescein Permanently stains hydrogel material\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-the-details-dpa-in-pregnancy-gap-lecture-08-summary\",\"heading\":\"DPA in Pregnancy (Gap Lecture 08 Summary)\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"All approved DPAs are FDA Category C in pregnancy (risk cannot be ruled out) If dilation is clinically necessary during pregnancy: tropicamide is the preferred agent Rationale: shortest duration of action (4–6 hours vs. 24 hours for cyclopentolate); least systemic exposure; most data available Always apply NLO technique to minimize systemic absorption Breastfeeding: advise patient to pump and discard for 24 hours after cyclopentolate; tropicamide shorter clearance\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-visual-map-dpa-receptor-action-summary\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — DPA Receptor-Action Summary\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"SYMPATHETIC PATHWAY α1 receptor (dilator pupillae) ├── Agonist → Phenylephrine → MYDRIASIS (no cycloplegia) └── Normal: NE from sympathetics PARASYMPATHETIC PATHWAY ( CN3 → ciliary ganglion → short ciliary nerves) M3 receptor (sphincter pupillae + ciliary muscle) ├── Agonist → Pilocarpine → MIOSIS + accommodation ↑ └── Antagonist → Tropicamide / Cyclopentolate → MYDRIASIS + CYCLOPLEGIA CORNEAL SENSORY NERVES ( CN5 ophthalmic) Na+ channels └── Blocker → Proparacaine → TOPICAL ANESTHESIA CORNEAL EPITHELIUM Fluorescein → accumulates at gaps → GREEN FLUORESCENCE under cobalt blue\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Feature Tropicamide Cyclopentolate Phenylephrine Class Anticholinergic Anticholinergic Sympathomimetic Receptor M3 antagonist M3 antagonist α1 agonist Mydriasis Yes Yes Yes Cycloplegia Yes (mild-moderate) Yes (strong) No Duration 4–6 hours 12–24 hours 4–6 hours Preferred in pregnancy Yes No No Pediatric use Yes First choice for cycloplegic Rx Adjunct Board clue Shortest duration cycloplegic Best cycloplegia in children Dilation only, no cycloplegia\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Phenylephrine concentration 2.5% (safe); 10% avoided due to systemic risk Tropicamide concentrations 0.5%, 1% Cyclopentolate concentrations 0.5%, 1%, 2% Proparacaine concentration 0.5% NLO duration 2 minutes Tropicamide onset 20–30 min Cyclopentolate onset 30–60 min Fluorescein excitation wavelength 465 nm (cobalt blue)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"5 DPAs — PTCPF P henylephrine → T ropicamide → C yclopentolate → P roparacaine → F luorescein (Or: \\\"Please Try Cycling Past Fields\\\") Mydriatics without cycloplegia Only phenylephrine — the only sympathomimetic in the list. Everything else that dilates also paralyzes. NLO = 2 fingers, 2 minutes Press the inner canthus for 2 minutes. This is the single most important systemic-safety step.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Tropicamide causes mydriasis only It also causes cycloplegia (it is M3 antagonist). Phenylephrine causes mydriasis only. The strongest cycloplegic for children is tropicamide Cyclopentolate has stronger, more reliable cycloplegia; atropine is stronger still but not an approved DPA. All DPAs are contraindicated in pregnancy They are Category C (risk not ruled out), but if clinically necessary, tropicamide is the preferred choice , not all are absolutely contraindicated. Fluorescein can be used with soft CLs in place Remove soft CLs before applying fluorescein; they stain permanently. NLO prevents the drug from working NLO prevents systemic drainage; the drug still works locally on the eye.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Number of approved DPAs 5 DPA that dilates WITHOUT cycloplegia Phenylephrine 2.5% (α1 agonist) Both mydriasis and cycloplegia Tropicamide, cyclopentolate (M3 antagonists) Preferred DPA in pregnancy Tropicamide NLO duration 2 minutes Absolute contraindication for mydriatics Narrow angle / angle-closure glaucoma Never prescribe for home use Proparacaine (destroys corneal sensation) Fluorescein: do not use with Soft contact lenses\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"1. A 32-year-old pregnant patient needs a dilated fundus exam. Which DPA is most appropriate? A. Cyclopentolate 1% B. Phenylephrine 10% C. Tropicamide 0.5% D. Proparacaine 0.5% Answer C. Tropicamide 0.5%. All DPAs are FDA Category C in pregnancy. When dilation is clinically necessary, tropicamide is the preferred agent because it has the shortest duration of action and least systemic exposure. Phenylephrine 10% is avoided due to its systemic cardiovascular risks. Cyclopentolate has a longer duration and more systemic exposure. Proparacaine is a local anesthetic, not a mydriatic. 2. Which of the following best explains why phenylephrine produces mydriasis without cycloplegia? A. It acts on M3 receptors selectively on the sphincter pupillae only B. It acts on α1 receptors on the dilator pupillae; the ciliary muscle has no α1 receptors C. It blocks acetylcholinesterase, preventing ACh from contracting the ciliary muscle D. It directly relaxes the ciliary muscle through a non-receptor mechanism Answer B. Phenylephrine is an α1 agonist that stimulates the dilator pupillae. The ciliary muscle is under purely parasympathetic (M3) control — it has no α1 receptors. Therefore, phenylephrine produces mydriasis without any effect on accommodation. Options A and D are incorrect mechanisms; option C describes indirect cholinomimetics, not phenylephrine.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1-01-dpa-examination-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F1 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA)\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the 5 DPAs from memory: name, concentration, class, receptor, action, and one key contraindication each. Do not look at the table. Drill 2 — Blank Table Draw the DPA comparison table (Tropicamide vs. Cyclopentolate vs. Phenylephrine) from memory: 7 rows, all filled. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a patient in 3 sentences why you are pressing their inner corner after putting in eye drops — without using the words \\\"systemic,\\\" \\\"absorption,\\\" or \\\"nasolacrimal.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back DPA that dilates only (no cycloplegia) Phenylephrine 2.5% — α1 agonist Preferred DPA in pregnancy Tropicamide 0.5% NLO — how long? 2 minutes Fluorescein — contraindicated with Soft contact lenses Cyclopentolate — receptor? M3 antagonist Proparacaine — never prescribe for home use because Abolishes pain → corneal damage goes undetected Mydriatic contraindicated in narrow angle All mydriatics (phenylephrine, tropicamide, cyclopentolate) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the complete DPA clinical examination workflow (Steps 1–7) on a blank page. Include what you check before instillation, how to perform NLO, and what to document. Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Blank Table + Flash Cards 3rd 3 days later Teach-Back Write 4th 1 week later Sequence from Scratch Final 2 weeks later All 5 — flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Pediatric optometry is about understanding how a child's visual system develops from birth, what can go wrong at each stage, and how to examine and manage a child who cannot reliably answer \\\"which is clearer, one or two?\\\" The key challenge is that children cannot self-report well, so tests must be adapted to their developmental level. The key diseases are amblyopia and strabismus — and early detection is what determines outcome. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"If a 2-year-old cannot read a Snellen chart, how do we know if they can see?\\\" This question opens the entire topic of pediatric VA testing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Why is early detection of amblyopia critical? The visual cortex has a critical period of plasticity (birth to approximately age 7–8, with peak sensitivity in years 1–3). During this window, the brain can be rewired — a deprived or suppressed eye can recover full function with the right treatment. After the critical period closes, the same treatment produces minimal improvement. Why does patching work in amblyopia? By covering the good eye, you force the brain to use the amblyopic eye. Repetitive stimulation during the critical period strengthens the visual cortex connections for that eye, recovering cortical representation and improving VA. Why does strabismus cause amblyopia? A misaligned eye projects a confused or diplopic image. The brain suppresses the deviating eye to avoid diplopia. Constant suppression means the visual cortex of the suppressed eye is never adequately stimulated → cortical cells for that eye atrophy → amblyopia develops.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-visual-development-milestones\",\"heading\":\"Visual Development Milestones\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Age Visual Milestone Birth No coordinated eye movement; responds to light; VA ~20/400–20/800 1 month Fixes briefly on a face; irregular fixation 2 months Follows large objects; tracks horizontally 3 months Fovea fully formed; fixes and follows well 3–4 months Eyes should be straight (any persistent deviation after this age is abnormal) 6 months Fixes for 1–2 minutes; develops convergence and depth perception 1 year VA ~20/70 3 years VA ~20/20; accommodation fully functional 7–12 years Age of emmetropization Refraction at birth: Neonates are typically hyperopic (+2.00 to +3.00D). This gradually resolves through emmetropization.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-pediatric-va-testing-methods\",\"heading\":\"Pediatric VA Testing Methods\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Method Age Principle Visually Evoked Potentials (VEP) Any age (infants) Brain response to reversing checkerboard pattern — objective, no verbal response needed Preferential Looking (PL) / Teller Acuity Cards Newborn to 2 years Infant preferentially looks at patterned vs. blank stimulus — spatial frequency at threshold = VA Optokinetic Nystagmus (OKN) drum 0–3 months Involuntary nystagmus when moving stripes pass before the eyes — present = seeing Cardiff Acuity Cards 1–3 years Pictures on cards; child looks toward the picture HOTV / Lea Symbols 2–5 years Matching task — child matches letter or symbol without naming Allen figures 2–3 years Familiar pictures (car, cake, bird); child names or points Snellen chart 5 years and older (when alphabet is known) Standard\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-primitive-reflexes-board-relevant\",\"heading\":\"Primitive Reflexes (Board-Relevant)\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Primitive reflexes are present at birth and integrate (disappear) by specific ages. Their persistence beyond the expected integration age or absence when expected to be present both signal developmental problems. Reflex Emerges Integrates If Persistent Fear Paralysis Reflex 5 GW 9–12 GW Anxieties, OCD tendencies Root Reflex Birth 3–4 months Feeding problems Suck Reflex 32 GW 2–4 months Premature infants may lack it Moro (Startle) Birth 5–6 months ADHD, sensory processing difficulties ATNR (Tonic Neck) Birth 6–7 months Difficulty with reading/writing if not integrated STNR 6–9 months 9–11 months Posture, near vision problems Visual significance of unintegrated reflexes: ATNR links head turning to arm extension — if unintegrated, every head turn triggers arm movement, disrupting fixation and tracking. This can mimic convergence insufficiency or tracking disorders.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-amblyopia\",\"heading\":\"Amblyopia\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Definition: Decreased best-corrected VA in one or both eyes due to abnormal visual experience during the critical period, without structural pathology to explain the reduction. Types: Type Cause Key Feature Strabismic amblyopia Constant unilateral strabismus; brain suppresses deviating eye Most common in clinical practice Anisometropic amblyopia Significant refractive difference between eyes; blurred image in one eye Often discovered during school screening Meridional amblyopia Uncorrected astigmatism; one meridian consistently blurred Specific orientation of VA reduction Deprivation amblyopia Media opacity (cataract, ptosis, corneal scar) blocking image Worst prognosis if not treated urgently Diagnosis: VA worse in one eye (or both in bilateral deprivation) with best correction No pathology to account for the reduction History of amblyogenic factor during critical period Treatment: Correct the refractive error first — full time spectacle wear for 12–16 weeks before starting occlusion Patching of the fellow eye: 2 hours/day (mild) to full-time (severe) depending on depth Atropine penalization (1% atropine in the fellow eye): blurs the good eye for near — alternative to patching Dichoptic treatment (binocular stimulation): emerging; video games/apps designed to stimulate both eyes simultaneously Critical period: Best results before age 7; still some improvement up to age 12; minimal after.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-strabismus-pediatric\",\"heading\":\"Strabismus — Pediatric\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Infantile esotropia (congenital ET): Onset before 6 months Large-angle esotropia (>30 pd) Alternating fixation pattern Associated with dissociated vertical deviation (DVD) and inferior oblique overaction Treatment: surgery after age 6 months (most before 2 years) to establish binocularity Accommodative esotropia: Onset 2–3 years (when accommodation demand increases) Associated with hyperopia Correcting the hyperopia with full plus correction reduces or eliminates the deviation Treatment: full cycloplegic refraction → spectacles → check if deviation resolves Pseudostrabismus: Eyes appear crossed due to wide epicanthal folds or negative angle kappa — but Hirschberg test shows symmetric reflexes Reassure parents; no treatment needed; resolves as the nasal bridge develops\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-the-details-pediatric-examination-techniques\",\"heading\":\"Pediatric Examination Techniques\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Hirschberg corneal reflex test: Shine penlight at equal distance between eyes Normal: both reflexes centered symmetrically in each pupil Abnormal: reflex displaced from center → strabismus 1 mm of displacement = approximately 7 prism diopters (or 15 pd depending on source) Brückner test: Shine direct ophthalmoscope into both pupils simultaneously from 1 meter Normal: equal red reflex brightness in both eyes Abnormal: brighter reflex in deviating or amblyopic eye Krimsky test: Prism placed over the deviating eye until the corneal reflexes are symmetric Measures deviation when the patient will not cooperate with the cover test Lang stereotest: Random dot stereograms on a card; no glasses needed Child must see the embedded images to pass → confirms stereopsis → confirms fusion\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-visual-map-amblyopia-decision-flow\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — Amblyopia Decision Flow\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Child presents with possible amblyopia | v Cycloplegic refraction (tropicamide or cyclopentolate) | v Full spectacle correction prescribed → wear 12–16 weeks | v Retest VA with correction | +- --> VA normalized → spectacle-only (refractive amblyopia resolved) | +- --> VA still reduced → add patching of fellow eye | v 2 hrs/day (mild) to full-time (severe) Monitor VA every 4–8 weeks | v VA improving → continue VA plateau → reassess compliance, consider atropine\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Feature Strabismic Amblyopia Anisometropic Amblyopia Deprivation Amblyopia Cause Constant unilateral strabismus Refractive difference ≥ 1.50D sphere or 1.50D cylinder Media opacity (cataract, ptosis) Eye appearance Deviated eye Normal alignment May look normal or have lid/cornea problem Depth Moderate Mild to moderate Severe (worst prognosis) Treatment urgency Moderate Moderate High — remove opacity immediately Board clue Suppression on sensory testing Found on school screening Dense amblyopia despite normal ocular exam\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Eyes should be straight by 3–4 months Normal VA at 1 year ~20/70 Normal VA at 3 years ~20/20 Critical period peak Birth to 3 years Critical period closes ~7–8 years Hirschberg 1 mm displacement ~7 pd of deviation Infantile ET: deviation size > 30 pd Accommodative ET onset 2–3 years\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"DEVSS Types of amblyopia — D eprivation, E xotropic (any strabismus), V isual form deprivation (same as D), S trabismic, S ensory \\\"3–4 months rule\\\" Eyes must be straight by 3–4 months. Any persistent deviation after this is pathological. Patching sequence Full Rx first → then patch. Never patch without correcting refractive error first — you may be patching the wrong eye if the Rx changes the preferred eye.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Pseudostrabismus needs treatment It resolves as the nasal bridge widens; no treatment needed. Hirschberg shows symmetric reflexes. Amblyopia cannot be treated after age 7 — Partially Treatment is less effective after age 7, but improvement is still possible up to ~age 12; after that, minimal gains. Patching is always the first step in amblyopia treatment Cycloplegic refraction and full spectacle wear for 12–16 weeks comes first. Patching is added only if spectacles alone don't normalize VA. Accommodative esotropia requires surgery Full cycloplegic refraction (full plus correction) is the first treatment. Surgery is only needed if residual deviation remains after maximal optical correction.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Eyes should be straight by 3–4 months VA test for infants Preferential looking / Teller Acuity Cards VA test for 2–5 year olds HOTV, Lea Symbols, Allen figures Worst prognosis amblyopia Deprivation amblyopia First step in amblyopia treatment Cycloplegic Rx + full spectacle correction Accommodative ET treatment Full cycloplegic correction (full plus) Pseudostrabismus — Hirschberg Symmetric reflexes (no true deviation) Critical period Peaks 1–3 years; closes ~7–8 years\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"1. A 4-year-old with a best corrected VA of 20/80 in the left eye and 20/20 in the right eye is found to have a 3.50D hyperopic difference between the eyes. What is the most likely diagnosis and first treatment step? A. Strabismic amblyopia; start immediate patching of the right eye B. Anisometropic amblyopia; prescribe full cycloplegic correction and observe for 12–16 weeks C. Deprivation amblyopia; refer for surgical removal of media opacity D. Pseudoamblyopia; reassure and retest in 1 year Answer B. Anisometropic amblyopia — significant refractive difference (> 1.50D) between eyes, reduced VA in the more ametropic eye, normal alignment. First step is always cycloplegic refraction and full spectacle correction. Patching is added only if VA does not normalize after 12–16 weeks of spectacle wear. 2. A parent brings in a 2-year-old whose eyes appear to cross. On Hirschberg testing, both corneal reflexes are centered symmetrically. What is the most likely diagnosis? A. Infantile esotropia — refer for surgical alignment B. Accommodative esotropia — prescribe full plus correction C. Pseudostrabismus — reassure; no treatment needed D. Strabismic amblyopia — patch the preferred eye Answer C. Symmetric Hirschberg reflexes rule out true strabismus. The appearance of crossed eyes with normal reflexes is pseudostrabismus, caused by wide epicanthal folds. It resolves as the nasal bridge develops. No treatment is needed.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2-01-pediatric-optometry-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F2 — Pediatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the visual development milestones from birth to age 3, and the 4 types of amblyopia with their distinguishing feature each. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the pediatric VA testing table: Method / Age / Principle — 7 methods, all rows filled from memory. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain the critical period to a parent whose 6-year-old was just diagnosed with amblyopia. Emphasize urgency without the word \\\"critical period.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Eyes straight by 3–4 months VA at 1 year 20/70 VA at 3 years 20/20 Worst amblyopia prognosis Deprivation Pseudostrabismus Hirschberg Symmetric reflexes First step in amblyopia treatment Full Rx + spectacle wear 12–16 weeks Accommodative ET treatment Full cycloplegic correction (full plus Rx) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the amblyopia management flow from diagnosis to resolution on a blank page. Include each decision point and what triggers the next step. Source: Pediatric Optometry | BV Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Geriatric optometry is about understanding how aging changes every part of the eye and visual system, how systemic diseases common in the elderly (diabetes, hypertension, thyroid disease) manifest in the eye, and how to manage these patients including ophthalmic correction for their special needs. The most tested areas are AMD, diabetic retinopathy, hypertensive retinopathy, and glaucoma in the elderly — because these are the leading causes of irreversible vision loss in the aging population. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"If your patient is 75 years old and has both diabetes and glaucoma, where do you start the eye exam and why?\\\" This forces students to think about systemic-ocular links and prioritization.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Why does the lens yellow and harden with age? Lens proteins (crystallins) undergo progressive cross-linking and oxidation throughout life. There is no turnover of lens fiber cells — every fiber laid down from embryonic development remains. Over decades, these proteins denature, yellow (from accumulation of UV-generated chromophores), and become less elastic. The loss of elasticity is presbyopia; the yellowing and opacity formation is nuclear cataract. Why does diabetic retinopathy cause vision loss through neovascularization? Chronic hyperglycemia damages retinal capillary endothelial cells and pericytes. Pericyte loss destabilizes vessel walls → microaneurysms and non-perfusion. Non-perfused retina secretes VEGF (vascular endothelial growth factor) → signals for new vessel growth. But new vessels (NVD/NVE) are fragile, structurally defective, and grow into the vitreous → vitreous hemorrhage, traction retinal detachment → severe vision loss.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-age-related-anatomical-changes-in-the-eye\",\"heading\":\"Age-Related Anatomical Changes in the Eye\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Structure Change with Aging Clinical Consequence Cornea Arcus senilis (lipid deposition at periphery); decreased sensitivity; flatten Reduced corneal reflex; increased susceptibility to infection Anterior chamber Shallows as lens thickens Increased risk of angle closure Iris Atrophy of dilator muscle; iris rigidity Miosis (small pupil); poor dilation; reduced low-light vision Lens Yellowing, nuclear sclerosis, decreased elasticity Nuclear cataract; presbyopia; increased short-wavelength absorption Vitreous Syneresis (liquefaction) and posterior vitreous detachment (PVD) Floaters; risk of retinal tear if vitreous pulls on a retinal vessel Retina Rod loss (peripheral); cone changes at macula; decreased sensitivity Reduced contrast sensitivity; slower dark adaptation Optic nerve Decreased axon count; increased C:D ratio Must distinguish from glaucomatous damage Tear film Reduced lacrimal gland secretion; altered lipid layer Dry eye disease — most common complaint in geriatric patients\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-age-related-macular-degeneration-amd\",\"heading\":\"Age-Related Macular Degeneration (AMD)\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"From Gap Lecture 13 — full content Classification: Type Frequency Pathology Vision Loss Dry AMD ~85% Drusen accumulation; RPE atrophy; geographic atrophy Slow, progressive Wet AMD (neovascular) ~15% Choroidal neovascularization (CNV) through Bruch's membrane Rapid, severe Drusen types: Hard drusen (small, discrete) = lower risk Soft drusen (large, confluent, indistinct borders) = high risk for progression Stages of Dry AMD: Early: small drusen (<63 µm), no pigmentary changes, VA usually normal Intermediate: medium drusen (63–124 µm) or pigmentary abnormality Advanced GA (Geographic Atrophy): large RPE/photoreceptor loss, severe central vision loss Wet AMD key signs: Sudden metamorphopsia or central vision loss Subretinal fluid, hemorrhage, macular edema (on OCT) Disciform scar = end-stage (Junius-Kuhnt) Management: Stage Management Early / intermediate dry AREDS2 supplements (25% risk reduction); Amsler grid monitoring; annual review Advanced GA Low vision assessment; rehabilitation; no proven treatment to reverse atrophy Wet AMD (CNV) Anti-VEGF intravitreal injections (bevacizumab / ranibizumab / aflibercept); urgent referral AREDS2 Formula (daily): Vitamin C: 500 mg Vitamin E: 400 IU Lutein: 10 mg Zeaxanthin: 2 mg Zinc: 80 mg Copper: 2 mg Anti-VEGF agents: Bevacizumab (Avastin) — off-label, least expensive Ranibizumab (Lucentis) — FDA-approved for wet AMD Aflibercept (Eylea) — FDA-approved; less frequent injections required\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-diabetic-retinopathy-dr\",\"heading\":\"Diabetic Retinopathy (DR)\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Pathophysiology: Chronic hyperglycemia → pericyte loss → microaneurysms → retinal ischemia → VEGF release → neovascularization Classification: Stage Features Non-Proliferative DR (NPDR) — Mild Microaneurysms only NPDR — Moderate Microaneurysms + dot/blot hemorrhages + hard exudates + soft exudates (cotton wool spots) NPDR — Severe (4-2-1 rule) Hemorrhages in 4 quadrants; venous beading in 2 quadrants; IRMA in 1 quadrant Proliferative DR (PDR) Neovascularization (NVD or NVE); vitreous hemorrhage; traction retinal detachment Diabetic Macular Edema (DME): Most common cause of vision loss in DR (not neovascularization) Fluid accumulation in the macula → blurred central vision Clinically significant macular edema (CSME): edema within 500 µm of fovea, or hard exudates with adjacent thickening within 500 µm, or thickening ≥ one disc area within one disc diameter of fovea Management: Stage Management Mild–moderate NPDR Optimize glycemic control; 6–12 month review Severe NPDR / early PDR Pan-retinal photocoagulation (PRP) PDR with vitreous hemorrhage or TRD Vitrectomy DME Anti-VEGF (first line); focal/grid laser (second line) Optometric role: Screen annually; detect early DR; refer when moderate NPDR or worse, or any DME.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-hypertensive-retinopathy-htr\",\"heading\":\"Hypertensive Retinopathy (HTR)\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Pathophysiology: Chronic hypertension → arteriole wall thickening (arteriolosclerosis) → reduced lumen → AV nicking → flame hemorrhages → cotton wool spots → papilledema (in severe hypertensive crisis) Classification (Scheie / Keith-Wagener-Barker grading): Grade Features Grade 1 Mild narrowing of arterioles; increased arteriovenous (AV) ratio Grade 2 Moderate narrowing + AV nicking (arteriovenous crossing changes) Grade 3 Grade 2 + flame hemorrhages + cotton wool spots + hard exudates Grade 4 Grade 3 + papilledema (optic disc swelling) — hypertensive emergency Normal AV ratio: 2:3 (artery:vein). In HTR: ratio narrows (arteries thin, veins compressed). AV nicking (Gunn's sign / Salus sign): Arteriole crosses over vein and compresses it → vein appears indented or deflected at the crossing — sign of arteriolosclerosis. Management: Refer for blood pressure management. Grade 4 = medical emergency.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-geriatric-binocular-vision-anomalies\",\"heading\":\"Geriatric Binocular Vision Anomalies\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Common in elderly: Exophoria at near increases as accommodative convergence decreases with presbyopia Esotropia can develop in patients with long-standing exo who decompensate Vertical deviations from skew deviation in brainstem ischemia Diplopia from CN palsies — microvascular (DM/HTN) is the most common cause\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-the-details-ophthalmic-correction-for-elderly-special-needs\",\"heading\":\"Ophthalmic Correction for Elderly Special Needs\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Need Solution Reading and near work Progressive lenses or bifocals with appropriate add Low light / night driving High-transmission lenses; anti-reflection coating Photophobia (cataract, AMD) Absorptive lenses (CPF filters); polarized lenses Dry eye Lubricating drops; optimize CL wear schedule Low vision High-add spectacles, magnifiers, telescopes (see F7) Depth perception issues Caution with progressive for stairs; may need separate reading glasses\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Feature Dry AMD Wet AMD Frequency 85% 15% Pathology Drusen; RPE atrophy; GA CNV; subretinal fluid; hemorrhage Onset Gradual Sudden Severity Moderate Severe (rapid if untreated) Treatment AREDS2 supplements Anti-VEGF injections Board clue Drusen on fundus Metamorphopsia + sudden vision loss Feature DR HTR Vessels Microaneurysms; neovascularization Arteriolosclerosis; AV nicking Exudates Hard exudates in rings (circinate) Hard exudates in macular star pattern Specific sign Cotton wool spots, NVD, NVE AV nicking; grade 4 = papilledema Key cause Diabetes Hypertension\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"AMD: leading cause of irreversible vision loss in Adults > 60 in developed countries Wet AMD: frequency ~15% of AMD AREDS2: risk reduction ~25% progression from intermediate to advanced AREDS2: Vitamin C 500 mg AREDS2: Lutein 10 mg AREDS2: Zeaxanthin 2 mg Normal AV ratio 2:3 Grade 4 HTR Papilledema = hypertensive emergency DR: most common cause of vision loss Diabetic macular edema (DME)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"AREDS2 vitamins \\\"C-E-LZ\\\" → Vitamin C, Vitamin E, Lutein, Zeaxanthin (+ Zinc and Copper) Wet AMD treatment \\\"B-R-A\\\" → Bevacizumab, Ranibizumab, Aflibercept (anti-VEGF agents) HTR grades 1–4 \\\"Narrow, Nick, Flame, Papilledema\\\" — each grade adds the next finding. DR 4-2-1 rule for severe NPDR Hemorrhages in 4 quadrants; venous beading in 2 quadrants; IRMA in 1 quadrant → any ONE of these = severe NPDR, high risk for PDR.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Dry AMD is the most common cause of severe vision loss in AMD Wet AMD (only 15% of cases) causes the majority of severe vision loss; dry AMD progresses slowly. AREDS2 supplements treat AMD They reduce the risk of progression from intermediate to advanced; they do not treat existing disease or reverse damage. Grade 4 hypertensive retinopathy is characterized by AV nicking AV nicking = Grade 2. Grade 4 = papilledema (hypertensive emergency, referring sign). The most common cause of vision loss in DR is PDR (neovascularization) Diabetic macular edema (DME) is the most common cause of vision loss in DR.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Dry AMD vs. wet AMD frequency 85% dry / 15% wet Wet AMD treatment Anti-VEGF (bevacizumab, ranibizumab, aflibercept) AREDS2 risk reduction 25% Normal AV ratio 2:3 Grade 4 HTR = Papilledema = hypertensive emergency DR most common vision loss cause Diabetic macular edema Severe NPDR rule 4-2-1 rule Drusen: high risk type Soft drusen (large, confluent)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"1. A 68-year-old patient with a 10-year history of diabetes presents with best corrected VA of 20/50 in the right eye. Fundus shows thickening of the retina within 500 µm of the fovea with adjacent hard exudates. What is the diagnosis and appropriate management? A. Moderate NPDR; observe and recheck in 12 months B. Clinically significant macular edema (CSME); urgent referral for anti-VEGF treatment C. Proliferative DR; pan-retinal photocoagulation D. Dry AMD with macular drusen; AREDS2 supplementation Answer B. The findings (retinal thickening within 500 µm of fovea + hard exudates with thickening within 500 µm) meet the criteria for clinically significant macular edema (CSME). This requires urgent referral for treatment (anti-VEGF is first-line). This is not PDR (no neovascularization), not AMD (hard exudates in diabetic pattern), and not a watch-and-wait situation. 2. A 72-year-old patient reports sudden onset of central distortion (wavy lines) in the right eye over 2 days. Fundus exam shows subretinal fluid and hemorrhage near the fovea. What is the most likely diagnosis? A. Dry AMD with geographic atrophy B. Wet AMD with choroidal neovascularization C. Diabetic macular edema D. Hypertensive retinopathy grade 3 Answer B. Sudden onset of metamorphopsia (wavy lines) + subretinal fluid and hemorrhage at the macula = wet AMD with choroidal neovascularization until proven otherwise. This is urgent — refer for anti-VEGF injection. Dry AMD progresses gradually; DME is associated with diabetes and has a different fundus picture; HTR grade 3 shows flame hemorrhages and cotton wool spots but not subretinal hemorrhage.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3-01-geriatric-optometry-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F3 — Geriatric Optometry\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the 4 stages of DR, the 4 grades of HTR, and the AREDS2 formula from memory. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the Dry AMD vs. Wet AMD comparison table from memory. Then reproduce the DR vs. HTR comparison table. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to an elderly patient why they need to use the Amsler grid every day at home. Do not use the words \\\"AMD,\\\" \\\"drusen,\\\" or \\\"hemorrhage.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Wet AMD treatment Anti-VEGF: bevacizumab, ranibizumab, aflibercept AREDS2 risk reduction 25% Grade 4 HTR finding Papilledema Normal AV ratio 2:3 Most common DR vision loss cause DME DR severe NPDR rule 4-2-1 Soft drusen = High risk for progression Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the DR classification sequence from mild NPDR to PDR on a blank page, with the defining finding for each stage and the management at each stage. Source: AMD Gap Lecture 13 | Geriatric/Anatomical Changes | LV DR and HTR reviewers Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Neuro-optometry is about understanding what happens to vision when the brain or cranial nerves are damaged. The board tests three main areas: cranial nerve palsies (which muscle is affected and how to localize the lesion), nystagmus (classify the waveform and identify the cause), and cortical visual impairment (the brain cannot process what the intact eye sends). Mastery here depends on knowing the anatomy of each nerve, because the presentation tells you exactly where the lesion is. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"If a patient walks in with one eye drifting inward and double vision that is worse at distance, which nerve is affected and how do you know?\\\" Walking through this builds the entire neuro-optometry framework.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Why does CN4 palsy cause vertical diplopia on downgaze? The superior oblique's primary action in the adducted position is depression. When the eye looks down and in (as in reading), the SO is the main depressor. If CN4 is paretic, this depression fails → the eye stays high → vertical diplopia, worst on downgaze toward the nose. This is why patients tilt their head to the opposite shoulder — to rotate the affected eye into a position where it sees straight without the SO. Why is CN6 called a \\\"false localizing sign\\\"? CN6 has the longest intracranial course of the ocular motor nerves, traveling along the clivus before entering the cavernous sinus. Elevated intracranial pressure stretches the nerve anywhere along this course, not just at the actual source of the ICP rise. So a CN6 palsy doesn't tell you where the lesion is — it tells you the ICP is elevated.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-details-cn4-trochlear-nerve-palsy\",\"heading\":\"CN4 — Trochlear Nerve Palsy\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"What it innervates: Superior oblique (SO) only — one nerve, one muscle. Why CN4 is special: Only CN to exit the dorsal (posterior) brainstem Longest intracranial course = most vulnerable to trauma CN4 nucleus is contralateral to the muscle it innervates (right CN4 nucleus → left SO) Clinical triad: Sign Mechanism Hypertropia (affected eye higher) SO underacts → eye rides up; contralateral IO compensates poorly Head tilt toward opposite shoulder Compensatory — keeps eyes aligned without using the paretic meridian Chin depression Avoids downgaze where SO is most needed Parks-Bielschowsky 3-Step Test: Which eye is hypertropic in primary gaze? → Identifies the hypertropic eye Does hypertropia worsen in right gaze or left gaze? → Identifies which pair of vertically acting muscles is involved Bielschowsky head tilt test — tilt toward the hypertropic eye: if hypertropia worsens → CN4 palsy confirmed Why Bielschowsky works: Tilting toward the hypertropic eye reflexively intorts that eye. The SO handles this intorsion. If SO is paretic, the superior rectus takes over intorsion — but also elevates the eye → hypertropia worsens. Causes: Congenital: most common overall (look for old photos with head tilt) Trauma: most common acquired cause (vulnerable at tentorial edge) Microvascular: DM, HTN — resolves in 3–6 months Bilateral CN4 palsy → suspect raised ICP or severe head trauma Management: Prism (base-down over hypertropic eye); observation for microvascular; surgery for persistent cases.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-details-cn6-abducens-nerve-palsy\",\"heading\":\"CN6 — Abducens Nerve Palsy\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"What it innervates: Lateral rectus (LR) only. Cardinal sign: Esotropia of the affected eye (unopposed MR action when LR is paretic) Clinical features: Feature Description Esotropia Worse at distance than near; incomitant Failure of abduction Cannot cross midline toward temple Horizontal diplopia Worse on ipsilateral gaze Face turn toward paretic side Compensatory; moves eye away from its action field False localizing sign: CN6 palsy with elevated ICP — nerve is compressed along its long clivus course regardless of lesion location. Causes: Microvascular (most common in adults): DM, HTN — resolves in 3–4 months Raised ICP: false localizing Trauma: basilar skull fracture Gradenigo's syndrome: CN6 palsy + ipsilateral facial pain + otitis media → petrous apex Children: rule out pontine glioma (urgent MRI) Key distinction from accommodative esotropia: CN6 palsy: acquired, incomitant, restricted abduction Accommodative ET: comitant, full ductions, associated with hyperopia Management: Patch or Fresnel prism; observation; botulinum toxin to MR; surgery for permanent cases.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-details-cn3-oculomotor-nerve-palsy-brief\",\"heading\":\"CN3 — Oculomotor Nerve Palsy (Brief)\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"What it innervates: SR, MR, IR, IO (4 recti + IO), levator palpebrae, pupillary sphincter (parasympathetic) Complete CN3 palsy: Ptosis (levator paralysis) Eye down and out (SO and LR unopposed) Fixed dilated pupil (mydriasis — parasympathetic involved) Diplopia Pupil-involving vs. pupil-sparing: Pupil-involved + painful = posterior communicating artery aneurysm (PCA aneurysm) — neurosurgical emergency Pupil-sparing = microvascular (DM, HTN) — monitor and resolve in 3 months Board pearl: Any third nerve palsy with pupil involvement = aneurysm until proven otherwise. This is a neurosurgical emergency.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-details-nystagmus\",\"heading\":\"Nystagmus\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Definition: Involuntary, rhythmic oscillation of the eyes. Classification by waveform: Type Description Localization Jerk nystagmus Slow drift + fast corrective saccade; named for FAST phase Vestibular, cerebellar, CNS Pendular nystagmus Equal velocity in both directions; no distinct fast phase MS (acquired); infantile (INS) Congenital / Infantile Nystagmus Syndrome (INS): Onset < 6 months Horizontal in all gaze positions (uniplanar) Dampens with convergence Null point → abnormal head position (AHP) is therapeutic Associated: albinism, congenital cataract, aniridia, achromatopsia Latent / Manifest-Latent Nystagmus: Only appears or worsens when one eye is covered Fast phase toward the viewing eye Associated with infantile esotropia Clinical trap: use +5.00 lens over \\\"occluded\\\" eye (fogs without triggering reflex) to get true VA Acquired Nystagmus — Key Types: Type Direction Localization Cause Downbeat Fast phase down Craniocervical junction Arnold-Chiari, cerebellar atrophy Upbeat Fast phase up Medulla/pons Brainstem infarct, Wernicke's See-saw One eye rises and intorts while other falls Parasellar Craniopharyngioma; bitemporal hemianopsia Periodic alternating (PAN) Reverses direction every ~90 sec Cerebellum (nodulus) Drug-induced (phenytoin), cerebellar lesion Vestibular Horizontal + torsional Peripheral: labyrinth; Central: brainstem BPPV vs. stroke Gaze-evoked Appears only in eccentric gaze Cerebellar / drug Anticonvulsants, cerebellar disease Alexander's Law: In jerk nystagmus, amplitude increases when gazing in the direction of the fast phase.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-the-details-cortical-visual-impairment-cvi\",\"heading\":\"Cortical Visual Impairment (CVI)\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Definition: Vision loss from retrogeniculate pathway damage (optic radiations / visual cortex) with structurally normal eyes (or vision worse than ocular pathology explains). Most common cause of visual impairment in children in developed countries. Causes: Perinatal hypoxia-ischemia (HIE, periventricular leukomalacia) — most common Premature birth (white matter injury) Hydrocephalus, TBI, CNS infections, metabolic disorders Roman-Kay 10 Behavioral Features of CVI: Preference for color (especially red and yellow) Need for movement to sustain attention Visual latency (delayed visual response) Visual field preference (lower fields often impaired) Difficulty with visual complexity (crowded/cluttered environments) Light-gazing; non-purposeful gaze Difficulty with distance viewing Atypical visual reflexes Difficulty with novel visual stimuli Absence of visually guided reach (severe cases) Diagnosis: Clinical (history + Roman-Kay features) + MRI (retrogeniculate injury) + VEP (delayed) Management: No cure; multidisciplinary rehabilitation; environmental modification (reduce visual clutter; use bright colors; single objects); functional vision training.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-visual-map-cn-palsy-quick-reference\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — CN Palsy Quick Reference\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"DIPLOPIA ONSET | +- --> HORIZONTAL DIPLOPIA (worse at distance) | → Esotropia + failed abduction → CN6 PALSY | → Check: Is this incomitant? → Yes = CN6 | → Gradenigo? (ear pain + facial pain) = Petrous apex | +- --> VERTICAL DIPLOPIA (worse on downgaze) | → Hypertropia + head tilt away → CN4 PALSY | → Parks-Bielschowsky 3-step → confirms SO | +- --> PTOSIS + EYE DOWN AND OUT | → CN3 PALSY | → Pupil involved? → ANEURYSM (emergency) | → Pupil spared? → Microvascular (observe 3 months) | +- --> NYSTAGMUS → Horizontal, present since birth, dampens on convergence → INS → Downbeat → craniocervical junction → See-saw + bitemporal VF loss → parasellar lesion → Appears on covering one eye → Latent nystagmus\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Feature CN4 Palsy CN6 Palsy CN3 Palsy Muscle affected Superior oblique Lateral rectus SR, MR, IR, IO, levator Diplopia direction Vertical (diagonal) Horizontal Oblique / any direction Eye position Hypertropia Esotropia Down and out Head posture Tilt away, chin down Turn toward paretic side May have no compensation Pupil involvement No No Yes (mydriasis) if compressive Worst on Downgaze (reading, stairs) Distance fixation, ipsilateral gaze All directions Emergency flag Bilateral → raised ICP Any CN6 in child Pupil-involved = aneurysm\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"CN4 nucleus Contralateral to the muscle CN4 palsy — most common acquired cause Trauma CN6 palsy — most common in adults Microvascular (DM/HTN) Microvascular CN6: expected resolution 3–4 months Microvascular CN4: expected resolution 3–6 months INS: onset < 6 months of life PAN nystagmus reversal interval ~90 seconds CVI: most common cause in children Perinatal hypoxia-ischemia\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"CN palsies — \\\"SO4, LR6, AO3\\\" Superior Oblique = CN4; Lateral Rectus = CN6; All Others = CN3 CN4 head posture \\\"Away and down\\\" — head tilts toward the opposite shoulder, chin down Bielschowsky \\\"Tilt toward the high eye — if it gets higher, that eye's SO is paretic\\\" CN3 pupil rule \\\"Pupil down = put your phone down and call neurosurgery\\\" — pupil-involving CN3 = aneurysm = emergency\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"CN4 palsy is named for the fast phase of nystagmus This is the naming rule for jerk nystagmus, not CN palsies. CN6 palsy always localizes to the pons CN6 is the false localizing sign; it can be compressed anywhere along its long course, especially with raised ICP. Congenital nystagmus is always vertical INS is characteristically horizontal in all gaze positions. Vertical nystagmus is always acquired. CVI patients have abnormal ocular findings The eyes are structurally normal in CVI; the vision loss is cortical. Pupils react normally; OCT shows normal retina. Latent nystagmus is tested by occluding one eye with a patch Occlusion triggers it, worsening VA. Use a +5.00 lens to fog the eye without triggering the reflex.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer CN4 palsy: 3-step test Parks-Bielschowsky CN4: head posture Tilt away from affected eye; chin down CN6: false localizing sign Raised ICP compresses nerve along clivus CN3 pupil-involving = PCA aneurysm — neurosurgical emergency INS: waveform Horizontal in all gaze positions INS: dampens with Convergence Latent nystagmus VA test Use +5.00 fog, not patch CVI: most common cause Perinatal hypoxia-ischemia CVI: eyes are Structurally normal\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"1. A 45-year-old diabetic patient reports vertical diplopia that is worst when going down stairs and when reading. On examination, the right eye is hypertropic and the patient tilts the head to the left. Bielschowsky head tilt test worsens the hypertropia when tilted right. What is the diagnosis? A. Right CN6 palsy B. Right CN3 palsy C. Right CN4 palsy D. Left CN4 palsy Answer C. Right CN4 palsy. Vertical diplopia worst on downgaze + right hypertropia + head tilt to the left (away from affected side) + positive Bielschowsky when tilted toward the hypertropic (right) eye = right superior oblique palsy = right CN4 palsy. 2. A 2-year-old child is referred for poor visual tracking. The parents note that she uses one eye more than the other and has difficulty looking at complex images. MRI shows periventricular leukomalacia. VA testing with preferential looking shows reduced responses. Which diagnosis best fits? A. Infantile esotropia with amblyopia B. Latent nystagmus C. Cortical visual impairment (CVI) D. Congenital cataract Answer C. Cortical Visual Impairment. History of neurological insult (periventricular leukomalacia — white matter damage) + behavioral visual characteristics (preference, difficulty with complexity, visual latency) + normal-appearing anterior and posterior segments + reduced VEP-based VA = CVI. The diagnosis is behavioral and neuroimaging-based, not based on ocular structural findings.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4-01-neuro-optometry-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F4 — Neuro-Optometry and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the CN palsy triad for CN4, CN6, and CN3 from memory. Include the head posture compensation for each, and the emergency flag for CN3. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the CN palsy comparison table from memory: 8 rows (muscle, diplopia direction, eye position, head posture, pupil, worst on, emergency flag). Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a student why tilting the head toward the hypertropic eye worsens CN4 palsy — without using the words \\\"intorsion,\\\" \\\"superior oblique,\\\" or \\\"superior rectus.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back SO4, LR6 — what innervates all other EOM? CN3 CN6 = false localizing sign because Long clivus course; any ICP rise compresses it CN3 pupil-involved = PCA aneurysm → emergency INS waveform Horizontal in ALL gaze positions Latent nystagmus — test VA with +5.00 fog lens, not patch Downbeat nystagmus localizes to Craniocervical junction CVI most common cause Periventricular leukomalacia / HIE Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the Parks-Bielschowsky 3-step test from memory: step 1, step 2, step 3, and the reasoning for why step 3 works. Source: Gap Lectures 01 (CN4), 02 (CN6), 03 (Nystagmus), 04 (CVI) Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Occupational optometry is about ensuring workers can see safely and efficiently in their specific work environment. It covers three things: understanding the visual demands of different jobs, identifying ocular hazards in the workplace, and prescribing the right protective eyewear and corrective devices for those demands. Environmental optometry is the broader principle — how the visual system interacts with any environment, including the workplace. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"A welder, an office worker on a computer all day, and a surgeon all have different visual demands. What do they share that makes them all occupational optometry patients?\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-key-definitions\",\"heading\":\"Key Definitions\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Term Definition Occupational Optometry Portion of optometric practice concerned with efficient and safe visual functioning within the work environment Environmental Optometry Discipline concerned with the interaction of the visual system with the environment (home, school, work, recreation, transport) Industrial Vision Devoted to protection of the eye in the workplace from flying objects, radiation, and lasers Occupational (Industrial) Hygiene Art and science dedicated to anticipation, recognition, evaluation, and control of workplace environmental stressors\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-regulatory-framework\",\"heading\":\"Regulatory Framework\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"International: WHO (World Health Organization) — collaborates with member states on occupational health surveys ILO (International Labour Organization) — prevention of occupational injuries; promotion of safety and well-being ICOH (International Commission on Occupational Health) — specialist committees on specific hazards Philippines (Local): DOLE (Department of Labor and Employment) — implements labor laws and policies OSHS (Occupational Safety and Health Standards) — conducts research on workplace safety; monitors working environments; conducts medical examinations for workers exposed to hazardous substances SSS (Social Security System) — RA 8282 — protection against sickness, disability, maternity, old age, death GSIS (Government Service Insurance System) — same as SSS for government employees\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-ocular-hazards-in-the-workplace\",\"heading\":\"Ocular Hazards in the Workplace\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Hazard Type Examples Ocular Risk Mechanical / Particulate Grinding, drilling, carpentry, construction Corneal foreign body; penetrating injury Radiation — UV Welding arc, solar exposure, tanning booths Photokeratitis (welder's flash); pterygium; cataract Radiation — Infrared (IR) Glassblowing, furnace work, foundry Thermal damage to cornea and lens; IR cataract Radiation — Visible light Laser use, arc welding Retinal photocoagulation; macular burn Chemical splash Laboratories, agriculture, manufacturing Chemical burns (acid or alkali) Computer / Digital display Office work, programming, data entry Computer vision syndrome (CVS): eye strain, dry eye, headaches Priority in chemical burns: Irrigate FIRST with water or saline for at least 20–30 minutes. Take history AFTER. This is a strict rule — alkali burns penetrate deeper and faster.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-computer-vision-syndrome-cvs-digital-eye-strain\",\"heading\":\"Computer Vision Syndrome (CVS) / Digital Eye Strain\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Definition: A cluster of eye and vision problems related to prolonged use of computers and digital devices. Symptoms: Eye strain, blurred near vision, dry eyes, headaches, neck and shoulder pain Causes: Reduced blink rate during screen use (normal: 15–20/min; screen: ~5/min) Accommodative demand at screen distance (usually 50–70 cm) Glare from screen or overhead lighting Uncorrected or under-corrected refractive error Poor workstation ergonomics Management — 20-20-20 rule: Every 20 minutes, look at something 20 feet away for 20 seconds. Prescribing for screen users: Single-vision near lenses for presbyopes who use progressive and struggle at screen distance Anti-reflection coating to reduce glare Screen distance add: typically 0.50–1.00D less than full near add Blue-light filtering lenses (optional; evidence is limited but patient-acceptable)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-protective-eyewear\",\"heading\":\"Protective Eyewear\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"OSHS standards for protective eyewear apply in the Philippines. Types of protection: Protection Type Indication Safety glasses (with side shields) Moderate impact hazard; grinding, chipping Goggles (sealed) Chemical splash; fine dust; severe impact Face shield Full-face chemical splash protection; in addition to goggles, not instead Welding helmet / filtered goggles UV and IR radiation from welding arc Laser safety goggles Specific wavelength-blocking for laser type used Lens standards (ANSI Z87.1 / Philippines equivalent): Impact resistance: polycarbonate is preferred (highest impact resistance) Side protection required for most industrial environments UV protection required for outdoor and welding work Shade number system for welding filters: Shade number increases with arc intensity Higher shade = darker lens = more protection from the brighter arc Shade 10–13 typically used for arc welding\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-6-basic-employee-benefits-philippines-labor-law-testable\",\"heading\":\"6 Basic Employee Benefits (Philippines Labor Law — Testable)\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"SSS / GSIS contributions PhilHealth (National Health Insurance Program — NHIP) Pag-IBIG (HDMF — Home Development and Mutual Fund) 13th month pay (due December 24) Service incentive leave (5 days per year after 1 year of service) Meal and rest periods Leave entitlements (testable): Maternity leave: 105 days (RA 11210 — Expanded Maternity Leave Law); additional 30 days without pay; +15 days for solo mothers Paternity leave: 7 working days (RA 8187) Sick/vacation leave: 15 days each with pay (for government employees)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-vision-standards-for-specific-occupations\",\"heading\":\"Vision Standards for Specific Occupations\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Occupation Vision Requirement Drivers (commercial) Minimum VA with correction; adequate peripheral fields; color vision Pilots Strict VA and color vision standards (Civil Aviation Authority) Seafarers (MARINA standards) Specified distance VA; color vision (Ishihara/Farnsworth D-15) Police / Military VA and color vision standards per agency Industrial workers (hazardous) Pre-employment eye exam; periodic occupational exams\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-the-details-ocular-safety-plan-key-components\",\"heading\":\"Ocular Safety Plan — Key Components\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"An optometrist developing an ocular safety plan for a workplace should include: Hazard identification and risk assessment Selection and provision of appropriate protective eyewear Employee training on eye safety and PPE use Pre-employment and periodic vision examinations Emergency protocols (eye wash stations, chemical spill procedures) Record-keeping and reporting of occupational eye injuries\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Feature Industrial Vision Occupational Vision Environmental Vision Focus Eye protection in workplace Ensuring adequate visual skills for the job Interaction of visual system with any environment Hazard emphasis Flying objects, radiation, lasers Refractive needs, binocular demands Lighting, glare, display design Prescription concern Protective eyewear selection Task-specific optics Environmental modification\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Maternity leave (RA 11210) 105 days Paternity leave (RA 8187) 7 working days Service incentive leave 5 days/year after 1 year of service 13th month pay due December 24 20-20-20 rule 20 min / 20 feet / 20 seconds Normal blink rate 15–20 per minute Screen blink rate ~5 per minute Chemical burn: first action Irrigate 20–30 min BEFORE history\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"CVS = 3 C's Convergence demand + Computer glare + Can't blink normally 20-20-20 \\\"Every 20 minutes, 20 feet, 20 seconds\\\" — can be written as 20/20/20 Chemical burn rule \\\"Water before words\\\" — irrigate before you take a history 6 employee benefits SSS/GSIS — PhilHealth — Pag-IBIG — 13th month — SIL — Meals\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"A face shield replaces goggles in chemical splash situations A face shield is always in addition to, not a replacement for, splash goggles. The face shield protects the face; the sealed goggles protect the eyes. GSIS covers private sector employees GSIS is for government employees; SSS is for private sector. Maternity leave is 60 days under current law RA 11210 (2019) expanded it to 105 days. Chemical burns — history first, then irrigate Irrigate immediately. The cause matters less than stopping ongoing damage. All occupational eye exams are the same The exam is tailored to the job's visual demands — a driver needs fields and color vision assessed; a computer worker needs accommodative function assessed.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Chemical burn — first step Irrigate (water/saline) for 20–30 min CVS 20-20-20 rule Every 20 min → 20 feet → 20 sec Maternity leave (RA 11210) 105 days Paternity leave (RA 8187) 7 working days OSHS under DOLE Best lens material for protective eyewear Polycarbonate IR radiation risk Thermal lens/cornea damage; IR cataract UV radiation in welding Photokeratitis (welder's flash)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"1. A worker splashes a chemical solvent into their eye. What is the immediate correct action? A. Identify the chemical first, then call poison control before irrigating B. Apply a bandage contact lens to protect the cornea C. Irrigate with clean water or saline for at least 20–30 minutes immediately D. Instill proparacaine and refer to the emergency room without irrigation Answer C. Irrigation is the first and most critical action regardless of the chemical involved. Alkali burns (especially) continue to penetrate deeper every second without irrigation. History and identification are done AFTER starting irrigation. 2. A graphic designer working 10 hours daily on a computer complains of eye strain, headache, and blurred vision at the end of the day. Which of the following is NOT part of the management? A. Prescribing anti-reflection coated lenses B. Advising the 20-20-20 rule C. Prescribing a slightly reduced near add for screen distance if presbyopic D. Prescribing cycloplegic drops for daily use to relax the ciliary muscle Answer D. Cycloplegic drops are diagnostic agents — never prescribed for daily home use. They abolish accommodation, which would make near work impossible and cause photophobia. Management of CVS includes AR coating, the 20-20-20 rule, workstation optimization, and possibly task-specific lenses.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5-01-occupational-optometry-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F5 — Occupational and Environmental Optometry\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the 6 employee benefits, the 4 types of workplace ocular hazards with examples, and the 20-20-20 rule from memory. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the ocular hazard table from memory: Hazard type / Examples / Ocular risk — 6 rows. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a factory manager why protective goggles must be used in addition to a face shield — in 3 sentences, without using the word \\\"sealed.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Chemical burn first action Irrigate 20–30 min before history Maternity leave days 105 (RA 11210) Paternity leave days 7 (RA 8187) 13th month pay due December 24 CVS 20-20-20 Every 20 min → 20 feet → 20 sec Protective eyewear material Polycarbonate GSIS vs. SSS GSIS = government; SSS = private sector Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the components of an occupational vision safety plan from memory — 6 components, what each addresses. Source: Occupational and Industrial Optometry | Gap Lecture 10 (SSS/PhilHealth/Pag-IBIG) Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Sports vision is the branch of optometry that evaluates and enhances an athlete's visual performance. The eyes are the primary input system for sport — if the visual input is inaccurate, delayed, or incomplete, motor output (catching, hitting, throwing) suffers. Sports vision goes beyond measuring 20/20 acuity. It tests dynamic acuity, depth perception, reaction time, eye-hand coordination, and peripheral awareness — the visual skills specific to athletic performance. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"A baseball batter with 20/20 VA still can't hit a fastball consistently. What visual skill is likely deficient and how would you test it?\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-key-definitions\",\"heading\":\"Key Definitions\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Term Definition Sports Vision Program addressing all visual needs of an athlete — assessment, correction, protection, and enhancement Sight Ability to see (sensory input; organ = eye) Vision Ability to gain meaning from what the eyes see (brain integration) Dynamic Visual Acuity VA for a moving target or while the observer is moving Static Visual Acuity VA for a stationary target Basic premise: Eyes input → brain integrates + other senses → body responds (arms, legs, balance). If the eye's message is inaccurate, incomplete, or delayed → performance suffers.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-services-in-sports-vision\",\"heading\":\"Services in Sports Vision\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Detection of visual problems affecting performance Correction of refractive errors Enhancement of visual skills through vision training Protection from ocular injury Assessment and management of sports-related ocular trauma Sports vision counselling Stages of sports vision delivery: Ocular health examination Prescription of corrective device Dispensing of protective eyewear Sports-related injuries and first aid Sports vision counselling Visual skill testing Vision training / enhancement\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-visual-skills-in-sports\",\"heading\":\"Visual Skills in Sports\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Sensory skills: Static visual acuity (high and low contrast) Dynamic visual acuity Color vision Depth perception Peripheral vision Speed of recognition Cognitive skills: Visual closure Visual discrimination Visual memory Visual spatial relationships Visual figure-ground Visual sequential memory Visual form constancy Motor skills: Eye-hand coordination Eye-body coordination Central-peripheral awareness\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-sports-vision-assessment\",\"heading\":\"Sports Vision Assessment\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Test What It Measures Instrument Static VA Clarity at rest Snellen / ETDRS chart Dynamic VA Clarity for a moving target Tachistoscope, Sherman Dynamic Acuity Disc, Marsden Ball Contrast sensitivity Fine spatial frequency discrimination Pelli-Robson chart; Sine-Wave Grating chart Depth perception Stereoscopic vision Stereo Fly Test; Randot; pencil test (2-lang) Binocular vision Fusion, phoria, vergence Worth 4 Dot, Maddox rod, RAF rule, Brock string, tranaglyph Accommodation Amplitude and facility Flipper lens; RAF rule Eye-hand coordination Motor response accuracy Wayne Saccadic Fixator; Chaos Ball Visual memory Short-term visual recall Visual Sequencer Peripheral awareness Central-peripheral integration Amsler grid (central); confrontation test (field)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-tinted-lenses-for-sports\",\"heading\":\"Tinted Lenses for Sports\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Tint / Color Wavelengths Filtered Benefits Best Sport / Condition Green Broad uniform Transmits all colors evenly; general purpose All outdoor activities; rain or sun Brown / Amber Blue and violet Improves contrast; depth perception (red element) Golf; tennis; high-altitude; partly cloudy to sunny Yellow Blue and violet Greater clarity in fog, haze, low light Fishing; boating; distance judgment sports Blue / Purple Red and yellow (partial) Fashionable; reduces glare; contour visibility Golf; mountain biking; target shooting Gray Uniform (neutral density) Reduces intensity without color distortion Driving; general sun use Orange / Red Most short wavelengths Maximum contrast; eliminates blue-wave glare Achromatopsia; RP; severe photophobia\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-the-details-protective-eyewear-in-sports\",\"heading\":\"Protective Eyewear in Sports\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Why it matters: Sports account for a significant proportion of eye injuries in young people. Most are preventable with proper protective eyewear. ASTM International Standards (F803): Racquet sports (squash, racquetball, tennis): require ASTM F803-certified polycarbonate lenses Hockey: requires full face shield or certified hockey visor Baseball/softball: batting helmets with polycarbonate face guards Key material: Polycarbonate lenses — most impact resistant; absorb UV inherently; 30–40% thinner than CR-39 for the same power. Contact lenses in sports: Soft CLs: appropriate for most sports; no protective function; daily disposables preferred for sports use (hygiene, cost of loss) RGP: may dislodge; not ideal for contact sports CLs do not provide UV or impact protection — protective eyewear is still required\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-visual-map-sports-vision-service-flow\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — Sports Vision Service Flow\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"ATHLETE PRESENTS FOR SPORTS VISION ASSESSMENT | v OCULAR HEALTH EXAM (Slit lamp, fundus, IOP ) | v REFRACTIVE ASSESSMENT (Static VA, cycloplegic if needed, best correction) | v VISUAL SKILLS BATTERY Static VA → Dynamic VA → Contrast Sensitivity Depth Perception → BV (phoria, vergence) → Accommodation Eye-Hand Coordination → Peripheral Awareness | v IDENTIFY DEFICIENT SKILLS | +- --> Optical correction needed → Prescribe + counsel on CL/eyewear for sport +- --> Visual skill deficit → Vision training program (Brock string, tranaglyphs, Wayne fixator) +- --> Protection needed → Sport-appropriate protective eyewear ( ASTM standard) | v FOLLOW-UP AND PERFORMANCE MONITORING\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Feature Static VA Dynamic VA Target Stationary Moving Tested with Snellen / ETDRS Tachistoscope / Marsden Ball Sport relevance Baseline; needed for all Critical for ball sports, combat sports Board clue Standard 20/20 testing \\\"The player sees well but can't track the ball\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Sports vision primary lens material Polycarbonate ASTM F803 Racquet sports protective eyewear standard Normal blink rate 15–20 per minute Tachistoscope exposure time 0.01 seconds\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Sports vision = S-C-P-E Assessment, Correction, Protection, Enhancement (also called vision training) Tint for depth perception sports (golf/tennis) Brown/amber — \\\"Brown for Ball sports\\\" (contains red element, enhances depth) Yellow tint \\\"Yellow = foggy weather\\\" — increases contrast in haze and low light conditions\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"20/20 VA means no visual deficiency for sports Dynamic VA, depth perception, eye-hand coordination, and peripheral awareness are all independent skills that 20/20 does not measure. Contact lenses provide protection in sports CLs provide no impact or UV protection. Protective eyewear is still required. Gray tint improves contrast for sports Gray is a neutral density filter — it reduces all wavelengths equally without improving contrast. Brown/amber improves contrast. ASTM F803 applies to all sports F803 applies specifically to racquet sports. Other sports have different standards (hockey visor, baseball batting helmet).\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Best tint for fog/haze visibility Yellow Best tint for depth perception (golf/tennis) Brown or amber Dynamic VA instrument Tachistoscope; Marsden Ball Eye-hand coordination instrument Wayne Saccadic Fixator Contrast sensitivity chart Pelli-Robson Best protective eyewear material Polycarbonate Racquet sports standard ASTM F803 CLs provide protection? No — still need protective eyewear\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"1. A tennis player with 20/20 static VA reports difficulty tracking the ball on serve. Which visual skill is most likely deficient and what instrument would you use to assess it? A. Color vision; Ishihara plates B. Dynamic visual acuity; Tachistoscope or Marsden Ball C. Stereopsis; Stereo Fly Test D. Contrast sensitivity; Pelli-Robson chart Answer B. Difficulty tracking a moving ball despite normal static VA indicates a dynamic visual acuity problem. The tachistoscope (presents targets for 0.01 seconds) or the Marsden Ball (moving target in three dimensions) is used to assess dynamic VA. 2. A golfer asks what tint would best help them on partly cloudy to sunny days and improve their depth perception for distance judgment. What would you recommend? A. Gray B. Yellow C. Brown or amber D. Blue Answer C. Brown or amber. These tints contain a red element that enhances depth perception — beneficial for judging distance in golf. They work well in partly cloudy to sunny conditions. Gray reduces intensity without improving contrast. Yellow is better for haze and low light. Blue is cosmetically popular but not clinically superior for this purpose.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6-01-sports-vision-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F6 — Sports Vision\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the sports vision visual skills categories (sensory, cognitive, motor) with 3 examples under each from memory. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the tinted lenses for sports table from memory: Tint / Benefits / Best Sport / Condition — 6 rows. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to an athlete why having 20/20 acuity is not enough for peak sports performance. Use a specific example from their sport. Do not use the term \\\"dynamic visual acuity.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Yellow tint — best condition Fog, haze, low light Brown/amber — best sport Golf, tennis (depth perception) Tachistoscope — measures Dynamic visual acuity Wayne Saccadic Fixator — measures Eye-hand coordination Racquet sports eyewear standard ASTM F803 Best material for sports protection Polycarbonate Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the sports vision assessment battery in order — from baseline health exam to skill testing to prescribing and training — 7 stages. Source: Sports Vision Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Low vision is vision loss that cannot be fully corrected with standard glasses, contact lenses, or medical treatment, yet leaves some usable vision. The goal of low vision care is not to restore 20/20 — it is to maximize the patient's functional vision for their specific daily tasks. This requires choosing the right magnification device, training the patient to use eccentric viewing if the fovea is damaged, and modifying the environment to support whatever vision remains. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"A patient with 20/200 VA wants to read the newspaper. What magnification do they need, and where does that number come from?\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-key-definitions\",\"heading\":\"Key Definitions\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"WHO definition of Blindness: VA ≤ 20/200 (or equivalent) in the better eye after best correction; OR visual field < 10° from fixation Legal Blindness (US standard, also used in PH exams): VA ≤ 20/200 with best correction in the better eye; OR visual field ≤ 20° in the widest meridian WHO definition of Low Vision: VA < 20/70 (6/18) but > 20/200 in the better eye after best correction; OR visual field < 20° from fixation, but some usable vision remains Functional definition (most clinically relevant): A person with low vision cannot fully remediate their vision impairment with conventional spectacles, CLs, or medical intervention, and this causes restriction in daily life. ICD-11 Classification (2018): Category VA Range Mild 20/40 – 20/60 Moderate < 20/60 – 20/200 Severe < 20/200 – 20/400 Blindness < 20/400 (worse than 3/60)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-common-causes-of-low-vision\",\"heading\":\"Common Causes of Low Vision\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Adults over 50: Cataract (62.6%) — most common globally; avoidable Refractive error (19.7%) Glaucoma (5.8%) Posterior segment disorders (4.7%) Corneal opacity (0.9%) Children: Refractive error (33.3%) Congenital anomalies (25%) Retinal degeneration (16.7%) Vitamin A deficiency (8.3%) Global: 285 million visually impaired worldwide; 39 million blind; 246 million low vision; 80% of blindness is avoidable.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-low-vision-rehabilitation-concepts\",\"heading\":\"Low Vision Rehabilitation Concepts\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Rehabilitation vs. Habilitation: Rehabilitation: Re-teaching a skill to someone who had it and lost it (acquired vision loss) Habilitation: Teaching a skill to someone who never had it (congenital vision loss) The rehabilitation chain: Visual disorder → visual impairment (functional limitation) → visual disability (skill reduction) → visual handicap (psychosocial/economic consequence) The goal of rehabilitation is to break the chain before it reaches handicap — maximize remaining function at the impairment level.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-magnification-principles-and-calculation\",\"heading\":\"Magnification — Principles and Calculation\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Why magnification works: Enlarging the retinal image allows it to be processed by remaining functioning photoreceptors outside the damaged fovea. Four types of magnification: Type How It Works Example Relative size Make the object physically larger Large-print books, enlarged font on phone Relative distance Move closer to the object Bring reading material from 40 cm to 10 cm Angular Use a lens or optical device to enlarge the visual angle Magnifiers, telescopes Electronic Digitally enlarge and enhance CCTV, tablet with zoom Calculating required magnification: M = Required VA / Present Near VA Or using dioptric method: M = Required add power / 4 (Reference standard: 4D = 1x at 25 cm) Example: Patient best near VA: N24 at 40 cm Task demand: N8 M = 24/8 = 3× Required add: 3 × 4 = +12.00D Working distance: 100/12 = 8.3 cm\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-low-vision-devices\",\"heading\":\"Low Vision Devices\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Near devices: Device Power Range Advantage Limitation Spectacle magnifier (high add) +4.00D to +40.00D Hands-free; best for sustained reading Very short working distance Handheld magnifier Variable Portable; flexible working distance Needs steady hand; not hands-free Stand magnifier Variable Stable; no hand steadiness needed; useful in tremor Fixed focal distance; shorter field Electronic magnifier (CCTV/tablet) Variable electronic Best for sustained reading; contrast control; adjustable Expensive; less portable Distance devices: Device Type Use Monocular telescope Hand-held or spectacle-mounted Spot viewing (TV, signs, boards) Binocular telescope Spectacle-mounted Extended distance viewing Telemicroscope Telescope focused at near Specific near tasks at a set distance Non-optical aids: Aid Purpose Typoscope Black card with window cut out; reduces glare and isolates the reading line Reading stand Holds material at correct distance and angle; reduces fatigue Filters / absorptive lenses Reduces glare; improves contrast (CPF series) Lighting control Task lighting; lamp positioning; reduce veiling glare Large-print materials Relative size magnification\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-eccentric-viewing-ev-training\",\"heading\":\"Eccentric Viewing (EV) Training\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"When the fovea is damaged (AMD, macular scar, macular dystrophy), the patient must learn to use a healthier peripheral retinal area as the preferred retinal locus (PRL). Training methods: Steady eye strategy: teach patient to hold their eye steadily on a peripheral fixation point Clock face method: describe where the scotoma is on a clock face; teach patient to look \\\"off-center\\\" by a specific amount and direction Amsler grid: monitor the scotoma size and location\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-the-details-referral-and-follow-up-in-low-vision\",\"heading\":\"Referral and Follow-Up in Low Vision\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"When to refer: VA worse than 20/70 after best correction that cannot be further improved medically Patient has a task they cannot perform with current correction Low vision team: Low vision optometrist: device prescription and training Orientation and mobility specialist: safe travel training Occupational therapist: activities of daily living Social worker: psychosocial and financial support Teacher of the visually impaired: literacy and education\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-visual-map-low-vision-management-flow\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — Low Vision Management Flow\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"PATIENT WITH REDUCED VA | v Best corrected VA (trial frame; large lens steps for low VA patients) | v Is VA ≥ 20/70? → Conventional spectacle management | v Is VA < 20/70 → Low vision assessment | v Document: Distance VA + Near VA + Visual Field + Contrast Sensitivity | v Calculate required magnification for patient's primary task | v Select appropriate device (Near: magnifier/spectacle; Distance: telescope) | v Demonstrate device; patient trial; check VA with device | v Train: insertion, use, eccentric viewing if needed | v Follow-up: task performance, device comfort, environment modification\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"WHO blindness VA cutoff ≤ 20/200 in better eye with best correction WHO low vision VA range < 20/70 to > 20/200 Legal blindness VA ≤ 20/200; or field ≤ 20° Reference magnification standard 4D = 1× at 25 cm Globally visually impaired 285 million Globally blind 39 million Leading cause globally Cataract (62.6%) % avoidable blindness 80%\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"4 magnification types — RRАЕ Relative size, Relative distance, Angular, Electronic Magnification formula shortcut \\\"Add ÷ 4 = times\\\" — divide the needed add power by 4 to get the magnification, or multiply the magnification by 4 to get the add. Low vision device selection Near sustained work → spectacle magnifier; near spot reading → handheld; tremor patient → stand magnifier; distance spotting → monocular telescope\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"All patients with low vision need telescopes Telescopes are for distance tasks. Most low vision patients need near magnification first. Prescribing from uncorrected VA Magnification is calculated from best-corrected VA, not uncorrected. Always refract first. The goal of low vision care is 20/20 The goal is functional vision for the patient's specific needs. Trying to achieve 20/20 in low vision patients is unrealistic and misleading. Eccentric viewing training is only for AMD Any central scotoma (macular dystrophy, histoplasmosis, macular scar from any cause) may benefit from EV training.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer WHO low vision cutoff < 20/70 in better eye WHO blindness cutoff ≤ 20/200 in better eye Reference standard for magnification 4D = 1× Magnification formula M = Required VA / Present VA Equivalent add M × 4 Most common cause of blindness globally Cataract % avoidable blindness 80% Best device for sustained reading (tremor patient) Stand magnifier\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"1. A patient with AMD has best corrected near VA of N32 at 40 cm. Their goal is to read N8 print. What magnification and add power are needed? A. 2×; +8.00D add B. 4×; +16.00D add C. 3×; +12.00D add D. 2×; +12.00D add Answer B. 4×; +16.00D add. M = 32/8 = 4×. Equivalent add = 4 × 4 = +16.00D. Working distance = 100/16 = 6.25 cm. The patient must read at approximately 6 cm from the lens. 2. Which of the following best describes the goal of low vision rehabilitation? A. Restore best corrected VA to 20/20 through stronger lenses B. Maximize functional vision for the patient's specific daily tasks using optical and non-optical aids C. Replace all current spectacles with a single-lens magnifier system D. Provide training only for patients with VA better than 20/200 Answer B. Low vision rehabilitation aims to maximize the patient's functional use of remaining vision — not restore normal VA. It is task-specific and uses a combination of optical devices, non-optical aids, environmental modifications, and eccentric viewing training based on the patient's needs.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7-01-low-vision-and-rehabilitation-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F7 — Low Vision and Rehabilitation\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the WHO definitions for blindness and low vision (with VA cutoffs), the magnification formula, and 4 types of near LV devices from memory. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the LV near devices table: Device / Power Range / Advantage / Limitation — 4 rows. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a patient with AMD why the goal of their visit is not to make their vision \\\"normal\\\" — in 4 sentences, without using the phrase \\\"low vision.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back 4D = ? magnification 1× WHO blindness cutoff ≤ 20/200 better eye WHO LV cutoff < 20/70 better eye Magnification formula M = required VA / present VA Equivalent add formula M × 4 Best for tremor patient near Stand magnifier Most common cause of blindness globally Cataract Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the low vision management flow from initial presentation to follow-up — 7 steps — on a blank page. Source: Low Vision | Gap Lecture 13 (AMD) | LV Definition/Prevalence series Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"This subtopic covers two separate but related areas. Ocular prosthesis is for patients who have lost an eye — the goal is cosmetic rehabilitation, socket health, and psychological support. Absorptive lenses are for patients who need selective filtering of light — either to protect the eye from UV/IR radiation or to improve functional vision in patients with photophobia and low contrast sensitivity. The board tests prosthesis types and care schedules, and absorptive lens prescribing matched to specific diagnoses. Teaching angle: Ask: \\\"A patient whose eye was removed 6 months ago is now having daily irritation and discharge. What are the three most likely causes and how do you manage each?\\\"\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-a-ocular-prosthesis-why-it-is-needed\",\"heading\":\"Why It Is Needed\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"After loss of an eye (enucleation, evisceration) or severe disfigurement (phthisis bulbi, anophthalmos), an ocular prosthesis: Maintains the volume of the orbit (prevents socket collapse) Provides cosmetic rehabilitation Maintains fornix depth (prevents contracted socket) Supports psychological well-being Surgical procedures: Enucleation: Complete removal of the globe; orbital implant placed; prosthesis over the implant Evisceration: Intraocular contents removed; scleral shell preserved; better motility Exenteration: Orbital contents removed (radical; for malignancy) — full prosthesis or orbital prosthesis required\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-a-ocular-prosthesis-types-of-ocular-prostheses\",\"heading\":\"Types of Ocular Prostheses\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Type Description Use Stock (ready-made) Pre-manufactured; standard sizes; generic iris Temporary; resource-limited settings Custom prosthesis (PMMA) Hand-crafted; individually fitted by ocularist; PMMA material Standard of care for long-term rehabilitation Scleral shell Thin custom shell over an existing shrunken globe (phthisis) Phthisis bulbi; microphthalmos Conformer Clear plastic shell placed immediately post-surgery Prevents socket contraction during healing; replaced by definitive prosthesis at 6–8 weeks Material: Polymethylmethacrylate (PMMA / acrylic) — same material used for some CL lenses and ophthalmic lens materials.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-a-ocular-prosthesis-care-and-maintenance-schedule\",\"heading\":\"Care and Maintenance Schedule\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Task Frequency Daily cleaning Remove; rinse with saline; reinsert Socket hygiene Flush socket with sterile saline each time Polishing by ocularist Every 6–12 months Replacement (adults) Every 5–7 years Replacement (children) More frequently — growing orbit requires larger prosthesis Sleeping Most patients keep prosthesis in; remove only on ocularist's advice What to use: Sterile saline, mild soap. Never alcohol, detergents, or tap water for soaking (Acanthamoeba risk from tap water). Signs to see the ocularist: Increased discharge Socket redness / irritation Visible scratches on prosthesis Reduced motility Poor cosmetic match (indicates socket volume change)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-a-ocular-prosthesis-contracted-socket\",\"heading\":\"Contracted Socket\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Complication of poor prosthetic care or prolonged absence of prosthesis Fornices shrink → socket volume decreases → cannot retain prosthesis Prevention: Consistent prosthesis wear; immediate conformer placement post-surgery\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-b-absorptive-lenses-the-electromagnetic-spectrum-board-relevant-wavelengths\",\"heading\":\"The Electromagnetic Spectrum — Board-Relevant Wavelengths\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Range Wavelength Ocular Risk UV-C 100–280 nm Blocked by atmosphere; minimal clinical concern outdoors UV-B 280–315 nm Photokeratitis; climatic droplet keratopathy; cataract UV-A 315–400 nm Cataract; possible macular damage HEV / Blue light 400–500 nm Implicated in retinal phototoxicity; ARMD Visible 400–700 nm Normal photopic vision Infrared (IR) > 700 nm Thermal damage; IR cataract (glassblowers, furnace workers) Standard clear lenses (CR-39, poly, hi-index) block UV up to ~380 nm. Polycarbonate blocks UV up to 385 nm inherently.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-b-absorptive-lenses-photochromic-lenses\",\"heading\":\"Photochromic Lenses\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Mechanism: Silver halide crystals (silver chloride/bromide in glass) or organic dye molecules (plastic) that darken reversibly when exposed to UV Activate outdoors (UV present); clear indoors Limitation: Do not activate inside a car — windshield blocks UV Darkening time: 30–60 seconds; clearing time: 2–5 minutes\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-b-absorptive-lenses-corning-cpf-contrast-preservation-filters\",\"heading\":\"Corning CPF (Contrast Preservation Filters)\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Longpass filters designed for patients with photosensitivity and reduced contrast sensitivity (low vision, cataract, RP, AMD). Filter Cutoff Wavelength Color Primary Use CPF 450 Cuts below 450 nm Very light yellow Minimal photophobia; early lens changes CPF 511 Cuts below 511 nm Yellow-orange Moderate photophobia; nuclear cataract CPF 527 Cuts below 527 nm Orange RP; glaucoma; macular disease Wratten filter numbers: Used in occupational and research contexts; higher number = longer cutoff wavelength = more blocking of short-wave light. Examples: Wratten #12 = yellow; Wratten #15 = deep yellow; Wratten #22 = orange; Wratten #29 = red.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-part-b-absorptive-lenses-diagnosis-linked-absorptive-lens-prescribing\",\"heading\":\"Diagnosis-Linked Absorptive Lens Prescribing\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Diagnosis Recommended Lens Albinism Deep absorptive (orange/red tint); 80–90% transmission blocking; UV 400 essential Aniridia High-transmission absorptive; photochromic or fixed tint; pupil replica lens (cosmetic) Achromatopsia (rod monochromacy) Red or deep orange tint; eliminates short-wavelength stimulation of remaining cone photoreceptors; CPF 527 or darker Retinitis Pigmentosa (RP) Yellow or amber (CPF 511/527); reduces blue-light scatter; protects remaining rods; photochromic acceptable Age-Related Macular Degeneration Yellow/amber tint; AREDS2 lutein and zeaxanthin (dietary); CPF 450–511 Cataract (pre-surgical) CPF 511 or 527 to reduce glare from light scatter in the lens Glaucoma Absorptive to manage photophobia; avoid heavy tints that reduce available light for already-restricted fields Cone dystrophy Red-blocking; similar to achromatopsia prescription\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-visual-map-absorptive-lens-prescribing-decision\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map — Absorptive Lens Prescribing Decision\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"PATIENT WITH PHOTOPHOBIA OR CONTRAST DIFFICULTY | v Identify diagnosis: | +- --> Achromatopsia / Cone dystrophy → Red/deep orange tint ( CPF 527 +) +- --> RP → Amber/yellow ( CPF 511 or 527) +- --> Cataract (pre-op) → CPF 511 or 527 +- --> AMD → CPF 450 –511; Amsler monitoring +- --> Albinism / Aniridia → High-absorption tint + UV 400 +- --> Glaucoma → Light absorptive; avoid dark tints | v Select: — Fixed tint for consistent indoor/outdoor photophobia — Photochromic for variable conditions (note: does not work in car) — CPF filter if contrast loss is the primary complaint\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-comparisons-that-matter\",\"heading\":\"Comparisons That Matter\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Feature Stock Prosthesis Custom PMMA Prosthesis Fit Standard Individually fitted to socket Cosmesis Poor color match Hand-painted; matched to fellow eye Motility Minimal Better (coordinated with implant) Discharge More (poor fit) Less Duration Temporary 5–7 years (adults) Standard of care No Yes Feature CPF 450 CPF 511 CPF 527 Cutoff < 450 nm < 511 nm < 527 nm Color Light yellow Yellow-orange Orange Indication Mild photophobia Moderate; cataract RP; macular disease; glaucoma Blocking intensity Least Moderate Most\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Prosthesis material PMMA (polymethylmethacrylate) Prosthesis polishing frequency Every 6–12 months Adult prosthesis replacement Every 5–7 years Conformer worn until 6–8 weeks post-surgery (then replaced by custom) UV-B range 280–315 nm UV-A range 315–400 nm UV 400 label Blocks all UV below 400 nm CPF 527 cutoff < 527 nm (orange)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Prosthesis types — SCSC Stock, Custom, Scleral shell, Conformer CPF numbers = cutoff in nm CPF 450 cuts at 450 nm; CPF 511 at 511 nm; CPF 527 at 527 nm — the number IS the cutoff. RP + achromatopsia tint rule \\\"Red goes to zero rods, orange helps the rest\\\" — achromatopsia patients need to eliminate short-wave stimulation entirely (deep orange/red); RP patients still have some rods, so amber/yellow (CPF 511/527) improves contrast without blocking everything.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"A scleral shell is used after enucleation A scleral shell fits over an existing (but shrunken) globe (phthisis bulbi, microphthalmos). After enucleation, the globe is gone — a custom prosthesis is used over the orbital implant. Photochromic lenses work in a car Car windshields block UV, which is what activates photochromic lenses. They remain clear while driving. CPF 527 is appropriate for all photophobia CPF 527 (orange, cuts below 527 nm) is for RP, macular disease, and glaucoma. For mild photophobia or early lens changes, CPF 450 (light yellow) is more appropriate. Tap water is safe for soaking a prosthesis Tap water carries Acanthamoeba risk and is not sterile. Use sterile saline. A conformer is the definitive prosthesis A conformer is a temporary clear placeholder placed immediately after surgery to maintain socket shape. The custom PMMA prosthesis is fitted at 6–8 weeks once healing is complete.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Prosthesis standard of care Custom PMMA by a certified ocularist Conformer purpose Prevent socket contraction post-surgery Prosthesis polishing Every 6–12 months Adult replacement Every 5–7 years CPF 527 primary use RP; macular disease; glaucoma Achromatopsia lens Deep orange or red tint Albinism lens Deep absorptive + UV 400 Photochromic limitation Does not activate behind car windshield UV-B causes Photokeratitis; cataract\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"1. A patient with achromatopsia (complete rod monochromacy) is extremely photophobic and reports glare and difficulty in any lit environment. Which absorptive lens is most appropriate? A. Light yellow (CPF 450) B. Gray (neutral density) C. Deep orange or red tint (CPF 527 or darker) D. Green tint for general outdoor use Answer C. Achromatopsia patients have non-functional cones and rely entirely on rods. Rods are most sensitive in the mid-spectrum (peak ~507 nm) and are overwhelmed by bright light. A deep orange or red longpass filter (CPF 527 or darker) eliminates the short and mid-wavelength stimulation that causes overwhelming photophobia and allows the remaining rod function to operate comfortably. Light yellow (CPF 450) is not sufficient. Gray reduces all wavelengths equally without targeted relief. 2. A patient's eye was surgically removed 6 months ago. They are now wearing a stock prosthesis and report daily discharge and socket irritation. What is the next step? A. Prescribe topical antibiotics and reassure B. Refer for a custom PMMA prosthesis fitted by a certified ocularist C. Switch to a scleral shell D. Instruct the patient to stop wearing the prosthesis to allow the socket to heal Answer B. The stock (ready-made) prosthesis is a poor fit — it cannot conform to the individual socket, which leads to chronic discharge and irritation. The standard of care is a custom PMMA prosthesis fitted by a certified ocularist. Six months is sufficient healing time for proper fitting. Stopping prosthesis wear risks contracted socket, not healing.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the 4 prosthesis types (SCSC) with the specific indication for each, and the CPF filter table (450/511/527 — cutoff, color, use) from memory. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the diagnosis-linked absorptive lens table from memory: 8 diagnoses with the recommended lens for each. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain to a patient who lost their eye 2 months ago why you are recommending a custom prosthesis instead of the ready-made one — in 3 sentences without using the word \\\"PMMA.\\\" Drill 4 — Flash Card Prompts Front Back Conformer purpose Prevent socket contraction post-surgery Custom prosthesis material PMMA Prosthesis polishing frequency Every 6–12 months Adult prosthesis replacement Every 5–7 years CPF number = Cutoff wavelength in nm Achromatopsia tint Deep orange or red RP tint Amber / CPF 511 or 527 Photochromic limitation Does not activate behind car windshield (no UV) Drill 5 — Sequence from Scratch Write the ocular prosthesis care schedule from memory: what to do daily, every 6–12 months, and every 5–7 years; what products to use; what to avoid. Source: Gap Lecture 05 (Ocular Prosthesis) | Gap Lecture 12 (Absorptive Lenses)\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8-01-prosthesis-and-absorptive-lenses-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"F8 — Ocular Prosthesis and Absorptive Lenses\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. Dilation drug — cue: with vs without cycloplegia. Dilate without cycloplegia = phenylephrine (α1). Dilate with cycloplegia = tropicamide / cyclopentolate (M3 block). Trap: \\\"phenylephrine causes cycloplegia\\\" — it has none. Pregnancy dilation — cue: pregnant patient needs dilation. Tropicamide (shortest, least exposure) + nasolacrimal occlusion. Trap: phenylephrine 10% (cardiovascular) in pregnancy. CN3 pupil rule — cue: third-nerve palsy + pupil. Pupil- involving = posterior communicating artery aneurysm (neurosurgical emergency). Pupil- spared = ischemic. Trap: observing a pupil-involving CN3 palsy. Vertical deviation 3-step — cue: a hyperdeviation worse on tilt. Parks-Bielschowsky 3-step localizes a CN4 (superior oblique) palsy; head tilts away , chin down. Trap: tilting the head toward the affected side. Absorptive/UV — cue: UV band or filter. UVC highest energy (blocked by ozone); UV400 standard; CPF filters cut blue for specific diagnoses. Trap: calling UVA the highest-energy band. Note written: June 2026 | Confidence: [ ] Low [ ] Okay [ ] Solid\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"F.strategy\",\"subject\":\"F\",\"label\":\"Clinical Optometry — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/F-Clinical-Optometry-and-Specialties/F-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Clinical Optometry and Specialties · the read-before-you-test reference for all 8 areas F1 DPA F2 Pediatric F3 Geriatric F4 Neuro F5 Occupational F6 Sports F7 Low Vision F8 Prosthesis\"},{\"anchor\":\"f1\",\"heading\":\"F1Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"5 DPAs: Phenylephrine, Tropicamide, Cyclopentolate, Proparacaine, Fluorescein. Phenylephrine (α1) dilates with NO cycloplegia. Tropicamide / cyclopentolate (M3 block) dilate AND cycloplege. Tropicamide is preferred in pregnancy; cyclopentolate gives the stronger pediatric cycloplegia (watch CNS effects at 2%). Proparacaine blocks Na⁺ channels, office-use only (masks corneal damage). Fluorescein glows under cobalt blue (465 nm), never with soft lenses. NLO 2 min limits systemic absorption. All mydriatics: avoid in angle-closure. Trap: tropicamide dilates without cycloplegia. No — that is phenylephrine; tropicamide does both.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f2\",\"heading\":\"F2Pediatric Optometry\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Milestones: eyes straight by 3–4 months. VA tests: infants → preferential looking (Teller); preschool → HOTV / Lea / Allen. Critical period peaks 1–3, closes ~7–8 (some gain to ~12). Amblyopia order: cycloplegic refraction + full glasses (12–16 wks) FIRST; add patching only if VA doesn't normalize. Deprivation = worst prognosis. Accommodative ET → full cycloplegic plus. Pseudostrabismus (epicanthal folds) = symmetric Hirschberg reflexes = reassure, no treatment. Trap: patching is the first amblyopia step. No — full spectacle correction comes first.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f3\",\"heading\":\"F3Geriatric Optometry\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"AMD: 85% dry / 15% wet, but wet causes most severe vision loss → anti-VEGF. AREDS2 lowers progression risk ~25% (does not reverse). Soft confluent drusen = high risk. Hypertensive retinopathy (KWB): AV nicking = grade 2; papilledema = grade 4 (emergency). Normal A:V ratio 2:3. Diabetic retinopathy: most common vision-loss cause = diabetic macular edema (CSME within 500 µm of fovea); severe NPDR = 4-2-1. Trap: dry AMD causes most severe vision loss. No — wet AMD does, despite being only 15%.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f4\",\"heading\":\"F4Neuro-Optometry\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Cranial nerves: pupil-involving CN3 = PCA aneurysm (emergency). CN6 = false localizing sign (raised ICP). CN4 palsy = vertical diplopia worse on downgaze; head tilt away; Parks-Bielschowsky 3-step. Nystagmus: INS is horizontal in all gaze and dampens with convergence. Vertical nystagmus = always acquired. Latent nystagmus VA test = +5.00 fog (not a patch). CVI: most common cause = perinatal hypoxia-ischemia; the eyes are structurally normal (normal pupils and OCT); diagnosis is behavioral + neuroimaging. Trap: occlude one eye to test latent nystagmus. No — occlusion triggers it; fog with +5.00 instead.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f5\",\"heading\":\"F5Occupational Optometry\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Chemical splash: irrigate immediately 20–30 min (before identifying the chemical). Safety lens = polycarbonate. Welding UV → photokeratitis; IR → thermal/IR cataract. CVS: 20-20-20 rule (every 20 min, 20 ft, 20 sec) + AR coating; never prescribe daily home cycloplegics. Philippine labor: maternity leave (RA 11210) = 105 days; paternity (RA 8187) = 7 days; OSHS under DOLE; GSIS = government, SSS = private. Face shield is used WITH goggles, not instead. Trap: identify the chemical before irrigating. No — irrigate first; the cause matters less than stopping damage.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f6\",\"heading\":\"F6Sports Vision\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Tints: Yellow = fog/haze/low light · Brown/amber = depth perception (golf/tennis) · Gray = neutral density (no contrast gain). Skills & tools: dynamic VA = tachistoscope / Marsden ball; eye-hand coordination = Wayne Saccadic Fixator; contrast = Pelli-Robson. 20/20 static VA does not measure these. Protection: polycarbonate eyewear; racquet sports use ASTM F803. Contact lenses give NO impact or UV protection. Trap: gray tint improves contrast. No — gray is neutral density; brown/amber improves contrast.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f7\",\"heading\":\"F7Low Vision & Rehabilitation\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"WHO cutoffs: low vision = worse than 20/70; blindness = 20/200 or worse (better eye). Goal = functional vision for the task, NOT 20/20. Magnification math: reference 4 D = 1× ; M = required VA / present VA ; equivalent add = M × 4 . (N32 → N8 = 4× = +16 D, WD ~6 cm.) Devices: telescopes = distance (most patients need near first); stand magnifier for tremor/sustained reading. Eccentric viewing helps any central scotoma. Calculate from best-corrected VA. Trap: all low vision patients need telescopes. No — most need near magnification first.\"},{\"anchor\":\"f8\",\"heading\":\"F8Prosthesis & Absorptive Lenses\",\"topic\":\"Subject F — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Prosthetics: conformer = temporary post-op placeholder; custom PMMA prosthesis (certified ocularist) fitted at 6–8 weeks; polish every 6–12 months, replace every 5–7 years. Scleral shell = over a shrunken globe (not after enucleation). Soak in sterile saline, not tap water. Absorptive filters: CPF 527 (orange) = RP / macular disease / glaucoma · achromatopsia = deep orange/red · albinism = deep absorptive + UV 400. Photochromic lenses do not darken in a car (the windshield blocks UV). Trap: a scleral shell is used after enucleation. No — it fits over a shrunken globe; after enucleation a custom prosthesis sits over the implant. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject F strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"G.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"G\",\"label\":\"Ocular Pharmacology — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/G-Ocular-Pharmacology/G-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Before you can understand any eye drop, you need the rules that apply to every drug. Pharmacology splits into two halves that mirror each other: Pharmacokinetics is what the body does to the drug . Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Excretion (ADME). Think of the drug as a traveler: how it gets in, where it goes, how it gets broken down, how it leaves. Pharmacodynamics is what the drug does to the body . Mechanism of action and the effect it produces, almost always by binding a receptor. Everything else in this note (routes, dosing, half-life, therapeutic index, the prescription, the controlled-substance schedules) hangs off those two ideas. Teaching angle: ask \\\"what the body does to the drug, and what the drug does to the body.\\\" If you can sort any fact into one of those two buckets, you understand where it belongs.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Why split pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics at all? Because they answer different questions. Kinetics decides how much drug reaches the target and for how long. Dynamics decides what happens once it gets there. A drug can have a perfect mechanism (good dynamics) and still fail because it never reaches the eye in useful amounts (bad kinetics). Both must work. Why does the liver matter so much? The liver is the main site of metabolism. It chemically rewrites drugs, usually turning fat-soluble drugs into water-soluble metabolites the kidney can flush out. This is also why the route of administration matters: anything swallowed passes through the liver first (first-pass effect) and loses some potency before it ever reaches the blood. Why are most drugs weak bases or weak acids? Because the body absorbs the uncharged (non-ionized) form across lipid membranes. Lipid-soluble equals uncharged equals absorbable. The pH of the environment decides how much of the drug is in that absorbable form. This is the single idea behind absorption, corneal penetration, and even why you alkalinize urine to dump a barbiturate overdose. Why do we care about half-life? Because it tells you how often to dose and how long an effect lasts. It is the bridge between a chemistry fact and a clinical schedule.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Pharmacokinetics What the body does to the drug (ADME) \\\"Body acts on drug\\\" Pharmacodynamics What the drug does to the body (MOA + effect) \\\"Drug acts on body\\\" Pharmacognosy Identification of crude naturally occurring drugs \\\"Gnosy = knowing the plant\\\" Posology Study of drug dosage \\\"Poso = how much\\\" Toxicology Study of poisons and toxic effects Potency Lowest dose that produces the desired effect Low dose works = high potency Efficacy Maximum effect a drug can produce regardless of dose Ceiling of effect Bioavailability Fraction of unchanged drug reaching systemic circulation IV = 100% Tolerance Reduced effect after repeated exposure (enzyme induction) Need more for same effect Tachyphylaxis Tolerance developing rapidly after only a few doses Fast tolerance Hypersensitivity / hyperreactive Usual effect at unexpectedly low dose Hyporeactive Usual effect at unexpectedly large dose Idiosyncratic reaction Illogical, unpredictable reaction (mydriatic causing miosis) No logical PK cause Placebo No intrinsic activity but may give therapeutic benefit Drug name layers: Chemical name (full structure, never used) → Generic name (active ingredient, scientific, widely used) → Brand / trade / proprietary name (company name). A generic drug is one whose patent expired or was never patented.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-pharmacokinetics-adme\",\"heading\":\"Pharmacokinetics — ADME\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"1. Absorption — how the drug gets into the blood Five transport mechanisms: Mechanism Direction Energy Carrier Moves Simple diffusion (most drugs) High to low No No Lipid-soluble drugs Facilitated diffusion High to low No Yes Lipid-insoluble drugs Active transport Low to high Yes Yes Electrolytes Filtration Pressure gradient No No Small molecules through pores Pinocytosis Endo/exocytosis Yes No Dissolved substances Main factor affecting diffusion is molecular size (then shape, then charge). Lipid-soluble = uncharged = non-ionized = non-polar = alkaline form. Examples: alkaloids, anesthetics, weak bases, corticosteroids. Extremely lipophilic drugs get trapped in the corneal epithelium and release slowly, so too much lipid solubility also hurts penetration. The eye needs a drug that is both lipid- and water-soluble to cross all corneal layers (epithelium = lipid, stroma = water). First-pass effect: gastric acid plus liver metabolism degrade an oral drug before it reaches circulation. Routes that bypass it: sublingual, buccal, rectal (partially), and all parenteral routes. 2. Distribution — where the drug goes Drug travels in two forms: Free / unbound = active, reaches the target, produces effect. Bound (to albumin) = inactive reservoir, stays in blood until released or excreted. Only the free fraction works. Barriers that limit distribution: blood-brain barrier and blood-ocular barrier. 3. Metabolism / Biotransformation — mostly in the liver Goal: make the drug more polar (water-soluble) so the kidney can excrete it. Enzyme system: hepatic microsomal cytochrome P-450 . Phase What happens Reactions Phase I Unmask or add a polar group (OH, SH, NH₂) Oxidation (most common, via P-450), Reduction, Hydrolysis Phase II Conjugate the drug to a polar molecule (glucuronate, sulfate, glycine, acetate, methyl, glutathione) Conjugation Organs of metabolism: liver (main) , kidneys, lungs, adrenal glands. 4. Excretion — how the drug leaves Main organ: kidneys (glomerular filtration + tubular secretion). Minor routes: liver/bile, lungs, GIT, and glands (lacrimal, salivary, sweat, sebaceous, mammary). The mammary route is why nursing mothers need caution. Atropine is excreted unchanged in urine , which is why a urine test for atropine toxicity exists (the \\\"cat eye test\\\"). Penicillin is not metabolized by the liver ; it is removed by renal excretion.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-formula-breakdowns\",\"heading\":\"Formula Breakdowns\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Half-life (t½) and the elimination constant k = 0.693 / t½ Plain language: half-life is the time for the plasma drug level to fall by 50%. The number 0.693 links half-life to the elimination rate constant k. The parts: t½ = half-life (time). k (or Ke) = elimination rate constant (fraction removed per unit time). 0.693 = the natural log of 2 (ln 2). Where it comes from: drug elimination is usually first-order (exponential decay). Solving \\\"half remains\\\" in an exponential gives ln 2 = 0.693. So 0.693 is not arbitrary, it is what \\\"half\\\" equals in exponential math. Analogy: like a phone battery that always loses half its remaining charge in the same time, no matter how full it started. Why this form: writing k = 0.693/t½ lets you convert an easily measured half-life into the rate constant used in clearance and dosing math. Limits: only valid for first-order kinetics. Zero-order drugs (alcohol, phenytoin at high dose) eliminate at a constant amount, not a constant fraction, so half-life is not fixed. Cross-subject link: same exponential decay math as radioactive isotopes in physics and as light absorbance fall-off, which you have already met in optics. Two half-lives to name: Distribution half-life (t½ α): fast early drop as drug spreads into tissues. Elimination half-life (t½ β): slower drop from metabolism and excretion. Volume of distribution Vd = total amount of drug in body / concentration of drug in plasma Most important PK parameter. It estimates how much the drug hides in tissues versus stays in plasma. A large Vd means the drug is heavily tissue-bound (little left in blood). A small Vd means it stays mostly in plasma. Body clearance Cl = Vd × Ke = Vd × (0.693 / t½) Clearance is the volume of plasma fully cleared of drug per unit time. It ties the two parameters above together: how much is around (Vd) times how fast it leaves (Ke). Therapeutic index (margin of safety) TI = LD₅₀ / ED₅₀ Plain language: how safe a drug is. The gap between the dose that helps and the dose that kills. Parts: LD₅₀ = dose lethal to 50% of subjects. ED₅₀ = dose effective in 50% of subjects. Origin: both come from quantal dose-response curves run across a population. Analogy: the shoulder of a mountain road. A wide shoulder (high TI) is forgiving; a narrow one (low TI) means small errors are fatal. Why this form: a ratio makes safety comparable across drugs of very different potency. Limits: a high TI does not mean zero side effects, only a wide lethal margin. Cross-link: related to the therapeutic window , the dose range that sits above the effective dose but below the toxic dose. Narrow-window drugs (and narrow TI drugs) need blood-level monitoring.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-routes-of-administration\",\"heading\":\"Routes of Administration\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"SYSTEMIC (reaches general circulation) Alimentary (passes liver) Parenteral (bypasses first pass) Oral - safest, first-pass Intradermal - skin testing Buccal - bypasses liver Subcutaneous Sublingual - bypasses liver Intramuscular Rectal - partial bypass Intravenous - no absorption step Intra-arterial / Intracardiac (special) LOCAL (little systemic effect) Topical - eye, nose, throat, airway, vagina, ear Local injectables - nerve block, epidural, spinal KINETIC RULE Zero-order absorption = 100% reaches blood = IV, IA, IC only First-order absorption = constant fraction reaches blood = every other route Alimentary advantages: safest, convenient, no sterile technique. Disadvantage: variable bioavailability, first-pass loss. Parenteral advantages: rapid (ER use), accurate dose. Disadvantage: needs sterile technique and trained staff, rapid absorption can be toxic.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-dosing\",\"heading\":\"Dosing\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Loading (initial) dose: higher first dose to reach therapeutic plasma level fast. Maintenance dose: the amount that keeps the effect going. Therapeutic dose: computed from body weight (kg). Toxic dose: approximate, independent of body weight. Mydriatic dosing example: intermittent, one drop every 5 minutes until full mydriasis. Drug interaction effects to separate carefully: Additive: 1 + 1 = 2 (combined effect equals the sum). Synergism: 1 + 1 > 2 (combined effect greater than the sum). Potentiation: 0 + 1 > 1 (a drug with no effect of its own boosts a second drug).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-pharmacodynamics-receptors-and-antagonism\",\"heading\":\"Pharmacodynamics — Receptors and Antagonism\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Receptor: the lock; drug is the key (lock-and-key principle). Sites: type I cell membrane, type II cytoplasm, type III nucleus. Affinity: strength of attraction between drug and receptor. High affinity binds even at low concentration. Bonds: covalent = strongest = irreversible. Van der Waals = weakest but most important (reversible, most drugs). Term Definition Agonist Binds receptor and produces the effect Antagonist Binds receptor and blocks the agonist Competitive antagonist Reversible, same site, weak Van der Waals bond, overcome by more agonist Non-competitive antagonist Irreversible covalent bond, not overcome by more agonist Physiologic antagonism Two drugs, two different receptors, opposite effects Chemical antagonism Two drugs combine into an inactive third compound\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-the-details-prescription-order-po-and-the-law\",\"heading\":\"Prescription Order (PO) and the Law\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Eight parts of a prescription: Practitioner information (name, degree, license, PTR, S2 number) Patient information (name, address, age, sex) Date Superscription = the symbol Rx (Latin recipe , \\\"to take\\\") Inscription = drug, concentration, dosage form Subscription = directions to the pharmacist (how much to dispense) Signatura (Sig.) = directions to the patient (route, amount, frequency, duration) Refill / labeling / signature S2 number is required for controlled/regulated drugs and is not renewed after 6 months. FDA monitors existing drugs and approves new ones; concerns are efficacy and safety. PDEA is the Philippine enforcement agency for controlled substances. OTC drugs dispense without a prescription; Legend/Rx drugs need a prescriber. Three legal doctrines: Informed consent: patient must understand the procedure, alternatives, pros/cons, and risks before deciding. Respondeat superior (\\\"let the master answer\\\"): the superior is responsible for a subordinate's actions. Minors and incompetents: need guardian consent.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"ln 2 constant in half-life 0.693 Bioavailability by IV 100% (zero-order) Ointment oil:water 80% oil / 20% water Cream oil:water 50% / 50% Teaspoon 5 mL Tablespoon 15 mL Schedule II written Rx supplied within 72 hours Schedule III/IV refills not more than 5x, not beyond 6 months Years to develop a new drug ~10 years Drug-development phases Preclinical (animals) → Phase I (healthy volunteers) → II (200–300 patients) → III (1000–3000) → IV (post-market)\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"ADME Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Excretion (the kinetics journey). \\\"Body to drug = kinetics; drug to body = dynamics.\\\" Lipid = Uncharged = Alkaline = Absorbable (one chain, four words). 0.693 is ln 2 , the math meaning of \\\"half.\\\" Liver metabolizes, kidney excretes. Potency = position (low dose), Efficacy = ceiling (max effect). Additive sum, Synergy more, Potentiation zero-plus-one. Rx parts order Practitioner, Patient, Date, Superscription, Inscription, Subscription, Sig, Refill. Controlled schedules I to V abuse potential falls as the number rises (I = heroin/LSD, no medical use; V = loperamide, lowest abuse).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"potency and efficacy are the same. Potency is how little you need; efficacy is how much effect is possible. A drug can be very potent but have low efficacy. IV drugs undergo absorption. IV, IA, and IC bypass absorption entirely (zero-order, 100% bioavailable). the liver excretes drugs. Careful. The liver metabolizes (and eliminates by changing the drug); the kidney excretes . more lipid solubility always means better eye penetration. Too lipophilic and the drug gets stuck in the corneal epithelium. The cornea needs a drug that is both lipid- and water-soluble. competitive antagonism cannot be overcome. Competitive (Van der Waals, reversible) is overcome by more agonist; non-competitive (covalent, irreversible) is not. Schedule I drugs can be prescribed with extra paperwork. Schedule I has no accepted medical use and is not available for therapeutic prescription. atropine is metabolized before excretion. It is excreted unchanged in urine (basis of the toxicity test).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer What the body does to the drug Pharmacokinetics (ADME) What the drug does to the body Pharmacodynamics (MOA + effect) Main organ of metabolism Liver (cytochrome P-450) Main organ of excretion Kidneys Most important PK parameter Volume of distribution Half-life constant 0.693 (ln 2) Therapeutic index LD₅₀ / ED₅₀ Routes with 100% bioavailability IV, IA, IC (zero-order) Strongest receptor bond Covalent (irreversible) Weakest but most important bond Van der Waals (reversible) Symbol Rx means Recipe, \\\"to take\\\" Drug with no medical use Schedule I (heroin, LSD)\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"1. A drug produces its maximum possible effect at a relatively low dose. Which two properties does this describe? A. Low potency, high efficacy B. High potency, high efficacy C. High potency, low efficacy D. Low potency, low efficacy Answer B. Acting at a low dose describes high potency. Reaching the maximum possible effect describes high efficacy. The two are independent: potency is about the dose needed, efficacy is about the size of the effect. 2. Which route of administration delivers 100% of the drug to the systemic circulation? A. Oral B. Sublingual C. Intravenous D. Rectal Answer C. Intravenous. IV (along with intra-arterial and intracardiac) bypasses absorption entirely, so bioavailability is 100% and follows zero-order kinetics. The other routes all involve an absorption step and a constant fraction reaching the blood (first-order). 3. A drug is excreted unchanged in the urine and forms the basis of a urine toxicity test. Which drug? A. Penicillin B. Atropine C. Tropicamide D. Phenobarbital Answer B. Atropine. It is excreted unchanged in urine, the basis of the atropine toxicity (\\\"cat eye\\\") test. Penicillin is also renally excreted but is the classic example of a drug not metabolized by the liver, not the toxicity-test drug. Phenobarbital is excreted unchanged too but the source ties the urine test specifically to atropine. 4. Two drugs are given together. Drug X has no effect of its own but increases the effect of Drug Y. This is: A. Additive effect B. Synergism C. Potentiation D. Antagonism Answer C. Potentiation. A drug lacking its own effect that boosts another is potentiation (0 + 1 > 1). Additive is sum of two active drugs; synergism is two active drugs producing more than their sum. 5. Which best describes a competitive antagonist? A. Forms an irreversible covalent bond and cannot be displaced B. Binds a different receptor to produce an opposite effect C. Reversibly competes at the same receptor and is overcome by more agonist D. Combines with the agonist to form an inactive compound Answer C. A competitive antagonist uses a weak, reversible Van der Waals bond at the same receptor, so adding more agonist overcomes it. Option A is non-competitive, B is physiologic antagonism, D is chemical antagonism.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1-01-general-pharmacology-principles-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"G1 — General Pharmacology Principles\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump On a blank page write the ADME chain and, under each letter, the main organ involved and one key fact. Do not look. Drill 2 — Blank Table Redraw the three-transport table (simple diffusion, facilitated diffusion, active transport) with direction, energy, carrier, and what each moves. Drill 3 — Teach-Back Write Explain potency vs efficacy to a classmate in three sentences using a real example. No looking. Drill 4 — Formula From Scratch Write the four formulas (k = 0.693/t½, Vd, Cl, TI) and label every term. Then state one limit of each. Drill 5 — Sequence Write the eight parts of a prescription order in order, then label which two parts use Latin (Superscription = Rx, Signatura = Sig). Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Blank Table + Formulas 3rd 3 days Teach-Back 4th 1 week Sequence Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Almost every drug that acts on the eye works through the autonomic nervous system , and the pupil is the clearest place to see it. Think of the pupil as a tug of war between two muscles: Sphincter pupillae (circular, parasympathetic , M3 receptor) pulls the pupil closed (miosis). Dilator pupillae (radial, sympathetic , α1 receptor) pulls the pupil open (mydriasis). To move the pupil you can either push your own muscle (give an agonist) or release the opponent (block the other side). That single idea generates a 2x2 grid that explains every mydriatic, miotic, and cycloplegic on the board. Sympathetic (adrenergic) Parasympathetic (cholinergic) Agonist (mimic, turn ON) Sympathomimetic → dilate , no cycloplegia Parasympathomimetic → constrict (miosis) Antagonist (block, turn OFF) Sympatholytic → constrict Parasympatholytic → dilate + cycloplegia Teaching angle: never memorize the four effects. For any drug, name the system and whether it mimics or blocks, then ask \\\"am I pushing my muscle or releasing the opponent?\\\" The effect rebuilds itself.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Why do the two dilators behave differently (one keeps near vision, one loses it)? The dilators sit on a diagonal: a sympathomimetic (push the dilator) and a parasympatholytic (release the sphincter). The fork between them is the ciliary muscle , which is run by the same parasympathetic M3 nerve as the sphincter. So a parasympatholytic that relaxes the sphincter also paralyzes the ciliary muscle and adds cycloplegia . A sympathomimetic never touches the ciliary muscle, so it dilates with near vision intact. Why does pilocarpine lower eye pressure? It is a direct M3 agonist. It contracts the ciliary muscle (Brucke's fibers), which pulls open the trabecular meshwork and lets aqueous drain. So a \\\"constrictor\\\" is also a glaucoma drug, because the same muscle that focuses the lens also tugs the drain open. Why are all mydriatics dangerous in a narrow angle? Dilation bunches the peripheral iris into the angle and blocks the trabecular meshwork, which can trigger acute angle-closure. This is the one contraindication that applies to every dilating drug in this note. Why do we test pupils with cocaine and hydroxyamphetamine? Because they act at different points along the sympathetic chain. Cocaine needs a working nerve releasing NE; hydroxyamphetamine needs an intact final neuron to release stored NE. Putting them in sequence localizes a Horner lesion to a specific neuron.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Mydriasis Greek mydros Pupil dilation; α1 agonist or M3 antagonist Miosis Greek meioun = to lessen Pupil constriction; M3 agonist or α1 antagonist Cycloplegia kyklos = circle + plege = paralysis Ciliary muscle paralysis; loss of accommodation Sympathomimetic mimics the sympathetic system Adrenergic agonist; dilates without cycloplegia Parasympatholytic lyses the parasympathetic system Antimuscarinic; dilates plus cycloplegia Agonist Greek agon = contest Binds and activates the receptor (\\\"push your muscle\\\") Antagonist anti = against Blocks the receptor (\\\"release the opponent\\\") Denervation supersensitivity upregulated receptors Why an Adie's pupil responds to weak 0.1% pilocarpine ISA intrinsic sympathomimetic activity A beta blocker that also acts as a partial agonist MSA membrane-stabilizing activity Local-anesthetic property of some beta blockers Decongestant vasoconstrictor α1 agonist that blanches conjunctival vessels\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-neurotransmitters-and-their-handling\",\"heading\":\"Neurotransmitters and their handling\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Sympathetic (adrenergic) Parasympathetic (cholinergic) Transmitter Norepinephrine (NE) Acetylcholine (ACh) Degrading enzyme MAO + COMT Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) Breakdown product Vanillylmandelic acid (VMA) Acetate + choline Receptors α1, α2, β1, β2, β3 Nicotinic, Muscarinic M1/M2/M3 NE synthesis chain (rate-limiting step is the first one): Tyrosine → (tyrosine hydroxylase, rate-limiting ) → DOPA → (DOPA decarboxylase) → Dopamine → (dopamine β-hydroxylase) → NE → (in adrenal medulla) → Epinephrine. Reserpine blocks transport into the vesicle.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-receptor-number-rule\",\"heading\":\"Receptor number rule\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Number = action: 1 constricts/contracts, 2 dilates. Receptor Ocular location Effect α1 Dilator pupillae, conjunctival vessels, trabecular meshwork, Mueller's muscle Mydriasis, vasoconstriction, opens trabecula, lid retraction α2 Ciliary process (inhibitory, presynaptic) Decrease aqueous secretion (the glaucoma brake) β1 Heart Tachycardia, increased output β2 Ciliary process (excitatory), ciliary muscle, bronchi Increase aqueous secretion; relax ciliary muscle; bronchodilation M3 Sphincter pupillae, ciliary (Brucke's) muscle Miosis; accommodation; opens trabecula indirectly Nicotinic EOM Contraction\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-box-1-parasympathomimetics-cholinergic-agonists-miosis\",\"heading\":\"Box 1 — Parasympathomimetics (cholinergic agonists): MIOSIS\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Effects: miosis, accommodation, increased aqueous outflow, conjunctival/ciliary injection. Direct-acting (bind the receptor): Acetylcholine 1%: destroyed instantly by AChE; intracameral to constrict pupil after cataract extraction. Methacholine 2.5%: resists AChE; diagnoses the tonic pupil in Adie's . Carbachol (0.75–3%): not hydrolyzed by AChE; powerful miotic, second-line when pilocarpine fails; poor corneal penetration so combined with BAK. Pilocarpine (0.25–10%): the prototype. Onset 2 h, duration 8 h. Lowers IOP (open and angle-closure), constricts pupil, and counters mydriasis from epinephrine/phenylephrine/tropicamide. 0.1% pilocarpine constricts an Adie's pupil (denervation supersensitivity) but not a normal one; 0.5–1% constricts a normal pupil. Contraindicated in malignant glaucoma. Most common side effect: miosis and accommodative spasm (drug-induced myopia). Indirect-acting (AChE inhibitors, raise ACh): Reversible (carbamyl ester): Physostigmine (0.25–0.5%) and Demecarium (two physostigmines). Uses: open-angle glaucoma, lice on lid margins. Irreversible (organophosphate): Echothiopate and DFP (diisopropylfluorophosphate). Long-acting miotics for accommodative esotropia and aphakic glaucoma. Classic side effect: iris cysts (prevented/reversed with 2.5% phenylephrine), and echothiopate can cause retinal detachment. Poisoning agents in the same family: parathion, malathion (insecticides), and nerve gas (tabun, soman, sarin). Antidote: atropine. Clinical test: Tensilon (edrophonium) test for myasthenia gravis. Short-acting AChE inhibitor; muscle strength improves in myasthenia. Atropine is kept ready as the antidote for cholinergic crisis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-box-2-parasympatholytics-cholinergic-antagonists-mydriasis-cycloplegia\",\"heading\":\"Box 2 — Parasympatholytics (cholinergic antagonists): MYDRIASIS + CYCLOPLEGIA\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Block M3 → sphincter relaxes (mydriasis) and ciliary muscle relaxes (cycloplegia). All are contraindicated in angle-closure glaucoma. Uses: uveitis (break/prevent synechiae), cycloplegic refraction, relieve ciliary spasm, penalization in amblyopia. The cycloplegic duration table (very high yield): Drug Mydriasis onset Cycloplegia onset Duration Note Atropine 0.5–3% 30 min 1 h 14 days Strongest, longest. From Atropa belladonna . Amblyopia penalization, child cycloplegic refraction, anterior uveitis Homatropine 2–5% 30 min 30–90 min 6 h–4 days Intermediate. Primary use: iridocyclitis Scopolamine 0.25% 40 min 40 min 24 h From Scopolia . Rarely used diagnostically Cyclopentolate 0.5–2% 15–30 min 15–45 min 6–24 h Drug of choice for routine cycloplegia. CNS effects in children (use 0.5–1%) Tropicamide 0.5–1% 20–30 min 20–25 min 4–6 h Most common mydriatic; weak cycloplegic, DOC for routine mydriasis. Safest in children and cardiac patients (no vasopressor effect) Listed strongest → weakest cycloplegic. Atropine poisoning treatment: physostigmine 1–4 mg IV. Eucatropine: used as a provocative test for suspected narrow-angle glaucoma. Botulinum toxin A (from Clostridium botulinum ): blocks ACh release at the neuromuscular junction (inhibits calcium at the synaptic cleft). Max effect 1–2 weeks, lasts 2–6 months. Uses: strabismus surgery, blepharospasm, hemifacial spasm, lid retraction in Graves. Side effects: ptosis, diplopia, exposure keratopathy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-box-3-sympathomimetics-adrenergic-agonists-mydriasis-without-cycloplegia\",\"heading\":\"Box 3 — Sympathomimetics (adrenergic agonists): MYDRIASIS without cycloplegia\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Direct-acting: Decongestants (α1, vasoconstrict conjunctival vessels): naphazoline, tetrahydrozoline, oxymetazoline. Apraclonidine (0.5–1%): α2 agonist (clonidine derivative). Lowers IOP after laser (trabeculoplasty, iridotomy, YAG capsulotomy) without affecting BP or pulse. Brimonidine (0.2%, newest α2 agonist): lowers IOP by decreasing aqueous secretion. Epinephrine (0.5–2%): non-selective; lowers IOP three ways (α1 opens trabecula, α2 cuts secretion, but β raises secretion). Dilates a Horner pupil at 0.1% (denervation supersensitivity). Contraindicated in angle-closure, aphakia (cystoid macular edema), CVD, diabetes. Rarely used now; replaced by dipivefrin (a more lipophilic pro-drug converted to epinephrine). Phenylephrine (0.12 / 2.5 / 10%): synthetic, selective α1 agonist on the dilator. 0.12% = decongestant; 2.5% and 10% = mydriasis with no cycloplegia . Onset 30–60 min, duration 4–6 h. 2.5% delivers 1.25 mg systemically, 10% delivers 5 mg (avoid 10% in cardiac/HPN patients). Indirect-acting (change NE level, do not bind receptor): Hydroxyamphetamine 1%: releases stored NE; does not cross the blood-brain barrier. Cocaine 4%: blocks NE reuptake; also a local anesthetic. From Erythroxylon coca . The two pupil tests (commit these cold): Horner's syndrome (sympathetic lesion): ptosis (Mueller), miosis (dilator), anhidrosis. Cocaine test: a Horner pupil fails to dilate (no NE present to block reuptake of). Confirms Horner at any level. Hydroxyamphetamine test: localizes the lesion. Dilates in central/preganglionic lesions (final neuron intact, NE stores releasable); fails to dilate in postganglionic lesions (final neuron dead). Adie's tonic pupil (parasympathetic, ciliary ganglion): constricts to 0.1% pilocarpine (supersensitive); a normal pupil needs 0.5–1%.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-the-details-box-4-sympatholytics-adrenergic-antagonists-miosis-lower-iop\",\"heading\":\"Box 4 — Sympatholytics (adrenergic antagonists): MIOSIS / lower IOP\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Two extra properties to know: ISA (intrinsic sympathomimetic activity, acts as partial agonist) and MSA (membrane-stabilizing activity, local-anesthetic effect). Alpha-1 blockers (effects: miosis, ptosis, conjunctival hyperemia): Dapiprazole 0.5% (Rev-Eyes): reverses mydriasis from phenylephrine and tropicamide. Thymoxamine 0.5–1%: orphan drug, reverses 2.5% phenylephrine; no effect on aqueous secretion; helps differentiate glaucoma types. Beta blockers (MOA: decrease aqueous secretion): Non-selective: Timolol 0.25–0.5% (no ISA/MSA), Levobunolol, Metipranolol, Carteolol. Contraindicated in asthma/COPD and insulin-dependent diabetes. Cardio-selective (safer in asthma): Betaxolol, Metoprolol. Systemic side effects: bradycardia, hypotension (most common), bronchoconstriction (non-selective), masking of hypoglycemia.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Pilocarpine onset / duration 2 h / 8 h Adie's pupil constricts to 0.1% pilocarpine Horner pupil dilates to 0.1% epinephrine (vs 1% normal) Atropine duration 14 days Tropicamide duration 4–6 h (shortest cycloplegic) Strongest → weakest cycloplegic Atropine > Homatropine > Scopolamine > Cyclopentolate > Tropicamide Phenylephrine mydriatic strength 2.5% and 10% Botulinum effect duration 2–6 months Rate-limiting step of NE synthesis Tyrosine → DOPA (tyrosine hydroxylase)\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"THE PUPIL — A TUG OF WAR ───────────────────────── SPHINCTER (circular, parasympathetic, M3) → MIOSIS (closes) DILATOR (radial, sympathetic, α1) → MYDRIASIS (opens) THE 2x2 — push your muscle or release the opponent ────────────────────────────────────────────────── SYMPATHETIC PARASYMPATHETIC AGONIST → dilate (no cyclo) → constrict (miosis) ANTAGONIST → constrict → dilate + CYCLOPLEGIA NE SYNTHESIS (rate-limiting = first step) ────────────────────────────────────────── Tyrosine → [tyrosine hydroxylase ★] → DOPA → Dopamine → NE → Epinephrine SUFFIX DECODER ────────────── -olol = beta blocker · -onidine = α2 agonist · -zoline = α1 decongestant -stigmine = AChE inhibitor · -tropine = antimuscarinic\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"The 2x2 grid agonist/antagonist × sympathetic/parasympathetic. Dilators on the diagonal. Number = action 1 constricts, 2 dilates. (α1 mydriasis, α2 cuts aqueous, β2 raises aqueous.) Cycloplegic ladder \\\"A Home So Cool Today\\\" Atropine, Homatropine, Scopolamine, Cyclopentolate, Tropicamide (strongest to weakest). Adie's = 0.1% pilo; Horner = 0.1% epi. Both \\\"weak drug works because the muscle is supersensitive.\\\" Cocaine confirms Horner, hydroxyamphetamine localizes it. Suffix decoder -olol = beta blocker, -onidine = α2 agonist, -zoline = α1 decongestant, -stigmine = AChE inhibitor, -tropine = antimuscarinic. Iris cysts = echothiopate/DFP; fix with 2.5% phenylephrine. All mydriatics: avoid in angle-closure glaucoma.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"tropicamide is the strongest cycloplegic. It is the weakest and shortest ; atropine is strongest. Cyclopentolate is the routine cycloplegic of choice. phenylephrine causes cycloplegia. It is α1 only; mydriasis with no cycloplegia (ciliary muscle has no α1). a Horner pupil dilates with cocaine. It fails to dilate (no NE to block reuptake of). That failure is the positive test. β2 stimulation lowers eye pressure. β2 on the ciliary process increases aqueous secretion. The IOP-lowering adrenergic targets are α2 (brake) and beta blockade . Adie's pupil responds to 1% pilocarpine like normal. Careful. It constricts to 0.1% because of denervation supersensitivity; that low-dose response is the diagnostic feature. pilocarpine is contraindicated in angle-closure. It is used in angle-closure (it constricts and pulls the iris out of the angle); the contraindication is malignant glaucoma . The mydriatics are the ones contraindicated in angle-closure. beta blockers are safe in asthma. for non-selective (timolol). Use cardio-selective (betaxolol) if airway disease.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Sphincter receptor / dilator receptor M3 (parasympathetic) / α1 (sympathetic) Dilate WITHOUT cycloplegia Phenylephrine (α1 agonist) Dilate WITH cycloplegia Atropine, homatropine, scopolamine, cyclopentolate, tropicamide Routine cycloplegic of choice Cyclopentolate Routine mydriatic of choice Tropicamide Strongest/longest cycloplegic Atropine (14 days) Lowers aqueous secretion α2 agonists (brimonidine), beta blockers Adie's pupil test 0.1% pilocarpine constricts Horner confirm / localize Cocaine confirms / hydroxyamphetamine localizes Myasthenia test Tensilon (edrophonium) Iris cysts caused by Echothiopate, DFP (reverse with phenylephrine) Organophosphate poisoning antidote Atropine Universal mydriatic contraindication Angle-closure glaucoma\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"1. A drug dilates the pupil but the patient's near vision stays sharp. The drug most likely acts on: A. M3 muscarinic receptors (antagonist) B. α1 adrenergic receptors (agonist) C. β2 receptors (agonist) D. Nicotinic receptors Answer B. Mydriasis with intact accommodation means the ciliary muscle was untouched. Only the sympathetic α1 dilator pathway (phenylephrine) does this. M3 blockade (A) would also paralyze the ciliary muscle and cause cycloplegia. 2. A tonic, poorly reactive pupil constricts briskly to 0.1% pilocarpine. The diagnosis is: A. Horner's syndrome B. Third nerve palsy C. Adie's tonic pupil D. Argyll Robertson pupil Answer C. Adie's tonic pupil. Denervation supersensitivity at the ciliary ganglion makes it constrict to a dose (0.1%) too weak to affect a normal pupil. Horner's is a sympathetic lesion tested with cocaine/hydroxyamphetamine. 3. In a suspected Horner's syndrome, which result confirms the diagnosis? A. The affected pupil dilates widely with 4% cocaine B. The affected pupil fails to dilate with 4% cocaine C. Both pupils dilate equally with hydroxyamphetamine D. The affected pupil constricts with pilocarpine Answer B. Cocaine blocks NE reuptake, but a Horner eye is not releasing NE, so there is nothing to potentiate and the pupil fails to dilate. Hydroxyamphetamine is then used to localize the lesion level. 4. Which agent is the drug of choice for routine cycloplegic refraction, balancing strength and duration? A. Atropine 1% B. Tropicamide 1% C. Cyclopentolate 1% D. Phenylephrine 2.5% Answer C. Cyclopentolate 1%. It gives reliable cycloplegia with a far shorter duration than atropine (14 days). Tropicamide is too weak a cycloplegic; phenylephrine has none. 5. A glaucoma patient with asthma needs an IOP-lowering beta blocker. The safest choice is: A. Timolol (non-selective) B. Levobunolol (non-selective) C. Betaxolol (cardio-selective) D. Carteolol (non-selective) Answer C. Betaxolol. Cardio-selective (β1) blockers spare the β2 receptors in the airway, so they are safer in asthma and COPD. Non-selective blockers risk bronchoconstriction.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2-01-autonomic-drugs-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"G2 — Autonomic (Ocular) Drugs\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Draw the empty 2x2 grid (agonist/antagonist × sympathetic/parasympathetic) and fill each box with its effect and one example drug. No looking. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the cycloplegic duration table (5 drugs, mydriasis/cycloplegia onset, duration). Order them strongest to weakest. Drill 3 — Derive, Don't Recall Given \\\"brimonidine,\\\" write the suffix, the receptor (α2), the action (decrease aqueous), and the use. Repeat for timolol, phenylephrine, pilocarpine, dapiprazole. Drill 4 — Clinical Tests Write the cocaine test, hydroxyamphetamine test, and Adie's pilocarpine test from memory: drug, expected result, what it localizes. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a parasympatholytic causes cycloplegia but a sympathomimetic does not. Use the word \\\"ciliary muscle.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump (the grid) 2nd Next day Blank Table + Derive 3rd 3 days Clinical Tests 4th 1 week Teach-Back Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Diagnostic agents are drugs you use to see something, not to treat. They fall into three families: Mydriatics and cycloplegics (to open the pupil and study the fundus or refraction). Covered in detail in G2-01-Autonomic-Drugs . Topical anesthetics (to numb the cornea so you can touch it: tonometry, foreign body, gonioscopy). Dyes (to stain and reveal: epithelial defects, tear film, leaks, drainage). This note focuses on the anesthetics and dyes. The single most testable idea is matching the right dye to what it stains, and the right anesthetic to the right procedure. Teaching angle: anesthetics work by one mechanism (block the sodium channel). Dyes differ by one question: does it stain living defects (fluorescein) or dead/devitalized cells and mucus (rose bengal, lissamine)? Sort every dye by that question.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Why does an anesthetic fail in an infected, inflamed eye? Local anesthetics are weak bases. They cross the nerve membrane only in the uncharged (non-ionized) form. Infected tissue is acidic, which pushes the drug into its charged form, so less enters the nerve and the block is weak. This is why you cannot reliably numb an abscess. Why does fluorescein glow only where the epithelium is broken? Intact epithelium is a lipid barrier the water-soluble dye cannot enter. Where cells are missing, the dye floods the intercellular spaces and the stroma, then fluoresces yellow-green under cobalt blue. No defect, no stain. Why use rose bengal before fluorescein in a dry eye workup? Rose bengal stains devitalized cells and mucus (the hallmark of dry eye) and is read in red light without fluorescence. Fluorescein would flood the tear film and obscure the subtle devitalized-cell pattern, so you stain with rose bengal first. Why does proparacaine sting so little and act so fast? It is an ester with very low tissue irritation and poor corneal penetration, so it numbs the surface in seconds and wears off in about 20 minutes without deep effects. That speed and gentleness make it the everyday tonometry drop.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Topical anesthetic numbs the surface Blocks the Na+ channel on sensory nerves Ester anesthetic one \\\"i\\\" before -caine Plasma pseudo-cholinesterase; less allergenic, shorter acting Amide anesthetic two \\\"i\\\"s before -caine Liver-metabolized; more potent, longer acting Non-ionized form uncharged base The only form that crosses the nerve membrane Fluorescein low-MW dye (376) Stains epithelial defects; glows under cobalt blue Rose bengal brilliant red dye Stains devitalized cells and mucus; early dry eye Devitalized cells dead/dying cells The dry-eye target stained by rose bengal / lissamine Quenching loss of fluorescence Occurs above pH 8 or above ~0.001% concentration Seidel test fluorescein stream Detects an aqueous wound leak TBUT tear break-up time Time to first dry spot; measures tear film stability Applanation flattening the cornea Goldmann tonometry; needs fluorescein plus anesthetic\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-the-details-topical-anesthetics\",\"heading\":\"Topical Anesthetics\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Mechanism: block the sodium (Na+) channel on sensory nerves, stopping depolarization and pain conduction. Two theories: specific receptor (block the channel) and membrane expansion (insert into the membrane and deform the channel). Calcium normally regulates Na+ movement, so anesthetics also compete with calcium. Ester vs Amide (count the letter \\\"i\\\" in the name before -caine): Feature Esters (one \\\"i\\\") Amides (two \\\"i\\\"s) Examples Co c aine, Pro c aine, Tetra c aine, Benzo c aine, Proparacaine, Benoxinate L i doca i ne, Bup i vaca i ne, Mep i vaca i ne, Pr i loca i ne Metabolized by Plasma pseudo-cholinesterase Liver Toxicity / allergy Less toxic, less allergic More potent, longer acting Duration Shorter Longer The four topical agents to know: Agent Conc Key facts Proparacaine 0.5% Most used. Onset 5–15 sec, duration ~20 min. Least irritating/allergic. Tonometry, gonioscopy, minor procedures Tetracaine 0.5% 10x as potent as cocaine, longer acting, more stinging. FB removal, corneal scraping, ERG Benoxinate 0.4% Combined with fluorescein (Fluress) for applanation. Has antibacterial property Cocaine 2–10% The only natural anesthetic; also mydriatic + vasoconstrictor. Diagnoses Horner's (4–10%). NOT used for tonometry (softens cornea, false low reading). Addictive Key uses by procedure: Goldmann applanation = proparacaine or benoxinate. ERG = tetracaine. Forced duction test = cocaine or lidocaine. Corneal epithelial debridement = cocaine. Comparison drill — the \\\"which anesthetic\\\" questions (commonly tested, easy to miss): Most toxic to the corneal epithelium: tetracaine (most potent → most epithelial-toxic and most stinging). Least stinging / gentlest: proparacaine (the routine tonometry drop). Least bactericidal: proparacaine. Benoxinate, by contrast, carries an antibacterial property. Low antibacterial activity is actually the desirable trait right before culturing. Highest convulsion risk if it reaches the bloodstream: tetracaine (most potent → greatest CNS-excitation/seizure risk; any agent can do this at high systemic levels). Concentration is not depth: past the effective concentration, adding more does NOT deepen anesthesia — it only adds toxicity and stinging. Culture BEFORE the anesthetic: anesthetic drops and their preservatives are bacteriostatic and suppress organism growth, giving a false-negative culture. Injectable note: add epinephrine (1:100,000–1:200,000) to prolong the block by vasoconstriction; add bicarbonate to raise the non-ionized fraction and speed absorption; add hyaluronidase (spreading factor) to widen tissue spread. Side effects: mild stinging/burning (most common), shortened TBUT, reduced reflex tearing and blinking, slowed epithelial healing. Never prescribe for home use (masks pain → corneal damage, see F1-01-DPA-Examination ). Systemic toxicity is CNS (excitation then seizures, the most serious) and CVS (arrhythmia, hypotension).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-the-details-diagnostic-dyes\",\"heading\":\"Diagnostic Dyes\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"The organizing question: what does it stain? Fluorescein stains epithelial defects (where cells are missing). Rose bengal, lissamine, methylene blue stain devitalized cells and mucus (dead/dying tissue). Trypan blue, ICG stain endothelium (used in surgery). Fluorescein (the workhorse): Low molecular weight (376). Orange crystal, yellow in solution. Fluoresces yellow-green under cobalt blue (465–490 nm absorption) in weak alkali. Stains epithelial defects bright green; will not stain dead cells or mucus. Stains soft contact lenses (remove them first); promotes Pseudomonas growth. Quenching phenomenon: fluorescence drops above pH 8 or above ~0.001% concentration. Uses: TBUT, applanation tonometry, RGP fit pattern, Seidel test, Jones test, IV fluorescein angiography (retinal/choroidal vessels). Diagnostic tests built on fluorescein: TBUT: time for the first dry spot to appear in the tear film. Seidel test: detects aqueous leak from a wound (dye streams green against the yellow-orange background). Jones I: dye reaches the nose = patent drainage. Jones II: irrigate after a negative Jones I; dye recovered = partial block at duct; no dye = block at canaliculi/puncta. The dye comparison table (memorize this grid): Dye Epithelial defect Devitalized cells / mucus Endothelium Extra property Fluorescein ✓ – – – Fluorexon ✓ ✓ – High MW, safe on soft CL Rose Bengal – ✓ – Antiviral; use before fluorescein Indocyanine green – – ✓ IV; choroidal angiography (805 nm) Methylene blue – ✓ – Antibacterial; stains corneal nerves Trypan blue – ✓ ✓ Stains anterior capsule for capsulorhexis Lissamine green – ✓ – Antiviral; screens vitamin A deficiency Argyrol – ✓ – Checks pre-op scrub adequacy Rose bengal: brilliant red, seen with the naked eye, stains nucleus more than cytoplasm. Best for early KCS / Sjogren's and herpetic dendrites. Stings (the anesthetic added to ease it can itself kill cells and give a false positive). Indocyanine green: protein-bound, infrared, better for choroidal neovascular membranes than fluorescein. Trypan blue: anionic, no side effects; checks endothelial integrity for grafting and stains the capsule in phaco. Lissamine green: gentler alternative to rose bengal; screens xerophthalmia. Negative staining (fluorescein): dye pools AROUND a raised area and is displaced off the elevated surface, so the bump reads dark against the surrounding green. It signals elevated epithelium (e.g. epithelial basement membrane dystrophy) — NOT pits or pockets. Positive staining, by contrast, is dye filling a true defect/depression. True dendrite vs pseudodendrite (rose bengal pattern): a true HSV dendrite stains at its margins / ulcer bed (a real ulcer with terminal end-bulbs). Rose bengal filling the center of the lesion points to a pseudodendrite (herpes zoster, healing epithelium, drug toxicity) — raised, heaped epithelium rather than a true ulcer. Rose bengal is the classic conjunctival stain and has the stronger antiviral property; lissamine green stains the same devitalized cells but is far gentler.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Proparacaine onset / duration 5–15 sec / ~20 min Cocaine for Horner's 4–10% Fluorescein absorption peak 465–490 nm (cobalt blue) Fluorescein emission peak 520–530 nm Fluorescein MW 376 Quenching threshold pH > 8 or conc > 0.001% Benoxinate potency 10x cocaine, 2x tetracaine ICG absorption peak 805 nm (infrared) Injectable epinephrine for block 1:100,000–1:200,000\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"TOPICAL ANESTHETIC — block the pain ──────────────────────────────────── Weak base → only UNCHARGED form crosses nerve → blocks Na+ channel → no depolarization acidic (infected) tissue → drug IONIZED → weak block ESTER (one \\\"i\\\") → plasma pseudo-cholinesterase · less allergic · shorter AMIDE (two \\\"i\\\"s) → LIVER · longer acting DYE SORTING — what does it stain? ────────────────────────────────── Epithelial DEFECT (missing cells) → FLUORESCEIN (green under cobalt blue) Devitalized cells / mucus → ROSE BENGAL / LISSAMINE (dry eye; rose BEFORE fluorescein) Endothelium / capsule → TRYPAN BLUE / ICG (surgery) FLUORESCEIN-BASED TESTS ─────────────────────── TBUT → tear stability · Seidel → wound leak · Jones I/II → lacrimal drainage\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Anesthetic mechanism \\\"block the Na channel, stop the pain signal.\\\" Ester vs amide count the i's. One i = ester (cocaine, procaine, tetracaine, proparacaine). Two i's = amide (lidocaine, bupivacaine). Dye sorting fluorescein = the living gap; rose bengal/lissamine = the dead cells; trypan/ICG = the endothelium . \\\"Rose before fluorescein\\\" in a dry eye workup. Cocaine: numbs, dilates, and diagnoses Horner's, but never for tonometry (softens cornea). Fluorescein + soft CL = permanent stain. Remove first. Jones I to the nose; Jones II irrigate to localize.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"fluorescein stains dead cells. It stains epithelial defects (missing cells); rose bengal and lissamine stain dead/devitalized cells. cocaine is a good tonometry anesthetic. It softens the cornea and gives a falsely low IOP. Use proparacaine or benoxinate. anesthetics work better in infected tissue because of more blood flow. Acidic infected tissue ionizes the drug and weakens the block. rose bengal is read under cobalt blue like fluorescein. It is a red dye seen in white light; it does not depend on fluorescence the way fluorescein does. apply fluorescein first, then rose bengal. order for dry eye. Rose bengal first , then fluorescein. amides are metabolized by plasma cholinesterase. Amides are metabolized by the liver ; esters by plasma pseudo-cholinesterase. a higher-concentration anesthetic drop gives deeper anesthesia. Past the effective concentration, more only adds toxicity and stinging — depth does not keep climbing. take the culture after numbing the eye for comfort. Culture first — the anesthetic and its preservative are bacteriostatic and cause a false-negative. negative staining means pits or pockets in the epithelium. Negative staining marks an elevated area (dye displaced off a raised surface); pits/depressions give positive staining. proparacaine is antibacterial like benoxinate. Proparacaine is the least bactericidal; benoxinate carries the antibacterial property.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Anesthetic mechanism Block Na+ channel Ester vs amide rule Count the \\\"i\\\"s (one = ester) Everyday tonometry anesthetic Proparacaine 0.5% Anesthetic that diagnoses Horner's Cocaine 4–10% Stains epithelial defects Fluorescein Stains devitalized cells / mucus Rose bengal, lissamine, methylene blue Stains endothelium / capsule Trypan blue, ICG Used before fluorescein in dry eye Rose bengal Detects aqueous wound leak Seidel test (fluorescein) Tests lacrimal drainage Jones I and II (fluorescein) Dye that must not touch soft CL Fluorescein\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"1. A topical anesthetic fails to numb a heavily infected, inflamed cornea. The best explanation is: A. Infection destroys the sodium channels B. The acidic tissue ionizes the drug, so less enters the nerve C. Inflammation washes the drug away too quickly D. Bacteria metabolize the anesthetic Answer B. Anesthetics cross the nerve in their uncharged form. Acidic (infected) tissue shifts the weak base to its charged form, reducing penetration and weakening the block. 2. Which dye is best for detecting the devitalized cells of early keratoconjunctivitis sicca? A. Fluorescein B. Trypan blue C. Rose bengal D. Indocyanine green Answer C. Rose bengal. It stains devitalized cells and mucus, the early marker of dry eye/Sjogren's. Fluorescein stains epithelial defects , not dead cells; ICG and trypan blue are for endothelium/surgery. 3. For Goldmann applanation tonometry, the appropriate anesthetic and dye combination is: A. Cocaine and rose bengal B. Proparacaine (or benoxinate) and fluorescein C. Tetracaine and ICG D. Lidocaine and lissamine green Answer B. Applanation needs a fast gentle anesthetic (proparacaine or benoxinate, the latter pre-mixed with fluorescein as Fluress) plus fluorescein to define the tear meniscus and applanation area. Cocaine is contraindicated (softens cornea). 4. A patient has a post-cataract wound. You instill fluorescein and see a green stream flowing from the incision against a yellow-orange background. This is a positive: A. Jones I test B. Seidel test C. TBUT D. Schirmer test Answer B. Seidel test. A streaming green flow of diluted aqueous against the concentrated dye background confirms a wound leak. 5. Which statement about ester versus amide anesthetics is correct? A. Amides are metabolized by plasma cholinesterase B. Esters have two \\\"i\\\"s in their generic name C. Esters are metabolized by plasma pseudo-cholinesterase and are less allergenic per dose D. Amides are shorter acting than esters Answer C. Esters (one \\\"i\\\") are broken down by plasma pseudo-cholinesterase and tend to be less toxic per the source. Amides (two \\\"i\\\"s) are liver-metabolized and longer acting.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3-01-diagnostic-pharmaceutical-agents-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"G3 — Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the three diagnostic families (mydriatics/cycloplegics, anesthetics, dyes) and two example agents under each. No looking. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the dye comparison grid (8 dyes × stains epithelial defect / devitalized cells / endothelium / extra property). Drill 3 — Match the Procedure For tonometry, ERG, forced duction, gonioscopy, and corneal scraping, write the anesthetic of choice from memory. Drill 4 — Sort by \\\"i\\\" List ten -caine drugs and tag each ester or amide by counting the i's. Then state how each group is metabolized. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why fluorescein only glows where the epithelium is broken. Use the word \\\"barrier.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Dye Grid 3rd 3 days Match the Procedure 4th 1 week Sort by \\\"i\\\" Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Therapeutic agents treat disease (diagnostic agents only reveal it). Three big jobs dominate the board: Lower eye pressure (anti-glaucoma): either make less aqueous or drain more. Kill the bug (anti-infectives): antibiotics, antivirals, antifungals. Calm inflammation (corticosteroids, NSAIDs, antihistamines). The glaucoma drugs are the heart of this note. Everything about them comes from one equation: IOP depends on aqueous made minus aqueous drained. Every drug either turns the tap down (less secretion) or opens the drain wider (more outflow). Teaching angle: for any glaucoma drug, ask one question: \\\"does this cut production or boost outflow?\\\" Then the side effects and combinations follow.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Why are prostaglandin analogs first-line for glaucoma? They open the uveoscleral outflow, a second drainage route that bypasses the diseased trabecular meshwork. Once-daily dosing, strong effect, and few systemic risks make them the modern first choice. The price is cosmetic: iris darkening and longer lashes. Why do beta blockers and CAIs lower pressure the same way but cause different harms? Both cut aqueous production at the ciliary body. Beta blockers do it by blocking adenylate cyclase (so they hit the lungs and heart too: asthma and bradycardia). CAIs do it by blocking carbonic anhydrase (so they cause paresthesia, diuresis, and a metallic taste, because the same enzyme works in the kidney). Same goal, different collateral. Why does long-term steroid use cause glaucoma and cataract? Steroids let glycosaminoglycans pile up in the trabecular meshwork, clogging outflow (steroid-response glaucoma after 4 to 6 weeks; permanent after about 18 months). They also drive posterior subcapsular cataract. So the drug that calms the eye can quietly blind it, which is why steroid courses are monitored. Why can a beautiful antibiotic still poison the eye or ear? Aminoglycosides are excellent against gram-negative bugs but are ototoxic and nephrotoxic beyond five days. Chloramphenicol risks aplastic anemia. Choosing an antibiotic is always benefit against its specific toxicity.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Anti-glaucoma agent lowers IOP Cuts aqueous production or boosts outflow Prostaglandin analog prostaglandin mimic First-line; opens uveoscleral outflow Carbonic anhydrase inhibitor blocks the enzyme Cuts aqueous secretion; a sulfonamide (sulfa caution) Osmotic agent osmotic gradient Pulls water from the eye in acute angle-closure Uveoscleral outflow alternate drain Bypasses the trabecular meshwork; prostaglandin target Corticosteroid adrenal steroid Inhibits phospholipase A2; risks glaucoma + PSC cataract NSAID non-steroidal anti-inflammatory Inhibits cyclooxygenase; no IOP change Phospholipase A2 upstream enzyme Steroid target; blocking it stops PGs and leukotrienes Steroid-response glaucoma GAG buildup in TM Open-angle IOP rise after 4–6 weeks of steroids Aminoglycoside protein-synthesis inhibitor Gram-negative cover; oto/nephrotoxic beyond 5 days Mast-cell stabilizer blocks degranulation Cromolyn; prevents calcium influx in allergy\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-the-details-anti-glaucoma-agents-the-core\",\"heading\":\"Anti-Glaucoma Agents (the core)\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"The aqueous equation: IOP rises from too much secretion or too little outflow (trabecular ~80%, uveoscleral 10 to 20%). Normal IOP 10 to 21 mmHg, glaucoma usually >21. Three enzymes that make aqueous (drug targets): Na/K-ATPase, carbonic anhydrase (CAI target), adenylate cyclase (beta-blocker target). The five medical classes, sorted by mechanism: Class Example (cap color) Mechanism Notes Prostaglandin analogs Latanoprost, travoprost, bimatoprost (turquoise) ↑ uveoscleral outflow First-line. S/E: iris heterochromia, longer/darker lashes Beta blockers Timolol (yellow/blue) ↓ secretion (block adenylate cyclase) Avoid non-selective in asthma/COPD/IDDM; use betaxolol Alpha-2 agonists Brimonidine, apraclonidine (purple) ↓ secretion (+ some outflow) Apraclonidine lowers IOP after laser Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors Dorzolamide, brinzolamide; oral acetazolamide (orange) ↓ secretion (block carbonic anhydrase) S/E: paresthesia (most common), diuresis, metallic taste, acidosis Cholinergics / miotics Pilocarpine, carbachol (green) ↑ trabecular outflow (ciliary muscle pulls drain open) Drug-induced myopia, miosis Acetazolamide specifics: oral CAI, 250 mg every 4 h. S/E: nephrolithiasis, potassium loss, transient myopia (ciliary swelling shallows the chamber), aplastic anemia, metabolic acidosis. Contraindicated in sulfa allergy, Addison's, kidney/liver disease. Osmotic agents (acute angle-closure, pre-op): pull water out by osmotic gradient. Mannitol: IV, large molecule stays in blood, safe in renal disease, most used. Glycerin: oral, raises blood glucose (avoid in diabetes). Isosorbide: oral, safe in diabetes (not metabolized to glucose). Urea: IV, avoid in renal disease. Open angle = treat medically; angle-closure = treat surgically (laser peripheral iridotomy with YAG/argon). Pilocarpine is used in acute angle-closure to pull the iris out of the angle. Gonioscopy grading (Shaffer): Grade Structures seen Angle Closure risk 4 Ciliary body 35–45° Impossible 3 Scleral spur 25–35° Impossible 2 Trabeculum only 20° Possible 1 Schwalbe's line only 10° Probable 0 Iridocorneal contact 0° Closed/imminent The comprehensive glaucoma exam: Tonometry (pressure), Ophthalmoscopy (disc), Perimetry (field), Gonioscopy (angle), Pachymetry (corneal thickness; thin cornea is a strong risk predictor).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-the-details-anti-infective-agents\",\"heading\":\"Anti-Infective Agents\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Antibiotics by mechanism (high yield): Mechanism Examples Inhibit cell wall synthesis Penicillin, cephalosporin, bacitracin, vancomycin Alter cell membrane Polymyxin B Inhibit protein synthesis Aminoglycosides, tetracycline, macrolides, chloramphenicol Inhibit nucleic acid (DNA gyrase) Quinolones, rifampicin Block folic acid (antimetabolite) Sulfonamides Ocular pearls: Tetracycline: drug of choice for trachoma and inclusion conjunctivitis. Avoid in children and pregnancy (teeth, bone). Aminoglycosides (gentamicin, tobramycin, neomycin): gram-negative coverage; ototoxic and nephrotoxic beyond 5 days. Neomycin also covers Acanthamoeba. Fluoroquinolones (cipro, oflox, levoflox): broad; avoid in children/pregnancy (cartilage). Chloramphenicol: DOC for typhoid; risk of aplastic anemia. Macrolides (erythromycin): for penicillin-allergic patients. Antifungals: inhibit ergosterol synthesis. Natamycin (polyene) is the topical workhorse for filamentary fungi (Fusarium, Aspergillus); amphotericin B (most potent, IV) for systemic; fungi are linked to contact-lens solution contamination. Antivirals: topical trifluridine, vidarabine, acyclovir for herpes/VZV; IV ganciclovir/foscarnet and intravitreal fomivirsen for CMV retinitis. Idoxuridine was the first approved antiviral. Antimalarial ocular toxicity (chloroquine/hydroxychloroquine): corneal verticillata (whorl deposits), bull's-eye maculopathy , halos, color (tritan) defects, decreased VA (earliest sign). Anti-TB ocular toxicity: ethambutol and isoniazid cause optic neuritis ; streptomycin is ototoxic/nephrotoxic.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-the-details-anti-inflammatory-agents\",\"heading\":\"Anti-Inflammatory Agents\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Corticosteroids (the big one): MOA: inhibit phospholipase A2 → less prostaglandins AND leukotrienes (upstream of NSAIDs). Anterior segment disease: topical is most effective. Posterior segment: systemic, periocular, or intravitreal. Ocular side effects (must know): steroid-response open-angle glaucoma (4 to 6 weeks; permanent after ~18 months), posterior subcapsular cataract , secondary infection (fungal, herpes), delayed healing, mydriasis, ptosis. Contraindications: herpetic/viral keratitis, fungal disease, untreated infection, post-FB removal (delays healing). Potency ladder: cortisone (least) < hydrocortisone < prednisone/prednisolone (10x cortisone) < dexamethasone/betamethasone (30 to 50x). Fluorometholone has the least IOP rise, so it is the safer steroid in glaucoma-prone eyes. Systemic side effects: Cushingoid moon face, osteoporosis, PUD, hyperglycemia, immunosuppression, mood change. NSAIDs: inhibit cyclooxygenase → less prostaglandins. Effects: reduce surgical miosis, stabilize blood-aqueous barrier, no IOP change, can worsen herpes. Examples: ketorolac (allergic conjunctivitis), diclofenac, flurbiprofen. Antihistamines / mast-cell stabilizers: block H1 (levocabastine) or stabilize mast cells ( cromolyn sodium 4% , prevents calcium influx and degranulation) for vernal/atopic/seasonal allergic conjunctivitis.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Normal IOP 10–21 mmHg Trabecular vs uveoscleral outflow ~80% / 10–20% Acetazolamide dosing 250 mg every 4 h Steroid glaucoma onset / permanence 4–6 weeks / ~18 months Dexamethasone potency vs cortisone 30–50x Aminoglycoside toxicity threshold >5 days First-line glaucoma class Prostaglandin analogs Argon laser trabeculoplasty IOP drop ~75% (2–3x per eye lifetime)\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"THE AQUEOUS EQUATION — IOP = made − drained ───────────────────────────────────────────── CUT PRODUCTION (3): Beta blockers · Alpha-2 agonists · CAIs BOOST OUTFLOW (2): Prostaglandins → UVEOSCLERAL · Miotics → TRABECULAR \\\"three down, two out\\\" GLAUCOMA TYPE → TREATMENT ───────────────────────── OPEN angle → medical (drops) CLOSED angle → SURGICAL emergency: laser iridotomy (pilocarpine temporizes) INFLAMMATION CASCADE — where the drugs cut ─────────────────────────────────────────── Membrane phospholipids → [phospholipase A2] ← STEROIDS block here (also stop leukotrienes) → arachidonic acid → [cyclooxygenase] ← NSAIDs block here → PROSTAGLANDINS\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"The aqueous equation IOP = made − drained. Every glaucoma drug cuts production or boosts outflow. Cut production (3) Beta blockers, Alpha-2 agonists, CAIs. Boost outflow (2): Prostaglandins (uveoscleral), Miotics (trabecular). \\\"Three down, two out.\\\" Cap colors Red mydriatic, Green miotic, Yellow/blue beta blocker, Orange CAI, Turquoise prostaglandin, Purple adrenergic, Pink steroid. CAI = carbonic anhydrase = kidney too (paresthesia, diuresis, metallic taste, stones). Steroid eye = glaucoma + posterior subcapsular cataract. Fluorometholone is the safe one. Antibiotic toxicities aminoglycoside = ears/kidney; chloramphenicol = aplastic anemia; ethambutol = optic neuritis; chloroquine = bull's-eye macula. Tetracycline = trachoma. Steroids work upstream (phospholipase A2); NSAIDs work downstream (COX).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"beta blockers lower IOP by increasing outflow. They decrease production (block adenylate cyclase). prostaglandins drain through the trabecular meshwork. They open the uveoscleral route. acetazolamide is safe in sulfa allergy. It is a sulfonamide; avoid in sulfa allergy. steroids and NSAIDs share the same enzyme target. Steroids block phospholipase A2 (upstream, also stops leukotrienes); NSAIDs block COX only. the safest steroid for an eye at glaucoma risk is dexamethasone. Fluorometholone raises IOP least. angle-closure glaucoma is treated medically first. Angle-closure is a surgical emergency (laser iridotomy); medical drops are temporizing. chloroquine's earliest sign is the bull's-eye. Careful. The earliest functional sign is decreased VA / color change ; the bull's-eye is the classic late fundus finding.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer First-line glaucoma drug Prostaglandin analog (uveoscleral outflow) Classes that cut aqueous production Beta blockers, alpha-2 agonists, CAIs Classes that boost outflow Prostaglandins (uveoscleral), miotics (trabecular) Safe beta blocker in asthma Betaxolol (cardio-selective) Acetazolamide class / caution CAI / sulfa allergy Acute angle-closure osmotic Mannitol (IV) Steroid MOA Inhibit phospholipase A2 Steroid ocular S/E Glaucoma + posterior subcapsular cataract Safest steroid for IOP Fluorometholone DOC trachoma Tetracycline Aminoglycoside toxicity Oto/nephrotoxic >5 days Optic neuritis from TB drug Ethambutol, isoniazid Bull's-eye maculopathy Chloroquine\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"1. Which glaucoma drug class lowers IOP by increasing uveoscleral outflow? A. Beta blockers B. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors C. Prostaglandin analogs D. Alpha-2 agonists Answer C. Prostaglandin analogs. They open the uveoscleral route and are first-line. The other three all reduce aqueous production. 2. A patient on long-term topical dexamethasone develops gradually rising IOP and a posterior subcapsular cataract. The mechanism of the pressure rise is: A. Increased aqueous production B. Glycosaminoglycan accumulation in the trabecular meshwork C. Pupillary block D. Ciliary body swelling Answer B. Steroids cause GAG buildup in the trabecular meshwork, reducing outflow (steroid-response glaucoma after 4 to 6 weeks). Posterior subcapsular cataract is the classic lens side effect. 3. Which antibiotic is the drug of choice for trachoma? A. Gentamicin B. Tetracycline C. Penicillin D. Polymyxin B Answer B. Tetracycline. It is the DOC for trachoma and inclusion conjunctivitis. Avoid in children and pregnancy. 4. A glaucoma patient with a sulfa allergy should avoid which agent? A. Timolol B. Latanoprost C. Acetazolamide D. Pilocarpine Answer C. Acetazolamide. It is a sulfonamide (carbonic anhydrase inhibitor), contraindicated in sulfa allergy. The others are unrelated chemically. 5. Which steroid is preferred when an anti-inflammatory is needed in an eye prone to high IOP? A. Dexamethasone B. Betamethasone C. Prednisolone D. Fluorometholone Answer D. Fluorometholone. It produces the least IOP elevation, making it the safer choice in steroid responders and glaucoma-prone eyes.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4-01-therapeutic-ophthalmic-agents-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"G4 — Therapeutic Ophthalmic Agents\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Draw the aqueous equation, then list the five glaucoma classes under \\\"cut production\\\" or \\\"boost outflow.\\\" Add one example per class. Drill 2 — Blank Table Reproduce the five-class glaucoma table (class, example, cap color, mechanism). No looking. Drill 3 — Toxicity Match Write the signature toxicity for: aminoglycoside, chloramphenicol, ethambutol, chloroquine, long-term steroid. One line each. Drill 4 — Steroid Ladder List the corticosteroid potency ladder from cortisone to dexamethasone, and circle the one that is safest for IOP. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a CAI causes tingling and a metallic taste. Use the word \\\"kidney.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump (aqueous equation) 2nd Next day Glaucoma Table 3rd 3 days Toxicity Match 4th 1 week Steroid Ladder Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"This note has two halves: Systemic drugs that hurt the eye. A patient swallows a pill for the heart, lungs, or joints, and it leaves a fingerprint somewhere in the eye: cornea, lens, retina, optic nerve, or color vision. The board loves to give you the drug and ask for the finding (or the reverse). These are pattern-matching points, almost free if you drill the pairs. Special populations. Pregnancy, children, and the elderly change which drug you reach for, because their bodies handle drugs differently. Teaching angle: for the toxicity half, do not memorize long lists. Anchor on the signature pairs (chloroquine = bull's-eye macula, digitalis = yellow vision, ethambutol = optic neuritis). The classic exam item is a single drug and a single finding.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Why is tropicamide the preferred dilator in pregnancy? All ocular agents are FDA Category C (risk not ruled out). Tropicamide has the shortest duration and least systemic absorption, so when you must dilate, it exposes mother and fetus the least. Always add nasolacrimal occlusion. (See G1-01-General-Pharmacology-Principles and F1-01-DPA-Examination .) Why do children react badly to cyclopentolate, and the elderly to many systemic drugs? Children have an immature liver, so a normal dose builds up and reaches the brain (cyclopentolate causes hallucinations and seizures, especially at 2%). The elderly have a declining liver and kidney, so drugs clear slowly and accumulate. Both are dosing problems caused by the same organ: a metabolizing system that is either not ready or wearing out. Why do so many drugs cause cornea verticillata (a whorl pattern)? Amphiphilic drugs (chloroquine, amiodarone, indomethacin, tamoxifen) bind lipids and get trapped in the basal corneal epithelium, where they deposit in a golden-brown whorl that follows the cornea's natural cell-migration spiral. Different drugs, one mechanism, one pattern. Why do anticholinergic drugs trigger acute angle-closure? They dilate the pupil. In a narrow angle, dilation bunches the iris into the drain and blocks outflow. So antihistamines, tricyclics, and motion-sickness scopolamine can all precipitate an attack in a susceptible eye.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Cornea verticillata whorl keratopathy Golden whorl from amphiphilic drugs (CATI) Xanthopsia Greek xanthos = yellow Yellow vision; the classic digitalis effect Bull's-eye maculopathy ring of RPE depigmentation Classic late chloroquine retinal finding Pseudotumor cerebri raised ICP, no mass Papilledema from vitamin A excess, OCPs, tetracycline Amphiphilic drug lipid- and water-loving Binds lipids; deposits in cornea (verticillata) FDA Category C risk not ruled out The class of all ocular drugs in pregnancy Idiosyncratic reaction illogical response e.g. a mydriatic paradoxically causing miosis Tritan defect blue-yellow color loss Earliest color change in several drug toxicities Polypharmacy many concurrent drugs Raises interaction/toxicity risk in the elderly Retrobulbar neuritis inflammation behind the globe Ethambutol / INH optic toxicity pattern\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-the-details-ocular-side-effects-by-structure\",\"heading\":\"Ocular Side Effects by Structure\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Cornea: Cornea verticillata (whorl keratopathy): chloroquine, amiodarone (anterior deposits), indomethacin, tamoxifen, chlorpromazine, suramin. Band keratopathy: excess vitamin D. Gold salts: chrysiasis. Deferoxamine: corneal discoloration. Lens (cataract): Corticosteroids: posterior subcapsular cataract. Phenothiazines (thioridazine, chlorpromazine): stellate anterior subcapsular deposits; also corneal endothelial dusting. Statins (lovastatin), strong miotics. Retina: Chloroquine / hydroxychloroquine: bull's-eye maculopathy. Phenothiazines, indomethacin: pigmentary retinopathy, cystoid macular edema. Tamoxifen: crystalline retinopathy. Oral contraceptives: vascular occlusion (CRAO, CRVO). Quinine: vessel attenuation. Niacin: cystoid macular edema. Optic nerve: Ethambutol, isoniazid (INH), chloramphenicol, streptomycin: optic/retrobulbar neuritis and atrophy. Lithium, oral contraceptives, amiodarone, excess vitamin A: papilledema / pseudotumor cerebri. Ethanol: toxic amblyopia (VA loss, tritan defect, centrocecal scotoma). Color vision: Digitalis: xanthopsia (yellow/\\\"snowy\\\" vision). Amiodarone: colored halos. Ethambutol, INH: red-green defect. Indomethacin, chloroquine, phenothiazine: tritan (blue-yellow, earliest, hits ganglion cells). IOP and angle: Steroids: open-angle glaucoma (GAG buildup in trabecular meshwork). Anticholinergics, antihistamines, tricyclics, benzodiazepines, scopolamine, amphetamines: acute angle-closure with pupillary block. Drugs that lower IOP: beta blockers, diuretics, CAIs, marijuana. Refraction shift: Transient myopia: sulfonamides, tetracycline, acetazolamide, steroids, hydrochlorothiazide (ciliary body edema shifts the lens forward). Hyperopia: oral hypoglycemic agents (fluid uptake lowers lens index). Surface and contact lens: Dry eye: oral retinoids, antihistamines, anticholinergics, diuretics. Blepharoconjunctivitis: isotretinoin, amiodarone, gold salts, methotrexate, rifampin. Contact lens intolerance (CLI): isotretinoin (8 to 10%), vitamin A, antihistamines, tricyclics, oral contraceptives, phenothiazines.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-the-details-the-signature-pairs-drill-these-cold\",\"heading\":\"The Signature Pairs (drill these cold)\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Drug Classic ocular finding Chloroquine / hydroxychloroquine Bull's-eye maculopathy + cornea verticillata + tritan Amiodarone Cornea verticillata (anterior) + colored halos Ethambutol / INH Optic neuritis + red-green defect Digitalis Xanthopsia (yellow vision) Corticosteroids PSC cataract + open-angle glaucoma + myopia Phenothiazines (thioridazine) Stellate anterior cataract + pigmentary retinopathy Tamoxifen Crystalline retinopathy + cornea verticillata Chloramphenicol Aplastic anemia + optic neuritis Vitamin A excess Pseudotumor cerebri / papilledema Oral contraceptives CRVO / CRAO + pseudotumor Isotretinoin Dry eye + CLI + blepharoconjunctivitis Topiramate / sulfonamides Acute transient myopia + angle-closure\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-the-details-special-populations\",\"heading\":\"Special Populations\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Pregnancy: All ocular drugs are FDA Category C . If dilation is required: tropicamide (shortest duration, least exposure) + nasolacrimal occlusion. Avoid phenylephrine 10% (cardiovascular), tetracycline/fluoroquinolones (fetal bone/cartilage). Pediatric: Immature liver → systemic toxicity. Cyclopentolate CNS effects (hallucination, seizure) at 2%; use 0.5 to 1% and press the lacrimal sac. Atropine is used for cycloplegic refraction and amblyopia penalization but watch for systemic anticholinergic toxicity (flush, fever, tachycardia). Geriatric: Declining liver and kidney → slowed clearance, drug accumulation, higher toxicity risk. More polypharmacy → more drug interactions and more of the systemic toxicities above (chronic amiodarone, statins, diuretics). Higher baseline angle-closure risk; be cautious dilating. Idiosyncratic / sensitivity terms (from G1-01-General-Pharmacology-Principles ): women carry a higher unexplained toxicity risk; idiosyncratic reactions are illogical (a mydriatic causing miosis).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Pregnancy category, ocular drugs C Preferred dilator in pregnancy Tropicamide + NLO Cyclopentolate safe pediatric strength 0.5–1% Isotretinoin CLI rate 8–10% Steroid glaucoma onset / permanent 4–6 weeks / ~18 months\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"SYSTEMIC DRUG → OCULAR STRUCTURE IT HITS ───────────────────────────────────────── CORNEA (verticillata) → chloroquine · amiodarone · tamoxifen · indomethacin ( CATI ) LENS (cataract) → steroids = POSTERIOR · phenothiazines = ANTERIOR stellate RETINA → chloroquine = bull's-eye · phenothiazine = pigmentary · OCP = occlusion OPTIC NERVE → ethambutol · INH · chloramphenicol → neuritis COLOR VISION → digitalis = YELLOW (xanthopsia) · ethambutol = red-green IOP / ANGLE → steroids = open-angle · anticholinergics = angle-closure SPECIAL POPULATIONS — one organ story ────────────────────────────────────── PREGNANCY → all Category C → tropicamide + NLO (least exposure) PEDIATRIC → immature LIVER → cyclopentolate 0.5–1% ( CNS toxicity at 2%) GERIATRIC → failing liver/kidney → slow clearance + polypharmacy → more toxicity\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Signature pairs first. Chloroquine = bull's-eye; digitalis = yellow; ethambutol = optic neuritis; amiodarone = halos + whorls; steroid = cataract + glaucoma. Cornea verticillata \\\"CATI\\\" Chloroquine, Amiodarone, Tamoxifen, Indomethacin. Lower IOP drugs Beta blockers, Diuretics, CAIs, Marijuana. Special populations = one organ story immature liver (kids), failing liver/kidney (elderly), shared fetus (pregnancy). Anticholinergic = dilation = angle-closure risk. Xanthopsia = digitalis (think Van Gogh's yellow period, a digitalis legend).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"amiodarone whorl keratopathy means the drug must be stopped. Usually not. The corneal deposits are common, dose-related, and reversible; the dangerous amiodarone effect to watch is optic neuropathy . chloroquine's earliest sign is the bull's-eye. The bull's-eye is the classic late macular finding; early change is reduced VA and color (tritan). steroids cause anterior subcapsular cataract. Steroids cause posterior subcapsular cataract; phenothiazines cause the anterior stellate one. ethambutol causes a blue-yellow defect. Ethambutol/INH classically cause a red-green defect. all dilators are equally safe in pregnancy. Tropicamide is preferred; phenylephrine 10% is avoided. digitalis causes blue vision. Digitalis causes xanthopsia (yellow).\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Bull's-eye maculopathy Chloroquine / hydroxychloroquine Yellow vision (xanthopsia) Digitalis Optic neuritis + red-green defect Ethambutol, INH Colored halos + anterior whorls Amiodarone PSC cataract + glaucoma Corticosteroids Anterior stellate cataract Phenothiazines Aplastic anemia Chloramphenicol Pseudotumor cerebri Excess vitamin A, OCPs, tetracycline Transient myopia Sulfonamides, acetazolamide, steroids Preferred dilator in pregnancy Tropicamide + NLO Cyclopentolate pediatric strength 0.5–1%\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"1. A patient on long-term hydroxychloroquine for lupus reports trouble with central vision. The classic fundus finding is: A. Cherry-red spot B. Bull's-eye maculopathy C. Cotton-wool spots D. Disc neovascularization Answer B. Bull's-eye maculopathy. Chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine cause a ring of RPE depigmentation around a spared center. Early change is reduced VA and tritan color loss. 2. A cardiac patient on digitalis complains that everything looks yellow (\\\"snowy\\\"). This is: A. Cyanopsia B. Erythropsia C. Xanthopsia D. Chloropsia Answer C. Xanthopsia. A yellow tinge to vision is the classic digitalis effect. 3. A TB patient on ethambutol reports dimming vision and trouble telling red from green. The toxicity is: A. Optic neuritis with red-green defect B. Cataract C. Angle-closure glaucoma D. Pigmentary retinopathy Answer A. Ethambutol (and INH) cause optic neuritis/neuropathy with a red-green color defect. This is a reason to monitor color vision and fields in patients on anti-TB therapy. 4. Which drug is preferred when a pregnant patient requires pupil dilation? A. Phenylephrine 10% B. Atropine 1% C. Tropicamide 0.5% D. Cyclopentolate 2% Answer C. Tropicamide 0.5%. Shortest duration and least systemic exposure among Category C agents. Add nasolacrimal occlusion. 5. A child given 2% cyclopentolate becomes disoriented and hallucinates. The cause is: A. Allergic reaction B. Systemic anticholinergic CNS toxicity from immature hepatic metabolism C. Angle-closure glaucoma D. Local anesthetic overdose Answer B. A child's immature liver lets the drug accumulate and cross into the CNS, producing anticholinergic toxicity. Use 0.5 to 1% and apply lacrimal sac pressure.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the 12 signature drug-to-finding pairs from memory. Score yourself; circle the misses. Drill 2 — Reverse Recall Given findings (bull's-eye, xanthopsia, anterior stellate cataract, red-green defect, colored halos), name the drug for each. Drill 3 — By Structure List one toxic drug each for cornea, lens, retina, optic nerve, and color vision. No looking. Drill 4 — Special Populations Write the dosing rule and the reason for pregnancy, pediatric, and geriatric patients in one line each. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why a child reacts worse than an adult to the same cyclopentolate dose. Use the word \\\"liver.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Signature Pairs 2nd Next day Reverse Recall 3rd 3 days By Structure 4th 1 week Special Populations Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5-01-special-populations-and-drug-effects-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"G5 — Special Populations and Ocular Side Effects of Systemic Drugs\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. Autonomic pupil effect — cue: agonist/antagonist + system. Number rule: 1 constricts, 2 dilates (α1 mydriasis, α2 cuts aqueous, β2 raises aqueous). Dilate w/o cycloplegia = sympathomimetic; dilate + cycloplegia = parasympatholytic; constrict = parasympathomimetic. Trap: \\\"β2 stimulation lowers IOP\\\" — β2 increases aqueous. Cycloplegic strength — cue: strongest/longest vs routine. Atropine = strongest/longest (14 d); tropicamide = weakest/shortest; cyclopentolate = routine DOC. Trap: \\\"tropicamide is the strongest cycloplegic.\\\" Glaucoma drug mechanism — cue: cut production vs boost outflow. Cut production (3): β-blockers, α2 agonists, CAIs. Boost outflow (2): prostaglandins ( uveoscleral ), miotics ( trabecular ). Trap: \\\"β-blockers increase outflow\\\" or \\\"prostaglandins drain trabecular.\\\" Pupil-test pairs — cue: cocaine / hydroxyamphetamine / pilocarpine. Cocaine confirms Horner (fails to dilate); hydroxyamphetamine localizes ; 0.1% pilocarpine constricts an Adie's pupil. Trap: a Horner pupil \\\"dilates with cocaine\\\" — it fails to. Drug → ocular sign — cue: the drug named. Chloroquine = bull's-eye (late); digitalis = xanthopsia (yellow); ethambutol/INH = optic neuritis + red-green; steroid = PSC cataract + glaucoma. Trap: \\\"ethambutol = blue-yellow defect\\\" — it's red-green .\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"G.strategy\",\"subject\":\"G\",\"label\":\"Ocular Pharmacology — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/G-Ocular-Pharmacology/G-Subject-Exam-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Ocular Pharmacology · the read-before-you-test reference for all 5 topics G1 Principles G2 Autonomic G3 Diagnostic G4 Therapeutic G5 Side Effects\"},{\"anchor\":\"g1\",\"heading\":\"G1General Pharmacology Principles\",\"topic\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Two buckets: Kinetics = what the body does to the drug (ADME). Dynamics = what the drug does to the body (receptor + effect). Core rules: liver metabolizes (P-450), kidney excretes. Lipid = uncharged = absorbable. k = 0.693/t½ (0.693 = ln 2). Vd = most important parameter. TI = LD50/ED50 . Combos: Additive 1+1=2 · Synergism 1+1>2 · Potentiation 0+1>1. Bonds: covalent = strongest (irreversible); Van der Waals = weakest, most common (reversible = competitive antagonism). Misc: potency = low dose, efficacy = max effect. IV = 100% bioavailable. Atropine excreted unchanged in urine. Schedule I = no medical use. Rx = recipe ('to take'). Trap: potency equals efficacy. No — potency is the dose needed; efficacy is the maximum effect.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g2\",\"heading\":\"G2Autonomic Drugs\",\"topic\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"2x2 grid: Sphincter = M3 (parasympathetic, miosis); dilator = α1 (sympathetic, mydriasis). Number rule: 1 constricts, 2 dilates (α1 mydriasis, α2 cuts aqueous, β2 raises aqueous). Cycloplegic Duration Atropine (strongest) 14 days Homatropine 6 h – 4 days Scopolamine 24 h Cyclopentolate (routine cycloplegic) 6–24 h Tropicamide (routine mydriatic, weakest) 4–6 h Pupil tests: Adie's constricts to 0.1% pilocarpine; Horner's: cocaine confirms (fails to dilate), hydroxyamphetamine localizes. Echothiopate/DFP = iris cysts (reverse with 2.5% phenylephrine). Organophosphate poisoning antidote = atropine. Suffixes: -olol = beta blocker · -onidine = α2 agonist · -zoline = α1 decongestant · -stigmine = AChE inhibitor. Trap: tropicamide is the strongest cycloplegic. No — it is the weakest/shortest; atropine is strongest.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g3\",\"heading\":\"G3Diagnostic Agents (Anesthetics & Dyes)\",\"topic\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Anesthetics block Na⁺ channels. Count the i's: one = ester (cocaine, proparacaine, tetracaine; plasma cholinesterase), two = amide (lidocaine; liver). Proparacaine = everyday drop; cocaine diagnoses Horner's but NOT for tonometry (softens cornea). Dye sorting: Fluorescein = the living gap (epithelial defects, cobalt blue 465 nm) · Rose bengal / lissamine = the dead cells (use rose bengal before fluorescein) · Trypan / ICG = the endothelium/choroid. Tests: Seidel = aqueous wound leak; Jones I/II = lacrimal drainage. Add epinephrine to prolong a block, bicarbonate to speed it. Trap: anesthetics work better in infected tissue. No — acidic tissue ionizes the drug and weakens the block.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g4\",\"heading\":\"G4Therapeutic Agents\",\"topic\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Glaucoma \\\"3 down, 2 out\\\": cut production = Beta blockers, Alpha-2 agonists, CAIs. Boost outflow = Prostaglandins (uveoscleral, first-line), Miotics (trabecular). Watch-outs: acetazolamide (CAI) = sulfa allergy + paresthesia; betaxolol is the asthma-safe beta blocker; mannitol IV for acute angle-closure. Steroids inhibit phospholipase A2 → ocular S/E = glaucoma + posterior subcapsular cataract; fluorometholone is safest for IOP. Antibiotic pearls: tetracycline = trachoma DOC; aminoglycosides = oto/nephrotoxic >5 days; chloramphenicol = aplastic anemia; ethambutol/INH = optic neuritis; natamycin = filamentary fungi. Trap: prostaglandins drain through the trabeculum. No — they open the uveoscleral route. Trap: acetazolamide is safe in sulfa allergy. No — it is a sulfonamide; avoid it.\"},{\"anchor\":\"g5\",\"heading\":\"G5Ocular Side Effects & Special Populations\",\"topic\":\"Subject G — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Drug Classic ocular finding Chloroquine / hydroxychloroquine Bull's-eye maculopathy (+ verticillata, tritan) Digitalis Xanthopsia (yellow vision) Ethambutol / INH Optic neuritis + red-green defect Amiodarone Cornea verticillata + colored halos Corticosteroids PSC cataract + glaucoma Phenothiazines Stellate anterior cataract Tamoxifen Crystalline retinopathy Cornea verticillata \\\"CATI\\\": Chloroquine, Amiodarone, Tamoxifen, Indomethacin. Lower IOP: beta blockers, diuretics, CAIs, marijuana. Special populations: pregnancy → all Category C, tropicamide + NLO preferred. Pediatric → immature liver; cyclopentolate 2% = CNS toxicity (use 0.5–1%). Geriatric → slowed clearance, accumulation. Trap: steroids cause anterior subcapsular cataract. No — steroids = posterior subcapsular; phenothiazines = anterior stellate. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject G strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"H.reviewer\",\"subject\":\"H\",\"label\":\"Jurisprudence & Ethics — Reviewer\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/H-Jurisprudence-and-Ethics/H-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 is the Revised Optometry Law of 1995 . It is the single law that defines what optometry is, who may practice it, how you get licensed, who regulates you, and what gets you punished. It repealed the old RA 1998 . Think of it as answering five questions: What is the practice of optometry? (the acts you are allowed to do) Who may practice? (registered, licensed optometrists only, with narrow exceptions) How do you become one? (the licensure exam and registration) Who watches over you? (the Board of Optometry, under the PRC) What is forbidden, and what is the penalty? (prohibited acts and penal provisions) Teaching angle: the board loves the numbers (5 board members, 75% passing, 3-year renewal, 1 to 8 years jail). Lock the numbers first; they are the cheapest marks in jurisprudence.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Why does optometry need its own law at all? Because optometrists use diagnostic drugs and make clinical decisions that affect health. The State declares optometry part of primary health care , so it regulates entry and conduct to protect the public, the same reason medicine and pharmacy are licensed. Why can a physician examine the eye without an optometry license, but a public health worker can only do a visual acuity test? The law protects scope by training. A physician with post-graduate eye training is more qualified, so examining the eye is allowed and is not \\\"practicing optometry.\\\" A public health worker in a blindness-prevention program is trained only for screening, so they may do visual acuity and screening only , nothing more. Scope follows competence. Why does the law require a separate pharmacology certification before using DPAs? Diagnostic drugs are real pharmaceuticals with real risks (see F1-01-DPA-Examination and G2-01-Autonomic-Drugs ). Section 31 requires those trained before the law to pass a special pharmacology certification before they may instill DPAs. Using DPAs untrained is a prohibited act, injury or not. Why is the Board term non-renewable and staggered? Five-year non-renewable terms, with one member rotating out each year, keep the Board independent and continuous: no one entrenches, and experience is never lost all at once. The senior member becomes chairperson in the final year.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 Republic Act 8050 Revised Optometry Law of 1995; repealed RA 1998 PRC Professional Regulation Commission Government body that supervises the Board of Optometry Board of Optometry regulatory board 5 members, 5-year non-renewable term, under the PRC Certificate of registration proof of registration Issued by PRC after the oath; displayed in the clinic Professional license renewable credential Renewed every 3 years with continuing education DPA Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agent Requires pharmacology certification (Sec 31) to use Orthoptics Greek orthos = straight + optikos = sight Eye-muscle and vision training within optometry's scope Primary health care first-contact care RA 8050 declares optometry a regular component of it Integration (Sec 36) one national organization All ODs integrated; it promulgates the Code of Ethics Quorum minimum present to act 3 of the 5 board members Prohibited act (Sec 32) forbidden conduct e.g. comparative/price advertising, untrained DPA use\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-what-the-law-is\",\"heading\":\"What the Law Is\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Title: Revised Optometry Law of 1995 (RA 8050). Repealed RA 1998 (the old Optometry Law). State policy: optometry is an essential profession and a regular component of the primary health care system . Optometry (definition): the science and art of examining the eye, analyzing ocular function, prescribing and dispensing lenses/prisms/contact lenses/low-vision aids, conducting ocular exercises and orthoptics, installing prosthetics, using authorized DPAs, and other measures for the aid, correction, or relief of the human eye.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-historical-milestones-jurisprudence-background\",\"heading\":\"Historical Milestones (jurisprudence background)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"The board loves \\\"firsts\\\" and the law lineage. Source: Cinco, \\\"Optometry: Legal and Professional Aspects.\\\" Law lineage: Optometry Law of 1917 (first, written in Spanish; amended 1919) to RA 1998 (1957) to RA 8050 (1995). The 1917 law created the Junta Examinadora (Board of Examiners), later renamed the Board of Optometry by PD 223 (as amended by PD 657). First optometric clinic with refraction + first lens-grinding shop: R.M. Clark, Manila, 1902 . First optometry school: Philippine College of Optometry (to 1925). First university-affiliated college: Centro Escolar University, 1928 . Registration Certificate No. 1 (per PRC records): issued March 11, 1918 to Sabater . Associations: OAP (1936, Justo Gonzalez first president) + PODA + PROA merged in 1979 into Samahan Ng Optometrist Sa Pilipinas (SOP) , the integrated national body. Regional/world: IFAPAO founded at the 1st APOC (Manila, 1978 ); later became APCO . IOOL became the WCO . First International Optometrist of the Year (1988) was M. Cinco . Deeper coverage in the Law Book (full) reviewer linked from the H reviewer bar.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-acts-constituting-practice-sec-4\",\"heading\":\"Acts Constituting Practice (Sec 4)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"(a) Examining the eye (subjective + objective, with DPAs and instruments); (b) prescribing and dispensing lenses, prisms, contact lenses, frames; (c) ocular exercises, vision training, orthoptics, prosthetics; (d) counseling on vision and eye care; (e) establishing offices/clinics; (f) collecting professional fees for acts a to d.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-who-may-practice-sec-5-exceptions\",\"heading\":\"Who May Practice (Sec 5 exceptions)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Only registered, licensed optometrists. Exceptions: Physicians with post-graduate eye training (and a physician's eye exam during a physical is not \\\"practicing optometry\\\"). Public health workers in the blindness-prevention program: visual acuity test and visual screening only . Disclosure (Sec 6): indicate license number and expiry on documents; display the certificate of registration conspicuously in the clinic.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-the-board-of-optometry\",\"heading\":\"The Board of Optometry\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Item Rule Members 5 , appointed by the President from 10 nominees of the accredited national organization Term 5 years, non-renewable , staggered (one rotates out yearly; senior becomes chair in final year) Quorum 3 members Votes for an administrative decision 3 members Supervision Under the PRC (Professional Regulation Commission) Removal By the President for neglect, incompetence, malpractice, or unethical conduct\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-licensure-sec-17-to-29\",\"heading\":\"Licensure (Sec 17 to 29)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Exam given at least once a year by the Board. Requirements (Sec 19): Filipino citizen, good moral character, Doctor of Optometry (O.D.) from an accredited school after a 6-year course . Passing (Sec 20): general average of at least 75%, with no subject below 50%. Results reported to PRC within 60 days . Fail 3 times → must take a refresher course before re-examination (Sec 22). Take the oath , then PRC issues the certificate of registration and professional license . License renewal every 3 years with continuing education and fees (Sec 29). Appeals (Sec 27): appeal a revocation/suspension to the PRC within 15 days .\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-dpas-and-pharmacology-sec-31\",\"heading\":\"DPAs and Pharmacology (Sec 31)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Optometrists practicing before the law must take a pharmacology course and pass a special certification exam before using DPAs. The 5 approved DPAs are detailed in F1-01-DPA-Examination : phenylephrine, tropicamide, cyclopentolate, proparacaine, fluorescein (plus miotics).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-prohibited-acts-sec-32-and-penalties-sec-33\",\"heading\":\"Prohibited Acts (Sec 32) and Penalties (Sec 33)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Prohibited: (a) false evidence to the Board; (b) posing as a registered optometrist without a license; (c) comparative/price advertising (\\\"better than others,\\\" cheaper fees/lenses); (d) DPA use by an untrained optometrist; (e) using unauthorized drugs; (f) unauthorized practice; (g) any violation of the Act or its rules. Penalty (Sec 33): imprisonment of 1 to 8 years , or a fine of P10,000 to P40,000 , or both , at the court's discretion. Administrative penalties (Sec 26 revocation/suspension) also apply.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-the-details-integration-and-ethics-sec-36-to-40\",\"heading\":\"Integration and Ethics (Sec 36 to 40)\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"All optometrists are integrated into one national organization , which promulgates the Code of Professional Ethics (adopted by the Board, approved by PRC). Six ethical duties (Sec 40): primary responsibility to the visual welfare of the public ; promote best standards; continuously improve proficiency; serve all equally regardless of race/creed/status; respect confidentiality ; and refer when medical or other attention is needed. (Expanded in H2-01-Bioethics-and-Code-of-Ethics .)\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Law number / title RA 8050 / Revised Optometry Law of 1995 Repealed RA 1998 Board members 5 (from 10 nominees) Board term 5 years, non-renewable Quorum / admin vote 3 / 3 Passing grade 75% average, none below 50% Results to PRC within 60 days Refresher trigger fail 3 times License renewal every 3 years Appeal period 15 days to PRC Penalty 1–8 years jail, P10,000–40,000 fine, or both Course length 6-year O.D.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 — THE LICENSURE PATHWAY ─────────────────────────────── 6-year O.D. (accredited) → BOARD EXAM (≥1×/yr) → PASS = 75% avg, none < 50% → oath → PRC issues CERTIFICATE OF REGISTRATION + professional LICENSE → renew every 3 YEARS (CE + fees) FAIL 3× → REFRESHER course before retake revoked / suspended → APPEAL to PRC within 15 DAYS BOARD OF OPTOMETRY ────────────────── President appoints 5 members ← 10 nominees (accredited national org) 5-year term, NON- renewable, staggered (senior = chair in final year) quorum 3 · administrative decision 3 · under the PRC WHO MAY PRACTICE (Sec 5) ──────────────────────── Registered licensed OD → full scope Physician + PG eye training → may examine the eye Public health worker → VA + screening ONLY\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 = 1995, repealed RA 1998 (8050 is newer and bigger than 1998). Board of \\\"5 from 10,\\\" 5-year non-renewable, quorum 3. 75 over 50 pass at 75% average, never below 50% in any subject. 3 strikes = refresher; 3-year renewal; 3 to appeal? No, 15 days to appeal. Penalty \\\"1 to 8, 10 to 40\\\" 1 to 8 years, P10,000 to P40,000. Public health workers: VA and screening only. No comparative or price advertising (prohibited act c).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 repealed RA 1998, so 1998 is newer. The numbers mislead. RA 8050 (1995) is the current law ; RA 1998 was the older one it replaced. a public health worker may dispense glasses under the blindness program. Only visual acuity and screening . the Board has 7 members. 5 , from 10 nominees. passing is a 75% average with no rule on individual subjects. No subject may fall below 50% . license renews every 5 years (like the Board term). 3 years . advertising lower fees is allowed if true. Comparative and price advertising is a prohibited act . appeals have 30 days. 15 days to the PRC. Registration Certificate No. 1 went to the reputed \\\"first,\\\" Federico Sarabia. per PRC records. It was issued to Sabater (March 11, 1918). RA 8050 lists 6 DPAs. As originally written it lists 5 ; the 6th (Cyclopentolate) came from the 2008 IRR . Match the count to what the question asks. RA 8050 still requires CPD to renew a license. That Sec. 29 requirement was repealed by Sec. 20 of RA 8981 (PRC Modernization Act of 2000).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer RA 8050 common name Revised Optometry Law of 1995 Law it repealed RA 1998 Regulatory agency PRC (Board of Optometry under it) Board members / nominees 5 / 10 Board term 5 years, non-renewable Passing grade 75% avg, none below 50% Renewal of license every 3 years Fail 3x consequence refresher course Appeal window 15 days Penalty range 1–8 years, P10,000–40,000, or both Public health worker scope VA + screening only Required to use DPAs pharmacology certification (Sec 31)\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"1. A candidate scores a 78% general average but gets 48% in one subject. Under RA 8050, the candidate: A. Passes (average is above 75%) B. Fails (a subject is below 50%) C. Passes conditionally D. Must retake only that subject Answer B. Fails. Section 20 requires at least a 75% average AND no rating below 50% in any subject. The 48% disqualifies despite the high average. 2. Who may legally examine the human eye without an optometry license under RA 8050? A. Any pharmacist B. A physician with post-graduate eye training C. An optician D. A contact lens salesperson Answer B. Section 5 exempts physicians with post-graduate training in diagnosis and treatment of eye disease. Public health workers may do only visual acuity testing and screening. 3. The Board of Optometry is composed of how many members, and from how many nominees? A. 3 members from 6 nominees B. 5 members from 10 nominees C. 7 members from 14 nominees D. 5 members from 5 nominees Answer B. 5 members from 10 nominees , appointed by the President on PRC recommendation, from the accredited national organization's list. 4. An optometrist places an ad claiming \\\"lower fees than any clinic in town.\\\" Under RA 8050 this is: A. Allowed if the claim is true B. A prohibited act C. Allowed with Board approval D. Allowed only in print media Answer B. A prohibited act. Section 32(c) prohibits advertising conveying that one optometrist is better or charges lower fees. Truth is no defense. 5. A person convicted of unauthorized practice of optometry faces what penalty? A. Fine only, up to P5,000 B. Imprisonment of 1 to 8 years, or fine of P10,000 to P40,000, or both C. License suspension only D. Community service Answer B. Section 33 sets imprisonment of 1 to 8 years, or a fine of P10,000 to P40,000, or both, at the court's discretion, plus applicable administrative penalties.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1-01-ra8050-optometry-law-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"H1 — RA 8050: The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the five questions RA 8050 answers (what, who, how, who regulates, what is forbidden) and one fact under each. Drill 2 — Numbers Sprint From memory write: board members, nominees, term, quorum, passing grade, renewal period, appeal window, penalty range. Drill 3 — Scope Lines Write the two Section 5 exceptions and exactly what each is allowed to do. Drill 4 — Prohibited Acts List the seven prohibited acts (Sec 32) in your own words. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why RA 8050 requires a separate pharmacology certification to use DPAs. Use \\\"risk.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Numbers Sprint 2nd Next day Brain Dump 3rd 3 days Scope Lines 4th 1 week Prohibited Acts Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Ethics is not law. Law tells you what you must do or face punishment; ethics tells you what you ought to do as a professional. The whole field rests on four principles (Beauchamp and Childress): Autonomy: respect the patient's right to decide (the basis of informed consent). Beneficence: do good, act in the patient's best interest. Non-maleficence: do no harm (primum non nocere). Justice: treat patients fairly and equally. The RA 8050 Code of Professional Ethics (Sec 40) is just these four principles written into optometric duties. Master the four, and the code, the scenarios, and the traps all fall out of them. Teaching angle: for any ethics scenario, name which of the four principles is in play. Most questions are testing autonomy (consent) or non-maleficence (harm/referral).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Why is informed consent the same thing as autonomy, not just a signature? Autonomy means a competent patient has the right to accept or refuse care. That right is meaningless unless the patient actually understands what they are agreeing to, so informed consent requires disclosure of the diagnosis, the options, the risks, the benefits, and the alternatives. A signed form without understanding is not consent; it is paperwork. Why does non-maleficence not mean \\\"never do anything risky\\\"? Every useful treatment carries some risk (dilating drops, contact lenses, even a referral that worries a patient). Non-maleficence is a balance, not a ban: the expected benefit must outweigh the expected harm. Doing nothing is also a choice with consequences, so \\\"first do no harm\\\" means weigh, do not freeze. Why must you keep monitoring a patient who refuses your referral? Autonomy lets the patient refuse, but beneficence and non-maleficence do not let you abandon them. You document the refusal, re-explain the risk, and keep caring for them at each visit. The principles work together; one does not cancel the others. Why is treating a PhilHealth patient worse than a private patient an ethics violation? Justice requires the same standard of care for similar cases regardless of ability to pay, race, creed, or status. Care quality is not a product tier. Distributive justice is exactly this: equal access to the same standard.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Autonomy Greek autos = self + nomos = rule Patient's right to decide; basis of informed consent Beneficence Latin bene = good + facere = to do Acting in the patient's best interest Non-maleficence Latin male = bad + facere \\\"Do no harm\\\"; benefit must outweigh harm Justice Latin justitia = fairness Equal standard of care regardless of status Informed consent knowing agreement Understanding diagnosis, options, risks; not just a signature Assent Latin assentire = agree A child's agreement alongside parental consent Primum non nocere Latin = \\\"first, do no harm\\\" The motto of non-maleficence Confidentiality Latin confidere = to trust Patient records and diagnoses are privileged Distributive justice fair allocation Same standard for PhilHealth and private patients alike Beauchamp & Childress framework authors Originated the four-principles model of bioethics\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-the-four-principles\",\"heading\":\"The Four Principles\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Principle Meaning Optometric application Violation example Autonomy Patient's right to decide Informed consent; respect refusal Instilling a DPA without explaining side effects or getting consent Beneficence Do good, best interest Prescribe what the patient truly needs; monitor proactively Selling an unneeded Rx upgrade for profit Non-maleficence Do no harm Avoid contraindicated drugs; refer beyond scope Fitting extended-wear lenses in a non-compliant patient with prior keratitis Justice Fairness, equal care Same standard regardless of status Substandard exam for a PhilHealth vs private patient\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-informed-consent-the-heart-of-autonomy\",\"heading\":\"Informed Consent (the heart of autonomy)\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Four components: the patient is informed of (1) the diagnosis and its implications, (2) the treatment options and expected outcomes, (3) the risks and alternatives, and (4) voluntarily agrees or declines without coercion . Special populations: Minors: a parent or guardian consents; seek assent from older children. Incompetent patients: a guardian or surrogate decides. Emergency: consent may be waived when delay would cause serious harm. (These mirror the legal doctrines in G1-01-General-Pharmacology-Principles : informed consent, respondeat superior, and consent for minors/incompetents.)\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-the-ra-8050-code-of-ethics-sec-40-mapped-to-principles\",\"heading\":\"The RA 8050 Code of Ethics (Sec 40) mapped to principles\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Sec 40 duty Maps to Primary responsibility = visual welfare of the public Beneficence Promote the best possible standards of care Beneficence Continuously improve proficiency Continuous competence Render services with equal diligence to all (race, creed, status) Justice Respect confidential information Autonomy / trust Refer for medical attention when indicated Non-maleficence A violation of the Code is unethical conduct , punishable by suspension or prohibition from practice (RA 8050 Sec 26).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-additional-professional-principles\",\"heading\":\"Additional Professional Principles\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Confidentiality: records and diagnoses are privileged; no disclosure without consent. Referral obligation: refer when a condition is beyond your competence or scope. Continuous competence: keep current through continuing education (ties to the 3-year license renewal in H1-01-RA8050-Optometry-Law ). Collegiality: professional respect; do not disparage colleagues. Protection of the vulnerable: extra care for children, elderly, and cognitively impaired patients.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-the-details-worked-scenarios\",\"heading\":\"Worked Scenarios\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Patient refuses referral for a suspicious disc: autonomy lets them refuse; document clearly, re-counsel the risk, keep monitoring, do not abandon. Company offers a gift to prescribe their lenses exclusively: justice and beneficence say lens choice must follow clinical merit, not commercial ties; decline. A minor arrives alone for a contact lens fit: autonomy requires parent/guardian consent; defer until obtained.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"THE FOUR PRINCIPLES (Beauchamp & Childress) ──────────────────────────────────────────── AUTONOMY → informed consent; respect refusal BENEFICENCE → do good; prescribe what is truly needed NON-MALEFICENCE → primum non nocere; refer beyond scope JUSTICE → same standard for everyone INFORMED CONSENT = autonomy in action ────────────────────────────────────── Diagnosis → options + outcomes → risks + alternatives → VOLUNTARY agreement (no coercion) Minor → parent/guardian consents (child gives ASSENT ) Incompetent → guardian / surrogate decides Emergency → consent may be WAIVED if delay causes harm SEC 40 CODE DUTY → which principle ────────────────────────────────── Visual welfare of the public → BENEFICENCE Equal diligence to all → JUSTICE Refer when indicated → NON-MALEFICENCE Respect confidentiality → AUTONOMY / trust\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"The four: \\\"A-B-N-J\\\" Autonomy, Beneficence, Non-maleficence, Justice. Autonomy = informed consent (the right, not the form). Non-maleficence = primum non nocere = benefit must beat harm (not \\\"never risk\\\"). Justice = same standard for everyone. Sec 40 = the four principles in optometric clothing. Most-tested: autonomy (consent) and non-maleficence (referral/contraindication). Refusal of referral: document, re-counsel, do not abandon.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"informed consent is just getting a signature. It is the patient understanding diagnosis, options, risks, and alternatives. It is the expression of autonomy. non-maleficence means avoiding all risk. It means the expected benefit must outweigh the expected harm. if a competent patient refuses care, you have done your duty and can discharge them. You document, re-counsel, and continue to monitor; abandonment is unethical. a minor can consent to their own contact lens fitting. A parent or guardian consents; the child gives assent. ethics and law are the same. Law is enforceable rules with penalties; ethics is professional moral obligation (though RA 8050 makes a Code violation punishable). treating a charity patient with a quicker, lesser exam is acceptable resource management. Justice requires the same standard of care.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer The four principles Autonomy, beneficence, non-maleficence, justice Framework authors Beauchamp and Childress Informed consent is an expression of Autonomy \\\"Do no harm\\\" Latin Primum non nocere Minor's consent Parent/guardian (child gives assent) Emergency consent May be waived if delay causes harm Equal care regardless of status Justice (distributive) Refer beyond scope Non-maleficence Code of Ethics location RA 8050 Sec 40 Penalty for Code violation Suspension/prohibition (Sec 26)\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"1. An optometrist instills a dilating drop without telling the patient it will blur near vision and cause light sensitivity, and without asking permission. Which principle is violated? A. Justice B. Beneficence C. Autonomy (informed consent) D. Collegiality Answer C. Autonomy. Failing to disclose effects and obtain consent violates the patient's right to make an informed decision. 2. Choosing not to fit extended-wear lenses in a non-compliant patient with a history of microbial keratitis primarily reflects which principle? A. Autonomy B. Non-maleficence C. Justice D. Confidentiality Answer B. Non-maleficence. Avoiding a foreseeable harm whose risk outweighs the benefit is \\\"do no harm.\\\" 3. A competent adult refuses referral for a suspicious optic disc. The most ethical action is: A. Refuse to see the patient again B. Override the refusal and refer anyway C. Document the refusal, re-counsel the risk, and continue monitoring D. Report the patient to the Board Answer C. Autonomy allows refusal, but beneficence and non-maleficence require continued care: document, re-counsel, and keep monitoring. 4. Providing a faster, lesser examination to a PhilHealth patient than to a private patient with the same complaint violates: A. Autonomy B. Beneficence C. Justice D. Non-maleficence Answer C. Justice. Distributive justice requires the same standard of care regardless of ability to pay or status. 5. Under RA 8050 Section 40, which duty corresponds most directly to the principle of non-maleficence? A. Consider the visual welfare of the public as the primary responsibility B. Refer for medical attention when indicated C. Render services with equal diligence to all D. Respect confidentiality Answer B. Referring when a condition exceeds your competence prevents harm, the core of non-maleficence. Visual welfare is beneficence; equal diligence is justice; confidentiality protects trust/autonomy.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2-01-bioethics-and-code-of-ethics-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"H2 — Bioethics and the Code of Professional Ethics\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the four principles with a one-line definition and one optometric example each. No looking. Drill 2 — Map the Code Write the six Sec 40 duties and the principle each maps to. Drill 3 — Consent Components List the four components of informed consent and the three special-population rules (minor, incompetent, emergency). Drill 4 — Name the Principle For five scenarios (unneeded Rx upgrade, no consent for DPA, unequal care, refusing a kickback, fitting risky lenses), name the principle in play. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why informed consent is more than a signature. Use the word \\\"understand.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Map the Code 3rd 3 days Consent Components 4th 1 week Name the Principle Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-simple-version\",\"heading\":\"The Simple Version\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Practice management is the business and regulatory side of running a clinic. Three blocks: Setting up the business: the government registrations every clinic needs (DTI, Barangay, Mayor, BIR). Running a compliant clinic: what the Board Resolution No. 11 (Series of 2016) requires of your office (instruments, room size, displays, no commercialization). Advertising and conduct: what you may and may not say to attract patients ( Board Resolution No. 1, Series of 2008 , and RA 8050 Sec 32). Teaching angle: the recurring theme is professionalism over commercialization . Almost every rule exists to keep optometry a profession, not a retail counter. When unsure on an exam item, pick the answer that protects professional dignity.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-but-why\",\"heading\":\"But Why?\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Why so many separate registrations to open one clinic? Each agency licenses a different thing: DTI registers your business name , the Barangay clears your location , the Mayor issues the business permit to operate, and the BIR registers you for taxes . They stack because each level of government has its own authority over a part of running a business. Why must the exam room be enclosed, a set size, and free of the product display? Because the law wants the clinical act separated from the sales act. A defined, professional examination space (minimum 10 square meters , 3-meter test distance) signals that the patient is receiving health care, not shopping. Frames and sunglasses must not be used to identify or highlight the practice, to protect optometry's image against commercialization. Why is chair time the sole discretion of the doctor? Because clinical decisions must be free of commercial pressure. The optical's manager or owner cannot tell the optometrist to rush an exam to see more customers. The doctor decides the method, procedure, and time; that independence is what makes it a profession. Why are price and \\\"free service\\\" ads prohibited? Because competing on price and giveaways turns eye care into a discount race, which degrades standards and dignity. The law allows only true, honest, dignified, objective information. You may say what you do, not that you are cheaper or better than colleagues.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-details-terminology-unpacked\",\"heading\":\"Terminology Unpacked\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"DTI Department of Trade and Industry Registers the business name (5-year certificate) BIR Bureau of Internal Revenue Registers TIN and books of accounts (taxes) TIN Taxpayer Identification Number Issued by BIR on registration Barangay clearance local location clearance Clears the clinic's location to operate Mayor's permit business permit Allows operation after fire/sanitation inspections COR Certificate of Registration Proof of registration; displayed in the clinic PIC Professional Identification Card Current PRC ID; displayed and kept updated COGS Certificate of Good Standing Displayed credential of standing CPD Continuing Professional Development Certificates displayed; supports 3-year renewal Respondeat superior Latin \\\"let the master answer\\\" Optometrist is responsible for delegated staff acts Board Resolution PRC Board issuance Res 11 (2016) clinic rules; Res 1 (2008) advertising Commercialization turning care into retail What the office and advertising rules guard against\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-details-1-setting-up-the-business-sole-proprietorship\",\"heading\":\"1. Setting Up the Business (sole proprietorship)\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Step Agency What you get 1 DTI (Department of Trade and Industry) Business name registration (submit up to 3 name choices; certificate valid 5 years ) 2 Barangay Barangay clearance / certificate of business registration (pay community tax) 3 Mayor's office Mayor's / business permit (after inspections: fire, sanitation, electrical, etc.) 4 BIR (Bureau of Internal Revenue) Certificate of registration, TIN , and registered books of accounts\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-details-2-compliant-clinic-board-resolution-no-11-series-of-2016\",\"heading\":\"2. Compliant Clinic (Board Resolution No. 11, Series of 2016)\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Office/Clinic (Rule VII, Sec 44): Notify the Board of your clinic location and submit photographs within 30 days of securing the premises; report any change of location. The clinic must be used exclusively for optometry, enclosed and apart from commercial concerns. Display: names and specializations of the optometrists, valid CORs, updated PICs (professional ID cards), Certificates of Good Standing, and CPD certificates. Only optometry-related certificates and diplomas may be shown. The clinic must be manned by a licensed optometrist during operating hours . Instruments and Equipment (Sec 46): Ocular exam: slit-lamp, ophthalmoscope, retinoscope, phoropter, trial lens set, VA chart, Ishihara plates, Amsler grid, contrast sensitivity chart, tangent screen. Binocular vision: penlight + occluder, prism bar + loose prisms, Maddox wing, RAF rule, Worth Four Dot, Stereo Fly. Contact lens: keratometer (or topographer), CL trial lenses. Optional: Schiotz/Goldmann tonometer, automated tangent screen, automated perimeter. Physical Facilities (Sec 47): Examination/treatment room: minimum 10 square meters , test distance at least 3 meters , optometrist's name posted outside. Receiving area: for registration and forms; only optometry-related certificates displayed. Product display area: frames/sunglasses must not be used to highlight or identify the practice ; no commercialization; no advertisement of free services. Ophthalmic laboratory: separate from the exam room. Locker rooms, pantry, stockroom must be separate from the service area. Service delivery (Sec 5, Board Res 11): minimum services for school-aged children, adults (18+), and seniors (60+); management options include spectacle correction, safety eyewear, contact lenses, and basic vision therapy. Time and Manner of Examination (Sec 48): chair time, method, and procedure are the sole discretion of the handling doctor , free from external influence (owners, managers, staff). Wear professional attire.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-details-3-advertising-and-conduct\",\"heading\":\"3. Advertising and Conduct\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 Sec 32(c) and Board Resolution No. 1 (Series of 2008), Rule VII Sec 39: An optometrist may use only true, honest, fair, dignified, objective information. Prohibited: self-laudatory claims (better/superior services, exclusivity); any reference to fees or lower-than-customary prices; advertising free exams, discounts, bonuses, premiums, prizes ; exaggerated or false warranties; undignified, immodest, or vulgar ads. Prohibited solicitation: canvassing; employing solicitors, agents, entertainers, or lecturers to attract patronage; using groups or organizations to solicit patients.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-the-details-4-labor-and-statutory-obligations-practical\",\"heading\":\"4. Labor and Statutory Obligations (practical)\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"An optometrist who employs staff (optical assistants, technicians) is an employer with basic obligations under Philippine labor standards: Mandatory government contributions: SSS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG for employees. Basic standards: minimum wage, statutory benefits (13th month pay, holiday/overtime premiums), and safe working conditions. The optometrist remains professionally responsible for delegated tasks ( respondeat superior , see G1-01-General-Pharmacology-Principles ): a non-optometrist staff member may not perform the acts that constitute the practice of optometry ( H1-01-RA8050-Optometry-Law ).\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-numbers-and-values-to-know\",\"heading\":\"Numbers and Values to Know\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"DTI name certificate validity 5 years Notify Board of clinic location within 30 days Minimum exam room area 10 square meters Minimum test distance 3 meters Setup order DTI → Barangay → Mayor → BIR Advertising standard true, honest, dignified, objective Mandatory employee contributions SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-visual-map\",\"heading\":\"Visual Map\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"BUSINESS SETUP — \\\" D-B-M-B \\\" ────────────────────────── DTI (business NAME , 5-yr) → BARANGAY (location clearance) → MAYOR (business PERMIT ) → BIR ( TIN + taxes) CLINIC LAYOUT (Board Resolution 11, 2016) ───────────────────────────────────────── Receiving area → optometry certificates ONLY Exam/treatment room → ≥ 10 SQ M, ≥ 3 M test distance, name posted outside Product display → frames must NOT identify or highlight the practice Ophthalmic lab → SEPARATE from the exam room ADVERTISING — true, honest, dignified, objective ───────────────────────────────────────────────── ALLOWED → dignified statement of services offered PROHIBITED → price / \\\"cheaper\\\" · \\\"better / best\\\" · FREE exams / discounts · solicitors\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-memory-anchors\",\"heading\":\"Memory Anchors\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Setup order \\\"D-B-M-B\\\" DTI (name) → Barangay (location) → Mayor (permit) → BIR (taxes). \\\"10 and 3\\\" 10 square meter exam room, 3 meter test distance. 30 days to notify the Board of your clinic location. Professionalism over commercialization is the answer to most practice items. Chair time = doctor's sole discretion (no external influence). Advertising: true, honest, dignified, objective. No price, no \\\"better than,\\\" no free-service ads. Display the CORs/PICs/COGS/CPD; only optometry certificates.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-board-traps\",\"heading\":\"Board Traps\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"you may advertise a free eye exam to attract new patients. Advertising free or discounted services is a prohibited act. the optical owner can set how long each exam takes to improve turnover. Chair time is the sole discretion of the optometrist , free of external influence. you can register with just the Mayor's permit. You need DTI (name), Barangay, Mayor, and BIR. the exam room minimum is 5 square meters. 10 square meters , with at least a 3-meter test distance. displaying many frames out front helps identify your clinic professionally. Product displays must not be used to highlight or identify the practice (anti-commercialization). you have a year to inform the Board of your clinic location. 30 days .\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-high-yield-summary\",\"heading\":\"High-Yield Summary\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Must-Know Answer Business setup order DTI → Barangay → Mayor → BIR DTI registers Business name (5-year certificate) BIR registers TIN, books of accounts (taxes) Notify Board of location within 30 days Exam room minimum size 10 sq m Minimum test distance 3 m Who controls chair time The handling optometrist Governing office rules Board Resolution No. 11 (2016) Governing advertising rules Board Resolution No. 1 (2008) + RA 8050 Sec 32 Advertising standard True, honest, dignified, objective Mandatory employee benefits SSS, PhilHealth, Pag-IBIG\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-practice-questions\",\"heading\":\"Practice Questions\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"1. What is the correct order of registrations to open a sole-proprietorship optometry clinic? A. BIR → Mayor → Barangay → DTI B. DTI → Barangay → Mayor → BIR C. Mayor → DTI → BIR → Barangay D. Barangay → BIR → DTI → Mayor Answer **B. DTI → Barangay → Mayor → BIR.** Register the name (DTI), clear the location (Barangay), get the permit (Mayor), then register for taxes (BIR). 2. An optical owner instructs the optometrist to limit each eye exam to ten minutes to serve more customers. This violates: A. Nothing; the owner runs the business B. The rule that chair time is the sole discretion of the handling doctor C. Advertising rules D. Labor law Answer B. Board Resolution No. 11 (Sec 48) makes chair time, method, and procedure the sole discretion of the optometrist, free from external influence by owners or managers. 3. Which advertisement is permitted under the rules? A. \\\"Lowest eyeglass prices in the city\\\" B. \\\"Free eye exam with every purchase\\\" C. A dignified statement of the services the clinic offers D. \\\"The best optometrist in the region\\\" Answer C. Only true, honest, dignified, objective information is allowed. Price claims, free-service offers, and self-laudatory superiority claims are prohibited. 4. The minimum examination room area and test distance required are: A. 5 sq m and 6 m B. 10 sq m and 3 m C. 20 sq m and 6 m D. 8 sq m and 4 m Answer B. 10 square meters with at least a 3-meter test distance (Board Resolution No. 11, Sec 47). 5. After securing clinic premises, within how many days must the optometrist notify the Board of the location? A. 15 days B. 30 days C. 60 days D. 90 days Answer B. 30 days , with photographs, to allow inspection and monitoring.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-pen-and-paper-drills\",\"heading\":\"Pen and Paper Drills\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Drill 1 — Brain Dump Write the four-step business setup with the agency and what each provides. No looking. Drill 2 — Clinic Checklist List the required displays in a clinic (CORs, PICs, COGS, CPD) and the exam-room minimums (size, distance, name posted). Drill 3 — Allowed vs Prohibited Ads Write three permitted and three prohibited advertising practices. Drill 4 — Equipment Recall List the ocular-exam instruments and the binocular-vision instruments required by Sec 46. Drill 5 — Teach-Back Explain in three sentences why product displays must not identify the practice. Use \\\"commercialization.\\\" Recall Interval Schedule Session When Drill 1st Same day Brain Dump 2nd Next day Clinic Checklist 3rd 3 days Allowed vs Prohibited Ads 4th 1 week Equipment Recall Final 2 weeks All five, flag gaps\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3-01-practice-management-and-labor-laws-fast-picks-exam-shortcuts\",\"heading\":\"Fast Picks — Exam Shortcuts\",\"topic\":\"H3 — Practice Management and Labor Laws\",\"text\":\"Read the options first, kill wrong values, then settle the flip. `cue → rule → trap`. The numbers — cue: any RA 8050 figure. Pass = 75% avg, none < 50% . Board = 5 from 10 , 5-yr non-renewable, quorum 3. License renews every 3 yrs . Appeal 15 days . Penalty 1–8 yrs / ₱10k–40k . Trap: \\\"license renews every 5 years\\\" (that's the board term , not the license — license is 3). Which law is current — cue: RA 8050 vs RA 1998. RA 8050 (1995) is current; it repealed RA 1998. Trap: \\\"RA 1998 is newer\\\" because the number is bigger. Four ethics principles — cue: the scenario's act. Consent/refusal = autonomy; refer beyond scope = non-maleficence; equal care regardless of status = justice; act in best interest = beneficence. Trap: matching \\\"refer when indicated\\\" to beneficence — it's non-maleficence . Advertising — cue: an ad claim. Allowed = true/honest/dignified statement of services. Prohibited = price, \\\"better/best,\\\" free exams/discounts. Trap: \\\"lower-fee ad is fine if it's true\\\" — truth is no defense; it's prohibited. Clinic + setup — cue: a facility number or registration. Exam room ≥10 sq m, ≥3 m test distance; notify Board within 30 days . Setup order: DTI → Barangay → Mayor → BIR . Trap: a 5 sq m room or starting with the Mayor's permit.\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"H.strategy\",\"subject\":\"H\",\"label\":\"Jurisprudence & Ethics — Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/H-Jurisprudence-and-Ethics/H-Subject-Exam-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Subject H — Strategy, Numbers & Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"\",\"text\":\"Jurisprudence and Ethics · the read-before-you-test reference for all 3 topics H1 RA 8050 H2 Bioethics H3 Practice Management\"},{\"anchor\":\"h1\",\"heading\":\"H1RA 8050 — The Revised Optometry Law of 1995\",\"topic\":\"Subject H — Strategy, Numbers & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Item Value Law / repealed RA 8050 (1995) repealed RA 1998 Board members / nominees 5 from 10 (appointed by the President) Board term 5 years, non-renewable Quorum / admin vote 3 / 3 Passing grade 75% average, none below 50% Results to PRC within 60 days Fail 3x refresher course required License renewal every 3 years (CPD) Appeal window 15 days to PRC Penalty 1–8 years, P10,000–40,000, or both Degree 6-year Doctor of Optometry Scope exceptions (Sec 5): physicians with post-graduate eye training are exempt; public health workers do visual acuity + screening only. Regulator = PRC. DPA use needs pharmacology certification (Sec 31). Code of Ethics = Sec 40 (6 duties). Trap: RA 1998 is newer than RA 8050. No — the numbers mislead; RA 8050 (1995) is current and repealed RA 1998. Trap: license renews every 5 years (like the Board term). No — license renews every 3 years.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h2\",\"heading\":\"H2Bioethics & Code of Ethics\",\"topic\":\"Subject H — Strategy, Numbers & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Four principles \\\"A-B-N-J\\\" (Beauchamp & Childress): Autonomy (informed consent), Beneficence (do good), Non-maleficence (do no harm), Justice (equal care). Sec 40 duty Principle Visual welfare of the public Beneficence Equal diligence to all Justice Confidentiality Autonomy / trust Refer when indicated Non-maleficence Consent: requires understanding of diagnosis, options, risks, alternatives (not a mere signature). Minor → guardian consents (child assents); emergency → may be waived. Refusal of referral → document, re-counsel, do not abandon. Doctrines: respondeat superior ('let the master answer'); informed consent; guardian consent for minors/incompetents. Most-tested principles: autonomy (consent) and non-maleficence (referral/contraindications). Trap: non-maleficence means avoiding all risk. No — the expected benefit must outweigh the expected harm.\"},{\"anchor\":\"h3\",\"heading\":\"H3Practice Management & Labor Laws\",\"topic\":\"Subject H — Strategy, Numbers & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Business setup \\\"D-B-M-B\\\": DTI (name, 5-yr cert) → Barangay (clearance) → Mayor (business permit) → BIR (TIN, books of accounts). Board Resolution No. 11 (2016): notify the Board of clinic location within 30 days ; exam room ≥ 10 sq m with ≥ 3 m test distance; display COR/PIC/COGS/CPD; clinic used exclusively for optometry and manned by a licensed optometrist; chair time = the optometrist's sole discretion . Advertising: only true, honest, dignified, objective information. Prohibited: price/comparative claims, free-service offers, and soliciting (canvassing). Product displays must not identify the practice (anti-commercialization). Labor: SSS (private) / GSIS (government) + PhilHealth + Pag-IBIG. Maternity = 105 days (RA 11210); paternity = 7 days (RA 8187); OSHS under DOLE. Trap: the optical owner sets exam time to boost turnover. No — chair time is the optometrist's sole discretion, free of external influence. Trap: you may advertise a free eye exam. No — free-service advertising is prohibited. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · Subject H strategy card Home Reviewer Strategy Exam\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"H.optolawbook\",\"subject\":\"H\",\"label\":\"Jurisprudence & Ethics — Law Book\",\"kind\":\"reviewer\",\"path\":\"/top2/H-Jurisprudence-and-Ethics/H-OPTOLAWBOOK-Reviewer.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Comprehensive reviewer built from \\\"Optometry: Legal and Professional Aspects\\\" (Claro M. Cinco, O.D.)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Personal study notes. Philippine Optometry Licensure Exam, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Subject H, 10%). This is a study digest, reorganized and rewritten for recall. It condenses the high-yield law and ethics content of the source text. The statutes it covers (RA 8050, the Code of Ethics, PRC laws) are public documents. Numbers, names, and section references are the parts examiners love, so they are pulled out and repeated deliberately.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"How to use this\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Read Part 2 (RA 8050) and Part 3 (Code of Ethics) first. Those two carry most of the exam weight. The history in Part 1 is pure recall points (dates, names, firsts). Parts 5 to 9 are the \\\"professional aspects\\\" that show up as scenario questions. The High-Yield Numbers table near the end is your night-before sheet.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The early record\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Jose Rizal trained in ophthalmology under Louis de Wecker in Paris (1885), also under Otto Becker (Germany) and Ernst Fuchs (Vienna). He operated on the cataract of his mother, Teodora Alonzo . A trial case attributed to him survives in the de Ocampo collection. First optometric clinic that actually did refraction, and the first lens-grinding shop, was set up in Manila by R.M. Clark in 1902 .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The three laws (memorize this chain)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Law Year What it did Optometry Law of 1917 1917 First regulatory law. Written in Spanish. Created the \\\"Junta Examinadora.\\\" Amendment 1919 Amended the 1917 law. RA 1998 1957 Amended the 1917 law; a Code of Ethics was named. RA 8050 1995 The Revised Optometry Law. Replaced RA 1998. Current law. Optometry gained legal recognition as a profession in the Philippines in 1917 . In that same year the US states of South Carolina, Wyoming, and Pennsylvania, plus the territories of Hawaii and Alaska, passed their optometry laws. The 1917 law created the Junta Examinadora (Board of Examiners) . It carried a grandfather clause, jokingly called \\\"examinacion de gracia,\\\" for those who already had an office at least one year before March 11, 1917 (Article 812). First Junta members: G.T. Herrmann, H.O. Haynor, William G. Moore, E.V. Bartholomai, and Justo Gonzalez.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Education firsts\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"First optometry school: the Philippine College of Optometry (operated up to 1925). William G. Moore was president, Justo Gonzalez was dean. First graduates: Bibiana Roxas de Jesus, C. Campomanes, and Pio Catoto. Registration Certificate No. 1 , per PRC records, was issued on March 11, 1918 to Dr. Manuel Sabater . (Federico Sarabia Sr. is often cited as the reputed first; he was the first Filipino to study optometry in the US, at the Northern Illinois College of Optometry, Chicago, 1905.) First university-affiliated optometry college: Centro Escolar University (CEU), 1928 , with Dr. Roy A. Thorson as its first dean. Later schools: Philippine College of Optometry, 1946 (now De Ocampo Memorial College ); Manila College of Optometry, 1951 . In 1980 the Council of Deans organized in Cebu, chaired by Dr. Claro M. Cinco (the author), and pushed the course from four years to six.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Professional associations\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"1917: Philippine Association of Optometrists (first one; went inactive). 1932: Philippine Optometric Association (Vicente Bernardo, president; lasted about four years). 1936: Optometric Association of the Philippines (OAP) , Justo Gonzalez as first president. Became a non-stock corporation in 1948. 1960s: PODA (Philippine Optometrists-Dispensers Association, grew out of POSA) and PROA (Philippine Registered Optometrists Association). 1979 merger (the PRC wanted a single association): OAP + PODA + PROA became Samahan Ng Optometrist Sa Pilipinas (SOP) . Around 37 OAP chapters joined. National optometric congress has run yearly since 1947 . In 1997 the 50th National Optometric Congress (also the 19th SOP Convention) was held in Baguio City.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Regional and world bodies\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The idea for a regional body was seeded at the joint AOA and Canadian congress in Toronto, July 1977 . The 1st Asian-Pacific Optometric Congress (APOC), Manila, July 1978 founded IFAPAO (International Federation of Asian and Pacific Associations of Optometrists). First officers, elected at the 2nd APOC in Bali (1979): Claro M. Cinco (president) , Fumio Morie of Japan (vice-president), Ali Asgar of Fiji (director), Damien Smith (secretary-general). IFAPAO later became APCO (Asian-Pacific Council of Optometry) . The IOOL (International Optometric and Optical League) became the WCO (World Council of Optometry) . The International Optometrist of the Year award: the very first, in 1988, went to Dr. Claro M. Cinco (handed over in Sydney by IOOL president G. Burtt Holmes). Later recipients include Svein Hommerstad (Norway) and Henry W. Hofstetter (USA, the \\\"Hofstetter formula\\\" name, who also wrote this book's foreword).\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 2: RA 8050, The Revised Optometry Law of 1995 (the core)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Full title: \\\"An Act Regulating the Practice of Optometry, Upgrading Optometric Education, Integrating Optometrists, and for Other Purposes.\\\" Approved June 7, 1995 by President Fidel V. Ramos . It was a consolidation of House Bill 14100 and Senate Bill 1998 (Senate passed June 3, 1995; House June 5, 1995).\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Foundational sections\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 1 Title: \\\"Revised Optometry Law of 1995.\\\" Sec. 2 State Policy: optometry is promoted as a regular component of the primary health care system .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Sec. 3 Definitions\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Optometry: the science and art of examining the eye, analyzing ocular function, prescribing and dispensing ophthalmic lenses, prisms, contact lenses and their accessories and solutions, low vision aids, ocular exercises, vision training, orthoptics, installing prosthetics, using diagnostic pharmaceutical agents, and other preventive or corrective measures. Optometrist: certified by the Board and registered with the PRC. Optometrist in good standing: holds a valid certificate of registration and a valid professional license. Diagnostic Pharmaceutical Agents (DPA), the five in the 2004 text (know the concentrations): Phenylephrine 2.5% Tropicamide 0.5% Proparacaine 0.5% Oxybuprocaine HCl 0.4% Fluorescein strips Set by the Board, approved by the DOH on the recommendation of the BFAD . (Current-law update: the 2008 IRR added Cyclopentolate , so the modern count is six agents. If a question quotes the RA 8050 original text, five is correct; if it asks the current DPA list, six.) Certificate of registration: signed by the PRC Commissioner and all Board members , bearing the seal. Professional license: a renewable card issued by the PRC. Code of professional ethics: the standards of conduct and moral duties, adopted and promulgated by the Board upon PRC approval.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Sec. 4 Acts that constitute the practice of optometry\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"(a) examination by subjective and objective procedures, including DPAs; (b) prescribing and dispensing ophthalmic lenses, prisms, contact lenses, frames and accessories; (c) ocular exercises, vision training, orthoptics, prosthetic devices; (d) counseling on vision and eye care and hygiene; (e) establishing offices and clinics; (f) collecting professional fees. Whether or not it was done for pay does not change whether an act counts as practice.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Sec. 5 Who is exempted from the practice\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Physicians with post-graduate training in the diagnosis and treatment of eye diseases. Physicians examining the eye during a physical exam. Government-trained public-health workers in the blindness-prevention program (they may do visual acuity testing and visual screening only ). Foreigners from reciprocity countries. Internationally known foreign experts. An optometry student or graduate working under the direct supervision and control of a registered optometrist .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Sec. 6 Disclosure of authority to practice\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The optometrist must show the professional license number and its expiration date on documents he signs, and must display the certificate of registration in a conspicuous place.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The Board of Optometry (Sec. 7 to 16)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 7 Composition: five (5) members , appointed by the President on the PRC's recommendation, chosen from a list of ten (10) nominees submitted by the integrated national organization. Sec. 8 Qualifications of a Board member: natural-born Filipino citizen; registered optometrist in good standing; at least 35 years old ; good moral character; in active practice for at least 10 years . A faculty member or anyone with a financial interest in an optometry school must give it up first. An officer of any optometric association is disqualified . Sec. 9 Term: five years, non-renewable. The first appointees were staggered (chair 5 years; others 4, 3, 2, 1) so one seat opens every year. A member in the last year of his term automatically becomes chairperson. A vacancy is filled only for the unexpired portion. Sec. 10 Removal or suspension: by the President , for neglect of duty, incompetence, malpractice, or unprofessional, unethical, immoral, or dishonorable conduct. The President may suspend a member for up to 60 days during an investigation. Sec. 11 Compensation: as set by PRC rules. Sec. 12 Functions and powers (a to p): promulgate and enforce rules; prepare and rate the licensure exam; oversee exam and registration; issue, suspend, revoke, reissue certificates and renew licenses; require continuing education for renewal; keep a registry; adopt and disseminate the Code of Ethics ; administer oaths; conduct hearings and investigations and issue subpoena ad testificandum and subpoena duces tecum , and punish for contempt; conduct ocular inspections; enjoin illegal practice; impose fines and penalties; evaluate optometric education; update the DPA list (mydriatics, cycloplegics, miotics, anesthetics, diagnostic dyes) with DOH and BFAD approval; and study practice conditions. Sec. 13 Quorum: three (3) members. Sec. 14 Votes in an administrative case: a decision needs three (3) votes. A disqualified or inhibited member is replaced by an optometrist in good standing, designated with PRC approval. Sec. 15 Supervision and records: the Board is under the general supervision of the PRC , and the PRC keeps all records. Sec. 16 Annual report to the PRC at the end of each calendar year.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The board examinations (Sec. 17 to 22)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 17: given at least once a year , at places and dates the PRC sets. Sec. 18 Scope: set by the Board, accounting for recent developments and CHED standards. Sec. 19 Who may take it: a Filipino citizen , of good moral character, holding a Doctor of Optometry (O.D.) degree from an accredited school after a six-year course . The listed subjects include optometric ethics and jurisprudence, practice management, public health optometry, low vision and pediatric optometry, contact lens practice, orthoptics and vision training, and neuro-optometry and visual fields. Sec. 20 Passing: a general average of at least 75% in all subjects, with no grade below 50% in any single subject. Sec. 21 Results: the Board reports ratings to the PRC within 60 days of the last exam day; the PRC publishes the list of passers (alphabetical, no ratings). Sec. 22 Reexamination: an applicant who fails a third time must show proof of a refresher course from an accredited school before sitting again.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Registration and licensure (Sec. 23 to 29)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 23 Oath: taken before the certificate is issued. Sec. 24 Disqualification from registration: lacks the Sec. 19 qualifications; failed the exam; convicted by final judgment of a crime involving moral turpitude ; found guilty by the Board of immoral or dishonorable conduct; or declared of unsound mind . Sec. 25 Registration: the PRC registers passers who took the oath and grants their licenses. Sec. 26 Revocation or suspension: the Board, after notice and hearing, may revoke a certificate or suspend a license for unprofessional or unethical conduct, malpractice, violation of the Act or its rules, or conviction of a crime involving moral turpitude. Sec. 27 Appeals: a Board revocation or suspension becomes final unless appealed to the PRC within 15 days of receipt. Sec. 28 Reinstatement, reissuance, replacement: the Board may reinstate a suspended certificate or replace a revoked one (and may waive re-examination), and may replace a lost, destroyed, or mutilated certificate. Sec. 29 Renewal: licenses are renewable every three (3) years , with continuing education and fees. Important trap: Section 29's continuing-education requirement for renewal was repealed by Section 20 of RA 8981 (the PRC Modernization Act of 2000) . So under the modern setup, CPD is not a hard condition for the base license renewal in the way RA 8050 first wrote it.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Education, prohibitions, penalties (Sec. 30 to 34)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 30 Technical Panel on Optometric Education: convened by CHED under Section 12 of RA 7722 (the Higher Education Act). It sets the minimum curriculum and teaching standards and monitors schools. Sec. 31 Competence in Pharmacology: anyone admitted to practice before RA 8050 must take a pharmacology course and pass a special certification exam before using DPAs. Sec. 32 Prohibited acts: (a) giving false or forged evidence to get a certificate or license; (b) posing as a registered optometrist without one; (c) advertising that one optometrist is better than others, or that he charges lower fees or sells cheaper frames or lenses ; (d) DPA use by an untrained optometrist (whether or not injury results); (e) using pharmaceutical agents beyond those authorized; (f) unauthorized practice under Sec. 5; (g) any other violation by a natural or juridical person. Sec. 33 Penalty: imprisonment of not less than 1 year and not more than 8 years, or a fine of not less than P10,000 and not more than P40,000, or both , at the court's discretion, plus the administrative penalties in Sec. 26. If the violator is a company or corporation, its managing officers are held liable. Sec. 34 Foreign reciprocity: a foreigner may sit the exam only if his country lets Filipinos practice there without restriction. The Board may still give a special permit to an internationally known foreign expert.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Integration and closing (Sec. 35 to 43)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Sec. 35 Rules: take effect 30 days after publication . Sec. 36 Integration: all optometrists join one national organization recognized by the Board and PRC. Already-registered optometrists may join within three years of effectivity. Sec. 37 Purposes of the integrated body: promulgate the Code of Ethics, define and enforce responsibilities, raise standards. Sec. 38 Fees and dues. Sec. 39 Other organizations are still allowed. Sec. 40 Code of Professional Ethics: the Board adopts the Code promulgated by the integrated body and gives it to new optometrists at their oath-taking. Sec. 41 Separability. Sec. 42 Repealing: repeals RA 1998 . Sec. 43 Effectivity: 15 days after publication in the Official Gazette or two national newspapers.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 3: The Code of Ethics for Optometrists\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Adopted by the Board under Sections 37 and 40 of RA 8050. The duty of every optometrist: keep the visual welfare of the patient uppermost at all times ; promote better care of the visual needs of mankind; keep abreast of educational and technical developments; see that no person is deprived of visual care regardless of race, creed, or financial status ; advise the patient when consultation or referral is needed; respect the patient's right to privacy and keep information in confidence , using data only for the patient's benefit; conduct himself as an exemplary citizen ; keep his office and practice at professional standards; keep cordial and unselfish relations with his own and other professions.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"AOA Supplement: Moral, Professional and Ethical Obligations\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Responsibilities in general: optometry is a profession; the prime concern is service to humanity , and financial gain is secondary. The optometrist should be an upright person of high moral character, keep current, and hold a scientific attitude. Toward patients: patience above all; a patient's character flaws are held in trust and never revealed except when the law requires; be frank and respectful; give timely notice of any sign of disease, without exaggerating or minimizing it; base fees on the type of service, skill, and knowledge involved. Toward the public: behave as a gentleman and uphold the profession's dignity; do not enter a contract that makes fair dealing with the public impossible; do not mislead the public; be an exemplary citizen and help enforce optometric laws; assist judicial authorities on optometric matters. Unethical and unprofessional acts (a long, testable list): employing lay persons to do the visual examination ; examining outside the regular clinic (unless the request was unsolicited); prescribing or fitting glasses where spectacle correction is contraindicated ; advertising to imply superiority ; practicing under a name other than the one on the certificate , or under a corporation or clinic name that is not the optometrist's own; soliciting patients , using solicitors or agents, or house-to-house canvassing , or paying to get patients; using the title \\\"Doctor\\\" or \\\"Dr.\\\" without adding \\\"optometry\\\" or \\\"optometrist\\\" ; displaying a name or title in letters larger than six inches at street level; advertising any fee or price (exam, lenses, glasses, frames, mountings); signboards with pictures of eyes or eyeglasses that strip away the professional image; using mobile units to canvass or solicit. Toward other optometrists: keep a cooperative and harmonious relationship; be a member of a professional association; expose corrupt or dishonest members to the Board ; consult in difficult cases; a consultant must return the patient to the original optometrist ; make no derogatory hints about a colleague whose patient you see; make no comment about a predecessor you succeed; treat a colleague's patient in an emergency as your own, then return him. Toward other professions: treat their fields with dignity and proper regard; cooperate to protect patient welfare; take part in public-health measures led by other groups.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The Professional Regulation Commission (PRC)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Supervision of the regulatory boards moved from the Bureau of Civil Service to the PRC. The PRC was created by PD 223 (as amended by PD 657) . It was later reorganized by RA 8981, the PRC Modernization Act of 2000 , which repealed PD 223. Composition: one full-time Chairperson and two full-time Commissioners , appointed by the President for a seven (7) year term with no reappointment . A Chairperson or Commissioner must be at least 40 years old , hold a valid license, and have at least five years of executive or management experience. One Commissioner must be a past Chairperson or member of a regulatory board. The Chairperson is the presiding officer and chief executive officer. Pay: the Chairperson at the level of a Department Secretary , the Commissioners at the level of an Undersecretary . The PRC may create regional offices under RA 8981.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The Board of Optometry\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"PD 223 (as amended by PD 657) renamed the \\\"Board of Examiners in Optometry\\\" to the \\\"Board of Optometry.\\\" Its composition, qualifications, and functions repeat Sections 7, 8, and 12 of RA 8050 (five members, ten nominees, age 35, ten years of practice, and so on). PMA v. Dr. Cruz: the President is not bound by the nominees the association recommends; a recommendation is only advice.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Prosecution guidelines (PRC Resolution No. 114, January 9, 1985)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The Board has jurisdiction over administrative cases where the respondent is a registered professional . A person without a valid certificate who practices is guilty of illegal practice and may be prosecuted at the relation of any interested party. Other prohibited acts are criminal offenses. Starting a criminal action against a non-professional is the Board's primary responsibility . The action is filed with the Provincial or City Fiscal , who files the information in court on a prima facie case. A registered professional may face a criminal action in addition to the administrative case.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Where cases go, and appeals\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Type of case Filed with Penalties Appeal to Administrative (Code of Ethics, IRR) Board of Optometry, PRC reprimand, suspension, revocation Office of the President through the PRC Commissioner Criminal Courts of law fine, imprisonment, or both Court of Appeals Civil Courts of law damages Court of Appeals\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 5: The Practice of Optometry (professional aspects)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The practice of optometry is a privilege or franchise the state grants under its police power (the power of the legislature to pass reasonable laws for public welfare, health, morality, and safety). Classic cases: People v. Pomar (46 Phil. 440) and US v. Gomez Jesus (31 Phil. 218) . Useful definitions: Diagnosis is identifying the nature of the anomaly. Treatment is applying a remedy. Prescription is ordering the use of a remedy (State v. Whipple). Dispensing is issuing an optical appliance that corrects a defect. An ophthalmic dispenser supplies and adapts prescribed products.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The lay-corporation problem (a favorite scenario)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"A corporation cannot practice optometry . It cannot meet the personal qualifications (good moral character, a degree, an oath), so it cannot practice directly, and it cannot do indirectly (by hiring licensed optometrists to sell lenses) what it cannot do directly. The IRR backs this up: Rule VIII (5) bars using a trade name other than the optometrist's own registered name, and Rule X, Section 47(g) bars non-optometrists and juridical persons from engaging in practice by employing optometrists. An optometrist who aids or abets such an arrangement can be suspended or revoked. An optometrist may work for a non-optometrist only as an in-house or retainer optometrist serving that employer's own employees, not the general public.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Faith healing and religious freedom\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The Optometry Law does not exempt faith healers, but the Constitution ( Art. III, Sec. 5 ) protects religious freedom in two parts: the freedom to believe and the freedom to act . A person who uses prayer alone is exercising religion. Once he picks up diagnostic instruments or optical devices , he is engaged in illegal practice. US precedent: People v. Handzik (1951) and People v. Wendel (1946).\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 6: Rights of the Optometrist\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Rights inherent in the privilege to practice: Right to choose patients. The privilege does not force him to accept anyone. Even if he is the only optometrist in town, and even in an emergency, nothing in the Code compels him to serve. Right to limit his practice by (a) specialty , (b) location or clinic , (c) days and hours , or (d) the dictates of his conscience . He can refuse cases outside his chosen specialty, the way an internist is not forced to do surgery. If he already accepted a case that needs continuing care, though, he must see it through even outside his usual hours. Right to determine the appropriate management procedures. Rights incidental to the privilege: exemption of his instruments and library from execution (tools of the trade); holding public or private office; performing certain services; compensation; and membership in optometric societies.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 7: Rights of Patients and Informed Consent\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"The patient has the right to be informed about a procedure and to consent to it. This rests on three ideas: The relationship is fiduciary (built on trust; the optometrist must disclose the true facts, and misrepresentation makes him liable). The patient has a right to self-determination. The classic line is Schloendorff v. Society of New York Hospital (Justice Cardozo, 1914): \\\"Every human being of adult years and sound mind has the right to determine what shall be done with his own body.\\\" See also Natanson v. Kline (1960) and Salgo v. Leland Stanford (1957) . The relationship is contractual ; a procedure outside that contract is void. When consent is not needed: In an emergency (for example, imminent injury from contact lens over-wear or a broken lens; the optometrist may remove the lens without consent, then refer). But if the patient is conscious and competent, or a representative is present, consent must still be obtained. When the law itself compels the procedure for public health, such as compulsory immunization under RA 3573 and PD 996 . Refusing vaccination is punishable. Right to refuse treatment: the patient may refuse care even when it could save his life; he is master of his own body. The state can still compel certain procedures (like immunization) under its police power. Termination of the relationship happens when the patient recovers, the patient withdraws, or the optometrist withdraws. On withdrawal the optometrist must hand records to his successor and inform the patient. The patient may discharge the optometrist at any time .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 8: Professional Fees\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"What sets the fee: the labor and time involved; the importance and responsibility of the case; the optometrist's standing (specialists and established practitioners charge more than new graduates); the value of the result to the patient (\\\" good result, good pay \\\"); the patient's financial ability (charity work is expected; no one should be denied care for money); the purchasing power of the peso; the customary local fee; and the cost of the materials dispensed. Who pays: primarily the patient (of legal age, sound mind, able to contract). Medical care counts as \\\"support\\\" under Article 290 of the Civil Code. If the patient dies or becomes incapable, the claim runs, in order, against the (1) spouse, (2) descendant of nearest degree, (3) ascendant of nearest degree, (4) brothers and sisters (Article 291). A third party's promise to pay does not release the patient. On a referral, the attending optometrist is not liable for the consultant's fee. When the patient may refuse to pay: when the service was expressly free ; when the fee was contingent on success and the treatment failed despite the patient's cooperation; or when the treatment was contrary to what was agreed . The book lists ten formal defenses to a fee claim, including that the charge is exorbitant, no service was rendered, the defendant is not the liable person, there was no consent, the optometrist was negligent , or the optometrist violated the contract.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"PART 9: Liabilities of the Optometrist\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Complaints come in three forms, and they can combine: Kind Filed with Penalty Administrative Board of Optometry, PRC reprimand, suspension, revocation Criminal Courts fine, imprisonment, or both Civil Courts damages\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Criminal liabilities\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Negligence is a failure to pay proper attention and use due diligence. The Test for Negligence (Picart v. Smith, 37 Phil. 809): would a prudent person in the actor's place foresee harm? If yes, the law imposes a duty to take precaution, and failing to do so is negligence. This is the reasonable-person standard. Fraud, deceit, and false advertising (to build up a clientele or to overstate one's skill). Issuance of false certificates (for example, a false report of a patient's vision to get work exemption or a job). Defamation (Art. 353, Revised Penal Code): a public and malicious imputation that causes dishonor. Libel is written (Art. 355). Slander is oral. Elements: an imputation causing dishonor, malice , and bad faith .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Civil liabilities (two causes of action)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Breach of contract. The optometrist is liable only if he specifically promised a cure or result and failed. He is not liable just for failing to cure when he never contracted to cure (Safian v. Aetna). In a breach-of-contract suit, expert testimony is not required and \\\"pain and suffering\\\" is not an element. The prudent rule: never guarantee results. Tort, that is, quasi-delict or breach of legal duty (Art. 2176, Civil Code): \\\"Whoever by act or omission causes damage to another, there being fault or negligence, is obliged to pay for the damage done.\\\" When there is no prior contract between the parties, this fault or negligence is a quasi-delict. Rights of the respondent in an administrative case mirror the Constitution and the Rules of Court: presumed innocent, heard by counsel, informed of the charge, a speedy and impartial hearing, the right to confront witnesses, and no self-incrimination.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"HIGH-YIELD NUMBERS (night-before sheet)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"Item Value First Optometry Law 1917 (amended 1919) RA 1998 1957 RA 8050 (Revised Optometry Law) 1995; approved June 7, 1995 RA 8981 (PRC Modernization Act) 2000 RA 7722 (Higher Education Act, CHED) referenced by Sec. 30 DPAs in RA 8050 Phenylephrine 2.5, Tropicamide 0.5, Proparacaine 0.5, Oxybuprocaine 0.4, Fluorescein strips (5); 6 with Cyclopentolate (2008 IRR) Board of Optometry members 5 (from 10 nominees) Board member: min age / min practice 35 years old / 10 years Board term 5 years, non-renewable Board quorum / votes to decide a case 3 / 3 Board member suspension during probe up to 60 days PRC: Chair + Commissioners / term 1 + 2 / 7 years, no reappointment PRC Chair min age / experience 40 years old / 5 years Optometry course length 6 years Passing the board 75% general average, none below 50% Result reporting to PRC within 60 days Fail 3 times refresher course required Appeal a Board decision to PRC within 15 days License renewal cycle every 3 years Penalty (Sec. 33) 1 to 8 years, or P10,000 to P40,000, or both Integration window for existing ODs 3 years IRR effectivity after publication 30 days Law effectivity after publication 15 days International Optometrist of the Year (first) 1988, Claro M. Cinco IFAPAO founded 1978 (1st APOC, Manila)\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"BOARD TRAPS\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"RA 8050 replaced RA 1998 , not the 1917 law directly. The chain is 1917 to RA 1998 (1957) to RA 8050 (1995). The DPA count depends on the source: RA 8050 as written lists 5 ; the current DPA list with Cyclopentolate is 6 . Section 29's CPD-for-renewal rule was repealed by RA 8981. Do not answer that CPD is a strict statutory condition of renewal under RA 8050 as it stands. Board term is 5 years and non-renewable . The PRC Commissioner term is 7 years, no reappointment . Do not swap them. Board decisions are appealed to the PRC within 15 days ; then to the Office of the President . Court cases go to the Court of Appeals . \\\"Board of Examiners in Optometry\\\" was renamed \\\"Board of Optometry\\\" by PD 223 (as amended by PD 657). Passing is 75% average with nothing below 50% . A single grade below 50% fails you even with a 75% average. In a breach-of-contract suit, expert testimony is not required and pain and suffering is not an element. That differs from a negligence (quasi-delict) suit. The public-health-worker exemption covers VA testing and visual screening only , nothing more.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"QUICK SELF-TEST (cover the answers)\",\"topic\":\"Optometry Law, Ethics and Jurisprudence (Board Review 2026)\",\"text\":\"How many members compose the Board of Optometry, and from how many nominees? Five, from a list of ten. What is the passing requirement in the board exam? A 75% general average with no grade below 50%. Which law replaced RA 1998? RA 8050, the Revised Optometry Law of 1995. List the five DPAs in RA 8050 with concentrations. Phenylephrine 2.5%, Tropicamide 0.5%, Proparacaine 0.5%, Oxybuprocaine 0.4%, Fluorescein strips. What is the penalty under Section 33? 1 to 8 years imprisonment, or a P10,000 to P40,000 fine, or both. Term of a Board member versus a PRC Commissioner? 5 years non-renewable versus 7 years no reappointment. Where do you appeal a Board decision, and within how many days? To the PRC within 15 days. What renamed the Board of Examiners in Optometry to the Board of Optometry? PD 223, as amended by PD 657. Who received the first International Optometrist of the Year award? Dr. Claro M. Cinco (1988). State the Test for Negligence and its case. Would a prudent person foresee harm? Picart v. Smith, 37 Phil. 809. End of reviewer. Source: Cinco, C.M., \\\"Optometry: Legal and Professional Aspects\\\" (Cebu City, 1987, 2004). Statutory content (RA 8050, RA 8981, Code of Ethics) reflects the source text; verify DPA count and CPD rules against the latest PRC issuances before the exam. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · print to PDF from your browser\"}]},{\"itemId\":\"G.g1-strategy\",\"subject\":\"G\",\"label\":\"Ocular Pharmacology — G1 Strategy\",\"kind\":\"strategy\",\"path\":\"/top2/G-Ocular-Pharmacology/G1-General-Pharmacology-Principles/G1-Strategy.html\",\"sections\":[{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"The one idea that organizes everything\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Sort every fact into one of two buckets. Kinetics = what the body does to the drug (ADME). Dynamics = what the drug does to the body (receptor + effect). If you can place a fact, you understand it. ADME = Absorption → Distribution → Metabolism → Excretion. The drug as a traveler: gets in, spreads out, gets broken down, leaves.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Core rules to never miss\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Liver metabolizes, kidney excretes. Liver uses cytochrome P-450 to make drugs water-soluble; kidney flushes them out. Lipid = Uncharged = Non-ionized = Alkaline = Absorbable. One chain. The body absorbs the uncharged form across membranes. The cornea needs both. Epithelium is lipid (needs lipid-soluble drug), stroma is water (needs water-soluble drug). A good eye drug is biphasic. Too lipophilic gets stuck. 0.693 is ln 2. It is the math meaning of \\\"half,\\\" not a random constant. k = 0.693 / t½ .\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Mnemonics\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Potency vs Efficacy: \\\"Potency = Position (how far left on the dose axis, low dose). Efficacy = Elevation (how high the ceiling).\\\" Potent ≠ effective. Drug combinations: Additive = 1+1=2. Synergism = 1+1>2. Potentiation = 0+1>1 (a dud boosts a real drug). Bonds: \\\"Covalent = Committed (irreversible, strongest). Van der Waals = Wavering (weakest, reversible, most drugs).\\\" Rx parts in order: \\\"Please Picture Doctors Saying I Sell Sealed Recipes\\\" → Practitioner, Patient, Date, Superscription, Inscription, Subscription, Sig, Refill. Controlled schedules: Number up, abuse down. I = Illegal (heroin, LSD, no medical use). V = Very low (loperamide).\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Quick-reference tables they test\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Transport Direction Energy Carrier Simple diffusion High → low No No Facilitated diffusion High → low No Yes Active transport Low → high Yes Yes Formula Meaning k = 0.693/t½ Elimination constant from half-life Vd = drug in body / plasma conc Tissue localization (most important parameter) Cl = Vd × Ke Plasma cleared per unit time TI = LD₅₀ / ED₅₀ Margin of safety\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Board traps (the wrong answers they bait you with)\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Potency = efficacy? No. Potency is dose needed; efficacy is max effect. Independent. IV undergoes absorption? No. IV, IA, IC skip absorption. 100% bioavailable, zero-order. Liver excretes? No. Liver metabolizes/eliminates; kidney excretes. More lipid = better eye penetration? No. Too lipophilic stays trapped in epithelium. Competitive antagonism is permanent? No. Competitive is reversible (beaten by more agonist). Non-competitive (covalent) is permanent. Schedule I can be prescribed? No. No accepted medical use.\"},{\"anchor\":\"\",\"heading\":\"Exam-room strategy for this subject\",\"topic\":\"G1 — Strategy, Rules & Mnemonics\",\"text\":\"Spot the keyword. \\\"Reaches circulation\\\" = bioavailability. \\\"Unexpectedly low dose works\\\" = hypersensitivity. \\\"Few doses then tolerance\\\" = tachyphylaxis. Tag the keyword first. Definitions are free points. G1 is heavy on vocabulary (potency, efficacy, posology, pharmacognosy). Lock these cold; they are the easiest marks in the whole subject. When a question gives numbers, it usually wants a formula (half-life, TI, Vd) or a schedule rule (72 hours, 6 months, 5 refills). Memorize those exact figures. Latin abbreviations show up. Know b.i.d, t.i.d, q.i.d, p.r.n, h.s, gtt, O.D./O.S./O.U., a.c., p.o. Tie it to the eye. Every principle has an ocular example in the source (atropine excretion, tropicamide dosing every 5 min, corneal biphasic penetration). The board loves the ocular version. WAA Board Review 2026 · Personal study notes · G1 General Pharmacology Principles\"}]}]}"

export const TOP2_INDEX = JSON.parse(RAW) as Top2Index
